<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP PRIORITY: A GOOD NIGHT'S SLEEP 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The personal requirements of hard-core business travelers
haven't changed all that much since Chaucer wrote ``The Canterbury
Tales'' in the 14th century. Speed and safety may dominate, but
getting a decent night's sleep still ranks way up on the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care who you are, you are going to be grumpy and out
of sorts if you've got sleep deprivation,'' said Dale Moss, the
director of worldwide sales for British Airways.
</P>
<P>
   I spoke with Moss last month in Miami Beach, where he gave the
keynote address at the annual PhoCusWright Internet travel
conference, where 800 delegates spent two days in a glitzy
high-technology environment thick with frenetic dot-com urgency. It
was a relief to find a quiet spot to discuss something as down to
earth as sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The subject is currently topical in business travel because many
airlines, scrambling to grab a bigger share of the lucrative
first-class and business-class market on international routes, are
outfitting the premium sections of their planes with new seats that
fold down flat, like beds. Late next year, Virgin Atlantic will up
the ante by introducing business-class seats that fold down into
four-foot-wide double beds. (Stand by, incidentally, for the smirky
advertising campaign.)
</P>
<P>
   Nothing so radical is planned at British Airways, which was the
first to introduce the so-called flying bed in its first-class
cabins three years ago. Next month, though, the carrier will be
trumpeting new fold-down (single) bed-seats in business class on
its New York-London routes, with expansion to other routes set for
later in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Selling premium seats as companies struggle to cut soaring
travel costs is a tricky strategy. Fewer companies than ever will
now spring for first- or business-class travel, though they work
all the angles to get free frequent-flier upgrades. So airlines are
lunging at the remaining full-fare premium-seat market with
promotions that stress the value of premium service and comfort _
including a good night's sleep _ over that awful cattle-car ride in
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty years ago, people used to fly to London on a Saturday
night so they could start their business on a Monday,'' Moss said,
laying out one rationale intended to move the stone hearts in those
corporate travel departments. ``People don't do that anymore. They
go Sunday night and they start their business on Monday. They go
right from the airplane to work. You've got to get some sleep to be
able to do that and be effective.''
</P>
<P>
   The incentive to sell the expensive seats is compelling,
especially on North Atlantic routes, which have been plagued with
excess capacity after carriers added planes that had been yanked
earlier this year from struggling Southeast Asia routes. So
airlines have been sharply discounting back-of-the-plane seats for
leisure travelers, which is not very profitable. On the other hand,
while first-class and business-class tickets make up about 14
percent of passengers on international flights, they account for 32
percent of revenue, according to the International Air Transport
Association.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways, its profits battered in recent years by fierce
competition from Air France, Continental Airlines and other
aggressive carriers, is getting some results going after that
elusive market. Its premium traffic rose 6.5 percent in November
over the year-earlier month, though the company has said that it
expects to report a loss for the current fiscal year, the first
deficit since the airline was privatized in 1987. Moss said the
idea was to polish the brand name and stress service in the premium
business-travel market, where price is not always the sole
determining factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that I want to gouge customers with higher prices,'' he
said. ``I want to give them better value, and I want to make some
money on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss, of course, is himself a hard-core business traveler. He
has logged 300,000 to 400,000 miles a year for the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Does he always fly first class or business class? ``When it is
available,'' he said. ``But if there's a customer with cash in hand
buying that last seat up front, just watch how fast I move to the
back of the plane, man.''
</P>
<P>
   Side Trips
</P>
<P>
   Chances of having a bag lost, delayed, pilfered or damaged on a
domestic flight continue to rise. In the first nine months of this
year, the rate of ``mishandled'' bags was 5.24 per 1,000
passengers, according to the Transportation Department. That is up
slightly from the period a year earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
