<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS SAY BUSH'S `SMIRK' DOES HIM POOR LIP SERVICE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ That people-winning smile of Gov. George W. Bush's may
have turned overnight into one of his biggest enemies, now known as
The Smirk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Far better a fun-loving grin than a grim-faced grimace,'' Bush
spokeswoman Karen Hughes said Tuesday. ``During his five years as
governor, I don't think anyone made an issue out of his smile. It
just goes to show the difference in presidential politics.''
</P>
<P>
   After two nationally televised debate appearances, suddenly the
pursed-lipped smile that crosses Bush's face in times of mirth and
stress has become fodder for talk radio and a symbol of the larger
question of whether Bush is a man of substance or an overgrown
fraternity boy.
</P>
<P>
   National commentators began commenting on Bush's smile last
month after he grinned repeatedly while delivering a speech on
international policy. The pace picked up last week after the Wall
Street Journal reported on the smirk after his first debate
appearance in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   But the tidal wave that shifted media questions from the temper
of Sen. John McCain of Arizona to the smile of George W. Bush was
set off Monday during a Republican presidential debate in Phoenix
when Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah made a joke about Bush lacking
experience to be president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I really believe that you need more experience before
you become president of the United States. That's why I'm thinking
of you as a vice-presidential candidate,'' Hatch said, while Bush
watched him, smirking.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was defensive on Tuesday when asked whether he worried that
voters would be turned off by his smirk during his televised
debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's your interpretation,'' Bush said, not smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have got to make up their minds. I try not to take
myself too seriously sometimes, but I know what I believe. I know
the principles by which I make decisions. And I feel comfortable
that I can lead our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he did not feel like he had been ``sandbagged'' by
Hatch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a pretty funny exchange. And should I be
fortunate enough to win my party's nomination and go on to win the
presidency, I won't hold all those years of experience in
Washington against him,'' Bush said. ``I'll let him carry my tax
package.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he believes voters eventually will gather enough
information on his experience as Texas governor and on his policy
positions to trust him as president.
</P>
<P>
   ``People make their judgments about candidates from a variety of
sources,'' Bush said. ``A lot of it has to do with the crowds in
Iowa, New Hampshire, South Carolina. They'll take impressions off
the debates. When it's all said and done, they'll make up their
minds.''
</P>
<P>
   But the question is what role the smirk will make in that
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Houston talk show host Dan Patrick on KPRC radio said Tuesday
that Bush's smirk makes it look like he thinks he is smarter than
the person who is talking to him.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally syndicated columnist Tony Snow, a former speech
writer for Bush's father, former President Bush, last month said
Bush acts more like he is pursuing a hobby than a calling to be
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key indicator is the smirk,'' Snow wrote. ``It gives
bystanders the sense they're not dealing with an heir to Abraham
Lincoln, Ronald Reagan or George Bush, but an exhibitionist frat
boy.''
</P>
<P>
   University of Texas political scientist Bruce Buchanan said
voter perceptions of things such as Bush's pursed lips can make a
difference when it comes time to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Body language is very important in presidential politics. It
can be decisive in some cases,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said there is a real difference between how Bush
projects in person and during televised debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing he is best at is connecting in these one-on-one
settings or on the stump,'' Buchanan said. ``Then on television, he
doesn't get to be that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan noted that Republican rival Steve Forbes has a frozen
smile and unblinking eyes that give him the appearance of being
``goofy,'' while Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic
front-runner, is viewed as wooden from his public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said former President Nixon was seen as ``scowling and
shifty-eyed,'' while former President Ford was known as ``stumbling
and bumbling.'' Former President Carter, he said, blinked too much
and smiled at inappropriate times. ``It gave people the creeps,''
Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Hall Jamieson, dean of the Annenberg School of
Communications at the University of Pennsylvania, said a smile such
as Bush's is open to the interpretation of the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``People's reaction to a nonverbal cue can be likened to a
Rorschach test,'' Jamieson said. ``If I don't like it, I will
interpret it as arrogance.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamieson said she watched Bush's reaction to Hatch repeatedly
and decided the governor's expressions were ``very ambiguous.'' She
said it either could be someone laughing at Hatch's joke or someone
smirking to hide anger.
</P>
<P>
   Jamieson said Bush's smile is very much like his father's, but
his father was older, had a breadth of experience and no one
questioned his qualifications to be president. But Gov. Bush is on
a national stage for the first time trying to convince voters that
he has presidential qualifications, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of `Is there an empty suit?' has taken the form
of this metaphor,'' Jamieson said.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said she does not see the alleged smirk. All she sees is
Bush's sense of humor, which is sometimes self-deprecating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has a wonderful sense of humor,'' Hughes said.
``That's a quality people appreciate.''
</P>
<P>
   After Bush flubbed a reporter's pop quiz recently to name the
heads of state in four international hot spots, he added a line to
his stump speech that his wife, Laura, had warned him not to try to
show off by naming all the world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, after a 1994 dove hunt in which he mistakenly shot a
low-flying Kildeer, Bush added a line to his speech that the cows
of Texas were thankful that it had not been deer season.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Republican political operative Charles Black said the
debate over Bush's smile or McCain's temper pales in a political
arena in which Gore and his challenger, Bill Bradley, are calling
each other liars.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we (Republicans) are reduced to facial expressions vs.
degrees of temper, we're OK because those won't be issues by next
November,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
