<HEADLINE>
UCONN BEATS ARIZONA, 78-69; MICHIGAN STATE BEATS KANSAS, 66-54 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Sixth-ranked Connecticut showed the experience of a
defending national champion Tuesday night, holding off a
second-half rally by Arizona and defeating the second-ranked
Wildcats, 78-69, in the Great Eight tournament at the United
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The early-season tournament featured an elite field, drawing six
of the top 10 teams in the country: In the first game Tuesday
night, Michigan State, No. 4, outhustled previously unbeaten Kansas
(No. 5), 66-54. On Wednesday night, Cincinnati (No. 1) plays North
Carolina (No. 7), after Temple meets Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut and Arizona swapped leads for 10 minutes to start
the game, before UConn used a barrage of 3-point field goals to
build a seven-point lead at halftime. The lead remained comfortable
until 10 minutes remained in the game, when Arizona began to close.
</P>
<P>
   With 3:26 to play, Arizona pulled within one point, 62-61.
Albert Mouring responded with five points, pushing the lead to
67-61 with 2:14 to play. Another basket, a steal, and a quick layup
by Edmund Saunders put the Huskies up by 10, 71-61, with 1:16 to
play.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona coach Lute Olson said the loss might do his team good
because players will listen to a coach more once they had lost a
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty obvious who the experienced team was,'' Olson
said. ``There were so many times we'd force a shot, especially
after the other guys did something right. A young player says, `I'm
going to get that back.'''
</P>
<P>
   The game matched two strong-bodied point guards, Khalid El-Amin,
the irrepressible junior who led Connecticut to the national
championship last March, and Jason Gardner, a freshman at Arizona
who was the high school player of the year in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner is expected to fill the slot of Jason Terry, an
all-American player on last year's Wildcat team, which lost in the
first round of the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner was quicker than El-Amin, with moments of flashy passing
and darting moves through the lane. But El-Amin had the shooting
touch, moving easily off of screens for midrange jump shots. He
scored 23 to lead all scorers, mostly on four 3-pointers. Gardner
managed 9 points and 7 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's other starting freshman, guard Gilbert Arenas,
finished with 18 points to lead the team.
</P>
<P>
   Another test came under the basket. Connecticut coach Jim
Calhoun hopes that Ajou Deng, a 6-11 sophomore who practiced with
the team last year, can replace Richard Hamilton, the most
consistent scorer last season, who is now in the National
Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   Olson holds similar hopes for Loren Woods, a 7-1 center and
Arizona's oldest starter, who transferred from Wake Forest as a
junior. Arizona needs him to dominate in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Woods had the better game, scoring 16 with nine
rebounds. Deng hit two long shots from the point in the first half,
and finished with 7 points and no rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's forwards, Saunders and Kevin Freeman, clamped down
on Arizona, holding Michael Wright and Richard Jefferson to a
combined 22 points, below their season average of 29. Freeman added
10 points.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Robertson had 15 points for the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   The first game of the night was won with experience. The older,
swifter Spartans outhustled the taller Jayhawks and outrebounded
them, 47 to 35.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were more aggressive,'' said Roy Williams, the Kansas
coach, ``and I don't mind saying it, they outhustled us. They had
more savvy to get the position, and when we had the position they
muscled us out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans, who started all seniors and juniors, began the
game with poise, while the Jayhawks, with a freshman and sophomore
in the starting lineup, appeared rattled. They shot only 32 percent
from the field in the first half. In the second half, however,
their shooting improved to 50 percent, and a pressing Kansas
defense caused enough turnovers to shorten a 20-point lead to only
six with five minutes to play. Still, Michigan State seemed to grab
every rebound, pushing the lead back out to double figures.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans went to the Final Four last season, and defeated
North Carolina in Chapel Hill on Wednesday. Against Kansas, the
Spartans shot poorly but rebounded relentlessly, finding enough
open shots to stretch out a 20-point lead on Kansas. Michigan State
is now 7-1, with its only loss to Kansas; Kansas is 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the game, the Spartans did not appear to miss Mateen
Cleaves, their senior leader and perhaps the best point guard in
the nation. Out another month with a broken foot, he led cheers
from the bench on crutches.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement at point guard, Charlie Bell, a junior, scored
21 points, including 13 in the first half as the Spartans built a
halftime lead of 39-23. He opened the second half with two more
baskets, stretching to a 20-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, Mateen would have stepped up and handled the ball
and carried us on his shoulders,'' Bell said. ``We didn't break
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State shoved and intimidated Eric Chenowith, the 7-1
center from Kansas; he was 2 of 6 from the field. Kenny Gregory led
Kansas with 14 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
