<SLUG> BC-DIABETES-FDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL RECOMMENDS FDA APPROVAL OF DEVICE FOR DIABETICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Shares in Cygnus Inc. soared Tuesday after an
advisory panel to the Food and Drug Administration recommended
approval of the company's GlucoWatch device, which helps diabetics
monitor the level of glucose in their blood.
</P>
<P>
   GlucoWatch is noninvasive and is meant as an alternative for the
finger-prick test that many diabetics perform several times daily.
It uses a low electrical current to draw fluid through the skin to
the wristwatch-sized device, where it is tested for sugar content
three times an hour. It is worn like a wristwatch. A previously
approved device produced by Minimed Inc. uses a sensor inserted
beneath the skin, typically in the abdomen, that draws fluid
through a thin wire to a small computer that monitors results every
five minutes for up to three days.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Cygnus rose $8.8125, or 95.9 percent, to $18, in
Nasdaq trading. Shares in Minimed fell $5, to $61.
</P>
<P>
   ``The product has lots of imperfections _ that almost goes
without saying _ but this is a very needy and troubled patient
population,'' said Kurt Kruger, an analyst with Banc of America
Securities. Although studies have repeatedly shown that frequent
glucose monitoring and tight control of sugar levels are critical
to reducing the side affects of diabetes, few patients are willing
to prick their fingers so often. ``The worst part of being a
diabetic is not insulin delivery, it's the finger tests,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The limitations of the GlucoWatch are that it requires a
three-hour warm-up period and calibration from a finger-stick blood
measurement. The device is capable of providing up to three
noninvasive glucose measurements an hour for 12 hours, so patients
must still prick their fingers twice every 24 hours. Cygnus said
the device was meant to supplement rather than replace the
finger-stick tests.
</P>
<P>
   The panel recommended approval with three conditions. The first
is an education program, which Cygnus said it had already been
discussing with the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   The second involves changes in the product's labeling. And
third, the committee suggested post-approval study of detection of
hypoglycemia and hyperglycemia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The GlucoWatch monitor is a powerful and unique tool that has
the potential to provide glucose information that has previously
been unavailable,'' John Hodgman, the chairman and chief executive
of Cygnus, said in a statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
