<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRODEUR CONTROLS PENGUINS, DEVILS WIN, 2-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The last three minutes of the second and
third periods were crucial stretches Tuesday night for the New
Jersey Devils as Jaromir Jagr and his Pittsburgh Penguin teammates,
who eliminated the Devils in the first round of the playoffs last
season, attacked relentlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in the playoffs, and in many games this season, New
Jersey goalie Martin Brodeur was on top of his game as the Devils
scored a 2-1 triumph over Pittsburgh before a Continental Arena
crowd of 13,117.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur made 24 saves and allowed a power-play goal to Jan
Hrdina with 2 minutes 46 seconds left in the game, when the
Penguins had six attackers against three Devils for 28 seconds
after Pittsburgh had pulled its goaltender for an extra attacker at
a time it already had a two-man advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur's brilliance helped the Devils (14-9-3) revive at home
after Saturday's loss to Calgary ended their unbeaten home streak
at 12 games, the longest such streak in the league this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all played well, and I'm happy we beat them,'' Brodeur
said. ``They came pretty strong there for a while late in the last
two periods, but we all played well. We want to play like that all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting with Brodeur, the Devils have rarely played this season
the way they did Tuesday night There were few flaws in their game
against the Penguins, and Brodeur and the penalty killers in
particular, led by Scott Stevens, were magnificent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a lot of pressure on them and tried to force the
puck,'' Stevens said of the penalty-killing units, which thwarted
the Penguins and Jagr six times in seven attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big, big, big saves all night,'' was the way coach Robbie
Ftorek described the play of Brodeur, who allowed under two goals
for the first time in six games.
</P>
<P>
   John Madden justified Ftorek's decision to play him for the
first time in five games by scoring the game's first goal, early in
the second period. Randy Mckay sealed the victory with his ninth
goal of the season midway through the last period by redirecting
Scott Niedermayer's shot from the left side. The goal came on the
power play, only the second power-play goal in the last 22 attempts
by the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins played without Tom Barrasso, their No. 1
goaltender, who served his first game of a four-game league
suspension for slashing and breaking the arm of Toronto's Yanic
Perrault in an overtime loss to the Toronto Maple Leafs on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Barrasso's place was taken by Jean-Sebastian Aubin, who was
promoted earlier in the day from the Penguins' top affiliate in the
minor leagues, the Wilkes-Barre/Scranton Penguins in the American
Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Aubin had just one victory in seven games in the minor leagues,
but he played with the confidence of a premier goaltender by making
39 saves. Aubin had little chance on Madden's goal, 2:55 into the
middle period, as Madden was allowed a second chance from close
range on the right. He also had little chance on McKay's
redirection from directly in front.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 39 things I liked about this game,'' Penguins coach
Kevin Constantine said. ``Both goalies were good, but I think Aubin
was better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
