<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPORTSNET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SITES SET FOR HEISMAN TROPHY HOPEFULS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's lower Manhattan. Tuxedos and cummerbunds are everywhere.
ESPN cameras are rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes this announcement: This year's winner of the best
site for a Heisman Trophy contender ...
</P>
<P>
   OK, so that's not going to happen. Web sites are probably going
to be the last thing brought up at Saturday's ceremony at the
Downtown Athletic Club.
</P>
<P>
   But if they are, here are the candidates:
</P>
<P>
   Cool Brees (www.drewbrees.net), a fan site dedicated to Purdue
quarterback Drew Brees.
</P>
<P>
   HerdQB.com, the official site for Marshall quarterback Chad
Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   The Ron Dayne Fan Club (www.rondayne.com), a fan site in
adoration of the record-setting Wisconsin running back.
</P>
<P>
   The Dynamic Michael Vick Website! (www.21cent.net/vick), a fan
site in tribute to the Virigina Tech freshman quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech quarterback Joe Hamilton has a one-page promotion
on the school's official site
(www.ramblinwreck.com/fbo/fbc/hamilton).
</P>
<P>
   And the winner ... Cool Brees.
</P>
<P>
   Endorsed by the Purdue quarterback at his own school page on the
Purdue server (cdweb.cc.purdue.edu/~brees), Cool Brees features a
critique of each game that Brees has played the past season.
</P>
<P>
   Created by Russ Lambert of Humble, Cool Brees also includes a
bulletin board, a Heisman watch, weekly statistics and
fan-submitted images of Brees' career with the Boilermakers and in
high school at Austin Westlake.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert was prompted to start the site last year when Brees led
the Boilermakers past Kansas State in the Alamo Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute the game ended, I ran to my computer to see if I
could find more information about Drew Brees online,'' Lambert
said. ``To my amazement, I couldn't find any sites about him.''
</P>
<P>
   A close runner-up is HerdQB.com. The site is designed by the
Marshall University's Education Technology department and
coordinated by the sports information office. It is highlighted by
a multimedia section where Pennington's fans can hear audio
highlights of his record-setting plays.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall used the same approach in promoting Randy Moss for the
Heisman in 1997. ``Our two attempts at promoting athletes for the
Heisman using the Web have been successful,'' said Brian Gunning,
assistant sports information director for Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   The first runner-up is the Ron Dayne Fan Club Page, which poses
this question: Who is your pick for the Heisman? The site's five
selections start with Ron Dayne, the record-setting Wisconsin
running back.
</P>
<P>
   Fans unsure of the answer can get suggestions from the Ron Dayne
newsletter or the Ron Dayne chat room. The site, which includes a
message board and links to online articles, is not as complete as
the school's official campaign site (www.wisc.edu/ath/greatdayne).
</P>
<P>
   Matt Campbell of Chicago created the Ron Dayne Fan Club Page
three years ago. Since he registered the domain name as
RonDayne.com, the site has attracted more than 25,000 daily hits,
Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dayne fans as far away as South Korea and Russia have e-mailed
and posted their support for Ron,'' Campbell said. ``Many of Ron's
family and friends have also posted their support, and I have even
gotten e-mail from old girlfriends thinking that Ron is actually
running the site and collecting the mail.''
</P>
<P>
   NO PROFITTING: So what's the rule for fan sites for
student-athletes? NCAA spokesman Wally Renfro said the only
stipulation with student-athlete sites or fan sites about
student-athletes is that they not advertise or not link to
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing that says a student-athlete can't have one,
but there is a problem if they advertise or hyperlink to
advertising,'' Renfro said. ``A fan can have a site on a certain
athlete; he just cannot profit from that site using the
student-athlete's name as an allure to the site.''
</P>
<P>
   Renfro said the NCAA has not run into a problem with this yet.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky men's basketball star Jamaal Magloire recently pulled
the plug on his 2-month-old personal site (www.magloire.com). While
Magloire's site did not have ads, it did have links to commercial
sites.
</P>
<P>
   NOTEWORTHY: MSNBCSports.com plans comprehensive coverage of the
Heisman presentation. Readers can vote for their choice and access
news and features on the top candidates. Also planned are on-demand
audio interviews with all finalists ... The NFL's official Super
Bowl site (www.superbowl.com), produced by the NFL and ESPN
Internet Group, was launched Monday with a video archive, player
video diaries and Web cams positioned around host city Atlanta ...
A $1 million prize is available at the FANSonly Network
(www.fansonly.com) for the contestant who correctly predicts the
winner of all 23 college football bowl games and the exact score of
the Nokia Sugar Bowl.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
