<HEADER>
A2416 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-ARMY-SCHOOLS-LADN     12-08 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-SCHOOLS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOND MONEY MAY SAVE BELMONT LEARNING CENTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREG GITTRICH 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The Los Angeles Unified School District's top two
administrators have mounted a campaign to influence key state
officials to release bond money that could pave the way for the
completion of the Belmont Learning Center, the Daily News learned
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the strategy includes restoring credibility to the
nation's second largest school district by recruiting the U.S. Army
Corps of Engineers to oversee school construction, a move announced
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   But close connections between the Belmont scandal and U.S. Army
Secretary Louis Caldera, the federal official in charge of the
Corps, muddle the unusual arrangement between Los Angeles Unified
and the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Caldera formerly worked for O'Melveny &AMP; Meyers, the law firm
being sued by the school district over its role in Belmont.
Further, he strongly supported building what has become the
nation's costliest school when he represented downtown Los Angeles
in the state legislature from 1992 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   With a final decision on the fate of Belmont nearing, LAUSD
Chief Operating Officer Howard Miller and incoming Superintendent
Ramon C. Cortines met privately with Assembly Speaker Antonio
Villaraigosa on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to the discussions said Miller and Cortines urged
the speaker to back off his stance against giving the district
state funds to complete Belmont atop an oil field seeping
potentially deadly and explosive gases.
</P>
<P>
   ``They broached the subject of loosening up some state funds for
Belmont and the speaker said that would be a possibility. But he
wanted to see their plan for accountability,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Miller and Cortines shared their plan to turn over
the district's billion-dollar construction program to the Army and
held up the agreement as a key move by LAUSD's new regime to bring
accountability to the district.
</P>
<P>
   Cortines referred all inquiries toMiller, who said neither he
nor Cortines lobbied Villaraigosa to loosen the state's purse
strings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to find out whether capital money from the
state would be available,'' Miller said. ``We need to know that and
evaluate that in order to make a final recommendation to the school
board.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most school construction projects, the vast majority of
the $170 million sunk into Belmont has come from LAUSD's general
fund, not state bond money.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators have refused to release any additional money for
Belmont, citing potential safety risks at the property and the
project's exorbitant costs.
</P>
<P>
   Villaraigosa's recent vow to stop the state from giving Belmont
even a ``dime'' remains a major factor in several school board
members' opposition to finishing the partially completed campus. It
will cost an estimated $112 million to finish Belmont and install a
safety system under the campus.
</P>
<P>
   While Cortines favors completing Belmont, Miller said he remains
undecided. The availability of state funding will be the biggest
factor in his final recommendation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting with Villaraigosa, Miller called a press
conference to roll out the district's agreement with the Army,
where he repeatedly insisted the federal agency was not being
tapped to rescue Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Miller said he would not close the door on using the
Army's expertise at Belmont if the board decides to complete the
school.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he was unaware of Caldera's connections to Belmont
until being contacted by the Daily News. He said he was not
concerned about the matter since the secretary did not play a role
in the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   While in the state Assembly, Caldera championed Belmont to the
school board on at least on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I urge you to continue in your efforts to build the Belmont .
. . without delay,'' Caldera told the board in October 1996. He
went on to compliment the legal tactics used by O'Melveny &AMP; Meyers
and defend the absence of competitive bidding in the project.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance records show Caldera received numerous
donations in 1996 from LAUSD consultants working on Belmont and
from a partner in the consortium chosen by the district to build
the campus.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Caldera said the secretary was traveling across
the Midwest and could not be reached immediately.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for O'Melveny &AMP; Meyers denied the firm had any
involvement in Miller's decision to bring in the Army. Ralph J.
Shapira, a partner at the firm, said the district's deal with the
Army was not connected to his firm's lobbying efforts to save
Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Several critics of Belmont, most notably state Sen. Tom Hayden,
D-Los Angeles, remained unconvinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always felt that they were going to build Belmont,'' Hayden
said. ``No large project has ever gone undone in Los Angeles. No
matter how fiscally irresponsible and how much danger to the public
health that it creates.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be simplistic to reduce it to lobbying. O'Melveny has
its prestige at stake . . . It has put the firm's name on Belmont.
In the higher circles of influence in L.A. that rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, O'Melveny &AMP; Meyers hired Cerrell &AMP; Associates, a
well-connected lobbying outfit, to defend completing Belmont. The
law firm has acknowledged that the move is its final effort to save
the $282 million project, which in turn would reduce the amount of
damages the district could claim in a malpractice lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   While the school board has been forbidden by the district's
lawyers to meet with O'Melveny &AMP; Meyers, Miller agreed to sit
through a short presentation by the law firm last month.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he cut the meeting short and met the firm with the
board's general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the school has indicated that they are leaning
toward scrapping Belmont in favor of building another high school
nearby. The board, however, has delayed its vote until Miller and
Cortines can offer their recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   They are expected to give a presentation to the board on
Tuesday. The board also will review a budget for the Corps to
oversee the construction of 150 new primary centers.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the board voted to stop all construction at Belmont
and padlock the site. Eight days ago, it fired the school's
developer, Temple Beaudry Partners, a consortium led by Kajima
Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
