<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2418 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     12-08 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
OK, so scratch Tom Osborne. Could Darrell Royal be Chet Gladchuk's
mystery candidate to take the football reins at the University of
Houston?
</P>
<P>
   How about Eddie Robinson? Bo Schembechler? Bud Grant? Bum
Phillips? Sid Gillman?
</P>
<P>
   Offhand, they're the only other living-legend types currently in
coaching retirement who come readily to mind. If Osborne, one of
the truly towering figures of college football, ever seriously
considered the equally towering challenge of starting fresh in
Houston at his friend Gladchuk's behest, anyone could be on the
athletic director's list. Anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Some insiders maintain that Gladchuk already has his man and is
only waiting for Friday to announce him to the world, after the
10-day job-posting period mandated by the state has expired.
Apparently, Osborne wasn't him, his presence on campus _ with his
wife in tow _ last week in a ``consulting'' capacity
notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Just passing through on the way to the Big 12 Championship Game,
Osborne explained. He has known Gladchuk for a number of years, and
an ex-Cornhuskers athletic department employee, Chris Bahl, is one
of UH's associate ADs. Tom was kind enough to drop by to give his
two cents' worth on what the Cougars are doing right and what
they're doing wrong. He has already filed a written report,
detailing his candid observations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, never let facts stand in the way of a good story.
Gladchuk had to vociferously deny a bogus radio bulletin out of
Nebraska on Tuesday that Osborne was taking the UH job for $1
million per year. While the reported salary alone seemed somewhere
between outlandish and absurd, given the Cougars' well-documented
financial straits, as long as they have alums such as John Moores
and John O'Quinn interested in the future of the school's athletic
program, money isn't necessarily an object.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, not all of us UH grads turned out to be waiters,
teachers, shoe salesmen and sports columnists. The clout exists to
hire almost anyone, if he's sold as the right anyone.
</P>
<P>
   These days, a million bucks isn't that big a deal. It's rumored
that Texas Tech AD Gerald Myers, upon hearing about Osborne's
``deal'' in Houston, got him on the phone and said, ``Hell, Tom, if
all it takes is a million, come on out to Tech.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Raiders are also in a search mode, having politely
requested, and received, Spike Dykes' retirement. Clemson's Rich
Rodriguez, one of the nation's ranking young ``A-list'' assistants,
was the front-runner and even visited Lubbock. However, he decided
to stay at Clemson and wait for Don Nehlen to ``retire,''
Spike-like, at Virginia next fall.
</P>
<P>
   Gladchuk would prefer to avoid the embarrassment of being
rebuffed in similar fashion, with his prized catch out perusing
real estate one day and offering a ``no, thanks'' the next. He's
going to extreme lengths to keep his finalists private, for their
sake and UH's. All he's on the record as saying is he wants the
best available coach and that, yes, he's in a hurry because he
doesn't want to hamstring the Cougars' recruiting efforts with any
undue deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he bounced Kim Helton less than 24 hours after the
season ended, ironically, with a three-game winning streak. But
because there has been no concrete evidence of formal contact
between the AD and the predictable, realistic candidates, the
intrigue builds daily.
</P>
<P>
   Chet's up to something, it appears _ and we can only hope. This
hire figures to be the one that jump-starts or finishes off UH's
bid to reclaim some stature as a Division I-A football school that
matters. Gladchuk strongly suspects a playoff for football's
national championship is inevitable, and he wants the Cougars
properly positioned to claim Conference USA's spot in the bracket,
after which on the field anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   It's about more than coaching, too. Chet's choice, aside from
being X's-and-O's compliant, has to have the charisma to rekindle
the dying fire in the constituents' bellies. A Tom Osborne, on
stature alone, could do that. But could a Tony Samuel?
</P>
<P>
   Samuel, a bright, young ex-Osborne assistant being touted by his
old boss, went 6-5 at New Mexico State. If you can win in Las
Cruces, you can win anywhere. Still, you wonder if he could sell
tickets in Houston from the get-go, which is when tickets need to
get going in exchange for hard currency.
</P>
<P>
   And if he did become an overnight success at UH, would Samuel's
head not be quickly turned by a higher-profile, better-paying
position elsewhere? Wanderlust is endemic to the coaching
profession. That's the dilemma Gladchuk faces. The hotter his hire,
the shorter the hiree's UH tenure may be.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why you go with a guy who has absolutely nothing
left to prove, and no bills to pay. Hmm, wonder if Clyde Drexler
knows anything about football?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
