<HEADER>
A2466 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BKN-LAKERS-WIZARDSWRITET     12-08 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS TAKE FIRST WITH WIN OVER WIZARDS
</HEADLINE>
 BKN-LAKERS-WIZARDS WRITETHRU-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Phil Jackson paid deference to the NBA scheduling
gods Tuesday morning, but the gods seemed to ignore his gesture.
</P>
<P>
   He canceled the Lakers' usual game-day shootaround, wisely
noting that a mere 19 hours separated today's tipoff in Sacramento
from last night's final buzzer against Washington at Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   But the same move that preserved their strength also sapped
their rhythm, and it took an extraordinary late effort to put away
a lousy Wizards team 91-80 Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The team that relies on rhythm had 24 left feet, and they kept
stepping on their dance partners' toes. Early shots hit more glass
than net, and it took three quarters before they finally found a
groove and recorded their seventh consecutive win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough. We didn't come in and get our normal shootaround
this morning,'' guard Derek Fisher said. ``So you think about it,
guys have basically just been kind of laying around, chilling all
day. Especially in that first half it makes it tough to find a
rhythm. It was evident tonight that we didn't have any rhythm on
the offensive end, didn't really have that spark or energy flowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach, he knew it would be that way, but he still felt like we
had to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing at 5 o'clock (tonight) is going to be tough. He had to
do something to at least give us a chance to catch our breath a
little bit. We're looking at 16 hours, and we'll be lacing up
again.''
</P>
<P>
   And playing for control of the Pacific Division. With the
Portland Trail Blazers (15-5) losing at home to the Miami Heat
(14-4), the Lakers (15-4) moved into first place by a half-game,
with the Kings (11-4) not far behind. The Lakers also improved to
the league's best mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there's 10 in a row then I'll be pleased,'' Jackson said
of the winning streak. ``I think this team's capable of winning 10
in a row, and it'd be a good landmark for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant and Shaquille O'Neal both sputtered early, Bryant
missing jump shots from all over the floor and O'Neal being denied
some of his usual post position by the Wizards' Ike Austin and
Jahidi White.
</P>
<P>
   It left O'Neal with just 10 points by halftime and Bryant 2 of 7
from the field as the Lakers managed just a one-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Both regained their form in time to save the win. O'Neal scored
20 points in the second half, playing 46 total minutes. He also
contributed 16 rebounds and seven blocked shots. Bryant scored 14
in the fourth quarter _ going 10 for 10 from the foul line _ to
finish with 21, despite 5-of-19 shooting from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working on my jump shot a great deal,'' Bryant said.
``Some of the shots were pretty good looks; I wasn't making them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson called it ``one of his most anxious first halves,'' and
Bryant didn't deny it. ``I'm anxious every game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No one else proved to be much help. Glen Rice was 5 for 14 from
the field, finishing with 15 points. Rick Fox added 11, but only
one point in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The starting backcourt of Derek Fisher and Ron Harper combined
for just six points, while the Wizards got most of their offense
from starting guards Mitch Richmond (23 points) and Rod Strickland
(12 points).
</P>
<P>
   Bad teams have often given the Lakers the biggest fits in recent
years. But they put away the Orlando Magic on Sunday by pouring it
on early, then riding out the rout. It appeared the Phil Jackson
Lakers had shed the bad habit of playing down to their opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a team has to develop a killer instinct for the
.500-or-less teams, the ones that are teams that are going to be
difficult on given nights, that have problems internally or have
injuries, but can rise up and be difficult on some nights,''
Jackson said. &UR; !dlim!!end! &LR; morning, but the gods seemed to ignore
his gesture.
</P>
<P>
   He canceled the Lakers' usual game-day shootaround, wisely
noting that a mere 19 hours separated today's tipoff in Sacramento
from last night's final buzzer against Washington at Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   But the same move that preserved their strength also sapped
their rhtyhm, and it took an extraordinary late effort to put away
a lousy Wizards team, 91-80, Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The team that relies on rhythm had 24 left feet, and they kept
stepping on their dance partners' toes. Early shots hit more glass
than net, and it took three quarters before they finally found a
groove and recorded their seventh straight win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough. We didn't come in and get our normal shootaround
this morning,'' guard Derek Fisher said. ``So you think about it,
guys have basically just been kind of laying around, chilling all
day. Especially in that first half it makes it tough to find a
rhythm. It was evident tonight that we didn't have any rhythm on
the offensive end, didn't really have that spark or energy flowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach, he knew it would be that way but he still felt like we
had to. ... Playing at 5 o'clock (today) is going to be tough. He
had to do something to at least give us a chance to catch our
breath a little bit. We're looking at 16 hours, and we'll be lacing
up again.''
</P>
<P>
   And playing for control of the Pacific Division. With the
Portland Trail Blazers losing at home to the Miami Heat, the Lakers
(15-4) moved into first place by a half-game, with the Kings not
far behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there's 10 in a row then I''l be pleased,'' Jackson said
of the winning streak. ``I think this team's capable of winning 10
in a row, and it'd be a good landmark for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant and Shaquille O'Neal both sputtered early, Bryant
missing jumpshots from all over the floor and O'Neal being denied
some of his usual post position by the Wizards' Ike Austin and
Jahidi White.
</P>
<P>
   It left O'Neal with just 10 points by halftime and Bryant 2 of 7
from the field, as the Lakers managed just a one-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Both regained their form in time to save the win. O'Neal scored
20 points in the second half, playing 46 total minutes. Bryant
scored 14 in the fourth quarter -- going 10 for 10 from the foul
line -- to finish with 21, despite 5-of-19 shooting from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working on my jumpshot a great deal,'' Bryant said.
``Some of the shots were pretty good looks, I wasn't making them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson called it ``one of his most anxious first halves,'' and
Bryant didn't deny it. ``I'm anxious every game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No one else proved to be much help. Glen Rice was 5 for 14 from
the field, finishing with 15 points. Rick Fox added 11, but only
one point in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The starting backcourt of Derek Fisher and Ron Harper combined
for just 6 points, while the Wizards got most of their offense from
starting guards Mitch Richmond (23 points) and Rod Strickland (12
points).
</P>
<P>
   Bad teams have often given the Lakers the biggest fits in recent
years. But they put away the Orlando Magic on Sunday by pouring it
on early, then riding out the rout. It appeared the Phil Jackson
Lakers had shed the bad habit of playing down to their opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a team has to develop a killer instinct for the
.500-or-less teams, the ones that are teams that are going to be
difficult on given nights, that have problems internally or have
injuries, but can rise up and be difficult on some nights,''
Jackson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
