<HEADLINE>
HARPER STILL A KEY FOR LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 BKN-LAKERSNOTES-LADN-SLANG (For use by LANG partners) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
  LOS ANGELES _ As coach Phil Jackson retools his rotation and
prepares to move Kobe Bryant back into the starting lineup, the one
thing that probably won't change is the Lakers' heavy reliance on
veteran Ron Harper.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At least, as long as his surgically repaired knee holds up.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-year veteran's defensive skills and knowledge of
Jackson's offense, mastered during his run with the Chicago Bulls,
have made Harper an invaluable asset. So much so that Jackson had
played him 30-plus minutes eight times in the first 18 games,
despite the fact Harper had offseason surgery on his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   He's averaging 29.1 minutes a game and is on pace to play 2,387
minutes this season _ his highest total since 1993-94.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Bryant back in the rotation, Harper is averaging 31
minutes a night. But he said he's not concerned about early
burnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good. I can't say I'm in pain or my knee hurts or
anything,'' said Harper, who turns 36 next month. ``For the time
that I have played, I feel very good.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certain games in which I'm going to play a large load.
I think that there are times (Jackson) will ease up on me,'' he
said. ``I know Phil, so I just go out and just play basketball. I'm
sure he's going to do the right thing. He's been doing it for the
last four years, so I have faith in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson wants Harper to play alongside the young Bryant as much
as possible ``to lead him out there and help him stabilize the
offense'' and said he's ``not concerned about'' Harper's health.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows how to get through a season,'' Jackson said. ``Last
year he played probably too many minutes (31.6 per game for the
Bulls) and had to have a little bit of an operation in the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until that time, I kind of nurtured him through three
seasons of championship ball where he's playing 18 to 22 or so
playoff games plus the regular season. We were able to put Ron down
in the course of a year and put him on the (injured list) and
restructure his training so ... the injured knee doesn't end up
debilitating him, causing more problems. That's one of the reasons
why Chip Schaefer, our trainer from the Bulls, is here, kind of
monitoring that. So I'm not concerned about that.''
</P>
<P>
   ROYAL PAINS: Jackson wasn't here last season, but is well aware
of the difficulty the Lakers had dealing with the athletic
Sacramento Kings, tonight's opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team had some experiences last year that weren't pleasant
against them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For our part, we're still learning the pace and tempo of games
against these types of teams, how to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
