r a BC-MARS-INVESTIGATION-SF     12-08 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-INVESTIGATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WAKE OF LATEST MARS FAILURE, NASA CHIEF CALLS FOR SPACE 
 PROGRAM INVESTIGATION
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  As NASA abandoned hope of communicating with the Mars Polar
Lander Tuesday, the agency's chief called the failed mission a
``wake-up call'' for the nation's space program and promised to
investigate every aspect of it.
<P>
   NASA administrator Daniel S. Goldin said in an interview with
The Chronicle that he will name a blue-ribbon committee of
independent experts in the next few days to take ``a good hard
look'' at its ambitious Mars program.
</P>
<P>
   But Goldin said the failure will not change the agency's plans
to launch another mission to the Martian surface in less than two
years.
</P>
<P>
   The last, best chance to make radio contact with the spacecraft
yielded only silence early Tuesday. A somber Richard Cook, the
spacecraft's operations manager at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory
in Pasadena, said the flight team had ``played its last ace.''
</P>
<P>
   The failure is the third time since 1993 that NASA has lost a
Mars spacecraft. The Mars Observer vanished just before it was to
enter the Red Planet's orbit in 1993, and just three months ago,
the Mars Climate Orbiter was destroyed because of a communication
glitch that mixed miles and kilometers.
</P>
<P>
   The Mars Pathfinder mission in 1997 was a spectacular success,
landing the first small rover vehicle to analyze Martian rocks on
the planet's arid red surface.
</P>
<P>
   NASA had mapped out an ambitious plan for visiting Mars in the
next decade, with three more missions scheduled for launch in 2001,
2003 and 2005. But Goldin said that given the latest failure, he
``cannot commit to maintain the momentum'' of the Mars program.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have accused the space agency of trying to do too much
with too little money with its ``faster, better, cheaper'' approach
to spaceflight, in which smaller, less expensive probes are
launched more often than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The $165 million Mars Polar Lander, along with its two
microprobes, which were supposed to slam into the surface
separately, was on a mission to study Martian weather and search
for water, which could help scientists determine whether life ever
existed on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   But NASA hasn't heard from the spacecraft since it attempted to
land Friday. Over four days and six opportunities to make contact,
NASA methodically eliminated possibilities that would explain the
lander's silence, including a misspointed antenna or a computer
reset.
</P>
<P>
   Among other possibilities: It crashed, burned up in the
atmosphere or was doomed by landing in a bad spot on the Martian
soil.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin suggested that the lander might well have reached its
Martian target only to fall into an unsuspected gully or onto a
boulder that the camera aboard Mars Global Surveyor, the lone
spacecraft now orbiting the planet, could not detect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may even have gotten too deep into some soft soil or a
crack in the frozen crust,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Future landing missions, Goldin said, must have far more
detailed knowledge of their target's terrain, which might require
orbiting spacecraft carrying cameras capable of far higher
resolution or sending down a whole fleet of probes to gather
close-up knowledge of the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Another need, Goldin said, is for the rapid development of more
``intelligent landers'' capable of probing the ground as the
landers descend and then altering course quickly if unanticipated
obstacles appear.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin said he would welcome a congressional hearing into the
failure. Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Huntington Beach, chairman of the
House subcommittee on space and aeronautics, said in an interview
Tuesday that he will hold such a hearing in February.
</P>
<P>
   Rohrabacher, a strong supporter of the space agency, said that
``NASA's science goals are excellent, but maybe the agency should
take off the shackles of launch dates that are too aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, chairman of the Senate committee that oversees
NASA's costs and missions, said in a statement: ``This failure does
not mean we should stop space exploration, but it does force us to
examine how we spent the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Friedman, executive director of the Planetary Society,
said Tuesday that at least two surveys conducted in the past few
days by professional polling organizations showed that ``Mars
exploration is supported and will continue'' despite the failure of
the lander mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that NASA will have to scale back the schedule of
its missions and make them less ambitious,'' Friedman said. ``But
the recent success of other space exploration missions, including
the Pathfinder, are a vindication of Dan Goldin's `faster, better,
cheaper' policy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be some congressional posturing'' as a result of
the most recent failure, ``but the public accepts the risks in
space exploration,'' said Friedman, whose organization includes
more than 100,000 space enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   At the Jet Propulsion Laboratory, mission controllers finally
gave up after six attempts to hear from the lander. ``We're
certainly disappointed, but we're extremely determined to recover
from this and go on,'' said project manager Cook.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, the lander's team made yet another effort to
listen for a signal by using Stanford University's huge
ultra-high-frequency antenna, a 46-meter radio dish that stands on
a high hill behind the Palo Alto campus and just above Interstate
280.
</P>
<P>
   Cook and his communications engineers sent commands to the
vanished lander to ``bend and stretch'' its main antenna in an
effort to reach a connection with the big Stanford dish.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers are also considering a plan to command the orbiting
Mars Global Surveyor to fly over the landing site during the next
few weeks to take pictures that might at least detect the lander's
parachute. The resolution of the camera is too low to detect the
lander itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
