<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 03:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2469 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-HONDA-CONGRESS-SFCHRO     12-08 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDA-CONGRESS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ASSEMBLY DEMOCRAT TO SEEK CAMPBELL'S SEAT  &HT;     By MARK SIMON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Spurred by a personal promise of support from
President Clinton, Democratic Assemblyman Mike Honda decided
Tuesday to plunge into the race for the South Bay congressional
seat being vacated by Republican Tom Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   It throws open a race Democrats had feared they could lose by
default and means a national focus on the campaign for the seat,
seen as one of a handful that could determine which party controls
the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats can gain the majority by winning five of the 10
Republican-held seats that are being left up for grabs by
incumbents running for higher office or retiring.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998 election, 99 percent of incumbents were re-elected,
while 11 of the 16 open, competitive seats changed party hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic search for a high-profile, well-established
candidate in the 15th Congressional District was reaching a
feverish pace as Friday's deadline for candidacy was approaching,
particularly after a Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee
poll showed Honda ahead of all the other Democrats and the leading
Republican, Assemblyman Jim Cunneen.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic insiders said the poll, taken in the past month,
shows Honda with 38 percent and Cunneen with 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With Campbell running for the U.S. Senate Republican nomination,
Democrats see his seat, which covers most of eastern Santa Clara
County, as ripe for the picking.
</P>
<P>
   Before Campbell was elected to the seat in a 1995 special
election, it was held for more than 20 years by Democrat Norm
Mineta.
</P>
<P>
   The district is 44.5 percent Democratic and 35.7 percent
Republican, numbers that political strategists say indicate a
district that could be won by either party.
</P>
<P>
   Local and national Democratic leaders have been scrambling to
find a prominent candidate who can take on Cunneen, a Campbell
protege with the backing of much of the local GOP machinery.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that Democratic hopes would have to ride on the
shoulders of two relative unknowns _ former Sunnyvale City
Councilwoman Robin Parker, who has had trouble raising money and
winning endorsements, and venture capitalist William Peacock, who
has won prominent endorsements from San Jose Mayor Ron Gonzales and
the local labor central committee and has loaned his campaign
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   That was not enough for local members of the Democratic
congressional delegation, such as Zoe Lofgren, who lobbied Honda
vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as Saturday, Honda, a former Santa Clara County
supervisor in his second term in the Assembly, was telling anyone
who asked that he would not run for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   What changed, he said in an interview Tuesday, was the
assurances he got from national Democrats that he would receive
significant financial and strategic help in the primary election.
</P>
<P>
   He said the details of that aid have yet to be nailed down. He
told Democratic leaders he would interpret a call from President
Clinton as a ``major indicator of support.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called Honda Tuesday morning, promising to headline a
major fund-raising event in the district, Honda said. By the
afternoon, Honda had filed candidate papers with Santa Clara County
elections officials. Tuesday evening, he boarded a plane for Japan
and a previously planned legislative visit there.
</P>
<P>
   Honda's decision left the continuing candidacies of Parker and
Peacock up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Tony Spitaleri said Parker had filed her candidacy
forms last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of right now, today, she is in the race for the long
haul,'' Spitaleri said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Peacock campaign consultant John Shallman said Peacock is
``definitely in the race to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Peacock was running for the seat when no one thought it
was winnable and has paid his dues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Honda's entry into the race is nothing more than
opportunism by a ladder-climbing politician who had to be dragged,
kicking and screaming, into the race at the last minute,'' Shallman
said.
</P>
<P>
   But one Democratic insider that while with Parker or Peacock,
the race could become competitive, ``Mike Honda just walks into it
and makes it a competitive race.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunneen campaign manager Kevin Spillane said the Democrats were
being unduly enthusiastic, and hinted that Honda was being more
than a little naive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a desperation move by the Democrats. They've seduced him
into running with a phone call from the president in the last three
days of filing. It's interesting that he bought the promises the
DCCC made to him,'' Spillane said.
</P>
<P>
   Spillane ran Campbell's 1995 special election campaign against
Democrat Jerry Estruth. ``They made a lot of promises to Jerry
Estruth and didn't deliver,'' Spillane said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the campaign will expose Honda as an ``old-line
liberal'' who is out of step with the politically moderate district
that is in the heart of Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he someone the high tech executives are going to feel
comfortable with? I don't think so,'' Spillane said.
</P>
<P>
   But Honda said he is a good match for the district, much like
the moderate Mineta was.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of the district will determine what they believe.
We agree on the issues. I don't think people see me as an
ideologue,'' Honda said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a very competitive race,'' said a
Democratic campaign strategist. ``This seat has a very affluent,
highly educated electorate that's very cognizant of the issues and
very unhappy with what's going on in Washington. Clearly, a message
that works there says it's time for a change in Washington.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 0322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
