r a BC-WILL&AMP;GRACE-PROP22-SFC     12-08 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILL&AMP;GRACE-PROP22-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAST OF `WILL &AMP; GRACE' COMES OUT AGAINST CALIFORNIA
PROPOSITION  THAT WOULD BAN SAME-SEX MARRIAGE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By ELAINE HERSCHER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a time when entertainment and politics are ever more closely
allied, the cast of the hit TV comedy show ``Will &AMP; Grace'' has
come out against a March ballot initiative that would prohibit
same-sex marriage.
</P>
<P>
   All four actors in the ensemble cast appear in a 30-second TV
spot in which they say California's so-called Knight Initiative
would ``legalize discrimination against gay and lesbian Americans
and their families.'' The spots will begin airing as early as next
month.
</P>
<P>
   Network stars frequently do public service announcements and
take political stands, but it is uncommon for an entire cast to
proselytize against a ballot measure, especially one as
controversial as Proposition 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unprecedented,'' said Mike Marshall, manager of the No
on Knight campaign. ``We can't think, in all of our collective
years in politics, of a top-rated TV show's cast coming out and
doing a message like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall describes it as a ``motivation piece'' aimed at young
viewers who might need an incentive to vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Knight Initiative, named after its sponsor, state Sen.
William J. ``Pete'' Knight, would limit marriage to the union of a
man and a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Its proponents say it restates current law and prohibits
recognition of same-sex marriages performed elsewhere if they ever
become legal in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the initiative is part of a campaign that
threatens domestic partner benefits, hospital visitation and
inheritance rights and other rights of lesbians and gay men.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent Field Poll, 50 percent of voters said they
favored the measure, 41 percent were opposed and 9 percent were
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   As an openly gay man with influence in Hollywood, ``Will &AMP;
Grace'' producer and co-creator Max Mutchnick said he wanted to do
more to fight the initiative than write a check. He did that, too,
but he also approached his show's cast and asked if they would be
interested in doing a spot.
</P>
<P>
   The actors _ Eric McCormack (Will), Debra Messing (Grace), Megan
Mullally (Karen) and Sean Hayes (Jack) _ readily agreed, Mutchnick
said, because their politics are in sync with his. The network,
NBC, was not consulted, Mutchnick said. In the show, both the
characters of Will and Jack are gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi. We are the cast of `Will &AMP; Grace,' '' McCormack begins.
``On March 7, Californians will go to the polls to vote either for
or against basic civil rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Glazier, communications director for the initiative, says
the debate is not about civil rights, but about being ``for or
against marriage between a man and a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Glazier said the campaign against the measure is supported by
``Hollywood liberals and the gay elite.'' He would not say whether
his campaign is gathering any ammunition from Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Mutchnick said he finds Proposition 22 ``repugnant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's mean-spirited and divisive and intrusive,'' he
said. Mutchnick said he is afraid that the measure would turn back
the clock for gays in such critical areas as hospital visits
between same-sex partners, who are not legal relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm hit viscerally by something, I have to respond,'' he
said. ``If I was in a situation where I was unable to see my lover,
I don't know what I would do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutchnick said no one in the cast worried that the TV spot would
alienate viewers or sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would imagine that people who support this initiative
wouldn't be big fans of the show,'' he said. ``The spot will appeal
to younger voters. I have their attention, and I feel we can remind
them about this by using these faces.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 0328EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 03:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2471 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-TRUMP-TECH-SFCHRON &LR;      12-08 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMP-TECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TRUMP SAYS HE TALKS TECH'S LANGUAGE  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD TRUMP 727 _ Developer Donald Trump _ sitting in splendor
in the gold-trimmed cabin of his private jetliner _ said Tuesday
that of all the men who aspire to lead the nation, he's the ``most
qualified'' to address the needs of Silicon Valley because ``most
of the presidential candidates have never made 10 cents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm much more qualified to speak to (high-tech
leaders) than most of the presidential candidates,'' Trump said in
an interview with The Chronicle aboard his plane as it swung across
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Silicon Valley ``the most incredible place on Earth, in
terms of revolution,'' Trump said, ``I think I'm much more
qualified to speak to them.''
</P>
<P>
   On the second day of his colorful exploratory California swing
to consider whether he'll seek the Reform Party presidential
nomination, the high-flying Trump talked about high tech,
speculated on whether he would release his tax statements, and said
that _ unlike other presidential candidates _ he is a ``quick
learner'' when it comes to tough stuff like foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   The gambling magnate said the odds are ``50-50'' he'll run for
leader of the free world and that he is edging closer to doing it.
</P>
<P>
   But while arguing that he is ``very, very seriously''
considering the quest, Trump studiously avoided serious issues in
favor of pithy quotes and a plenitude of chutzpah.
</P>
<P>
   Mobbed by media as he finished touring the Simon Wiesenthal
Center's Museum of Tolerance in Los Angeles, Trump said a trip to
the center would do Pat Buchanan _ his chief rival for the Reform
Party presidential nomination and a ``Hitler lover,'' according to
Trump _ a little good.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day at Anaheim's Arrowhead Pond hockey arena, Trump
strode on stage to fireworks before a cheering audience of 21,000
at motivational speaker Anthony Robbins ``Results 2000'' seminar.
He asked for political advice (``Who thinks I should run for
president?'') and offered some business tips (``When somebody
screws you, screw 'em back a lot harder. The Bible says `an eye for
an eye,' (but) give me a break.'').
</P>
<P>
   He minced no words about other 2000 presidential candidates such
as Democrat Bill Bradley (``so far left you can forget it ... the
ultimate hypocrite'') and Buchanan (`talk about right ... give me a
break.'')
</P>
<P>
   And, as always, Trump showed a plainspoken, uncanny knack for
showcasing No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tired of being bullsh_--ed by these moron politicians,''
he told a lunch crowd Tuesday, in his biggest applause line of the
trip. ``I watched the debates last night. Tell me, how smart are
these guys?''
</P>
<P>
   Trump hinted to reporters that he's more likely to run if Bush
and Vice President Al Gore end up as the nominees of their
respective parties. The developer said he may even go negative if
he puts as much as $100 million into a campaign. ``I can't rule
anything out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he really hit his stride aboard Trump 727, the black, red
and white jetliner with TRUMP emblazoned on the side in 6-foot gold
letters. Schmoozing a handful of political reporters invited for a
20-minute flight from Los Angeles to Long Beach, he roamed the
luxurious leather-lined plane, complete with mirror-polished cherry
wood tables, gold bathroom fixtures, 10-foot bar and paintings
carrying signatures such as ``Renoir.''
</P>
<P>
   As his willowly girlfriend Melania Knauss retired to the white
brocade bedroom, Trump said the 727 could serve as his presidential
campaign plane. ``I don't think you're going to do better,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Trump told The Chronicle he intends to spend plenty of time in
California in the next few months. He plans to be back in January
at the Nixon Library to hold a book-signing for his ``The America
We Deserve,'' which was published this month. (``A lot of people
think I'm pushing the book, but just remember, I had three No. 1
best-sellers,'' he said.)
</P>
<P>
   And Trump, noting he has ``lot of friends'' among the
millionaires of Silicon Valley, confirmed he'll visit in early 2000
to assess the amount of interest in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The developer/author and deal-maker said he understands Silicon
Valley's dealmakers, and he has monitored the rise of high-tech
wealth and the New Economy.
</P>
<P>
   But, as a guy who has lost $9 billion in his lifetime _ and
brags that he's made it all back and more _ Trump had a warning for
the valley's IPO wizards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a scary situation. Some of the companies are great
companies. And then others are not at all great. It is very scary
when the not-so-great ones are worth billions of dollars overnight.
They're going nowhere. They have no earnings, no revenues. They
have only one thing going, and that's lawsuits,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's dot-com madness _ it's been that way for a
long time,'' he said. ``I, personally, like feeling the asset. In
building, you know, everything is very tangible. With the dot.com,
it's nothing that you see so easily. Personally, I like being able
to touch and feel the brick and mortar.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he is ready for the personal scrutiny that will come
with a presidential run, Trump said without hesitation, ``I'm
totally ready. ... People know what they're getting. I've been
through it. I'm an open book. I've always been an open book.''
</P>
<P>
   But will he release his tax returns or medical records, as other
candidates have done? ``I'd consider releasing them,'' he said.
``But it's just something I haven't given any thought to.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't matter anyway, Trump said. ``I'm known as somebody
who's very competent, and very rich. That's a potent combination.
That's not so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle wire services contributed to this report.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
