<HEADER>
A2472 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BRADLEY-ENDORSEMENTS-     12-08 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-ENDORSEMENTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 SAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA REPRESENTATIVES BACK GORE'S CHALLENGER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two veteran San Francisco Bay Area congressmen _
George Miller of Martinez and Pete Stark of Fremont _ endorsed
Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley Tuesday, citing his
commitment to protecting the environment and providing health care
to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign heralded the endorsements as a major
development in a state that has long been considered a Gore
stronghold. The vice president has been endorsed by 20 of
California's 28 Democratic representatives, his campaign said.
</P>
<P>
   At a Washington news conference arranged by the Bradley
campaign, Miller praised the former New Jersey senator for helping
preserve the ecosystem of San Francisco Bay and the Sacramento
Delta by shepherding a landmark agreement between environmentalists
and agribusinesses through the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would never have happened without Sen. Bradley,'' said
Miller, the ranking Democrat on the House Natural Resources
Committee. ``I have fought side by side with this man in
legislative combat. ... I respect his integrity, his grasp of
intensely complex concepts and his determination to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller commended Gore for his ``very good environmental
record,'' but added that when it comes to California water, ``the
administration has just continued to drag its feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Stark, who chaired the health subcommittee of the House Ways and
Means Committee for 10 years, cited Bradley's $65 billion-a-year
plan to expand health insurance as the basis of his endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Bradley is willing to propose a big solution to America's
biggest problem _ 44 million uninsured Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Both criticized Gore for his unrelenting attacks on Bradley's
health proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you see an attempt by Sen. Bradley to engage this nation
in a very serious discussion about millions of children who are
uninsured ... and the first thing you get from the vice president
is an attack,'' Miller said. ``I think that's very unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane defended Gore's criticism as a
legitimate critique of a bad policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign isn't about shooting free throws. It's about
running for president,'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has proposed a more limited, and less expensive, health
care plan.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Washington, a strong advocate of expanding
health care, also threw his support behind Bradley, calling it
``unconscionable in the wealthiest nation in the world that we
alone, among industrialized nations, have not found a way to
provide health insurance to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The new support brought to nine the total members of the House
and Senate who have endorsed Bradley, as  &LR; compared to about 130 for
Gore. Gore's supporters include California Sens. Dianne Feinstein
and Barbara Boxer, Gov. Gray Davis, 11 state senators, and all but
two Democratic members of the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If endorsements are a test of the strength and support a
candidate is receiving, then by this measure Al Gore is doing
extraordinarily well,'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   At their news conference, Stark, Miller and McDermott had kind
words for Gore in their initial statements (Stark said Gore would
make a ``good president,'' and Miller called him a ``good and
decent'' man). But neither Miller nor Stark could contain their
frustration at Gore's centrist politics, his aggressive campaign
tactics and his association with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's moving to the right like a scared rabbit,'' warned Stark,
saying that many Bay Area voters may find Bradley closer to their
political leanings.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether relations with the White House would suffer as a
result of their endorsement, Stark said: ``It can't get much
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore holds a commanding lead in California. A Field Poll
conducted in October showed Gore with a lead of 45 percent to 17
percent among likely Democratic voters. The Gore campaign is
counting on the state to bolster their candidate's edge in case he
stumbles in eastern primaries like New Hampshire and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said Bradley could easily surge in California once voters
start to pay attention to the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, we will come into focus,'' Miller said. ``The vice
president is ahead, but the energy is clearly with the Bradley
campaign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
