<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 08:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2552 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN08-COX     12-08 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ ``Trash mouth'' is what it was called around
the house when I was a kid. ``We do not talk that way in polite
company,'' my mother would explain as she pointed me in the
direction of my room for yet another ``time out'' to reconsider the
wisdom of repeating unkind remarks or anything I might have seen
carved on Ronald Corbet's desk top.
</P>
<P>
   My father insisted rude talk was the result of a limited
vocabulary and that only ignorant people had to resort to it in
order to express themselves. Uncivil behavior he blamed on arrested
development and believed that with education, appropriate
socialization, AND the cessation of puberty, most of us would
outgrow the urge to talk trash in public.
</P>
<P>
   Years later I've found out what happens to those who don't. They
are destined
</P>
<P>
   to jobs on radio as ``shock jocks'' _ those bottom feeders in a
pond where rude
</P>
<P>
   behavior is labeled talent; where incitement to violence is
ludicrously referred to as humor, and where insulting people
because of their color, religion, and even handicaps, is considered
entertainment, and where, when called to account for their
malicious drivel, they cower behind the Constitution, invoking
their right to free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Constitutional right? I don't think so. Slanderous sleaze is NOT
what our founding fathers intended to protect when they came up
with the First Amendment. The Supreme Court has established that
freedom of speech does not include obscenity or language designed
to incite a riot, as recently happened on an afternoon talk show in
Toledo, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   This local shock jock was taking Rev. Jesse Jackson to task for
his role in the Decatur, Ill., controversy over the six boys who
had been expelled from a local high school for fighting. He
suggested that Mr. Jackson was intent on becoming a martyr like the
Rev. Martin Luther King, Jr., and offered to help out by calling a
Miami hotel with a name similar to the one where Dr. King had been
killed, and asking the reservations clerk for a room with a
balcony. Once arrangements had been made he commented, ``all we
need now is a shooter.''
</P>
<P>
   This is entertainment?
</P>
<P>
   And this was not the shock jock's first offense. During the 1996
Olympics he was called to task for wisecracking that he was afraid
Muhammad Ali (who suffers from Parkinson's disease) might drop the
Olympic torch on a ``greasy Middle Easterner'' and start a fire.
</P>
<P>
   This is humor?
</P>
<P>
   I don't think so. Humor doesn't hurt. Humor is not gender- or
race-oriented and it certainly doesn't include making fun of
people's differences.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can be rude _ that doesn't take wit or wisdom _ just
listen to schoolkids in the halls. And yet, according to what I
read, when one of these shock jocks finally pushes the envelope
beyond its limits and winds up unemployed, other sleaze stations
line up to offer him a better job AND more money.
</P>
<P>
   Does that make sense?
</P>
<P>
   But let's check out the flip side of the coin, folks. Isn't the
listening audience just as guilty of truly tasteless behavior as
the jock? All we have to do is tune it out. Radio stations, like
any other medium, are not into charity work _ trust me. When no one
listens, advertisers are unhappy, and it's a fact of life that if
the sponsors ain't happy _ ain't nobody happy.
</P>
<P>
   So, the next time sleaze seeps through your radio, you might
want to do what I did this morning at the gym when I'd finally had
my fill of lyrics dedicated to the ``Mu-thuh!'' word, and choruses
focused on copulation _ I took off my cross-trainer and threw it at
the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, you might not.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, Ohio, 43431. E-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
