<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 08:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2563 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BASEBALL-STORIES08-CO     12-08 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-STORIES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pitcher perfect: Baseball stories score
 &HT;    By George Bennett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Even for a triviaphile, John ``Blue
Moon'' Odom's version of how he got his nickname isn't an
especially exciting nugget. But it becomes oddly compelling when
it's presented in Odom's own neat handwriting, with ``Oakland A's
13'' written beneath his signature and a business card thrown in
from Blue Moon Painting Service that notes the proprietor is a
``Former Pitcher/Oakland A's.''
</P>
<P>
   He is calling attention to his past glory. Yet, in doing so, we
do not see another preening athletic ego but an ordinary man taking
deserved pride in the extraordinary moments of his past.
</P>
<P>
   That's often the effect in Seth Swirsky's second disarmingly
simple volume of baseball correspondence, ``Every Pitcher Tells A
Story.'' The book includes letters from Odom and about 100 other
ballplayers and baseball personages.
</P>
<P>
   As in his 1996 collection, ``Baseball Letters,'' Swirsky uses a
straightforward formula. He writes letters to baseball players _
asking, usually, about a single aspect of the player's career or
his role in some historical event. Then he reprints the responses,
playing them alongside some rare and attractive photos.
</P>
<P>
   The responses add a few pallets to the storehouse of baseball
lore, but the appeal of the book is the in-their-own-handwriting
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Old timers such as Mace Brown, who recounts Babe Ruth's final
home run, write in a kind of cursive no longer drilled into
elementary-schoolers. Modern players tend to print, often using all
capital letters.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Famer Steve Carlton uses letterhead reminding you he is
a 329-game winner. Luis Tiant writes in block letters on a piece of
lined notebook paper. Jerry Reuss sends a postcard of himself in a
Dodgers uniform, pithily answering a question about what it's like
to get together with his old teammates: ``Same players . . .
different wives.''
</P>
<P>
   The letters come from a mix of legends and journeymen. If
there's a common thread to them, it's the sense _ sometimes
acknowledged, often not _ that playing professional baseball was an
experience of fleeting magic that can never be recaptured.
</P>
<P>
   Balor Moore, a forgettable hurler who bounced between several
teams in the 1970s, recounts on a sheet of lined legal paper what
it was like to give up Mike Schmidt's first home run in 1972. Moore
has been out of the big leagues nearly two decades, but he
discusses the characteristics of his fastball as if he were still
toeing the rubber every fifth day: ``Normally my fastball away will
tail off the plate but in this instance it started low &AMP; away and
ran back over the heart of the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Yount, the older brother of Hall of Famer Robin Yount,
tells of his heartbreaking brush with the big leagues in 1971.
Called in to relieve for the Houston Astros, he stood on the mound
and threw a few warm-up pitches but pulled himself out because of
pain in his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   He never got another chance to pitch in a major-league game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I ever thought that would be my only opportunity to pitch
in the major leagues, I would have done so,'' Yount recalls in
upper- and lower-case letters. Later, he concludes, ``I now have a
great family and could not be much happier, except that void of not
accomplishing my boyhood dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   It's this wistfulness that pervades many of the letters. And it
isn't limited to those who had brief careers or missed
opportunities. Consider Bert Blyleven, who pitched 20 years, won
287 games, threw 60 shutouts, struck out more batters _ 3,701 _
than any hurler except Nolan Ryan and Steve Carlton, and played on
two World Championship teams.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Seth,'' Blyleven writes on Minnesota Twins stationery.
``I wish I could have pitched until I die.''
</P>
<P>
   George Bennett writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: georgebennett(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
