<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 08:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2564 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN08-CO     12-08 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Straits of Florida a political battleground
 &HT;    (For immediate release.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ On Dec. 31, it will have been 40 years since Fidel
Castro took power in Cuba. We have been involved in several wars
over that period: Vietnam, Panama, Iraq, Kosovo. Those wars come
and go, the issues never completely resolved but the combat ended
nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the war with Fidel Castro, fought chiefly on a
narrow, watery battlefield known as the Straits of Florida. U.S.
presidents may bellow in the White House against Communist Cuba,
and Castro may carry on protracted verbal assaults on the U.S. from
Havana, but the real battle is in the Straits.
</P>
<P>
   It is through the Straits of Florida that the rafters keep
coming, many trying to escape the rigors of a Communist society,
many others coming simply because they think they can earn an extra
buck in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the early years of Castroism, the rafters were acclaimed as
courageous people seeking asylum from the island. They were greeted
warmly by non-Cuban people.
</P>
<P>
   The perception of the raft people began to change, however.
After the Mariel boatlift in 1980, in which thousands of Cuban
criminals were compelled by a perverse Castro to come across, the
image declined.
</P>
<P>
   It continued its spiral downward when U.S. authorities came to
the realization that many of the rafters weren't rafters at all, at
least not until they were just a couple of miles off the South
Florida coast _ having been smuggled there by mother boats that
collected money from the refugees for the transit.
</P>
<P>
   American policy toward Cuban rafters is unlike that of refugees
from anywhere else. If you can put your foot down on land _ and
that can be done about 5 feet out from shore _ you can stay here,
be claimed by relatives and pursue those things that all Americans
pursue.
</P>
<P>
   But if your feet don't touch the ground and the Coast Guard puts
its arms around you, then, by agreement with Castro, it's back to
Cuba. The huge anti-Castro element centered in Miami never has
liked that deal; it wants all Cubans, whether they touch land here
or are discovered six miles off the Cuban coast, to be admitted to
the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   The fragile arrangement the U.S. has with Castro is threatened
by a 5-year-old boy whom the Coast Guard rescued from an inner tube
on Thanksgiving Day. His mother and 10 others drowned when their
boats capsized in the Straits. Since the youngster's arrival, the
anti-Castro legions in Miami have adopted him as a symbol. His
mother gave her life seeking a better one for her child, is the way
it is told _ and not unconvincingly.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government, soon beginning its fifth decade of not
knowing how to deal with Castro, has backed away from the current
situation and left it to the Florida courts to decide whether Elian
Gonzalez stays in the U.S. or is reunited in Cuba with his father
who, divorced from the mother, is demanding his return.
</P>
<P>
   Miami relatives have showered the boy with clothing, toys _ and
love. They also allowed the child to wear, for the cameras, a Cuban
American National Foundation T-shirt, the CANF being the most
vociferous and identifiable of anti-Castro organizations.
</P>
<P>
   That must have triggered Castro more than anything else. He
immediately demanded the boy's return within 72 hours or face a
rejection of renewal of his immigration deal with the U.S. Talks on
that are scheduled for this month.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem that conventional law is on the side of the
father, but there's nothing conventional when it comes to dealing
with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   If Castro follows through on his threat about immigration, then,
bizarrely, the Cuban exile community will have won a battle,
compliments of the 5-year-old. With Cuban cooperation on
repatriation of refugees dissolved, then anyone floating in the
Straits will be able to come here without fear of being sent back _
or, at the worst, be shipped to U.S.-held Guantanamo.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, people _ many good and others cunning _ have been
locked in a seemingly hopeless tug of war with the Castro
government. The boycott, like Castro, has a long, gray beard.
</P>
<P>
   That Castro has lasted 40 years despite an invasion, commando
raids, bellicosity and economic sanctions would indicate to me that
he is winning the war of the Straits. The fate of a 5-year-old boy
found floating there on an inner tube is just another in a
seemingly infinite conflict.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
