<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 08:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2565 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MINOR-COLUMN08-COX     12-08 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A stunning total for death by inefficiency
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's taken a couple of days for it all
to sink in. After all, the numbers are downright maddening: 98,000
people died last year from medical mistakes. The wrong medicine.
The wrong operation. The right scribbling on the wrong chart. Maybe
it was more. Maybe it was less. Thing is, no one out there is too
interested in keeping track.
</P>
<P>
   In my darkest moments, which come and go at whim, I worry. I
worry about my kid's grades. I worry about money. I worry that
George W. Bush will be my next president. And I worry about dying.
What would I do if I felt a lump in my breast? What would I do if
the semi behind me on the freeway didn't stop? But it turns out
cancer and car crashes shouldn't be my biggest worries. I have a
better chance of dying from the mishandling of a routine medical
event than I do cancer or traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers from the Institute of Medicine, affiliated with
the National Academy of Sciences, took an independent look at the
medical profession and released their findings earlier this week.
They said the industry could reduce the number of deaths each year
by half if it just kept track of accident trends and common
mistakes. The majority of what the researchers found was not
deliberate misconduct but mistakes due to poor communication, bad
handwriting, tired medical workers or malfunctioning equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has a medical horror story. Mine is my gall bladder
surgery. In the hours after the operation, I was shuffled from
floor to floor, post-op attendant to post-op attendant, without so
much as a glance from anyone in charge. I'm an insulin-dependent
diabetic, which was duly noted on my chart. But no one checked my
blood sugar. No one gave me food. My surgeon never checked on me.
My pain medicine never came. For 10 hours, I lay in a hospital bed,
too nauseated to move, too nauseated to leave. ``These
drive-through surgeries are awful,'' a nurse told me during a rare
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   I was angry enough to write the surgeon and the nursing
supervisor and my doctor and the hospital CEO _ all of which makes
me feel a little sheepish right now. Maybe I simply should have
thanked them. I lived.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, getting good health care comes down to
being a good consumer. Want to be heard in the X-ray room? Speak
up. Want to make sure you got Xanex at the pharmacy counter? Check
it yourself. Want to know for sure those are your test results the
lab tech is reading? Look at the chart. We live at a time when
there's more medical help out there than ever before, which means
we have to be more in charge than ever. And anyone who argues with
that is just plain wrong.
</P>
<P>
   It's a mystery to me how anyone could survive all those years of
medical school _ I can't sit patiently for five minutes. I couldn't
be a nurse. I couldn't draw blood. I couldn't stitch together a
crying kid's lip. I admire these people.
</P>
<P>
   I need these people.
</P>
<P>
   But how long are we going to expect perfection as they struggle
to survive in a world of paperwork and angry patients? How can
these people carefully tend to our illnesses when they've been told
to first fret about insurance cards and co-pays?
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, these medical mistakes won't always happen along
the lines of privilege. Some day, probably some day soon, someone
important will fall victim to the wrong pill, the wrong code on the
heart monitor machine, the wrong notation on the chart. And then
all the very incensed people in power will bustle about and appoint
committees and pay for studies and affect big change. A few of them
might even mention the 98,000 we lost last year.
</P>
<P>
   Emily J. Minor writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: emilyminor(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
