r k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN08-COX     12-08 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A fitting site for King's memorial
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shortcuts across the fruited plain:
</P>
<P>
   _ It is not far, physically, to FBI headquarters from the
prominent site on the Tidal Basin in Washington, D.C., near the
memorials to Thomas Jefferson and Franklin Roosevelt, that has been
selected for a memorial honoring Martin Luther King Jr. Some of the
other distances _ emotional, perceptual _ are a good bit greater.
</P>
<P>
   There is justice here, and poetic justice. After Lincoln and the
founders, King arguably did more than any other citizen to expand
and secure liberty for Americans. That's justice.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, King had not only to overcome an entrenched system
of forced segregation but to do so against the relentless animus of
FBI director J. Edgar Hoover. Hoover, who by dint of his position
should have been King's ally against oppression, instead spied on,
slandered and harassed King, even trying to provoke him to suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Hoover's campaign of venom contributed to the atmosphere in
which King was martyred.
</P>
<P>
   Now King becomes the only private citizen honored by an official
memorial in Washington. Hoover's work has not held up so well.
</P>
<P>
   Poetic justice.
</P>
<P>
   _ There's near unanimity in observers' declarations that in his
first quasi-debate with the other Republican presidential
aspirants, George W. Bush neither harmed nor distinguished himself.
His spinners have it that he won, but that is a boast founded
mainly on their relief he didn't blunder.
</P>
<P>
   Undecideds, however, are left to wonder, still undecided, about
the stature of a candidate unable to stand out in a field that
includes Gary Bauer, Steve Forbes, Orrin Hatch and Alan Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   To the degree that the case for Bush continues to rest
disproportionately on his ability to avoid committing fatal damage
to himself, John McCain's trailing footsteps may start sounding
closer.
</P>
<P>
   _ It has come to this: Select condom machines in some of the
better gas stations offer, in addition to the traditional models,
the ``Slick Willie,'' in packaging sporting the presidential seal.
</P>
<P>
   And Bill Clinton was worried that he'd leave no legacy.
</P>
<P>
   _ The deaths of those six firefighters in Worcester, Mass., were
sad, angering and frustrating in their needlessness.
</P>
<P>
   At stake was only a derelict warehouse, but two of the
firefighters worried that some of the homeless might be living
there and went in to search for them. The other four followed when
their comrades didn't come out.
</P>
<P>
   There were no homeless, a fact that detracts none from the
heroism but adds a sense of maddening futility to the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   We've made an informal but basic decision to live with endemic
homelessness rather than heal the mental illnesses and the drug and
alcohol addictions that are its largest cause.
</P>
<P>
   We are not heartless, just _ oh, resigned. We've reached a
fatalistic accommodation with the phenomenon to the point where we
don't even register most of its roiling social ripple effects.
</P>
<P>
   Until the ripple effects become an undertow.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
