<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 08:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2567 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN08-CO     12-08 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Net, personal charities offer more giving options
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Here's a happy holiday thought: Americans are giving
more than ever to charity.
</P>
<P>
   The Salvation Army alone brought in $1.2 billion from private
sources in 1998, according to The Chronicle of Philanthropy. The
newspaper also reported the most recent annual increase in overall
giving _ 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some new wrinkles in philanthropy _ do-it-yourself charities and
Internet giving _ could fuel even more growth.
</P>
<P>
   The year's end always brings an increase in donations to
charity. In part, that's because more charities ask for money right
about now, and charitable gifts are deductible on income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   For many givers, however, the major reason is that it feels
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of donors are motivated by the concept of
becoming better stewards and giving back to the institutions that
helped shape their values,'' said Todd Gillingham, an executive
with Lutheran Brotherhood, a Minneapolis-based financial services
company.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey last year, Gillingham noted, nearly half said they
gave the most to churches or synagogues. The United Way was in
second place; political and arts organizations were at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the study found that Southerners were more likely
than others to give to churches or synagogues.
</P>
<P>
   Private charities are an intriguing way to give.
</P>
<P>
   You can set up your own charitable fund now, perhaps even naming
it after yourself. You can contribute and take the tax deductions
right now, even if you put off the decisions on when to give and
which agencies will get your support. Another benefit is that
somebody else will do the paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to set up your own charity. One is to
establish a donor-advised fund through umbrella groups.
</P>
<P>
   The second option is to open a charitable account with a private
financial institution. The most prominent are the Vanguard's
Charitable Endowment Program (1-888-383-4483) and Fidelity
Investments' Charitable Gift Fund (1-800-682-4438).
</P>
<P>
   There are some limitations. The minimum to open a fund is $5,000
or more. Your contribution is irrevocable. You may have some
control over investment choices, but they will be limited.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has become a major resource for charitable giving.
You can search for charities that match your interests, check into
their credentials and even make your contributions electronically.
</P>
<P>
   At www.guidestar.org, you will find a database of more than
600,000 charities, and you can look at financial statements from
many of them. Scores of organizations are set up to take donations
over the Internet. Take a look at www.giveonline.org to make a
connection.
</P>
<P>
   Another alternative is www.charitableway.com, which maintains a
roster of retailers that give part of their sales to designated
charities. If you pick the American Hiking Society, for example,
you will find that Office Max gives 4 percent of online purchases
to it. You have to do your shopping through the Web site, and the
purchase price is probably not tax-deductible.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other factors to consider:
</P>
<P>
   _ Taxes: Your donations must be made by Dec. 31 to get the
credit this year. The charity must be a recognized nonprofit
organization, which is one reason for checking guidestar before you
give.
</P>
<P>
   If you are giving stocks or mutual fund shares, make sure you
have owned them for more than one year. Otherwise, your charitable
deduction will be limited to what you originally paid for the
shares _ not their appreciated value.
</P>
<P>
   People always say they give from the heart and not for tax
reasons. But one recent survey showed that people who itemize their
deductions gave an average of $1,277, or 2.1 percent of household
income, during 1998. Those who didn't claim the tax benefit
averaged $367, or 1.1 percent of income.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scams: The Internet has made it easy for con artists to hit on
consumers. The usual rules apply: Don't bite on emotional appeals,
high-pressure sales tactics or names that are almost the same as
well-known charities. Don't give out credit card numbers or other
personal information to unknown telephone solicitors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Your own family: Some adults pass the word to children and
close friends that they don't want any more stuff.
</P>
<P>
   A truly rewarding gift would be an acknowledgement of a donation
to a favorite charity.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
