A2569 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PRACTICAL-MAN08-COX     12-08 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-MAN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ignore the hype: It's the worst night in 1,000 years to party
 &HT;    By The Practical Man
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Millennium Madness is out of hand, and
the practical man felt the heat last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we doing for New Year's?'' his wife asked.
</P>
<P>
   She was baiting the bear, for the practical man's New Year's Eve
hasn't changed in 15 years. He puts the kids to bed, waits for his
wife to fall asleep on the couch, turns off Times Square and
reaches for the next book in his stack. The ritual is honed to
perfection and in no need of amendment. His wife knows this, but
she pressed on with glee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the millennium, you know. We should celebrate!''
</P>
<P>
   Details of the ensuing domestic dispute ain't nobody's dirty
business, but the practical man's daring effort to avoid a night
out did yield two points of public interest.
</P>
<P>
   First, the world isn't going to end. When the practical man was
in engineering school, he was unlucky enough to have a
superstitious lab partner. Whenever a calculation came out even _
2.000, say _ he would shout out ``Gee willikers! Look at this!''
The class would hush and stare, but to this dolt's utter
disappointment, nothing else happened. Numbers are abstract; their
relationship to the physical world is all in our heads. The Earth
isn't counting its laps around the sun, that palm tree in your back
yard doesn't know how old it is, and most important, the fields of
wheat in Kansas and the cattle herds in Texas don't care what year
it is. So relax.
</P>
<P>
   Second, there is no cause for celebration. Come Jan. 1, you will
still have to work for a living, still have to take out the trash,
still have to deal with your teenager. That stack of work you left
on your desk will be waiting on you when you get back, that car
payment will still be due. If you need an excuse to party, be the
practical man's guest, but don't blame him when you wake up
depressed and vaguely ashamed because you half expected things to
be different.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: Thank you for your comments on the use of
calculators in math class. As a math teacher, I've long argued that
they undermine our attempts to teach basic skills, but I've gotten
nowhere. Now I'm losing another battle over cursive handwriting. I
say it is important for a student to be able to write neatly and
legibly in cursive. But an administrator at our school says that
with computers, children don't need to learn cursive. Any ideas? _
Kathy
</P>
<P>
   Give it up, Kathy. You're wrong. Kids don't need to learn
cursive. They don't need to learn to draw pictures. They don't need
to learn to play an instrument, or write poetry, or dance, or make
jokes, or get up on stage. All that Shakespeare/Jim Carrey/Miles
Davis garbage that makes life worth living has no business in
school. Creative things that give us individual personalities and
self-respect run counter to the true purpose of public education,
which, as any school board pinhead will tell you, is to teach kids
how to get a ``good'' job as a faceless, number-crunching,
word-processing corporate drone.
</P>
<P>
   JUST KIDDING!! Cursive writing is no big thing in the practical
man's life. But it is one of the little things that's his alone. It
has also come in mighty handy for taking notes, signing his name
and writing fearsome Post-Its to his kids. Somehow, ``Listen up,
boy! I want those chores done before I get home!'' works better in
a deranged cursive than in tidy print.
</P>
<P>
   Your boss is obviously that most common of meatheads _ an
education major who failed to educate himself. Wise him up.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: I have a great job. I do work that I love
and everyone is nice to me and really cares about me. But I've
decided to quit and move thousands of miles away to marry my
boyfriend, a baseball-ticket salesman. Am I nuts? _ Lesley
</P>
<P>
   How sweet, and permit the practical man to predict the course of
your romance:
</P>
<P>
   A year of bliss: You primp. He preens.
</P>
<P>
   A year of pregnancy: You get fat. He pretends not to notice.
</P>
<P>
   A year of waning affection: You say, ``You used to love me.'' He
says, ``We used to have a sex life.''
</P>
<P>
   A lifetime of desperation: You watch the kids grow up. He
watches TV.
</P>
<P>
   Trust the practical man: You don't need to travel to board this
treadmill to oblivion. You can get on anywhere, and any guy will
do. But a job you love where the people love you is the holy grail
of adulthood. Few ever find it, and no one finds it twice.
</P>
<P>
   So, yeah, you're way nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Send questions and comments to The Practical Man, Accent, The
Palm Beach Post, P.O. Box 24696, West Palm Beach, FL 33416. E-mail:
PracticalMan(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 0830EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
