<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 08:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2570 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN08-COX     12-08 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This is no charity wedding
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When a ``to whom it may concern'' e-mail
came to the paper from a rapturously in love former Jupiter, Fla.,
resident now living in Washington, D.C., I became the designated
whom, and I was concerned.
</P>
<P>
   I was concerned to see in her letter that Gabriela Fernandez,
22, was afroth with happiness, a happiness so wholesome and sweet
and selfless that I feared she would burst into pure radiant energy
before burning down to a caramelized lump of beatitude.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriela, you see, wanted the world to know that she was getting
married to Michael McCoy, 24, also of Washington, on Nov. 27.
</P>
<P>
   That was then. The wedding went off swimmingly and the nupes are
on a boat somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   So, naturally, in anticipation of the wedding, she was in a
state of grace. But that wasn't what prompted her to write. It was
how she met her husband-to-be that compelled her to tell the world.
She met Michael at a Washington homeless shelter where both had
volunteered to work with children of parents receiving job
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``My purpose for writing is to let those who are seeking a
lifetime companion know that clubs and bars aren't the only place
to find a mate. You will find the kind of person you want to marry
volunteering their time to help the less fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Gabriela went on to explain that two years ago while finishing
up her last semester in public policy at Palm Beach Atlantic
College, she went through a bad patch after a failed relationship.
She did what she always does when feeling sorry for herself _ she
flung herself into helping others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the nation's capital to learn more about public
policy and while there, offered my services at a central D.C.
homeless shelter on Saturday mornings.''
</P>
<P>
   There she met Michael, an ecological engineer for the Maryland
Department of Environment, who came to the shelter to assist with
the children. ``Michael became my best friend and helper with these
inner-city children. From there, our relationship progressed and we
fell in love.''
</P>
<P>
   It struck me that there was more than good luck on my e-mailer's
side. She had odds. I mean, statistically, where are you more
likely to score with a good potential spouse resume, during last
call at the local meat rack, or unloading roof trusses at a Habitat
for Humanity work party?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always,'' she wrote, ``found my consolation in
volunteering.''
</P>
<P>
   Now just a darn minute. Always? Always is a lot. Define always,
I mentally challenged the feel-good bride-to-be of the year.
Admittedly, I was stewing in my own spiritual miserliness. Beyond
giving blood, I can probably count on one finger the times I've
volunteered for anything. I called Gabriela at work for the
National Criminal Justice Reference Service, where she works with
statistics, and thanked her for her thoughtful letter.
</P>
<P>
   And then I said, real casual-like, ``You mentioned in your
letter you always find your consolation in helping others.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she said, ``My family instilled that in me as far back
as I can remember. They're from Venezuela and did a lot of charity
work while I was growing up. Since eighth-grade, they've encouraged
me to go to places with various church groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Could she remember one or two such projects?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, one year we helped build an orphanage in Africa. This
was for children of victims of the AIDS virus. I learned to pour
concrete and roof a building. Another time a school group worked
with poor people in Colombia at a children's hospital. Once I led a
group to Mexico to build a church. I can make bricks from
scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, she chose PBAC not just because of the easy commute from
Jupiter, but because of the college's strong tradition of community
service as a requirement for graduation.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, I've had quite enough of this,'' I said to Gabriela.
``Where's the depravity?'' I said, stealing a line from
``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't this good. I can pass on what you say about
helping others as your own way to get yourself out of the dumps,
but until you tell me some of your filthy little secrets, nobody is
going to sit still for a sermon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I was afraid of this, that I would come off as some
kind of goody-goody, when I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not?'' I asked, hopefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to go to another country and help people. It's an
adventure. I have no illusion that I've gotten more out of learning
about other cultures than I've given by my so-called good works. In
fact, the money spent traveling might have been better spent just
sent to these places. The truth is, it was a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That isn't much of a confession,'' I sniffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, so you want to know the truth about me? All these things
I've talked about are easy. It was easy to love the children in the
homeless shelter when they run up and hug the first person to give
them some attention. It's easy to run off to another country for a
good cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the real world, the everyday world, the world that
counts that I don't measure up. How giving and gracious was I to
the guy who cut me off in traffic today?''
</P>
<P>
   How giving and gracious was she?
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave him something all right. How patient was I with my
annoying co-worker who really needed to talk to someone last week?
Did I even make eye contact, much less smile at the homeless person
I pass on the street every day? And the clerk who took forever to
pack my groceries? Did I show my annoyance?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Snappish, were you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was rude.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, there you have it, readers. Some of these people who fling
themselves at one cause or another are actually having a pretty
good time. Could it be that the real dirty little secret of
volunteerism is that there is a bit of Mother Teresa in all of us,
and that when we find it, we are not sacrificing but indulging?
</P>
<P>
   There's your depravity. Not that there's anything wrong with
that.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wiggins writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: ronwiggins(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
