</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2670 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA-1209-     12-08 2349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA-1209-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA 1209: Welcome to Elliottville. A family kind of
town
 &HT;    (Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. Photos and a sig/locator map are
available. Names and Pflugerville are CQ'd)
 &HT;    By Michele Chan Santos
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELLIOTTVILLE, Texas _ It's a faded green wooden sign at the
intersection of two dirt roads: ``Welcome to Elliottville, pop.
10.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliottville isn't a real town, one that's incorporated and on a
map and has people fighting all the time over annexation issues and
dog leash laws.
</P>
<P>
   No, Elliottville is a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   It's home to the Elliotts, a family that lives in a way others
might think vanished a long time ago, a place where the pudding is
made from scratch and the dogs are all friendly and don't have to
wear leashes at all.
</P>
<P>
   The four households that make up the Elliott clan put the sign
up years ago as a way to let party guests know that they were in
the right spot. The marker _ three miles west of Elgin and a mile
and a half south of U.S. 290 _ has hung there so long that some
people in Elgin think the town is real. (The Elliotts think that's
hilarious.)
</P>
<P>
   They are, by their own admission, old-fashioned. They believe in
homemade food, and staying married, and living near extended
family. In an age of microwave dinners, scattered relations and
single parenthood, it's hard to imagine that anyone lives the way
the Elliotts do.
</P>
<P>
   But spend a little time with them and you wonder why more people
don't.
</P>
<P>
   It's like being on Walton's Mountain, but without the saccharine
fakeness of that '70s TV show. Everyone is polite; everyone,
literally, is family. People constantly say ``Make yourself at
home'' to strangers, and there's a communal dog, Sadie, who's
welcome at every doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   Sit down and a plastic cup of sweetened ice tea appears. Sip it,
and relax, because no one's in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   They are not country people who have lived on the land for
generations and are trying to preserve their lifestyle in some kind
of rural oasis. In fact, they all used to live, and most of them
still work, in Austin. But over the years they decided the urban
life was not for them, that being able to drive five minutes to
Eckerd Drugs for cough syrup or being able to order pizza at 11
p.m. didn't make up for the traffic, noise and congestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all the stress of being in town, it's nice to be out
here with the cows,'' says Bruce Elliott, rounding up his herd as
the sun sets. The light in the field is magical, a soft orange that
makes a nearby pond glow. ``This is my favorite time of day. It's
nice to be home.''
</P>
<P>
   A tour of town
</P>
<P>
   Out here, the Elliotts own 117 acres. The men raise 60 head of
Red Brangus cattle, in addition to their city jobs; the kids fish
for bass and catfish, and play in their treehouse or the nearby
fields, watching out for briar patches and snakes. At 6 p.m., you
can always find a sit-down meal at one of the houses. Anybody in
the family is welcome. How do you know how much to cook? a visitor
asks, and the answer is, you just know. It always works out fine.
</P>
<P>
   Stand at the intersection where the sign hangs, and you can see
the homes of the whole family.
</P>
<P>
   Up to the left is the home of Wayne Elliott, 65, and his wife
Mary Ellen, 60. They own and run Universal Auto Title Services in
Austin, which has two Austin offices. They commute in every day, a
25- to 30-minute drive. Step inside their home, and there's a
pleasant smell of cake and potpourri. Long, comfortable couches and
scattered chairs form a large conversation area, big enough to
accommodate the whole family. Lace and ribbon decorate a homemade
photo album cover and other knickknacks.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road to the right is the home of Dorothy Tippie, 78,
Mary Ellen's mother. She lives alone (if living within a few steps
of your extended family can be considered alone). Dorothy raises
chickens, collecting their small brown eggs daily. The henhouse
continues inside, in a way _ she collects porcelain and ceramic
chickens, all sizes, and has more than 250 in a glass china cabinet
in her living room. A string of pink crocheted hearts hangs on the
front door, spelling out ``Welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy is often on her red Toro riding mower, tooling around.
She recently celebrated her birthday with a big party at the VFW
Hall in Elgin. At the party, she danced to the music of a live
country-western band, despite her problem knee, and looked
resplendent in a blue-and-gold outfit, with carefully applied
eyeshadow.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, a few steps away from Dorothy, is the home of
Bruce Elliott, 43, his wife, Tammie, 40, and their daughter,
Jennifer, 17. Bruce is Wayne and Mary Ellen's son, and works with
his parents at their auto title companies; Tammie works in Elgin
for a tile company. If Elliottville were Monaco, Jennifer would be
the princess. She was Miss Western Days '98 in Elgin, and the whole
family came to see her in her tiara and gown. She's a senior at
Elgin High School (``Home of the Mighty Maroons'') and one of those
teenagers whose resume is so packed it probably doesn't all fit on
one page: student council president, varsity cheerleader, vice
president of drama club, and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer is the only one who's ever been embarassed by the sign.
She hates when other teens ask, ``Are you one of the Elliotts from
Elliottville?'' Just talking about it, she blushes a little.
</P>
<P>
   Walk across the yard from Bruce and Tammie's place, and you're
at Sandy and Shane Harris' home. Sandy, 37, is Wayne and Mary
Ellen's daughter and Bruce's sister. She works with her parents and
brother at the title companies. Shane, Sandy's husband, is 38 and
an electrician with Kanetzky Electric Inc. in Austin. Their sons
Cade, 9, and Corey, 7, are both students at Copeland Elementary.
Shane's the comic in the family, and also the ``resident
exterminator'': One time he killed a snake that was swimming in
Mary Ellen's pool. When he cut its belly open, there were four baby
birds inside. In front of the Harris home, the boys' motorbikes are
parked; inside, there's a whole room devoted to Shane's hunting
trophies (but there's no trace of the snake).
</P>
<P>
   The birth of a farm
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen overnight, this move from the city to the
fields.
</P>
<P>
   When Bruce was a little boy, he had a horse named Sonny. The
family kept the horse in a stable; then the stable was sold and
they had to find a new place to keep him.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne and Mary Ellen decided to buy some land where they could
keep the horse, and ended up purchasing 50 acres, the core of the
property they now own. To help make the payments on the land, they
bought two small houses in Austin, moved them onto the property and
rented them out. They kept the horse in a stable, and set up a
little camping area for themselves, where they would come on the
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   After Bruce and Tammie were married in 1977, Bruce thought about
moving away from Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just lived to be in the country from the time I was able to
walk,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He and Tammie rented one of the houses on the property from his
parents. A few years later, when Shane and Sandy got married, they
moved into the other house. At that point, Wayne and Mary Ellen
gave each of their children the houses they were living in. Since
then, there have been additions and plenty of remodeling.
</P>
<P>
   But their addresses haven't changed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Wayne and Mary Ellen joined them on the land, in a
house they built up at the top of the hill. In 1995, Dorothy, tired
of being so far from the rest of the family, moved into her own
home, down the street from her grandkids.
</P>
<P>
   With the country move came a family-centered way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer, Cade and Corey hardly know what it would be like not
to have their grandparents a short walk away. They've grown up with
Sunday dinners at Mary Ellen's house. The family favorites are
roast beef, mashed potatoes and gravy, green beans, salad and
banana pudding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still use real potatoes, not boxed ones,'' Mary Ellen says
proudly. The Elliotts like doing things ``the old-timey way,'' she
says. ``With fresh green beans and tomatoes, and fresh okra.''
</P>
<P>
   Till death do us part
</P>
<P>
   Another mainstay of Elliott life, along with home-cooked meals
and courtesy, is staying married.
</P>
<P>
   The couples in Elliottville have been married a total of 133
years, if you count Dorothy, who was married for 50 years before
she was widowed.
</P>
<P>
   Brief courtships and long marriages are a family tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne met Mary Ellen just before her 16th birthday. She had just
started working at a burger joint where Wayne, 20, was the night
manager. His knees got weak every time she walked up to him. ``He's
crazy about you,'' the other girls told Mary Ellen. On their first
date, he offered her an engagement ring.
</P>
<P>
   They were married three months later, on June 26, 1955.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce and Tammie met at a stock show. He had recently graduated
from Lanier High School; she was still going there. They had mutual
friends, and similar interests (including living on a farm and
raising hogs or cattle), and were married several months later.
</P>
<P>
   Shane asked Sandy to the 1979 Lanier High School senior prom,
held at the Driskill Hotel. She wore a sleeveless blue flowered
dress; he wore a blue tuxedo. She was a little nervous, because
that was their first date. They were married in 1982, after she
graduated from Southwest Texas State University in San Marcos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't divorce in this family,'' Mary Ellen says.
</P>
<P>
   Skip the car locks
</P>
<P>
   If this were a visitor's guide to Elliottville, it would include
this tip: Learn the nicknames right away.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ellen is ``Meemy''; Wayne is ``Gossy''; Dorothy is
``Nanny''; Bruce is ``Unc.'' They were thus christened by the
children, and now everyone uses those names.
</P>
<P>
   Something else to know _ Sadie, the Australian shepherd, will go
up the hill to Wayne and Mary Ellen's house, but she won't come
back down unless someone gives her a ride in a car. (Someone always
does.)
</P>
<P>
   Gizmo, the Pekingese, knows how to ride on Corey's motorbike.
She sits in front of him and props her little paws on the
handlebars, the wind pushing her fur back as they zoom from house
to house, the dog yapping happily.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody locks their cars, except Dorothy, who still hasn't shed
all of her city ways. And if you're driving to work in the morning
and some of the cows have gotten out, it's your responsibility to
get them back behind the fence before you leave.
</P>
<P>
   On the weekends, there's always a project. It might be
rebuilding the barn fence, digging a new tank or working on the
chicken coop. The Elliotts used to raise exotic animals _ Boer
goats, hedgehogs, sugar gliders, potbellied pigs, emus. But there
wasn't much of a market for them, and now they just raise cattle,
and the chickens that Dorothy keeps.
</P>
<P>
   There's always an automobile to use if yours breaks down;
there's always someone to pick up your kids from school if you
can't. Early in October, for example, Shane and Sandy went to
Barbados for several days to celebrate their anniversary. While
they were snorkeling and enjoying the beach, Mary Ellen took care
of the kids, and Dorothy drove them to school.
</P>
<P>
   Getting along
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone could do this. Many people, if they had to live
within shouting distance of their parents or in-laws, would give up
in frustration after a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrie Engelman lives in Pflugerville and has been Sandy's best
friend since seventh grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I could live that close to my family,''
Engelman says, laughing. She admires the Elliotts' restraint.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all have a good relationship and respect their
boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   What do they do if there's a disagreement?
</P>
<P>
   If a couple fights, ``you keep it in your house,'' Shane says.
No making everyone else take sides or drawing the whole family into
an argument. ``You can't do that sort of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Population change
</P>
<P>
   They might have to change the sign next year.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer will graduate this spring, and hopes to attend Texas
A&AMP;M in the fall, majoring in political science or theater. That
would bring the population to nine (not counting a friend who's
renting a small house on their property).
</P>
<P>
   But after that, the sign probably won't change until Cade or
Corey graduate-- , more than a decade from now. The rest of the
Elliotts, it seems, plan to stay here forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's total tranquility here,'' Mary Ellen says. ``The
businesses are turmoil, and once you get away from there, and out
here, you can relax and you don't have to worry.''
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen years ago, Bruce and Tammie moved back to Austin for
several months, while she was pregnant with Jennifer. They came
back to the land on a fishing trip. Bruce noticed how quiet his
wife was, and then saw the tears running down her face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been home in nearly a year,'' Tammie said.
</P>
<P>
   They moved back to the land not long after.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't guess we'll leave again,'' Bruce says. ``I knew it was
the only place I wanted to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Cannon/AA-S Tammie Elliot, Bruce and Jennifer
</P>
<P>
   Bruce `Unc' Elliott and his wife, Tammie, once moved back to
Austin for a while, but came back to Elliottville. Their daughter,
Jennifer, is a senior at Elgin High.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Cannon/AA-S Dorothy Tippie
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Tippie (known as `Nanny') moved to town because she got
tired of being so far from her family. Now she's just a lawn mower
ride away.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Cannon/AA-S Shane Harris, Tammie, Cade, and Corey
</P>
<P>
   Shane and Sandy Harris are bringing up their sons Corey, right,
and Cade near their extended family in Elliottville.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the residents of Elliottville. All of them. There's no
traffic here and no noise, just family togetherness and the
pleasures of country living.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
