<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2672 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KELSO-COLUMN09-COX     12-08 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    And God said, 'Let there be leather seats'
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When you're really sorry, I mean really, really
sorry, shouldn't you be able to say so in comfort?
</P>
<P>
   Now, thanks to a company called Genuflex in Venice, Italy, you
can.
</P>
<P>
   According to Reuters news service, Genuflex markets a posh
$6,250 confessional booth that has air conditioning, heating, black
leather seats, soft lighting, a walnut finish and a hygienic filter
that separates the penitent from the priest.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, those doing the confessing can regulate the
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't this a little extravagant for a confessional? Heck, a
place like that in Austin would rent for about $950 a month. If
this kind of high-dollar religious equipment becomes trendy, the
next thing you know, the Baptists will be conducting baptisms in a
Jacuzzi.
</P>
<P>
   If Genuflex had catered the Last Supper, they probably would
have served lobster tail.
</P>
<P>
   I'm thinking of buying one of these things and turning it into a
game room. All you'd need to do is add a pool table, a dart board,
a TV set with DirecTV hookup, and the new inflatable cooler chair
from Budweiser that holds 12 cans under the cushion. Then you could
invite the guys over, and they could swap lies while they asked for
forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   I've never shot pool on my knees before, but there's a first
time for everything.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, this Genuflex confessional booth is fancy enough as
it is to be the Neiman Marcus his-and-hers gift. It certainly would
make for a unique Christmas present.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, when you stop to think about it, the fact that the
Italians are selling an air-conditioned confessional means just one
thing. The Italians don't have central air.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I'll admit it. I don't go to church. I probably should. I
might meet a better class of people than I do at the liquor store
where I stop on the way home from work. Then again, I might run
into the same people in church that I see at the liquor store.
Whether I'd recognize them dressed in a suit is another matter. But
isn't this comfortable confessional booth at cross purposes?
Shouldn't a person who is confessing his sins suffer a little?
</P>
<P>
   Instead of air conditioning, shouldn't there be a hot plate for
the confessor to sit on with a control knob that jacks up the
temperature according to the severity of the sin?
</P>
<P>
   You'd put it on three for car theft, and jack it up to nine for
carjacking.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Austin, I doubt if you could find a high-dollar
confessional booth such as the one Genuflex sells.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain level that people ought to feel comfortable
to confess their sins, but we don't have any big overstuffed chairs
in there,'' said the Rev. Jeffrey Allison, pastor of St. Ignatius
Martyr Church at 126 W. Oltorf St. in South Austin. He added that
his church's confessionals ``are just kind of plain and boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Father Allison's church has the standard wooden phone
booth-looking confessionals built into the back wall of the church.
The doors of the confessionals are locked during the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have people who would come in and sleep in here,''
Father Allison explained. Heck, with the Genuflex confessional,
this wouldn't be a problem. With the Genuflex booth, street people
could move in and take up housekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
