<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2675 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN09-COX     12-08 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    tandardized exams for U.S. students a way to improve schools
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush opposes a standardized
national test for public school students.
</P>
<P>
   That's a shame. A standardized national test would go a long way
toward educating millions of this nation's students, parents,
teachers, administrators and schools boards.
</P>
<P>
   A national test also would be an education for the nation's
taxpayers and lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   This education would not be in the three Rs but in knowing which
states and schools are doing a good job and which are not.
</P>
<P>
   Bush explains his opposition to a national test by saying that
education should be the job of states and local schools, not the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   But that answer is a dodge. It sounds good to his supporters _
and would-be supporters _ who favor state's rights and condemn Big
Government.
</P>
<P>
   The answer also sounds good to Americans who know that the
federal government really does little to fund or influence the
nation's public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 6 percent of the budgets of America's public schools
is supplied by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress, presidents, and cabinet officers have
bragged about their roles in shaping the course of America's public
education. They exaggerate. In truth, they have done little.
</P>
<P>
   What little money the federal government gives to the nation's
public schools is weighed down with strings and paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   Local taxpayers fund the lion's share of their own public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The state kicks in extra money, especially in an attempt to
equalize educational opportunities for children who live in
unprosperous school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Then the feds put in their two-cents worth.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal to establish a standardized national test for
public school students does not envision a federal take-over of
local public schools.
</P>
<P>
   That, indeed, would be a disaster. Imagine some bureaucracy like
the Postal Service or the Internal Revenue Service in charge of the
nation's public schools. It's a scary thought.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, it's difficult to imagine how any federal
bureaucracy could have done any worse than America's educators,
teacher unions and self-indulgent Baby Boomers during the past
decades.
</P>
<P>
   After years of feel-good education designed to boost the
self-esteem of students and parents, America began to realize that
many of its children could not read their high school diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   Due to social promotions and grade inflation, parents of honor
students were horrified to learn that their college-bound children
had to take no-credit remedial classes to learn what they should
have learned in high school or earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is a big fan of standardized state tests. He has seen how
they have been instrumental in boosting learning for Texas school
children.
</P>
<P>
   The grade-level Texas tests, which are curriculum based, have
begun to put accountability and responsibility back into public
education.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' standardized tests let students, parents, teachers,
administrators, school boards and taxpayers know how they are doing
compared to the standard as well as to other schools and school
districts around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Texas schools know exactly where they need to improve. The good
schools provide valuable models.
</P>
<P>
   A standardized national test for public school students could be
just as beneficial for states and the nation's public schools.
States and schools that do not meet the standard will know that
they need to improve.
</P>
<P>
   The states and schools that excelled on the standardized
national test would provide models for the others.
</P>
<P>
   A standardized national test must not come with strings. It must
not dictate curriculum. It should be a measurement of learning,
nothing more. But that would help.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texsa. E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
