<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2678 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-ERETAIL-KIDS-COX     12-08 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERETAIL-KIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web sites keep it simple; attract teen shoppers onlineBy Frances
Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teens shopping online are the same as the kids you see in the
mall. They love to shop, but they hate being treated like kids.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites marketing directly to kids are struggling to hit the
right note with young consumers and their parents. They're also
developing ways for kids to shop online without asking mom or dad
for a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study of 16-22-year-olds from Forrester Research,
47 percent or 12.4 million young adults are online and have an
average of $3,000-$5,000 to spend annually. Teens are extremely
loyal to their favorite brands, but that doesn't translate into
online visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marketers have this notion that young adults are very
different and go after the cool stuff,'' says Forrester analyst
Ekaterina Walsh. ``So they stack their sites with unnecessary
features like chat, games and music that kids don't expect from a
retailing site.''
</P>
<P>
   She points to Pepsi and Levis as two sites that have loaded up
with lots of ``hip'' Web gimmicks to lure young shoppers, but
instead are turning them away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Levis has its own music channel and a petition you can sign to
protest violence in schools,'' Walsh says. ``The one thing they had
that was useful, which they pulled out, was online purchasing. You
can do all kinds of things on the Levi's site but you can't shop.
Kids don't want to see music or games on a retailing site.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are making their own decision and they have been for a
long time, especially urban kids,'' says Ginger Thomson, president
of DoughNet, an online service for kids 13-18 who don't have the
credit cards typically needed for Web shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Parents can open a bank account for their kids with
www.DoughNet.com's virtual banking partner, US Access Bank in
Louisville, Ky. Purchases made from online retailers or donations
to non-profit organizations are deducted from the account.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh says young adults don't completely live up to their
rebellious images. They may not want to go shopping with mom and
dad, but they still want parental approval before they head out on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of those sites has a parent section,'' Walsh says.
``They want parents as allies. The pitch is what is the alternative
to not using DoughNet? Letting kids run loose in the mall with your
credit card? That's probably their worst nightmare. Sites like
these let parents determine where the kids can shop and what they
can buy.''
</P>
<P>
   It also keeps them away from pornography and extremely violent
books and videos. Another teen-oriented shopping site,
www.ICanBuy.com, has controls that allow parents to choose the
storestheir children can shop at and approve each purchase before
the youngster completes the order.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson says DoughNet members usethe site to shop and invest on
their own. It includes investment tools that help kids budget the
money in their account.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do want to be smarter about spending money, since they
don't have that much of it.'' (The average DoughNet member has $115
in his or her account.)
</P>
<P>
   Walsh says the best approach is not to treat teenagers like some
exotic species to be suckered into shopping, but to treat them like
adult shoppers. ``These kids are mature and pragmatic,'' she says.
``Especially the boys. They will pay extra to get something without
a hassle. They want quality for as little money as possible. They
are willing to hunt for brands and convenience. ``
</P>
<P>
   ``The best model is Wal-Mart,'' Walsh says. ``It's on top of
teens' lists of brands they like and sites they visit. Yet Wal-Mart
is a clean site. You can just get in, shop and get out. All the
people trying to attract kids are doing exactly the wrong thing.
That's the irony. It's really just old wine in a new bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   Detail of www.icanbuy.com
</P>
<P>
   Sites in this article:
</P>
<P>
   www.doughnet.com
</P>
<P>
   www.icanbuy.com
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
