<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2683 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS09-TAKE     12-08 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS09-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take 1 of two takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that a VCR can be programmed for the year 2000
by setting it to another year when the days and dates were
identical. Do you have that information?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's considerable disagreement about this. A widely
reported item in the Old Farmer's Almanac 2000 says that this can
be accomplished by setting the VCR to 1972, when the days of the
week had the same dates as those in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   However, a spokesman for the Consumer Electronics Manufacturing
Association in Arlington, Va., calls this an urban myth. His advice
for concerned homeowners who enjoy programming their VCRs to tape
future programs is to test the VCR for the Y2K bug by setting the
date forward to Jan. 1, and trying to record a program. If there's
a problem, contact the manufacturer's Web site or toll-free number
for software fixes or to get information about the manufacturer's
product Y2K compliance.
</P>
<P>
   The least painful way to know whether a specific device of any
kind _ anything from a coffee marker to a personal computer _ is
Y2K complaint is to check with its manufacturer. This is especially
important in the case of any safety or mechanical device.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have an address where I can send to donation to Linda
Tripp's legal defense fund?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Baltimore office of Tripp attorney Joseph Murtha says
donations can be mailed to: Linda R. Tripp Legal Defense Fund, 626
Admiral Drive, Suite 319-A, Annapolis, MD 21401. Checks should be
made out to the Linda R. Tripp Legal Defense Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Q: At one time, I had some stationary with a quotation something
like this: ``In spite of everything, I believe that people are
really good at heart.'' It may have been from Anne Frank. Do you
know the full quotation?
</P>
<P>
   A: Anne Frank wrote this in her diary: ``Ideas, dreams and
cherished hopes rise within us, only to be shattered. Yet I keep
them; because in spite of everything, I still believe people are
good at heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: When was the pacemaker invented, and by whom?
</P>
<P>
   A: The year was 1952. Paul Zoll, a cardiologist at Beth Israel
Hospital in Boston, was seeking a way to aid cardiac patients
suffering from Stokes-Adams attacks, a breakdown of the heart's
ability to beat regularly. Zoll inserted a bare wire into the
recipient's heart to convey electrical pulses provided by an
external pulse generator. Since the generator had to be plugged
into an electrical outlet, the patient's mobility was severely
limited.
</P>
<P>
   The first battery-powered external pulse generator was developed
in 1958 by Earl Bakken, an electrical engineer, at the request of
C. Walton Lillehei, an open-heart surgeon at the University of
Minnesota Medical School. It was the size of a transistor radio and
operated on flashlight batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Q:A high school friend of mine, Tori Murden, of Louisville, Ky.,
is attempting to become the first woman and the first American to
row solo across the Atlantic Ocean. Can you update me on her
progress?
</P>
<P>
   A: Murden's 12-weeks-plus odyssey ended successfully Dec. 3,
when she reached Guadeloupe after her 3,000-mile trip from the
Canary Islands. Murden is a member of the Sector No Limits Team of
athletes dedicated to testing the outer limits of human endurance.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the background of Barbara Olson, the anti-Clinton
lawyer who wrote ``Hell to Pay: The Unfolding Story of Hillary
Rodham Clinton''?
</P>
<P>
   A: A former federal prosecutor, Olson served as the chief
investigative counsel of the House Committee on Government Reform
and Oversight, where she spearheaded the investigation of the
Clinton administration's White House travel office firings and,
according to her publisher, uncovered what became known as the
``Filegate'' scandal. She also has served as the principal
assistant general counsel and solicitor to the House.
</P>
<P>
   A regular on the TV talk show circuit, Olson, who is in private
law practice, serves as an ongoing legal analyst for MSNBC. She
lives in Great Falls, Va., outside Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Q: According to rumor mills, J. Edgar Hoover was a
cross-dresser. Has there ever been any firm evidence to back this
up?
</P>
<P>
   A: The New York Times delved into this subject in a lengthy
article in 1993 in the wake of the best-selling book ``Official and
Confidential'' by Anthony Summers. The book stated that Hoover had
been a transvestite. But as the Times reported, ``There is no solid
proof for the transvestism charges'' as alleged in Summers' book.
More recently (in June 1998), the Times printed an editor's note
saying that previously published assertions about Hoover being a
cross-dresser came from a single, uncorroborated source quoted in a
1993 book, ``and should not have been presented as fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: It seems as if people of every nationality and language say
``OK,'' and it's universally understood. What is its origin?
</P>
<P>
   A: According to the Morris Dictionary of Word and Phrase
Origins, there are a number of theories. As the dictionary states,
everyone from presidents to plumbers has a pet theory. Some
examples:
</P>
<P>
   Woodrow Wilson thought it was from the Choctaw Indian language
and should be spelled ``okeh.'' But he apparently convinced few
people to convert to this belief.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Walker Read, a Columbia University professor, theorized
that it originated as an abbreviation for the Old Kinderhook Club,
a political organization supporting James Van Buren for the
presidency in 1840.
</P>
<P>
   And Charles Berlitz, the linguist, said it might have come from
Aux Cayes, a port in Haiti famous for its superior rum. This theory
holds that American sailors were so enthusiastic about the rum that
Aux Cayes _ later ``OK'' _ became their expression for approval.
</P>
<P>
   One other theory is said to be the most popular: Andrew Jackson,
while a court clerk in Tennessee, marked O.K. on legal documents as
an abbreviation for the illiterate ``Orl Kerrect.'' But Jackson
never was a court clerk, and he certainly wasn't illiterate, the
dictionary notes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I frequently hear about ``hurricane hunters'' who fly into
the storms. Who are these people? What kind of aircraft do they
use?
</P>
<P>
   A: They are members of the 53rd Weather Reconnaissance Squadron
of the Air Force Reserve, based out of Keesler Air Force Base in
Biloxi, Miss. They fly Lockheed WC-130 aircraft into tropical
storms and hurricanes to gather meteorological data for the
National Hurricane Center.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
