<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take two of two.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I saw where the family of golfer Jack Nicklaus attended the
funeral of Winnie Palmer, wife of Arnold Palmer. We used to live
near her. I didn't know she was sick. Do you have any details?
</P>
<P>
   A: Winifred ``Winnie'' Palmer, 65, died Nov. 20 of peritoneal
cancer at her home in Unity, Pa. A report in The Pittsburgh
Post-Gazette said she was diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's obituary said she was a philanthropist who
served as a board member of the Latrobe (Pa.) Area Hospital
Charitable Foundation; the Orlando (Fla.) Regional Healthcare
System, which operates the Arnold Palmer Hospital for Children and
Women; Adams Memorial Library in Latrobe; and St. Vincent College
in Latrobe. She also was the designer of the Arnold Palmer
Furniture Collection.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Clark, chief executive officer of Latrobe Area Hospital,
said Mrs. Palmer ``quietly helped many people, and the only
stipulation was that a big deal wasn't made of it.'' Two weeks
before she died, Clark said, she asked him what she could do for
the hospital. ``The world has lost a very special person,'' Clark
added.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her husband, she is survived by two daughters,
seven grandchildren, and her brother.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read recently that President Clinton is using a hearing aid
in each ear. I'm considering doing the same. What brand and model
does he use?
</P>
<P>
   A: When this subject first came up in 1997, the White House
declined to identify the brand. And Clinton spokesman Steve Boyd
told Q&AMP;A that its position hasn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   Mona Thomas of the American Speech-Language Hearing Association
said the White House probably wasn't revealing the brand because,
when Ronald Reagan was president, there was some ``industry
fallout'' after details about his hearing aids were disclosed. The
obvious reason: competing manufacturers would cry foul. Thomas
recommends asking your audiologist's advice, because the type of
aid that works best for one person may not be recommended for
someone else.
</P>
<P>
   One thing we can tell you: The type of aid Clinton chose is
described as ``completely in-canal.'' The cone-shaped devices are
smaller than a dime and can be inserted and removed quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can we contact SEC Commissioner Roy Kramer to express our
opinion about the controversial officiating in the Georgia-Georgia
Tech football game?
</P>
<P>
   A: Regular mail, 2201 Civic Center Blvd., Birmingham, AL 35203;
e-mail, feedback(at)secsports.com; telephone, 205-458-3000.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I contact the Second Amendment Foundation, which
promotes the legality of private gun ownership?
</P>
<P>
   A: Call the organization at 1-800-426-4302. Or, online, check
its Web site _ www.saf.org _ and use the message format.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported that South African Archbishop Desmond Tutu
had released a statement saying it isn't unusual for prostate
cancer to return two years after radiation treatment. I've never
heard that before. Will you expand on this?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a misstatement of the facts, said Tutu's surgeon, Dr.
Harry Clarke Jr. of Emory University Hospital in Atlanta. There is
a failure rate for radiation therapy, he added, but it is ``not a
common occurrence'' and such therapy ``is very effective in most
cases.'' Tutu is a visiting theology professor at Emory, as well as
chair of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission in his home
country.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read with interest about the treatment of South African
Archbishop Desmond Tutu's recurrence of prostate cancer. What
procedure was used initially to treat him in 1997?
</P>
<P>
   A: Dr. Harry Clarke Jr. of Emory University Hospital in Atlanta
described it as ``full-course external beam radiation therapy'' at
Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Social Security is increasing the retirement age for
receiving full benefits from 65 to 67. Who initiated this?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was part of a package of proposals agreed upon in January
1983 by the bipartisan National Commission on Social Security
Reform. Raising the retirement age was approved on an amendment by
Rep. J.J. Pickle (D-Texas). The package was signed into law on
April 20, 1983, by President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Commission members were Robert Ball, former Social Security
commissioner; Robert Beck, board chairman and CEO of the Prudential
Insurance Co. of America; Rep. Barber Conable Jr. (R-N.Y.); Sen.
Bob Dole (R-Kan.); Mary Falvey Fuller, member of the 1979 Advisory
Council on Social Security; Alan Greenspan, former chairman of the
Council of Economic Advisers; Sen. John Heinz (R-Pa.); former Rep.
Martha Keys (D-Kan.); Lane Kirkland, president of the AFL-CIO; Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan (D-N .Y.); Rep. Claude Pepper (D-Fla.);
Alexander Trowbridge, president of the National Association of
Manufacturers and former secretary of commerce; Sen. William
Armstrong (R-Colo.); Rep. Bill Archer (R-Texas); and former Rep.
Joe Waggoner Jr. (D-La.).
</P>
<P>
   Q: What exactly will be the procedure for taking the 2000
Census? Will forms be mailed to us?
</P>
<P>
   A: People with a ``city-style address'' will receive the
questionnaire in the mail, said Bea Piddock of the Census Bureau.
Those without such an address will have it delivered to their home.
A letter advising that the questionnaire is on the way will precede
the actual questionnaire, she added. The timetable: ``about
mid-March.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: This summer, Major League Baseball announced that a Henry
Aaron award would be introduced. But I never heard anything more
about it. Did anyone win it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. This was the first year for the Hank Aaron Award, which
is awarded to the top hitters in each league. In the National
League, Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs was the winner; in the
American League, Manny Ramirez of the Cleveland Indians. The awards
were established in honor of the 25th anniversary of Aaron's
hitting his 715th career home run, breaking Babe Ruth's record.
</P>
<P>
   The award is given to the hitter in each league with the highest
combined total in three categories, home runs, runs batted in, and
hits. Sosa had 180 hits, 141 RBIs and 63 home runs this year;
Ramirez had 174 hits, 165 RBIs and 44 homers. Other criteria, such
as batting average and slugging percentage, may be added in future
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want this award to be to hitters what the Cy Young is to
pitchers,'' Aaron said when the winners were announced Oct. 27.
``This is strictly for hitters. Everybody has had an award but the
hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has Chelsea Clinton dropped out of college? She was in the
news traveling overseas recently with President and Mrs. Clinton at
a time when colleges students were not on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   A: A spokeswoman at the first lady's press office said
information about Chelsea Clinton normally isn't given out, but she
confirmed that the first daughter is still enrolled at Stanford
University.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that Quentin Crisp died recently. We have always
enjoyed his tapes and TV appearances. Do you have any information
about his last few years?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 90-year-old actor, writer and gay activist died Nov. 21
in Manchester, England. Crisp, who was born in England on Christmas
Day 1908, didn't become widely known until 1968, when he published
his autobiography, ``The Naked Civil Servant.'' It later was made
into a TV play starring John Hurt. After that, Crisp moved to New
York and appeared in such films as ``Orlando,'' playing Queen
Elizabeth I, and Sting's video ``Englishman in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Crisp was in Atlanta in July for performances of ``An Evening
With Quentin Crisp.'' Most recently, he was in the news not for
anything he did himself, but for being the subject of a new one-man
play in London based on his writings. A review of Bush Theatre's
``Resident Alien'' in the Nov. 15 Times of London heaped praise on
the production, especially Bette Bourne as Crisp. The play is
scheduled to close its run on Dec. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find the names, addresses, telephone numbers and
e-mail addresses of members of Congress?
</P>
<P>
   A: Among the possibilities: Call Project Vote Smart's voters'
research hotline, 1-800-622-7627; or try www.visi.com/juan/congress
or www.vote-smart.org/congresstrack/contact or www.capweb.net if
you're online.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the standoff several years ago between federal agents and
Randy Weaver at Ruby Ridge, Idaho, Weaver's 14-year-old son was
fatally shot. Was it ever determined who fired the shot?
</P>
<P>
   A: After nearly four years of investigation, Boundary County,
Idaho, authorities in May 1996 said they found the bullet that
killed Sam Weaver. At first, federal agents speculated that the
teen was shot accidentally by his father or by family friend Kevin
Harris during a flurry of gunfire in August 1992. The shootout
occurred while a team of agents was attempting to arrest Randy
Weaver for failing to appear in federal court on an illegal weapons
charge.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1997, Boundary County Sheriff Greg Sprungl said
evidence showed that the boy was killed by a bullet fired from U.S.
Marshal Larry Cooper's 9 mm Colt. ``It is our opinion that Cooper
fired into a brushy area because he was trying to get to his buddy
who had just been shot and was dying,'' Sprungl said. Cooper's
buddy was Deputy Marshal William Degan, who also died in the
shootout. In testimony before the U.S. Senate Judiciary
subcommittee on terrorism in 1995, Cooper flatly denied that he
fired at young Weaver.
</P>
<P>
   Without admitting wrongdoing, the government later agreed to pay
Randy Weaver and his surviving children $3.1 million for the deaths
of his wife, Vicki, and son. Boundary County prosecutor Denise
Woodbury has said that, even if the marshals killed Sam Weaver,
they were acting in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   (ENDIT.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
