r d BC-FOOD-CENTTIMELINE09-C     12-08 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CENTTIMELINE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From fast-food burgers to health-store sprouts
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _
</P>
<P>
   1950
</P>
<P>
   _ Shoppers can now buy chicken in ``parts,'' but they
overwhelmingly opt for whole birds instead.
</P>
<P>
   _ Soldiers returning from the war want foreign foods such as
sukiyaki and coq au vin _ dishes they enjoyed abroad.
</P>
<P>
   1953
</P>
<P>
   _ McDonald brothers allow the first franchise of their burger
joint to open in Phoenix, Ariz. Ray Kroc takes over the company in
1954.
</P>
<P>
   1954
</P>
<P>
   _ Swanson introduces frozen (TV) dinners.
</P>
<P>
   _ A California cook blends Lipton Onion Soup Mix with sour
cream, serves it with potato chips, and California Dip takes off.
</P>
<P>
   1955
</P>
<P>
   _ The country goes crazy for Mamie Eisenhower's Million Dollar
Fudge recipe.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tappan introduces home-sized microwaves in department stores.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pizza becomes a staple of American teens.
</P>
<P>
   1956
</P>
<P>
   _ Portable charcoal grills are marketed to homeowners; patio
grill parties are the rage.
</P>
<P>
   _ The USDA reduces the seven food groups to four; fat is
eliminated as one of them.
</P>
<P>
   _ James Beard opens a cooking school in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   1957
</P>
<P>
   _ Saccharin sold as Sweet 'n Low.
</P>
<P>
   1958
</P>
<P>
   _ The FDA bans the use of known carcinogens in foods.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alaska becomes a state; baked Alaska is the dessert of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   1959
</P>
<P>
   _ Reuben Mattus introduces Haagen-Daz; it's a made-up name for
an ultra-rich ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hawaii become the 50th state, and backyard luaus become the
rage, complete with tiki torches and pineapple-topped burgers.
</P>
<P>
   1960
</P>
<P>
   _ A health-food craze begins; yogurt goes mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   _ DuPont introduces Teflon pans to homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   _ Salton's Hot Tray became the hot appliance of the decade for
buffets and progressive dinner parties.
</P>
<P>
   1962
</P>
<P>
   _ Julia Child is ensconced in American cookery via ``The French
Chef.'' She's neither French nor a chef, but brings classic haute
cuisine to American tables.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sprouts, and ``Berkeley'' health food become part of the new
food landscape.
</P>
<P>
   1963
</P>
<P>
   _ Weight Watchers is founded.
</P>
<P>
   _ GE sells a self-cleaning oven.
</P>
<P>
   1964
</P>
<P>
   _ Nachos introduced at Texas State Fair.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buffalo chicken wings introduced at Anchor Bar, Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   1965
</P>
<P>
   _ Gatorade is hatched at the University of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tang, taken by astronauts into outer space, is on earthly
breakfast tables.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pillsbury introduces the Doughboy as its mascot.
</P>
<P>
   1966
</P>
<P>
   _ A tunnel of fudge cake wins Pillsbury's Bake-Off, creating a
market for the Bundt pan.
</P>
<P>
   1968
</P>
<P>
   _ Keebler tells kids their cookies are baked by elves.
</P>
<P>
   _ Can you say fondue? Dipping cheese is a party rage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Communes bring about a ``back-to-nature'' movement; granola,
``gorp'' and trail mix are the new snack foods.
</P>
<P>
   1970
</P>
<P>
   _ Bagels come out of New York and go mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   1971
</P>
<P>
   _ Crockpots introduced to America; they're the best seller in
the '70s appliance wars.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alice Waters, a Berkeley, Calif., chef, begins a movement
among professional chefs to use seasonal and regional foods,
creating an entire cottage industry for boutique foods.
</P>
<P>
   _ First salad bar spotted at RJ Grunts in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   _ Starbuck's opens its first store in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   1973
</P>
<P>
   _ French chefs take up a new mantra: Nouvelle cuisine. Heavy,
classical cooking is turned upside down.
</P>
<P>
   _ The food processor is unveiled at the Chicago housewares show.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
