<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2691 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-DOGGIE-BAGS09-COX     12-08 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOGGIE-BAGS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You CAN take it with you
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kate Rawlings sputtered out halfway through her
expensive restaurant meal _ a ribeye steak on a mound of mashed
potatoes that could upend the Flintstones' car.
</P>
<P>
   So she asked the waitress for a doggie bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from a Depression-era family,'' said the 41-year-old
banker. ``I always take it home with me.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, real live doggies are lucky to get so much as a bone
from their owners' restaurant entrees. Most diners, like Rawlings,
turn their leftovers into a second meal for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, nearly two-thirds of Americans take their leftovers
home, and nearly all these people eat the food, according to a
survey commissioned by American Demographics magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``People get two meals for the price of one,'' says restaurateur
Karen Hilliard of Georgia Grille. Although Hilliard tries to keep
her portions reasonable, she says diners often fill up on
appetizers and homemade bread. ``By the time the entrees come they
may not be hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   But many restaurants, eager to lure value-conscious consumers,
pile it on. If they don't, somebody else will.
</P>
<P>
   ``Restaurants have figured out that the difference between 6
ounces of pasta on the plate and a pound-and-a-half of pasta is not
a lot of money,'' says John Imbergamo, president of the Imbergamo
Group, a restaurant consulting firm in Denver. ``These big-portion
restaurants are not running higher-than-normal food costs. And they
can really blow people away and put a strong value message into
their minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants that make their names with large portions _ the
Cheesecake Factory, Maggiano's Little Italy _ fill out the plates
with ``nonprotein-based menu items like pasta, mashed potatoes or
rice,'' Imbergamo says. ``Truthfully, does anybody really go to the
Cheesecake Factory because of the quality of the food? They go
because of the quantity.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it may be satisfying to receive so much food, the result
may not be good for you. Chris Rosenbloom, associate professor of
nutrition at Georgia State University, notes that portions often
wildly exceed the standard amounts that are necessary to provide
the fuel our bodies need: a half cup of vegetables, a piece of meat
the size of a deck of cards, a serving of pasta the size of your
fist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that hasn't been downsized in America is
restaurant portion sizes,'' he says. ``There's so much competition
for the dining dollar, so Americans have come to expect huge
portions and all the extras _ the bottomless pit salad bowl, the
free soft drink refills, the constantly replenished bread basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Craig, vice president of Weight Watchers International,
counsels dieters to notice the discrepancy between a restaurant
portion and a proper serving the moment it appears and ask for the
doggie bag immediately. ``You can often just split something in
half. It's almost easier to do when you first start.''
</P>
<P>
   And that may be all the easier to do thanks to a minitrend:
fancy bags that make the practice somehow seem more chic.
</P>
<P>
   At the Georgia Grille, Hilliard says the staff dresses up doggie
bags to make them more appetizing. If a dish comes with pretty
sauce squiggles on the plate, the leftovers come with pretty sauce
squiggles in the box.
</P>
<P>
   At Nona's Italian Kitchen in Buckhead, the staff takes the
packaging a step further. The remainders are fitted in properly
sized containers by the staff, outfitted with fresh bread and oil,
placed in a paper shopping bag and secured with a raffia bow. It
ends up looking more like a splurge from a Phipps Plaza boutique
than a box of leftover noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Nona's co-owner Justin Perlino says that he and his partners put
a lot of thought into this lavish look. ``We thought about it
before we opened. People (often package food-to-go) poorly. You get
your doggie bag in a cheap to-go container that leaks inside a bag
that rips. It ends up on the front seat of your car. We package it
so that people can re-create the experience of eating at Nona's at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there's an array of new bags and boxes: the black
plastic octagon with the convenient see-through lid, the sturdy and
oven-safe foil round, the clear plastic pint and quart deli tubs.
It makes sense. With so many containers in the fridge, you want to
easily distinguish the chocolate mousse from the pappardelle
Bolognese.
</P>
<P>
   Still, other restaurants such as Watershed and Floataway Cafe
prefer the natural look of heavy cardboard boxes. Floataway seals
the container with a sticker that reads, ``Woof, Woof ... I'm a
Doggy Box!''
</P>
<P>
   Not only are people asking for to-go containers at every
possible restaurant, they're also asking for them at private
functions.
</P>
<P>
   Good Housekeeping magazine etiquette expert Peggy Post was asked
recently about the appropriateness of taking food home from a
wedding. It seems that guests enjoyed such a long cocktail hour
that they couldn't finish their entrees and asked to have them
boxed up.
</P>
<P>
   Post responded, ``Taking food home from a wedding reception
isn't in keeping with the dignity and elegance of the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone hates to see leftovers _ and so many leftovers _ go
to waste.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
