</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOGGIEBAG-SAFE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keep your leftovers safe
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With all these doggie bags changing hands, there's
reason to worry about potential food safety risks.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Rosenbloom, associate professor of nutrition at Georgia
State University, recommends keeping leftovers no more than two or
three days in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   The doggie bag should also get into the fridge _ or into the
doggie, for that matter _ quickly. The United States Department of
Agriculture says perishable food should not be kept at room
temperature longer than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to a movie afterward,'' Rosenbloom says, ``you
can forget the doggie bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
