<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2693 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-EATWITH-KIDS09-COX     12-08 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EATWITH-KIDS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking kids out to eat doesn't have to leave bad taste in
parents' mouths
 &HT;    By Stephen J. O'Brien
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Before the four Curran kids ever step foot into a
fast-food joint or any other eating establishment, their parents
read them the restaurant-behavior act.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get a standardized lecture about how they're supposed to
act,'' their mom, Colleen, said as she escorted the youngsters into
Fazoli's restaurant in Waco one recent weekday. ``And we tell them
if they misbehave, we won't go out again.''
</P>
<P>
   The rules 11-year-old Rourke, 10-year-old Amanda, 7-year-old
Creed, and 2-year-old Megan are supposed to follow seem simple
enough: Watch your language. The food belongs on your plate or in
your mouth, not in the air. No discussion of bodily functions.
Don't bother other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes with a lot of work,'' their father, Troy, said.
``Even though we set down rules, we still have to address things
during the meal. Sometimes it's just whatever they're doing at that
moment that we have to say, 'You need to stop.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Curran kids usually do. Minus a messy face or two, some
high-pitched giggles and miniature appetites, the Curran table
wasn't much different than any other at Fazoli's.
</P>
<P>
   However, some etiquette experts would suggest the Currans are
the exception these days, not the rule.
</P>
<P>
   In today's fast-paced world, the art of parents teaching their
children manners and politeness at the dinner table has been lost,
some say.
</P>
<P>
   How kids behave in fast-food establishments and other
restaurants may not seem like the most pressing social issue in
America today, but restaurant-industry experts say the trend toward
eating out means more and more Americans _ both young and old _
will be sharing the same eating space in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
   That puts etiquette for all age groups at a premium.
</P>
<P>
   National Restaurant Association statistics suggest overall sales
will jump by 4.6 percent for the industry this year, a
$16.2-million increase over 1998 to $354 million. Most economists
and restaurant experts credit the increase to a strong economy
coupled with an explosion in the number of eateries available to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Many restaurants are developing specialty plates for kids that
come with prizes and toys to ensure the youngsters have a good time
along with the parents. More formal restaurants have even begun
developing cuisine, usually of the simpler, fried chicken variety,
aimed at the youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time as they try to satisfy cravings for food with
a bit more bite, some family restaurants are putting new emphasis
on kids,'' Gregg Cobrzynski said in the March issue of Nation's
Restaurant News, a publication of the National Restaurant
Association.
</P>
<P>
   At Miller's Texas Style Steaks in Waco, the menu includes
succulent sirloins, tender T-bones and, of course, french fries and
chicken nuggets for the kids. Owner Brenda Miller said the slew of
child dinners available for $3.95 means plenty of parents show up
with their youngsters for sit-down dinners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a family restaurant,'' Miller said. ``A lot of parents
bring their kids in on Friday nights and they all seem to enjoy the
food and atmosphere. The kids behave fine.''
</P>
<P>
   For those parents who are having trouble keeping the troops in
line, etiquette experts have a few hints.
</P>
<P>
   One thing they suggest is that every family have a dinner table
where, at least once or twice a week, the entire family sits down
to a meal. The television, computer, stereo and video games should
be turned off. Set down specific rules: close your mouth when you
chew, come to the table clean, no shouting, let other people talk.
Don't complain about the food _ whether you like it or not. Say
``please'' and ``thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Children should be taught to offer their seats to older people.
They should be told never to push forward in line at a restaurant
or in any other situation. Making fun of a brother or sister at the
table should not be acceptable. And, lastly, kids should eat with
forks and knives.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the youngsters used to following basic rules at home
should make it easier when going public, according to Daisy
Eyebright, author of ``A Manuel of Etiquette.'' ``Those who have
been accustomed to politeness and (good manners) at home are at
their ease in the most polished circles and do not suffer from the
confusion and embarrassment which are almost sure to follow any
lapse of rules of etiquette,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
