<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2694 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-CENTURY09-COX     12-08 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CENTURY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    International flavors, convenience shape tastes in '50s through
'70s
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ From the birth of fast food in the '50s,
to the cholesterol-conscious '70s, the American food pendulum swung
wide in the third quarter of this century.
</P>
<P>
   We left the dining room behind as we ate frozen dinners in front
of the TV, char-grilled steaks in the back yard, and scarfed down
burgers in our cars.
</P>
<P>
   Americans were ready to celebrate the return of their servicemen
by partying and spending the money that had been so tight.
</P>
<P>
   Tract housing, built to accommodate the thousands of GI-Bill
home buyers, created suburban neighborhoods full of young families.
The baby boom exploded.
</P>
<P>
   The houses featured kitchens with built-in refrigerators and
stoves, and in many cases, an electric dishwasher _
color-coordinated at last. Women gave Tupperware parties. Backyard
patios provided a place to put Dad's new charcoal grill. Dinner
parties for neighbors were informal, and hostesses traded theme
ideas, often tropical. Progressive dinners, where each course was
served in a different home, were a suburban invention.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, steel production returned to auto plants, gas was no
longer rationed, and the country was driving again. Road food
turned into drive-in food. Burger joints, where youthful waitresses
roller-skated up to the driver to take an order, were commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Kroc took over an assembly-line type eatery in 1954 and
McDonald's burgers were soon selling for 15 cents each around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Other chains followed: White Castle in the Midwest and Burger
King in Miami were two that branched across the nation. A
self-named colonel in Kentucky had people everywhere licking their
fingers over his fried chicken. A diner owner in California saw the
potential in roadside eateries that were open all night, and
Denny's was soon part of the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   On TV, Ed Sullivan shook his head and Elvis shook his pelvis,
while cooks shook Good Seasons salad dressing in glass cruets _ as
recommended on the Kraft Family Hour commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Television had become the pervasive medium. It would change the
foods we ate, and where we ate them. The family dinner hour, once
an institution, began a decline when families stopped talking to
watch ``the tube'' while eating. It would never recover.
</P>
<P>
   Slick food marketing began its ascent. A product could become an
overnight success with the right program placement or celebrity
pitchman. Twinkies was tied in with Howdy Doody throughout the
'50s, and became a staple of lunchboxes for both kids and adults.
</P>
<P>
   Casseroles were the Mom-food of the day. They were portable and
easily served on the buffet _ the new form of party service. Ground
meat was the convenience food of the '50s and for a couple of
decades to come. It was used in meat loaves, chili and that new
sandwich kids were talking about from the school cafeteria _ Sloppy
Joes.
</P>
<P>
   In the '50s, international flavors began to displace
``American'' foods. The servicemen on tour abroad had experienced
Italian pastas and wines, French stews and crusty breads and
Japanese sukiyaki and sake. They requested it in restaurants.
Chinese and Italian restaurants moved out of their ethnic
neighborhoods and joined suburbia.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the decade, Alaska and Hawaii were added as states
and we celebrated with Baked Alaska, a conundrum of a dessert, and
exotic tropical fruit cocktails served with pineapple-topped
burgers.
</P>
<P>
   Americans embraced the space race with fervor. Some bright
marketing exec saw potential in the moon men, and sent Tang around
the Earth in a sipping bag. The orange powder appeared on breakfast
tables around the world immediately afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The '60s found Julia Child making her mark as the matriarch of
everyday gourmet cooking with her TV show, ``The French Chef.''
Classic techniques that taught good cooking as an art form were
novel in America. Wine appreciation increased; roast chicken sales
soared once Julia trilled the recipe for coq au vin. Later in the
decade, Graham Kerr would gallop into TV cooking, and Jeff Smith
would bring frugality to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Parties continued, with hostesses trying to outdo one another in
the kitchen. Cooking magazines such as Sphere, Gourmet and Bon
Appetit satisfied urban cooks with new, trendy recipes and touted
must-have appliances, cookware and tools. The microwave was the
technological wonder of this decade, with predictions it would soon
displace conventional ovens. A convenience movement took hold as
cooks demanded more time away from their chores.
</P>
<P>
   But a political movement was starting to rock the country _
segregation, the Cold War and nuclear threats were a stark contrast
to life in the TV households where mom cooked in pearls and high
heels.
</P>
<P>
   Teens, who rebelled against a rigid, conservative society, found
promise in a youthful president. His sophisticated wife set off new
waves of international cooking when she hired a French chef for the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   The young people rejected the excesses of their parents,
including the haute cuisine. Rustic foods came of age. People
flocked to communes, where they went to ``live off the land'' a la
Euell Gibbons, who, in his book, ``Stalking the Wild Asparagus,''
promoted foraging for wild plants and berries.
</P>
<P>
   Hippies were eating bean sprouts and ``sun'' burgers made with
tofu. They waved copies of Rachel Carson's ``Silent Spring,'' which
touched off an environmental war over pesticide use on crops.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetarianism spilled over into the mainstream. Yogurt sales
jumped; bean sprouting jars were sold in supermarkets, and meatless
lasagna appeared on nights other than Friday. Bakers went to
natural food stores to get freshly ground wheat for their wheat
berry breads.
</P>
<P>
   While Aretha Franklin belted out R-E-S-P-E-C-T! ``soul food''
was gaining respect in American cuisine. Okra, sweet potatoes and
black-eyed peas were suddenly fashionable outside the South.
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock cemented the youth movement as the war in Vietnam
raged, and catapulted us into the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   A new reason for health foods came from the government:
Carcinogens in foods were scrutinized by the FDA, which banned
cyclamate, a binder used in saccharin products. Artificial
sweeteners in general came under fire; so did grilling over
charcoal. A study of heart patients linked salt to hypertension,
which in turn was linked to heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   But cheese was still good for you, and we ate tons of it at the
trendy wine-and-cheese affairs, and we dipped French bread squares
into the melted goo in fondue pots at every dinner party.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants became ``fern bars,'' so named for their hanging
plants. The salad bar was another '70s phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Italian food and restaurants serving anything with a red sauce
blossomed after ``The Godfather'' turned all things Sicilian into a
national obsession. A small but steady trend toward Mexican food
was on its heels; do-it-yourself taco kits hit supermarket shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, a national preoccupation with food, chefs and cooking
was forming. It would take off in the last quarter of the decade,
making fortunes for restaurateurs and chefs, and bringing
professional cooking techniques into the home.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
