<HEADER>
A2695 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-LATKES09-COX     12-08 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-LATKES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Latkes the healthy way
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Light, crispy latkes (potato pancakes)
are a traditional food at Hanukkah. Typically fried in oil, they
are representative of the story of a miracle in the Jewish
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   According to the story, pagans had extinguished the sacred
menorah in the temple and during a rededication, only one day's
worth of oil could be found to light it. Miraculously, the oil
burned for eight days instead. The eight days of Hanukkah
commemorate the miracle.
</P>
<P>
   For many diners who are on restricted diets or allergic to
certain foods, latkes are a problem. Here we offer alternatives to
the usual potato-egg-flour mixture that most cooks rely on.
</P>
<P>
   Eggs and wheat flour can cause food allergies for many people,
but it's not hard to get around those ingredients with
substitutions.
</P>
<P>
   For those on a low-fat diet, baking the latkes in the oven is a
solution, and using only egg whites in the binding and eliminating
the flour makes them diet-friendly, too.
</P>
<P>
   A select few are allergic to the potatoes themselves; sweet
potatoes are one solution, but hard squashes and even cheese can be
substituted with success. These are so tasty that cooks looking for
something different may want to feature them at the next Hanukkah
buffet.
</P>
<P>
   The following are recipes for nontraditional latkes.
</P>
<P>
   SWEET POTATO LATKES
</P>
<P>
   4large sweet potatoes, unpeeled, washed
</P>
<P>
   2egg whites, beaten until foamy
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Oil for frying
</P>
<P>
   On large holes of grater, or with slaw shredder, shred the sweet
potatoes. Mix, in a medium bowl, with salt and egg whites.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil to depth of 1/2 inch in heavy skillet over medium heat.
When oil is ready, form a small patty from the potatoes and drop
into the oil. Flatten slightly with back of spatula. Fry until
potato is brown, about 3 minutes; turn and brown other side. Repeat
with remaining batter.
</P>
<P>
   Drain on paper towels and keep warm in an oven.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with a cinnamon-flavored applesauce.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 12 latkes
</P>
<P>
   For dieters on a low-fat diet, the following will work well.
It's also a good recipe for those following the low-carbohydrate
diets.
</P>
<P>
   NONFAT RICOTTA LATKES
</P>
<P>
   115- or 16-ounce container non-fat ricotta cheese
</P>
<P>
   1cup egg substitute
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable spray for frying
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor fitted with a steel blade (or in a blender
in batches if necessary), process the ricotta cheese, egg
substitute, sugar and vanilla extract. Add flour and process until
batter is very smooth. Scape down sides of container a few times
during processing. (Batter will be thinner than most pancake
batters.)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat nonstick skillet over medium heat. Lightly spray with
vegetable spray. For each latke, spoon a 1 1/2- to 2 tablespoon
measure of batter into the greased skillet. Batter will spread to
form a 3-inch circle.
</P>
<P>
   Cook for about 3 minutes, or until a few bubbles appear on the
surface, and the tops are beginning to look dry. (Note: The latkes
will not rise at all.) Turn at once. Cook the latkes briefly on the
second side just until they are golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat with remaining batter. Serve warm with nonfat yogurt,
fresh fruit or topping of your choice.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 24 medium latkes.
</P>
<P>
   (Adapted from the ``New Jewish Holiday Cookbook'' by Gloria
Kaufer Greene, 1999, Times Books, $27.50)
</P>
<P>
   This oven-baked version of the latke, done in a muffin cup, also
saves on fat. For those who cannot tolerate wheat, it's also
flour-free.
</P>
<P>
   POTATO LATKE MUFFINS
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons plus 1/2 teaspoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2medium onions, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon paprika, plus a bit more for sprinkling
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4pounds baking potatoes, peeled
</P>
<P>
   2large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups applesauce (optional) for serving
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Heat 1 tablespoon plus 1/2 teaspoon
vegetable oil in a heavy nonstick skillet. Add onions and saute
over medium-low heat until softened. If pan becomes dry, add 1/2
tablespoon water. Add 1 teaspoon paprika, stir to blend and remove
from heat. Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Coarsely grate the potatoes. Put grated potatoes in a large
strainer and squeeze out excess liquid. Transfer potatoes to a
bowl. Add sauteed onions, eggs, salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Oil a nonstick 12-muffin pan, making sure to oil edges of bases.
Using a 1/3 cup measure, add scant measureful of potato mixture to
each muffin cup. Smooth tops lightly. Spoon 1/4 teaspoon oil over
each, and sprinkle with paprika. Bake about 45 minutes or until
brown at edges, and firm.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from oven and run spatula around edges of muffin cups to
release muffins. You can them leave them in the pan 15 to 30
minutes to keep them warm. Serve hot, accompanied by applesauce if
desired.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 muffins, or 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe from ``The Low-Fat Jewish Cookbook'' by Faye Levy, 1997,
Potter Books, $24.95.)
</P>
<P>
   This recipe uses a variety of root vegetables and eliminates
white potatoes. They're still fried, however.
</P>
<P>
   ROOT VEGETABLE LATKES
</P>
<P>
   1cup shredded carrot
</P>
<P>
   1cup shredded celeriac (celery root)
</P>
<P>
   1cup shredded parnsip
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup shredded leek (1 medium, trimmed and rinsed)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4cups shredded beets, rinsed and drained well
</P>
<P>
   2cups shredded boniato (Cuban sweet potato)
</P>
<P>
   2large eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup matzo meal
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon cracked black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil for frying
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl combine carrots, celeriac, parsnip, leek, beets
and boniato. Add eggs, matzo meal, salt and pepper; mix well.
</P>
<P>
   In a large heavy or cast-iron skillet, over medium heat, heat
vegetable oil. It should be about 1 inch deep.
</P>
<P>
   Form 1/4 cup vegetable mixture into patties and gently slide
into oil. Let cook for 6 to 8 minutes or until golden on one side.
Flip pancakes and continue cooking for 6 to 8 minutes or until
golden. Drain on paper towels or paper bags and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 18 pancakes.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Any hard vegetable, such as the hard squashes, could be
used in this recipe. Experiment to your own tastes.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe adapted from ``Jewish Holiday Style'' by Rita Milos
Brownstein, Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1999, $27.50.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
