<HEADER>
A2697 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-MING-TSAI09-COX     12-08 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-MING-TSAI09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Food Network personality has cooked up impressive career
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ He has fond and vivid memories of rolling
thousands of egg rolls on the ping-pong table of his Kettering home
for Dayton's annual World A'fair event.
</P>
<P>
   ``One year there was a power outage and we rolled them by
candlelight,'' says Ming Tsai, who is calling from the car on his
way to a book signing in Los Angeles. ``I love that international
festival.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Daytonian-area resident is still rolling in dough,
but these days we're not just talking egg rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Ming, who hosts the popular ``East Meets West With Ming Tsai''
on the Food Network _ the cable channel boasts 42 million viewers _
has become one of America's top celebrity chefs. He was profiled in
The New Yorker in November and is a regular contributor to CBS's
new Early Show with Bryant Gumbel and Jane Clayson.
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual for the Emmy Award-winning show host to receive
2,000
</P>
<P>
   e-mails a week from fans.
</P>
<P>
   He also runs Blue Ginger, a Wellesley, Mass., restaurant that
was named ``Best New Restaurant'' by Boston Magazine, and has just
authored his first cookbook, Blue Ginger: East Meets West Cooking
with Ming Tsai (Clarkson Potter, $32.50).
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Esquire's John Mariana labeled him ``the foremost
interpreter of East-West cuisine today.'' Ming describes his
cooking as a happy mingling of Chinese, Southeast Asian, Japanese,
French and American culinary traditions.
</P>
<P>
   If you watch him on TV, you'll hear frequent references to his
growing-up days in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great place to grow up,'' he says, ``but there was
not a lot of great Chinese food.''
</P>
<P>
   His mom, Iris Tsai, attempted to remedy that by offering Chinese
cooking classes and opening the Mandarin Kitchen in the Arcade
downtown. (She sold the business about 10 years ago and she and
husband Stephen, a chief scientist at Wright-Patterson Air Force
Base, have moved to Newport Beach, Calif.)
</P>
<P>
   Their son attended elementary school in Kettering and the Miami
Valley School in Washington Twp. before transferring to prep school
(Andover) in his sophomore year. From there, he studied mechanical
engineering at Yale University (his dad and grandfather both went
there), then eventually decided to switch to cooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in my family cooks,'' Ming says. ``My dad, my
grandparents, everyone except my brother.''
</P>
<P>
   His first cooking endeavor, at age 5, was a Duncan Hines cake
mix. By 8, he says he was attempting fried rice, noting, ``Maybe
it's because I was always hungry as a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   In his teens, he'd come home from school and work in his
mother's restaurant _ as chef, as manager. ``We also did a lot of
catering and all the festivals and affairs on the (Courthouse)
Square. It was a great way to make a little cash and spend time
with the family.''
</P>
<P>
   His favorite Dayton cuisine? ``Skyline Chili and Slyders at
White Castle.''
</P>
<P>
   Tsai studied at the prestigious Cordon Bleu in Paris, earned a
master's degree in hotel administration and hospitality marketing
at Cornell and by 1992 was working as a chef _ first in San
Francisco, later in Palo Alto, Calif., and Sante Fe, N.M. He moved
to the Boston area in 1998 and now lives in Needham with his wife
Polly (Talbott), also from Dayton. (The two were introduced by
Polly's brother _ Ming's squash coach at Yale _ because she had
studied Chinese in college.)
</P>
<P>
   Tsai typically heads for New York every three months, where he
tapes two weeks of shows for the Food Network. ``The taping is a
hoot. It's easy because 30 people work on the show and everyone is
working to help.''
</P>
<P>
   What's not so easy, he admits, is coming up with 180 recipes for
90 shows each year.
</P>
<P>
   He does his research with a lot of magazine and cookbook
reading, going to dives and ethnic restaurants. ``There's no such
thing as plagiarism in the chef world.''
</P>
<P>
   Ming believes Americans have more sophisticated palettes these
days because of technology and travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some research shows that people are going to restaurants more
often; some shows they're spending a lot on home kitchens. Food has
become a priority.''
</P>
<P>
   He says his goal is to demystify Asian techniques and
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that you don't bring in all these Asian spices
till you understand how they are traditionally used,'' he cautions.
</P>
<P>
   Take sesame oil, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Chinese cooking, you tend to use a tablespoon for 1 or 2
quarts of chicken stock. But see some cooks discover it and drizzle
it all over salad like it was olive oil and it completely ruins the
taste and the dish!''
</P>
<P>
   Ming says only about 10 percent of those who watch the Food
Network actually cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like CNN, people have it on and there's a comfort
level because everyone eats, it's part of daily life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ming says at least two rewarding things have come out of his
career: ``Even though I hope I don't look like Barney, kids love to
watch the show and I love kids. And a lot of culinary students have
told me that I'm the reason they went to culinary school.''
</P>
<P>
   As for being a celebrity, Ming maintains he's not recognized in
cities _ like his current hometown of Boston _ where the Food
Network isn't broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of being a celeb in cities where he is known?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can always get a table at restaurants,'' he says. ``That's
more important than the money or fame!''
</P>
<P>
   Meredith Moss writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: meredithmoss(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
