<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2699 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-ASK-A-DIETITIAN09-COX     12-08 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASK-A-DIETITIAN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Calories aren't only alcohol worry
 &HT;    By Karen Collins, M.S., R.D.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What's the best way to cut down on the calories I'm getting
from alcohol?
</P>
<P>
   A: The alcoholic drinks highest in calories are mixed drinks
made with cola, lemon-lime soda, or sweet mixes such as Tom Collins
or whiskey sour. Lowest-calorie choices are table wines, followed
by light beer or 80-proof liquor mixed with water or club soda.
</P>
<P>
   But calorie content is not the only problem with alcohol _
drinking too much seems to increase risk of many cancers of the
digestive system as well as breast cancer. Safe levels of alcohol
consist of no more than one standard-size drink per day for women,
and no more than two standard drinks per day for men. No matter
what you drink, by drinking more slowly to limit the amount, you
save calories and promote your total health.
</P>
<P>
   Juices and regular soda are some alternatives to alcohol, but
the 150 calories in each 12-ounce glass add up quickly. Consider
lower-calorie nonalcoholic choices such as club soda, tomato juice
(or nonalcoholic Bloody Marys), sparkling water or iced tea, if
available.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If I keep my calories low enough, can I lose weight without
exercise? I'm a born couch potato!
</P>
<P>
   A: It's definitely possible for most people to lose weight
without exercise by using low-calorie diets. The real question is
what the long-term results would be.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that without exercise, about a quarter of
weight loss can be muscle. Since muscle is the tissue that bums the
most calories, that means that you would not be able to eat as much
and maintain your new weight as someone of the same weight but with
more muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Many studies show physical activity as one of the best
predictors of who can maintain a lower weight.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, regular physical activity of some sort can help lower
your risk of heart disease, osteoporosis, and several forms of
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there are other ways to get some exercise without turning
to whatever form of activity you've tried in the past. Aim for a
slow, gradual start. Is there a pretty place you could enjoy
walking? What about beginner sports or dance lessons?
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere there is surely an activity that you would enjoy doing
to help keep you fit and healthy _ try to find at least one.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What supplements are the best antioxidants?
</P>
<P>
   A: Antioxidants are receiving a lot of attention because they
may play an important role in preventing cancer and other diseases
by destroying highly reactive substances called free radicals that
form in our bodies and damage our cells. Scientists have discovered
that vitamins C and E, beta carotene and its many carotenoid
cousins, the mineral selenium, and a host of phytochemicals all can
act as antioxidants, but don't let supplement advertisements
convince you that the best types and amounts have been pinpointed.
We have a lot more to learn before we can get that specific.
</P>
<P>
   What we do know, however, is that a plant-based diet _ a diet
centered around lots of vegetables, fruits and whole grains _
supplies the antioxidants and whatever other substances may be
important to effectively lower risk of cancer and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Ask a Dietitian questions were answered by Karen Collins, M.S.,
R.D. of the American Institute for Cancer Research. This column
originally ran in The Austin American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
