of the easiest gifts to purchase. (Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-LATKES _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Light, crispy latkes
(potato pancakes) are a traditional food at Hanukkah. Typically
fried in oil, they are representative of the story of a miracle in
the Jewish tradition. The story goes thatAccording to the story,
pagans had extinguished the sacred menorah in the temple and during
a rededication, only one day's worth of oil could be found to light
it. Miraculously, the oil burned for eight days instead. The eight
days of Hanukkah commemorate the miracle. (Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CENTURY _ From the birth of fast food in the '50s, to the
cholesterol-conscious '70s, the American food pendulum swung wide
in the third quarter of this century. We left the dining room
behind as we ate frozen dinners in front of the TV set,
char-grilled steaks in the backyard, and scarfed down burgers in
our cars. Americans were ready to celebrate the return of their
servicemen by partying and spending the money that had been so
tight. Tract housing, built to accommodate the thousands of GI-Bill
home buyers, created suburban neighborhoods full of young families.
The Baby Boom exploded. The houses featured kitchens with built-in
refrigerators and stoves, and in many cases, an electric dishwasher
_ color-coordinated at last. Women gave Tupperware parties.
Backyard patios provided a place to put Dad's new charcoal grill.
Dinner parties for neighbors were informal, and hostesses traded
theme ideas, often tropical. Progressive dinners, where each course
was served in a different home, were a suburban invention. (Palm
Beach Post). 70. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CENTRECIPES _ This recipe was a hit with homemakers once
sugar rationing ended after World War II. (Palm Beach Post). 35.
</P>
