<HEADER>
A2704 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-TOASTMASTER09-COX     12-08 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOASTMASTER09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ask the experts for good wine gifts under $10
 &HT;    By Dale Rice
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The holiday gift-giving season is upon us and,
if there's a wine aficionado on your list, just the idea of trying
to pick one bottle from thousands can be enough to send you rushing
toward the tie rack or the perfume counter.
</P>
<P>
   Slow down. Wine is one of the easiest gifts to purchase. Just
stop by a local wine merchant and ask for help. Tell him or her how
much you want to spend and that you'd like something interesting
for a gift. Whether your budget is less than $10 or more than $50,
the wine expert will be delighted to make suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   I want to emphasize that less-than-$10 point. Many people who
don't regularly shop for wine assume that it must be expensive to
be good. But that's not true. One local merchant recently
recommended several wines under $10 to me and each was enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   So whether you want to spend $10 or $100, there's something out
there to please the palate. And take it from me, the recipient will
appreciate the effort.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for other gift options, how about a book? Here
are some appealing items that have crossed my desk in recent
months:
</P>
<P>
   The revised and updated second edition of ``Wine Spectator's
California Wine'' by James Laube (Wine Spectator Press, $39.95) is
a comprehensive guide with tasting notes for 5,000 wines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terroir'' by James E. Wilson (University of California Press,
$50), a product of the Wine Appreciation Guild, is a serious look
at the role of geology, climate and culture in the making of French
wines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wine Lover's Cookbook'' by Sid Goldstein (Chronicle Books,
$22.95), well-organized and beautifully photographed, is a
collection of 100 original recipes designed to pair with and
showcase 13 popular varietals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sharing the Vineyard Table'' by Carolyn Wente and Kimball
Jones (Ten Speed Press, $29.95), a seasonal approach to cooking
with appropriate wine notes, is aptly subtitled ``A Celebration of
Wine and Food from the Wente Vineyards Restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   And with the millennium closing in, if you know someone who'd
like to learn more about champagne, there are options at both ends
of the spectrum:
</P>
<P>
   ``Christie's World Encyclopedia of Champagne and Sparkling
Wine'' (Wine Appreciation Guild, $50) is a sophisticated and
attractive guide to bubblies, arranged by country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Champagne for Dummies'' by Ed McCarthy (IDG Books, $16.99) is
an informative guide for those who want to learn about sparkling
wine in a simple and direct way.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you want to give a year's worth of advice, there's
the desktop ``365 Great Wines Calendar'' from Workman Publishing
($9.95), featuring a wine a day (250 of them under $10) with basic
information and descriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Uncorking tradition
</P>
<P>
   In France, it's the law. No Nouveau Beaujolais can be sold
before the third Thursday of November.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, it has been tradition to honor the same
release date _ printed distinctly across the top of some vintners'
cases.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't stop Austin's Central Market, which began
selling this year's Nouveau Beaujolais on Wednesday, Nov. 17, a day
ahead of everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a faux pas,'' said Central Market spokeswoman Nona
Evans. The wine staff, she explained, had prepared a display and
covered it, planning to reveal it on Nov. 18. Instead, ``one of the
nonwine folks'' removed the wraps, permitting it to be sold ahead
of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was poor communication on our part,'' Evans said. ``We have
done double-duty to make sure folks understand the importance and
meaning of tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   What next?
</P>
<P>
   Is this progress or what? Just in time for the new millennium,
7-Eleven is introducing its own sparkling wine from France. (No,
I'm not making this up.)
</P>
<P>
   The Mieux sparkler, with a suggested retail price of $6.99,
comes a year after the national convenience store chain entered the
wine market with a selection of domestic and imported wines ranging
from $5 to $15. Over that time, the company reports, wine sales at
7-Eleven have increased nearly 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like the nation's No. 1 beer retailer has hit on a good
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Rice writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: drice(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
