A2712 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-POOR-GRAVEYARD09-COX     12-08 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POOR-GRAVEYARD09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Giving dignity to the dead
 &HT;    By John Keilman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Willie Arnold slows his Grand Am and nods toward
a narrow slope that drops sharply into a grove of trees. At its
edge, a foot-tall concrete block marked with a 29 juts from the
ground like a molar.
</P>
<P>
   ``They mostly bury kids here,'' Arnold says. ``It's short and
they can fit a lot of them in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Death is not proud at Dayton's Westmont Cemetery. There are no
gravestones etched with tender words, no soaring stone angels or
stately mausoleums. Only numbered cubes, spaced about 30 feet
apart, indicate that 2,566 of the city's poor lie beneath the
grass.
</P>
<P>
   This is a potter's field, a no-frills burial ground for the
penniless and the forgotten. It lies on city jail property, and
about five times a year, inmates crack its soil and lower another
wooden box into the earth.
</P>
<P>
   Those buried here have died in nursing homes and hospitals, in
lonely apartments and on the street. They have no money, or as far
as anyone can tell, no family. Their cases are marked
``indigent/unclaimed'' and fall upon the desk of Montgomery County
coroner's investigator Harry Brown.
</P>
<P>
   A former cop, Brown fields about 20 such cases a year, using a
detective's ingenuity to untangle sad webs of poverty and
estrangement. A rap sheet might disclose a sister who hasn't spoken
to the dead man in years. A fingerprint can pinpoint the identity
beneath a fake name. In the recent case of an illegal alien killed
on Interstate 75, a letter discovered in his apartment led to his
mother in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   If Brown finds relatives, he asks if they want to assume
responsibility for the body. It is an expensive decision: The
average funeral costs nearly $5,800.
</P>
<P>
   One elderly man's son, reached in Nebraska after Brown followed
a trail of disconnected phone numbers, said he would be glad to
take care of everything. The sister of a General Motors retiree
didn't want to be bothered _ until she learned he had left behind
two suitcases filled with bonds and $70,000 in cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``They showed up the next day,'' Brown says.
</P>
<P>
   When the family can't or won't take charge of the funeral, Brown
digs into the dead person's finances, searching for insurance plans
or bank account statements. If the person owned a house, it can be
sold to pay for the burial. The federal government picks up the tab
for veterans, as the state does for Medicaid recipients. Everyone
else becomes the responsibility of the city, village or township in
which they live.
</P>
<P>
   Brown contacts local funeral homes willing to accept the $725 to
$750 government burial fee. Dayton's Bradford-Connolly and Glickler
Funeral Home is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Glickler says he takes a loss for these funerals but
considers them a public service. He'll do a cremation if the
deceased or his family expressed that wish, but the standard is
burial in a fiberboard coffin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the burials are much more costly, I still go that
route,'' he says. ``(Cremation) might violate their religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all Miami Valley communities bury their unclaimed or
indigent dead in private cemeteries. Only Dayton _ which sees most
of the cases _ has its own potter's field.
</P>
<P>
   The term comes from the Gospel of Matthew. The chief priests of
the Pharisees bought ``the potter's field'' as a burial ground for
strangers with the 30 pieces of silver Judas Iscariot cast back at
them. This origin, for some, gives the phrase a derisive stain:
Westmont Cemetery got its name because a jail superintendent's wife
hated the Biblical appellation.
</P>
<P>
   The graveyard opened in 1943, when the jail was a working farm,
and it has maintained its pastoral character. When you pass through
the motorized gate off Gettysburg Avenue _ entrance is by
appointment _ a road twists past bright brown cattle inmates still
raise for slaughter, past felled trees inmates chop and sell for
firewood.
</P>
<P>
   After a quarter-mile, the road ends at a four-acre meadow,
bordered on three sides by forest and studded throughout with
cryptic numbered cubes.
</P>
<P>
   The markers tell jail officials, if not the public, who is
buried where. That is necessary should a person's relatives finally
claim him, something acting jail superintendent Willie Arnold says
has happened twice in the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Once, a woman came to bury her brother elsewhere. But because
he, like everyone at Westmont, was buried in a wooden coffin and
wooden vault (private cemeteries use cement or metal vaults),
``wasn't nothing (left) but bones,'' Arnold says. The woman
identified her brother by a necklace.
</P>
<P>
   The last person buried here was a man named Nathaniel Jones Jr.
He was 38, a well-liked dishwasher at Ryan's Family Steak House in
Vandalia. He didn't show up for work Sept. 19, and when his sister
checked on him, she found him stretched lifeless and cold across a
bed. The coroner ruled his death an accidental cocaine overdose.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had no insurance, and his family, already strained from
burying another relative two weeks earlier, couldn't afford another
funeral. So on Sept. 23, about a dozen relatives and co-workers
gathered at Westmont to say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' sister, Estella Ervin, says the ceremony was quick and of
little comfort. The casket was closed because the burial fee didn't
allow for embalming, and mourners were hustled out of Westmont
before the body was interred.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't what I wanted for him,'' she says. ``I didn't like
the area. It just didn't look like no graveyard place, no
cemetery.''
</P>
<P>
   She is trying to save money to have her brother moved, a
sentiment jail officials often hear. But it rarely happens. In most
cases, family and friends move on. The plastic flowers they spike
into the ground fade in the sun, the wooden crosses they mount
swell with the rain and break. The dead fade from memory, if they
were ever there at all.
</P>
<P>
   For them, the jail staff in 1992 mounted a plaque upon a large,
pear-shaped stone at the end of the road. It reads:
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember me as you walk by
</P>
<P>
   As you are now, so once was I
</P>
<P>
   As I am now, soon you must be
</P>
<P>
   So walk on by, but think of me''
</P>
<P>
   John Keilman writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: johnkeilman(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
