<P>
   The breakdown:
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICAN CANDIDATES LEAVE MUCH TO BE DESIRED _ Columnist
James Garcia didn't know what to expect when he attended a recent
Republican presidential debate in Tempe, Ariz. ``It seemed like a
good opportunity to catch a glimpse of the new kinder,
compassionate and more inclusive GOP in action,'' Garcia writes.
Instead, Garcia was struck by the topics not mentioned by the
candidates. For example, they failed to discuss the ``guest
worker'' program under consideration in Arizona that would allow
laborers from Mexico and elsewhere to receive temporary work visas
so they can take jobs in the United States. The candidates also
failed to address the controversy over the future of bilingual
education in the state.
</P>
<P>
   STRAIGHT TALK ABOUT GAYS IN PUBLIC SCHOOLS. Family-values and
religious-right advocates are in an uproar over the publication and
distribution of a 12-page booklet, ``Just the Facts About Sexual
Orientation,'' to the superintendents of nearly 15,000 school
districts nationwide. The main premise of the booklet is the simple
fact that homosexuality is neither abnormal nor a mental illness _
a fact that is endorsed by a dozen of the nation's leading
professional health, mental-health and educational organizations.
``Just the Facts'' makes a case for acceptance of, and respect for,
gay and lesbian youths. ``No wonder the right wing is in an
uproar,'' writes columnist Chuck Colbert. ```Just the Facts'
debunks misinformation about homosexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   SPECIAL INTEREST GROUPS COME IN ALL SHAPES, SIZES AND COLORS _
``Housewife, banker, mechanic, doctor, lawyer, merchant or Indian
chief, we all become people with special interests when the
national elections roll around,'' writes columnist Tim Giago. In
this commentary, Giago discusses the current presidential
candidates and who he thinks will get most of the Native-American
vote. ``Bradley would best serve the special interests of the
Indian people. Gore and McCain would be excellent alternatives.
However, we are still months away from Election 2000, and many
things can happen between now and then,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK ON POSSIBLE AIDS ORIGIN IN AFRICA RECALLS SYPHILIS
EXPERIMENT AT HOME. This week, columnist Vernon Jarrett takes
another look at the controversial book ``The River: A Journey to
the Source of HIV and AIDS'' (Little Brown &AMP; Co.), in which author
Edward Hooper offers his theory on how AIDS began. Jarrett believes
that the content of the book resurrects the suspicion among
darker-skinned people that in recent history they have been used as
guinea pigs for scientific research. To bolster this argument,
Jarrett cites the infamous ``Tuskegee Syphilis Study'' of 1932 in
which 623 rural, unlettered black men in Macon County, Ala., took
part in a scientific study of this sexually transmitted disease.
Two-thirds of the participants were left untreated, and
consequently many died from the disease.
</P>
<P>
   IN A KIMCHEE JAR, A LESSON ABOUT LIFE. In this poignant essay
from A. Magazine, writer Hugh Son reflects on his tumultuous
relationship with his father, an immigrant from South Korea. ``When
a boy and his father look at each other, they sometimes see a
mirror reflection,'' he writes. ``The burgeoning young man sees in
the older gentleman his unchangeable past and his malleable future.
He despises and reveres his father, only as he singularly loves and
hates himself. He can see how he is growing tall and strong and new
to the world, just as his father is losing hair and becoming
thinner with years.''
</P>
<P>
   FOR MORE INFORMATION ABOUT NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE -- AND TO
RECEIVE THE SERVICE FOR 30 DAYS FOR FREE -- please contact sales
