<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2783 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-TALENTED-RIPLEY-ART-N     12-08 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALENTED-RIPLEY-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RIPLEY EFFECT  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from Women's Wear
Daily, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE showing Matt Damon as seen in the film ``The
Talented Mr. Ripley'' is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By HILARY DE VRIES 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ Anthony Minghella needs a cigarette.
Actually, he's in need of a brow-smoothing, stomach-soothing tonic
strong enough to calm the nerves of an Oscar-winning director about
to unveil his Next Big Film. But he'll settle for one of the
American Spirits he's clutching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you mind?'' he asks in his soft English accent, nodding
toward the roof deck of Fantasy Films, the Berkeley, Calif., studio
where the director has spent the past five months editing ``The
Talented Mr. Ripley'' _ his first film since his darkly romantic
epic, ``The English Patient,'' won Oscars for Best Picture and Best
Director three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry,'' he says, padding out to the windswept roof with
its dazzling, sun-raked view of the California hills, ``but it's
the only place where they let me smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Such consternation on the part of a director who is considered
to be, after a mere three films, a major Hollywood talent might
seem laughable or even pretentious. Especially given that ``The
Talented Mr. Ripley,'' due this holiday season, is already being
touted as an Oscar contender.
</P>
<P>
   The film, half romance, half psychological thriller, is not only
blessed with Minghella at the helm, but boasts the hippest,
handsomest, most Oscar-decorated young cast going: Matt Damon,
Gwyneth Paltrow, Cate Blanchett and Jude Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, several potential blessings did fall on this project,''
says Minghella, smiling, just for a moment, behind his Armani
sunglasses before his brow furrows once again. ``But as with all
blessings, there's a curse attached. And there's an expectation of
what kind of film this will be, because it's so inflected with the
casting.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Minghella says, all those Oscars _ Best Actress for
Paltrow (``Shakespeare in Love''), Best Screenplay for Damon
(``Good Will Hunting'') and a Best Actress nomination for Blanchett
(``Elizabeth'') _ happened after he'd handpicked a cast of what he
considered talented character actors rather than movie stars.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Minghella, who says his own Oscar win ``changed my life in
no ways'' (he still lives in the same Hampstead home in London with
his wife, producer and choreographer Carolyn Choa, and their two
children), is feeling the pressure that befalls a bona fide
Hollywood outsider who finds himself squinting in the limelight.
Especially when you consider that at $40 million, ``The Talented
Mr. Ripley'' _ a co-production from Paramount and Miramax _ is
Minghella's biggest-budget film to date.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm as nervous as it is possible to be, because I know the
audience is not going to have an easy night in the cinema,'' he
says, trying, vainly perhaps, to deflate some of the film's
pre-opening hype.
</P>
<P>
   Adapted by Minghella from Patricia Highsmith's 1953 suspense
novel, ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' is the story of a wealthy young
playboy (Law) and his equally privileged girlfriend (Paltrow), who
are befriended during a trip through Italy by Tom Ripley (Damon), a
young American who does more than just envy his friends' lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central character is not a hero in any sense of the word.
He's a man who commits murder and isn't caught,'' Minghella
cautions. ``There are no enemies. There's not even a central
protagonist-antagonist dynamic,'' he says with resignation. ``It's
really a journey into a purgatory.''
</P>
<P>
   That Minghella can spout such aphorisms without
self-consciousness reveals much about the kind of thoughtful,
philosophic observer of human nature he is. With his close-cropped
goatee, bullet-shaped head and quiet, almost monkish demeanor,
Minghella looks like the Soprano brother who ditched the mob for a
more contemplative, scholarly life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very intense,'' says Matt Damon, who became close friends
with the director during the film's 14-week shoot last year. ``He's
also the most caring man, who has the patience of Job.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, the 45-year-old director, a former playwright and
university lecturer, has never been one for convention.
</P>
<P>
   The son of Italian immigrants living on the Isle of Wight,
Minghella spent the first part of his career as an academic
teaching literature at the University of Hull. That was followed by
a decade in which he was considered one of Britain's most promising
young dramatists. (His 1985 play, ``Made in Bangkok,'' remains his
best-known work.)
</P>
<P>
   When Minghella finally stepped behind the camera in 1991 to
direct his first film, ``Truly, Madly, Deeply,'' it was, he
recalls, ``the moment when I suddenly realized what I was meant to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only had he found the perfect outlet for his intensely
visual imagination, but Minghella discovered a broader canvas on
which to explore themes that had bedeviled him since childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father left Italy and came to England because he saw it as
a place of bounty and opportunity,'' says the director, whose
father still works as an ice-cream seller on Wight. ``But I grew up
on an island looking at England. When I'm in England, I feel
Italian, and when I'm in Italy, I feel English _ and I always feel
like I've got my face pressed up against the glass.''
</P>
<P>
   That sense of the outsider, so apparent in his plays and ``The
English Patient,'' was also what drew him to ``Ripley.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I fixated on Ripley because I saw so many similarities (to
myself),'' says Minghella, who nonetheless seriously reworked
Highsmith's 1953 novel. He gave the film a strong injection of
glamour by updating the story by six years, to a time in Italy
known as Il Boom, when, Minghella explains, ``fashion began to
invade; when men were suddenly hanging around on Vespas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to imagine making this movie as if `La Dolce Vita' was
being shot on the next street,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Minghella brought an equally discriminating eye to casting. He
chose Damon to play the duplicitous Ripley, he says, ``because Matt
seems to be somebody you can trust, so your first instinct is to
root for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwyneth Paltrow, he adds, also plays against expectations as
Dickie's unsuspecting lover, who ages about 20 years throughout the
course of the film.
</P>
<P>
   Finding the right actor to play Dickie Greenleaf, the
Gatsby-esque American scion, proved more difficult. After looking
at several American actors, Minghella selected Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for someone who effortlessly summoned class, and
that is so much simpler for an English actor.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Cate Blanchett, who actively lobbied for a role in the
film and who plays Meredith Logue, the young woman who falls for
Ripley, Minghella says, ``She's the kind of present you don't get
very often. She and Gywneth have that same long-limbed thoroughbred
quality, and to see these two big engines working together was
fantastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film is very concerned with the beguiling surface and the
chaos that lurks beneath that, and so Italy is almost a
character,'' says Minghella, shaking his head at the memory of
struggling to shoot in crowded public places like Venice's Piazza
San Marco and the Spanish Steps in Rome. ``It's like what Edith
Wharton said: `Why would you be anywhere else when you can be in
Italy?'
</P>
<P>
   ``But Italy can be very dark, very primitive,'' says the
director, sounding suddenly like a man concerned less with
Hollywood than with his own cultural past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole film plays that game between surface and reality.
It's about beauty with thorns.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Hilary de Vries is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
