<HEADER>
A2790 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     12-08 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT QUESTION UP FOR DEBATE: WHO CARES?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a great old laugh line about self-absorption. The
variations are endless, but it basically goes like this: ``Oh,
please, we've talked enough about me. Let's talk about you.
(Pause.) What do you think of me?''
</P>
<P>
   And that pretty much describes the give and take among the
Republican presidential candidates in Monday night's so-called
debate on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   The media blasted Thursday's debate because it didn't allow the
candidates to ask one another questions. This one did, and the
result raised a question for the rest of us: Who cares?
</P>
<P>
   The six candidates had zero interest in quizzing one another on
issues or philosophy; all they wanted to do was use the Q-and-A
segment to promote themselves or to coax an opponent into agreeing
with them on this or that policy proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush was so adept at this technique that he
was able to elicit praise from both the opponents whom he
questioned: Orrin Hatch and John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, there was one exchange, between Bush and Gary
Bauer, that actually approached a level of discourse that might
reasonably be described as debate. Bauer got the ball rolling by
challenging Bush on his approach to U.S.-China relations. How could
America do business with China, Bauer wanted to know, in the face
of China's abysmal record on human rights?
</P>
<P>
   Bush agreed with Bauer that China's treatment of its own people
and its neighbors is horrendous but said that America's best hope
of promoting change is to continue to exchange goods and ideas with
the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we turn our back on China and isolate China, things
will get worse,'' Bush said. ``Imagine if the Internet took hold in
China. Imagine how freedom would spread ... our greatest export to
the world has been, is and always will be the incredible freedom we
understand in America. And that's why it's important for us to
trade with China, to encourage the growth of an entrepreneurial
class and get that ... breath of freedom in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a good moment for Bauer, who believes that the United
States should take a tougher line with China, and an even better
moment for Bush, who displayed the sort of passion and spontaneity
that his critics say his campaign has lacked.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it was only a moment. The entire exchange lasted
less than three minutes, and the really contentious part was over
in about 55 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was back to business as usual. You know: ``Mr. Opponent,
wouldn't you agree with me that I'm a really nice person and a
credit to my wonderful family?''
</P>
<P>
   Do you suppose there was a time when people actually made voting
decisions on the basis of these candidate ``debates'' or ``forums''
or ``joint appearances'' _ or whatever you want to call them?
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, if we can believe the lore, John F. Kennedy turned
around the whole presidential election by handing Richard Nixon his
head in the first of a series of debates.
</P>
<P>
   But this stuff was new back then. Debates are held so early and
so often nowadays that lots of voters are inclined to tune them
out.
</P>
<P>
   The pundits and politicos keep saying that all Bush needs to do
in the debates is protect his front-runner status by holding his
own and avoiding any major gaffes. When he does that, of course,
the same people who say that he needs to hold his own and avoid
major gaffes turn around and criticize him for not doing more.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy being top dog.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, the debates are a waste of everybody's time and
effort because all but two of the six participants are no-chance
candidates who merely clutter up the stage and prevent the real
candidates, Bush and McCain, from effectively presenting their
views.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an idea. Why not dump the formal debates and let Bush and
McCain make the rounds of the chat shows _ Larry King, Sam and
Cokie, ``Meet the Press''? The candidates could kick around ideas
and issues the same way that Bush and Bauer did in their fleeting
encounter Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't be any worse than what they're doing now.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
