<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-BIG09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leftover tracks do little to enhance B.I.G.'s reputation
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oh, this is too easy. What we have here is an album cobbled
together of rhymes the rapper Notorious B.I.G recorded before he
was killed in March 1997. They decided not to put them on his 1994
debut, ``Ready to Die,'' or his second and last original effort,
the 1997 double album ``Life After Death.'' And it's pretty clear
why they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Um, what else is there to say? How about it's almost
disrespectful to offer this as a final album, a final portrait of a
man who became one of hip-hop's best storytellers in a few short
years. Sure, the new tracks that have been laid underneath B.I.G.'s
dated slang, cliches and sex tales are at times engaging (``Let Me
Get Down''), danceable (``Hope You (Expletive) Sleep'') and, with
the exception of the use of the lethargic sample of Prince's
``Kiss'' (``Would You Die for Me''), at least of the moment. And
this album _ full of featured guests such as his protege Lil Kim
(``Notorious B.I.G.''), Eminem (``Dead Wrong'') and Too Short on
the devilishly fun ``Big Booty (Expletive)'' _ should help fans
stay patient with this.
</P>
<P>
   But the most powerful words on this old-raps reunion come not
from this great thick-tongued lyricist, but his mother, when she
says at the end of the album: ``If I had to change anything in my
son's life that would have allowed him to be here today, I would
have deterred him from a career in music. ... If he hadn't chosen
that lifestyle, that career, my son would be alive today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Born Again''
</P>
<P>
   The Notorious B.I.G.
</P>
<P>
   Arista. 18 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
