<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2795 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-METALLICA09-COX     12-08 0338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-METALLICA09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Metallica clicks on collaboration
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greatest of all heavy metal rock acts, Metallica has arrived at
an unusually graceful middle age. And post-Woodstock III, the San
Francisco four-piece's stately sturm und drang seems almost
old-school: Where current metal-wise acts like Limp Bizkit and Korn
dabble in hip-hop and self-flagellation, Metallica is stridently
secure in its manliness and its method. At once head-crushing and
fearlessly soaring, the band masters defiant anthems that belong
someplace between the wrestling ring and the opera house.
</P>
<P>
   ``S&AMP;M,'' Metallica's two-CD stocking stuffer of a concept album,
implies the former and delivers the latter. Recorded live with the
San Francisco Symphony and conductor Michael Kamen, it's a ``with
strings'' adaptation of the Metallica songbook that exploits the
band's overt Wagnerian tendencies to maximum effect. What's
surprising is that it actually makes perfect sense. A Finnish
string quartet, Apocalyptica, already turned Metallica into chamber
music (as heard on the soundtrack to Neil LaButte's vicious film
comedy ``Your Friends and Neighbors''), and both the band's
gargantuan sense of wallop and the grandiose mathematics of
frontman James Hetfield's guitar solos are easily emulated or
augmented by an orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   It is kind of goofy to hear ``Of Wolf and Man,'' for instance,
as lycanthropic opera. And you do wonder when the group will
release another album of new, all-original studio material. (The
last was ``Load'' in 1996.) Yet, what makes ``S&AMP;M'' compelling is
its sense of rock 'n' roll fantasy fulfilled. After all, what metal
dude hasn't wanted to ride with the Valkyries?
</P>
<P>
   ``S&AMP;M''
</P>
<P>
   Metallica with Michael Kamen, conductor, and the San Francisco
Symphony Orchestra. Elektra. 21 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
