A2796 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS09-COX     12-08 0374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino and Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Breathe''
</P>
<P>
   Faith Hill. Warner Brothers. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Celine Dion, John Mellencamp and the programming department at
VH1, heads up: Country's Mississippi mama Faith Hill has made a
twang-free pop album so absolutely mainstream it can be piped into
the Gap. With her Wal-Mart accent bridled into mall-speak, Hill is
alternately a rocker out of the Melissa Etheridge school of
gut-wailing (``What's in It for Me''), an as-credits-roll balladeer
(``Let's Make Love,'' a duet with husband Tim McGraw) and a
big-sister singer for the teen set, a la Martina McBride (``The Way
You Love Me). No wonder ``Breathe'' debuted at No. 1 on the
Billboard 200 album chart, ahead of Mariah Carey. But if you can
forget that Hill used to be a searing country singer and accept
this as pop, it's better than average.
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Enrique''
</P>
<P>
   Enrique Iglesias. Interscope. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   You need a scorecard these days to keep up with the Latin
crossover artists populating the charts. Ricky Martin, Marc Anthony
and Enrique Iglesias have all hit the Top 10 this year and there
are sure to be more following in their footsteps. Martin has the
hip-swiveling sex appeal, Anthony the musical credentials. What
distinguishes Iglesias? Oodles of pop smarts and a dazzling,
flexible voice that pulls even the most cloying ballads from the
pit of mediocrity. He's not infallible, though. The CD's one major
misstep comes with ``Could I Have This Kiss Forever.'' A product of
the Diane Warren (``My Heart Will Go On'') dial-a-cliche
songwriting assembly line, the song finds Iglesias battling in vain
against the histrionics of duet partner Whitney Houston and the
syrupy material. Just skip directly from ``Oyeme'' to the
entertaining, if ickily titled, ``You're My 1'' and pretend for a
moment that Warren doesn't exist. ``Enrique'' and the world both
sound a whole lot better that way.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino and Shane Harrison write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
