<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2799 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-CAKE-RECIPES1STT     12-08 1513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CAKE-RECIPES1STTAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sweet secrets of the doctor and diva
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take one bite of the Ambrosia Cake and hear the heavenly
Christmas angels sing. And so what if we rarely get Christmas snow?
We can make coconut-covered snowballs that taste far better than
the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   We chose a few recipes from ``The Cake Mix Doctor'' (Workman
Publishing, $14.95) that will help make the holidays cheery. And
while we didn't have room to run the lengthy and detailed recipes
from Sylvia Weinstock's ``Sweet Celebrations: The Art of Decorating
Beautiful Cakes'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $35), we do offer her Basic
Buttercream Icing on. We also offer a short tutorial on using gum
paste, or sugar dough, to add a little extra dazzle to your holiday
cakes.
</P>
<P>
   Cake Doctor
</P>
<P>
   Lethal Peppermint
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 28-30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Assembly time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   One bite of this delight and you'll feel like you're in one of
those York peppermint patty commercials with the winter wind
whipping around you. Dress this up for the holiday table with candy
canes.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Ganache (see below)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon peppermint schnapps
</P>
<P>
   Solid vegetable shortening for greasing the pans
</P>
<P>
   Flour for dusting the pans
</P>
<P>
   1 package (18.25 ounces) plain devil's food cake mix
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil, such as canola, corn, safflower, soybean
or sunflower
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon pure vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/2 recipe Peppermint Buttercream Frosting (see below)
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the Chocolate Ganache, adding the peppermint schnapps
after all the chocolate has melted. Let the ganache cool.
</P>
<P>
   Place a rack in the center of the oven and preheat the oven to
350 degrees. Generously grease two 9-inch round cake pans with
solid vegetable shortening, then dust with flour. Shake out the
excess flour. Set the pans aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place the cake mix, cocoa powder, buttermilk, oil, eggs and
vanilla in a large mixing bowl. Blend with an electric mixer on low
speed for 1 minute. Stop the machine and scrape down the sides of
the bowl with a rubber spatula. Increase the mixer speed to medium
and beat 2 minutes more, scraping down the sides again if needed.
The batter should look thick and combined. Divide the batter
between the prepared pans, smoothing it out with the rubber
spatula. Place the pans in the oven side by side.
</P>
<P>
   Bake the cakes until they spring back when lightly pressed with
your finger and just start to pull away from the sides of the pan,
28 to 30 minutes. Remove the pans from the oven and place them on
wire racks to cool for 10 minutes. Run a dinner knife around the
edge of each layer and invert each onto a rack, then invert them
again onto another rack (see photo) so that the cakes are right
side up. Cool completely, 30 minutes more.
</P>
<P>
   While the cakes are baking or cooling, prepare half a recipe of
Peppermint Buttercream Frosting. When cakes are cool, place one
cake layer, right side up, on a serving platter. Spread the top
with Peppermint Buttercream Frosting. Place the second layer, right
side up, on top of the first layer and frost the top and sides of
the cake with Chocolate Ganache. Work with clean, smooth strokes.
Chill the cake until ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with ganache and 1/2 recipe buttercream): 391
calories, 5 grams protein, 22 grams fat (percent calories from fat,
52), 46 grams carbohydrates, 72 milligrams cholesterol, 324
milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Ganache
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 cups, enough to thinly frost a 2- or 3-layer cake
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: 10 minutes to 4 hours
</P>
<P>
   Who knew something so versatile and simple could be so divine?
You can substitute peppermint extract for the schnapps if you'd
like.
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup heavy whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces semisweet chocolate, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon liqueur such as Grand Marnier, framboise or
peppermint schnapps (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Place the cream in a small heavy saucepan over medium heat.
Bring to a boil, stirring, about 5 minutes. Meanwhile, place the
chopped chocolate in a large mixing bowl. Remove the pan from the
heat and pour the hot cream over the chopped chocolate. Stir until
the chocolate is melted. Stir in the liqueur, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   To use this ganache as a glaze, let it stand at room temperature
for 10 minutes before spooning over a cooled cake. To use the
ganache as a frosting or filling, let it stand at room temperature
for 4 hours, or chill it until it thickens and is spreadable.
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon: 47 calories, less than 1 gram protein, 4 grams
fat (percent calories from fat, 69), 4 grams carbohydrates, 4
milligrams cholesterol, 1 milligram sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Peppermint
</P>
<P>
   Buttercream Frosting
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 1/2 cups, enough to frost a 2- or 3-layer cake
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here, we give you the full recipe of this frosting, which is
ideal for any number of holiday cakes. For instance, a full recipe
would be delightful atop a plain white cake. For Lethal Peppermint
Chocolate Cake, you'll only need half this amount (so use 4
tablespoons butter, 1/4 cup confectioners' sugar, 1 to 2
tablespoons milk and 1 tablespoon schnapps).
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons (1 stick) butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely crushed peppermint candy (about 7 peppermint
sticks)
</P>
<P>
   3 cups confectioners' sugar, sifted
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons peppermint schnapps or 1/2 teaspoon
peppermint extract
</P>
<P>
   Place the butter in a large mixing bowl. Blend with an electric
mixer on low speed until fluffy, 30 seconds. Stop the machine and
add the peppermint candy, confectioners' sugar, 2 tablespoons milk
and 1 tablespoon peppermint schnapps. Blend with the mixer on low
speed until the sugar is well-incorporated, 1 minute. Increase the
speed to medium and beat until the frosting lightens and is fluffy,
1 minute more. Blend in up to 1 tablespoon milk or peppermint
schnapps if the frosting seems too stiff. Use to frost or fill the
cake of your choice.
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon: 35 calories, trace protein, 1 gram fat (percent
calories from fat, 22), 7 grams carbohydrates, 2 milligrams
cholesterol, 9 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Ambrosia Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Assembly time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Anne Byrn remembers having ambrosia, a mixture of orange
sections and coconut, on the sideboard every Christmas Eve as a
child. It's that food for the gods that inspired this holiday cake.
</P>
<P>
   For the pineapple and orange filling:
</P>
<P>
   1 can (8 ounces) crushed pineapple in juice, drained
</P>
<P>
   1 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   For the cake:
</P>
<P>
   Solid vegetable shortening for greasing the pans
</P>
<P>
   Flour for dusting the pans
</P>
<P>
   1 package (18.25 ounces) white cake mix with pudding
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup vegetable oil, such as canola, corn, safflower, soybean
or sunflower
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 package (6 ounces; 1 3/4 cups) frozen unsweetened grated
coconut, thawed
</P>
<P>
   Marshmallow Frosting
</P>
<P>
   For the filling: Combine the pineapple, orange juice and sugar
in a medium-size saucepan. Cook over medium heat, stirring
constantly, until the mixture is thickened, 20 to 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the filling into a bowl and cover with plastic wrap.
Refrigerate the filling so that it will cool completely, about 1
hour. Stir the filling before using it.
</P>
<P>
   Place a rack in the center of the oven and preheat the oven to
350 degrees. Generously grease three 9-inch round cake pans with
solid vegetable shortening, then dust with flour. Shake out the
excess flour. Set the pans aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place the cake mix, water, oil and eggs in a large mixing bowl.
Blend with an electric mixer on low speed for 1 minute. Stop the
machine and scrape down the sides of the bowl with a rubber
spatula. Increase the mixer speed to medium and beat 2 minutes
more, scraping down the sides of the bowl if needed. The batter
should look well-combined and thickened. Fold in the coconut until
it is well-distributed. Divide the batter among the prepared pans,
smoothing it out with the rubber spatula, and place them in the
oven; if your oven is not large enough, place two pans on the
center rack and the third pan in the center of the highest rack.
</P>
<P>
   Bake the cakes until they spring back when lightly pressed with
your finger and just start to pull away from the sides of the pans,
18 to 20 minutes. Be careful not to overbake the layer on the
highest oven rack. Remove the pans from the oven and place them on
wire racks to cool for 10 minutes. Run a dinner knife around the
edge of the cakes and invert each onto a rack, then invert them
again onto another rack so that the cakes are right side up. Allow
them to cool completely, 30 minutes. Meanwhile, prepare the
Marshmallow Frosting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
