<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2800 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-CAKE1STTAKE09-CO     12-08 1479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CAKE1STTAKE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flawless desserts and sumptuous sweets with a little help from
the Cake Diva and the Cake Doctor
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A centerpiece for the party buffet. A sweet surprise for the
carolers from church. A dazzler for the Christmas Eve feast. The
final indulgence of a millennium.
</P>
<P>
   A mere cookie won't do. Pie is a Thanksgiving has-been, and
candy is fine for the chorus line, but not for center stage.
</P>
<P>
   Let's eat cake.
</P>
<P>
   Whether fantastically decorated or merely plopped from the bundt
pan, cakes can make holiday occasions special. And in the past few
weeks, I've had occasion to make cakes with two bakers who have
decidedly different styles. But both deliver stylishly delicious
results.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Weinstock is the cake decorator for the stars, with the
cost of some of her confections reaching five figures. InStyle
Magazine referred to her as ``New York's reigning cake diva.'' Her
new cookbook, ``Sweet Celebrations: The Art of Decorating Beautiful
Cakes'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $35) shows why. The photos alone make
the book as worthy of the coffee table as the kitchen counter.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Byrn's cake art is a little more down-to-earth (and a great
deal more affordable). The former Atlanta Journal-Constitution food
editor has taken the lowly cake mix and doctored it to create
luscious desserts you'd swear were made from scratch or purchased
from a fancy bakery. Her new book is ``The Cake Mix Doctor''
(Workman Publishing, $14.95).
</P>
<P>
   Here's what the diva and the doctor had to share.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stories by Reagan Walker
</P>
<P>
   THE CAKE DIVA
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Weinstock has re-created everything from cathedrals to
teacups using flour, sugar, eggs and such. Her clients include
Oprah Winfrey, Whitney Houston and Ted Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Bon Appetit called her the ``Leonardo da Vinci of wedding
cakes.'' In fact, some could put on a whole wedding for the cost of
one of her masterful confections. She's even shipped cakes as far
as Japan and Saudia Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   And she was coming to my house!
</P>
<P>
   Where there is no cake stand. No offset spatula. No pastry bags
or tips or sharp knives. And no history of cake baking, other than
the occasional chocolate layer or hummingbird cake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry about it. We'll wing it,'' Weinstock, 69, assured
me the day before her visit.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstock was in Atlanta to promote her first (and, by her
contention, last) cookbook, ``Sweet Celebrations: The Art of
Decorating Beautiful Cakes.'' So it seemed like a good idea to
invite her over for a little tutorial on jazzing up cake.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I issued the invitation before I saw the book. Before
I saw the re-creation of Alice's Tea Party, down to the crown on
the King of Heart's head. Before I saw the five-layer wedding cakes
draped in nosegays and swags of sugar-dough roses so intricate I'd
swear they were real. Before I saw a cake that looked exactly like
a potted iris.
</P>
<P>
   This book is ideal for those who like to look more than cook,
for arts-and-crafts types who'll marvel at the cake construction
and for cake hobbyists. In fact, those who've dabbled in cake
decorating will find it thrilling. There are projects you can
tackle right off and others to aspire to.
</P>
<P>
   I found it daunting, even after choosing one of the easier cakes
in the book _ a simple gift-box cake that uses a basic square shape
and some elementary decorations.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that the decorations required tips and bags, cardboard
circles and something called gum paste. Not to mention dozens of
eggs, pounds of butter, cups of sugar and tubes of food coloring.
</P>
<P>
   A trip to Michaels Arts &AMP; Crafts and the grocery store got me
started. I borrowed a turntable from a co-worker. (Weinstock said
she couldn't decorate a cake without one.) Then I trekked out to
Cake Art in Stone Mountain for the 3-inch-deep square cake pans
(mine were only 2 inches deep).
</P>
<P>
   Some 75 miles and $150 later, I had assembled all the tools and
ingredients. Then the countdown began. Monday night, I made the
buttercream. Tuesday night, I made the cream cheese filling.
Wednesday night and Thursday morning, I made the cakes and gum
paste.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Wednesday, I met Weinstock at a luncheon where I
witnessed pastry chefs from area restaurants gather in awe around
the diminutive grandmother (wearing her signature extra-large round
glasses) as she described how she mastered the art of re-creating
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional flowers made from icing were too thick. They
didn't look real. They weren't botanically correct,'' she
explained.
</P>
<P>
   So she switched to sugar dough (also called gum paste), a
concoction most home cooks purchase as a dry mix. Once water is
added, it's like a ball of stiff dough, which can be rolled thin
and then shaped. ``I would go to a florist and buy a single flower,
and then re-create every detail by bending and shaping the sugar
dough,'' she said. ``The florist couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, she brought a few of those botanically correct flowers
along for our cake, so I wouldn't have to meet that test. I fell
short on a few others. When Weinstock arrived at my house at 3 p.m.
along with her husband, Ben, she immediately sized up the
situation. Two layers of my cake were still too warm to work with
and the gum paste was as hard as rock.
</P>
<P>
   So the cake hit the freezer and, after conferring with Ben, we
threw the gum paste into the microwave. Sure enough, it softened up
enough to work with.
</P>
<P>
   Ben is frequently an adviser on her cake projects. When they
married in 1949, the couple didn't even have enough money for a
wedding cake. She worked as a schoolteacher as he struggled through
law school. While raising three daughters on Long Island, they
frequently took weekend skiing trips to the Catskills.
</P>
<P>
   There, once it was clear Sylvia would not ski, Ben encouraged
her to bake. So she spent many hours by the side of retired New
York chef George Keller learning about pastry. Soon, with the help
of friends in the restaurant and catering business, she established
herself as the consummate cake decorator.
</P>
<P>
   Ben, now retired, is often at her shop and is considered the
chief cake architect on tricky projects. But Weinstock knows most
home cooks who attempt to use her book probably won't have the
assistance of a husband or a staff of 15. When Ben belabored the
leveling of a cake, she snapped: ``Housewives don't have time to
make it perfect. Hurry up.''
</P>
<P>
   Thusly, we marched on, slicing each of four cakes in half,
creating eight thin layers. Then filling and stacking and icing.
All of this with dull knives and inferior tools. ``Do you have a
spatula that's attached to the handle?'' she asked after the second
time the rubber head popped off.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the final result was breathtaking. And while the novice
isn't likely to re-create the flowers we topped the cake with, many
of the other decorations were quite simple _ piped from a bag with
a round tip or cut from a sheet of gum paste rolled thin, much the
way you cut cookies.
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of an hour, Weinstock decorated a cake pretty as a
present, though it probably would have sold on the lower end of her
scale. Simple cakes for 30 start at $350; wedding cakes start at
$1,000. Eleven-foot confections can soar as high as $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't apologize for the cost, because intense labor and
time go into each cake. And every cake is unique. In fact, when Ted
Turner first saw his daughter's wedding cake draped in elaborate
flowers, he turned to Weinstock and asked how much it had cost him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not enough,'' Weinstock quipped. Diva la difference.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Weinstock's Basic Buttercream Icing
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 cups Preparation time: 5 minutes Cooking time: 50
minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is the classic buttercream icing Weinstock uses for many of
her cakes. It's not the kind with confectioners' sugar that you may
be used to. Here, you use egg whites, sugar and butter to create
pure silk. This is an all-purpose icing that can be colored for
decorating. You can find clear vanilla in cake-decorating and craft
stores. This amount of icing is enough for a three-tier cake.
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   13 large egg whites
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds (12 sticks) unsalted butter, at room temperature and
cut into half sticks
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons clear vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan, combine the sugar and 3/4 cup water,
mixing with a wooden spoon until the sugar is mostly dissolved.
Place the pan on the stove, and use a clean pastry brush to paint
the area just above the water line with water. Place the pan over
medium heat. Do not stir, but watch the mixture to be sure it does
not caramelize or burn. Bring the mixture to 240 degrees on a candy
thermometer (the soft-ball stage). This should take 5 to 7 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
