<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dried fruit whets appetite with sweet-tart taste
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most of the year, Americans use dried fruit for snacks,
lunch box items and trail mix. But during the holiday season, the
cellophane packages of dried fruit emerge to a more prominent spot
on supermarket shelves as we begin to use them for desserts and
delicacies.
</P>
<P>
   In other parts of the world, however _ notably in the
</P>
<P>
   Mediterranean, Africa, the Middle East and India _ dried fruit
is a culinary staple used year-round in a multitude of ways in
everyday cooking. Thousands of years ago, the Egyptians, Chinese
and a number of ancient cultures developed methods of drying foods
to preserve them for consumption well after the harvest, and the
practice spread throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   While most other foods are now preserved by canning, freezing
and other modern methods, the unique qualities of dried fruit
assured their popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Now is a good time to give those cellophane packets a closer
look and think about using dried fruit to enhance more than just
holiday fare. The rich, sweet-tart taste and texture of dried
fruits can marry well with beef, lamb, pork, fish and fowl and give
depth and interest to soups, stews, sauces and gravies, rice,
breads, stuffings, salads, salsas and pasta. Adopting dried fruit
as a pantry staple lets you add an exotic gourmet touch to any
meal. If stored in airtight containers, dried fruit can last for
months.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO GO
</P>
<P>
   Visit these sites to learn more about dried fruit and how to
include it in everyday menus. Many dried fruit recipes on the
Internet come from farms and manufacturers. Dried fruits can also
be purchased online.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hadley Farms, at www.hadleys.com/
</P>
<P>
   cgi-bin/recipeindex.pl, has a nice selection of recipes using
dried dates, cherries, apricots, bananas, apples and cranberries in
a variety of dishes including souffles, stuffings and desserts.
Note how a simple skillet chicken is turned into a gourmet
centerpiece with the addition of a dried fruit compote.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Zoria Farms distributes dried apricots, cherries, peaches,
nectarines, pears, apple rings and more. For three pages of
wonderful family recipes using mostly apricots, visit
www.zoria.com/index.htm. Take note of Connie Zoria's luscious
Apricot Cuccidatti, a frosted Italian delicacy that blends a
filling of apricots, figs, almonds, walnuts, orange marmalade,
honey, cinnamon, nutmeg, allspice and vermouth into a light crust.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For a mother lode of dried fruit recipes you can use at every
meal, from braised Moroccan lamb with prunes, almonds and apricots
to oranges and figs in spiced red wine, search ``dried fruit'' at
the Jewish Food Recipe Archives at
www.eskimo.com/(tilde)jefffree/recipes/.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A search of ingredients at www.mymenus.com yields an array of
recipes, from a turkey stuffing using dried cherries, raisins,
currants and prunes to a dried fruit compote in puff pastry shells
that bathes dark and golden raisins, prunes, figs, apricots, pears
and apples in white wine.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An article from Britain entitled ``Dried Fruit and Why It's
Good for You'' provides nutritional information and suggestions on
how to incorporate dried fruit into your diet and your ``larder.''
See it at www.worldfoods.co.uk/articles/driedfruit/.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you are interested in drying your own fruit, see:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.ag.ohio-state.edu/(tilde)ohioline/hyg-fact/5000/5347.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.marketreport.com/preserves21.htm
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.backwoodshome.com/articles/shaffer58.html
</P>
<P>
   Thai Chicken Salad With Figs
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 55 minutes Chilling time: 1
hour Cooking time: about 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 whole skinless chicken breast
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup honey
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon light soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon red pepper flakes, crushed
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons fresh ginger root,
</P>
<P>
   very finely minced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dried figs, stems removed, cut lengthwise in eighths
</P>
<P>
   2 green onions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   1/2 small cantaloupe, seeded, pared and cut in julienne strips
(about 2 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper, ribs and seeds removed, cut in julienne
strips (about 1 1/2 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1 small cucumber, peeled, seeded and cut in julienne strips
(about 2 cups)
</P>
<P>
   Assorted mixed salad greens
</P>
<P>
   Mint sprigs for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Add oil to medium skillet and saute chicken breast until done,
about 10 minutes. Set aside to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Combine lime juice, honey, soy sauce, pepper flakes and ginger
root in medium bowl; mix well. Shred cooled chicken and add, along
with figs, onions and mint; toss to coat evenly. Cover and
refrigerate for 1 hour, stirring occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to serve, combine cantaloupe, pepper strips and
cucumber with marinated chicken and toss gently but thoroughly.
Line serving bowl or salad plates with greens and arrange mixture
in center. Garnish with mint sprigs if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 221 calories, 16 grams protein, 4 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 17), 32 grams carbohydrates, 43
milligrams cholesterol, 153 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Detail from www.hadleys.com
</P>
<P>
   /cgi-bin/recipeindex.pl
</P>
<P>
   Detail from www.zoria.com/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
