<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Earthquake Cake proves a favorite for holiday
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tessie Knighton of Stone Mountain, Ga., came looking
for two cake recipes. She wanted Mile-High Buttermilk Cake, with
three layers, lemon filling and fluffy frosting, all topped with
more lemon filling; and the Earthquake Cake, a kind of upside-down
German chocolate cake with a cream cheese layer she calls ``to die
for.''
</P>
<P>
   We still don't have a Mile-High recipe for Knighton but wanted
to go ahead and republish the popular Earthquake Cake while we
wait.
</P>
<P>
   Very easy to make, it's a good choice for the holidays with or
without the cola-cocoa frosting.
</P>
<P>
   California
</P>
<P>
   Earthquake Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: about 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   For the cake:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   1 can (3.5 ounces) sweetened flaked coconut
</P>
<P>
   1 box German chocolate cake mix (prepare batter according to
package directions)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) margarine, melted
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 pound box confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   For the optional frosting:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsweetened cocoa
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons cola
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup margarine
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease a 9-by-13-inch baking pan.
</P>
<P>
   Cover the bottom of the pan with the nuts and coconut. Pour
prepared cake mix batter over the nuts and coconut.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, combine melted margarine and cream cheese. If
you will not be frosting the cake, add all the confectioners'
sugar. If you will frost the cake, add 2 cups confectioners' sugar
now, reserving the remainder for the frosting. Beat until smooth.
Spoon over the batter but do not spread.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 45 minutes. You cannot test for doneness with a cake
tester, because cake will appear sticky even when it is done.
Remove from oven and cool on rack.
</P>
<P>
   Optional frosting: In a small saucepan over medium heat, combine
cocoa, cola and margarine. Bring to a boil, stirring constantly.
Add remaining confectioners' sugar and beat with a whisk until
smooth. Spread over cooled cake.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without frosting): 286 calories, 2 grams protein,
17 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 54), 33 grams
carbohydrates, 16 milligrams cholesterol, 136 milligrams sodium, 1
gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with frosting): 341 calories, 2 grams protein, 23
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 61), 34 grams carbohydrates,
16 milligrams cholesterol, 214 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chris Drake (e-mail) asks for two recipes. One is a cupcake
with a lemon pudding-like filling topped with confectioners' sugar.
</P>
<P>
   The other is a dark muffin she had at a church breakfast buffet.
It is ``very rich, moist and tender'' and includes sunflower seeds
and maybe molasses.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cathy Brody (e-mail) lost her recipe from middle school home
economics for a snack treat confection she'd like to make again
with her children. It includes peanut butter and wheat germ.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Judy Ackerman of Lilburn asks for a recipe for beef stroganoff
she believes was published here in 1969. Because our online
archives go back only to 1985, we're hoping another reader has held
onto it and will pass it along.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   To request copies of recipes that have been published in the
newspaper, call The Stacks at 404-614-2610.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
