<HEADER>
A2803 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-MINIS09-COX     12-08 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini movie reviews
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Inspector Gadget'' (PG) _ The best gag is the first one in
Disney's big-screen version of TV's popular animated part-human,
part-machine, mucho-gizmo lawman. Matthew Broderick is perfectly
cast as Gadget. Rupert Everett goes over the top as badman Sanford
Solex. Kids will enjoy watching them both. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The School of Flesh'' (R) _ A smart, cool-hot drama of
sexual obsession. Isabel Huppert, the grand sphinx of French
cinema, plays Dominique, a wealthy, single Parisian whose life
changes when she steps into a bar one night and locks eyes with a
hustler. It is smartly edited, trusting us to keep up with it,
never delivering a scene that feels contrived. The tone is the
epitome of French sophistication, refusing to be scandalized by
sexuality, but never underestimating its irrational power. In
French with subtitles. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Trippin''' (R) _ It keeps trippin' up on its own mixed
message. Deon Richmond plays Greg, aka ``G,'' a high school senior
whose plans for college keep getting waylaid by his fantasies of
living the phat life, surrounded by gorgeous women. The movie has
genuine flashes of charm and heart, but they're undermined by the
filmmakers' pandering to the basic instincts of its target teen
audience. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Marius and Jeannette'' (unrated) _ Not a major film but a
minor delight. A slowly evolving romance between a forty-ish single
mom (Ariane Ascaride) and a middle-aged security guard and an
endearing study of a mutually nourishing working-class
neighborhood. It's a nice place to live and an even nicer place to
visit on an easygoing afternoon at the movies. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Chinatown'' (R) _ The 13-minute clip of interviews with
director Roman Polanski, producer Robert Evans and writer Robert
Towne are just intriguing enough to make you want more talk about
this 1974 classic. It sure would have been nice to hear Jack and
Faye talking, too. That's the only real goody on the new DVD
release, and while it's not nearly enough for fans, the crisp
digital transfer of the Nicholson-Dunaway movie makes up for the
disappointment. ($14.95 VHS, $29.99 DVD). Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray and Bob Longino write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
