<HEADER>
A2806 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-CAKE-RECIPES2NDT     12-08 1920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CAKE-RECIPES2NDTAKE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: prepare the Marshmallow Frosting.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble: Place one cake layer, right side up, on a serving
platter. Spread the top of the cake layer with half of the filling,
spreading the filling with a rubber spatula up to 1 inch from the
cake edge. Place the second cake layer, right side up, on top of
the filling. Spread the second layer with the remaining half of the
filling, spreading it up to 1 inch from the cake edge. Top the two
layers with the remaining cake layer, right side up, and spread
frosting on the top and sides of the cake with clean, smooth
strokes. Garnish the cake generously with the coconut, pressing it
around the sides and top of the cake. Slice and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (including Marshmallow Frosting): 399 calories, 4
grams protein, 17 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 38), 60
grams carbohydrates, 80 milligrams cholesterol, 236 milligrams
sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Snowballs
</P>
<P>
   Makes 48 snowballs
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 35 to 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Assembly time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   These magical treats are sure to satisfy kids, carolers and
elves. I bet Santa would like to have one, too, so remember to
leave one sitting out for when he visits your house.
</P>
<P>
   Solid vegetable shortening for greasing the pan
</P>
<P>
   Flour for dusting the pan
</P>
<P>
   1 package (18.25 ounces) plain white cake mix
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil, such as canola, corn, safflower, soybean
or sunflower
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon pure vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2 recipes Marshmallow Frosting (see above)
</P>
<P>
   1 package (12 ounces; 3 cups) frozen unsweetened grated coconut,
thawed
</P>
<P>
   Place a rack in the center of the oven and preheat the oven to
350 degrees. Generously grease a 13-by-9 inch baking pan with solid
vegetable shortening, then dust with flour. Shake out the excess
flour. Set the pan aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place the cake mix, sour cream, oil, eggs and vanilla in a large
mixing bowl. Blend with an electric mixer on low speed for 1
minute. Stop the machine and scrape down the sides of the bowl with
a rubber spatula. Increase the mixer speed to medium and beat 2
minutes more, scraping down the sides of the bowl if needed. The
batter should look well-combined and thickened. Pour the batter
into the prepared pan, smoothing it out with the rubber spatula.
Place the pan in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Bake the cake until it is lightly browned and springs back when
lightly pressed with your finger, 35 to 40 minutes. Remove the pan
from the oven and place it on a wire rack to cool for 20 minutes.
Run a dinner knife around the edge of the cake and invert it onto a
rack, then invert it again onto another rack so that the cake is
right side up. Allow it to cool completely, 30 minutes more.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, prepare two recipes of Marshmallow Frosting, using a
large saucepan.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble: Place the coconut in a shallow pan. Cut the cake
into 48 squares, about 1 1/2 inches each, making 8 slices down the
long side of the pan and 6 slices across. Remove the squares and
spread each on all sides with some of the Marshmallow Frosting.
Roll each frosted square in cococut. Place the snowballs, as you
finish them, in a single layer on large serving platters or in a
single layer in plastic storage boxes. Continue the process until
all the snowballs have been assembled. Cover the platters with wax
paper or place the lids on the storage boxes. Place the snowballs
in the refrigerator to chill until firm, about 30 minutes. Serve at
once or keep refrigerated until serving time.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (including double recipe Marshmallow Frosting): 179
calories, 2 grams protein, 10 grams fat (percent calories from fat,
51), 21 grams carbohydrates, 42 milligrams cholesterol, 85
milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Marshmallow Frosting
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 1/2 cups, enough to frost a 2- or 3-layer cake
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   2 large egg whites
</P>
<P>
   1 jar (7 ounces; 1 1/2 cups) marshmallow creme
</P>
<P>
   Place sugar, water and egg whites in a medium-size heavy
saucepan. Cook over low heat, beating continuously with an electric
hand mixer on high speed until soft peaks form, 2 to 3 minutes. If
mixer has a cord, make sure to keep it away from the burner. Remove
pan from heat. Add marshmallow creme and beat mixture with mixer on
high speed until stiff peaks form, 2 minutes more. Use at once to
frost the cake of your choice.
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon: 21 calories, less than 1 gram protein, less than
1 gram fat (percent calories from fat, 12), 5 grams carbohydrates,
11 milligrams cholesterol, 2 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Amaretto Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 8 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45 -50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Assembly time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Amaretto is an almond-flavored liqueur that is ideal for adding
to cake batters. Byrn got this recipe from Peggy Davis of
Nashville, who prepares this cake not only for entertaining but
also for giving at Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   For the cake:
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil spray for misting the pan
</P>
<P>
   Flour for dusting the pan
</P>
<P>
   1 package (18.25 ounces) plain yellow cake mix
</P>
<P>
   1 package (5.1 ounces) vanilla instant pudding mix
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup amaretto
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil, such as canola, corn, safflower, soybean
or sunflower
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon pure almond extract, optional
</P>
<P>
   For the glaze and garnish:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup confectioners' sugar, sifted
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 tablespoons amaretto
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup slivered almonds, toasted
</P>
<P>
   Place a rack in the center of the oven and preheat the oven to
350 degrees. Lightly mist a 10-inch tube pan with vegetable oil
spray, then dust with flour. Shake out the excess flour. Set the
pan aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place the cake mix, pudding mix, amaretto, water, oil, eggs and
almond extract in a large mixing bowl. Blend with an electic mixer
on low speed for 1 minute. Stop the machine and scrape down the
sides of the bowl with a rubber spatula. Increase the mixer speed
to medium and beat for 2 minutes more, scraping the sides down
again if needed. The batter should look thick and smooth. Pour the
batter into the prepared pan, smoothing it out with the rubber
spatula. Place the pan in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Bake the cake until it is golden brown and springs back when
lightly pressed with your finger, 45 to 50 minutes. Remove the pan
from the oven and place it on a wire rack to cool for 20 minutes.
Run a long, sharp knife around the edge of the cake and invert it
onto a rack and then again onto a serving platter so that it is
right side up.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the glaze: Place the confectioners' sugar and amaretto
in a small mixing bowl and stir until well-combined. Spoon the
glaze over the top of the warm cake, allowing it to drizzle down
the sides. Scatter the toasted almonds over the top to garnish.
Allow the cake to cool completely before slicing.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 323 calories, 5 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 40), 44 grams carbohydrates, 80
milligrams cholesterol, 273 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Cinnamon Chocolate-Apricot Coffee Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time: 40-45 minutes Cooling
time: 20 minutes -1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Here's a special treat for Christmas breakfast or with coffee
when an old friend in town for the holidays drops by. You can
substitute dried cherries for the apricots if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil spray for misting the pan
</P>
<P>
   Flour for dusting the pan
</P>
<P>
   1 package (18.25 ounces) plain white cake mix
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup finely chopped dried apricots or dried cherries
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup miniature semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 package (3.4 ounces) vanilla instant pudding mix
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil, such as canola, corn, safflower, soybean
or sunflower
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   Place a rack in the center of the oven and preheat the oven to
350 degrees. Lightly mist a 12-cup bundt pan with vegetable oil
spray, then dust with flour. Shake out the excess flour. Set the
pan aside.
</P>
<P>
   For the streusel filling, place 2 tablespoons cake mix, the
apricots, chocolate chips and cinnamon in a small mixing bowl and
stir until well-combined. Set aside the bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Place the remaining cake mix, pudding mix, sour cream, oil,
sugar and eggs in a large mixing bowl. Blend with an electric mixer
on low speed for 1 minute. Stop the machine and scrape down the
sides of the bowl with a rubber spatula. Increase the mixer speed
to medium and beat 2 minutes more, scraping down the sides again if
needed. The batter should look thick and smooth. Pour 2/3 of the
batter into the prepared pan and smooth the top with the rubber
spatula. Spoon the filling over the batter in the pan. Pour the
remaining 1/3 of the batter over the filling and smooth it out with
the rubber spatula. Place the pan in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Bake the cake until it is light brown and springs back when
lightly pressed with your finger, 40 to 45 minutes. Remove the pan
from the oven and place it on a wire rack to cool for 20 mintues.
Run a long, sharp knife around the edge of the cake and invert it
onto a rack to complete cooling. Or transfer the cake to a serving
platter to slice and eat while still warm. Sift the confectioners'
sugar over the top for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 334 calories, 5 grams protein, 18 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 48), 41 grams carbohydrates, 87
milligrams cholesterol, 269 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   More advice from authors
</P>
<P>
   For those interested in cakes, there are a number of new books
on the market beyond Sylvia Weinstock's and Anne Byrn's. Here are a
few to consider:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Title: ``James McNair's Cakes''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Author: James McNair
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Publisher and price: Chronicle Books, $16.95
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Number of recipes: 42
</P>
<P>
   James McNair is the master of single-subject cookbooks. In his
26th, he offers up recipes for familiar favorites, like basic
poundcake, yellow cake and white cake. But he also offers more
inventive fare, like Bananas Foster Cake, Passion Fruit Cake and
Molten Chocolate Babycakes. The Three-Milk Cake looks absolutely
divine. Most recipes hold to a page.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Title: ``Betty Crocker's New Cake Decorating''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Author: Home economists of Betty Crocker
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Publisher and price: Macmillan, $16.95
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Number of recipes: 93
</P>
<P>
   Need a cake that looks like a bicycle? How about one that looks
like a burger? Or, in honor of our city's favorite newcomers, how
about a panda cake? This new Betty Crocker is the answer. It has a
number of inventive cakes created largely from cutting and shaping
cakes baked in basic 9-inch round or 13-by-9-inch rectangular
baking pans. Great to have on hand for birthdays and holidays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Title: ``The Art of the Cake: Modern French Baking and
Decorating''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Authors: Bruce Healy and Paul Bugat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Publisher and price: William Morrow, $35
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Number of recipes: More than 100
</P>
<P>
   No silly animal shapes here. This is a book for those interested
in more sophisticated, European-style cakes. There is fairly
detailed guidance for creating French pastries, including hundreds
of step-by-step line drawings. For the holidays, the lemon meringue
yule log might be festive. The Alhambra, a chocolate-hazelnut
sponge cake, looks divine.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
