<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2807 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-CAKE2NDTAKE09-CO     12-08 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CAKE2NDTAKE09-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: take 5 to 7 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   As the sugar nears the required temperature, place the egg
whites in the large bowl of an electric mixer. Beat the egg whites
at medium speed until they turn from opaque to white and begin to
hold soft peaks. They should be at least double in volume in about
3 to 5 minutes. Do not overbeat.
</P>
<P>
   When the sugar is ready, turn the mixer on high and very slowly
and carefully pour the hot sugar mixture into the egg whites. Pour
in a very thin stream near the edge of the bowl. Beat for 20 to 35
minutes on medium to high speed. The egg whites will lose some of
their volume and the mixture should resemble a very thick meringue.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, reduce the speed to medium or low and add the
room-temperature butter pieces, one at a time. The mixture will
break and begin to look like cottage cheese, but don't worry. Keep
the mixer running, continue adding butter and let the mixer whip
the buttercream until it begins to get smooth again. This could
take up to 10 minutes. Once the mixture is smooth, add the vanilla
and beat for 5 minutes more. Chill until ready to use, or freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon: 137 calories, 1 gram protein, 12 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 76), 8 grams carbohydrates, 31
milligrams cholesterol, 13 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   The magic of gum paste
</P>
<P>
   One of the most useful tips I picked up from my time with Sylvia
Weinstock was the use of sugar dough, also called gum paste, for
decorating. It's wonderfully pliable (and edible) dough that can be
cut or shaped in almost any manner. Beginners may simply want to
work with cookie cutters.
</P>
<P>
   I found the dry mix at Michaels Arts &AMP; Crafts. You simply mix it
with water, though the Wilton mix I used should have called for
more water to make the dough soft and pliable. Once you have a soft
ball to work with, tear off a chunk, add food coloring and work it
in until the color is even. Then roll the mixture out thinly like a
pie crust. Here, Weinstock shows how to form a ribbon. Again, basic
shapes and cookie cutters are a great place for beginners to start.
Simply cut out and then apply to the cake where desired. Weinstock
includes step-by-step instructions for creating several different
flowers and ribbons in her book.
</P>
<P>
   The Cake Doctor
</P>
<P>
   Anne Byrn was a cake-mix snob. You know the kind. They would
never dare to allow Duncan, Betty or the Doughboy near their cake
pans.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom in her 20 years of food writing did Byrn tear off the top
of a box mix. She was a purist, baking cakes from scratch _ even if
it took hours and even if the results weren't always consistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disappointing when it doesn't turn out right or when
it's dry within a day,'' said Byrn, whose career includes a stint
as food editor for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's an admission Byrn can make freely now that she
is a reformed cake-mix snob. In fact, she's the author and namesake
of a new cookbook, ``The Cake Mix Doctor'' (Workman Publishing,
$14.95).
</P>
<P>
   The reformation came a couple of years ago, when Byrn wrote a
column for The Tennessean, the daily newspaper in Nashville, where
she now lives. She shared with readers tips and recipes from her
friends and family on how to doctor up cake mixes. Then, she asked
readers to share theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Within a week, she had mail bins full of letters, some 500
addressed to the Cake Mix Doctor. Byrn began testing and tasting
the concoctions of creative home cooks, and soon she had more than
150 recipes and a cookbook was born _ one so popular it went into a
third printing in the first month of sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a book for Middle America. You know, the folks who
appreciate good food and cooking, but who don't always have a half
day to bake a cake,'' said Byrn, 43-year-old mother of three.
</P>
<P>
   To prove her point, she recently baked, frosted and adorned a
Lethal Peppermint Chocolate Cake in my kitchen. It was pretty
enough for the Christmas table, and it took only about two hours
start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   We started with a simple ganache. Byrn includes a nice explainer
in the book on the irresistible chocolate sauce made of chopped
semisweet chocolate and hot whipping cream. The proportions change
depending on whether you want a sauce, frosting or truffles. We
added a little peppermint schnapps for flavor.
</P>
<P>
   It took about 5 minutes to mix, but then ganache needs to sit at
room temperature for several hours. We took a shortcut and put it
in the fridge _ a decision we'd pay for later.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the cake. Cake mixes are convenient because you can simply
dump all the ingredients in the bowl, mix and pour. With scratch
cakes, there's a certain order to the blending of ingredients and
the mixing time is usually longer.
</P>
<P>
   Byrn started by whisking the devil's food cake mix in a bowl to
eliminate any lumps. Then she added 3 tablespoons cocoa. ``Adding
cocoa will add a lot of depth to the cake. The only thing you have
to be careful of is, it will make the cake drier, so don't
overcook,'' said Byrn.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Byrn added buttermilk, one of her favorite doctoring
ingredients. ``It marries beautifully with chocolate. It adds
moisture without a lot of fat, and the acidity brings out the
flavor,'' she said. After that, the standard eggs, vegetable oil
and vanilla extract were stirred in. Total mixing time was only 3
to 4 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While the cake baked, we whipped up the Peppermint Buttercream
Frosting. Again, it's an easy mixture of powdered sugar, butter,
milk and, for this variety, crushed peppermint candy. The
preparation took 10 minutes, leaving us plenty of time for a chat
while soap operas murmured on the kitchen television.
</P>
<P>
   When the cakes were done and had rested in their pans for 10
minutes, Byrn flipped them out onto a rack, and then flipped them
again to preserve their dome-shaped tops. ``I think the dome tops
are what give a cake that homemade look,'' she said. No leveling
with a knife for her.
</P>
<P>
   While the cakes cooled, we checked in on our ganache, only to
discover we had allowed it to become too cold and stiff. It was
hard to manage. No matter. There was a doctor in the house. Byrn
quickly heated up a few tablespoons of cream and blended it in to
soften the spread.
</P>
<P>
   She put the first layer on a cake stand and smeared it with a
thick blanket of the Peppermint Buttercream Frosting, stopping just
before the edges of the cake. The top layer went on, and then the
ganache was smoothed over the entire cake. For that extra Christmas
touch, we dusted the top with crushed peppermint and added a few
miniature candy canes to the sides. Some holly sprigs on the cake
stand were the final touch.
</P>
<P>
   We took a moment to admire the work and snap a few photos. Then
we cut a hunk out, grabbed our forks and dug in. Scrumptious.
</P>
<P>
   Even a cake-mix snob would agree.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
