<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TREE-WOMAN (San Francisco) _ Julia ``Butterfly'' Hill is ready
to descend from the lofty old redwood tree that has been her home
for two years, but only if Pacific Lumber Co. drops its demand that
she muzzle herself when she hits the ground. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-SURVIVALISTS (Fort Davis, Texas) _ In the hills of western
Texas and northwestern Arkansas, some doomsayers who believe the
Y2K computer bug will spark global shortages and chaos are taking
refuge in well-stocked compounds. ``Most of them are nice,'' says
Bill Cotton, a real estate agent in Arkansas. ``They don't want to
be bothered. They don't want any publicity at all.'' By ROY BRAGG.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-VETERANS (Austin, Texas) _ Researchers at the
University of Texas at Austin are in a race against time. In an
oral history project called ``U.S. Latinos &AMP; World War II: Changes
Seen, Changes Wrought,'' professors, interviewers and a documentary
filmmaker plan to collect the stories of Mexican-American veterans
of World War II. By DAVID UHLER.
</P>
<P>
   UNARMED-SHERIFF (Pearsall, Texas) _ Sheriff Carl Burris of Frio
County is forbidden to carry a gun and, at the Golden Fried
Chicken, regulars sometimes wonder if he should be locked in the
jail he oversees. Yet apart from gossip and the missing holster,
there are few reminders that a year ago, FBI agents accused the
sheriff of stealing cash and selling marijuana, which had been
seized from smugglers and stored in his department. By MARO
ROBBINS.
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYOR (Sacramento, Calif.) _ he California Democratic Party
is offering legislative staffers up to four free nights in the San
Francisco Hilton if they agree to spend their days walking
precincts for Mayor Willie Brown. By ROBERT SALLADAY and LANCE
WILLIAMS.
