<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LONDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LONDON, THE ART OF TALK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for Scranton and all needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ ``You're not as brainy as you think you are,'' shouts
the man standing on the stepladder. ``There's a lot you don't
know.'' (Is he reading my wife's mind?) ``For example, how many
leaves are there on that tree?''
</P>
<P>
   With a brisk fall breeze altering the count by the second, this
is a question too tough for me, so I drag Marcia along to the next
soapbox orator holding forth at Speakers' Corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you believe your grandmommy was a big fish?'' he demands.
Now, this is a query I can answer. I saw self-same grandmommy just
a month or so ago, and though she grew up swimming in the St.
Lawrence River, she's most definitely a land-based biped.
</P>
<P>
   But Marcia is more interested in the youngish guy from the
Association of World Federalists who has drawn a crowd of several
dozen with his dire warning that the oceans are rising and tropical
diseases spreading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is responsible for dealing with this kind of stuff?'' he
demands. ``Nice Mr. Blair with his wavy hands?'' His own flutter
through the air in imitation. ``No, there is no authority in the
world to deal with global problems.''
</P>
<P>
   No, indeed. But as long as there's a Speakers' Corner, there
will be someone to talk about them. Since Parliament's 1872 law
making it legal to declaim on any topic, the northeast corner of
Hyde Park, just a few yards from the Marble Arch Underground stop,
has been the favored place for Sunday speechifying.
</P>
<P>
   Religion and politics are always on the agenda, but it's not
just the fire and brimstone crowd warning about eternal damnation
or moldy Marxists yammering about the proletariat. During England's
great beer debate of the mid-1980s, for example, you could
regularly hear purists pouring forth on the virtues of freehouses
and real ale. And it's not just oratory, but a give-and-take where
interaction with the audience is part of the fun.
</P>
<P>
   Some of it is legitimate objection, but most is just (usually)
good-natured heckling. One day a half decade ago I watched a
hirsute street preacher hold forth on the promise of heaven, only
to be interrupted by a cockney skeptic with a pressing question.
</P>
<P>
   ``D'yeh 'alf to 'ave a long beard to be a 'oly man?'' he
inquired. ``Eh've always wanted to be a 'oly man, but I just can't
grow a long beard.''
</P>
<P>
   On this particular day in early November, there's some of the
same spirit abroad at the corner. A few yards on, a 35-ish
professional type holds forth about _ I kid you not _ the need to
change the accounting system, particularly the depreciation of
assets, to give investors a more level playing field.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can get to a real economic rate-of-return measure, we
can better understand prices,'' he promises. ``Then we can identify
promising firms and we can add real value, not only for ourselves
but for our investors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you against money?'' shouts a bystander, evidently reading
into the recondite call for more legible ledgers a more Marxist
condemnation of capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no,'' replies the orator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then shut up and give me yours,'' returns his criticaster,
still missing the point, but delighted with his own wit.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, a man who disdains money is a pauper,'' answers the
speaker, casting a suggestive glance at his unkempt questioner.
</P>
<P>
   And without missing a beat, he's back on the subject of more
accurate accounting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   London is a city of marvelous museums, but oddly, because the
National Gallery and the Tate are so dazzling, the city's smaller
jewels are often overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   One that definitely is, is Sir John Soane's Museum, in Lincoln's
Inn Field, just a few blocks from the Holborn Underground stop.
</P>
<P>
   Soane (1753-1837) was an architect by trade, a collector (and
something of a pack rat) by avocation. His home is a treat not
simply because of the opportunity it offers to tour a stately
English townhouse set in one of London's most interesting
residential squares. Or because it's free.
</P>
<P>
   The big draw is the work by William Hogarth, England's first
truly great painter. Hogarth was, among other things, a satirist,
and the two series of paintings on display here _ ``The Rake's
Progress'' and ``An Election'' _ hilariously trace corruption both
spiritual and electoral.
</P>
<P>
   In the first, the viewer sees Tom Rakewell, a young Oxford
student, inherit a fortune from his miserly father, forsake his
pregnant fiancee, and order a suit of clothes to inaugurate his
career as spendthrift and roue.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent canvases chronicle Tom through the accumulation of
parasitic hangers-on; an orgy at the infamous Rose Tavern, where a
harlot lifts his watch while otherwise distracting him; his arrest
for debt as he makes his way to royal court; his marriage to an
elderly one-eyed dowager to redeem his fortunes; a further descent
into gambling, debauchery, debt, and, ultimately, prison; and,
finally, his death in the Bedlam madhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The paintings are rich with witty detail, and puzzling out the
pictorial story, with the help of a museum pamphlet, is a delight.
</P>
<P>
   Just as rewarding, if a bit more difficult to decipher, is ``An
Election,'' a four-painting series that chronicles the liquor,
bribes, and blandishments with which the Whigs and the Tories
pursued votes in the election in 1854, through to the corrupt and
riotous victory celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The two series alone make this museum worth a trip, but they are
far from its only attractions. And the opportunity, afterward, to
tour the nearby law courts adds to the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A 10-minute walk toward the Thames brings you to the Courtauld
Gallery at Somerset House, Strand, which one critic has called the
best small museum in the world. And with good reason. This gallery
of 530 paintings contains an expansive collection of Peter Paul
Rubens and a broad range of Impressionism and post-Impressionism
works, including paintings by Cezanne, Degas, Gauguin, Modigliani,
Monet, Manet, Pissarro, Renoir, Seurat, Sisley, and van Gogh.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you have an afternoon or an hour you can spend it
profitably here. Yet in the various times I've been, I've never
seen more than perhaps 20 people browsing through the several
floors of its collection. That's puzzling, since the Courtauld's is
hardly a collection of lesser-known works. Indeed, the museum
boasts several of the world's best-known paintings.
</P>
<P>
   One is Edouard Manet's masterpiece, ``A Bar at the
Folies-Bergere,'' in which a wistful barmaid stares diffidently
back at a customer whose own intent look, reflected back at us from
a mirror behind her, suggests it may be her rather than a drink
he's interested in buying _ even as the angle of reflection seems
to put the viewer in the position of the man who has elicited her
melancholic gaze.
</P>
<P>
   A second is a work most everyone knows, van Gogh's
``Self-Portrait with Bandaged Ear,'' painted in Arles after his
quarrel with Gauguin about aesthetic inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   If Manet caught a certain melancholy plaintiveness in ``A Bar at
the Folies-Bergere,'' Renoir freezes romantic disillusionment in
``The Theatre Box,'' in which a beautiful woman in pearls and
decollete stares pensively out at us while her escort, behind her,
scans the other boxes with his opera glasses. The expression on her
face suggests she knows he's looking at other women _ and that long
years have resigned her to it.
</P>
<P>
   The Courtauld also has two famous nudes. One is Modigliani's
captivatingly erotic ``Nude,'' a work whose inclusion of pubic hair
so scandalized the Paris police when it was first shown in 1917
that they ordered the entire exhibit closed.
</P>
<P>
   A second is a smaller version of Manet's ``Le Dejeuner sur
l'herbe'' (``Luncheon on the Grass''), which hangs in Paris's Musee
d'Orsay. This painting shows two women, one naked, with two dressed
men. And no idealized nymph or Venus is she, cloaking her nudity in
the acceptable antiquity of classical illusion. With the painting
set in the everyday France of 1863, her nakedness, and the bold,
defiant way she returns the viewer's gaze _ suggesting prostitution
or at least libertinism _ set critics ahowl.
</P>
<P>
   And if you favor blues and greens over that blasted ochre that
dominates so much of Cezanne's palette, you just may declare his
rendering of the ``Lake at Annecy,'' in the French foothills of the
Alps, the most pleasing painting Cezanne ever produced.
</P>
<P>
   The Wallace Collection, in Hertford House in Manchester Square
(just a short walk from the Bond Street tube stop), is another
formerly private collection housed in the home of its onetime
owner, Sir Richard Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is both an art museum and a showcase for decorative arts,
including one of the world's finest collections of porcelain and
rooms of armor, which means the ornate mansion really does have
something for most everyone.
</P>
<P>
   But the cornerstone of its collection is the paintings, which
include works by Titian, Poussin, Rembrandt, van Dyck, Rubens,
Velazquez, and Boucher.
</P>
<P>
   The Wallace Collection is free, so it's worth a trip even if the
17th and 18th centuries aren't necessarily your first love in art.
In a 15-minute tour of the main gallery you can see the
collection's masterpieces, including Titian's ``Perseus and
Andromeda,'' Nicolas Poussin's ``A Dance to the Music of Time,''
Rembrandt's ``Titus,'' a portrait of his son at 16, and the work
the museum is best-known for, Frans Hals's ``The Laughing
Cavalier.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Victoria and Albert Museum, with its huge collection of
decorative, fine and applied art, hardly ranks as either a small
museum or one that's often overlooked. Just yards from the South
Kensington Underground stop, it's a massive museum that boasts more
than seven miles of rooms, and any normal visitor will find himself
suffering from museum overload, that mysterious malady that can
only be treated by repairing to the nearest pub to dose oneself
with a pint of lager, before he's seen a fraction of the
collection.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is one little-known aspect of the V &AMP; A: the Print
Room in the Henry Cole Wing. This is where the museum keeps its
off-display collection of more than half a million watercolors,
engravings, etchings, and the like. It's really a research room for
art scholars, yet if you wash your hands and put away your pens,
sit up straight, and speak quietly, the curators will bring you
portfolios of work from any of scores of artists.
</P>
<P>
   On our visit, we requested Joseph Mallord William Turner's
watercolors. Ten minutes later, a curator had delivered to us a box
of 18 paintings, and we sat there reverential as Ruskin admiring
Turner's genius. No, we didn't know how many leaves were left upon
the tree in Speakers' Corner, but we felt brainy indeed for making
our latest London discovery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
