<HEADLINE>
TREASURES OF QUEENSLAND: REEF AND RAIN FOREST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for Scranton and all needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITSUNDAY, Australia _ Barry and I had becomes fast friends,
swimming alongside each other off Hayman Island, a paradise of a
place on the Great Barrier Reef. But now it was time for lunch, so
I clambered back aboard the boat . . . and threw Barry a hunk of
bread, which was quickly engulfed by his big blue lips.
</P>
<P>
   Barry, you see, is a fish _ a giant Maori wrasse, to be precise.
He's about 3 feet long and has a handsome hump that he didn't mind
letting me pat. Barry (as in Barrier) is a familiar figure off the
island as he greets snorkelers and swims around with hundreds of
his smaller friends _ just a sampling of the 1,500 species of fish
found in the 1,250-mile-long Great Barrier Reef, stretching along
the continent's northeastern coast.
</P>
<P>
   The reef, with its fish and coral and islands and waters in
several shades of green, is a treasure. But then again so is the
Wet Tropics rain forest, which brings you the world as it was
millions of years ago. The rain forest area stretches from about
125 miles north of Cairns, the biggest city in the area, to some
185 miles south. Together, the reef and the rain forest make up
nature's dynamic duo in Tropical North Queensland. Both are World
Heritage Sites and neither should be missed. Fortunately both are
easy to visit without the need to rough it, because the area has no
shortage of stylish resorts and fine restaurants along with a
plethora of knowledgeable guides and transportation that can be a
treat in itself. The tropical north is home to 600 tours from
Cairns alone. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Great Barrier Reef &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to meeting Barry and other finny fellows, I was awed
just seeing the reef, with its 300 kinds of living, breathing,
sometimes waving coral, some hard, others soft and frondlike, and
still others looking a lot like big brains. (Despite their
appearance, they are animals, not plants. They have cells that
catch prey and openings for material to move in and out.) Add to
that 4,000 kinds of mollusk, 400 species of sponge, anemone,
crustaceans, and echinoderms, as well as 500 kinds of seaweed, six
species of turtles, thousands of birds, and the last great
population of those curious aquatic mammals called dugong.
</P>
<P>
   Whales come to the warm waters around the reef to give birth,
and are best viewed from July to October. What's more, there are
600 continental islands and 300 cays, or reef islands, many of them
emerald-colored and fringed with sandy beaches. You'll never see
all that the reef _ actually a complex of more than 2,900 reefs _
has to offer. But it's fun to view as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   You don't even have to get wet, thanks to helicopter flyovers
and rides in semisubmersible, glass-bottomed vessels. (One of those
boats is a yellow ``submarine'' near a tiny island named Bali Hai.)
My first view of the reef involved a copter flight from Hamilton
Island and a Fantasea cruise in a high-speed catamaran, complete
with a buffet lunch and lots of beverages.
</P>
<P>
   But there is nothing like getting in the water to view the
multicolored fish up close. Boat tours make snorkeling equipment
available (and if I can snorkel, getting just a wee bit of the
Pacific Ocean up my nose, it must be easy), and there are charters
for certified scuba divers. There is such peace in floating amid
the fish and the coral that I was eager to repeat the experience a
few days later on a day sail from magical Hayman Island. Good thing
I did or I never would have met my friend Barry. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The rain forest &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A visit to Australia's rain forests transports you back millions
of years to when Australia was part of a supercontinent called
Gondwana. Plant lovers will rejoice in the diverse kinds that grow
in this forest, where more than half of the annual 13 feet of
rainfall is caught by the plants before it reaches the ground. A
canopy of leaves filters the bright tropical sunlight, leaving the
forest floor dark and cool.
</P>
<P>
   And animal lovers, if they are fortunate, have a chance to see
58 frog species, 100 mammal, 327 bird, 162 reptile, 64 native fish,
and more than 40,000 insect species. (You wouldn't want to see all
of the insects at once, certainly.) The creatures, of course, don't
come out to greet you, so you may want to visit a place like the
Rainforest Habitat Wildlife Sanctuary in Port Douglas, where for a
few dollars admission you are assured of seeing bats, crocodiles,
marsupials, and cassowaries _ more than 150 species in all, most of
which roam freely and many of which can be viewed from walkways.
For an extra donation, you even get to pat or photograph a
eucalyptus-munching koala.
</P>
<P>
   In the Port Douglas area, a guide from Australian Wilderness
Safaris showed off a swatch of the Daintree rain forest area, with
its cool waters, prehistoric ferns, and sunlight softened by the
canopies of leaves. And in Cairns, a ride on the Skyrail, a
4.7-mile cableway, brought memorable views of forest and waterfall,
with exploratory stops along the way and a lively village called
Kuranda at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunate travelers, though, take their Skyrail ride at the
beginning or end of a trip on the Great South Pacific Express,
Australia's glistening answer to the Venice-Simplon Orient Express
(they're part of the same company). The Great South Pacific Express
goes through the forest, right past the waterfalls, past great
farms and fields where kangaroos and cattle can be spotted, and
near small towns that look like stage sets of the 1800s' American
West. A day at the Great Barrier Reef is also part of this luxury
train trip.
</P>
<P>
   The twin treasures of reef and rain forest can fill many a day,
and yet that's hardly all the untamed nature that Queensland _ and
not only its tropical north _ offers. Queenland, the second-largest
Australian state (it's 2 1/2 times the size of Texas), has 400
natural and environmental parks, the world's tallest vegetated sand
hills, the nation's densest jungles, and its driest desserts. There
are many beautiful beaches, too, although from approximately
November through May, swimming is restricted to netted areas. The
reason is box jellyfish, which you don't want to mess with. (``How
do you know when the jellyfish are gone?'' I asked an Australian.
``Easy,'' he replied. ``I toss my friend in, and if he comes out
all right, then I go in.'') In the capital city of Brisbane,
meanwhile, are the famed Botanic Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Queensland, you're amazing . . . naturally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
