<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO NEED TO ROUGH IT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for Scranton and all needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mention Australia and many think of koalas and kangaroos and
crocodiles and cassowaries. And well they should, because nature
puts on a splendid show. But amid all the natural wonders, some
visitors may be surprised to find resorts that offer fine food and
excellent accommodations while keeping in harmony with their
surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the top resorts in Tropical North Queensland,
all of which I have at least visited. Costs vary but most places
have packages that lower the prices and add to the amenities. All
have pools and lush landscaping, offer nature excursions, and serve
good food, including Australia's excellent seafood and lamb, as
well as the nation's excellent wines.
</P>
<P>
   Kewara Beach Resort, 20 minutes north of Cairns in Northern
Queensland, is surrounded by forests and the Coral Sea. Its design,
including wooden carvings and Aboriginal artifacts, is intended to
reflect the lifestyle and traditions of the Torres Strait
Islanders. Listed prices begin at about $125 US per room. Phone
800-525-4800 or, on the Web, visit www.kewarrabeachresort.com.au.
</P>
<P>
   Thala Beach Lodge is some 12 miles south of the lively village
of Port Douglas. The 145-acre resort includes 1.2 miles of sandy
beach. Even a walk along that beach there has its rewards, such as
the sight of parrots in the nearby trees. Listed prices begin at
about $155 US. Call 07-4057-5300 or visit www.thalabeach.com.au.
</P>
<P>
   Silky Oaks Lodge, also near Port Douglas, is literally
surrounded by the Daintree rain forest _ a platypus is even said to
inhabit the resort's waters. There are 60 chalets near treetop
level and overlooking the Mossman River. On the lodge grounds is a
nursery where orphaned wallabies are taken care of until they are
mature enough to be returned to the forest. The two I met, Sandy
and Sheila, weren't at all shy. Listed prices begin at about $255
US. Phone 132-469 in Australia or e-mail
resorts-reservations(at)poaustralia.com.
</P>
<P>
   Reef House is a boutique hotel in the pleasant beach town of
Palm Cove, and is built so that it seems to be an extension of the
outdoors, with its ferns, bougainvillea, gardens, and three
swimming pools. The Corals Restaurant is a good place to try those
lobsterlike crustaceans, bay bugs, which taste a lot better than
their name sounds. Cocktails include a ``strawgasm,'' made with
chcolate and strawberry liqueurs and cream. Listed room prices
begin at about $148 US. Call 61-74055-3633.
</P>
<P>
   The Great South Pacific Express is a luxury hotel, a grand
restaurant, and a scenic ride all in one. The latest member of the
Venice-Simplon Orient Express family (in partnership with
Queensland Rail), the South Pacific Express has routes encompassing
the rain forest, the Great Barrier Reef, Brisbane, and Sydney. The
train features gleaming woods (Australian red cedar prime among
them), multicolored upholstery, elaborate marquetry, and
stained-glass clerestory roofs. With its doting stewards and
waiters, dining carriages, piano lounge, and observation deck, the
Express is designed to appeal to the high-end traveler. Breakfast
and afternoon tea are served in passengers' compartments while
gourmet dinner dishes can range from coral trout with roasted
aubergine to ash mountain rack of lamb on a tomato risotto.
Two-night Brisbane-Cairns trips begin at $1,430 US, with breakfast,
afternoon tea, dinner, and an excursion by air to the Great Barrier
Reef included. Call 800-524-2420 or, on the Web, visit
www.orient-expresstrains.com/.
</P>
<P>
   Hayman frequently pops up in lists of the world's five top
resorts. A favorite of celebrities, luxury lovers, and nature fans
alike, Hayman boasts scenery that rivals even that of my beloved
Hawaii. Tropical gardens and white-sand beaches help this 31-acre
resort blend in with the rest of 960-acre Hayman Island, the
northernmost of the Whitsunday Islands. There are 203 rooms
overlooking swimming pools, beaches, and the sea. There are also
six restaurants ranging from formal to casual, and a wine cellar
with more than 20,000 bottles. A wedding chapel sits on a hill. And
throughout the grounds there are statuary, paintings, gardens,
shops, a children's club, a library, and game rooms. Activities
include tennis, squash, table tennis, volleyball, a nine-hole
putting green, nature walking, a dive center, parasailing,
waterskiing, fishing, snorkeling, scuba diving, windsurfing, and
boating. Helicopters and seaplanes are also available for exploring
the islands, and excursions include a day at Whitehaven, one of the
world's best beaches. Hayman, not surprisingly, is a member of
Leading Hotels of the World. Listed prices range from about $350 to
about $2,000 US. Phone 800-223-6800.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
