<HEADER>
A2819 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-CANCER-SEXUALITY-NYTS     12-08 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-SEXUALITY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCER PATIENTS' SEXUALITY TOO OFTEN IGNORED  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 BY KEVIN K. SINGER  
 c.1999 Oncology.com  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Survival may be the first priority when one receives a diagnosis
of cancer, but at some point many patients become concerned with
the effects that battling the disease will have on their sexuality
and, ultimately, their self-esteem and relationships.
</P>
<P>
   At the recent Oncology Nursing Society's 10th Annual Fall
Institute in Salt Lake City, two health-care professionals outlined
the problems cancer patients face in terms of their sexuality, and
discussed strategies to help them cope and overcome their
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Whether dealing with hair loss or fatigue, the vast majority of
cancer patients have some worries that relate, either directly or
indirectly, to their sexuality. But in the past, the focus has
often been mainly on concrete sexual problems, such as impotence or
vaginal dryness.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the research that has been done has been in focused
cancer groups,'' said presenter Sandra Mitchell, a nurse
practitioner at the University of Maryland Cancer Center in
Baltimore. ``We don't have a good sense of how widespread the
problem is.''
</P>
<P>
   Sexual issues arising from cancer are typically disease-,
treatment- and/or gender- specific, commented Edward B. Rubenstein,
M.D., associate professor of medicine at the M.D. Anderson Cancer
Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, treatment of prostate, testicular, ovarian and
breast cancers can directly impact one's sexuality. For prostate
cancer, a significant minority of men who receive surgery or
radiation become impotent, and hormonal therapy causes what is
called chemical castration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those patients lose sexual desire and function,'' Rubenstein
said.
</P>
<P>
   For women, a mastectomy isn't simply the removal of a breast;
it's also the disfigurement of a sexual organ that for many is a
symbol of their femininity.
</P>
<P>
   Radiation to pelvic areas can decrease a woman's natural vaginal
lubrication, and hormonal therapies often wreak havoc on sexuality.
The libido suffers greatly, said presenter Judy Shell, R.N., a
Ph.D. candidate who is a medical family therapist at Central
Florida Cancer Centers in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Even with cancers not related to sexual organs, systemic
treatment may cause problems, for example raising the specter of
infertility.
</P>
<P>
   Lymphoma, for instance, requires fairly aggressive chemotherapy.
``If the patients are in the reproductive ages, they may lose
gonadal function,'' Rubenstein said. ``It may be permanent.''
</P>
<P>
   Colon cancer patients often have to wear a colostomy bag, and
head-and-neck cancer patients may have a tracheotomy tube or
discoloring of the face due to radiation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those kinds of issues really impact a person's sexuality and
how they view themselves as men and women,'' said Shell. ``Who we
are as men and women can be impacted no matter what the cancer
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Hair loss, one of the most common and visible effects of cancer
treatment, can devastate a person's self-image as a sexual being.
``Hair is a symbol of social status, personality and attraction,''
Shell said. ``Baldness can signify illness, and, culturally, ill
and sick people are asexualized.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatigue, pain, nausea and vomiting also play havoc with one's
sexuality. ``A lot of the aggressive chemotherapies knock you for a
loop,'' Rubenstein said. ``The side effects can be pretty
debilitating and can interfere with sexual desire.''
</P>
<P>
   On the most basic psychological level, cancer and subsequent
treatment can affect a patient's sexuality by undermining their
view of themselves as capable, healthy human beings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every patient has some sexuality concerns, not just in terms
of intimate sexual relations, but who they are as men and women,''
Shell said. ``Sexuality is not just sex.''
</P>
<P>
   For single patients, the question becomes: Who will find me
attractive, and how or what do I tell any potential partners about
the disease?
</P>
<P>
   For those already involved with someone, the illness forever
alters that relationship. ``Cancer affects the relationship,
sometimes for the good, and sometimes not for the good,'' Mitchell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Stressing that sexuality isn't simply intercourse, Shell said
that when battling cancer, many patients need some level of
intimacy and support. ``Often, they're more interested in just
[being] held,'' she said. ``They need to feel connected and loved.
They need a sense of security, which is really important.''
</P>
<P>
   Shell tells couples dealing with cancer to talk. ``At the point
in time they should be closest to someone, that's when they're
furthest apart,'' she said. ``One of our jobs is to help them
communicate with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to sexuality, however, communication in general is
often a problem, since the topic is often seen as taboo by patients
and doctors preoccupied with fighting cancer. Patients may think
sex shouldn't be a priority, Shell said, or they may have been told
this in no uncertain terms by health-care professionals. When
raising questions about sex, some patients have heard they should
be happy to be alive. ``People have been reprimanded,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said it's important that doctors and nurses have the
kind of relationship with their patients in which they can talk
about these problems, or at least refer them to someone who can.
``It's not something you're generally going to talk to your
next-door neighbor about,'' she said. ``It's a very private
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Health-care professionals can also provide simple, commonsense
tips to facilitate sexuality, Shell said. For instance, Shell
counsels those who experience fatigue to schedule sexual activity
around the time of day they feel most energetic, even though it may
not be their usual time for intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Simplicity is key to overcoming some of these concerns. After
battling breast cancer, Jacqueline Brandwynne became engrossed in
the topic of women's sexuality during and after cancer treatment.
She consulted cancer patients, therapists and gynecologists, and
developed a vaginal lubricant for her Very Private line of
products. She also composed a seven-step program to guide women
back into their sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to do things that are real,'' Brandwynne said. ``(The
seven-step program) gives them a logical sequence.''
</P>
<P>
   Before doctors and nurses can offer any help, they have to
reevaluate their view of sexuality, both Shell and Mitchell noted.
The preferred model, they agreed, should incorporate physiological,
interpersonal, psychological and cultural aspects of the patients
and their sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also very important to validate for the person the
importance of their concerns,'' Mitchell said, ``and normalize
those concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   (Oncology.com is a comprehensive source of online cancer news
and information. The Web site is at http://www.oncology.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Other helpful web sites on the impact of cancer on sexuality and
how to cope with it include:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.cancercare.org/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.gildasclub.org/
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by the New York Times Syndicate)
</P>
</TEXT>
