<HEADLINE>
1999 COLTS: HORSES OF A DIFFERENT COLOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the midst of a joyous celebration hours after a dramatic win
in Miami that stamped his team ``for real,'' a friend leaned over
and asked Indianapolis general manager Bill Polian: ``Can we fit
all of these guys in under the salary cap next year?''
</P>
<P>
   Polian realized that no matter how many games his upstart Colts
win, the reality is, he is going to have a difficult job keeping
this promising young team together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was enjoying the win until that moment,'' said Polian with a
laugh, ``but there was the thought of the salary cap right in the
middle of my mind again. It's like a toothache. It's always there.
It never goes away. There are times when you don't think about it,
but then it always comes back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colts, at 10-2, are in first place in the NFL's toughest
division, the AFC East, and have the best young team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Bill Parcells said earlier this year about us,'' offered
Polian, ``when you have a good young team, you have salary cap
problems. But the important thing we have to do is to take
advantage of these players while we have them, and to keep our core
group together as long as we possibly can. In this league, under
the present rules, the window of opportunity only lasts so long.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colts had a monster win last Sunday, beating the Dolphins,
34-31, in a shootout that went right down to the wire, but Polian
said it was not their biggest victory of the season. He thought the
most important win was against the Jets in New York the sixth week
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Polian's explanation requires a little setting up.
</P>
<P>
   In Week 2 against the Patriots, his young team built a 28-7
halftime lead but allowed the Patriots to come back for a 31-28
victory in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   In Week 5, the Colts built another big lead, this time at home
against Miami, and watched it evaporate. Miami scored 25 points in
the second half and was helped at the finish by a controversial
officiating call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team was devastated after that Miami game,'' said Polian.
``We had our guts ripped out. When I walked in our locker toom
after the game, it was like walking into a losing Super Bowl locker
room'' _ which Polian did four times as GM of the Buffalo Bills.
``That's the only thing I could relate it to. We got a bad deal on
a call at the end of the game, and we all felt we had the game
taken away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   His team was 2-2 after four weeks, which is just about what the
preseason prognosticators felt they would be (the Colts were a
consensus pick to finish last in the AFC East). After crushing
defeats to preseason favorites New England and Miami, there was no
telling which way the young team was going to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to go into New York to play Parcells and the Jets, and
we knew that was going to be tough,'' said Polian. ``It's always
tough to go up against him. But Jim Mora was great that week.
Everything he said and did in practice was positive. He wouldn't
let our kids get down. He kept pumping them up, telling them we
were going to win and get back on track. Then we won the game
(16-13) on a big play at the end, and that turned the season for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Colts have ripped off eight straight. Their
offense, directed by second-year quarterback Peyton Manning, and
built around the running of rookie Edgerrin James and wide receiver
Marvin Harrison, is the most explosive in the game.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was a move that Polian made back in the spring that
helped make this surprising surge _ from last to first in 12 months
_ possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly,'' said Polian, ``there are some things that have
happened that have surprised us as well. We thought we had a chance
to be pretty good but knew the only way it could happen was if all
the pieces fell in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``James was the most difficult part of it, and he has played far
beyond any expectations we had for him. We knew we had to let
Marshall Faulk go. We also knew he was an outstanding player and
had over 2,000 combined yards for us the year before. We felt that
no matter what we did, we couldn't make up for those yards. But
James has done that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second part is the continued growth of Manning and
Harrison. A year ago they showed they had the potential to be a
great passing combination. But we didn't know if they would
continue to improve, and they have.
</P>
<P>
   ``Third, we lost two wide receivers and had to use (Terrance)
Wilkins. We knew he was a terrific kick returner, and insurance as
a wideout, but since we were forced to play him because of injury
to two other players, he has been tremendous. Every game he makes
at least one big play in the passing game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we went out and picked up some veteran free agents to
help us on defense. Our defense was just about the worst in the
league last year. (Defensive end) Chad Bratzke had to continue to
play the way he did with the Giants, and he did. (Linebacker)
Cornelius Bennett had to be reborn, and give us a big lift. He has.
Bennett is playing like the Bennett we had in Buffalo. On
Wednesdays he looks dead. On Sundays, he plays like he has
discovered the fountain of youth.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Patriots get to Indianapolis this Sunday, it will be a
different setting than the one they have been accustomed to over
the years. There will be no empty seats; all are sold for the rest
of the year. And no fans sitting on their hands, waiting for
something bad to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our building is alive,'' said Polian. ``We have finally gotten
it to be an advantage for us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
