u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      12-08 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROY BROWN GETS TO SPREAD HIS WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The catch was just the beginning. When Troy
Brown twisted to receive a pass from Drew Bledsoe at the 45-yard
line Sunday night, his momentum continued to carry him downfield.
He reached the 30 before any Dallas defenders caught on. A would-be
tackler grabbed at Brown's waist but quickly slipped to the turf as
the elusive receiver ran laterally.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could prevent Brown from crossing the sideline to stop
the clock. As the final moments of the second quarter elapsed _
with the Patriots trying to score before halftime _ Brown eluded
one Cowboy after another. Deion Sanders finally wrapped his arms
around Brown. Still, Brown spun the cornerback in a big circle as
he stepped out of bounds. All Sanders could do was snap his fingers
at the receiver that got away.
</P>
<P>
   In the larger scheme of a snapped losing streak and reawakened
playoff hopes, it was easy to forget the 19-yard catch Brown made
late in the half. But it was just the type of play the receiver
prides himself on. It is also just the type of effort the Patriots
need as they make their push for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to be involved,'' said Brown. ``With this team and the
players here, the opportunities are few and far between, so you
have to make the best of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to set a fire under some of these guys. They come over
and say, `I like the way you play. You get me all pumped up.' A
5-yard catch you turn into 15 yards, break a couple of tackles on
it, run over a couple people and it gets everybody jacked up.
That's the thing we need on this team to get everybody going.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Dallas, New England (and Brown) benefited from a spread
offense that employed five receivers. It was a new look emphasized
at practice last week and is likely to remain in the playbook for
the rest of the season. At a time when offensive coordinator Ernie
Zampese has been criticized for predictability, the five-receiver
package showed resourcefulness and a hint of creative thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Creativeness on the part of the coaches was rewarded with extra
effort by the players, particularly the receivers. They played
physically, took on defenders, and tried to make greater gains. In
the process, they silenced concerns about their ability to get off
the line and get free.
</P>
<P>
   The more open set-up allowed Brown to be at his best, catching
the ball and then running for more yardage. He led the Patriots
with four receptions for 40 yards. Brown also contributed three
punt returns for 32 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy Brown just needs to get the ball,'' said coach Pete
Carroll. ``He does good things not only on the punt returns, but
catching and running. He was effective again. He's an important guy
on third down for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The ability to motivate teammates has increasingly made Brown an
essential part of the New England offense. But it took time for
coaches to realize the impact that a 5-foot-10-inch, 190-pound wide
receiver could make.
</P>
<P>
   In college, Brown starred at Division 1-AA Marshall, but then he
struggled during the early years of his professional career. He was
cut from the Patriots by Bill Parcells in August 1994, but after
unsuccessful tryouts with Carroll's Jets and the Kansas City
Chiefs, Brown's career path led back to Foxborough at midseason.
</P>
<P>
   He soon began to show that he belonged. In 1995 and '96, Brown
played in every regular-season game. In 1997, he started in place
of an injured Terry Glenn for six games, setting career highs with
41 receptions, 607 yards, and 6 touchdowns. Last season, he was the
team's primary punt returner and reserve receiver.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Brown has caught 22 passes for 297 yards and a
touchdown. Still the team's primary punt returner, he has 24
returns for 190 yards (7.9-yard average). Against Kansas City in
mid October, Brown sprained his left ankle on a kickoff return and
has not been put in that position again. He missed three games with
the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a playmaker,'' said Zampese. ``Every time he touches the
football, something good happens. We'd love to get him involved
more.''
</P>
<P>
   The five-receiver package would be one way. Against the Cowboys,
Brown's most important reception came during the Patriots
fourth-quarter touchdown drive. On second and 6, he caught an
11-yard pass to move the ball to the Dallas 17.
</P>
<P>
   Zampese hopes the five-receiver sets will frustrate defenses by
presenting matchup difficulties. And Brown believes it will make
Bledsoe's job easier by making it less likely that the quarterback
will force passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy it,'' said Brown. ``All the guys enjoy it as
receivers. I don't think the running backs enjoy it a whole lot.
But I think that it was something we had to do, to spread everyone
out and create some more lanes. It's something new now, so I think
you'll probably see it the rest of the year. We have guys on the
field that can make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   And Brown ranks right at the top of the list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
