<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-WOMEN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN FIND BALANCE IN BIOTECH WORKPLACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  BOSTON _ Conventional wisdom has it that men run the show in
the world of technology.
</P>
<P>
   But in the laboratories and executive suites of biotechnology,
the workplace has been relatively hospitable to women. In small and
medium-sized biotech firms, for instance, up to 50 percent of
research scientists are women.
</P>
<P>
   The reason has largely to do with balancing work and family,
according to a study by the Radcliffe Public Policy Institute due
out Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biotech is a more friendly environment for professional women
than academia and most industries,'' said Paula Rayman, director of
the Radcliffe institute and a principal author of the study,
entitled ``Professional Pathways: Examining Work, Family, and
Community in the Biotechnology Industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The report concludes that the relatively young companies in
Greater Boston's biotech industry offer ``relatively reasonable
hours, enabling parents, and particularly women, to have
professional science careers while raising children.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike older industries, biotechnology is largely a product of
the 1990s. Biotech firms tend to be small and young. Without an old
boys' network or other hiring baggage, women have gotten in on the
ground floor. Thus, it's an industry with a significant fraction of
women at all levels.
</P>
<P>
   Una S. Ryan, president and chief executive of Avant
Immunotherapeutics Inc., maintains that women scientists are
attracted to biotechnology because they are judged solely by their
work, rather than office politics or other variables.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, women scientists can be enthused and really concentrate
on their work and not fight the extraneous issues of making sure
everything is fair,'' said Ryan, whose research department now has
17 women and 19 men.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech scientists also work on projects that have long
development times; it can take up to 10 years to develop a drug.
Since science cannot be hurried, there is not the pell-mell rush
found with Internet start-ups. That puts less time pressure on the
average workday at biotech firms, enabling flexible work schedules,
the report noted.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is that unlike the rich pharmaceutical industry,
small biotech firms are financially vulnerable, some scrambling for
money to meet payrolls, others facing changing strategies due to
scientific uncertainties _ all of which can lead to layoffs and
company closings.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech professionals, however, say the rewards of the drug
discovery research and the experiences they gain at cutting-edge
science outweigh most job security issues, according to the study.
Moreover, if a biotech professional's employer founders, she
probably can find another job relatively easily because the
industry is growing. And chances are good that the next job will
have flexible hours and possibly part-time positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biotech careers present new patterns that allow professionals
to tolerate more job uncertainty and economic vulnerability than
professions of old,'' the Radcliffe study found.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, men and women biotech professionals view their work
environment as a middle ground between pharmaceutical laboratories,
which tend to operate under traditional corporate hierarchies, and
academia, which has research autonomy but a ``publish or perish
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The study reported that women see academic science as the most
difficult environment, making biotechnology look good in
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Still, all is not rosy in biotech, the study suggests. Among the
findings:
</P>
<P>
   --Doctoral degrees seem necessary for women to move up to senior
jobs, compared to men, who have advanced with lesser academic
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   --Men hold the majority of the most influential and
well-compensated positions in biotech firms.
</P>
<P>
   --Individual negotiations and accommodations remain the primary
ways to set up long-term alternative work arrangements. Typically,
there is no policy that benefits everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Although biotech is seen as a workplace of the future, the study
found that women in biotech still shoulder the majority of family
responsibilites, such as child rearing, despite more flexible hours
than those in other industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opportunities to create more flexible work arrangements that
could benefit both employees and employers are seldom exploited in
any systematic way,'' the report concludes.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Cheryl Murphy, a mother of two and an executive at
Aquila Biopharmaceuticals Inc., has found. Having spent 12 years at
the company and its predecessor, Cambridge Biotechnology Inc., she
said the company is good with informal arrangements if her children
are sick, but there is no flex time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company does not help with day care issues,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Michelle Eldrige, a manufacturing supervisor at
Genzyme Tissue Repair in Cambridge, said company benefits include a
service that helped her to place an advertisement in local papers
to find child care for her two children, along with a flexible
schedule. She works four 10-hour days.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot beat the benefits,'' said Eldridge, who has six men
and no women reporting to her.
</P>
<P>
   The Radcliffe report, which included 100 interviews and five
focus groups, is based largely on studies of employees at three
small Massachusetts companies: Aquila of Framingham, Avant of
Needham, and Cambridge-based Genzyme Tissue Repair, which is a
majority-owned subsidiary of Genzyme Corp. Both Aquila and Avant
have female chief executives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
