A2830 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-NEWS-BOS &LR;      12-08 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-NEWS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN NEWSCASTS GET LURID AS VOTE NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A soft-porn video featuring the federal prosecutor. A
prostitute talking about her politician clients. Public officials
tied to religious cults. A sadistic kidnapper executing a terrified
hostage.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights from the latest Hollywood thriller? No, it's the
prime-time news on Russian television. With parliamentary elections
just weeks away here, television has become a blunt weapon. And as
politicians use their media empires to sling slime at one another
before a cynical and bewildered public, subtlety, and often taste,
are the first victims.
</P>
<P>
   Every Sunday night, Russia's major television networks broadcast
``60 Minutes''-style current affairs programs that are supposed to
enlighten the public about the hot issues of the day. But lately
the issues have become so hot that it is a good idea to put the
kids to bed before watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``These programs are not for young children,'' said Leonid
Kesselman, a St. Petersburg-based sociologist, adding that when he
watches the Sunday night news shows, he makes sure his 6-year-old
son is nowhere near the television set.
</P>
<P>
   The top rated of these programs is ``The Sergei Dorenko Show,''
broadcast on ORT television _ Russia's largest network, reaching 98
percent of this vast country's homes. In October Dorenko showed an
eight-minute film of a man he claimed was federal prosecutor Yury
Skuratov frolicking in bed naked with two prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Before showing the video, Dorenko _ one of Russia's best known
and most trusted news anchors _ looked earnestly into the camera
and told viewers that he ``agonized for a long time about whether
to show the tape,'' but decided that ``nobody can limit the right
of people to know all about their leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorenko did, however, warn parents not to allow their children
to watch, because if they did, they would have ``a hard time
teaching them patriotism.''
</P>
<P>
   Why show a film of prosecutorial sex on the evening news? Most
here say the broadcast and others like it are weapons in Russia's
political battles on the eve of elections.
</P>
<P>
   The ORT network is controlled by Kremlin-connected tycoon Boris
Berezovsky, and the station vigorously protects the interests of
President Boris N. Yeltsin and his inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov found himself on ORT's hit list after he initiated
corruption allegations against Yeltsin's family and some of the
president's closest allies, including Berezovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Another one of Dorenko's and ORT's favorite targets is Moscow
Mayor Yury Luzhkov, a Kremlin foe who heads the opposition
political party Fatherland-All. In a particularly bizarre segment
during a broadcast this week, Dorenko showed an image of Luzhkov's
face and used computer graphics to make him resemble, among other
people, Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Every week, viewers across Russia tune into Dorenko's program.
Some watch because they believe him and think he is exposing
corruption in high places, while others, curious about what Dorenko
will do next, watch for the shock value.
</P>
<P>
   And some simply view his program as a form of comic relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch these programs purely for entertainment and don't take
them seriously,'' said Tatyana Semyonova, a 50-year-old postal
worker. ``Every time I watch these shows it makes me feel superior
to the authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   And for viewers who aren't entertained by what one television
station is offering, changing the channel rarely helps.
</P>
<P>
   On the same night that Dorenko was offering up sex as news,
another station called TV-Center, which is controlled by Luzhkov,
was giving its viewers blood. On a program called ``Secret Files,''
TV-Center broadcast graphic footage of a hostage in Chechnya being
beheaded.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to showing the footage, the show's host said that he had
information that Berezovsky, and by implication the Kremlin, was
tied to kidnapping rings in Chechnya that were committing similar
atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer volume of allegations flying across Russia's airwaves
can be bewildering.
</P>
<P>
   ORT's Dorenko has accused Luzhkov of having ties to the Japanese
cult Aum Shrinrikyo, which in 1995 used sarin gas in a deadly
attack in the Tokyo subway. The station has also accused Luzhkov
and his allies of complicity in the 1996 murder of American
businessman Paul Tatum.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the opposition NTV television station, which
is sympathetic to Luzhkov, offers its viewers a steady diet of
reporting on corruption in the Kremlin. The station has led a
campaign to expose abuses among Yeltsin's inner circle of informal
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all very harmful for the public's trust in the
authorities,'' said Kesselman, the sociologist. ``But in the long
run this could turn out to have a positive effect. The less people
are prepared to trust the authorities, the more they are able to
reach their own conclusions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 1255EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
