<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2832 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-SCHOOL-TESTING-BOS     12-08 1396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-SCHOOL-TESTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPROVEMENTS FOUND IN THIS YEAR'S SCHOOL TEST RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE AND BETH DALEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The wealthiest communities in Massachusetts continue to
produce the most impressive MCAS results, but the more important
scores come from those districts that showed significant
improvement _ a hodgepodge of tiny towns, charter schools, and
small cities sprinkled across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Provincetown, Petersham, Swampscott, Gardner, and the
Renaissance Charter School in Boston all showed notable increases
in this year's MCAS results compared to the 1998 scores, according
to a Globe analysis of the district results released by the state
Department of Education Tuesday. Some of the communities improved
districtwide while others only in certain grades.
</P>
<P>
   Even Boston, whose overall score remains at the bottom of the
MCAS rankings, had some reason to celebrate: Boston schools were
among the top 60 most improved districts in the state.
</P>
<P>
   These districts, among others, had more students who scored
higher than last year's test takers. That means, for example, that
student performance jumped from the `failing' category to `needs
improvement' or from `proficient' to `advanced,' thanks to
everything from educators teaching to the test, to sheer luck.
</P>
<P>
   In the town of Harvard, which for the second year was the number
one scoring school district overall, superintendent Mihran Keoseian
gave partial credit for that achievement to ``the gene pool.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is ours to lose, given the gene pool that comes
through the door,'' Keoseian said. ``Our kids are well-prepared.
But it's not just the kids.'' He said good and disciplined
teaching, an intense focus on writing across the grades, rigorous
homework assignments, and class participation also played a part.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the state imploring districts all year to teach to
the MCAS test, Keoseian said he sent out a mandate that teachers
not teach to the test. Even so, the curriculum and teaching methods
there have again propelled the town's schools to the top of the
MCAS heap.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Comprehensive Assessement System is the
barometer of seven years of Education Reform, an initiative to
equalize education in the state and improve achievement. Given to
students in grades 4, 8, and 10 last spring, the 10th grade exam
will become a requirement for graduation for the class of 2003.
Students will have to pass the math and English portion of the exam
with a score of 220 on both subjects.
</P>
<P>
   While some school districts celebrated their scores, other
educators were also cautious: Small numbers of students being
tested can significantly skew results, it typically takes three
years of data to develop a solid trend, and it will continue to
take years of work to graduate students who will be able to compete
in the global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a very small school in a very small town and if a child
is on either end of this thing, it can change the outcome a lot,''
said Glenede Albertine, the fourth grade teacher at the Petersham
Center School. Petersham had the most improved fourth grade
statewide, with a cumulative score 4 percent higher than last
year's, according to the Globe analysis.
</P>
<P>
   There were only 10 fourth-graders in the school and all took the
exam last year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Albertine and others acknowledged that their efforts at
academic improvements were paying off. After-school, Saturday, and
summer programs, aligning curriculum with MCAS, and encouraging
teachers to band together to push students toward excellence were
all credited with helping boost scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year, we took the approach that we were going to
administer this test without impacting our sacred programs in the
school,'' said Peter Sack, principal of Swampscott High School. The
district was ranked 74th in the state by a Globe analysis last
year, and this year came in 23d.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when we got the (1998) results, we came to a different
conclusion and decided MCAS reigns supreme,'' Sack said, ``and we
did anything we needed to to create a positive testing
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Sack said teachers motivated the 10th graders by, in part,
imploring them to take pride in their community and help educators
figure out how to better prepare other students for the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them, `If you give it your best shot, and we see what
went wrong, we'll know this is an area we can improve on so your
younger brothers and sisters can do better on the test,' '' Sack
said. ``And it worked. The kids did an extraordinary job.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Fay, a headmaster at the 1,140-student Renaissance Charter
School in downtown Boston, credited his students with applying
themselves and showing some of the most improved eighth-grade
scores in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a lot of time with the eighth-graders telling them
they were doing it for themselves, how important it was for them to
get used to test-taking,'' Fay said. ``We extended math and reading
blocks and familarized the kids with test taking and terms. One
year doesn't make a trend but we are working hard here. I am proud
of the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayland this year also can boast about the eighth-grade scores:
Wayland's eighth grade was the best in the state. Principal Richard
Schaye attributes the students' success to changes made after last
year's MCAS results.
</P>
<P>
   ``We increased our emphasis on writing, not just in English, but
in math and science as well. We look at any glaring mismatches
between our curriculum and the frameworks. We made very few
wholesale changes because we don't have enough of a history to know
what we would want to change and what we would not want to
change,'' Schaye said. ``We haven't had time yet to know what
caused the increase and we continue to think that the data won't be
fully useful for three to five years when you can see trends and
the population studied gets larger.''
</P>
<P>
   Other districts that can boast best scores in the state include
Conway, for best in fourth grade, and Cohasset, for best in 10th
grade.
</P>
<P>
   State education officials had no comment on the
district-by-district scores, saying they prefer to focus on
individual schools' improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ranking the districts is the press looking at box scores and
horse racing,'' said the education department's deputy
commissioner, Alan Safran. ``The commissioner is focusing his
attention on how kids achieve despite tremendous challenges . . .
schools that face high poverty rates and still make kids achieve.
That's what it's all about for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The release of the scores also sparked renewed criticism of the
test throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   About 150 educators, parents, and community members in Western
Massachusetts have begun meeting to organize a grass-roots campaign
to suspend testing until there is a statewide dialogue with
educators about what students should be required to know.
</P>
<P>
   And Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly said he expects a court
case to be filed over MCAS because some students are not yet being
taught the material they are being tested on. Indeed, some
curriculum frameworks, such as science, are still incomplete, yet
students are tested on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   But many school officials, regardless of their personal opinions
of MCAS, said they believe MCAS is here to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Provincetown, which won the state's ``most
improved'' recognition both overall and for Grade 8, according to
the Globe analysis, said they are focused on getting students to
perform better on the test and to improve academically overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to acknowledge the work of the principal and staff,''
said Superintendent Susan Fleming. ``We have aligned curriculum,
we're focused on professional development. But staff has encouraged
kids in failure areas to work hard.''
</P>
<P>
   While Fleming noted that her tiny district at the tip of Cape
Cod with only 350 students may have had statistical fluctuations
because of its size, she said school staff hold conferences with
students, give extra help to children doing poorly, and celebrate
those students doing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about getting kids to believe they can do it,'' Fleming
said. ``Now, it's can we keep these scores going in this
direction?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff writer Hermione Malone contribued to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 1256EST &QL; 
