<P>
   PITINO-PITCHMAN (Boston) _ Nowadays, even basketball coaches can
use their star power to market products. Celtics coach Rick Pitino
has business ventures ranging from being pitchman for Citizens Bank
to investing in a thoroughbred race horse and marketing a line of
pasta and sauces. By Gregg Krupa. 1900 words. (f and s coding)
PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-WOMEN (Boston) _ Contrary to popular wisdom that
technology is a man's world, biotechnology is relatively hospitable
to women. The reason has largely to do with balancing work and
family, says a new study. By Ronald Rosenberg. 900 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN (Undated) _ How Eaton Vance turned its small
and withering mutual fund business into what has become, pound for
pound, one of the nation's hottest-selling fund companies. By
Steven Syre and Charles Stein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PATRIOTS (Foxborough, Mass.) -- Amid reawakened playoff
hopes it's easy to forget the 19-yard catch Troy Brown made, just
the play he prides himself on, just the kind the Patriots need. By
Shira Springer. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Colts, at 10-2, are in
first place in the NFL's toughest division, the AFC East, and have
the best young team in the league. By Will McDonough.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
