<HEADLINE>
GLOOMY DAYS ARE GONE FOR EATON VANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think of it as stepping to the plate with two strikes already
against you.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton Vance Corp. was a small mutual fund company competing in
an industry in which a handful of the largest competitors win
nearly all the new business _ week in and week out. Worse, investor
demand for its bread-and-butter bond fund business had all but
evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   Against that forbidding backdrop, the old-line Boston money
management firm has climbed to unlikely prominence as one of the
fund industry's best-selling stories.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton Vance is still no one's idea of a money management giant,
with about $41 billion under management as of Oct. 31. But that
figure is up 41 percent in a year and has nearly doubled over the
last two years.
</P>
<P>
   The company's 1999 mutual fund sales, relative to its assets
already under management, are among the industry's most impressive
and dollar-for-dollar are in a virtual dead heat with the much
larger Putnam Investments through the first nine months of the
year, according to Financial Research Corp., a Boston consulting
firm.
</P>
<P>
   In a market that has lost its appetite for most financial
stocks, Eaton Vance shares are up 53 percent over the last 12
months. They have soared 247 percent over the last three years,
while other local midzsize money management firms like Liberty
Financial Cos. (up 4 percent) and Pioneer Group (down 37 percent)
have gone nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much razzle-dazzle in the strategy that propelled
Eaton Vance out of a gloomy situation, but it has proven to be a
potential growth plan for small money management firms that can't
count on supercharged fund performances to lift them.
</P>
<P>
   The idea: Identify small investment market niches and become a
leading competitor within them.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Eaton Vance was undeniably in trouble. Its
prominence as a manager of municipal bond funds and other
fixed-income investments was scarcely a selling point amid a
roaring stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, top managers who controlled Eaton Vance's voting stock
were divided over whether to sell the company or press on. By
September of 1996, managers who wanted Eaton Vance to remain
independent prevailed, and longtime executive James Hawkes
succeeded M. Dozier Gardner as chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just dead in the water as an equity manager, going
nowhere,'' Hawkes said. ``In fact, we were going backwards. It was
critical for us to create a growth plan to get our equity products
going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Eaton Vance launched a type of investment that was almost
unheard of at the time, a mutual managed to minimize the tax bite
of gains to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tax-managed funds really fit their normal (investment)
profile,'' said mutual fund consultant Geoff Bobroff. ``They were
adroit enough to seize upon it as a strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a product that cut across the fund industry current of
the time, when new investment products all raced to capture money
in 401(k) plans and other retirement plans that faced no immediate
capital gains or income taxes. Often, they traded stocks in their
portfolios to maximize gains without consideration of the tax hit
some customers would pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conflict between who you are serving has grown,'' said
Hawkes. ``Our banner was mutual funds for people who pay taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Awareness of after-tax returns has grown since then, trumpeted
most effectively by Vanguard Group. Now there are many more
competitors, but Eaton Vance's three funds (a fourth will be
offered early next year) own about 25 percent of the tax-managed
niche of the mutual fund market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is early in the process, and the concept will
have legs,'' said John Rekenthaler, research director at
Morningstar Inc. ``It has investment validity.'' He predicts funds
will routinely publish pretax and after-tax performance figures
within a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton Vance's other investment niche: funds that invest in bank
loans. They aren't glitzy and won't generate huge returns, but the
funds have brought billions of dollars worth of business to the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Though more investment firms compete for those customers, Eaton
Vance has its claws on a big chunk of the market.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest threat to the strategy that helped Eaton Vance grow:
success will attract powerful competitors, especially for
tax-managed stock funds.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkes isn't worried yet. Eaton Vance has the only tax-managed
international product on the market, and the original growth fund
is an entrenched favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, the more people are fighting for the business,
the more the (tax-managed) concept is validated,'' he said. ``It's
kind of our song, and everyone else is singing it. If our
performance continues to be strong and we truly deliver a
tax-efficient fund, we'll do just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
