<HEADLINE>
THE SEASONAL SORROWS OF THE JOYES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
The Joyes 
110 Threadwillow Drive 
Bluefish Cove, MA 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Friends,
</P>
<P>
   Here it is: our last Christmas message of the millennium! The
past 12 months have been so busy, it's almost as if we've packed in
a thousand years' worth of fabulous activities since I last wrote
you!
</P>
<P>
   (That's for sure. Managing this family is starting to feel like
a multiple life sentence.)
</P>
<P>
   Jon's successful Y2K consultancy is just wrapping up a few odds
and ends before year-end. World's End Ventures has succeeded beyond
our wildest dreams, and it's comforting to know that Jon's clients,
at least, aren't the ones who will be paying overtime to staff up
their critical facilities on New Year's Eve. Their comfort level
with Jon's superb preparation is 2,000 percent!
</P>
<P>
   (His clients would be nuts to have any living thing within 50
miles of where Jon has worked. He did some software work for
Bluefish Power &AMP; Light, and they've decided to shut down their
generators for 72 hours on either side of New Year's Eve, lest
Jon's data bungling blow everyone to kingdom come. They're sending
free boxes of candles to customers as a subtle hint.)
</P>
<P>
   Jon Jr. is finally out of college, and out of the nest! We think
he's a cinch for law or business school, but he's decided to go his
own way for a while with some educational tourism and exotic
foreign travel. His last letter was from Jerusalem!
</P>
<P>
   (What a future this kid has. Right out of UMass he told us he
got a job as a ``roadie'' _ does that mean drug dealer? _ for a
rock group called Rage Against the Machine. Barely a week later we
spotted him on CNN, stoking fires and hurling Molotov cocktails at
Woodstock '99. The New York state police saw the same footage, so
Jon wired him a one-way ticket to nowhere. Now he's camping
somewhere on the Mount of Olives, peddling magic mushrooms to the
Second Coming crowd. Good work if you can get it . . .)
</P>
<P>
   And how's the ``baby'' of the family? She's 21 years old! We can
hardly believe it! It seems like only yesterday . . . well, I bet
any number of you could fill in the blanks where your own children
are concerned. Johanna's done us proud _ again! _ and decided to go
back to college and finish that degree!
</P>
<P>
   (It seems like only yesterday that she and Tawnee got rousted
for soliciting, except this time they couldn't lap-dance their way
out of juvenile court. The DA laid down the law: Framingham State
or the Framingham Pen. Johanna says she's taking a lot of
ornithology courses to prepare for medical school. Whatever.)
</P>
<P>
   I know, you're thinking: Joyce, what about YOU? Well, I'm just
fine, thank you. My on-line indulgence business,
Send$500You'reSaved.com, proved to be so successful that I sold it
to a multinational conglomerate. I'm using the proceeds to launch
yet another entrepreneurial venture in the travel industry!
</P>
<P>
   (It was when the archdiocese started burning crosses on my lawn
that I thought maybe it was time to sell the pay-for-penance
business back to the people who invented it in the first place. But
I've come up with something even better: East-to-West, first-class
only, round-the-world-plane trips on New Year's Eve!
</P>
<P>
   It's the ultimate millennium party idea _ twenty-fours hours'
worth of New Year's Eve! And the suckers are snapping it up. Wait,
it gets better; I convinced Jon to take the Cairo-Papua New Guinea
flight, by telling him that all the flight attendants were
professional belly dancers. Now if I can just maneuver another
chronically depressed Egypt Air pilot into the cockpit . . .)
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping that 1999 has been as fun and productive for your
family as it has been for ours! A Joye-ous holiday to one and all!
</P>
<P>
   FROM THE JOYES _ JOYCE, JONATHAN, JJ AND JOHANNA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 1302EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
