<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2844 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-BOSSTONES-BOS &LR;      12-08 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BOSSTONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DICKY BARRETT'S IMPRESSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's that time of year again. Shopping. Eating.
Celebrating. Thrashing about an airless subterranean rock club. If
it's December, this must be the Hometown Throwdown _ a raucous,
five-night valentine from the ska-punk heroes the Mighty Mighty
Bosstones to their beloved hometown of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a big year for the Bosstones. The octet scored its
first platinum album (sales exceeding 1 million copies) with
``Let's Face It,'' their fifth album, which soared on the strength
of the hit single ``The Impression That I Get.'' The band was given
a star on the Tower Records Walk of Fame on Newbury Street,
dedicated by none other than the Clash's Joe Strummer.
</P>
<P>
   After 13 years of do-it-yourself career moves, the Bosstones
have signed on with a manager, Arthur Spivak, who also handles Tori
Amos. Perhaps most remarkable is that the Bosstones survived the
Seagrams-Universal megamerger with their record contract, not to
mention their spirits and their integrity, intact. The band is
mixing 21 new songs (recorded at the Longview Farms Studio in
Carlyle, Mass.??) this week in New York, which will ultimately be
whittled down to 15 or 16 for the next Mighty Mighty Bosstones
album, due out in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   At such a dazzling millennial crossroads, it would be downright
irresponsible not to query the Bosstones' dazzling frontman, Dicky
Barrett, for some insights and hindsight, recollections and
predictions, stock-taking and muckraking. To begin, the singer
would like readers to know that, yes, there were some high points
in the past 1,000 years. Neither Limp Bizkit nor Christina Aguilera
was among them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's your fondest Hometown Throwdown memory?
</P>
<P>
   A. I can't really say. They kind of all blur. It's like a week
of standing in a cyclone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's the proudest moment of your career?
</P>
<P>
   A. (Guffaws. . .) I laugh at the word career.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. OK. What's the proudest moment of your pathetic little life?
</P>
<P>
   A. I attribute it to you! I never thought what I do would be
called a career. Really, standing around at the Rat and
entertaining eight friends. The whole band is built around pride.
We're proud of our city, and we're proud of each other.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Complete this sentence: In 20 years I hope to be. . .
</P>
<P>
   A. Buried? No. As happy as I am today.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's the most valuable lesson you've learned?
</P>
<P>
   A.
</P>
<P>
   That I barely know anything and knowing that when you realize
that, you know a lot. I think it might tie in with ignorance is
bliss.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's your biggest regret?
</P>
<P>
   A. At the risk of sounding Sinatra-esque, regrets . . . I've had
so few. Too few to mention.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You're disturbingly well-adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. My friends say, ``Dude, you're still the same dude.''
You know, you have to start out being Marilyn Manson to become
Marilyn Manson. Although he's very pleasant to me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you have a philosophy that sustains you?
</P>
<P>
   A. Nothing I can really put into words. It's the way I live.
I've always considered people to be the most important.
</P>
<P>
   (The conversation derails when first one maid, then another,
lets herself into Barrett's room at Manhattan's tony Paramount
Hotel. Barrett begins ballparking the distance from his bed to the
wall (12 inches), his bed to the bathroom (12 inches), and his bed
to the front door (12 inches). The mathematical correlation between
the room size and the nightly rate troubles him.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's your favorite beer?
</P>
<P>
   A. This is bad, but I like Budweiser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does plaid matter?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yeah. Absolutely, to me and my life. It's definitely the
flag. When we first started wearing it there was very little plaid
anywhere, and it was one of the things we did to set ourselves
apart. Fans latched onto it, the symbolism of it, the multicolors,
coming from north, south, east, and west. Plaid is the symbol of
everything we are. We don't cover everything we own any more, but
it's in our hearts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What are you doing New Year's Eve?
</P>
<P>
   A. Nothing. Absolutely nothing. But there are people already
staking out their spots in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   (Brief but poignant discussion ensues about Dick Clark's
diminished role in the upcoming New Year's festivities, followed by
discussion of whether Clark rang in Y1K.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are you going Hollywood? (Barrett recently appeared as Bill
Haley in the television film ``Shake, Rattle, and Roll'')
</P>
<P>
   A. Oh, yeah. The offers are just rolling in for the Bill Haley
guy. I'm gonna be like Adam West, the guy who played Batman on TV.
I'm gonna be (upset) if other people play Bill Haley.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's the best thing about Boston?
</P>
<P>
   A. Everything. It's such a wonderful place. Name a category.
History? People? Music? Growing up I never even thought I'd ever
see any place else. (He grew up in Norwood and since then has lived
in several Boston neighborhoods and Cambridge.) I've never been
tempted to leave. Now having been to so many different places, I
still feel the same way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What would you like to do that you haven't done?
</P>
<P>
   A. I'd like to do a good TV appearance. This is probably pretty
shallow and selfish of me. But this is strictly the band. . . . We
haven't done Letterman or ``Saturday Night Live'' and been
satisfied with it. I'd also like to solve Boston's homeless
problem. One or the other.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. If you could go back in time and change anything, what would
you change?
</P>
<P>
   A. Bill Haley's haircut. I'd give him a cooler 'do.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Project a few weeks into the future and complete this
sentence: On the first day of Christmas, my true love gave to me .
. .
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't really want to tell you. Well, I don't need anything.
I get nice sweaters and really good books.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Choose four objects to put into a time capsule that will be
opened in 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   A. A plaid jacket. The Red Sox were really classy this year. OK,
they didn't go all the way. But I wasn't disappointed. So a Red Sox
cap. I'd probably put in Michael MacDonald's book, ``All Souls.''
It's about a kid from Southie. And how about a Clash album? I would
say the boxed set, ``Clash on Broadway.'' We need something punk
rock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 1303EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
