<HEADER>
A2854 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-EXPENSIVE-NEWYEARS-BO     12-08 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPENSIVE-NEWYEARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA PAIR TO PUT ON THE RITZ WITH $100,000 NEW YEAR'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE HATFIELD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ She likes caviar and champagne, rubrum lilies, and
staying at the Ritz-Carlton.
</P>
<P>
   He likes racing his antique cars around the world, waltz
evenings, dressing in black tie, and staying at the Ritz.
</P>
<P>
   They are the kind of people you might expect to buy the hotel's
sole ``Ultimate Millennium Experience'' package for New Year's
weekend in Boston _ and they did, for a cool $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Why, you might ask, would Wendy and Dean Edmonds leave their
lovely Florida home and fancy club to come north for what could be
one of the coldest weekends of the winter? ``The Ritz is an old
hangout from previous days,'' says Dean S. Edmonds Jr., a New York
native who attended Massachusetts Institute of Technology and lived
here most years from 1943 to 1991, before retiring as a physics
professor at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up another reason to celebrate the change from 1999
to 2000, according to Edmonds, an aeronautics authority who writes
college physics texts. ``This is the first turn of the century in
400 years which happens to be a leap year,'' says Edmonds, 74,
whose father was a leading patent lawyer and prominent investor.
</P>
<P>
   A fine ballroom dancer, according to those who know him, the
younger Edmonds was a regular at Boston's waltz evenings and the
Consul's Ball during the years he lived and taught here. He is a
Gilbert and Sullivan aficionado. And he owns two airplanes, 14
cars, and a Type 55 Bugatti roadster that has won prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Edmonds, who met her husband during a party at a
Ritz-Carlton in Florida, says, ``I'm from Boston. I adore Boston
and have spent lots of time at the Ritz there. They do everything
so beautifully, and they're working with us in planning this
weekend so that it is going to be unforgettable.''
</P>
<P>
   She is the former Wendy Adams of Manchester, born in Cohasset,
the daughter of E. Carlton Nickerson of the Chatham and Orleans
Nickersons, and is a Mayflower descendant. The Barnstable campus of
Cape Cod Community College is about to be named Nickerson Campus
after her father.
</P>
<P>
   She learned how to race antique cars before she met her husband,
helped him restore their 1927 Bentley, and races with him in
Florida, Texas, and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what they'll get for $100,000 when they return for the
millennium:
</P>
<P>
   The Ritz celebration begins when the couple, who just celebrated
their sixth anniversary, are picked up at Logan Airport in a
chauffeur-driven Jaguar on the afternoon of Dec. 30 and brought to
the Presidential Suite, the hotel's premier room. The suite has its
own dining room and 24-hour private butler service.
</P>
<P>
   They won't need to carry a lot of luggage. His tails and dinner
jackets and her gowns (one of which is being made of cream-colored
duchesse satin in Florida and then flown to New York, where a
furrier will add a sable edge) will be sent ahead of time, pressed,
and settled into the closet of the Presidential Suite before the
couple's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of the 30th, the Edmondses have asked six friends
to a special dinner in the Ritz wine cellar, the menu of which she
has been planning since July. ``I want very special wines,'' she
says, adding that one will be the great old French wine Petrus,
from Bordeaux. A violinist will entertain the diners.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be many courses,'' she says. ``I've thought about
having everything _ all the food _ be white. We had a dinner
similar to that in Venice with friends, and it was very nice. If we
don't have all white food, we will at least include white truffles
in the menu.'' They'll also have a private cocktail party for those
friends in their suite before going to the wine cellar.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of New Year's Eve, they will enjoy breakfast in
bed and be treated to a massage as part of the package. ``I'll be
drinking champagne all day and will just enjoy having no `home
work,' which for me means organizing and running the . . . house
and gardening down there'' in Florida, says Wendy Edmonds.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband will receive an 18-karat gold Bulgari Chrono watch
with crocodile-skin strap and she a ladies' 18-karat gold Bulgari
Quadrato watch with Tubogas bracelet as part of the package.
They'll get a magnum of Taittinger champagne and two Baccarat
crystal flutes in a custom-designed gift box, in addition to a
photo album, engraved stationery, and Bulgari perfume.
</P>
<P>
   Before going downstairs to the Ritz grand ballroom to dine and
dance to the live music of Peter Duchin, the couple plan to jump
into the Jag and pop over to Brookline for the annual New Year's
Eve party given by a close friend from BU days, Howard B. Gottlieb,
founder and director of the university's Department of Special
Collections. Dean Edmonds is a director of the BU Library.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Edmonds will add a tiara to her cream-colored ensemble _
``Why not?'' she says. ``The Ritz always makes me feel cosseted,
like a queen.'' She has other gowns for the other two nights she'll
be at the Ritz, but for New Year's Eve, the skirt is full and the
ensemble will include a sable-trimmed matching cape.
</P>
<P>
   On the first morning of the year 2000, the Ritz will put on a
brunch for the Edmondses' extended family from the Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   There'll be a final private dinner in the Presidential Suite for
six more friends on Jan. 2. That dinner also will be black tie, and
the special Chateau Yquem will be one of the wines served. Wendy
has arranged for Gilbert and Sullivan entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Their limo will take them to the airport on Jan. 3 for the trip
back to Florida. ``I guess it was my idea to do this at first,''
says Wendy Edmonds. ``We usually travel to Europe each fall, and
then we usually spend New Year's Eve at our club in Florida. But I
said, for the millennium, let's go to the Ritz. They will fill our
room with flowers and candles, and they have been so fabulous about
planning this weekend. I don't think I could wish for anything
more. I guess you could call it `buying a memory.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 1306EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
