<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2861 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FIREFIGHTER-TRADITION     12-08 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREFIGHTER-TRADITION-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREFIGHTING FAMILY GRAPPLES WITH A HISTORY FULL OF SORROW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ James McGuirk remembers how he and other
neighborhood children would run after the fire engines that clanged
past their homes. He would scamper along proudly, point at the man
perched on the end of the ladder and shout, ``That's my Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   McGuirk also recalls how he and other friends would gather at
the station in the city's Burncoat section, climb all over the fire
engines and slide down the fire pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The firemen were heroes to us, just by being there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To McGuirk they were also family.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1942, when James's father, Francis A. McGuirk, grew weary
of his wire factory job and joined the Worcester Fire Department,
the McGuirks have carried on a proud tradition serving on the
firefighting force.
</P>
<P>
   Francis McGuirk's brother William joined after him. Then came
their sister Catherine's son, their sister Mary's son, their sister
Alice's son and two grandsons, and then William's son.
</P>
<P>
   Nine McGuirks in all have served, including Joseph T. McGuirk,
38, of Leicester, who died in the fire at the Worcester Cold
Storage and Warehouse Co. building Friday. The family has
collectively given more than 200 years of service to the
department.
</P>
<P>
   And they have suffered heavily for it.
</P>
<P>
   When Joseph McGuirk, affectionately known as Joey, perished in
the blaze that engulfed the warehouse, he became the fifth McGuirk
to die of fire-related injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The family was always aware of the risks of what they considered
an honorable calling. James McGuirk said his father tried not to
speak of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want to worry us,'' said McGuirk, his eyes filling
with tears. ``But what happened to Joey is something we all grew up
with. We knew what the risks were.''
</P>
<P>
   In those early days, the work held even more peril. Until the
1970s, Worcester firefighters did not have individual air tanks to
protect them from the fumes. ``Firemen were smoke eaters,'' said
McGuirk, now 61, who heads the science department at South High
Community School.
</P>
<P>
   He said he watched his uncle, William T. McGuirk Sr., die of
fire-related damage to his heart and lungs. His own father and his
cousin Robert Johnson died of heart problems that were deemed to be
job-related. Another cousin, John McMahon, died from injuries
sustained on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough job,'' said William T. McGuirk Jr., Joseph's
brother, who retired in 1985 after 20 years of service. ``But the
equipment's getting better all the time. And you help save a life,
save someone's property. It's very gratifying.''
</P>
<P>
   There were McGuirks on the scene on March 3, 1946, when sheets
of flames, whipped by high winds, leapt 300 feet in the air from
the North Works warehouse of the American Steel and Wire Co. before
firefighters quelled the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   McGuirks battled in sweltering summer heat on July 12, 1960,
when fires raged out of control for four hours, gutting the Charles
Dowd Box Co. warehouse on Ludlow Street.
</P>
<P>
   McGuirks fought the tragic flash fire in the Indian Hill section
of Worcester in 1968, when five teenagers were trapped in their
clubhouse and died; and the inferno that destroyed two plastic
factories in Webster Square on May 4, 1977; and the arson blaze
that claimed seven lives on April 20, 1983, in the Central
Community House about two blocks north of Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   The McGuirks came from Ireland, emigrating during the Great
Potato Famine of 1847. They began in eastern Canada and made their
way to Worcester in the 1880s, where they worked as tenant farmers
or factory workers in the wire mills.
</P>
<P>
   Charles McGuirk came to Worcester as a child and married an
Irish immigrant, Annie Doyle. They had 14 children; nine survived.
Francis A. McGuirk was the only one of his siblings to get any
college education.
</P>
<P>
   He was a family leader. ``Everyone looked up to him,'' said his
son, James.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph T. McGuirk, who died in Friday's fire, was the most
recent member of the family to be inducted into the force, having
been sworn in two years ago this week.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of his relatives, he had always wanted to be a
firefighter and quickly bonded with the others in his unit, Engine
No. 3. ``He was very friendly, popular, and well-respected,'' said
Bernie Bastardo, 56, a fellow firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   Bastardo remembered other McGuirk relatives, Joseph McGuirk's
cousins, who became firefighters: Robert Johnson, who served from
1949 to 1974, ``a very professional guy with a good sense of
humor,'' he said; and feisty John J. McMahon, who fought fires for
more than 35 years before his death in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all knew each other. We're all working-class people, all in
the same boat together. . . . We like going to work,'' Bastardo
said. ``And we're all hurting now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bastardo was sitting with some of his comrades on a concrete
bunker Tuesday near the charred remains of the warehouse. Behind
them, a fire engine was festooned with wreaths, flowers, and notes
of gratitude for the six men who died.
</P>
<P>
   Workers were still sifting through the smoldering rubble, but
treacherous conditions continued to make their search difficult.
Only one body had been found.
</P>
<P>
   William T. McGuirk was standing near the fire engine, exhausted
by the vigil at the fire scene.
</P>
<P>
   But he seemed to speak for all the McGuirks when he reflected on
their firefighting tradition: ``It's in the bloodlines. It's in
this family,'' he said. ``It's a dedication, like a calling.''
</P>
<P>
   The fatigue and frustration of the search for his brother's body
were in his voice, and the sadness of yet another loss for a family
that has given so much for Worcester.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
