<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN COALITION PONDERS WOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition, once a powerful political and religious
force, is facing serious financial and organizational problems.
</P>
<P>
   The direct-mail fund-raiser for the coalition, which was once
the leading voice of the religious right, has sued the group for
nonpayment of bills, and the coalition's Washington lobbying chief
has quit.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit filed in Alexandria, Va., Stephen Winchell and
Associates accused the coalition of failing to pay $400,000 in
bills even though the company helped raise $7 million for the
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Randy Tate, the coalition's top Washington lobbyist
and its former executive director, has stepped down.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition spokesman Chris Freund insisted that the organization
was not in any serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we have some financial and other issues to deal
with,'' Freund said. ``But, again, we're quite confident we can.
We're looking forward to the new year.''
</P>
<P>
   Tate's departure, according to published reports, leaves very
few people in senior management position at the coalition's
Washington headquarters who were in those same posts a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition reorganized itself following an Internal Revenue
Service ruling that denied the group's tax-exempt status.
</P>
<P>
   Freund said the coalition's current debt was about $2 million,
which he said was ``manageable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some vendors we owe some money to, but we're working
out repayment schedules,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After being founded by Pat Robertson in 1989, following his
unsuccessful presidential bid, the coalition reached its high point
in the mid-1990s when it was led by Ralph Reed, who left to become
a campaign adviser. The organization has struggled ever since.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The traditional view of family is threatened by ``narrow
individualism and ethical relativism,'' Pope John Paul II said last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The pontiff warned of ``disastrous consequences'' if society
jettisons the view of family based on marriage between a man and a
woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some sectors of society question the very understanding of the
family as a stable community founded on marriage between a man and
a women,'' John Paul told about 7,000 people who attended his
weekly general audience at the Vatican. ``New definitions of
marriage and the family are being put forward which foster narrow
individualism and ethical relativism.''
</P>
<P>
   And he warned, ``Where the family gives way, society lacks its
connective tissue with disastrous consequences that attack people,
particularly the weakest, from children to adolescents to the
handicapped, the sick, and the elderly.''
</P>
<P>
   --After several years of trying, the Swedish Church of
Scientology has persuaded that nation's government to grant the
church tax-exempt status.
</P>
</TEXT>
