<HEADER>
A2875 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-JESUS-BAPTIZE-BOS &LR;      12-08 1495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESUS-BAPTIZE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLASH OF CLAIMS IN THE HOLY LAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WADI KHARRAR, Jordan _ Five years ago, this was a front line in
the Arab-Israeli conflict _ a barren desert landscape interrupted
only by barbed wire, an infantry battalion's watchtower, and a
field of small flags marking land mines buried beneath the chalky
terrain.
</P>
<P>
   As troops redeployed after the peace agreement between Jordan
and Israel in 1994, a tank rolled over what appeared to be an
ancient foundation, and its treads revealed a mosaic tile floor.
</P>
<P>
   Following the chance find, Jordanian archeologist Mohammad
Waheeb waited for specialists to finish the tedious task of
clearing the land mines, then began his work. After two years of
studying biblical texts and dating archeological artifacts, Waheeb
concluded he had found the site where Jesus was baptized by John
the Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what the Gospel According to John describes as
`Bethany beyond the Jordan,' '' said Waheeb, holding an open Bible
in one hand and a rolled map in the other as he squinted in the
early morning sun across the desert plain and toward the eastern
banks of the Jordan River.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very holy place. Can you feel it?'' he asked as a dry
wind rolled across the sands and the sun baked the desert expanse.
</P>
<P>
   His conclusions, which could prove to be some of the most
significant in biblical archeology in decades, have made this place
a front line once again: not a military front, but a forward
position in the battle between Israel and Jordan over tourists'
dollars _ potentially hundreds of millions of dollars _ as
Christian pilgrims flock to the Holy Land to retrace the path of
Jesus on the 2000th anniversary of his birth.
</P>
<P>
   On the West Bank of the Jordan River, Israel also lays claim to
what it believes is the spot where Jesus was baptized, at a place
at the mouth of the Jordan not far from Jericho, a location that
Israeli maps refer to as ``Kasser-el-Yahud'' _ ``Fortress of the
Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   The rival claims represent a classic Holy Land struggle _ one in
which the Jewish state and a neighboring Muslim kingdom squabble
over a sacred Christian site.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's Minister of Tourism and Antiquities, Aqel Biltaji,
quipped, ``If people want to go to the West Bank of the Jordan
River, we are not going to stop them. We are just saying they are
in the wrong place.''
</P>
<P>
   And Israel's Uri Mor, director of the division of Christian
communities in the Ministry of Religious Affairs, responded, ``How
do they know he (John the Baptist) lived there? Do they have any
proof? Pilgrims have been coming to the site at Kasser-el-Yahud for
years now, and they're used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The bickering can leave even the most faithful feeling cynical
about the millennial hype around the 3 to 4 million tourists
expected to come to the Holy Land over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, this has become about the crass materialism of
the tourist trade,'' said Father Jerome Murphy-O'Connor, a
Dominican priest and renowned biblical historian who has lived in
Jerusalem for 30 years. ``The thing to remember is the spirituality
a Christian believer could feel on either side of the river.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jordan, which flows south from Mount Hermon to the Sea of
Galilee, becomes a slow, winding, olive-colored stream before it
empties into the Dead Sea at 1,300 feet below sea level.
</P>
<P>
   On the Jordanian side, about two miles east from where it feeds
into the Dead Sea, a small hill overlooks a thin patch of reeds
around a natural spring. Here, Waheeb, working with 20
archeologists and 100 laborers, has unearthed the stone foundations
of three early Christian monasteries, a chapel, and three pools
used to collect water from the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the type of ceramic material used in an aqueduct
leading to one of the pools and the mortar used in construction of
one monastery, Waheeb believes the structures could date as far
back as the third century A.D. Waheeb says he has also found coins
and pottery that date to the first century, at about the time that
John the Baptist was ``a voice in the wilderness,'' as scripture
tells it, performing his ministry in this remote desert outpost.
</P>
<P>
   The Jordanian government has spent $1 million on excavating the
site and is now investing a further $6 million, most of it coming
from the US Agency for International Development, to develop it for
tourism.
</P>
<P>
   With the clearing of land mines in the final stage, Jordan hopes
to turn this sand-blown, fly-infested, arid land into a tourist
mecca. There are plans for hotels, a visitors center, a John the
Baptist Research Center, and baptismal pools for the ritual
anointing of Christian pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
   Officials hope to open the site, which is today still a closed
military area, to tourism by March, when the Pope is expected to
tour the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religious tourism depends on religious sites, and we have just
added one of the most sacred sites in Christianity,'' boasted
Beltaji from his office at Jordan's Tourism Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   One American official in Jordan, who asked not to be identified,
expressed some skepticism about the project, calling the archeology
``a Toys-R-Us operation'' and suggesting that the plans for
development were grandiose. But Beltaji is a believer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are blessed in this land to have been visited by the
prophets of the Bible, including John the Baptist. And we eagerly
want to share that with the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Jordan may have a strong emerging market here is that
Israel has not been so eager to share its site.
</P>
<P>
   When Israel captured the area from Jordan in 1967, frequent
cross-border attacks and terrorism led the Israelis to restrict
access. It is still a declared ``military area'' in which Christian
churches are permitted to hold pilgrimages and prayer services only
three times a year.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1967 war, tens of thousands of Orthodox Christians
from the West Bank and Jerusalem would flock to the river bank
during holy days on traditional pilgrimages that went back at least
1,000 years. There are monasteries and chapels there built on
foundations dating back to the fourth and fifth centuries, which
have been built and rebuilt as a result of earthquakes and wars.
</P>
<P>
   But Biblical historians say the tradition of pilgrimages on the
west side grew up as a matter of convenience. Most pilgrims came
from Jerusalem, and it was easier to observe the baptism site from
the west than to hire a boat to cross the river.
</P>
<P>
   In part because of Jordan's aggressive plans to promote its
site, Israel is now planning to open the Kasser-el-Yehud site for
expanded tourism. Israeli officials have been quoted in local
newspapers as saying that by next year as many as 10 buses a day
would be permitted to the site, which is currently flanked by
barbed wire fencing that reads ``Land mines: Danger.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, in response to Christian complaints about the
restrictions on access to Kasser-el-Yahud, Israel opened a tourist
center at Kibbutz Kinneret, where the Jordan flows out of the Sea
of Galilee. Although it is some 65 miles north of the actual site,
the kibbutz has done a booming business. Tourists from America and
Europe come in sandals and sun hats and fill up soda bottles with
river water they consider holy.
</P>
<P>
   The truth of the matter is that biblical archaelogy can be more
of an interpretive art than a science, especially in a part of the
world where earthquakes, war, and the shifting sands of time have
endlessly altered the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Still, archeological experts who have visited the Jordanian site
say the findings at Wadi Kharrar are solid. And Jordanian scholars'
reading of scripture is sound in that the gospels place Jesus on
the east side of the Jordan before he was baptized.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very intriguing findings,'' said Rev. Eugenio
Alliata, an archeologist with the Roman Catholic Order of
Franciscans, which has custody of holy sites. The foundations at
Wadi Kharrar ``certainly date back at least to the fifth century,
and there is a strong basis of fact to say that John the Baptist
would have used this site for baptisms.''
</P>
<P>
   Alliata described the finding as one of the most significant
since the discovery in 1968 of the house of St. Peter on the banks
of the Galilee in Caperneum.
</P>
<P>
   But Alliata said that even though John the Baptist may have
worked on the east bank of the Jordan River, the gospels place
Jesus' baptism in the River Jordan itself, not at the spring where
Jordanian archeologists and officials claim it happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these locations are very close to each other and can be
placed within a high degree of certainty within a mile or so,''
said Alliata.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth,'' he added, is that ``observing the spot where
Jesus Christ was baptized can be done from the east or the west. It
doesn't matter which side of the river you are on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
