<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE WASHINGTON'S EXAMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He went riding during a December snowfall, developed a sore
throat and died two days later at his Mount Vernon estate. Two
centuries after his death, American conservatives can claim George
Washington, mostly because liberals are still stuck in 1960s
pacificism.
</P>
<P>
   Political wars over his legacy were as intense as those over his
graven image. A 1772 portrait by Charles Wilson Peale is both more
soldierly and more humane than the unfinished Gilbert Stuart
portrait of Washington sternly pondering his toothache, so familiar
on dollar bills and February auto sales. This is the ``Athenaeum
portrait,'' named after the Boston institution that owned it.
Painted in 1796, it seems unfinished because the artist was still
selling copies before delivering the final product to Martha
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Another Boston institution, the Old North Church, has owned
since 1817 a bust that shows the general apparently without his
irksome choppers. In 1824, when the Marquis de Lafayette visited
the church, he remarked, ``Yes, that is the man I know and more
like him than any other portrait.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington, 67, died Dec. 14, 1799, some 45 years before the
invention of the telegraph. News traveled slowly then, gathering
the majestic moss of myth and legend. Geographer Allan R. Pred , in
``Urban Growth and the Circulation of Information,'' charted how
long it took for the news of Washington's death to reach the
frontiers of the new nation he heled build: a week to reach New
York, 11 days to Boston, 19 days to Kentucky, and 24 days to
western Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   He took no salary as commanding general of the revolutionary
forces or as president. He shunned all royal trappings, which only
increased his popularity. His successor as president and skeptical
admirer was calm in his appraisal. ``Instead of adoring Washington,
mankind should applaud the nation which educated him,'' John Adams
said in 1785. ``I glory in the character of a Washington, because I
know him to be only an exemplification of the American character.''
</P>
<P>
   A plaster-saint depiction by Mason Locke Weems, an Episcopal
parson, infantilized the life of Washington into a mush of copybook
maxims and chopped-down cherry tree. By the 1960s, such caricatures
enraged the history-is-bunk brigades and quarantined Washington
from liberal approval.
</P>
<P>
   When the tall Virginian confronted skeptical New England troops
at Cambridge Common in July of 1775, he could have been taking
command of Woodstock Nation. He saw, he said, ``a mixed multitude
of people . . . under very little discipline, order, or
government.''
</P>
<P>
   By next March 17, after Henry Knox transported the cannons of
Fort Ticonderoga 300 snowy miles, Washington trained the captured
weapons on the British fleet and liberated Boston
</P>
<P>
   He was not a notably successful general, unlike U.S. Grant or
George S. Patton. But he stood for the superiority of civilian
rule, which alone should endear him to liberals. His Farewell
Address condemned ``those overgrown military establishments which,
under any form of government, are inauspicious to liberty.''
Another old soldier, Dwight D. Eisenhower, echoed this warning in
his own farewell in 1960, coining ``the military-industrial
complex.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Vietnam hangover finally subsides, Washington may
become a liberal hero again. In the meantime, conservative scholars
assess him with varying degrees of success.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Richard Norton Smith, who has been director of both the
Herbert Hoover and the Gerald R. Ford presidential libraries,
published ``Patriarch,'' which focused on the nation's first
presidency, on ``George Washington under political, not military
siege,'' when the old general ``sparked more awe than affection.''
Smith concedes that ``George Washington is out of fashion, too
remote in time and temperament, too encased in marbled veneration,
to engage our emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   But in 1996, Richard Brookhiser, an editor of National Review,
confidently wrote ``a moral biography, in the tradition of
Plutarch,'' whom, he notes, ``was very popular with 18th century
Americans; they knew something about the power of example that we
have forgotten. When he lived, Washington had the ability to give
strength to debates and to dying men. His life still has the power
to inspire anyone who studies it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 1313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
