<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NOT-SO-SUPERMARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve McQueen was lucky. He fought the Blob only in a movie. We
are attacked on every trip to the supermarket. The oozing monster
in McQueen's 1958 movie has been likened to a scary cherry Jell-O.
Today, the Jell-O is still coming for you in the baking aisle.
Aiieeee! You turn. You run. You make it to the corner into the next
aisle. You think you have escaped.
</P>
<P>
   But noooooo! You turn the corner only to see an avalanche of
corn chips and potato chips cascading off the shelves. Eeeeeek! You
turn. You run for the next aisle. You think you are safe. But
noooooo! You turn into the next aisle only to stare up at a
oncoming tidal wave of soda pop. You scream. You turn. You run for
your life. You flee for the fruits, vegetable, and tofu. You are
bawling in the fetal position, partially out of fear, and partially
because you hid behind the onions.
</P>
<P>
   You stay until you think the Blob has passed. Whimpering,
shaking uncontrollably, and crouched down on all fours, you inch
toward the checkout counter. You make it. You think . . .
</P>
<P>
   Noooooo! Just as you go ``Whew,'' you hear an ominous rumble.
You were so focused on the checkout counter, you did not see the
brick wall of candy collapsing on you. You look up, but now you are
too weak. You cannot scream. You cannot turn. You cannot run. You
are buried. You are engulfed.
</P>
<P>
   You become the Blob itself.
</P>
<P>
   We will not kill the Blob until we blow up the supermarket.
After new studies that found over 50 percent of US adults to be
overweight, Jeffrey Koplan, director of the Centers for Disease
Control, proclaimed obesity an ``epidemic.'' Part of the reason, he
said, was ``the availability of more food and foods with higher
energy content, the growth of the fast-food industry, the increased
numbers and marketing of snack foods.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere are such foods more available than at the supermarket.
The United States produces enough ``food'' to jam 3,800 calories a
day into every American (which really means more since tiny
children don't need that many). This is up from 3,300 calories per
person, per day in 1970. The average man and woman need only 2,500
and 2,000 calories a day, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Most nutritionists say the rise in calories comes mostly from
junk foods. The food pyramids put out by the government urge us to
eat mostly grains, fruits, and vegetables and a moderate amount of
meat, fish, and dairy. As for fats, oils and sweets, the advice is
to ``use sparingly.''
</P>
<P>
   The supermarket uses a perverted inverted pyramid. Around
Boston, I paced a Star Market in Cambridge, a Stop &AMP; Shop in
Lexington, and the Washington Park Supermarket in Roxbury. Using my
normal gait (I figured a tape measure would attract attention), I
measured the aisles of allegedly edible products in footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   All the stores, whether working class or wealthy, were houses of
nutritional horrors. On average, 33 percent of the shelves were
loaded with the empty calories of sugar drinks, chips, candy, and
desserts. This was nearly twice the space for fruits and vegetables
(18 percent), three times the space for meat and seafood (10
percent) and six times the space for non-caloric items such as
coffee, tea, spices, and water (5 percent).
</P>
<P>
   This is conservative, excluding the galling aisle of sugar
cereals, since a lightweight argument could be made that you can
find a couple of grains and vitamins under the snowpack of sugar. A
box of Cocoa Krispies takes such liberties, as it features
basketball star Grant Hill holding up the food pyramid. The pyramid
says to eat sweets sparingly. The second ingredient in Cocoa
Krispies is sugar.
</P>
<P>
   This is perplexing. No one holds a gun to your head to go to
McDonald's. But unless you have a year-round hothouse,
slaughterhouse, and a thresher in the backyard, and a couple of
Guernseys in your cellar, you do have to go to a supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   Supermarkets are not passive places. Unpackaged, unloved, and
monotonous walls of green vegetables compete with trash packaged in
circus colors to convince us to eat every last one of those 3,800
calories. The 1998 spending on advertising in the United States by
Hershey, Mars, Coke, and Pepsi (Pepsi sells Lay's and Doritos
chips) was $3 billion. That would fund the Boston public schools
for six years.
</P>
<P>
   Again, you might say, no one forced you to throw that Reese's
into the cart. But a study published this year by researchers at
the University of Wisconsin and the University of California at
Berkeley found that impulse buying accounts for 68 percent of
purchases at supermarkets and mass merchandisers.
</P>
<P>
   The supermarkets exploit this by placing the trash everywhere.
You never see brussel sprouts in aisles for Jell-O, but you find
candy hanging over vegetables, soda with fresh fruit, cookies next
to meat, and pastries next to the seafood.
</P>
<P>
   The government's pyramid has no chance against this disaster.
One of every three feet of the shelves tempt you with trash.
Temptation means certain capture. Empty calories go in, pounds ooze
onto our bellies. Until we change this, the terror continues. In
1958, the Blob was an alien. Today, it is us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
