<HEADLINE>
PSST! HERE'S HOW TO GET THE PASSWORD
</HEADLINE>
 CPT- COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  DEAR DR.
BOMBAY: My son uses WordPerfect 5.2. He saved his letters and notes
to a file and used a password that he cannot remember. I was told
that there was a ``password-cracking'' software program that could
solve our problem. Let me hasten to add that I am not a hacker.
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ No Entry
</P>
<P>
   DEAR NO: You promise you're not going to use this information to
hack into your boss's steamy love letters to that redhead in
Accounting? Good! I knew I could trust you.
</P>
<P>
   Normally I don't like to hand out information that could be used
for anything other than benevolent purposes, unless, of course,
it's part of some practical joke that will make somebody look
really, really stupid. But maybe if I tell you how to break back
into your own documents, other people will realize how silly it is
to try to protect anything with a password as long as there are
legions of four-eyed, dateless geeks out there spending every
waking hour cracking every password they come across.
</P>
<P>
   Just go to Yahoo! and search for ``wpcrack'' or ``wpuncryp,''
and you'll find dozens of pages full of cracking tools for almost
every popular application. How secure do you you feel now?
Remember, the only totally protected document is the one on the
floppy in your shirt pocket.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Can I type a letter in Microsoft Works, then
get on the Internet and transfer that letter to e-mail? I have been
typing the letters in the e-mail program, but sometimes, if it is
more than a few lines I will lose the dial-up connection.
</P>
<P>
   _ Postage Due
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DUE: I got in the habit of composing offline back in the
olden days, when America Online actually used to charge by the
minute. It's not that I was cheap, but with all the big words I use
to impress people, I spent most of my time thumbing through a
thesaurus.
</P>
<P>
   Write your letter in just about any Windows word processor, then
define the entire thing by dragging your mouse through it with the
left button held down. Some programs will do it for you if you
press Control-A. Now copy the defined text to the Windows Clipboard
(a temporary holding area) with Control-C, or go to your program's
Edit menu and select Copy. Connect to the Internet, call up your
e-mail program and start a new letter. Paste the contents of the
Clipboard into the letter with Control-V. You might have to poke
around your mail program's menus if Control-V doesn't do the
pasting.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Would you have any idea where I might find an
old Windows 95 program called Microsoft Bob? I have inquired at
local computer stores and have had no luck.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bobless
</P>
<P>
   DEAR BOBLESS: You're just lucky I'm not going to take a cheap
shot. Well, maybe I spoke too soon. Bob was Microsoft's goofy
attempt to dumb down Windows with a warm-and-fuzzy user interface.
It installed on top of Windows, turning a $3,000 investment in
computing horsepower into something that looked like it was made by
Playskool. Bob was slow, cranky and bug-riddled, and, as a
graphical interface, it made an excellent Frisbee. In fact, I had a
copy up until a few weeks ago when I needed something to fling at
the neighbor's toy poodle.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, this was not one of Microsoft's shining moments,
and it's doubtful you'll find a copy at any retailer. Try computer
swap meets or post a query in some of the Microsoft newsgroups on
the Net. If nothing else, it'll give people a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay says he recently supersized a meal he
obtained from the former Bob project manager, but we think he's
exaggerating again. Bob aficionados may complain to
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: 390-7257. In
real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-03-99 1330EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
