<SLUG> BC-BUYER'S-EDGE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love to buy, hate to wrap? Let someone else take over
 &HT;    By Sabine Morrow
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Deck the halls, trim the tree, shop till you drop and
then sit back and enjoy all that the holiday season has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Whoa! Don't put your feet up and start sipping that eggnog just
yet.
</P>
<P>
   There's one more monumental chore to undertake, and it's one
most of us dread about as much as opening those credit card bills
in January: wrapping all the loot.
</P>
<P>
   You can take the Martha Stewart approach and dig out the glue
gun, brandish enough gold paint to gild the neighborhood and even
print your own wrapping paper. Or you can let someone else's nimble
fingers do the cutting, folding and taping for you.
</P>
<P>
   Most large department stores offer gift-wrapping services. Of
course, it's a hassle to stand in line with an armful of robes,
shirts and Uncle Buddy's favorite brand of gym socks. However, many
places will let you drop off the gifts and return for them later.
Remember, you'll pay for a wrap job, unless you have a preferred
customer card, which some major stores offer to their most prized
credit customers.
</P>
<P>
   Many boutiques and gift shops offer free gift wrapping and a few
already have selected items prewrapped _ as do the big department
stores. Some stores that don't offer gift wrapping provide
complimentary signature boxes that don't need any embellishment.
For instance, Nordstrom's elegant metallic boxes are almost as
welcome as the gifts they contain.
</P>
<P>
   And who wouldn't love to find a sky blue Tiffany &AMP; Co. box tied
with a festive ribbon under the tree? No need to sully that
surprise with Santa paper.
</P>
<P>
   Most stores will only handle merchandise bought from them.
However, places like Wrapsody _ which has kiosks at various metro
Atlanta malls _ will wrap anything from anywhere. And you can leave
a batch of presents to be wrapped, shop a bit more, then pick them
up.
</P>
<P>
   There is a middle ground for those who don't want to do their
own wrapping and yet refuse to stand in line. JC Penney sells
prewrapped boxes that include tissue and a bow. Martha Stewart
might not approve, but it's a quick and easy alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at some local wrappings.
</P>
<P>
   Pro wrapper favors simple, elegant
</P>
<P>
   For Margie Perry, gift wrapping is an art form.
</P>
<P>
   The professional wrapper (left) has been wrapping gifts at
Rich's for 26 years, and last year she won a $500 consolation prize
in the 3M Scotch Tape wrapping contest in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes, patience and skill; tender loving care,'' said
Perry, who works at Rich's Greenbriar store in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expressions of joy you see on the faces of customers when
they see the wrapped package makes me feel good. I like beautiful
things, and gift wrap is both a reflection and an expression of who
I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry shares these tips for wrapping the perfect package:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Less is more. Make the wrap simple, yet elegant.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fold garments to the size of the box, making sure to tuck any
tickets out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use decorative seals on tissue inside the box.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Put as little tape on wrapping paper as possible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Crease wrapping paper on all edges of the box.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Finish the ends of ribbon with an angled cut or an inverted V.
</P>
<P>
   Sabine Morrow writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
