<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEB-SHOPPING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO NEEDS ELVES WHEN A MOUSE DELIVERS? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY   c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON, Mass. _ A crush of shoppers filled the aisles Friday
at the Burlington Mall. In the brick-and-mortar world of malls and
stores, the day after Thanksgiving is one of the busiest shopping
days of the year, and the traditional kickoff of theholiday
season.
</P>
<P>
   Not far away, staring at a bank of video screens in a windowless
room, as many as 60 analysts for GTE Internetworking were also
gearing up for the holiday rush. But for these engineers, who help
ensure the smooth flow of consumer traffic on Internet shopping
sites, it's the Monday after Thanksgiving that will be a key test
of whether the Net is ready to handle the rush of shoppers expected
to go on line this year.
</P>
<P>
   Crunch time on the Web often comes on the boss's time. At the
office, many consumers have access to high-speed Internet
connections, which are far faster than their modems at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as people don't want to admit it, a lot of people are
shopping at work,'' said Chris Yetman, a vice president who helps
run GTE Internetworking's Burlington operations center, which
oversees the firewalls that keep credit card transactions secure
and fix potential trouble spots that could cause on-line gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lunch hours on a work day are some of our busiest times,''
said Jonathan Morris, executive vice president of Bluefly.com,
which bills itself as the Filene's Basement of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   At toysmart.com, marketing director Kelly McGovern had her own
theory about heavy midday activity on her Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our customers are stay-at-home moms with small
children,'' she said. ``Stay-at-home moms shop during their kids'
nap time.''
</P>
<P>
   With more holiday shoppers than ever expected to go on line this
year, e-commerce retailers won't be busy just at noon.
</P>
<P>
   In a particularly optimistic forecast, the accounting firm Ernst
&AMP; Young projected that the number of on-line holiday shoppers this
year will be triple that of last year; on-line sales are expected
to total $12 billion to $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   At Lands' End Inc., which sells everything from cashmere
sweaters to Portuguese flannel sheets, that means the Monday after
Thanksgiving could be busier than ever, both for catalog sales and
for business on its Web site _ landsend.com.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bass, Lands' End's vice president of e-commerce, said
Mondays are usually the busiest for the company. People window-shop
at a mall over the weekend or browse through a catalog, then get
down to business on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   L. L. Bean Inc. also enjoys big Mondays. For its catalogs and
Web site, the busiest time of the year is often during the second
week in December, spokesman Rich Donaldson said.
</P>
<P>
   That could be a period during which mall retailers experience a
lull. Typically, consumers spend a lot over the Thanksgiving
weekend, take a break, then shop with renewed fervor as Christmas
draws nigh. Often, some of the busiest days of the year fall just
before Dec. 25.
</P>
<P>
   But because e-commerce retailers need at least a day to ship a
Web site purchase to a consumer, their last-minute frenzy comes
earlier than it does at the malls.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, 1998 was the year on-line holiday shopping went
mainstream. So it's hard to make declarations about changes in
shopping habits based on the statistics of a single year.
</P>
<P>
   Cable television channels that specialize in retailing have
hardly changed shopping patterns. In general, the Home Shopping
Network sees a business rhythm similar to what traditional
retailers report _ a strong burst of activity over Thanksgiving
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many retail Web sites are coping with a flood of new
business as consumers get comfortable shopping on line.
</P>
<P>
   On a weekly basis, L. L. Bean's sales volumes can be three to
four times greater than for the same periods last year. And Lands'
End reports its increases are nearly comparable.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the big jump in on-line shopping is that retail
Web sites are now attracting a diverse group of consumers, women as
well as men, the old as well as the young.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just Gen-Xers,'' said Ed Lubieniecki, an Ernst &AMP;
Young partner who specializes in ``e-business.''
</P>
<P>
   While some things change, others remain the same. Like many
traditional retailers, e-commerce Web sites will do a big chunk of
their annual sales during the holiday shopping period.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart.com expects that it could ring up 90 percent of its
annual sales between October and December.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher E. Vroom, an e-commerce analyst at Thomas Weisel
Partners, said this could be a breakthrough year for on-line toy
buying.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping in toy stores can be such a wretched experience that
many parents will shop instead at sites such as toysmart.com,
eToys.com, or RedRocket.com, he said. But it's possible that
someone could have just as bad an experience on line as they could
in a toy store, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When shoppers endure an unpleasant experience in a mall, they
may be inclined to stick it out. But with retail Web sites, the
competition is just a mouse click away.
</P>
<P>
   On-line toy shoppers, take note. A clever child can retrace the
Web sites that parents have shopped at on a home computer.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Symantec Corp., the folks best known for Norton
anti-virus software, have included a special feature on the Norton
SystemWorks 2000 software package. The feature erases the
footprints left by a PC user shopping on line.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want your kid peeking in the closet where you've
hidden all the toys,'' said Rowan Trollope, Symantec's research
director. ``And you don't want your 8-year-old retracing your
footsteps on the computer to see what you've ordered.''
</P>
<P>
   (Nosy nippers may be one more reason why consumers do their
on-line shopping at work.)
</P>
<P>
   All that shopping from the workplace may help e-commerce
retailers. For traditional stores, it can be all peaks and valleys,
with slow Mondays and frenzied weekends, and such an erratic pace
can make for a bad experience for consumers dealing with
overwhelmed clerks.
</P>
<P>
   But because of the freedom the Internet gives consumers,
allowing them to shop at almost any time, the pace is sometimes
steadier.
</P>
<P>
   For someone such as Send.com founder Mike Lannon, it's hard to
draw sweeping conclusions about on-line shopping habits.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Lannon sold only wine. But in 1999, this year, Send.com
also began selling other products, including cigars, flowers, and
spa visits.
</P>
<P>
   Given the expanded product offerings and the Web's boom, almost
every day has the potential for being the day after Thanksgiving
for Send.com. Said Lannon: ``Every day this week has been the
busiest day of the year for us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-01-99 1341EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
