r l BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATIONS     12-08 1533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATIONS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Discover city's `pockets' full of charm
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Forget chestnuts roasting on an open fire, Jack
Frost nipping at your nose. And don't even think about folks
dressed up like Eskimos.
</P>
<P>
   In this historic coastal city, signs that the holidays have
arrived are a bit more subtle.
</P>
<P>
   A festive wreath hangs from the outstretched hand of the statue
of stern-faced Colonial evangelist John Wesley in Reynolds Square.
The stone swans in Forsyth Square fountain sport jolly red bows
around their slender necks. The Savannah River Queen paddlewheeler
is draped in garlands of greenery. And horse and carriage drivers
don jaunty Santa caps.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish moss _ not icicles _ drips from ancient live oaks, and
the city's version of the Rockefeller Center ice rink is an inside
affair. At the Savannah Civic Center's exhibition hall,
Savannahians in jeans and T-shirts gamely lace up skates and wobble
out onto the ice under a canopy of lights and flanked by a forest
of gaily decorated Christmas trees.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps best of all _ at least for the shop-till-you-drop
set _ there's fabulous shopping throughout the historic district.
You'll walk your tootsies off visiting hundreds of boutiques, gift
emporiums, antique shops and art galleries.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, one very special Christmas place is the Holiday
Shoppe at Ex Libris, sponsored by the Savannah College of Art and
Design. The shop, across Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard from the
Savannah Visitor's Center, is filled with gifts, pastries and
coffees from around the world. Throughout December, there will be
children's story hours on Saturdays, performances and holiday
seminars. Call 912-525-5225 for more information.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit to Savannah, we accepted the fact that we
couldn't hit every shop in town and concentrated our shopping in
two areas, along Whitaker Street between Jones and Taylor streets
and around the intersection of Bull and Liberty streets near the
Desoto Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   Those areas covered, we spent our remaining two hours checking
out the new shops in old storefronts along Broughton Street and
made a quick run through an old favorite, the City Market, a
two-block complex with an eclectic mix of shops, galleries, artists
studios and restaurants. We skipped River Street this time, but
it's worth a stroll.
</P>
<P>
   We started our day at Saints and Shamrocks, where Jeanne
Zittrauer and her family have been selling Irish imports and
religious books, videos, music and gifts to both tourists and
Savannah's large Irish-Catholic population for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Next, we dropped by Morning Star Gallery, where glass artist
Mark McKim showed us a sparkling array of blown glass and stained
glass. That's his Guardian Angel stained glass featuring a cherub
in the window.
</P>
<P>
   The fashion-conscious can find something really unusual at
Gaucho or across Bull Street at Chutzpah. Down Bull Street at the
Arts and Crafts Emporium is a wonderland of handmade wares by more
than 300 artists. And don't miss Soho South Cafe, where you'll
lunch on creative cuisine at mix-matched tables and chairs in a
street cafe-like setting surrounded by art and antiques.
</P>
<P>
   After lunch, head for the corner of Whitaker and Jones streets.
Here, you'll find the Market, a former piano factory that anchors a
nifty row of shops along the block south to Taylor Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turned it into a European marketplace,'' said Melissa
Bagby, who owns the business with Beth Clapp. ``We bought the whole
thing and did it with no money. We got the first CADA (Coastal Area
District Development Authority) loan in the city. We did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagby, Clapp and other female proprietors in the area refer to
themselves as the ``Whitaker women.'' And they're making quite an
impact.
</P>
<P>
   Down Whitaker at Edison Lighting, owner Gale Singer sums up the
area rather succinctly: ``We're a nice little pocket of better
goods.''
</P>
<P>
   Savannah is full of such ``pockets'' of shopping. And we can't
wait to find them all.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: From Atlanta, take I-75 south to I-16. Travel
east on I-16 into downtown Savannah. It's about a four-hour drive.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Most shops are open 10 a.m.-6 p.m., but hours vary.
Some are open Sunday afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Parking lots are dotted about town. Metered parking
is also available, but make sure you feed the meter; no sooner than
the red violation flag goes up, an $8 ticket is slapped on your
window. Visitors can buy a day pass that costs $5 and is valid for
a 48-hour period. Get one at the Parking Services office at 100 E.
Bryan St.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: In shops and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: Most shops are accessible, although there
are steps down to some street-level shops.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 1-877-728-2662 or on the Web at
www.savannahvisit.com (Savannah Area Convention and Visitors
Bureau). The Savannah Scene Web site is also helpful:
www.savannah.com.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Accommodations: We wouldn't think of staying anywhere but an
inn _ of which there are more than 30 in the historic district.
Expect to pay at least $80 a night; some tariffs run considerably
higher. For a selection, call for a Simply Savannah Visitor's Guide
at 1-877-728-2662 or check the Web at www.savannahvisit.com.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dining: Have lunch surrounded by art and antiques at newcomer
Soho South Cafe (12 W. Liberty St., 912-233-1633) after you shop
the Liberty and Bull intersection. We recommend the Andalusian
Chicken Salad ($8.75) and mixed berry shortcake ($5). If you find
yourself in the Whitaker and Jones street area at lunchtime, try
the home cooking at Mrs. Wilkes Dining Room (107 W. Jones St.,
912-232-5997). If lunchtime finds you at the City Market, go for
the Southern buffet at The Lady and Sons (311 W. Congress St.,
912-233-2600).
</P>
<P>
   Beyond shopping
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  12th Annual Holiday Tour of Historic Inns. This self-guided
walking tour Saturday and Sunday features 13 inns decorated for the
holidays. Guest enjoy refreshments in parlors as hosts share the
history of the inns. Included on the tour are Bed &AMP; Breakfast Inn,
117 W. Gordon St.; Eliza Thompson House, 5 W. Jones St.; Foley
House, 14 W. Hull St.; Gaston Street Gallery, 211 E. Gaston St.;
The Gastonian, 220 E. Gaston St.; Hamilton Turner Inn, 330 Abercorn
St.; Magnolia Place Inn, 503 Whitaker St.; Manor House, 201 W.
Liberty St.; Olde Harbor Inn, 508 E. Factors Walk; Planters Inn, 29
Abercorn St.; Presidents' Quarters, 225 E. President St.;
17Hundred90, 307 E. President St.; and Joan's on Jones, 17 W. Jones
St. Tickets are $17, available on tour days at all participating
inns. Hours are 1-5 p.m. both days. 912-232-5678.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  25th Annual Holiday Tour of Homes. If you've ever wanted to
get a peek inside some of Savannah's most sumptuous homes, this is
your chance. The Downtown Neighborhood Association opens the doors
to 25 Colonial, antebellum and Victorian homes in the historic
district. Three self-guided tours, each featuring a different group
of homes, are scheduled for 1-5 p.m. ($25) and 5-8 p.m. ($15) Dec.
18 and 1-5 p.m. Dec. 19 ($25). A ticket for all three tours is $60.
Tickets: 912-233-0220.
</P>
<P>
   Browsing through Savannah shops we found . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Blown glass vase by Paul Bendzunas, $79. Morning Star Gallery,
8 E. Liberty St. 912-233-4307.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Giselle Shepatin jacket made from scraps of fabrics from Paris
couture houses, $460. Gaucho, Liberty and Bull streets.
912-232-7414.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Celtic design advent candleholder, $27. Saints and Shamrocks,
309 Bull St. 912-233-8858.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hand-painted French country chair, $145. The Market at Jones
and Whitaker, 401 Whitaker St. 912-
</P>
<P>
   231-1006.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Place card holders shaped like tiny handbags, $18 each. One
Fish, Two Fish, 405 Whitaker St. 912-447-4600.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Antique German-made Steiff stuffed lion ($275) and lamb
($120). Pierce Antiques, 101 W. Jones St. 912-238-3525.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Talavera pottery from Mexico, $85. 101, 101 W. Taylor St.
912-201-9112.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of Savannah shops:
</P>
<P>
   These shops are along Whitaker between Jones and Taylor streets.
</P>
<P>
   The Market at Jones and Whitaker, 401 Whitaker St.
</P>
<P>
   One Fish, Two Fish, 405 Whitaker St.
</P>
<P>
   Edison Lighting, 407 Whitaker St.
</P>
<P>
   Off the Wall _ A Gallery of Contemporary Art and Objects, 412
Whitaker St.
</P>
<P>
   Benign Decay Antiques and Interiors, 412-B Whitaker St.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce Antiques, 101 W. Jones St.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh Mountain Ironworks, 417 Whitaker St.
</P>
<P>
   101, Furniture and Fine Decorative Arts, 101 W. Taylor St.
</P>
<P>
   Bothwell Gallery, 422 Whitaker St. 912-233-5132.
</P>
<P>
   These shops are within a block of the intersection of Bull and
Liberty streets.
</P>
<P>
   Saints and Shamrocks, 309 Bull St.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte's Corner, Bull and Liberty streets.
</P>
<P>
   Chutzpah, Bull and Liberty streets.
</P>
<P>
   Gaucho, Bull and Liberty streets.
</P>
<P>
   Morning Star Gallery, 8 E. Liberty St.
</P>
<P>
   Arts and Crafts Emporium, 234 Bull St.
</P>
<P>
   Savannah Fine Arts Gallery and Paradise Wild, 12 W. Liberty St.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
