<HEADLINE>
IN LOVE FOR ALL THE RIGHT REASONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY   c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To judge by the latest sales figures, consumers are falling in
love with Apple Computer's new iBook line of laptops. And for the
wrong reason, I'll wager.
</P>
<P>
   It is, after all, cute. Even cuter than the iMac desktop
machines that began Apple's renaissance. Compared to the common
ruck of black and gray and beige PC laptops, the iBook stands out
like a cocktail waitress in a convent.
</P>
<P>
   And in truth, the $1,600 iBook is a pretty good computer, or so
it seems when I'm using it on my dining-room table. Alas, it's not
nearly so much fun on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Though it boasts a thin, light lithium ion battery, the iBook
still comes in at 6.6 pounds, not counting the power adapter. I
felt every ounce of the weight after trudging through a few
airports in search of connecting flights. The iBook's built-in
plastic handle cuts into your fingers, and its gaudy good looks are
an invitation to thieves. So I ended up schlepping it about in a
canvas shoulder bag. I suspect most users will, if only to protect
the pretty case. So why bother with a built-in handle?
</P>
<P>
   The iBook's designers must believe that the Internet will render
air travel obsolete. Why else design a portable computer that can't
be used comfortably on an airplane? In the past couple of months,
I've tried the iBook on a number of 727s, as well as a 757 and an
MD-88. It's impossible to fully open the iBook's huge,
clamshell-shaped lid on an airline tray, even before the guy in
front of you tilts his seat back. I know the iBook was meant for
students and casual users who don't fly very often. Still, why not
a portable that's a bit more portable?
</P>
<P>
   Once I arrived at a destination, I found the iBook a much more
congenial companion, with a gorgeous 12-inch display, a solid
keyboard feel and decent performance _ especially after Apple sent
an extra 32 megabytes of memory. The idea was to illustrate how
easy it is to upgrade the unit. I was duly impressed, but also
frustrated by the fact that the iBook comes with a measly 32 megs
of memory as standard-issue. And while the 3.2-gigabyte hard drive
is adequate, it's small compared to PC laptops.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the iBook suffers from the same fundamental flaw as
the original iMac. It's not so much a serious computer as a fashion
accessory that can run spreadsheets.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, I have begun to succumb to the iBook's charm, now that
I've had a chance to try out its most fashionable accessory _
built-in wireless networking.
</P>
<P>
   Apple calls it AirPort. For $99, you can plug a card into the
iBook that connects to an antenna already built into the laptop.
Instantly, the machine becomes capable of sending and receiving
data at speeds of up to 11 million bits per second, faster than a
wired Ethernet connection.
</P>
<P>
   The new-generation iMacs also take AirPort cards, and since I
just happen to have the new iMac DV Special Edition in the
graphite-gray case, I slipped AirPort cards into the iMac and the
iBook to create an instant computer network for swapping files
between machines. With a range of 150 feet and a wireless signal
that can pass through walls, the AirPort is a cheap and simple way
to connect multiple home computers. By the way, AirPort uses an
international standard for wireless networking, so the system will
work with similar products made for Windows PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the $300 AirPort base station, a
flying-saucer-looking thing with a built in 56-kilobit modem and an
Ethernet connection. It can serve as a single connection point to
the Internet for a whole houseful of computers.
</P>
<P>
   The base station software was incompatible with my Internet
provider, Concentric Network. Apple says it will fix this in a
future upgrade. But then I signed up with the Earthlink Internet
service, and found I could wander the Web wirelessly, while the
base station sat 50 feet away. Apple plans another software upgrade
that'll let users turn any AirPort-equipped machine into a base
station, providing Internet access to other computers on the
wireless network.
</P>
<P>
   AirPort needs no dangling wires or prodding antennas. Install it
in an iBook, and the computer still looks cool. Only now, with
wireless networking, the iBook really is cool.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Hiawatha Bray can be reached by e-mail at Bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-02-99 1334EST &QL;
</P>
