<HEADLINE>
BRITANNICA SITE A HIT, BUT EXTRAS NEED WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN   c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Encyclopedia Britannica announced last month that it was
offering its 32-volume set for free on the Internet, up to 15
million people flocked to the Web site, which crashed within hours
and was down for days. In a single day, the site attracted more
traffic than last month's star-studded NetAid concert and last
year's Victoria's Secret fashion show combined.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Apparently, folks are desperate for credibility on the
Internet, and the 231-year-old publisher has a reputation for
reliability _ if not technical prowess. Hail Britannica.
</P>
<P>
   But let's not get too misty-eyed about the triumph of knowledge
over lingerie just yet. Britannica.com is back on line, and it's
sending out mixed signals. It fashions itself as an information
portal, with news from the Washington Post and 76 magazines, as
well as free e-mail and weather forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the e-mail and the weather and the news: Nobody goes to
the encyclopedia to check the temperature in Tucson. The research
tools are what matter most. And that's where the site is sending
out mixed signals. The encyclopedia itself is enough to make a
librarian's daughter dance: The searchable database instantly pulls
up Britannica's expert articles on everything from a-ak (an ancient
Asian music) to Zywiec (a Polish town). The hypertext links from
one article to another make preliminary research so easy it's hard
to imagine ever thumbing through the stacks again.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the encyclopedia entries, the site offers three
other kinds of material for each topic searched: a list of ``Best
Web sites,'' suggested magazine articles, and selected books. In
theory, that's a great idea. In practice, it's another thing
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the results for these searches:
</P>
<P>
   Boston _ The top Web site is www.bostonpunk.net, a site offering
an introduction to the city's punk rock scene. The top book on the
list is ``Boston Dog Lover's Companion: The Inside Scoop on Where
to Take Your Dog.'' For dog-free researchers, the book list
includes ``Boston Wedding Planner'' and ``God is a Bullet: A
Novel,'' by Boston Teran, a book described in a Globe review as
``disturbing and disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet _ The best Web sites include the Pediatric Internet
Directory, the Internet Baby Mall, and a site celebrating
Australia's Poetry Heritage. There is also a link to
netaddiction.com, a site for keyboard junkies.
</P>
<P>
   Mick Jagger _ There must be something going on down under,
because a search for the former Rolling Stone includes a link to a
site called ``Mick's Footy,'' a news site about the Australian
National Rugby League.
</P>
<P>
   Conducting a search hasn't been this much fun since the early
days of the Internet, when a query about breast cancer would yield
recipes for chicken breasts.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Devereaux, Britannica.com's vice president of product
development and editorial, admits that the search engine is creaky
and says the company is tweaking it. ``Most sites have the
opportunity to do what's called a `soft launch,' but we didn't have
that opportunity,'' he says. ``We sent out one press release on
Oct. 19, and we were swamped with requests.''
</P>
<P>
   Britannica.com also rates Web sites, an arduous task in a realm
where it's often hard to distinguish between fact and fiction. Some
of the capsule reviews are informative, but others lack the kind of
skepticism necessary on line. The review for Harry Knowles' Ain't
It Cool News, for instance, fails to mention that much of the
material found on the site is unreliable gossip.
</P>
<P>
   Britannica is messing around with its brand name, which stands
for facts and reliable research. But the Internet, by its nature,
is unreliable, and the encyclopedia editors have not figured out
how to communicate the difference yet. But you can't beat the price
for the encyclopedia entries, and the search results for the other
categories are certainly amusing. And hey, if you ever want to take
your dog to a punk rock club in Boston, Britannica can lead the
way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  Speaking of encyclopedic knowledge, it's next to impossible
to keep track of everything that's written about any given subject
these days. That's why we need Web sites like www.artsjournal.com,
a concise compilation of headlines in the arts from all over the
world. It's the brainchild of Douglas McLennon, a former reporter
for the Seattle Post-Intelligencer and the Seattle Weekly. McLennon
is at his home computer every morning by 5, combing through more
than 100 on-line publications to glean the best stories of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like curating a magazine,'' says McLennon. ``It's like
taking this vast sea of raw stuff out there and trying to put it
together in an interesting way.''
</P>
<P>
   The site, launched last month, has already gained the support of
two major foundations, and McLennon has plans to expand it. For
now, the site offers a simple, easy way to stay in touch with the
good, the bad, and the beautiful in the world of arts and films.
And every now and then it includes a link to a paper in Australia,
just like Britannica.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  If you can't attract users with Australian links, you can
always lure them with cash and prizes. This week, Lycos launched a
$5 million lottery promotion; users sign up to receive ``lucky
numbers'' to play against Lycos daily winning numbers. Last month,
CBS joined forces with a small Internet company to launch iWon.com,
a portal similar to ABC's go.com and NBC's Snap.com. The site is
giving away cold cash, with a daily prize of $10,000, a monthly
prize of $1 million, and an annual prize of $10 million. And
another company called epipo.com is paying users a small fee to
surf the Internet and look at selected ads while they browse. It's
the latest trend: If you pay them, they will come.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-02-99 1321EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
