<SLUG> BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Consumer protection forces also staked out on Internet
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's just common sense. More people shop this time of
year, so more people encounter problems with products that don't
live up to the billing, or they find customer service that seems
inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   There's help on the Web. Some of the most familiar names in
consumer protection have homes there, along with some effective
organizations that you may not know about.
</P>
<P>
   When most people think of consumer help, the Better Business
Bureau comes to mind. You'll find that site at www.bbb.org. There's
a nice, common-sense organizational method to this site. At the top
of the page, you'll find quick links to the areas that most
consumers need, which include: locating a BBB bureau in your area;
reading alerts about suspect businesses and business practices;
getting advice on resolving disputes; or filing a complaint with
the bureau. You can also go directly to www.bbb.org
</P>
<P>
   /complaints/company.html and use the pull-down menus to file a
complaint online.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Reports magazine tops the list for most people when it
comes to getting straight talk about products and scams. The
magazine has an excellent site at www.consumerreports.com/. Without
paying a cent, you can get solid consumer tips. But to read the
articles in the current issue of the magazine (last week there were
evaluations on DVD systems, a popular holiday gift; advice on
``bargain computers'' and the rebates that are becoming popular;
and a report on batteries), you must subscribe to the site.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how that works. You pay $3.95 a month or $24 for a year
($19 if you're a Consumer Reports magazine subscriber). Most pay
sites aren't worth the money since there's so much free information
on the Web. But if you find value in the sort of information
published in the magazine and don't want the print version, it may
make sense.
</P>
<P>
   While you're at it, make sure that you stop by the Consumers
Union site. It's the consumer advocacy Web site of Consumers Union,
publisher of Consumer Reports. You'll find it at www
</P>
<P>
   .consumersunion.org/. This is a good, hard-nosed site that
offers real help. And you can get the information in either English
or Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   If you need help or advice concerning a possible scam or
business fraud, a good site for you is the National Fraud
Information Center at www.fraud.org
</P>
<P>
   /welcome.htm. It was formed in 1992 by the National Consumers
League, which claims to be the oldest nonprofit consumer
organization in the United States, to deal with telemarketing
fraud. But with the growing popularity of e-commerce (and e-fraud),
a section on Internet fraud has been added. You can go directly to
that section at www.fraud
</P>
<P>
   .org/internet/intinfo.htm, or follow the links from the main
page.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has its own Web clearinghouse for
consumer complaints and advice at the site called U.S. Consumer
Gateway at www.consumer
</P>
<P>
   .gov/. You'll get consumer advice there, as you'd expect, as
well as tips on product safety, consumer fraud and also a review of
the companies that the FTC has taken action against.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-06-99 1137EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
