<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Spread joy, give away that old PC
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ My favorite computers _ the ones that have lasted for
years and years, even if it is just in my heart _ are the ones I
gave away.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the computer that sits on my desk now, they continue to
give me joy.
</P>
<P>
   Since part of my job is to tell you how to get the most from
computing, I feel comfortable telling you to consider giving a
computer away this holiday season. After all, many of you will get
a new one as a holiday gift.
</P>
<P>
   You may find that the best use for that old computer is to give
it to someone who doesn't have one.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing wrong with profiting from a good deed. Giving
the old computer away can serve as a good argument for doing
something you've been wanting to do anyway ... buy one of those
new, more powerful computers.
</P>
<P>
   But the best reason is to share the magic of computing with
someone less fortunate. A computer is just a box of silicon chips,
resistors and circuit boards. Yet, it can do magical things. Mine
is a terrific electronic typewriter as I write this column, but _
at the click of a mouse _ it can become an entertaining game
machine, or one of the world's best research tools. That's truly
magic.
</P>
<P>
   The good thing about sharing magic is that _ unlike sharing your
lunch _ the more you give the more magic you have.
</P>
<P>
   I don't need to make a long pitch about how computers are
important for kids. Going to school these days without a computer
puts a kid at a real disadvantage. The other kids go home and
cruise the Web for reference material and then prepare a fancy
homework project using pictures and information they found on the
Internet. Those without a computer are stuck doing things the
old-fashioned way. It's not impossible to get by that way, but why
not lift a burden in lives that already have enough challenges?
</P>
<P>
   The need for computers isn't limited to kids. One of the real
surprises _ at least for me _ is the way computers have changed the
lives of older people. Maybe, in your own family, there is a
relative who would never think of buying a computer but who could
profit from one. All of a sudden, with the aid of one of the free
e-mail services and a computer, a person who felt alone and out of
touch can have friends around the world.
</P>
<P>
   And there are still other places where a computer could make a
difference. Many charities and churches operate on a tight budget.
An extra computer, even an old clunker, can make things easier
there, too. Even the most outdated of computers can produce
correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't come up with a recipient for your old computer,
I'll offer a suggestion. There's an organization here in Atlanta
called Freebytes that refurbishes old computers and then finds a
good home for them. I'm sure that there are thousands of places
like this across the country; I just happen to know about this one.
You can read about them at www.freebytes.org. If you go to that Web
page, you'll find a history of the group, the kind of machines it
will accept, a mailing address and phone number. I recommend that
you check them out on the Web, but to get you started, the
telephone number is (404) 846-8414.
</P>
<P>
   And, even folks who don't have a computer to give away can help.
There's information on that page telling you how to volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   That's just one possible way to share the magic. There are
plenty of good homes for that old computer of yours, maybe even
within your own family. And that's half the fun of playing
millionaire for a day, finding just the right recipient. If you do,
I promise you the kind of magic that can make this the best holiday
season you've ever had.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-06-99 1137EST &QL;
</P>
