<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    E.com cometh, but it's a Mall world
 &HT;    (Package includes ONLINE-SHOPPING, ONLINE-DEALS, ONLINE-LISTS,
ONLINE-COLUMN.)
 &HT;    By Omar Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's 2 a.m. and the order just went through on Amazon.com for
some books I'll give as gifts later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the hype over Internet shopping was starting to
build. This year, it can't even be called hype. It's real. You can
shop whenever you want, buying CDs, movies and freshly baked
cookies, using the newest technology to have something delivered
via one of the oldest, by postal service.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping for books and movies online has become a habit for me.
When a new DVD that I want is released or the latest Stephen King
behemoth hits the shelves, I shop virtually, looking for the best
price and the lowest shipping.
</P>
<P>
   It's been more than a year since I've gone to the mall and
browsed the shelves at a Waldenbooks or B. Dalton's. Maybe it's the
best thing, that malls aren't the best place to shop anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Malls and superstores destroyed the mom and pop operations that
sold us our boots, our groceries, our books for so long. And now,
out of nowhere, the mom and pops of cyberland (these are
22-year-old moms and pops, I know), are beating back the retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Will malls, with their color-coded directories and parking lots
stretching out forever, die out?
</P>
<P>
   Part of me hopes so. There's Darwinism afoot, and right now,
e-commerce sites have the edge. It's easier. You don't deal with
crowds or parking. You don't even pay tax. It's inherently
appealing, easy, safer than you'd think.
</P>
<P>
   But then I think I'd miss the mall. At least two generations of
kids grew up in those stacked, air-conditioned shrines. We saw the
rise and fall and rise again of video arcades. Watched the Gap
dress us up until we couldn't tell each other apart. We shopped for
last minute-gifts attached to last-minute greeting cards chosen at
the Hallmark store.
</P>
<P>
   I think I would miss people watching, seeing those who dress up
to go to the mall, in high heels and bright lipstick, shopping at
Nine West for more high-heeled shoes to wear to another mall. I'd
miss the parents tempting fate with precariously poised strollers
teetering at escalator precipices.
</P>
<P>
   I might not miss greasy pizza, but I would miss the mayonnaise
at Chick-fil-A, caramel pecan Cinnabons and the famous Orange
Julius. In fact, let's just lay it out there, sons and daughters of
the digital age. Who is going to make us our Orange Julius fix
online? Who is going to put the starchy dehydrated milk powder in
the blender, mix it with fruit and serve it to us in a paper cup?
</P>
<P>
   I love and hate the mall. I want to avoid it, but when I'm there
I feel the magnetic pull of a junky, beautiful, wasteful and glossy
culture. If it were a dessert, it would be lime sherbet, all gaudy
and smooth, numbing and unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
   The online world of shopping can be cheaper. Faster. Easier. But
the mall is a guilty pleasure, a big tub of popcorn and sweets,
happy to drown us, to overload us, catering to our every whim; it's
got everything you need, want and can't have, the comforts and 72
degrees of manufactured air.
</P>
<P>
   Malls won't die. They'll just become more decadent. You may
contact Omar L. Gallaga, a writer for the Austin
American-Statesman, at ogallaga(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-06-99 1137EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
