<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-TOOLS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Marvelous, versatile maps detail Appalachian Trail
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There is a kind of romance about the Appalachian Trail
that touches most folks, I think, even if they never intend to set
foot on it. It's something of a miracle that the trail even exists,
all the way from Georgia to Maine, and that every year some people
walk the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   Maptech's marvelous set of four CD-ROMs, presenting linked U.S.
Geological Survey topograpical maps of the whole trail and vast
areas around it, will appeal to everyone. But it will be of
greatest interest to those who have, or plan to, walk some portion
of the trail.
</P>
<P>
   I'm no cartographer, but it seems to me that Maptech has put
these maps together and provided means of examining them that leave
little to be desired.
</P>
<P>
   Two general views are available _ each of the USGS maps
individually, or a seamless view of the entire area covered on the
disk. The single-map view is useful if you want to see the
information included on the edges of the maps. If you want to use
the two-map view, the screen is split into two windows on which
widely separated areas can be viewed next to each other.
</P>
<P>
   But the seamless view will probably be the one most used. Maps
of 1:24,000 scale and 1:100,000 are included and can be viewed at
zoom ratios of from 1:4 to 2:1. At 2:1, the map from edge to edge
of the window covers only about 1,350 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Changing from one cursor style to another produces various
results. The hand cursor, as usual, drags the map around. The
pointer is used to click on various symbols along the trail to
provide more information. For instance, at Blood Mountain, probably
the most popular point along the trail in Georgia, you find full
information on its historic significance, current rules for camping
and using the shelter and a couple of excellent photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Two distance tools are included. One is used to produce the
straight-line distance between two points, or even to find the
square footage of a defined area. The other is a freehand tool,
used for finding the actual distance along any trail, either the
Appalachian Trail or a trail you define.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a means of determining the true distance,
including changes in elevation. Terrain profiles and line-of-sight
information can be viewed for every track or distance line
established.
</P>
<P>
   The user can establish markers and create and edit tracks on any
of the maps. Those markers will appear in the go-to menu along with
all the markers already set up on the map.
</P>
<P>
   All the maps or sections of them can be printed out, along with
any self-defined features. Likewise, the trails and their waypoints
can be uploaded to a hand-held GPS device for carrying on the
trail.
</P>
<P>
   The maps contain an area of up to 3 miles on each side of the
trail. All the features of the maps _ campsites, latitude-longitude
grids and the like _ are in the form of overlays, which can be
removed and returned to view at will. Latitude and longitude of the
cursor, and the elevation of the point which it is touching, are
all shown in windows on the menu bar.
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways of finding some point on the maps. You can
search by name, or get an enormous list of place types, from caves
to mines, select one and look at the list produced. Coves,
incidentally, are included with valleys.
</P>
<P>
   The online help is the best I've seen.
</P>
<P>
   The four regional CDs that comprise the set can be purchased for
$39 apiece, and the set for $139. Go to www.maptech.com or call the
company at (800) 627-7236.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-06-99 1137EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
