<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Oracles of the online share their predictions
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What's the next development for the Internet? Read in
the December issue of Yahoo Internet Life magazine about what some
experts predict. Among the scholars and sages who sound off on the
topic for Yahoo Internet Life are Alan Dershowitz, Roger Ebert,
John Katz and Amy Sohn.
</P>
<P>
   Learn about the latest version of Apple's operating system, OS
9, in the December issue of MacWorld. The magazine offers an
in-depth look at what this new version offers. Among the things
discussed are OS 9's new voice print system, which lets users sign
on through vocal commands.
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Turn your personal handwriting into a font on your PC with Your
Handwriting. Published by Data Becker, this computer CD turns your
handwriting into a True Type font, which any PC can use to add a
personal touch to letters, memos, diaries and other documents.
Available only for PCs with operating system Windows 95 or higher,
Your Handwriting sells for about $20.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can use a digital rack of beef as a weapon. It's part of
the innovations in ``Dynamite Cop'' championed by the game's
developers. ``Dynamite Cop'' is a shoot-'em-up arcade game for Sega
Dreamcast. In this game, it's your job to rescue the president's
daughter from terrorist kidnappers. ``Dynamite Cop'' retails for
about $50.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   There's a growing number of online games. One of the newest is
Microsoft's ``Asheron's Call.'' It features a fictional world of
monsters and magic. The story line constanty evolves, so there is
no resolution or ending. You'll find ``Asheron's Call'' only on the
MSN online gaming service. It's located at www.zone.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
