<HEADER>
A3001 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-ONLINE-SHOPPING07     12-08 2264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ONLINE-SHOPPING07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Mine is the mouse that roars through the online stores
 &HT;    (Package includes ONLINE-SHOPPING, ONLINE-DEALS, ONLINE-LISTS,
ONLINE-COLUMN.)
 &HT;    By Nikol Lohr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's better to give than to receive.
</P>
<P>
   Ha!
</P>
<P>
   The best part of Christmas shopping is picking up a ton of stuff
for yourself, guilt-free. You just throw it in your basket (or
e-basket) along with everyone else's presents, and pretend it's
just another holiday gift expense. This little game is especially
easy to play when you're buying online. If you don't have to haul
in all the extra bags from your car, it's far simpler to overlook
that most of it's for you.
</P>
<P>
   Over years of this pattern, I've resigned myself to paying for
Christmas well into spring. Once you accept short-term debt as a
reality of a happy holiday season, it's easier to sit back and
enjoy the ride.
</P>
<P>
   And don't tell me I'm the only one who spends as much on herself
as on others. After all, you're the thoughtful shopper. You're the
one who painstakingly picks out the perfect gift for each person on
your list. But do they do the same? No. Never. Good luck getting a
single good present from any of those thugs on your Christmas list.
</P>
<P>
   So, to dull the pain of those ill-fitting sweaters, that cheap
perfume and the tacky costume jewelry, here is my holiday shopping
prescription: One for you, one for me. Think of it as a flu shot
for the Christmas-morning blues.
</P>
<P>
   All in the Family
</P>
<P>
   Grandpa: Archie McPhee, Playboy, Buy.com.
</P>
<P>
   One for him: My grandpa is one of those Depression-era humbugs
who hoards rubber bands and thinks everything I own is ``a bunch of
junk.'' Last year, for the first time ever, I actually found a
present he didn't immediately pooh-pooh: a copy of Peter Jennings'
``The Century'' ($36 at Buy.com _ Dad liked it so much he's getting
a copy this year _ at $7 less than Amazon's price). Hoping to cash
in on last year's success with Grandpa, I started with a
large-print copy of Tom Brokaw's ``The Greatest Generation''
($10.95), purchased from Buy.com, which is usually cheaper than
both Amazon ($12.48) and Barnes and Noble ($12.50).
</P>
<P>
   Then I turned to my grandpa's only other known interests: clocks
and girls. Where else but Archie McPhee (www.mcphee.com)? I chose a
Wiggling Hula Girl ($8.95) and the Sumo Clock ($19.95). And in case
the Wiggling Hula Girl didn't quite fit the bill, I threw in a
magazine subscription ($19.97/12 issues) from Playboy
(playboy.com).
</P>
<P>
   And one for me: Popping Martian Thing, Monkey in Fez, and
Monster Woman salt and pepper shakers ($7.95 each set) and a
Surprise Package ($19.95).
</P>
<P>
   Bonus: Archie McPhee throws in free gifts with every order, and
Playboy also gives some freebies with subscriptions. Bummer: I've
had some sketchy customer service from Buy.com. The prices are
really good there, but you won't get Amazon's dependability. Avoid
backordered items and you should be fine.
</P>
<P>
   Mom: Amazon, 800.com and Living Arts.
</P>
<P>
   One for her: Every family has one person held hostage by
technology. In my family, it's my mom. After nearly a decade of
trying to decipher my father's complex system of remote controls,
my mother finally gave up and now pretty much just watches the
channel that comes up when she turns on the TV. And forget about
the VCR. Even if she could decode it, good luck recording anything
on that one tape they user over and over. So when my mom expressed
an interest in my new yoga tapes, I abandoned them as a gift idea _
until I found a $179 Toshiba TV/VCR combo at Amazon.com, the last
place I looked. With simple operation (only one remote control, vs.
my father's system of three) and a compact size, she could move the
TV from her bedroom to the kitchen. Amazon also had the AM/PM Yoga
for Beginners set ($12.59). But I used a slightly lower price on
Yoga Practice for Beginners ($12.45) at 800.com as an excuse to buy
a CD I've been wanting. To complete the package: a yoga set with
mat, blocks and a strap for $44 at Living Arts
(www.livingarts.com).
</P>
<P>
   And one for me: VTech Digital Cordless Phone with handset caller
ID and answering machine ($99) from Amazon and the Flossie and the
Unicorns CD from 800.com ($11.45 _ cheaper than both Amazon and
CDNow).
</P>
<P>
   Bonus: Amazon's relatively new electronics department has great
deals. 800.com has nice prices on videos and music, plus free
shipping on some electronics and a free DVD allowance with DVD
player purchases. Living Arts offers one-stop shopping for all
things Zen: You'll find aromatherapy, meditation aids, home
accessories and wonderful back-care contraptions. Bummer: Living
Arts can be slow to notify customers of backorders.
</P>
<P>
   Dad: Outpost
</P>
<P>
   If I had my girlfriend Suzanne's dad, I'd head over to Build.com
and get him some swank new gadget or specialty power tools. Failing
that, I'd visit OmahaSteaks.com for a fancy meat pack. But my dad
always buys himself whatever he wants. I knew ``The Century'' was a
good bet, but I had to find something else cool for the pater. My
dad sells and buys a ton of stuff on eBay, so he's always uploading
images. Although he has a digital camera, I know from experience
that a low-end scanner beats the pants off a low-end camera for
small items, so I headed over to Outpost (outpost.com) and found a
scanner (several choices under $125). I also grabbed a bundle of
Zip disks ($99/10) for his new Zip drive.
</P>
<P>
   And one for me: a 10 mb smartcard ($84.50) for my Nikon Coolpix
950.
</P>
<P>
   Aunts: Eve
</P>
<P>
   One for her: For my aunts, BeneFit Kitten (sparkly body powder,
$22) from Eve.com, a purveyor of some of the best boutique
cosmetics.
</P>
<P>
   One for me: BeneFit FakeIts Dr. Feelgood ($24).
</P>
<P>
   Bonus: Free shipping and gift wrapping makes this one of my
favorite gift sources for out-of-town friends.
</P>
<P>
   Little Cousins: Archie McPhee and American Science Surplus
</P>
<P>
   One for the kiddies: I got a few extra crowd-pleasing surprise
packs ($19.95 each) at Archie McPhee (www.mcphee.
</P>
<P>
   com). Then it was off to American Science Surplus
(www.sciplus.com), one of my favorite sites, for a whole mess of
random, strange, and quasi-scientific items. Here are a few: a set
of 40 plastic culture tubes with rack, $1.75; colorful mylar bubble
pouches, $2.25/3; square hobby dishes, $1.50/12; Cup O' Lab mug
(featuring a clear plastic compartment encasing mini test tubes,
syringe and patient chart), $1.75, and hundreds of little jars,
bottles, bags and toys for under $2. They also have about any
science kit you could think of, piles of kitchen stuff, motors and
electronic parts, model and lab materials, even a nice selection of
quality microscopes.
</P>
<P>
   Young biologists will love the Owl Pellets ($9.50/3),
regurgitated globs from the gullets of barn owls, which are both
educational and and high-scoring in the gross-out department (pick
these for the kid of your most squeamish in-law). Dissolved in
water and bleach, they'll yield an entire rodent skeleton!
</P>
<P>
   And one for me: I love any excuse to spend hours on this site.
American Science Surplus is the dim sum of the online shopping
world. The descriptions and quirky drawings are a hoot.
</P>
<P>
   Godmother and her daughter: Girlshop
</P>
<P>
   For them: You'd never know my godmother was an old lady by her
accessories, so for her I headed over to Girlshop
(www.girlshop.com), a great collection of young, hip boutiques. I
picked the fuzzy hot pink checkbook wallet ($20) from the Greg
Harmon boutique for Rosemary, and an animal print version for her
equally funky daughter, Yvonne.
</P>
<P>
   And one for me: Not one to be left out, I bought myself a hot
pink one.
</P>
<P>
   Bonus: A Girlshop gift certificate means you get to shop a slew
of specialty boutiques at once. The Girlshop stores include some of
New York's hippest shops. The Bummer: It may be gorgeous, but it
ain't cheap. The wallets were definitely at the bargain end of
Girlshop's swag. On the other hand, browsing Girlshop is cheaper
than flying to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Fido (or Fluffy)
</P>
<P>
   One for her: Contrary to what you might expect, shopping for the
pets doesn't have to be a selfless act. Fill Fido's stocking at
PetSmart (petsmart.com) and you'll get free pet food.
</P>
<P>
   Spend $20 on nonfood items (including treats) and get a free
small bag of dog food or a small bag or case of cat food. A $35
purchase nets you a medium bag or case. And throw down $50 on pet
gifts and get any size bag or case of dog or cat food free! Each of
les mutts got three 8'' pressed rawhide (they last longer than the
familar knotted form) bones ($1.69 each), plus a Buster Cube
($12.99) and a package of Pork Snouts ($4.99 _ they're not at all
as gross as they sound) to share. After I threw in a package of
hooves for my parents' pooch ($2.49), a smoked knuckle ($2.99) for
little Toddy, a Deluxe Crazy Grunting Rat for Nancy ($8.99), and a
few more bags of snouts and hooves for the other mutts on the list,
I had earned a big bag of dog food, which would cover December.
</P>
<P>
   And one for me: OK, so it's not exactly for you, but not having
to fork out for the pet food will make it easier for you to 1)
rationalize splurging on the pooch when you know he doesn't know
Christmas from Tuesday; 2) convince yourself you're not one of
those freaky dog people; or 3) buy yourself something nice with the
scratch you would've blown on kibble. If you're shopping for other
people's pets, take advantage of the free food and drop it off at a
local shelter.
</P>
<P>
   The bonus: Fast delivery, no lugging bags of chow from your car
to your door, and $4.95 shipping fee regardless of the size of your
order. The bummer: Not a true bummer _ just something you should
know about the site. When you do a search or browse a category, the
sizes and prices first displayed are rarely the only choices, which
can be confusing. So if you see ``Pressed Rawhide $4.99'' or
``Nutro Natural Senior $4.79,'' go ahead and click. You'll also
find $.89, $1.49 and $6.99 bones and the larger bags of dog food.
</P>
<P>
   Friends in Need
</P>
<P>
   Girlfriend 1: Domestications
</P>
<P>
   One for her: My best friend is a minimalist, making her
impossible to shop for. But even minimalists must sleep, and I've
noticed Sue's mattress was looking a little saggy. Although I
couldn't spring for a new mattress, I figured a feather bed would
do wonders for the comfort and appearance of her bed, so I headed
to Domestications (www.domestications.com) for a really nice $99
baffled featherbed.
</P>
<P>
   And one for me: A pillow top mattress pad to perk up my shabby
old guest mattress ($19.99). I got a free pillow and $20 off the
catalog price on my item. If you're in the market for a lot of
linens, they have a buyer's club: $20 gets you 10 percent off%
everything for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Girlfriend 2: eBay and PlanetRx.com
</P>
<P>
   One for her: Another girlfriend gets a vintage trinket box ($12)
from eBay (www. ebay.com), filled with an assortment of
</P>
<P>
   M Professionals sassy nail polishes ($1.49 each) from PlanetRx
(www.planetrx.com). Darling!
</P>
<P>
   And one for me: While I was sniffing around eBay, I found a
vintage pink enameled metal Kenmore hairdryer to add to my
collection. And from PlanetRx, Healing Arts aromatherapy samplers
in lavender and tea tree ($11.87 each).
</P>
<P>
   Bonus: You can find anything on eBay, and if you become
obsessive about it (as most people do) and use restraint (as few
people do), then you can get really great prices. You could
actually fill your whole list on eBay, if you start shopping now,
stick to sellers with good ratings and pay with money orders
instead of personal checks.
</P>
<P>
   For stocking stuffers, basket stuffers, and beauty products,
PlanetRx has low prices, huge selection, great specials and great
customer service. Shipping at PlanetRx is free if you spend $30 or
fill a prescription. Bummer: While eBay's fun, it's quite easy to
get caught up in the moment and overbid. You're also depending on
individuals, rather than a company, to meet your requests. Make
sure to read the fine print so that you know exactly what you're
getting. Finally, consider the weight of the item you're bidding
on: The shipping could make it significantly more costly.
</P>
<P>
   Girlfriend 3: Kustom Girl
</P>
<P>
   One for her: For one of my more extravagant girlfriends, I chose
Kustom Girl's (www.kustomgirl.com) fabulous nail decals
($6.50/sheet) in Hot Rod (purple and red flames) and Tiger Lady
(tiger stripes). Other Kustom Girl designs sport leopard spots, old
school tattoo designs, Japanese designs and characters, and the
more demure flowers and butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   And one for me: I picked up another sheet of Hot Rod.
</P>
<P>
   Boyfriend: Tiki Trader
</P>
<P>
   One for him: For my luau-loving former roommate, I staked out
Tiki Traders (www.tikitrader.com). Although the site's low-tech
(you have to e-mail or call in your order) and wouldn't win any
beauty contests, it's worth the inconvenience. For Kevin, I got a
green tiki mug and an Easter Island tiki mug ($11.95/pair), tiki
cocktail napkins ($7.75/240), and half a dozen Ropa Nui Moai Tiki
Tumblers ($17.90/dozen).
</P>
<P>
   And one for me: I kept the other half of the dozen Ropa Nui Moai
plastic tiki tumblers, plus snapped up a pair of Surfin' Wahini
mugs ($19.95/pair), a set of cocktail napkins, and some Tiki
Coasters ($7.95/eight).
</P>
<P>
   Nikol Lohr is an Austin writer and Webmeister. You may mail
e-mail her at nikol(at)disgruntledhousewife.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
