<HEADLINE>
THE NET IS, ONCE AGAIN, YOUR FRIEND
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News   LOS ANGELES _
Procrastinate any longer and these holiday bail-out presents won't
be delivered by Christmas.
<TEXT>
<P>
   So point, click and pay. Be done with it. Pass the eggnog.
</P>
<P>
   Personal video players: We endorse TiVo (www.tivo.com) over
Replay TV (www.replaytv.com), and the $499 receiver that records 14
hours of programming should be sufficient. TiVo can also be ordered
on Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Satellite TV dish: Now with access to free network channels, the
value of DirecTV or EchoStar system (each about $129 plus
installation costs) is even alluring. An authorized DirecTV online
dealer is American Satellite &AMP; Entertainment (www.needadish.com),
which EchoStar's Dish Network setup can be had on its site
(www.dishnetwork.com).
</P>
<P>
   Video game systems: Sega DreamCast is the flavor of the
millennium ($199.99) and can be ordered on the company site
(www.sega.com) along with games (NFL 2K and NBA 2K, Bass Fishing)
and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Road trips: Through a service called Sports Travel
(www.sportstravelandtours.com), affiliated with The Sporting News,
gift certificates from $25 to $1,000 would be the way to start any
of the dozens of sports-related excursion packages.
</P>
<P>
   Personalized gloves, bats and balls: Among the items at the
Rawlings online store link (www.rawlings.com) are gloves running
$219.99; bats at $34.95 and footballs at $85.95, each stitched,
stamped or emblazoned with whatever name you choose. The Louisville
Slugger site (www.slugger.com) asks $45 for its name bats, but goes
one better _ it'll engrave an actual signature for $60.
</P>
<P>
   Gift books: More than 30 to choose from at Sports Publishing
Inc.'s site (autographedsportsbooks.com), leather-bound and signed,
sold on a first-come basis. Included is the Dodgers Encyclopedia,
signed by Manny Mota, Duke Snider, Carl Erskine and Davey Lopes,
for $99.95.
</P>
<P>
   Golf equipment: The SeeMore putter, which the late Payne Stewart
endorsed and used to win the U.S. Open, has a site
(www.seemore.com) that handles orders and helps determine the right
size. All mallet models are out of stock, however. Price: $129.95.
</P>
<P>
   There are also several clever packages on Golfballs.com
(www.golfballs.com), including one called the ``illegal gift set''
($22.95) that all-but-guarantees to improve distance off the tee.
Wrapping included.
</P>
<P>
   General sporting goods: Hundreds are out there, but we'd check
out Direct Sports (www.directsports.com) or Wilson sports' site
(www.wilsonsuperstore.com) for starters. Also, at WhatsHotNow
(www.whatshotnow.com), specializing in pop-culture items, the
sports link has a top-10 list of stuff ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   Calendars: Half the proceeds to the $14.95 Track Girls 2000
calendar (www.vaultstuff.com) goes to the Florence Griffith-Joyner
Community Empowerment Foundation. So the tastefully done
black-and-white photos of naked female track stars like UCLA high
jumper Amy Acuff are worthy of the effort. Amazon.com also has some
10,000 calendars to pick from, specifically ones dedicated to Heidi
Klum ($12.99), Sports Illustrated's Swimsuit models ($12.99), the
Swedish Bikini Team ($12.95) and, soon, the Australian women's
soccer team. Again, a nude calendar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-05-99 2013EST &QL;
</P>
