<HEADLINE>
TRENDY GIFTS FOR TEENS 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: THIS PIECE MAY BE PUBLISHED ONLY BY SUBSCRIBERS
TO ``NEXT,'' A NEW COLUMN ON TRENDS FOR THE UNDER-30 CROWD, WRITTEN
BY JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM, PRESIDENT OF YOUTH INTELLIGENCE. FOR
INFORMATION ON BECOMING A CHARTER CLIENT _ OR TO SEE MORE SAMPLES _
CALL YOUR NEW YORK TIMES SYNDICATE SALES REPRESENTATIVE AT (888)
269-8796. EDITORS WHO SIGN UP BEFORE THE END OF THE YEAR WILL GET A
COPY OF YI'S RESPECTED ``CASSANDRA REPORT,'' WHICH FOCUSES ON
WHAT'S HOT AND WHAT'S NOT WITH GENERATIONS X AND WHY?  
 (FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE)
</HEADLINE>
  By JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember last year, when the gift you got your teen was the gift
he or she really wanted _ the year before? This Christmas, be ahead
of the curve: Get something the teen in your life may not yet know
he (or she) wants _ but will soon! Here are some ideas:
 &UR; FOR HER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ STICKER JEWELRY: Less painful than tattoos, less permanent
than Mehndi and less expensive than a trip to the jeweler, these
bracelets, necklaces and earrings make great gifts. Teens today are
very much into self-expression and individualism, and sticker
jewelry gives them a chance to make a statement _ without making a
lifetime commitment. Just stick on a few pieces _ wherever _ and
go. (They peel off just as easily.)
</P>
<P>
   Where to get it: Express stores nationwide for $13-$20.
</P>
<P>
   _ TOO-FACED LIP-GLOSS RING: This clever makeup designer has
created a fashion accessory with a purpose: Each chic little ring
features a pot of lip gloss. They come in delectable colors that go
with almost any fashion-forward look.
</P>
<P>
   Where to get it: www.toofaced.com or Bloomingdale's stores
nationwide for about $12 each.
</P>
<P>
   _ THE BARE BAND: Hair accessories from New York salon Bumble and
Bumble are as eagerly awaited by teens as Christmas vacation. New
this season are cool bands of clear or colored rubberized plastic
that look hot as they tame tresses.
</P>
<P>
   Where to get it: Call Bumble and Bumble at (888)-7-BUMBLE; each
band costs $14.99.
</P>
<P>
   _ POWERPUFF GIRLS GEAR: These animated creatures (from the
series on The Cartoon Network) take Girl Power to a new level.
Teens love their feminism, superpowers and style. They could take
on Pokemon any day.
</P>
<P>
   Where to get it: www.trend-zone.com or Hot Topic stores
nationwide. (T-shirts are about $17.)
 &UR; FOR HIM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ SOAP SHOES: Give these to the guy who's always looking for the
next ``hot'' sport or activity. They're fun because they take the
skateboard out of skateboarding. With metal plates on the inside
arches, Soap shoes make it easy to practice jumps and tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Where to get it: Pacific Sunwear stores or local skate shops for
about $100.
</P>
<P>
   _ CUSTARD BAGS: These messenger bags/one-arm packs/DJ sacks are
cool enough to be trendy but not so cool that your guy will look
like he's trying too hard. Where to get it: Urban Outfitters stores
nationwide for about $30 to $50.
</P>
<P>
   _ SEGA DREAMCAST: Excellent graphics and cool games make this
video-game system the one teens are already talking about. And it's
available NOW _ while Sony's much-anticipated new system won't be
ready until 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Where to get it: Game stores for about $199. Or try eToys.com
 &UR; FOR BOTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ RIO: As it becomes easier and easier to customize music
choices, an MP3 player like the Rio will become a necessary piece
of equipment. No longer do you have to buy an entire CD to hear one
hit song. You can download music from the Internet to create custom
compilations. Once you tire of the mix, simply store the tracks on
your PC and pump in another set.
</P>
<P>
   Where to get it: Electronics stores for $200 or less.
</P>
<P>
   _ HOLOGRAM CAMERA: With all the expensive new technology, it's
nice to find a cool camera that's affordable. These disposable
numbers from 3D Magic produce groovy 3D images.
</P>
<P>
   Where to get it: Camera shops for about $18 or check the
company's web site at 3disin.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ HIP-LOOKING PHILIPS TV: Today's teens demand good form as well
as function. This 13-inch set, called the ``new vision'' (model
13PTBOL), features an ice-blue metallic color, glow-in-the-dark
legs and a look reminiscent of the hot Apple iMac computer. While
it may not have better programming, this set at least looks better
than most _ on or off.
</P>
<P>
   Where to get it: Electronics stores for about $250.
</P>
<P>
   _ SWIFFER: OK, this cleaning gizmo may never be on your teen's
wish list, but it's actually fun to use. It picks up lint, cat hair
and all those other scary things that may be lurking in his or her
room. Just don't make it your ONLY gift.
</P>
<P>
   Where to get it: Target, Wal-Mart, K-Mart or most major
supermarkets for about $13.
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; BOX: BE ON THE LOOKOUT FOR ... &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REPTILE-SKIN BAGS
</P>
<P>
   PORTABLE DVDS
</P>
<P>
   SPANISH SHAWLS
</P>
<P>
   FAKE-FUR VESTS
</P>
<P>
   ACTOR TOBY MCGUIRE (FROM ``THE ICE STORM'')
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jane Rinzler Buckingham is the president of Youth
Intelligence, a market-research firm specializing in the 7- to
35-year-old market. Her company publishes the Cassandra Report, a
comprehensive survey focused on identifying emerging trends among
Generations X and Why?) &QL;
</P>
