<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3018 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-N     12-08 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE ON TRIAL IN MARS MISSION  
 A DOT-COM TAKES AIM AT THE MARKET FOR GREEN POWER  
 A PET SITE THAT WANTS TO KNOW ALL ABOUT YOUR DOG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the ultimate field test: The temperature was minus 75 and
the terrain was entirely unfamiliar. And with a $165 million NASA
mission at stake, there was no room for errors _ or even error
messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the luxury of rebooting,'' said Curt Shacker,
vice president of marketing at Wind River Systems, a software
company based in Alameda, Calif., that supplied the operating
system for the Mars Polar Lander.
</P>
<P>
   After a trip that took 11 months, the spacecraft was to have
landed on Mars last Friday and sent an electronic message back to
the National Aeronautics and Space Administration to confirm its
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there was a silence that continued through late Sunday
afternoon, with NASA mission control and Wind River officials
playing a tense waiting game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got signals that the operating system was performing as it
should have,'' said John Fogelin, vice president of engineering.
``The frustrating thing is, if we don't establish contact, we may
never know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Wind River's Vx Works, a commercially available computer
operating system, is acting as the brains of the lander,
controlling its various arms and collection devices and
transmitting data back to NASA.
</P>
<P>
   The program is embedded on an IBM microprocessor, just as it was
in the Mars Pathfinder mission in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Wind River said NASA selected Vx Works because of its
reliability and compactness (its code fills only a fourth of a
floppy disk), and because modifying commercial products is cheaper
than creating one's own.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high for all the participants. Exploration of the
planet has been studded with technical failures.
</P>
<P>
   Ten weeks ago, for example, the $125 million Mars Climate
Orbiter, a sibling of the Polar Lander, burned up in the planet's
atmosphere because of a failure to convert navigation data from
feet and inches into metric units. (The orbiter was also using the
Wind River operating system, but the disaster was caused by human
error, company officials want to make clear.)
</P>
<P>
   But the Mars mission is only a small part of Wind River's
business, Shacker says. Currently, Vx Works is the control center
for digital cameras and other consumer products. Telephone and
other communications companies use it to program chips for network
equipment, and Wind River's future emphasis will be on extending
Internet capabilities to pagers, hand-held computers and new types
of data phones.
</P>
<P>
   So does this past weekend's uncertainty curb Wind River's
appetite for space expeditions? ``We're obviously very upset,''
Fogelin said. ``But we have no interest in backing off. It's too
much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
<P>
   A Dot-Com Takes Aim at the Market for Green Power
</P>
<P>
   Add another product to the lengthening list of things you can
buy with a mouse click. Now it's green energy: power derived from
windmills, solar panels, anything that does not pollute the air.
</P>
<P>
   GreenMountain.com plays middleman between wind farms _ and other
clean sources of electricity _ and consumers who want to feel
guilt-free when they flick an electric switch.
</P>
<P>
   Its business plan is based on the premise that, given a choice,
consumers and businesses will want to buy electricity that was
generated in environmentally sound ways.
</P>
<P>
   And energy deregulation, which mandates that local utilities
will have to deliver power from competing sources across their
existing grids, is now making that choice possible.
</P>
<P>
   So far, GreenMountain.com, although based in South Burlington,
Vt., operates only in Pennsylvania and California, which were among
the first states to embrace deregulation. But it has its eye on New
Jersey for next year, and is ready to mount marketing blitzes as
other states deregulate.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the dot-com label, which the company adopted last year,
changing its name from Green Mountain Energy Resources. It wants to
do most of its selling, billing and customer communication through
its Web site, and the old name did not create the visceral pull
that prompts customers to log on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to signal that we are a modern company that's using
the most efficient and environmentally friendly means to do all our
business,'' Dennis Kelly, the company's chief executive, said.
</P>
<P>
   _ CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH
</P>
<P>
   A Pet Site That Wants to Know All About Your Dog
</P>
<P>
   Consumers wary of the information that Web sites gather about
them have one more reason to lose sleep: An Internet company now
wants to compile dossiers on their dogs.
</P>
<P>
   PogoPet.com, which rolled out last week, is the latest entrant
in the increasingly cluttered category of pet Web sites. The
difference between this venture and its competitors, company
executives say, is that PogoPet will compile personal data on a pet
owner's dog or cat and use it to deliver information tailored to
that pet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a Labrador, and I sometimes forget to administer
heartworm pills, and I feel a lot of anxiety and guilt about it,''
said Stacey Estrella, PogoPet's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Estrella said the site, which serves only dog and cat
owners, would ease such worries by sending e-mail reminders about a
pet's medical needs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, to avail themselves of such services, consumers must
first provide some information, including the age, breed and
favorite activities of the pets.
</P>
<P>
   PogoPet never shares personally identifiable data about a user's
pets with others, Ms. Estrella said. It will instead deliver
advertisements on behalf of marketers while keeping the user's
identity secret.
</P>
<P>
   It is a policy that will doubtlessly go far to placate owners _
not to mention some dogs who may not want to go public with that
pesky halitosis problem.
</P>
<P>
   _ BOB TEDESCHI
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-05-99 1822EST &QL;
</P>
