<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3023 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-WEBSHOP-WOES06-CO     12-08 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEBSHOP-WOES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Holiday shopping stampede causing Web site woes
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This online shopping thing just sounds so easy,
doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   You log on, go to a Web site, click on the stuff you want and
everything magically turns up at your home.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's only been a few weeks since the official start of the
holiday shopping season and many online shopping sites are starting
to look like the Grinch has already been there and stolen
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers looking for the hot Nintendo Pokemon trading cards or
video games didn't find much some days last week at eToys or KBkids
except ``sorry, out of stock'' messages and an offer of e-mail when
a new shipment comes in.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers looking for chic pashmina shawls at the discount
clothing and accessory site BlueFly.com also were getting ``out of
stock'' messages during the days just after Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to say how business is at online video/DVD seller
Reel.com _ shoppers trying to get into the site were greeted with
an error message saying ``server too busy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter Communications analyst David Schatsky says that this is
the dark side of online retailing, particularly during the holiday
season. As more and more shoppers come online, Web retailers are
having trouble keeping up with increasing demand both for access to
the sites themselves and merchandise availability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The holiday season means a lot of people and a lot of
orders,'' he says. ``Last year, sites were crashing and response
time was slow. This year many sites have invested in hardware and
servers to address those problems, but we still anticipate problems
on the back end.''
</P>
<P>
   Schatsky says that only 10 percent of online retailers said they
could handle an overnight doubling of shopping volume _ and volume
at Christmastime can more than double.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson here,'' he says, ``is that Internet commerce is
much more than a Web site and a marketing plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter predicts that those who will have especially rough going
are sites launching for the first time this holiday season. ``It's
a risky proposition for brand-new sites to launch in a time of peak
volume,'' he says. ``It takes a long time to get a Web site
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Angela Kapp, who heads up all the Internet ventures for the
Estee Lauder cosmetics company, which includes the Clinique, Bobbi
Brown and Origins Web sites, says that whenever she launches a
site, it's only about 70 percent the way she'd like it to be. ``It
usually takes time and user feedback to figure out what users
really want and how they interact with the site,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Seiff, president and CEO of Bluefly.com, says that the
nature of the site means that inventory is limited and he's likely
to run out of items. Still, shoppers visit the site in search of
other deals besides the shawls. Seiff says he never would have been
able to make it through the Thanksgiving holiday weekend without
massive upgrades to the site's software and increased staffing in
the customer service department.
</P>
<P>
   Estee Lauder and Bluefly may have learned from experience, but
brand-new sites may not know what they're up against when it comes
to filling orders and helping out confused first-time shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's madness,'' Schatsky says of new sites planning to go live
for the first time in the holiday season. ``Wal-Mart decided to
delay redesigning and expanding its site until next year,
recognizing that the human factors and the logistics are not
something you want to dabble with during the crucial holiday
season.''
</P>
<P>
   So, while you will be able to log on to every shopping site your
heart desires, you may find the virtual equivalent of empty
shelves. Delayed delivery dates or other problems have less to do
with Internet technology than with the simple laws of supply and
demand.
</P>
<P>
   It's also important to remember that, even though you are
shopping at home, perhaps in your pajamas at 2 a.m., online
retailing isn't much different from plain old-fashioned catalog
shopping. Your order has been taken, but now the people at the Web
site have to find the product, package it, gift-wrap it, if
necessary, and get it to you.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Amazon.com have spent the past year setting up
distribution centers all over the county, including one in Georgia,
to cut down on shipping costs and speed delivery to users. Other
companies chose to base their warehouses in Chicago or other
Midwestern airport hubs so delivery can be held down to three days.
</P>
<P>
   As you shop, beware that things can still go wrong, even if the
perfect gifts for your loved ones are in stock. Some sites may have
people keying in orders or packaging items. Errors can and will
occur.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Web site is running smoothly, there could be
problems down the line. Sites such as Barnes &AMP; Noble and
1-800-Flowers.com have been beefing up technical and customer
support to make sure problems are solved, orders are delivered and
there are plenty of goods in stock.
</P>
<P>
   If something should go wrong, remember, the problem might not be
the retailer, it might be your PC. If your computer crashes as you
are about to finalize a transaction, you may have to call or e-mail
to find out if the order was processed. Rowan Trollope, director of
development and an e-commerce specialist with Symantec, makers of
Norton computer protection software, suggests keeping your computer
in top shape to prevent crashes or other electronic mishaps. ``The
bottom line is the computer is being used for something that is
important to the user, so it had better be running,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holiday shopping will not be problem-free,'' Schatsky says,
``but it does beat the mall.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
