<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SOUTHPARK-WEB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SOUTH PARK' CREATORS PLAN CARTOON SERIES FOR THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (jt) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the latest examples of how Hollywood is trying
to turn the Internet into an entertainment venue, the creators of
the television show ``South Park'' said they had agreed to make a
series of 39 short cartoons for the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   The cartoons, which will be different from South Park, will be
distributed starting next March on Shockwave.com, an entertainment
Web site run by Macromedia Inc., a software company. Trey Parker
and Matt Stone, the creators of ``South Park,'' will receive equity
of less than 10 percent in Shockwave.com, which is being run as a
separate subsidiary of Macromedia and is expected to eventually
issue its own shares to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in the entertainment and computer industries, from
Steven Spielberg to unknown animators and directors, are
distributing or planning to distribute cartoons, television
programs and movies through the Internet. Still, it is unclear how
successful this will be as a business.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said he and his partner were attracted to the Web by the
freedom it offered to go beyond the language and content
restrictions of television. ``We're definitely excited to push
those limits,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and Parker had turned down offers to do Web programs
in the past because the Internet technology was so crude. ``It's
really just now the technology made it possible to do cool stuff on
the Web, especially in animation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the Web-based entertainment is derived from
television, movies or comic books, Parker and Stone will create new
characters and a new series that will be seen first on the
Internet. If a creation succeeds on the Web, it might then be sold
or distributed to TV networks or movie studios, having already
built up an audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we can deliver from the get-go are millions of viewers,''
said Mike Simpson, executive vice president of the William Morris
Agency, which represented Stone and Parker. This could become a
much less expensive and risky way to develop new shows than making
full-length pilots, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Parker and Stone will retain the copyrights to their work,
although Shockwave.com will share in revenues even from television
programs or movies based on the Internet characters, according to
Rob Burgess, chairman and chief executive of Macromedia, which is
based in San Francisco. ``We think it's a watershed deal with
Hollywood,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The animations will be two to five minutes long and will be
viewable using Macromedia's Flash software, which the company says
is already on 200 million computers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the barriers to entertainment on the Web is the poor
video image quality and long transmission times. But that is not as
big a problem for animation because software like Flash allows
cartoons with near television quality to be transmitted reasonably
fast. Image quality is even less of a factor for the crude type of
animation in ``South Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Shockwave.com last week received investments totaling $44
million from Sequoia Capital, the venture capital firm that backed
such companies as Cisco Systems and Yahoo, and from Jim Clark, the
entrepreneur who started Silicon Graphics and Netscape
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-07-99 2223EST &QL;
</P>
