<SLUG> BC-WEB-HEALTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS CORP. TEAMS UP WITH WEB COMPANY IN HEALTH VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Clark, the co-founder of Netscape Communications Corp., and
media baron Rupert Murdoch have formed an alliance in an attempt to
seize a chunk of the growing Internet health information craze.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch's New York-based News Corp. and Clark's Atlanta-based
Healtheon/WebMD Corp. on Tuesday announced a partnership in which
Healtheon will exchange its medical programming for a half-interest
in News Corp.'s The Health
</P>
<P>
   Network cable TV station.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also calls for Healtheon to assume a 100 percent share
of News Corp.'s thehealthnetwork.com Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The financial terms of the partnership include $700 million in
branding services provided by News Corp. over 10 years and a $100
million purchase of Healtheon/WebMD stock at $50 per share.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the alliance includes a $100 million cash
investment by News Corp. in an international joint venture and a
$62.5 million five-year licensing agreement for syndication of
WebMD daily broadcast content.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we announced an ideal partnership to help us achieve our
goal of establishing a multimedia, multirevenue-generating business
in the trillion-dollar health care industry,'' Murdoch, chairman
and chief executive of the News Corp., said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Clark founded Healtheon 1996 after he was dismayed by the
complicated forms he had to fill out during a hospital visit.
</P>
<P>
   The company links physicians, insurers, labs and pharmacies over
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD, launched in October 1998, offers Internet information
services to doctors. The two companies merged in May.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. is Murdoch's sprawling entertainment, news, newspaper
and Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   The deal broadens Healtheon's potential while helping News Corp.
expand its reach into the Internet and an important growth
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health is clearly one of the biggest areas of our lives and
economy,'' said Stephen Fitzgibbons, a senior research analyst
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist in San Francisco. ``News Corp., which is trying
to be a broad media player, especially on the Internet, is smart to
move into this area.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 1426EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
