<HEADER>
A3060 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-MISS-JULIE-FEATU     12-08 1833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MISS-JULIE-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING CHANCES WITH `MISS JULIE'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After being cast as an oversize hor &UR; s &LR;  d'oeuvre opposite a
mutant shark in her previous big-screen adventure, Saffron Burrows
was understandably eager to fasten onto a fleshier role.
</P>
<P>
   So when veteran director Mike Figgis chose Burrows to star in
his film adaptation of August Strindberg's erotically frenzied play
``Miss Julie,'' he was confident he'd found the ideal man-eating
19th-century femme fatale.
</P>
<P>
   Figgis already had seen Burrows in ``Deep Blue Sea'' and he'd
worked with her twice before, on his feature films ``One Night
Stand'' and the risky but critically well-received ``The Loss of
Sexual Innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   The director also felt sure that, having proven his industry
mettle with commercial hits such as ``Leaving Las Vegas'' and
``Internal Affairs,'' he'd be able to shelter the young British
actress from the Hollywood piranha pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``She felt I would be strong enough to protect her and to help
her,'' the director says. ``In other words, she'd get the
guidance.''
</P>
<P>
   And if she didn't, Burrows, 26, knew she could complain directly
to the worldly, older man who sleeps beside her whenever they
happen to be in the same city.
</P>
<P>
   His name? Mike Figgis.
</P>
<P>
   In Hollywood, of course, it's accepted standard practice for
off-screen romantic partners to collaborate on-camera as well.
</P>
<P>
   What's unusual about ``Miss Julie,'' which opens Friday at area
theaters, is the nerve-racking degree of claustrophobic intimacy
and psychological brutality that suffuses Strindberg's 1888 play -
not something most couples other than Liz Taylor and the late
Richard Burton probably would want to import into their own
bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the knowledge that certain industry predators
would be licking their lips in anticipation of the biggest
potential for a his-and-hers box-office contretemps since Blake
Edwards bombed with Julie Andrews in ``Darling Lili.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which, initially, made for a situation that Figgis, 51,
understatedly describes as ``really tricky. !ital!Really!off!
tricky.``
</P>
<P>
   ``You know it's one of the best parts ever written for a
woman,'' Figgis says. ``You know that if you put your partner in a
film, if you fail you will be so castigated and so ridiculed for
doing it, and she will be made to suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, as ``Miss Julie'' has begun gathering positive
word-of-mouth from its initial press screenings, the film makers
are aware not everyone in Hollywood will be lining up to bless the
happy couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are people who won't like it because they
disagree with our interpretation, or because they know about Mike's
and my relationship,'' says Burrows, an assured, witty and calmly
articulate young woman. ``I'm prepared for that.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, controversy is nothing new to ``Miss Julie.'' Once
banned in Strindberg's Swedish homeland for its fiery themes of
sexual and class transgression, this tragic three-character soap
opera retains its power to stir a modern audience.
</P>
<P>
   Structurally and in other ways, the play bears a strong
resemblance to Edward Albee's ``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?''
</P>
<P>
   The action takes place in the kitchen of a wealthy count's
isolated country estate. Miss Julie, the count's beautiful,
headstrong daughter, has decided to seduce Jean, the count's
ambitious foot-servant.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of a single evening, their flirtation turns
increasingly dangerous and desperate, as the emotionally unstable
Miss Julie seeks to escape from the stifling confines of her
assigned class and gender, while Jean schemes to use his social
superior as a ticket to the middle-class respectability he
ruthlessly craves.
</P>
<P>
   The third leg of this isosceles love-hate triangle is Christine,
the count's cook and Jean's clandestine mistress, played in the
film by Maria Doyle Kennedy (``Moll Flanders,'' ``The General.'').
</P>
<P>
   But most of the time the play's focus, like the film's, stays
relentlessly locked on its two antagonists, as they circle each
other in a seductive, suicidal pas de deux that ends in the
physical death of one of them and the spiritual destruction of the
other. Shot in long takes on Super 16mm with two roaming hand-held
cameras, the film never strays more than a few feet from the
kitchen, so that the audience comes to share the characters'
feelings of entrapment.
</P>
<P>
   Part of what made the play radical (and ultimately popular) in
its own time was its blunt depiction of how sex and class can
intersect to produce a complicated power struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the last generation to really see the
connection (between sex and power) was the Elizabethans,'' says
Peter Mullan, the Scotland-born actor-director who plays Jean.
``Because (to the Elizabethans) it was so out there, so obvious.
You know, shag an aristocrat and you can eat for a year! These
days, obviously, are a damn sight more complex. We've reduced it
now to Monica (Lewinsky) stories and cigar jokes, when in actual
fact it's much, much more complex.''
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that ``Miss Julie'' still reverberates in the 1990s,
Figgis had been wanting to make the film for at least eight years.
Although other film makers were known to be considering big-screen
versions, Figgis reasoned that ``the text was 100 years old
already, so it wasn't like a hot script that if I didn't do it next
week it would get gobbled up.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what attracted him to such a biting and difficult play,
generally less well-known than such comparable contemporary works
as Henrik Ibsen's ``Hedda Gabler,'' Figgis replies unhesitatingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (`Miss Julie') is tough. I mean, it's very
uncompromising,'' he says. ``I mean, I went to see `American
Beauty' yesterday, and that's a film that's coming out as a kind of
tough, sort of uncompromising look at relationships. And yet I
found it to be really soft, in fact, very compromising. And `Miss
Julie' doesn't do that. It actually gets tougher by increments. And
it doesn't let the audience off the hook. It's a really adult
film.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Figgis had two very different actors in mind for
Miss Julie and Jean: Juliette Binoche, a best supporting actress
Oscar winner for ``The English Patient,'' and Nicolas Cage, a best
actor Oscar winner for Figgis' ``Leaving Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   But when both became tied up with other projects, Figgis decided
on an open casting call. He suggested that Burrows a relative
unknown who at the time was shooting Renny Harlin's sci-fi thriller
about genetically altered sharks, ``Deep Blue Sea'' read for the
part of Miss Julie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be unfair not to include you just because of our
relationship,'' he told Burrows. ``That's as unfair as putting you
in the film (a priori).
</P>
<P>
   ``So I made her single read-through the entire script. And then
I said, `That wasn't bad.' And actually it was very good. But you
know, it's not an easy script, and the psychology is never what it
seems to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Two more private read-throughs followed, with Figgis passing
along ideas and suggestions in the form of notes. By the third
reading, Figgis felt he'd found his leading lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a certain point you've got to kind of go with your hunch,''
he says. ``And I kind of thought, well, I know that she's a very
intelligent actress and that she listens carefully. And what then
becomes vitally important is who's playing Jean.''
</P>
<P>
   Figgis says he decided to approach Mullan after ``about 10
minutes'' of watching his portrayal of a recovering alcoholic in
Ken Loach's ``My Name Is Joe,'' for which Mullan won the 1998 best
actor award at Cannes.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days later, Figgis took the train up from London to
Glasgow, Scotland, where Mullan lives. They chatted about the
project in a local pub, after which Figgis offered the actor the
job. Mullan said OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really was as casual as that,'' Figgis says.
</P>
<P>
   For the director, the chief remaining question was how his stars
would get along on a project that required them to be on-screen
together for one intense, 15-minute take after another.
</P>
<P>
   Mullan, born to a poor working-class Glasgow family, had gotten
his start as an actor performing agitprop theater and heavily
politicized community drama at prisons and unemployed-workers'
centers. He also was one of the founders of Scotland's recently
formed Socialist Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I put the two of them together, that was a very, I think,
worrying moment for everybody,'' Figgis says. ``I think Saffron was
terrified of meeting Peter because he's older and a very respected
actor and clearly a very experienced actor and very hardcore
left-wing. You know, not one with any sympathy for lovies. I was
aware of the fact that he probably didn't know Saffron's work and
I'd told him what our relationship was. There was no point in not
being open about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as it turned out, there wasn't. Not only did the actors
instantly hit it off, they discovered they shared a similar
worldview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very similar politically,'' says Burrows, who hails
from a long line of social activists. ``I often get quite
frustrated with a sort of apathetic liberalism that seems to exist
amongst actors, a kind of sitting on the fence, or there's often a
general look on life that is a little too wishy-washy for me. And
Peter is incredibly passionate about class politics and about the
state of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   While a mutual appreciation of Marxist social theory isn't
normally required in Hollywood, mutual trust between actors usually
helps. Their off-screen rapport allowed Burrows and Mullan to
establish a supportive on-screen chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `How could Jean be so mean and all this stuff?'''
Mullan remarks. ``And it's like, well, I really like Saffron, and
Saffron really liked me, and trusted me, and I trust her. That's
how. Because then I can play the game to the full, I can get
horribler and horribler and we'd laugh about it. Like, `Wow, you
were really horrible on that one!'''
</P>
<P>
   With the project passing into the rear-view mirror, Burrows says
she's been gratified by the feedback she's already received from
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when I look back on this, I know this is going to be
one of the things I'm most proud of,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Her partner sounds equally proud - but his memory may be longer.
He mentions one famous Hollywood actor who withdrew from the
project, and some Industry investors who turned ``very negative,''
after Burrows was cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really upset me,'' Figgis says, ``in the sense that they
can think what they like, but if they don't have enough respect for
me to actually realize that I would never in a million years
particularly if I had a great deal of affection for somebody would
ever put them in the situation of basically killing their career.
And so that I found very interesting. And I can't wait for those
people to see the film, and to meet them again.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
