<HEADLINE>
ORAL HISTORY PROJECT FOCUSES ON HISPANIC VETERANS OF WORLD WAR II 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID UHLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Researchers at the University of Texas at Austin
are in a race against time. In an oral history project called
``U.S. Latinos &AMP; World War II: Changes Seen, Changes Wrought,''
professors, interviewers and a documentary filmmaker plan to
collect the stories of Mexican-American veterans of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics who served in uniform and as civilians at military
installations are being sought for the project. The youngest among
them, however, are in their early 70s.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has about 12 million living World War II
veterans of all ethnic backgrounds. Five thousand of them die every
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``God willing, these people are going to be with us for a few
years so that we can hear them,'' said Maggie Rivas-Rodriguez, a
journalism professor and leader of the project. ``There are some
amazing stories about the obstacles these people were able to
overcome during the war, on the home front and the battlefield.
They made tremendous contributions. Those contributions just have
not been given their due.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the problems, according to Rivas-Rodriguez, has been the
limited number of journalists, scholars and authors able and
willing to document the achievements of Hispanics from an older
generation.
</P>
<P>
   The 1940s were ``a time when Latinos were not considered a big
part of society,'' Rivas-Rodriguez said. ``Hispanics have
historically been treated as outsiders.''
</P>
<P>
   The University of Texas project's look at the war and its
aftermath, as seen through the eyes of Hispanic men and women, has
several components. In addition to an oral history archive,
researchers plan to create a photography collection and publish a
book with pictures and interview excerpts. Also on the agenda: a
film by Hector Galan, an internationally acclaimed documentary
producer.
</P>
<P>
   An academic conference at the university in May 2000 is expected
to attract papers, scholars and additional financial support for
the project.
</P>
<P>
   Rivas-Rodriguez's work on ``U.S. Latinos &AMP; World War II'' has
already yielded some surprising finds for her _ within her own
family. Besides learning details about her mother's wartime work at
Kelly Air Force Base in San Antonio, Rivas-Rodriguez also
discovered her father, an Army veteran, had seen combat in the
Aleutian Islands during a rare Japanese attack on North American
soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I've heard a lot of people say is, `It's time for
our young people _ all young people, not just Latino young people _
to realize that there are some living heroes out there,''
Rivas-Rodriguez said. ``We don't have to watch these fictional
heroes on `Star Wars' for our little boys and girls to be thinking,
`I want to grow up like that.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For more information, contact Maggie Rivas-Rodriguez at
512-471-1924 or by e-mail at latinoarchives(at)www.utexas.edu. The
project's Web site is www.utexas.edu/projects/latinoarchives/)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
