<SLUG> BC-Y2K-SURVIVALISTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEARING Y2K, SURVIVALISTS HEAD TO THE HILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Ark., Texas)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROY BRAGG  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT DAVIS, Texas _ Some doomsayers believe the Y2K computer bug
will spark global shortages and chaos. But if it happens, odds are
it will not affect life in places such as Warbonnet or Crow's Nest.
</P>
<P>
   High in the Davis Mountains of western Texas, at the end of
steep, rutted roads and across gaping granite canyons, these are
places barely accessible by vehicle and are occupied by people who,
as far as the modern world is concerned, have ceased to exist.
</P>
<P>
   The area long has been one of those places where people go, for
various reasons, to drop off the map. Now, for those who fear what
2000 brings, there's another reason to hide.
</P>
<P>
   There is, for example, the reclusive businessman who has built
his own private sanctuary here in a rough-hewn stretch of the Texas
badlands.
</P>
<P>
   Residents who have seen his place describe buried propane tanks,
new water wells, a barn full of freeze-dried food and a military
surplus armored vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have met the property owner describe him as polite and
intelligent. And secretive.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of the Y2K survivalists, the name given to people
afraid of fallout when some computer systems, unable to recognize
the 2000 as the valid follow-up to 1999, try to roll over to the
new year.
</P>
<P>
   Although the federal government and most businesses say the
country is well prepared for the new year, hard-core survivalists
envision a world that hasn't prepared adequately for certain
systemic computer crashes. That, in turn, will create an
apocalyptic world akin to the post-nuclear wastelands of the ``Mad
Max'' movies.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows exactly how many frightened people have taken to
the hills, but experts say there could be thousands _ hunkered down
with months' worth of food, a self-sufficient power system and a
strong feeling that the modern world will end in January.
</P>
<P>
   Sociologists and anthropologists studying Y2K survivalists say
they are just a variation of an ever-present subculture in American
life. For those people, the end is always near.
</P>
<P>
   ``They begin with the ideas that they're already waiting for
some kind of collapse,'' said David Frankfurter, an associate
professor of religious studies and history at the University of New
Hampshire in Durham. ``In a way, they know the world's going to
hell and the end of time is coming and Christ is coming back. Even
though everyone else thinks things are getting better, (to them)
it's just a conspiracy to keep us ignorant.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Lamy, associate professor of sociology and anthropology
at Castleton College in Castleton, Vt., calls it the ``Millennium
Myth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In an uncertain, chaotic world, a world where you don't
believe in any of your institutions, how do you find any answers?
How do you get a grip on what's going on? You plug into the
Millennium Myth. (The Y2K bug) is another one of those plagues or
times that God predicted.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has been more vigilant and virulent on the subject than
doomsayer Gary North, a former computer programmer, historian and
Y2K survivalist. On his Web site, www.garynorth.com, he states
flatly that our time is up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean that society is running out of time to fix this
problem,'' North writes on his Internet site. ``Society has already
run out of time for that. There are not enough programmers to fix
it. The technical problems cannot be fixed on a systemwide basis.
The Millennium Bug will hit in 2000, no matter what those in
authority decide to do now. As a system, the world economy is now
beyond the point of no return. We are running out of time as
individuals to evade the falling dominoes.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't North's first stab at Armageddon. In the 1970s, he
predicted nuclear holocaust would engulf the planet in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, he predicted the world would be decimated by the
AIDS plague in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   And North, like the Fort Davis landowner, declined repeated
requests for interviews. The staff at his Tyler office said he has
moved to northwest Arkansas, also a magnet for Y2K survivalists.
</P>
<P>
   When survivalists venture out of the woods, many go to
Huntsville, Ark., the seat of Madison County, to stock up on
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cotton, a real estate agent there, said many bought land in
1998 and the first half of 1999. Like western Texas, northwest
Arkansas already has drawn people who have wanted to disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them are nice,'' Cotton said. ``They don't want to be
bothered. They don't want any publicity at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashing in on the Y2K hoopla is North, who gives seminars on Y2K
preparedness and packages his speeches and tips in the newsletter
``Remnant Review.''
</P>
<P>
   For optimistic nihilists among his readers, North _ who predicts
a banking collapse and other financial catastrophes _ offers a
two-year subscription to the Remnant Review.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
