<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3084 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-PITINO-PITCHMAN-ART-B     12-08 1875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PITINO-PITCHMAN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S RICK PITINO INC. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In Rick Pitino's best-selling business book, ``Success
is a Choice,'' the Boston Celtics coach urges readers to recapture
the optimism of youth in their lives and careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to feel once again that the world is full of
possibilities,'' Pitino says.
</P>
<P>
   The heralded coach clearly follows his own advice. When it comes
to Pitino's life and career, the possibilities seemingly are
endless.
</P>
<P>
   Pursuing a variety of ventures away from the parquet floor,
Pitino has created an extensive shadow career. He may not yet have
the fortunes of the Boston Celtics turned around, but he is
creating his own fortune. Neither Pitino nor his representatives
would comment, but information culled from his business partners
and from observers suggests that his ancillary incomes add at least
25 percent to his annual coaching salary of $5 million _ and closer
to 40 percent in a year when he publishes a book.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino is one of a tiny group of coaches capable of using their
talents as communicators and motivators to develop lucrative
enterprises on the side. While coaches have long sought additional
incomes from things like shoe endorsements and local television
shows, Pitino is a leading example of a more recent trend: the
coach as conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a select group that also includes Bill Parcells and John
Madden from the NFL and Pat Riley and Phil Jackson in the NBA,''
said Bob Williams, president of Burns Sports Celebrity Service, a
Chicago company that links advertisers with sports figures. ``They
are attractive to the business world and intelligent enough to know
how to take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers, however, suggest that Pitino's marketability has
been diminished by the lack of a quick turnaround in the Celtics'
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has been held back by three things: the NBA strike,
the poor performance of the team, and the fact that he commands top
dollar,'' said a marketing official at a major Boston firm, who
requested anonymity. ``When your team is in the tank, you're not
that popular.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fact remains that, away from the Celtics, this coach
could almost call himself Pitino Inc. _ a far-flung, highly
diversified corporation that walks on two legs.
</P>
<P>
   He is among the most highly paid motivational speakers in the
country, much in demand by Fortune 500 companies that, according to
observers, pay him $40,000 to $60,000 per appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be one of the best speakers I have ever heard in my
life,'' said Matt Meli, a senior vice president for J. Walter
Thompson, the advertising firm that represents Ford Motor Co. in
its sponsorship of the Celtics _ a $250,000-per-year deal that
includes personal appearances by Pitino, but no direct fee for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone involved with Ford feels really good about spending
money with the team, in part because he is such a fine
ambassador,'' Meli said.
</P>
<P>
   As a pitchman for Citizens Bank, Pitino earns $250,000 per year,
Williams estimates. He is now in the third year of a five-year
contract. Citizens' commercials featuring Pitino air 12 to 15 times
a week, increasing to 20 when the Celtics are in town for a series
of home games, said Peter Joyce, vice president and brand director
of Citizens' advertising firm, Holland Mark Edmund Ingalls, in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   As a commercial spokesman for Rodman Ford, of Hyde Park and
Norwood, Pitino earns another $75,000 to $100,000, Williams said.
The commercials appear most often on cable channels, especially
those featuring sports, said Dan Rodman, president of Rodman Ford.
</P>
<P>
   The coach is also an author.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino's first motivational book, for Broadway Books/Random
House, topped The New York Times bestseller list for business books
for the entire month of March 1997. That means, for that month
alone, Pitino was earning about $3.50 per book on sales of at least
80,000 books, according to publishing industry sources. Spokeswomen
for Broadway Books would not reveal the total number of sales, but
the company claims at least 500,000 readers for the book,
co-written with a Providence Journal-Bulletin sports columnist,
Bill Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   A second motivational book _ its working title is ``Lead to
Succeed,'' Reynolds said _ is slated for publication in May, just
in time to be a gift idea for Father's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is ``The Rick Pitino Show'' on WBZ-TV. It airs at 11
a.m. on Sundays, when it has about a 3 rating _ meaning that it is
watched in about 190,000 households, or 8 percent of the homes
using television at that time.
</P>
<P>
   The rebroadcast of the show, at 12:30 a.m. on Monday, has about
a 3 rating and a 9 share.
</P>
<P>
   Industry sources said that Pitino is paid a flat fee for the
program and owns no production rights, including any opportunity to
benefit directly from the sale of advertising for the show. A
spokeswoman for WBZ-TV would not reveal any details about the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The coach also owns thoroughbred racehorses _ including the
fourth-place finisher in the 1998 Kentucky Derby, Halory Hunter.
Pitino purchased the horse for $135,000; it earned $713,120 in its
racing career and is now garnering stud fees.
</P>
<P>
   And, as if he needed more to do, Pitino is a purveyor of six
types of pasta, three sauces and two salsas. His income from
Louisville, Ky.-based Pitino Foods comes from an undisclosed
royalty that he is paid off the top, and from his take as a 25
percent shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   All of that money goes to the Daniel Pitino Foundation, a
charity named after his infant son who died in 1987 of congenital
conditions, said Salvatore Rubino, who helps run Pitino Foods. That
money is then disbursed, by Pitino, to various children's charities
in Massachusetts, including Children's Hospital and The Make a Wish
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   According to records in the Massachusetts Office of the Attorney
General, the Kentucky-based foundation received about $957,000 in
contributions and revenue in the year ending March 31 and
distributed about $466,000 to charities. It spent about $477,000 on
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   All of Pitino's side interests are in addition to serving full
time as both president and head coach of the Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done very well, and it is his reputation as a coach and
the power of his personality that is driving all of this,'' said
Patrick McGee, a vice president at Octagon Athlete Representation
in Virginia. ``The guy is just a charismatic leader, and he has
been so great with underdogs throughout his career and bringing
teams back from bad times.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you watch a game and you watch him and the way he coaches
and how much it all means to him and what he instills in those
guys, he makes you want to root for him,'' McGee said.
</P>
<P>
   What companies like about Pitino _ and about coaches like
Parcells, Riley, and Jackson _ is that they are easily recognizable
symbols of both success and good management.
</P>
<P>
   ``If corporations are looking for spokespeople or motivational
speakers, they want to associate with a winner,'' said Peter Land,
general manager of the sports and entertainment marketing practice
at Edelman Public Relations Worldwide in New York. Land is also a
former director of marketing communications for the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches also are people managers, and that's what we do in
business every day,'' Land said. ``Those successful NBA coaches
blend the skills of 12 individuals, hoping to come up with a
victorious result. It is not that different from any other
workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino refuses to talk about all of the moonlighting _ at least
until after the basketball season.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the season, as far as Rick is concerned, it is all
about basketball,'' said Jeff Twiss, the Celtics' spokesman.
``After the season, he'd be happy to talk about it, though.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Pitino _ the acclaimed communicator, who
preaches that doing it well is a key to success _ knows he should
not be talking about his nonbasketball business during the season,
especially when he is so far from accomplishing his goal of
bringing an NBA championship back to a storied franchise. His
instincts clearly tell him that it would only send the players, the
fans and his boss, Celtics owner Paul Gaston, the wrong message.
</P>
<P>
   Some who are watching Pitino spin out his successes off the
court wonder when and if the on-the-court performance of the team _
which clearly is not at the top level _ will begin to affect his
ancillary ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, spokesmen for two major companies in Boston said that
after listening to pitches from Pitino, they decided not to hire
him to represent the companies. Both spokesmen requested anonymity
for themselves and their firms. ``We may not have been interested,
regardless, but three things have sort of come together to hurt him
_ the NBA strike, the poor performance of the team, and the fact
that he commands top dollar,'' said one of the spokesmen.
</P>
<P>
   Some coaches shun the extracurricular work until they get their
teams on the right track. McGee said his firm has tried to
encourage Washington Redskins coach Norv Turner to take advantage
of several business opportunties offered to him and to begin
cultivating others.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't do it,'' McGee said. ``He says, `I can't really do
anything until I win. I don't want to be out in front of my players
making money before we have some success.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But other observers say that Pitino's record as a successful
coach _ and as a successful businessman _ was so well established
before he got to the Celtics that it makes little difference if the
team is losing.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, they say, it is acknowledged that the Celtics were in a
deep hole when the franchise hired Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that anytime soon this guy's public image and
marketability are (going to be) diminished by the Celtics'
performance,'' Land said. ``From one year to the next in the NBA,
it is very difficult to have that kind of seismic transformation.''
</P>
<P>
   It is all a long way from the early 1980s, when Pitino had an
apartment in Kenmore Square and walked to his job at Boston
University. He is not only a coach of considerable repute, whose
contract with the storied Celtics franchise rewrote the rules on
how much money NBA coaches are worth, but an accomplished
businessman, best-selling author, and speaker of national acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just love the guy,'' Rodman said.
</P>
<P>
   The auto dealership has an annual Ride for Kids, a bike tour
that last September raised $1.3 million for five agencies serving
youths in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked him if he would help in any way, and he went way
beyond the call,'' Rodman said. ``He came to our breakfast and gave
a tremendous motivational speech about the importance of
cooperation and teamwork, and then he supported the event
financially with a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the few guys out there in sports that's still the
full package. When he does a deal with you, he supports you with
his time, energy and even money. He brings it all with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
