<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAT BEFORE YOU MAKE A DEAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ I recently ``overheard'' several travelers engaged in
a lively conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Some excerpts:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I'm thinking about using Priceline for a Walt Disney World
vacation. We are not going until August. Would it be best to submit
a bid now or would we get a better deal if we waited? Thinking of
submitting a $45 bid for a 3-star hotel. What do you think?''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I would not recommend using Priceline this far in advance.
Remember, what you get is nonrefundable and nonchangeable.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I put in a bid of $45 for an Orlando airport hotel for Jan.
11 and got a room at the Sheraton.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Here are winning bids for Walt Disney World-area hotels that
I am aware of: Wyndham Orlando, $50; Hampton Inn, $50; Marriott
World Plaza, $90; Hyatt Kissimmee, $60. ...''
</P>
<P>
   No, this isn't another advertisement for Priceline.com. None of
the ``voices'' above is William Shatner's.
</P>
<P>
   It's just casual chat around the neighborhood _ albeit a vast
online neighborhood. And while the conversationalists are quick to
tout a bargain find, they aren't shy in citing disappointments
either.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in this discussion are among 115 members in an
online travel club begun 3 1/2 months ago by Houstonian Sheryl
Mexic. The forum (accessed at
http://clubs.yahoo.com/clubs/pricelinedeals) is dedicated to
fostering a better understanding of the bidding system associated
with flights and hotel stays booked through Priceline _ a
fast-growing company that, if my correspondence is any gauge, has
both fascinated and confounded many travelers. To a lesser extent,
lodging arranged via Expedia's Hotel Price Matcher service also is
covered.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of thousands of forums open to free participation on
the Internet. Indeed, individuals all over the world spend hours
talking about sports, politics, movies _ and almost every
imaginable aspect of travel.
</P>
<P>
   As a novice, I accessed http://clubs.yahoo.com _ one of several
addresses devoted to interactive conversation _ and clicked on the
``travel'' icon to get an idea of what's available. I'll concede my
astonishment at discovering clubs whose topics range from dude
ranching to whale watching.
</P>
<P>
   The Yahoo site alone includes 73 cruise-related clubs, 58 with
lodging reviews, 25 clubs for backpackers, 19 for rail aficionados
and 15 for motorcycle tourists. The scope varies: The Travel
Corner, a multipurpose forum, includes 1,247 members while Real
Surfing Real Surfers hopes to crest above its five current
participants.
</P>
<P>
   Two clubs are dedicated only to ghost towns, although the first
entry I encountered read _ perhaps appropriately _ ``This site sure
isn't very active.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen travel-related Yahoo clubs are geared specifically to
seniors, 20 to singles, 16 to women, eight to teen-agers and 23 to
gay and lesbian travelers.
</P>
<P>
   And Yahoo clubs merely scratch the surface of available travel
chat:
</P>
<P>
   At www.smarterliving.com, forum topics range from cruising with
children to ``What are you doing New Year's Eve?''
</P>
<P>
   At www.fodors.com, a forum on skiing has started.
</P>
<P>
   At http://talk.webflyer.com, business travelers chat not only
with each other but with Randy Petersen, the acknowledged guru of
frequent flyer programs.
</P>
<P>
   Mexic, an active participant in numerous forums, began her club
in August. It costs nothing, she says, to form a Yahoo club; nor
does she receive any remuneration. She has no affiliation with
Priceline or Expedia. ``I'm just a person with expensive tastes who
relishes a good bargain,'' she says. ``And I enjoy sharing that
bargain with others.''
</P>
<P>
   As an administrative assistant for a Houston business, Mexic
began utilizing Priceline not for herself but to find deals for
co-workers. She maintained a record of each successful bid and
gradually developed a strategy, elements of which she passes along
to other club members. Now, member input helps Mexic and other
participants expand on that strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Mexic applauds the basic Priceline concept by which individuals
name the price they are willing to pay (a bid) for air or lodging
on a certain date. For air travel, no carrier or time of day can be
specified; for hotels, no one property can be requested, but
bidders choose from an arbitrary ratings system _ 3-star, 4-star,
etc. _ and pinpoint an area such as ``airport'' or ``downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Mexic says, ``I can't stress enough the importance of doing
your homework. Before making a hotel bid, check each chain's Web
site to see what prices are available for your travel dates. That
gives you a guide. Check for other air fare deals, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never bid too high. I can think of only one time that my first
bid was accepted. But that's good. If that first bid is accepted, I
start wondering, `How much lower should I have gone?'''
</P>
<P>
   As for regulations that restrict the number of bids allowed,
Mexic's strategy covers that angle, too.
</P>
<P>
   Her favorite bargain? Mexic paid $50 per night for a room at
Houston's deluxe Luxury Collection Hotel during the Thanksgiving
holiday period.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can generally get really good deals, too, at downtown New
York City hotels on weekends, though not in December,'' she says.
``I've seen bids accepted for $80 per night on weekends and
$100-$120 per night on weekdays at Sheraton hotels in Manhattan.''
</P>
<P>
   Her main concern about Priceline? ``When you bid for a 4-star
hotel and arrive to find 3-star or 2-star quality, there needs to
be a recourse,'' she says. ``Quality can vary greatly even within
the same chain.'' Members are encouraged to post reports on
properties where their bids are accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Readers intrigued by Mexic's club _ or by other travel-related
forums _ can first access and read postings without joining.
Information about free membership is provided.
</P>
<P>
   For information about Priceline, access www.priceline.com. For
information about Expedia's Hotel Price Matcher, access
www.expedia.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
