<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3089 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-HOLIDAY-BOOKS-     12-08 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HOLIDAY-BOOKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY BOOKS THAT WILL MAKE GREAT GIFTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
and HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fulfill the wanderlust of a friend or family member with a
guidebook this holiday season. Here are some that we'd be proud to
give or receive:
</P>
<P>
   Title of the year goes to ``100 Things to Do Before You Die:
Travel Events You Just Can't Miss'' (Taylor, $15.95).
</P>
<P>
   Authors Neil Teplica and Dave Freeman are founders of
WhatsGoingOn.com, and their book reflects the Web site's addiction
to adventure and adrenaline.
</P>
<P>
   While serving up familiar events such as the Academy Awards
ceremony in Los Angeles and Bastille Day in Paris, the book also
introduces exotic treats. Among them: the National Hollerin'
Contest in North Carolina, the Chung Yuan Ghost Month Festival in
Taiwan, and Hogmanay, described as the ``boisterous, boozy,
soulful, and very Scottish way to ring in the new year.''
</P>
<P>
   Using icons to denote events that are ``dangerous'' or ``grandma
approved,'' the book is fun reading. But we grumble at the authors'
decision to give only their own Web site as a resource for
travelers.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar vein is Alan S. Davis' ``The Fun Also Rises:
International Travel Guide'' (Greenline, $19.95). But Davis gets
the prize _ and our praise _ for thoroughness.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to presenting 50 travel destinations keyed to
special events, Davis suggests three-day, fun-filled itineraries
for each city and provides contact numbers for hotels, restaurants
and attractions. Among events featured are the Cape Minstrel
Festival in South Africa, the Vienna Opera Ball in Austria and
Trinidad's Carnival.
</P>
<P>
   As a bonus, Davis also includes his Millennium List, which
charts 100 of the most fun U.S. and international events in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Cheers to David D'Aprix and his ``Non-Connoisseur's Menu Guide''
(Living Language, $10.95). D'Aprix offers straightforward advice on
how to dine in foreign countries without feeling foreign.
</P>
<P>
   Divided into three sections (French, Italian and Spanish/Latin
American), the guide tackles each cuisine from ``apertif'' to
after-dinner drink. Along the way, readers discover ``feijoada,'' a
stew and the national dish of Brazil; the origins of Fettuccini
Alfredo; and that, ``oui,'' it is common for one person to order
two desserts in France.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to tips on regional dishes and beverages, the guide
lists spices, sauces and preparation techniques that can aid in
deciphering a menu. Also helpful is the pronunciations for foreign
words and phrases.
</P>
<P>
   After all that eating, you may want to check out ``Traveling on
the Run: A Complete Guide to Fitness &AMP; Running Around the World''
(SIMS, $14.95).
</P>
<P>
   Written by Stewart and Barbara Sims, this guide covers more than
90 cities in remarkable detail. Many are obvious tourist centers
such as New York, Sydney and Paris, but the guide also includes
places such as Baton Rouge, La., Birmingham, Ala., and Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Maps accompanying each city pinpoint running routes, hotels with
fitness facilities, tourist attractions and other landmarks. Each
city listing also includes running clubs and retail stores that
cater to athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Chapters dedicated to marathon training, stretching and a list
of sports medicine doctors round out this comprehensive guide.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrating its 26th Jubilee, Rome is anticipating more than 30
million visitors, nearly triple its average, in 2000. To help
pilgrims and tourists navigate their way through the crush, Fodor's
offers ``Holy Rome: A Millennium Guide to the Christian Sights''
($21).
</P>
<P>
   ``Holy Rome'' takes readers through the city's Christian
history, from Paul's arrival in 61 AD to Pope John Paul II. Along
the way, the guide's Italian authors _ all experts on religious
history and art _ share fascinating tales of faith and saints. For
the traveler, there is comprehensive coverage of attractions such
as the basilica of St. Maria in Trastevere, the Chiaramonti Museum
and the Appian Way, which linked Rome to southern Italy.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 230 color photographs, this slick publication is
as much Christian keepsake as guidebook.
</P>
<P>
   Online addicts may find Ken Leebow's ``300 Incredible Things for
Travelers on the Internet'' (300 Incredible.com, $8.95) a bit
basic, but this paperback is a valuable guide for anyone just
starting to weave through a wide-ranging Web of travel information.
</P>
<P>
   Leebow, billed as ``Mr. Internet,'' specifies 300 travel-related
categories, beginning with large multipurpose sites. Addresses that
focus on transportation, lodging, attractions and overall trip
planning are recommended. He tells where to find information on
state and national parks; how to locate a listing of more than
100,000 restaurants in 47 countries; where to access details on
rental properties throughout the world; and how to reach
out-of-town newspapers' online sites.
</P>
<P>
   Want to take a virtual tour of Elvis Presley's Graceland? Study
evaluations of various cruise lines? Access an up-to-date snow
report at a ski resort? Leebow points the way.
</P>
<P>
   This is another in a series that already includes ``300
Incredible Things for Kids on the Internet,'' ``300 Incredible
Things for Sports Fans on the Internet'' and ``300 Incredible
Things for Beanie Lovers on the Internet.'' Twenty volumes are
planned by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Another solid new electronic-media resource is the ``Vacation
Travel Mart's Online Travel Guide &AMP; Logbook'' (Britannia Travel
Press, $12.95) by Jacques Abita and Jim Woodman.
</P>
<P>
   The premise and organization of this 256-page paperback is
simple: Listings are provided (alphabetically) for official Web
sites and other recommended online services in nations throughout
the world and for U.S. states and major cities and Canadian
provinces. Toll-free numbers for requesting information (and
airline Web sites and toll-free numbers) also are included.
</P>
<P>
   The spiral-bound book is designed for use beside a computer and
includes pages for notations.
</P>
<P>
   Write to Britannia Travel Press, 17250 Collins Ave., Sunny Isles
Beach, Fla. 33160.
</P>
<P>
   It's a publication you hope you'll never need to use. But just
in case ... ``The Worst-Case Scenario Survival Handbook''
(Chronicle Books, $14.95), by Joshua Piven and David Borgenicht,
offers tips on such unlikely (we hope) happenstances as ``How to
Win a Swordfight,'' ``How to Ram a Car'' and ``How to Survive if
You are in the Line of Gunfire.''
</P>
<P>
   The relevance to travel, you ask? Much of the treatise is
general in scope, but adventure travelers may want to take heed of
``How to Escape from Quicksand,'' ``How to Fend Off a Shark,''
``How to Escape from Killer Bees,'' ``How to Get to the Surface if
Your Scuba Tank Runs Out of Air'' or ``How to Survive When Lost in
the Mountains (or Desert).''
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, there is ``How to Deliver a Baby in a Taxicab'' and
``How to Land a Plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Chances are you won't find many other books whose advisory board
includes physicians, stuntmen, bomb squad officers, bullfighters,
locksmiths, alligator farmers, demolition derby drivers and
avalanche rescue patrol members.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Family Travel: The Farther You Go, The Closer You Get''
(Travelers' Tales, $17.95), Laura Manske edits a compilation of 45
personal stories about, as she puts it, ``devotion and affection,
fervor and yearning, laughter and surprise _ about embracing family
history, about better understanding the immediate family, about
becoming a new family.''
</P>
<P>
   Contributors include Paul Reiser, Michael Crichton, Calvin
Trillin, Mary Morris and Robert Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   Like other volumes in the award-winning Travelers' Tales series,
this is an ideal vacation companion in that most stories are less
than 10 pages in length. When the family is ready to play, you can
put it down and easily resume later. Chances are that most
contributions here will rekindle memories _ or remind that a family
vacation is long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
