<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3091 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-08 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOW PECAN LEAVES AS THEY COME DOWN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: Would it be all right to leave my pecan leaves on
my lawn and just mow over them, or would it ruin my grass?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can mow and mulch the leaves into small bits that will
easily break down. But I would do this on a fairly regular basis,
say weekly, until all the leaves have fallen. It's difficult to
plow through a thick layer.
</P>
<P>
   More important, you want to avoid a layer of leaves that blocks
light and air from reaching your grass _ whether the leaves are
pecan, oak or sycamore. If there's already a heavy layer on your
lawn, you might rake and bag most of the leaves, then run the mower
over those remaining. But don't put the bags by the curb. Instead
use that good organic matter in your garden. We bag excess leaves,
add a little water and set the bags aside to make leaf mold. Then
we gradually add the leaf mold to the compost pile.
</P>
<P>
   You also could just spread some of the leaves out in your beds.
Do the same with leaf mold.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When and what do I feed my satsuma?
</P>
<P>
   A: Usually, citrus requires only nitrogen. You can apply a
nitrogen fertilizer monthly from March through August on young
trees. The amount depends on the age of the tree and the size of
the trunk. A 1-year-old tree would take 1/4 cup of ammonium nitrate
per inch of trunk diameter. A 3-year-old tree would take 1 cup per
inch of trunk diameter a foot off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Citrus is considered mature at 4 years, so all you should need
is an application of nitrogen in March (1 cup per inch of
diameter). Water it well. You can substitute cottonseed meal at the
rate of 9 quarts per inch of diameter. It takes more, but it costs
less, and it's organic. Cut back if the tree is growing too well.
You don't want excessive growth.
</P>
<P>
   Satsumas are sweet, virtually seedless and cold-tolerant to 20
degrees or slightly below. Keep in mind that while hardy citrus
plants can tolerate cold, the fruit won't, so either pick it or
protect it. The fruit will freeze and split.
</P>
<P>
   Citrus prefers a slightly acidic soil, but while it is not
overly picky and is tolerant of sand or clay, good drainage is
important. Plant high, with the graft union well above soil level,
to prevent the roots from being too wet and to avoid foot rot
disease. Then mulch.
</P>
<P>
   Citrus requires minimum pruning. Remove suckers and dead or
diseased wood as they appear, but while you may want to
occasionally shape your tree, heavier pruning may slow fruit
production if you remove too much foliage. If a tree becomes leggy,
prune (preferably in February) to promote branching and give it
more light.
</P>
<P>
   As your tree matures, it will yield heavier crops. Flower and
fruit drop is common, and there's nothing you can do about it. Less
fruit can mean larger fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Satsumas attract swallowtail butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have crab grass that is taking over my front beds. I have
tried two herbicides. I have dug the weeds out, down to the roots.
These are 6 to 10 inches beneath the surface. Can you recommend
something to wipe the crab grass out without killing my roses and
hibiscus in the process?
</P>
<P>
   One of my plumerias bloomed this summer. I noticed long, hard
pods about two weeks after the blooms were gone. What are they, and
is there anything special I should do about them this winter?
</P>
<P>
   A: Since the weed is in your flowers, I would recommend digging,
even though it's a pain, then placing a 2- to 3-inch layer of mulch
in the bed to at least slow the return of the weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Crab grass is a warm-season annual, so it may die out soon. To
try to prevent it from reappearing later, apply a pre-emergent
herbicide about two weeks before the last anticipated frost _
usually the end of February. A second application 90 days later
might also prove helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I care for a large schefflera and am enclosing a few leaves
to show my problems. It is near a large window and receives
filtered light from the morning sun. I've been told the spots are
sunburn and the lighter-colored leaves could be from a lack of
light. The lighter leaves started near the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   A: It is difficult to get a good reading from leaves that are
mailed, as they are often damaged. But see the following for
possible answers to your problems.
</P>
<P>
   Improper watering is often the trouble with indoor plants,
especially in cooler weather. If there are crisp, brown spots or
patches on the leaves, underwatering is likely the cause. If there
are soft, dark-brown areas, the plant is receiving too much water.
</P>
<P>
   If the foliage has straw-colored spots or patches, the cause
could be watering with cold water, water splashing on the leaves or
too much sun. Avoid hot, direct rays. Scheffleras like bright
indirect sun.
</P>
<P>
   If an occasional lower leaf yellows and falls, don't worry. This
is normal. If several bottom leaves yellow at the same time and
drop, the plant is getting too much water. Or the plant could be in
a cold draft.
</P>
<P>
   Should leaves at the top yellow but remain firm, the cause could
be the use of hard water. City water can contain a lot of calcium,
which ties up the iron in the soil. When a plant cannot absorb
needed iron, as well as magnesium, the result is yellowish leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Flush the soil occasionally to wash away unwanted buildups.
Fertilize your plant biweekly or monthly during warm months.
Sprinkle Epsom salts, a magnesium source, around the pot (and water
in) two or three times a year to help unleash needed nutrients.
Iron chelate, applied according to package directions, will boost
iron supplies and in turn help green up your plant.
</P>
<P>
   When you water, make sure it drains well. Empty any water in the
saucer. Do not water again until the soil is dry to the touch. Use
your finger to test moisture down in the pot. Sometimes when the
bottom is wet and the top is dry, we water, but the roots are
already getting sufficient moisture. Scheffleras seem to do best in
lightly moist soil.
</P>
<P>
   Repot every two years to give the roots a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
