r a BC-DOTCOMGUY-TEX     12-08 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOTCOMGUY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOTCOMGUY TO PURCHASE ALL NEEDS VIA WEB, WON'T LEAVE HOUSE FOR A
YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREA AHLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Truly wired Web surfers have suggested that all they need to
survive is a high-speed Internet connection, a computer and a
credit card.
</P>
<P>
   A 26-year-old Dallas native intends to prove that.
</P>
<P>
   Meet DotComGuy, who was known as Mitch Maddox before, he said,
he legally changed his name this fall. He will enter an empty house
in the Lake Highlands neighborhood of Dallas with only a donated
laptop computer and an Internet connection at noon Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In a marketing stunt that would make P.T. Barnum proud, he
intends to live exclusively off purchases made on the Internet for
a year. He says he will not leave the house.
</P>
<P>
   And in a twist that recalls the films ``EdTV'' and ``The Truman
Show,'' the world will be able to watch DotComGuy's adventure 24
hours a day, seven days a week on www.dotcomguy.com via a streaming
video Web cast.
</P>
<P>
   The point for DotComGuy and his corporate sponsors is to
demonstrate the usefulness and reliability of e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``DotComGuy can become a reference point for people before they
buy a product and where to go and purchase it,'' he said. ``We're
looking to provide a forum for people to talk about their Internet
experiences to share and learn from each other.''
</P>
<P>
   DotComGuy and his sponsors have established these ground rules
for his cyberspace journey:
</P>
<P>
   He has to buy everything he needs over the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   He can leave the house and grounds only in the event of a
serious illness or death in his immediate family.
</P>
<P>
   He may go outside, but only to his back yard. (The yard is
large, with a creek running through it.)
</P>
<P>
   He can have visitors. In fact, he will probably have many
cyber-guests and celebrity visitors.
</P>
<P>
   DotComGuy said he had the idea for the project about a year ago.
But it didn't become a reality until a few months ago, when he
spoke with Len Critcher, a buddy from junior high school, about how
to make it work.
</P>
<P>
   The two formed DotComGuy Inc., with Critcher as president.
DotComGuy, a former computer systems manager, said he sold some
stock and cashed in his 401(k) plan to finance the venture.
</P>
<P>
   The two have also lined up sponsors who will provide funding or
goods. Most sponsors are involved in technology or electronic
commerce, and they hope that the publicity will translate into
online customers.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway is providing the computer. Other sponsors _ who call the
project ``clever,'' ``edgy,'' and ``pretty strange'' _ include
Net.B(at)k, Mall.com, radio station KDGE/94.5 FM and Peapod.com, a
grocery service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may attract a lot of consumers, based on the novelty of
it,'' said Amy Larson, senior loyalty marketing manager at
Peapod.com.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Kerin, a Southern Methodist University marketing
professor, called the project an ``interesting publicity stunt.''
</P>
<P>
   He said e-commerce companies that do not have an established
reputation need to overcome consumer uncertainty about security and
delivery. That's why many online companies are spending millions on
advertising in traditional media like radio, television and print
to get people to visit their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Mall.com, which is based in Austin, jumped on board after an
impromptu meeting with the DotComGuy founders at the Mall.com 500
Indy-car race in Fort Worth in October.
</P>
<P>
   Critcher, who will produce the 24-hour Web cast, said the
project gave Mall.com a way to increase its exposure while
educating consumers on how to use its site.
</P>
<P>
   Although the project may seem extreme, DotComGuy is not going
where no one has gone before. He's just doing it for a longer time.
In November, ABC's ``Good Morning America'' program put two
29-year-old New Yorkers in an ``e-cave'' for one week with a bed, a
refrigerator, a $500 daily stipend and a computer to access the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Other news organizations, such as The Wall Street Journal, have
done similar Internet living experiences.
</P>
<P>
   While sitting in a house for a year may make some people
stir-crazy, DotComGuy will be well-paid. His first monthly paycheck
will be only $24. But the amount will double each month as an
incentive to stay. If he makes it through December, DotComGuy will
be paid a total of $98,280.
</P>
<P>
   DotComGuy said it was necessary to live in the house for a full
year to demonstrate the full extent of the Web, beyond just
shopping for groceries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wired life is going to be a very hot issue for lots of
people in the future,'' said Gordon Stark, vice president of
marketing at Panja, a DotComGuy sponsor. ``These guys are probably
going to show in a short period of time exactly how this technology
is going to impact the way we live and work.''
</P>
<P>
   Panja, a Dallas electronics company, will let DotComGuy use its
Panja 1000 entertainment device that allows users to download
Internet music and video files directly to stereo systems or
television sets.
</P>
<P>
   DotComGuy will also be able to step into the Internet,
literally. As part of the programming, DotComGuy will occasionally
review Web sites by standing in front of a green screen through
which a Web site is displayed. It works much like a weather
forecast on television.
</P>
<P>
   The company also plans to host cyber-chats, keep DotComGuy's
personal journal online, and possibly set up a rating system for
sites that DotComGuy has used or demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
   While DotComGuy will be incorporating the Internet into his
daily living, he said he probably will also buy high-tech items
that might not be in the typical family budget to demonstrate the
tech possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Critcher said DotComGuy is not limited to visiting sites from
sponsors, nor does he have a daily spending limit. But because the
founders have tapped their own resources for initial funding,
Critcher said, the budget is not unlimited.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
