<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADIES TAKE THE CAKE, AND CHEESE RING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two recipes today from American first ladies.
</P>
<P>
   The first is Lady Bird Johnson's lemon cake recipe. This cake
was baked for Luci's White House wedding and was much-publicized at
the time. Ann Strawser of Arlington, Texas, sent the recipe. She
used to make it for a friend who couldn't eat egg whites.
</P>
<P>
   LADY BIRD'S FAMOUS LEMON CAKE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Serves 16
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup butter or margarine, room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   8 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups cake flour
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated lemon rind
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Cream butter and sugar until fluffy. In a separate bowl, beat
egg yolks until light and lemon-colored; blend into creamed
mixture. Sift together flour, baking powder and salt; resift 3
times. Add sifted ingredients to creamed mixture in thirds,
alternating with milk. Beat the batter thoroughly after each
addition.
</P>
<P>
   Add vanilla, lemon rind and lemon juice; beat 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in greased 10-inch bundt pan in preheated oven at 325
degrees for 1 hour or until cake tester inserted in center comes
out clean.
</P>
<P>
   You can also can use three 9-inch round cake pans; bake at 350
degrees for 25 minutes. Double the frosting recipe for a layer
cake.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon icing:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter or margarine, room temperature
</P>
<P>
   Grated rind of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Juice of one lemon
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cream (or more, until spreading consistency)
</P>
<P>
   Yellow food coloring, if desired
</P>
<P>
   Combine and beat, adding cream until desired consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 318 calories, 15 grams fat, 44
grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 108 milligrams cholesterol,
328 milligrams sodium, 42 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Emma Jean Ross of Euless, Texas, wrote looking for Rosalynn
Carter's recipe for a cheese ring. She checked all the Jell-O
recipes she could and came up empty.
</P>
<P>
   Because Rosalynn is a Southerner, it's reasonable to think the
recipe would include Jell-O. However, there's not a bit of gelatin
in this composed appetizer.
</P>
<P>
   ROSALYNN'S PLAINS CHEESE RING
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   1 pound sharp Cheddar cheese, finely grated
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecan
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   6 twists freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Dash of cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   12-ounce jar strawberry preserves
</P>
<P>
   Whole-grain crackers or melba toast
</P>
<P>
   Combine cheese with mayonnaise, chopped nuts and onions. Mix in
black pepper and cayenne, and blend thoroughly. Press into 3-cup
ring mold. Refrigerate for at least 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, dip mold into a pan of hot water for 15-20 seconds
before turning out onto a serving platter. Fill center with
strawberry preserves and serve at once with whole-grain crackers or
melba toast.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving with 12-ounce jar of strawberry
preserves: 639 calories, 50 grams fat, 35 grams carbohydrates, 16
grams protein, 76 milligrams cholesterol, 515 milligrams sodium, 71
percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The White House Family Cookbook.'' by Henry Haller (Random
House, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Requests:
</P>
<P>
   Julie Carson saw a sweet-potato pudding recipe being
demonstrated on a TV show. It included sweet potatoes, sugar,
butter, milk and eggs, but she's not sure which spices were
included. Does anyone have such a recipe?
</P>
<P>
   A reader is looking for the recipe for fruited rice pudding
(which includes pineapple preserves and currants). The recipe was
included in the Southern Living annual recipe collection for 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Juanice Walther has misplaced a recipe that used frozen bread
rolls and pudding to make a coffeecake.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Jones of Cleburne, Texas, recalls the chile con queso
served at the Jiminez restaurant when it was on Grand Avenue in
north Fort Worth during the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was before queso really became a hot seller everywhere,
and theirs was very different. We were told that it was made with
five different cheeses, and it was almost completely white with
just a very slight tint of yellow. As the yellow queso became more
popular, theirs became very yellow as well. It was not nearly as
tasty as the original.''
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone have a clue about this one?
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
