<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3114 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-DIABETICS-HOLIDAYS-2n     12-08 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIABETICS-HOLIDAYS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: to flour mixture. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add warm water by the tablespoonful to crust mixture, if
necessary. Round dough into a ball and let stand, covered, at room
temperature for 15-30 minutes. Roll crust out on a lightly floured
surface to form a circle. Fit into 9-inch pie pan.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The New Diabetic Cookbook'' by Mabel Cavaiani (Contemporary
Books, $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   APPLE KUGEL
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound broad noodles
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup egg substitute
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon fructose, optional
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 small tart apple such as Granny Smith, peeled, cored and
thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup golden raisins
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped toasted almonds
</P>
<P>
   Butter-flavored cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon dry bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   Add noodles to rapidly boiling water and cook according to
package directions until tender. Drain. Toss with margarine. Mix
remaining ingredients except cooking spray and bread crumbs. Toss
with noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Lightly spray a 9-inch square
baking pan with cooking spray. Pour noodle mixture into pan. Top
with bread crumbs. Bake for 40 to 45 minutes, until a knife
inserted in center comes out clean. Serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 107 calories, 2 grams fat, 18
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 18 milligrams cholesterol, 32
milligrams sodium, 17 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Joslin Diabetes Gourmet Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CRANBERRY RELISH PIE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups ground cranberries
</P>
<P>
   1 cup ground Golden Delicious apples, unpeeled
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup ground orange pulp and peel
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated fructose
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Unbaked double Cheddar-cheese crust, recipe below
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons low-calorie margarine
</P>
<P>
   Combine fruits, fructose, flour, cinnamon and nutmeg in a bowl.
Toss to mix. Place pie crust in 9-inch pan and fill with fruit
mixture. Dot with margarine. Adjust top crust, flute or pinch
hedges, and cut slits in top to allow steam to escape. Bake at 425
degrees for 40 to 50 minutes or until lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   Cheddar-cheese crust:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Dash salt
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup grated sharp Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup solid shortening
</P>
<P>
   5 to 6 tablespoons ice water
</P>
<P>
   Combine flour, salt, cheese and shortening in a food processor
with a steel blade. Pulse on high until mixture turns into coarse
crumbs. On low, add water through feeder tube, 1 tablespoon at a
time, until dough starts to form a ball. Form dough into a ball
with your hands. Wrap in plastic wrap and chill for 2 hours. Divide
dough in half and roll out both halves on lightly floured surface.
Arrange bottom crust in pie pan. Add filling. Adjust top crust,
scoring or cutting slits to allow steam to escape. Seal edges.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: calories, grams fat, grams
carbohydrates, grams protein, milligrams cholesterol, milligrams
sodium, percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Diabetic Cakes, Pies and Other Scrumptious Desserts'' by
Mary Jane Finsand (Sterling, Out of Print)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   RAISIN SOUR-CREAM PIE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   8-inch baked pie shell, baked
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar replacement
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cold skim milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped raisins
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   3 egg yolks, beaten
</P>
<P>
   8-inch baked pie shell, baked
</P>
<P>
   Nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Mix flour, sugar replacement, skim milk, buttermilk, sour cream,
raisins and lemon juice in top of a double boiler. Stir to blend
thoroughly. Place over hot water, then cook and stir until mixture
thickens. Pour a little of the mixture into beaten egg yolks, then
return to boiler. Cook and stir 3 minutes longer. Remove from heat
and allow to cool. Transfer to baked pie shell. Sprinkle with
nutmeg. Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving (includes pie crust): calories,
grams fat, grams carbohydrates, grams protein, milligrams
cholesterol, milligrams sodium, percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Diabetic Cakes, Pies and Other Scrumptious Desserts''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PEANUT BUTTER BALLS
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 dozen
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped dates
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped raisins
</P>
<P>
   1 cup coarsely chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup molasses
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chunky peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons orange juice (unsweetened)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shredded coconut
</P>
<P>
   Using a wet knife or scissors, cut dates and raisins into small
pieces. Combine walnuts, dates and raisins in a medium-sized bowl.
Stir in molasses.
</P>
<P>
   Add peanut butter, stirring until fruit and nuts are evenly
distributed. Stir in enough orange juice to moisten mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Roll a teaspoon of batter into a small ball, then roll ball in
coconut. Form all the batter into balls.
</P>
<P>
   Store in an airtight container. Flavor improves after a day of
storage.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: calories, grams fat, grams
carbohydrates, grams protein, milligrams cholesterol, milligrams
sodium, percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Sugarless Baking Book'' by Patricia Terris Mayo
(Shambhala, out of print)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Here's a rundown of the artificial sweeteners on the market.
</P>
<P>
   SACCHARIN
</P>
<P>
   Commercial names: Sweet 'N Low, Sugar Twin
</P>
<P>
   Properties: 300 times sweeter than sugar; long shelf life,
heat-stable. Slightly bitter aftertaste.
</P>
<P>
   Safety: On a government list of likely carcinogens.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ASPARTAME
</P>
<P>
   Commercial names: NutraSweet, Equal, NatraTaste
</P>
<P>
   Properties: 200 times sweeter than sugar. Unstable when heated,
so if used in cooking, should be added at the very end or heated
for only very brief periods. Tastes similar to sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Safety: People who have phenylketonuria, a rare genetic
disorder, should not use; their bodies cannot process an amino acid
found in aspartame.
</P>
<P>
   Other people have complained of headaches and allergic
reactions, but no side effects have been scientifically documented.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ACESULFAME K
</P>
<P>
   Commercial name: Sunett
</P>
<P>
   Properties: 200 times sweeter than sugar. Stable when heated,
long shelf life. Often used in conjunction with other artificial
sweeteners to stabilize them in baking and to help retain sweetness
over time. No aftertaste.
</P>
<P>
   Safety: Some critics say tests to determine safety were sloppily
conducted, and that it's impossible to tell whether the substance
can cause cancer or not. Supporters note that more than 90 studies
have shown it to be safe.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SUCRALOSE
</P>
<P>
   Commercial name: Splenda
</P>
<P>
   Properties: 600 times sweeter than sugar. Stable when heated.
Tastes very much like sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Safety: 100 studies conducted over 20 years found no risk to
humans.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Note: Sugar substitutes also come in granulated form, usually
measured the same as sugar in a recipe. These include Splenda
granular, Equal Spoonful, Sugar Twin Spoonable and Sugar Twin
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   _ From staff and wire reports
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
