<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3115 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-DIABETICS-HOLIDAYS-12     12-08 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIABETICS-HOLIDAYS-1200(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUGAR-FREE SALVATION FOR THOSE WHO CAN'T EAT SUGAR-LADEN HOLIDAY
TREATS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL NUCKOLS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Visions of sugarplums are dancing in everybody's heads this time
of year.
</P>
<P>
   For diabetics, though, the debate over whether to indulge has
more serious consequences than for most folks. The consumption of
too many carbohydrates (of which sugar is one type) raises blood
sugar, possibly resulting in long-range complications such as
blindness and kidney damage.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, though, sugar is no longer completely forbidden.
Instead, experts tell diabetics that it's acceptable to work some
sugar into their meal plans. So sweetmeats (as well as other
holiday favorites such as stuffing and sweet potatoes) can be
carefully incorporated into a diabetic diet.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, ``They go into deprivation; at the holidays, they
would overdo it,'' says Diane Wallace, a registered dietitian and
certified diabetes educator with Huguley Health System of North
Texas. A bit of sugar now and then helps keep the sweet tooth under
control.
</P>
<P>
   If you intend to eat dessert, ``cut back on potatoes, sweet
potatoes, stuffing _ eat smaller portions of those,'' Wallace
advises.
</P>
<P>
   Diabetics should follow dietary guidelines established for them
individually by a dietitian. In addition to sugar, fat intake
should be considered, as diabetics are at greater risk for heart
disease than the general population, and some are overweight.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace suggests that diabetics pace themselves during the
holidays: ``Try not to save up and eat a large meal at the end of
the day. Snack a little so you're not tempted to overeat. And
exercise (performed on the day of a festive meal, such as
Christmas) can help bring down that blood sugar after eating a
little bit more than they were supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   The recipes provided here focus on sugar substitutes. If you're
converting some other recipe (one that calls for sugar), Wallace
warns that you shouldn't substitute a sugar alternative for more
than half the sugar in the recipe. ``The volume is so much less
when you're using a sugar substitute that the end product will come
out different,'' she says. (See list of sugar substitutes and their
uses.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BUCHE DE NOEL
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12
</P>
<P>
   Cake:
</P>
<P>
   5 large egg whites
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fructose, whirled in a blender or processor for 10
seconds
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sifted cake flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon almond extract
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   Filling:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream, whipped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fructose
</P>
<P>
   Meringue mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg white
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of cream of tartar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup superfine sugar
</P>
<P>
   Cake: Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Grease a 15-by-10-by-1-inch
jelly roll pan. Line bottom with wax paper.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, beat 5 egg whites until stiff. Add 1/4
cup fructose; beat well. Sift together remaining 1/4 cup fructose,
flour, baking powder and salt.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate bowl, beat egg yolks and almond extract until very
light and thick. Fold egg yolks into beaten egg whites. Gently fold
in dry ingredients a little at a time. Spread batter evenly in
prepared pan. Bake for 12 to 15 minutes, or until cake springs back
when touched lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Sift confectioners' sugar over a clean kitchen towel. Loosen
edges of cake; turn out onto towel. Remove wax paper carefully.
Roll up cake and towel from short side. Cool on a wire rack.
</P>
<P>
   Filling: Gently combine whipped cream, cocoa and fructose.
Unroll cake and remove towel. Spread a third of filling on cake.
Reroll cake. Cut off a 1-inch slice from one end; set aside. Place
cake, seam side down, on an oval or rectangular serving platter.
Gently press cut-off slice into side of ``trunk'' to simulate a
sawed-off branch.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve 3 tablespoons cream mixture to use when assembling
mushrooms. Chill until ready to use.
</P>
<P>
   Spread remaining cream mixture on ``trunk'' and ``branch,'' with
long strokes from one end to the other. Use tines of a fork to
simulate bark. Chill cake.
</P>
<P>
   Meringue mushrooms: Preheat oven to 250 degrees. Grease and
flour a cookie sheet.
</P>
<P>
   In a small mixing bowl, beat 1 egg white and cream of tartar
until foamy. Gradually beat in sugar until it forms stiff, glossy
peaks. Spoon into a pastry bag fitted with a large round tip. Don't
fill bag too full. Holding pastry bag fairly close to cookie sheet,
press out 3/4-inch-wide mushroom caps. Smooth top if peaked. For
stems, hold bag vertically; press out meringue. Pull straight up
until short stem forms. Continue to make mushroom stems. (Or, using
2 small spoons, form rounded mushroom caps and straight short
stems, smoothing out rough edges with the back of a spoon.)
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 30 to 40 minutes, until dry and ivory-colored. Loosen
with spatula. Cool on a wire rack.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble, make a small hole in underside of caps. Put in some
of the reserved cream. Insert pointed stem end.
</P>
<P>
   Top frosted cake with mushrooms. Refrigerate cake until serving
time.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving, with 2 meringue mushrooms: 150
calories, 8 grams fat, 16 grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 63
milligrams cholesterol, 107 milligrams sodium, 48 percent of
calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Joslin Diabetes Gourmet Cookbook'' by Bonnie Sanders
Polin and Frances Towner Giedt (Bantam Books, $29.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PUMPKIN PIE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   Filling:
</P>
<P>
   16-ounce can solid-pack pumpkin
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup liquid egg substitute
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   Sugar substitute equal to 1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons pumpkin pie spice
</P>
<P>
   1 2/3 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup instant nonfat dry milk
</P>
<P>
   1 unbaked pie crust, recipe below
</P>
<P>
   Combine filling ingredients and mix until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Pour filling into unbaked pie crust. Bake at 425 degrees for 15
minutes. Reduce oven temperature to 350 degrees without opening
oven door, and continue to bake for an additional 45 minutes, or
until a knife inserted in center of pie comes out clean. Cool to
room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Pie crust:
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup (2/3 stick) margarine
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Warm water
</P>
<P>
   Heat margarine and 2 tablespoons water together until margarine
is melted. Cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Place flour, baking powder and salt in mixing bowl and stir to
blend well. Stir margarine mixture with a fork to blend and add to
flour mixture.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
