<HEADER>
A3117 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-DIAMONDS-REVIEW-     12-08 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DIAMONDS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUGLAS CUTS FINE FIGURE IN `DIAMONDS'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use Friday, Dec. 10 or later. Fact box at bottom.) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is fitting that Miramax Films chose a movie set in Reno,
Nev., to gamble on Kirk Douglas' return to the screen in a lead
role less than four years after he suffered a speech-impairing
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diamonds'' pays off on the wager. Douglas, still vigorous at
83, carries the film with one of the best performances of his long
career, probably because many of his scenes are straight from the
heart.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas plays Harry Agensky, a former prize-winning boxer known
as the Polish Prince now dealing with old age, the aftermath of a
stroke and the death of his beloved wife. His son Lance (Dan
Aykroyd) and grandson Michael (Corbin Allred) arrive at his home in
western Canada with intentions of taking the old man to Banff. But
Harry brings up his oft-told tale of some diamonds he earned from a
Reno crime boss decades ago when he agreed to throw a fight, so
Harry, Lance and Michael impulsively head to the gaming mecca in
search of the hidden gems.
</P>
<P>
   It's a road trip all right, but not a standard buddy movie
because of the emotional baggage all three are dragging along on
this vacation. Harry mourns the losses of his wife, youth and
health; Lance still struggles with having felt neglected and
unloved by his father; and 15-year-old Michael is on the brink of
giving up allegiance to his own father in favor of his new stepdad.
</P>
<P>
   The whole father-son dynamic is a key element in ``Diamonds,''
and unfortunately it is the most trite aspect of Allan Aaron Katz's
script. The ``why can't you say you love me'' idea has been done
before (``East of Eden'' comes to mind), as has the concept of the
teen-age son rebelliously pushing his father's buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Harry's old-age issues, so often given to supporting players,
are well-developed here, in part because Douglas understands
first-hand the depression and frustrations common to stroke
sufferers. Harry is still full of bluster and ready go a few rounds
with all takers, but can break down and sob over his inadequacies.
Douglas also shows a knack for comedy and is not afraid to be the
butt of the humor.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas' nicest moments come in a scene with his longtime friend
Lauren Bacall, who plays Sin-dee, the senior citizen's answer to
the whore with a heart of gold, or, in this case, madam.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas' own stroke gives his performance an added credibility
as each word of dialogue is a deliberate effort. (By the way,
Douglas' lines are easily understood throughout the film.)
</P>
<P>
   Allred (also seen in ``Anywhere but Here'') is a natural as
Michael, fitting well with both Aykroyd and Douglas, even though
Aykroyd and Douglas don't always mesh with each other. He has funny
moments at Sin-Dee's brothel when he prepares to give up his
virginity to a prostitute named Sugar (Jenny McCarthy).
</P>
<P>
   Director John Asher, son of TV director William Asher, does a
straightforward job in his third feature. He makes good use of
Douglas' old footage from ``Champion,'' incorporating those
Republic Pictures boxing scenes into Harry's flashbacks to his
glory days. &QL; 
____ &UR;  &QL; 
The film: &LR;  ``Diamonds'' (PG-13; sexual content, drug use,
language). &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  Kirk Douglas, Dan Aykroyd, Corbin Allred, Lauren
Bacall, Jenny McCarthy. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR;  Directed by John Asher. Screenplay by Allan
Aaron Katz. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  97 minutes. &UR;  &QL; 
Playing: &LR;  AMC Century City for Oscar-qualifying run; opens wide in
January. &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR;  3 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
