<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, Dec. 9:
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS-FAVORITES (Undated) _ Five thousand years of recorded
history provided the House &AMP; Home section with a few thoughts on
holiday gifts for 1999. We looked back, then we looked forward, and
realized this: favorites never go away. by Marianne Rohrlich.
</P>
<P>
   MORONI-PROFILE (Undated) _ Lucretia Moroni is a mistress of
illusion. What a set designer does to the stage, she does to a
home. When she paints on panels of fabric, or on walls, ceilings
and floors, surfaces become mosaics, frescoes, taffeta. With paint,
she conjures Moroccan bazaars, Pompeiian courtyards, Indian souks.
She makes visual fantasies. By Elaine Louie.
</P>
<P>
   With MORONI-WALLS: Walls are vast, natural canvases, and
sometimes ordinary paint and wallpaper just won't do. By Elaine
Louie.
</P>
<P>
   LINEN-PARTIES (Undated) _ Ever been at a party at someone's
house when the drinks were passed around and conversation stopped
cold because the white cocktail napkins just didn't match the room?
In the world of ordinary mortals, probably not. But yes, it does
happen. A group of women were discussing such niceties at a Park
Avenue linen party just last week. By Monique P. Yazigi.
</P>
<P>
   PARZINGER-FURNISH (Undated) _ Tommi Parzinger's furnishings are
highly prized and heavily collected, as examples of a more
idiosyncratic, rarified mid-century design _ an elegant aside to
the Eameses, Knolls and Nelsons of the period _ that the market
calls ``high-style modernism.'' By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   OLD-TOOLS (Undated) _ All kinds of wonderful old tools _ cheap
and not so cheap _ can be found in a lot of places these days:
country auctions, flea markets, swap meets and, maybe best of all,
the Internet. By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With how-to drawing.
</P>
