<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3126 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-HILLARY'SCHOICE-     12-08 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HILLARY'SCHOICE-TEX </SLUG>
 
Gail Sheehy dissects Hillary's psyche 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Hillary's Choice''
</P>
<P>
   By Gail Sheehy
</P>
<P>
   Biography
</P>
<P>
   Random House, $23.95
</P>
<P>
   We can state, by now, that Bill and Hillary Clinton have
succeeded O.J. Simpson as America's emotional lightning rods.
People love them; love him/hate her; love her/hate him; or hate
them both. But many Americans judge others by whether they're in
what might be termed ``Clinton agreement''; they've learned all
they want to know about the first couple and dismiss any new
information or insights as extraneous.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect that's why Gail Sheehy's ``Hillary's Choice'' will
generate a little post-publication stir and then disappear. The
book itself, a study ofthe first lady by one of our best-known
sociologist/biographers, can objectively be called uneven. Sheehy
is a superb reporter, and even though many of her interviews
involve the often-quoted (Dick Morris again!), she elicits new,
fascinating testimony, especially from Hillary Clinton's brother
and mother.
</P>
<P>
   Periodically, though, Sheehy succumbs to temptation and launches
into cliche-ridden pop psychology, telling readers what ``all this
means'' when they ought to be making up their own minds. Having
spent so many words proving that Hillary is uncategorizable, Sheehy
tries the categorizing game herself and, by so doing, puts the
brakes on her book's undeniable momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the cause is the author's own, very obvious, inability
to decide whether she likes the first lady. We learn in the
earliest chapters that young Hillary grew up in a household just as
tormented, in its way, as the much-publicized emotion-racked
childhood home of future husband Bill. Deprived of paternal
affection _ Hugh Rodham Sr. withheld approval regarding anything
his daughter did _ Hillary went off to Wellesley College uncertain
of who she wanted to be, and tried on several personas before
graduation.
</P>
<P>
   What never changed, though, was the young woman's iron will
power when she did decide to support or work for a cause.
Gradually, her personal politics switched from Goldwater
Republicanism to Martin Luther King liberalism (as a teen-ager, she
met King briefly). The teen-ager who wore thick glasses and
body-swathing dresses evolved into a student leader whose strident
commencement address won a standing ovation from her peers. She
embarked on a torrid love affair (Sheehy perhaps provides too many
details here), set herself on the road to lucrative private law
practice, and gave everything up to marry an overweight womanizer
from the Arkansas backwoods.
</P>
<P>
   This throwing away of potential, this self-denial to further the
career of someone else, is the basis of Sheehy's title. And, as
events as well as this book make clear, that first choice of
Hillary's led to similarly difficult choices later on.
</P>
<P>
   The new Mrs. Clinton, Sheehy proves again and again, hated
Arkansas. She hated sublimating her emerging, forceful personality
to the sweet stereotype expected by Arkansas voters who otherwise
might not vote for Bill Clinton _ heaven save the Sooey State from
a feminist first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bill's philandering bruised his marriage but didn't destroy
it _ the Clintons had a beloved daughter to nurture and political
ambition to protect. Sheehy dramatically shows how Hillary
Clinton's nature lent itself to attacking her husband's political
and personal accusers instead of deciding, after a while, that the
man she married had wasted enough second chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary's Choice'' also recounts White House Hillary,
including the humiliation she suffered by her failure to effect
health-care reform. The Sheehy pop prognosis is that Hillary is
addicted to saving her husband, since she learned in childhood to
measure self-worth by rescuing others.
</P>
<P>
   If Sheehy is ambivalent about Hillary Clinton, her subject is
frankly displeased with the author. Her staff members have begun
denouncing portions of ``Hillary's Choice'' as inaccurate _ a case
in point is whether Hugh Rodham attended his daughter's Wellesley
graduation. Sheehy writes that he didn't; Hillary Clinton's
spokespeople insist that he did, and Rodham is dead, so no one can
ask him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary's Choice,'' read by anyone who hasn't made up his or
her mind about its subject, would be about a B-plus effort. It
won't replace ``Passages'' as the book for which Sheehy is
eventually remembered, but it's far from hack work. Unfortunately,
there are very few objective readers left. .MDUL/.MDNM/ (Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
