<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3128 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV1     12-08 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV12-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 12)  
 McGOVERN NOW UNDERSTANDS JOHNSON'S VIETNAM AGONY  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In this holiday season of surprises, it is
astounding to learn that Democrat George McGovern, a stern critic
of Lyndon B. Johnson, now judges him to have been one of the three
or four greatest presidents since Abraham Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there, on the Op-Ed page of the New York Times last Sunday,
was McGovern's confession, nearly three decades after the fact,
that he understands the ordeal Johnson suffered as result of the
war in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``My views on the war have not changed,'' wrote the one-time
South Dakota senator who ran for president in 1972 as an outspoken
critic of the war, ``but my opinion of Johnson has. I believe now
that with the exceptions of Woodrow Wilson and Franklin Roosevelt _
and perhaps Theodore Roosevelt _ Lyndon Johnson was the greatest
president since Abraham Lincoln.''
</P>
<P>
   McGovern's change of attitude is not a matter of the dove
suddenly discovering that the hawk was correct. It is rather one of
the dove belatedly realizing that the hawk suffered deep agony as
he dispatched young men and women to the bloody cauldron of
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern revised his thinking after reading that former
ambassador John Kenneth Galbraith had called for a reassessment of
Johnson and after studying presidential transcripts. The
transcripts covered Johnson's taped White House conversations with
Georgia's Richard Russell, chairman of the Senate Armed Service
Committee during Vietnam, and McGeorge Bundy, who served as
Johnson's national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling that Johnson, then Senate majority leader, and Russell
both opposed American intervention in Vietnam when the Eisenhower
administration proposed it in the 1950s, McGovern explained that
the tapes demonstrate how Johnson and Russell ``continued to have
terrible doubts and regrets, even while publicly supporting the
war.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of us who knew Johnson and covered his presidency were
aware long ago of Johnson's despair as the war went on and on,
claiming thousands of lives. He would leave his bed in the middle
of the night and go to the White House Situation Room, where he
could learn how many of the troops he sent into battle had been
shot from the skies or killed on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson succeeded the slain John F. Kennedy as president in
November 1963, America had 16,000 military advisers in Vietnam.
Thinking that the United States could defeat the communist Vietcong
and preserve South Vietnam as a bastion of democracy, Johnson
dispatched the first contingent of U.S. Marines to Southeast Asia
in 1965. He continued to escalate America's participation in the
war until in 1968 more than a half million U.S. troops were there.
</P>
<P>
   In the atmosphere of the Cold War, he felt, as almost any U.S.
president would have felt, that America had to make a strong stand
against communist aggression in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, anger over the war cut a bitter, bloody swath
through this country. College campuses and downtown streets erupted
into battlegrounds where antiwar militants and police fought each
other in excruciating confrontations. The cost in terms of American
unity was horrendous.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most forceful figures to occupy the presidency,
Johnson also was one of the most insecure and most volatile. He
could be as warm and gentle as a fur-lined glove and as devious and
demanding as a raging bull.
</P>
<P>
   When he entered the presidency he hoped to emulate his idol,
Franklin D. Roosevelt, who guided the United States successfully
through the Great Depression and World War II. Johnson, with his
``Great Society'' program, was determined to enact a remarkable
package of domestic reforms and then prevent America's Cold War
adversaries from expanding their domain.
</P>
<P>
   He achieved the first objective with the passage of Medicare and
Medicaid, with a massive infusion of federal money into education,
and with monumental civil rights laws that ended legalized racial
segregation in public accommodations and polling booths. But he
failed the second test when victory in Vietnam became unattainable.
</P>
<P>
   He finally decided in 1968 to forego another full term in the
White House because he could not heal the breech that separated
American from American.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite his involvement with the war,'' McGovern wrote,
``Johnson used his remarkable political skills to build the most
far-reaching progressive domestic program since the New Deal. ...
Johnson did more than any other president to advance civil rights,
education and housing, to name just three of his concerns, through
enactment of laws.''
</P>
<P>
   And when his presidency ended, he left behind the last balanced
budget that Americans would see until the final two years of Bill
Clinton's tenure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
