<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3139 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-BUSH-ROVE09-COX     12-08 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ROVE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS GOP NOMINEE, BUSH WOULD ACCEPT PUBLIC FUNDS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas will accept public
funds for his general election campaign if he wins the Republican
nomination, his top political aide said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's fund-raising prowess has allowed him to forgo federal
funding and avoid any spending restraints during the primary
campaign season. Bush and millionaire publisher Steve Forbes are
the only presidential candidates in both major parties who need not
abide by state-by-state spending curbs.
</P>
<P>
   In an hour-long breakfast meeting with reporters, Karl Rove, who
has drawn the strategic road map for the front-running Texas
Republican, noted that ``it is awfully difficult to raise $60
million or thereabouts between the convention and the Election Day
and still campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove dismissed any suggestion that it would be hypocritical of
Bush to defeat his Republican rivals for the nomination by spending
freely in the primaries, only to turn around and use taxpayer
money, without any outside help, for the final White House contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the logic of that at all,'' Rove said. ``The
people who have been critical of what we've done so far generally
favor the public financing route that we'll be taking if we win the
nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove also sought to deflect the idea, which has been widely
reported, that in two recent debates, in New Hampshire and Arizona,
Bush came across as an intellectual lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the burden of a front-runner,'' he said,
predicting that ``the race will now tighten because we face
candidates who are about to split their time (among early primary
battlegrounds). Everybody has to get past you to get into the first
place. That's just the facts of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove noted that Bush has actually doubled his debate experience
in his two recent outings. His two prior engagements were in Texas
gubernatorial races, against Ann Richards in 1994 and Gary Mauro in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   While conceding that Bush appeared somewhat stiff before the TV
cameras and may have been misconstrued as having smirked at his
primary opponents, Rove nevertheless said: ``People will make their
judgments about the whole person. Does he come across better when
he's sitting two feet away from you? You bet.''
</P>
<P>
   As Rove sees it, the political chemistry of the 2000 race from
the White House differs radically from recent such contests. This
means, he said, that there can be ``a great desire for change in
the country and a movement to deny a 'third term' to (Vice
President Al) Gore even though the nation appears to be
prosperous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I live in Austin,'' Rove, 48, noted, ``and there I a meet a
lot of high-tech people like those who work for Dell (Computer
Corp.) and who are generally left of center in their political
beliefs. And they say that they're responsible for the good
economy, and not the Clinton-Gore administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rove said, President Clinton's final year in office will
be consumed with ``protecting his legacy and electing a
successor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very strong emphasis in this White House on how to
shape issues to be of the greatest possible assistance to Al Gore.
That's just the reality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During his extended exchange with Washington-based political
journalists from major news outlets, Rove suggested that their
ability to influence voters may well dim ``with the rise of the new
media.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In my travels, more and more I hear from people who say
they've watched an entire Bush speech on C-SPAN,'' Rove reported.
In addition to the cable-sponsored public affairs channel, Rove
said, there appears to be a desire among voters in this election
cycle ``to bypass traditional media sources in learning about
candidates on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
