<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D.BIERSDORFER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How can I convert the icons on my computer desktop to ones I
want instead of the regular Windows 98 ones?
</P>
<P>
   A. Spicing up your computing day with desktop icons other than
the standard issue (like My Computer) is fairly easy. Once you have
the icon or icons you would like to use, go to the Start menu to
Settings, pick Control Panel and select Display.
</P>
<P>
   Click on the Effects tab in the box and then the Desktop Icons
option, which will show you all the default desktop icons. Click on
the icon you want to change, then click on the Change Icon button.
To select the replacement icon, click the Browse button, locate the
new icon file on your computer and click Open. You will see the
icon change, and if you like it, click on OK and close the box.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a Macintosh user, click once on the icon you wish to
use and press Command-I. This brings up the Get Info box. Click
once on the icon's picture. A small box outline will form around
the icon. Press Command-C to copy it. Close that Get Info box,
click once on the icon you wish to change and press Command-I
again. Click on the old icon, and when the box outline appears,
type Command-V to paste the new icon into place before closing the
Get Info box.
</P>
<P>
   To find new icons, try Icons Plus (www.iconsplus.com), a
freeware site that offers many icons with a pop-culture bent for
both Mac and Windows. The site also has a lengthy list of links to
other icon outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd St.,
New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
