<HEADER>
A3147 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     12-08 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEANING AND REPAIRING FURNITURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   No matter how careful people are, they are bound to scratch
furniture. Most of these mishaps are minor and can easily be be
erased or hidden before they become eyesores. However, no matter
how minor the blemish, you may not want to remove it yourself if
your furniture is a valuable antique.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture picks up dirt and dust that slowly works its way into
the waxed surface. Over time, this grime will dull the sheen of any
finish and obscure the beauty of the wood grain. Wood surfaces can
easily be cleaned with solvent, but be careful because some
solvents can remove or damage the finish. Alcohol, for example, can
dissolve a shellac finish. Mineral spirits work well and are
harmless to all finishes; still, it's a good practice to test any
solvent in an inconspicuous spot before working on a prominent
area.
</P>
<P>
   Also keep in mind that all solvents are flammable and toxic.
Read the directions carefully and take all precautions to prevent
fire and personal injury. Work in a ventilated area, and do not use
any solvent near an open flame. If you are going to do a lot of
work with a solvent, wear a respirator and rubber gloves.
</P>
<P>
   To clean furniture of wax and dirt build-up, wet a coarse, clean
rag with mineral spirits and wipe across the surface. Turn the rag
over to expose a clean side and wipe again. Continue this procedure
until the rag no longer picks up dirt.
</P>
<P>
   This technique works well with the large open surfaces, but it
may not remove the dirt that collects in the grooves and crevices
of carved areas. Clean these places with a cotton swab dipped in
mineral spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Scratches that are in the finish but do not cut into the wood
below can be removed with very fine steel wool (0000) and Danish
oil. Pour some oil into a pad of steel wool and rub with the grain.
Keep the pad saturated with oil and rub with a light touch; you
only want to remove the scratches in the finish without damaging
the stain underneath. Work cautiously near the edges or corners,
they can easily wear through.
</P>
<P>
   When the scratches are removed, wipe with a rag and mineral
spirits. Go over the area several times, opening the cloth
frequently to uncover clean fabric. You must remove all traces of
the Danish oil or it will repel the new finish.
</P>
<P>
   Allow the surface to dry thoroughly, at least 24 hours, then
spray it with a coat of clear lacquer. Hold the can at a 45-degree
angle about eight inches from the furniture surface. Press the
spray button and move the can in a continuous motion in line with
the grain.
</P>
<P>
   You may need to make several passes to cover a wide area. After
each pass, wipe the spray nozzle to prevent drips. Use newspapers
to cover areas that you don't want coated.. It takes a bit of
practice to spray lacquer in a smooth coat, so you may want to try
this technique on a piece of cardboard before committing yourself
to the furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Scratches that cut through the finish into the wood are lighter
in color than the surrounding wood and stand out as eyesores. These
must be colored so they blend with the adjacent area. You can use
an artist's permanent felt-tip marker, available in a variety of
colors in art supply stores.
</P>
<P>
   Gouges are deep scratches that must be filled as well as
colored; otherwise they will collect dirt and become permanently
discolored. Use colored furniture sticks for a filler and coloring
agent. Although these sticks come in a variety of colors, it is
unlikely that you will find one stick with the exact color of your
furniture. Buy several and blend them together to get a good color
match.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape a few flakes from each stick and knead them together with
your fingers. The kneading will blend the colors together and make
the putty pliable enough to press into the gouge. Use a small flat
stick or spatula to smooth the filler and to scrape away any
excess. Do not attempt to apply lacquer directly over the putty;
this will prevent it from drying properly and turn it into a sticky
blob. Instead, seal the patch with a light spray of shellac. This
will allow the putty to harden although it will remain pliable for
some time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
