   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Washington) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush will accept
federal matching funds for the fall election, presuming he wins the
nomination, a campaign spokesman says. That means the man with $70
million to spend will have to abide by spending limits, an option
he decided against for the primary. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GAYS (Washington) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush's top
campaign strategist, Karl Rove, defends the Republican presidential
front-runner's controversial decision to snub leaders of a gay GOP
group, the Log Cabin Republicans, asserting that they have
criticized Bush on a number of issues. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-INTERVIEW (Newark, N.J.) _ Presidential candidate Bill
Bradley, in an interview with reporters here, defends his
controversial remarks last week that, if elected, he would consider
a tax hike to pay for his health plan. The Democratic challenger
also discusses gay rights, immigration and environmental issues. By
DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NASA-DELAY (Undated) _ NASA again postpones the launch of the
shuttle Discovery because of a dented cooling pipe. The shuttle
crew is scheduled to rendezvous with the Hubble telescope for
long-delayed repairs. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   NASA-SHUTTLE (Undated) _ Once the Discovery gets off the ground,
spacewalking shuttle astronauts plan to hitch up with one of the
most valuable and productive pieces of hardware in space, the
Hubble observatory, and try to bring it back to life. Their
objective is to replace a half-dozen gyroscopes, key components in
the pointing system that enables Hubble to be aimed at stars.
Gyroscope failures forced astronomers to halt all observations with
the telescope Nov. 13. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   With: NASA-SHUTTLE-TASKS
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-FELONS (Austin, Texas) _ Despite Texas Gov. George W.
Bush's vow to crack down on gun law violators, state officials have
information that several hundred convicted felons in Texas may have
broken federal gun laws. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
