<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-OZ-BAUM-WEB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING TO THE LAND OF OZ IS EASIER ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By MICHAEL POLLAK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lyman Frank Baum, a gentle man with a gift for storytelling, was
entertaining his sons and their friends in Chicago one day in 1898.
He began a tale about a girl named Dorothy and how she met a
scarecrow. ``Where did they live?'' a small voice asked. As the
account goes, he looked at his two file drawers, A-N and O-Z.
</P>
<P>
   Next year is the publication centennial of America's greatest
fairyland, one that Baum created without the Grimms' horror or
ugliness or moralizing. The International Wizard of Oz Club
(www.ozclub.org) is already hard at work on a celebration July
20-23 at Indiana University at Bloomington.
</P>
<P>
   There will be scholarly papers (27 and growing), performances of
early Oz plays and films, an exhibition of rare Oziana and perhaps
a Russian Oz author _ Russians may not have invented the Emerald
City, but they and others are still expanding it.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Albright of Kansas City, Mo., vice president of the club
and the organizer of the centennial, wrote by e-mail that her
interest in Oz had begun with a dozen Oz books before she had even
known how to read. ``I simply opened them and fell in love,'' she
wrote. ``The sense of place Baum created in Oz was as tangible to
me as Kansas _ I was raised in Topeka. I've yet to encounter any
other fantasy land as utterly convincing.''
</P>
<P>
   Club members, and the countless fans who learned to read and
loved to dream on the Oz books, grieve that so many people know
only about a movie. There's a reason for that, and it makes Oz
online doubly important. The Oz books can be hard to find without a
Web guide. They have often been unpopular with teachers and
librarians _ for having no formal educational purpose, for not
preaching, for being too funny, too irreverent, too easy to read,
too imaginative, too undignified. Baum's style is simple and often
repetitive; it is his imagination that is spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   The voluminous Wonderful Wizard of Oz Web site by Eric Gjovaag
(www.eskimo.com/tiktok) has a history of Oz, information about the
centennial convention, lesson ideas for teachers, a message board
and Oz updates. Its 19-chapter Frequently Asked Questions about Oz
provide an exhaustive resource for every conceivable aspect of
Oziana in print, and on stage and screen.
</P>
<P>
   Gjovaag's site debunks two of the most frequent false rumors
about Oz. No, there is not a hanged man in the forest scene in the
movie, and no, Baum did not set out to write a parable about
populism. That myth arose from a 1964 article in the magazine
American Quarterly by a high-school teacher, Henry M. Littlefield,
who used Oz as an allegory to teach about the populist movement and
the election of 1896. Littlefield has since written that there is
no evidence that Baum intended a political message.
</P>
<P>
   The Emerald City of Oz site (www.emeraldcityofoz.com) has an
extensive online library, with both summaries and full text, of the
Oz books by Baum and by his successor as ``Royal Historian of Oz,''
Ruth Plumly Thompson, as well as the artist John R. Neill and later
successors. The Oz Library (homes.acmecity.com/oz/baum/123)
includes the text of 21 Oz books, plus many illustrations, as well
as the complete script for the 1939 movie.
</P>
<P>
   Jim's Wizard of Oz Website
(www.geocities.com/Hollywood/Hills/6396/index.html) has a good deal
of magic itself. On its Mouseovers Page, the movie's main
characters are shown as they appear in Kansas. Rolling the cursor
over them turns them into their Oz equivalents. The official Warner
Brothers Wizard of Oz movie site is
www.thewizardofoz.com/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   As for the synchronicity between the movie and Pink Floyd's 1973
album ``Dark Side of the Moon,'' which members of the rock group
have denied is intentional, try
www.xnet.com/arkiver/synch/dsotr.shtml.
</P>
<P>
   Piglet Press (www.halcyon.com/piglet/index.htm) produces and
sells audio versions of many Oz books; its Web site has many online
listening selections. Piglet Press also has a wonderfully
illustrated cross-referenced Oz encyclopedia. Try it out using one
of the best names in Oz: the Lord High Chigglewitz. The Piglet
index will remind you that his real name is Larry and he is the
chief Fuddleperson in Fuddlecumjig (in the north of the Quadling
country). He uses his jigsaw-puzzle skills to piece together the
Fuddles, who fly apart at the slightest provocation ... oh, never
mind. Just read ``The Emerald City of Oz.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
