<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3154 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-WEB-SAILOR-2TAKES     12-08 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-SAILOR-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO YEARS BEFORE THE MAST (AND THE COMPUTER) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Colo., N.C., Senegal, Brazil, Trinidad, Thailand)   (Circuits)  
(DW) 
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If wind, weather and luck hold out, the crew of the Makulu II, a
43-foot sailboat-turned-cyberspace-classroom, is expected to
complete a two-year voyage around the world on Saturday by sailing
into a Florida marina not far from where it started. But that news
would hardly be a surprise to the thousands, perhaps millions, of
students and the simply curious who have been following the crew's
exploits and explorations by way of e-mail and the crew's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike mariners of old, the six young men and women on board,
who look more like Ralph Lauren models than ship-weary sailors,
have been using computer technology to take anyone with access to
the World Wide Web along with them _ virtually, of course.
</P>
<P>
   They have shared practically everything online, like digital
pictures of their underwear drying in the sea breeze and weekly log
entries describing their adventures, as well as funeral rituals in
Southeast Asia, Carnival celebrations in Gibraltar and a solemn
tour of a former slave-trade house on an island off the coast of
West Africa.
</P>
<P>
   There have been the dispatches, sometimes routine and sometimes
hauntingly honest, uploaded to the Net from the Makulu II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crossing from Senegal to Brazil in this season is proving more
difficult than we thought!'' reads one of the weekly updates posted
on the Makulu II's Web site, www.reachtheworld.org. ``We did NOT
find the wind that we hoped would carry us southwest to Brazil. As
a result, we have changed our plan and are heading directly to
Trinidad, a 2,200-plus-mile passage that could take as long as 40
days.''
</P>
<P>
   The interactive adventure has all been done in the cause of
education _ that of the crew and, most important, the students who
are part of a global network of classrooms linked to the Makulu II
over the Internet, said Heather Halstead, the 25-year-old creator
and co-captain of the project. The crew receives as many as 200
messages a month from students and teachers. They are part of a
project that would not be possible without the relatively low-cost
computer-assisted communications available today, Ms. Halstead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been into teaching my whole life,'' Ms. Halstead
said in an interview in New York while on a break from the voyage
during which she visited with her family and some of the project's
participating schools. ``And I always knew I wanted to sail around
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obvious fun Ms. Halstead and her crew have had, the
pictures and dispatches that have been streaming from the crew have
hardly been the stuff of vacation postcards.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ms. Halstead, with the help of a group of educators,
created a curriculum center online that helps classroom teachers
use the experiences of the Makulu II crew to learn and teach about
world cultures and more. There have been lesson and activity guides
that have covered, among other subjects, African art and gravestone
art, world languages, origin myths and astronomy, cartography and
weather forecasting.
</P>
<P>
   The sailboat uses satellite-assisted navigation and
communications, which include an on-board telephone and e-mail. But
the services are expensive, she said. The telephone, which uses a
technology called side band radio that bounces signals off the
atmosphere, costs about $5 a minute, and e-mail costs almost a
penny per character, Ms. Halstead said. The crew also uses much
cheaper e-mail systems at cybercafes when it can find them on land,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   By communicating directly with Ms. Halstead, a sixth-grade class
was able to persuade the Makulu II crew to swing by Singapore to
complete a fact-finding itinerary; another school asked the crew to
ask middle school students in the Cook Islands questions they had
about their lives here; still another school used the Makulu II to
chat with children in a Thai fishing village.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wonderful experience for my students to be able to
feel a connection to real people as they studied the classroom
maps,'' said Pat Palazzolo, a ninth-grade teacher at the Upper St.
Clair High School in Clair, Pa. ``My students were fascinated by
the idea of people not much older than themselves involved in such
as adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Combining her interests in education and circumnavigating the
planet was far from easy for Ms. Halstead. Shortly after graduating
from Dartmouth in 1997 with an honors degree in American social
history and education, Ms. Halstead decided that she would indeed
do just that.
</P>
<P>
   The product of an affluent New York family, Ms. Halstead was
able to use money she inherited from her paternal grandfather _ the
inspiration for the voyage _ to buy the yacht with the idea of
recovering the money by selling the boat once the trip was
completed. But buying a ocean-going vessel was only the beginning.
She created the Reach the World Co., a nonprofit group that became
the organization base for the voyage and related educational
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Then in quick order, she said, she had to teach herself how to
insure a boat (something that would come in handy during the trip),
equip it so that she could communicate with students and teachers,
and select a crew.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a co-captain was simple. Ms. Halstead, who as a child
was terrified of boats, later fell in love with them at a summer
sailing camp she attended in the British Virgin Islands.
Eventually, she became an instructor and developed, she said, the
confidence to believe she could sail around the world. Sailing was
also in her blood. Her father, Clark Halstead, sails and her
maternal grandfather was a cruise director and merchant marine.
</P>
<P>
   As an instructor at the sailing camp, Ms. Halstead met Marc
Gustafson, also an instructor and an able sailor. Together, she and
Gustafson, who is 22 and a graduate of Elon College in North
Carolina and the Chapman School of Seamanship in Stuart, Fla., are
the Makulu II's skippers.
</P>
<P>
   The co-captains' first two days at the helm of the Makulu II
(which in Zulu roughly means ``big mama'') were not promising. In
trying to move the boat to a marina where the voyage would begin,
Gustafson ran it aground three times _ hard _ along Florida's
intercoastal waterway from Titusville to Fort Lauderdale before he
got the feel of the sailboat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a disaster,'' Ms. Halstead recalled. ``We were
discouraged, to say the least. We're like, we're never going to get
out of Florida. It's funny to look back on it now.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Crew members have numbered more than two dozen friends,
relatives and other volunteers who have sailed passages on the
Makulu II of varying lengths. The current crew has been onboard for
a semester. Each is required to contribute $1,000 a month to help
cover the cost of the voyage. Other costs are covered by donations
and grants to Reach the World.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really didn't believe she was going to pull it off,'' her
mother, Carol Halstead, said with a chuckle. ``But we kind of
encouraged her. Now the fact is that she is making it happen and it
is awe inspiring.''
</P>
<P>
   Shawn McCullough, 29, a former wilderness ranger from Boulder,
Colo., with little ocean-sailing experience, joined the crew in the
fall. He said he was sold on the idea shortly after speaking with
Heather Halstead and remembering how ``she was constantly sparking,
never letting the fire die out'' of the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that excited me most,'' McCullough said, was having a
child be able to write to us on the ocean and say, `Can you take a
picture of the sunrise in the middle of the Atlantic?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Halstead knows the feeling. Having taught in challenging
environments before, from the backwoods of Colorado to the bush in
Kenya during a semester break from college, she said she was moved
to create the floating classroom on the Makulu II to give teachers
and students richer resources with which to better explore the
world and its people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been out there long enough to see what the connections
are between different regions,'' she said, noting that she had been
able to see traces of different languages from the east coast of
Africa to the Middle East and various movements in dances in widely
separated cultures in the South Pacific, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've sort of had this idea of the world being an overlapping
of concentric circles, of cultural influences,'' Ms. Halstead said.
``It's really there. I love that.''
</P>
<P>
   While she and her crew have had trouble, including ripped sails
and serious engine trouble 50 hours out of Trinidad, the Makulu II
is expected to reach the Florida coast on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   When it arrives, Carol Halstead said, she will be both proud and
relieved. ``They have learned so much,'' she said of the voyage,
``but it has been a school of hard knocks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
