<HEADER>
A3158 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-$800-PHONE-SALES-     12-08 0253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-$800-PHONE-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMAGE IS KEY TO SELLING NOKIA'S $799 CELL PHONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(DW) 
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to claiming the hearts and pockets of the
disposable income crowd, Nokia doesn't mess around.
</P>
<P>
   The company has spent millions on print and television
advertising, event sponsorship and product placement for its
high-priced 8860 cell phone, and at last September's Emmy awards,
Nokia gave one to everyone who won or presented an award. ``Believe
you me, every single person who did not win an Emmy called
afterward, wanting one,'' said Megan Matthews, a Nokia spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Nice party favors, but at $799, are they selling? Apparently so.
</P>
<P>
   The 8860 was already a hot item in Europe and Asia when it made
its official debut in AT&AMP;T Wireless stores last month. Ken Woo, a
spokesman for AT&AMP;T Wireless, said the phone was selling well.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Woo said, he got a call from Barbara Walters'
assistant, inquiring about discounts. Ms. Walters, who recently
praised the phone on the air, wants to give away a half-dozen of
them as Christmas gifts, the assistant told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a high end device, it's selling quite well,'' said Brian
Modoff, an analyst with Deutsche Banc Alex Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Nokia is the 11th most recognized brand worldwide, ahead of
Mercedes, according to Interbrand, a consulting firm. ``They're
selling an image, not technology,'' Modoff said. ``They're very
good at technology, but image is the key.''  &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
