<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-ETIQUETTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFINITIVELY CORRECT BEHAVIOR, AVAILABLE IN ENCYCLOPEDIC DETAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By BONNIE ROTHMAN MORRIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just in time for holiday entertaining, Emily Post's
``Etiquette'' has been published on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Bartleby.com, the publisher of classic fiction, nonfiction and
reference works on the Web, has posted the original 1922 edition of
``Etiquette in Society, in Business, in Politics and at Home'' to
add to its growing library of reference books, including Bartlett's
``Familiar Quotations'' (ninth edition) and Strunk and White's
``Elements of Style.''
</P>
<P>
   When originally published, ``Etiquette'' was an instant hit,
selling one million copies, said Steven Van Leewan, founder and
publisher of Bartleby.com (www.bartleby.com). The book has since
gone through 16 revisions. ``Emily Post was a literary writer,
philosopher and feminist,'' Van Leewan said, ``a self-made woman
who was old-fashioned in a sense but who wanted this decorum to be
available to every American.''
</P>
<P>
   In the original edition of ``Etiquette,'' Mrs. Post's popular,
finger-wagging prose advised the nouveaux riches of the 1920s on
topics like how to dress their servants for a stand-up luncheon,
when women should remove their hats (almost never) and how to ask
someone to fill a place at a party when another guest suddenly
cancels (make sure they are very good friends and don't explain a
thing).
</P>
<P>
   On the Web site, an index allows readers to quickly scan through
1,500 subjects like ``Have Silver That Shines or None'' and ``The
`Cut Direct,''' which Mrs. Post explains as ignoring someone
standing directly in front of you on purpose, which ``is
practically unknown in polite society.''
</P>
<P>
   While Mrs. Post's 38 chapters on deportment may at first glance
seem arcane, much of her advice has trickled down and out into
modern-day living. Van Leewan noted that a perusal of the first
edition of ``Etiquette'' shows that good manners never change no
matter the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has advice on the subject. The etiquette-impaired can now
find updated advice about comportment on Web sites like How2.com
(www.how2.com) and Learn2.com (www.learn2.com). Though lacking Mrs.
Post's saucy style, these sites do touch on the essentials.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, How2.com offered a tutorial on uncorking a champagne
bottle without having champagne shoot across the living room.
Another How2.com lesson advised would-be dinner party givers on how
to set a formal table. The first rule: make it elegant. After the
party is over and the guests have gone, you can turn to Learn2.com
for lessons in the art of thank-you notes. Highlights include
getting out an actual piece of paper, a pen, an envelope and an
all-important stamp. For more experienced note writers, Learn2.com
has a lesson on how to make your own paper. Even Mrs. Post didn't
think of that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
