<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3160 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-BABYZ-GAME-NYT &LR;      12-08 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BABYZ-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL PARENTHOOD, COMPLETE WITH MESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.C. HERZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Stepford babies have arrived. Or rather, Babyz, the latest
virtual pet product from Mindscape, the company that brought us
Catz, Dogz and Creatures. Imagine Cabbage Patch dolls in the
twilight zone with an Internet master plan, and you begin to grasp
the insidious genius of Babyz.
</P>
<P>
   They're sold like Cabbage Patch dolls or puppies at the pound _
each package shows a picture of the virtual bundle of joy inside,
unique in all the world and waiting to be adopted and snuggled and
loved, along with 15 siblings also stored on disc. They're too
scrumptious for words, and they all have serial numbers _ in my
case, 5725-qcqa-aaaD-gbd, a roly-poly, towheaded little girl,
Cookie.
</P>
<P>
   Upon installation, the Babyz software requires a formal adoption
agreement before you can get any further into the program. (``I,
J.C., promise to love and care for Cookie, my newly adopted Babyz.
Every day that I play with Babyz, I will feed and play with Cookie.
I promise to nurture Cookie when sick and clean up after Cookie's
messes. I will be the best caretaker I can be and give Cookie a
good home.'')
</P>
<P>
   You sigh. Click Adopt.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to virtual parenthood: animated nursery toys,
storybooks, gurgles, mashed peas and dirty diapers. Mercifully, the
software does not support the DigiScents virtual odor technology.
But Babyz does support voice recognition _ it even comes with a
microphone so you can sit in front of your computer and repeat
single syllables in a high singsong voice in hopes that your
precious little string of ones and zeroes will learn to talk.
</P>
<P>
   They eventually acquire a vocabulary of 70 words if you're
sufficiently attentive and don't have any hang-ups about cooing,
``Ma, ma-MAH? MA-ma,'' to a monitor for hours on end. A text bar at
the bottom of the screen flashes hints and tips for the clueless
and negligent. ``Don't forget to give your Babyz tickles when
they've been good and to discourage naughty behaviors by telling
your Babyz `no,' using the microphone.''
</P>
<P>
   You can't spank Babyz or do anything abusive if you lose your
temper or get annoyed with the program. But in a world where
toddlers can simply be turned off, who needs corporal punishment?
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there are multiple opportunities to show
Babyz how much you love them. The hint bar has an endless stream of
suggestions, most of which involve baby accessories: clothing,
toys, a scrapbook to be filled with screen shots of candid Babyz
moments. And above all, the constant and insistent reminders to
visit the Babyz Web site, www.babyz.net: ``Talk to other Babyz
owners on the Babyz Talk bulletin board, visit the Babyz Gallery
and download new toyz and clothes. Find tips on how to care for
your Babyz and don't forget to check out the Babyz Linkz pages!''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is my imagination, but these reminders seem to
intensify the longer you go without visiting the Web site until,
like the parent of a feverish baby screaming in the middle of the
night, you relent. (``Yes, OK, OK, OK, I'll visit the Web site.
Shhhh. Shhhh.'')
</P>
<P>
   It is on the Babyz Web site that you realize the full scope and
extent of mind control enabled by this technology (paging Serling
... ).
</P>
<P>
   First of all, there is the adoption center where, after an
extremely coercive registration process, you can peruse a
searchable database of new Babyz to add to your collection. Hair
color, eye color, sex, complexion, you name it _ it's Gattaca in
booties.
</P>
<P>
   In a strange twist of eugenics, the Babyz sought are, like their
prospective parents, overwhelmingly female, and the cast-off orphan
babies are male. If you read the want ads, everyone is looking for
a little girl with green eyes and three pigtails and trying to
unload the little bald boys with glowing descriptions and requests
for good homes.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a system of foster programs, homeless shelters and
orphanages that lets you borrow unwanted Babyz for a while, without
the obligation to adopt. For the luckier Babyz who are chosen and
coddled, there is a whole range of user-run services: hospitals
that nurse sick Babyz back to health, day care centers with
real-world nannyz to tend your Babyz during the day and preschools
that will train your virtual offspring to read and play
instruments.
</P>
<P>
   A gallery allows proud parentz to show off pictures of their
Babyz. That goes on for hundreds of pages, with captions
(``Brittany,'' ``Trixie,'' ``Alexa,'' ``Pandora and Megan,''
``Katie standing,'' ``Katie asking for another block,'' ``Lara,''
``Lara awww my lil angel,'' ``Lara, yes her again AWWW.''). Most of
the pictures are of girls, with the notable exceptions of the
triplets Kyle, Brandon and Dillon, always pictured together, often
in costume. Kyle, Brandon and Dillon dressed as Men in Black. Kyle,
Brandon and Dillon as a pilgrim, a turkey and an Indian brave for
Thanksgiving, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the conspicuous display of toddlers one step further, the
site also features a number of pageants that require contestants to
submit images, along with explanations of why the virtual tot
deserves to win. The Babyz' moms often stress that a pageant
victory would increase their virtual infants' self-esteem. ``I love
my little Elizabeth so much,'' wrote Elizabeth's mother, Caroline,
``I'd be so proud if she'd win. I also know that she'd feel very
happy to know that she's won in something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love her to death,'' said Casey's mom, also named Casey,
``and because I worked so hard on the picture. Plus she is just
learning to walk and if there was a certificate that came with
winning or something, I would put it in a frame on Babyz so Case
can see it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's never too soon to start pushing Babyz _ you know how
difficult it is to get into the right schoolz.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
