<HEADER>
A3162 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-CELESTIAL-JUKEBOX     12-08 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CELESTIAL-JUKEBOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGAL SQUABBLES IN PATH OF INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANNE EISENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the recurring dreams of technology utopians is the idea
of the celestial jukebox. It's a metaphor for the Web of the future
in which individual terminals will have access to great digital
warehouses in the sky packed with petabits of digitally stored CDs,
books, television shows and any other copyrighted information or
entertainment imaginable _ all for micropayments too small to pinch
the wallet.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that consumers of the future will pay a few dollars
or cents _ or even a fraction of a cent _ to watch an episode of
``I Love Lucy,'' listen to an aria by Bryn Terfel or view a missed
Chemistry 101 lecture, deliverable on the spot to home or office.
</P>
<P>
   There are already companies like 1ClickCharge or Qpass that let
people run a chit or bill a credit card for single, low-cost items.
Some experts say companies like these will become part of a
gigantic business that will make it easy for consumers to buy
information or entertainment in small segments.
</P>
<P>
   As technology changes, the celestial jukebox will surely become
possible. In fact, it may be that the stickiest issues will involve
legal, not technical, questions. ``The juggernaut is moving _
there's an internal market logic to the celestial jukebox,'' said
Dr. Paul Goldstein, a law professor at Stanford University and
author of ``Copyright's Highway: From Gutenberg to the Celestial
Jukebox'' (Hill &AMP; Wang, 1994). ``But first there are hurdles to
deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   The hurdles Goldstein and others speak of are the tangled legal
issues of patents, trademarks, trade secrets and copyrights _ known
collectively as intellectual property issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intellectual property used to be a relative backwater, a
fairly quiet territory,'' said Rory Radding, a partner at the
Pennie &AMP; Edmonds law firm in New York. ``But the Internet has made
it red hot, right up there on the radar screen.'' Radding is
chairman of the New York State Bar Association's committee on
intellectual property on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the intellectual property issues associated with the
Internet involve the protection of copyrighted materials, like
music and books. New encryption methods are being developed to
prevent the unauthorized distribution of such material over the
Internet, but one question is how much encryption should be used to
prevent piracy without at the same time stifling a market.
</P>
<P>
   Patent disputes can involve the methods used to conduct business
over the Internet, not just the material being sold. The
business-methods issue arises from a ruling in July 1998 by the
Federal Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals, which ruled that companies
could patent such methods. In that case, the method involved a
computer system for managing portfolios. For 100 years, courts had
held that business methods themselves could not be patented, said
Barry Rein, a partner at Pennie &AMP; Edmonds, but the 1998 ruling ran
counter to that idea.
</P>
<P>
   Many Internet companies promptly started filing patents for
their methods, and some of them then sued other companies for
infringement. Amazon.com, for instance, won a patent for
``one-click ordering,'' an express service that lets customers
place orders without re-entering financial information each time
they buy. Amazon.com subsequently sued Barnesandnoble.com for its
one-click ``express lane'' method, saying it infringed on
Amazon.com's one-click patent.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon won the first round in this dispute: Last week a U.S.
District Court judge in Seattle issued a preliminary injunction
ordering Barnesandnoble.com to stop using the one-click system
because of Amazon's patent claim.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is significant because companies often use similar
software to do business online. ``Any new entrant into commercial
space on the celestial jukebox has to worry about its business plan
being cut off at the knees by a patent infringement lawsuit,''
Goldstein said. ``This issue could effectively bring e-commerce to
a halt.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hagen, a senior analyst at Forrester Research in Cambridge,
Mass., said companies who spend fortunes to set up retail Internet
sites might be given pause by the specter of patent infringement
suits. ``They won't keep on investing unless that money is
protected,'' he said. ``And when you have a patent on such a vague
process, you can completely chill an entire marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people in the field say the law alone is not going to solve
infringement issues. ``Intellectual property owners will look for
alternatives to the legal system,'' said Dr. David Post, a law
professor at Temple University who originated one of the first
Internet law courses. ``If I'm sitting on $100 million in
intellectual property, I'm not going to wait around for the complex
legal world to sort itself out.''
</P>
<P>
   Post predicted that in the recording industry, encryption would
be the solution to intellectual property problems. ``The recording
industry will eventually succeed in promulgating standards that
will allow them to encrypt files so they can't be accessed without
contractual terms and conditions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Allen, an analyst who is the lead author of a Forrester
report called ``The Intellectual Property Mess,'' said encryption
would take the owners of intellectual property rights only so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rights owners can't rely on technology alone to stop
infringement'' if they are going to be able to compete in the
e-commerce market of the future, she said. ``If you don't want to
miss out on $3.2 trillion in commerce worldwide by 2003, you're
going to have to think of other solutions,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Allen draws a parallel with the fight the movie industry had
over VCRs because it thought the devices would hurt its business.
``If this had continued, the industry would have missed out on a
new revenue stream,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Post recognizes the complex problems of intellectual property
rights on the Internet, but he is confident that the age of the
celestial jukebox will arrive anyway. ``I can't sell you access to
my course for a few pennies yet, but the arrow is clearly pointing
in that direction,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
