<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Thursday, Dec. 9. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SYRIA-TALKS (Washington) _ President Clinton said
Wednesday that Israel and Syria had agreed to resume the peace
talks that they broke off in 1996, with a first round of
negotiations to be held in Washington next week. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-BOSNIA (Washington) _ A look at the situation in
Bosnia-Herzegovina as NATO peacekeepers enter their fifth year on
patrol there. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Znamenskoye, Russia) _ Many Chechens like
neither the rebels nor the Russians: a look at one town and how it
fared under Chechen rule and now back under Russian rule. By
Michael R. Gordon. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-GAY-SLAYING (Fort Campbell, Ky.) _ The story of the
harassment and bludgeon slaying of an Army private who feared
expulsion from the service for being gay is emerging here this week
at a court martial that gay rights proponents say lays bare grave
flaws in the military's ``Don't Ask, Don't Tell'' policy. By
Francis X. Clines. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-GAYS-MRSCLINTON _ Hillary Rodham Clinton said Wednesday that
the ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy to allow homosexuals to serve
in the military had been a failure, and she said she would work as
U.S. senator to overturn what was one of the first programs put in
place by President Clinton when he took office in 1993. By Adam
Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   GENE-THERAPY-DEATH (Bethesda, Md.) _ A teen-ager who died after
experimental gene therapy earlier this year succumbed to acute
respiratory distress syndrome, researchers said Wednesday as a U.S.
panel on gene therapy opened a three-day hearing on the death. But
they said they were mystified as to how the treatment killed him.
By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-U.S.-TRIAL (San Juan, Puerto Rico) _ A federal jury on
Wednesday acquitted five Cuban exiles of charges that they
conspired to assassinate Fidel Castro. It was the first time that
such charges had ever been brought in the United States.
(Developing; Summary from wires.) By Tim Golden.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HOMELESS-RULING (NEW YORK) _ After an emergency court hearing
on Wednesday afternoon, one state Supreme Court judge, and possibly
two, are expected to order a temporary halt to the Giuliani
administration's plan to make work and other welfare rules a
condition of shelter for homeless families under threat of seeking
foster care for their children. By Nina Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-TOBACCO (Paris) _ In what could be the opening of a
European front in the war against tobacco, a French court ruled
Wednesday that French cigarette maker Seita was partly to blame for
a smoker's death. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
</TEXT>
