<HEADER>
A3167 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-ZUZU'S-LIFE-TEX     12-08 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZUZU'S-LIFE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILD ACTRESS TREASURED FILM ROLE AS A HIGH SPOT IN LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PERY STEWART 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Karolyn Grimes likes to say that she has been in bed with some
of the biggest stars in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   A juvenile actress in movies during the 1940s, Grimes shared the
screen with John Wayne, Bing Crosby, Cary Grant, David Niven and
other screen notables. Her most memorable portrayal was Zuzu,
daughter of Everyguy hero George Bailey in director Frank Capra's
classic 1946 film, ``It's a Wonderful Life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I played everyone's daughter back then,'' Grimes said. ``It
seems they were always tucking me into bed.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Karolyn's screen father in ``Wonderful Life'' was, of
course, James Stewart. It's hardly a surprise that when Grimes
makes personal appearances to share her memories of the film, the
question she is most often asked is, ``What was it like working
with Jimmy Stewart?''
</P>
<P>
   Grimes' ``Wonderful'' travels brought her to Fort Worth last
week, when a live theater production of ``It's a Wonderful Life''
opened at Stage West. As she visited with first-nighters, the
Stewart query brought an answer that was succinct and appropriate:
``Wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Six-year-old Karolyn looked up to Stewart, figuratively and
literally.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, he was 6-4,'' Grimes said. ``He was very patient.
Among other things, he taught me that it was all right to fluff a
line.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Grimes did not fluff Zuzu's famous line: ``Every
time a bell rings, an angel gets his wings.'' It's probably the
most-quoted sentence of a movie that is part of America's holiday
tradition, thanks largely to Stewart's performance as a
self-doubting man who (with the help of a wingless apprentice
angel) comes to realize that he has enriched many lives.
</P>
<P>
   The film was not always thus embraced, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a success when it first came out,'' Grimes said.
``It lost $500,000 at the get-go.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem, Grimes feels, is that the movie was marketed as a
romantic comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is kind of dark. Capra shot three endings for the
picture. And while the one he wound up using was happy, don't
forget that evil was not punished. Mr. Potter was never exposed for
taking that $8,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Lionel Barrymore, who portrayed Mr. Potter, was reshaped for the
role, Grimes revealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The makeup people remade his head,'' she said. ``They made it
bigger, so he would look more formidable.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Wonderful Life'' radio play currently at Stage West is
co-produced by Texas Wesleyan University and the WARM Place. The
latter, an acronym for What About Remembering Me, is a nonprofit
agency providing grief support to children, their families and
young adults who have lost a loved one.
</P>
<P>
   Grimes was happy to lend her celebrity to such a project,
because she has had her share of grieving and coping.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 14, my mother died. She had been sick for several
years. Then my father got killed in an automobile accident when I
was 15. That was the end of my Hollywood career. I became an
orphan, and the court shipped me to a little town in Missouri
called Osceola. I lived with my father's brother. It wasn't a great
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, Grimes outlived two husbands and a son.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I've been there, done it. I can't really help anybody else,
except to tell them what I did to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   The eventual popularity of ``It's a Wonderful Life'' spawned a
cottage industry for Grimes and her husband, psychologist Chris
Brunell. . Working out of their home in Carnation, Wash., they
publish a slick-looking newsletter, ``The Zuzu News,'' official
organ of the Zuzu Society, which is Web-sited at www.zuzu.net.
</P>
<P>
   Through the magazine and at personal appearances, Grimes markets
``Wonderful Life''-related souvenirs. (Yes, one of them is a bell.
Did you have to ask?)
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDUL/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
