<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3170 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-RAISING-BOYS-TEX     12-08 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAISING-BOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUSHING `MANLY' BEHAVIOR IS A MISTAKE, EXPERTS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Rebecca Edwards visited a local kindergarten class on the
first day of school, she was amazed to see something she would
never have noticed if she weren't looking for it.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, a community educator at the Parenting Center in Fort
Worth, watched parents bring their children into the classroom and
attempt to calm their inevitable separation anxieties. While the
parents of some girls in the classroom lingered to ease their
daughters' transition, the teacher asked the only remaining mother
of a boy to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was more accepting of mothers staying with their
daughters,'' Edwards says.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Edwards could tell, it was a textbook example of what
psychologist William Pollack means when he writes that, unlike
girls, ``Boys are pushed to separate from their mother
prematurely.'' The consequences, the Harvard Medical School
professor said, can be traumatic.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that society treats boys differently than
girls, just as it treats men differently than women. But a growing
chorus of psychologists and sociologists is warning that our
expectations for boys may be harmful to them. Our tendency to steer
them toward traditional male roles, they say, may be curbing their
natural identities or, in extreme cases, propelling them to
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys today are in serious trouble,'' begins Pollack's
oft-cited book ``Real Boys: Rescuing Our Sons From the Myths of
Boyhood.'' Pollack's assertions _ that boys are forced to be too
independent too soon and are shamed into adhering to a strict,
traditional code of manhood _ are shared by numerous experts. Many
are beginning to speak up, and parents are taking note.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards bought ``Real Boys'' after seeing Pollack interviewed on
``The Oprah Winfrey Show.'' Spurred by his message, Edwards offered
the first ``Raising Sons'' class through the Parenting Center in
September, attracting twice as many people as the class on raising
girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are increasingly concerned about the kinds of
messages that we bombard our male children and male adolescents
with,'' says David Lisak, an associate professor of psychology at
the University of Massachusetts-Boston. Cumulatively, he notes,
those messages ``have the effect of instilling in them the sense
that there are certain parts of their humanity that they really
need to disavow.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollack calls it the ``Boy Code'': ``a set of behaviors, rules
of conduct, cultural shibboleths and even a lexicon, that is
inculcated into boys by our society _ from the very beginning of a
boy's life.'' Long before their first day of kindergarten, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the code is based on ``outmoded ideas of
masculinity,'' Pollack writes, including the long-held beliefs that
men should be emotionally stoic and not too sensitive or dependent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys are allowed to be courageous and strong,'' says Edwards,
``but they're not allowed to be fearful, they're not allowed to be
vulnerable, and they're not even allowed to be some good feelings
like gentle and caring.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Dunham has made a concerted effort to shield her sons from
those pressures. Dunham, a Fort Worth mother of two boys, ages 14
and 10, has encouraged them ``to express their feelings more, not
to `Be a man and buck up and tough it out.' I wanted them to be as
comfortable as possible talking about their feelings, because I
think that makes a healthy man.''
</P>
<P>
   Her 14-year-old still tells her everything, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Many people, including parents of boys, argue that ``masculine''
traits are inbred _ that their sons are naturally less inclined to
show emotions or to want to nurture dolls. But numerous gender
experts contend that most of those behaviors are learned and,
because of that, don't reflect boys' true nature.
</P>
<P>
   In a world where men and women are becoming equal partners in
the office and at home, these professionals say, the pressure on
boys to be ``manly'' won't serve them well. In fact, they argue,
it's already causing them trouble, especially in school.
</P>
<P>
   Boys receive lower grades than girls in every subject except
12th-grade physics, they drop out and are kicked out of school more
often, and they make up the overwhelming majority of special
education students, according to researchers. Four times as many
boys as girls commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of boys feel shortchanged,'' says Aaron Kipnis, a
clinical psychologist and author of ``Angry Young Men.'' ``There is
a narrow range of behavior that is celebrated in boys. (Either) you
make a lot of touchdowns, a lot of money, or you make good
grades.''
</P>
<P>
   While girls who don't fit in often turn to one another for
support, psychologists say, boys are more apt to turn inward and
feel marginalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of shame, a lot of sense of not being good
enough, tall enough, strong enough,'' Kipnis adds. ``We have half a
million boys taking steroids in America now ... so there is
something that's happening to the soul of our young men, to their
interior lives, and a lot of that has to do with our cultural
values.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is evidence that boys are feeling more pressure to
live up to stereotyped masculine ideals. Doctors are diagnosing
more eating disorders in male patients, and research suggests that
boys are much more preoccupied with their looks than they used to
be, notes Susan Bordo, a women's studies professor at the
University of Kentucky and author of ``The Male Body.''
</P>
<P>
   When Carol Ray's nearly 8-year-old son couldn't find a pair of
clean jeans one recent morning, Ray, who lives in Fort Worth,
suggested that he wear sweat pants. He refused. ``I look awful in
sweat pants,'' he protested.
</P>
<P>
   That may or may not be a reflection of peer pressure. But Bordo
says the stress boys feel shouldn't be underestimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this generation is facing some elements that we can't
even imagine,'' she says. ``The degree to which very powerful
cultural images have an enormous grip on their psychic lives, the
conflicting messages sent to them ...''
</P>
<P>
   For the younger generation of males, Bordo says, conflict arises
between messages they receive about communicating openly and being
respectful of girls on the one hand _ through programs such as
sexual harassment awareness _ and the fear of being called a
``wimp'' on the other.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist Mark Kiselica agrees, but he cautions against
painting too gloomy a picture. ``Most kids are faring pretty
well,'' says Kiselica, an associate professor at the College of New
Jersey. ``We are not a nation of psychiatric patients or
criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Boys will thrive if we give them the freedom to be themselves
and communicate with them on their level, Kiselica says. Finding a
group of like-minded parents may be just as important.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't parent in a box,'' Edwards says. ``Instead of
thinking only about `what happens in my house,' we need to think
about `what's happening in my community.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
