<HEADER>
A3171 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-HOLIDAY-KIDSBOOKS-TEX     12-08 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-KIDSBOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM HANUKKAH TO CHRISTMAS TO RAMADAN THROUGH TERIFFIC BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SANDY GUERRA-CLINE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some young believers call the holidays Christmas. Others,
Ramadan. Still others, Hanukkah.
</P>
<P>
   For Christians, Muslims and Jews, December is a month rich in
religious traditions. Children's books offer families a chance to
read about their traditions as well as learn about other families
and what they hold most holy.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Muslim community will begin a monthlong fast _
from dawn to dusk each day _ called Ramadan, or Ramadhan. Here are
two children's books that highlight the importance of a child's
first fast. (Generally, the Islamic faith requires only people in
their teens and older to participate, but children are encouraged
to fast as much as they are able during the holiday.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Zaki's Ramadhan Fast'' by Ann P. El-Moslimany is a wonderful
introduction to the Islamic tradition for non-Muslim children in
grades K-3. The author, who is a teacher and grandmother, takes a
loving approach to a boy's first attempt at fasting. Zaki eats
breakfast with his family before sunrise, then goes back to bed.
When he wakes, the lingering smell of muffins makes his stomach
rumble. Will Zaki keep his fast?
</P>
<P>
   ``First Fast'' by Uthman Hutchinson is an ``easy reader'' for
children in grades 1 and 2. Jamaal is only 6, but he is determined
to fast like his older brother and sister. Fasting makes him
sleepy, and as he drifts in and out of the day, his elders lovingly
keep him moving in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   These paperback books, and a ``My Ramadhan Fun Pack'' filled
with activities and crafts, are available from Astrolabe Pictures,
(800) 392-7876, or at www.astrolabepictures.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish celebration of Hanukkah, an annual remembrance of
ancient miracles _ the triumph of the Maccabees and the light that
burned for eight days on a single day's supply of oil _ began at
sundown Dec. 3. In Jewish homes, each night another candle in the
family menorah is lighted, until all eight candles burn bright. Two
books explain the festival and traditions in very different ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hershel and the Hanukkah Goblins'' by Eric Kimmel (Holiday
House, $6.95 paperback) A band of fearsome goblins stops a village
from celebrating Hanukkah until a quick-witted and brave traveler
comes along. This Caldecott Honor Book owes as much of its power to
Trina Schart Hyman's dark illustrations as it does to Kimmel's
clever storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hanukkah! A Three-Dimensional Celebration'' by Sara Freedland
(Candlewick Press, $18.99 hardback) Hanukkah traditions are
explained in detail in this gorgeous pop-up book that is more
family keepsake than simple storybook. It includes songs, a recipe
for latkes (potato pancakes) and a paper dreidl game that you
assemble yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Any of an assortment of Christmas stories would make fine
additions to a holiday bookshelf. The are books with spiritual
threads that bind families close with repeated readings year after
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Is the Star'' by Joyce Dunbar (Voyager Books, $6
paperback) A beautiful retelling of the story of the Nativity that
one of my children realized is told in the gentle singsong manner
of ``The House That Jack Built.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Angel'' by Geraldine McCaughrean (Barnes &AMP; Noble Books,
$4.98 hardback) The charming story of Micah the shepherd boy and a
little angel, misfits both, and the gifts they receive from the
baby king.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Black Snowman'' by Phil Mendez (Scholastic, $5.99
paperback) This is the book my children asked for again and again.
Jacob Miller can't see the spirit of Christmas for the poverty
around him. A scrap of kente cloth provides the magic ... but will
Jacob believe in time to save his little brother Peewee?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legend of the Candy Cane'' by Lori Walburg (Zondervan
Publishing, $14.99 hardback) A delightful tale of a frontier town,
a mysterious stranger and the religious history behind the
Christmas candy.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kwanzaa is a cultural _ and not religious _ celebration
of the season, it is nonetheless a spiritual one.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Kwanzaa Celebration'' by Nancy Williams (Little Simon,
$12.95) is a bright pop-up book for the littlest readers. It
explains the seven principles _ and seven days _ of the
African-American holiday, which begins Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
