<HEADER>
A3172 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-NEW-FORMAT-AUDIO-     12-08 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-NEW-FORMAT-AUDIO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON NEW DVD FORMATS, THE SOUND OF GOOD THINGS TO COME 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are confusing times for anyone stepping into the world of
consumer electronics. The established order of things is being
shaken on every front. There is MP3, HDTV, digital cable and
satellite television.
</P>
<P>
   And now consumers can no longer take for granted even that
reliable bulwark of the audio world, the compact disc player. Two
new challengers are on the market, and all of the world's major
equipment manufacturers and record publishers are pushing to phase
out the compact disc and replace it with Super Audio CD or
DVD-Audio.
</P>
<P>
   Super Audio CD is a format backed by Sony and Philips, while
every other manufacturer is supporting DVD-Audio. Both new formats
use as a base a DVD, a disc that can hold seven times as much
information as a CD. With that extra capacity, both formats promise
higher-quality audio as well as multichannel sound and the
possibility of offering video clips, liner notes and other
information along with the music. But they record and store the
data in different formats, and Sony argues that its format gives
Super Audio CDs superior sound quality. DVD-Audio proponents say
their product can sound just as good.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's first Super Audio CD players are in the stores right now.
The flagship product has a price of $5,000. The company is also
selling a scaled-down model that costs $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   Panasonic had expected to be the first major company to sell a
DVD-Audio player; the company had planned to send its first model
to stores late this month. But on Dec. 1, Panasonic announced that
the player would be delayed for about six months so the company
could incorporate a new copy-protection system into it.
</P>
<P>
   When some European hackers let it be known in October that they
had broken the copy-protection scheme used on DVD videodiscs, the
news rattled the record industry, prompting Panasonic's delay. At
least one other company, Pioneer, said it intended to proceed with
plans to begin selling DVD-Audio players in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   The Panasonic player is to cost $1,200 and will be marketed
under the Technics brand. Another model will be sold under the
Panasonic brand and will cost $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Sony and Panasonic products are both being heavily promoted,
primarily in magazine advertisements, and other companies will be
entering the market very soon. But right away, consumers should
know two things:
</P>
<P>
   First, these new products  &UR; do &LR;  sound quite a bit better than CD
players.
</P>
<P>
   And second, no one needs to rush out to buy one.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in the industry agrees that the transition will take
many years. CD players and CDs will be manufactured for quite a
long time. And even when the CD player is eventually supplanted by
one or both of these new formats, the formats that win out will
still play CDs. So none of the recordings you buy today will be
made obsolete, unlike the situation when the industry moved from
vinyl records to compact discs in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   So for the moment, these formats are most likely to appeal only
to those who must have the latest in audio equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, buyers of Sony's Super Audio CD player can choose
from among roughly 40 Super Audio CDs, and that number is expected
to double in the next two or three months. Only a handful of
DVD-Audio discs from specialty manufacturers are on the market now,
though a great number of titles from the major record labels should
reach the stores early next year.
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, a Super Audio CD player will not play
DVD-Audio or DVD videodiscs, while a DVD-Audio player will play DVD
video discs but not Super Audio CDs.
</P>
<P>
   I reviewed both products and found, sure enough, that both offer
a notable leap forward in sound quality. But they are not equal.
And some features that will be available on later-generation
players are not available on these.
</P>
<P>
   Sony was first to deliver a Super Audio CD player to be reviewed
for this article. Company executives see high-end audiophiles as
the most likely customers, so they are quite concerned about
reviews. As a result, Sony sent three people to install the player.
And, apparently not satisfied with my speakers, they brought along
a pair of their own that cost $16,000. The team spent about three
hours setting everything up.
</P>
<P>
   After the Sony people had left, I listened at first with their
model SS-M9ED speakers, then with my own, Infinity Composition
Preludes. In both cases, the difference between conventional CDs
and Super Audio CDs was like the difference between sparkling cider
and Piper Heidseck champagne. Once you hear a Super Audio CD, you
will never want to go back. The sound was richer and warmer. It
seemed so much more real, as if a veil had been lifted, that it
brought spontaneous smiles to several listeners' faces. One
longstanding complaint about CDs is that they add a harsh edge to
strings, voices, piano. With the new format, that harsh edge was
gone.
</P>
<P>
   Sony lent me two dozen discs, including a few recordings that
were also available on CD. Playing both simultaneously, and
switching back and forth between the two, the CD sounded muddy,
even primitive. Everyone who listened to this player over several
weeks, even those with just a casual interest in audio, agreed:
This new format is a winner.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, Panasonic delivered the first DVD-Audio
player, a preproduction model of the Technics player. It arrived
via United Parcel Service, unaccompanied by a technical team.
</P>
<P>
   Classic Records, a small label in Los Angeles that has been
producing DVD-Audio discs for more than a year, provided eight of
them, along with several CD versions of the same recordings. But
since I had no common recordings in both Super Audio CD and
DVD-Audio format, I was unable to do a direct comparison. In the
end, however, it wasn't really necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, there was a clear difference, though it was much
subtler. Some casual listeners could not hear it. With DVD-Audio,
the music sounded warmer, less constrained. But it still held a bit
of a harsh edge on some instruments and did not offer the absolute
clarity and realism that came through on Super Audio CDs.
</P>
<P>
   DVD-Audio discs will come in several flavors, some offering
higher resolution than others. And the highest-resolution discs are
not yet being made. They may compete more effectively with Super
Audio CDs.
</P>
<P>
   For now the question consumers might ask is whether this is the
right time to buy one of these new formats. Certainly, for the
die-hard early adopter who wants the best new thing right away,
Sony's new product _ and perhaps the DVD-Audio player, if the
higher-resolution discs do in fact sound better _ perform exactly
as advertised.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are several good reasons to wait. For one, the Sony
player offers only stereo. Later versions will offer the choice of
stereo or multichannel audio, which is the clear direction the
music industry is taking.
</P>
<P>
   The Panasonic player is already multichannel. It can play stereo
discs or those with six channels of surround sound. But to play
multichannel music, a consumer must have a receiver or
pre-amplifier that has a six-channel input _ six separate plugs.
Only a few new receivers offer that option.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, one digital connection will carry all six channels,
as it does now on DVD video players. (Once the copy-protection
problem has been resolved, a digital output will be feasible.
Panasonic has not said whether the players to be sold in six months
will offer that, but six months is not generally enough time for a
manufacturer to modify a major product.)
</P>
<P>
   What's more, right now consumers must choose between Super Audio
CD and DVD-Audio. But two manufacturers, Philips and Pioneer, have
already announced plans to begin selling players next year that
will play both formats. Pioneer's player will be on sale in the
spring for $4,000. Others later in the year are certain to be less
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   These so-called universal decks will offer a choice of
two-channel or multichannel audio. By then, they should be able to
provide one-jack digital outputs that will work with most modern
receivers and pre-amplifiers. And they will play everything: Super
Audio CD's, DVD-Audio discs, DVD-videodiscs and CDs. By then a much
larger library of music in both formats will be in the stores.
</P>
<P>
   So the greater part of wisdom seems to argue for waiting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
