<HEADER>
A3180 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-PHONE-DESIGNERS-A     12-08 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PHONE-DESIGNERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM PHONE TO FASHION, NOKIA STYLE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Finland, France)   (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frank Nuovo, chief designer at Nokia, sits in his spacious
office in Calabasas, Calif., surrounded by several generations of
cell phones he has had a hand in creating, and ponders the
serendipitous turns in his career that led to a full-time fixation
on mobile communications.
</P>
<P>
   The first came one day just before Christmas more than a decade
ago, when Nuovo was a young industrial designer at Designworks/USA,
a consulting firm near Los Angeles. A call came from an executive
at nearby Nokia who was looking for design help with a new line of
mobile phones. Nuovo happened to be the only one in the office, so
he took the call.
</P>
<P>
   Now Nuovo, who is 38, is credited with helping Nokia (pronounced
NO-kee-ah) do for cell phones what Swatch did for watches. His idea
_ turning cell phones into fashion statements _ has been hugely
successful. This year, said Brian Modoff, an analyst with Deutsche
Banc Alex Brown, almost one in every three phones sold worldwide
was made by Nokia, which has blended its fashionable image with a
reputation for making sturdy phones that are easy to use.
</P>
<P>
   The most ubiquitous of Nuovo's products are the 5100 and 6100
Series phones. One secret of the phones' success is their ability
to change thks. An owner can swap faceplates to make a phone
match a shade of nail polish. It is not unusual for someone to buy
a new Nokia phone along with four or five different covers. Nuovo,
himself a fashion hound, considers a cell phone to be as visible an
accessory as his Milus wristwatch.
</P>
<P>
   The newest rage is the 8210, the smallest digital phone on the
market in Europe. It was introduced in October in Paris, not at a
consumer electronics conference but at a fashion show for the
designer Kenzo.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nokia is based in Helsinki, Finland, and has nine major
offices around the world with design components, the company's
principal design center is the one tucked into a bland office park
in Calabasas, about an hour northwest of downtown Los Angeles. That
fact has everything to do with Nuovo, a native Californian who
preferred not to uproot his family to move to Finland when he went
to work for Nokia full time in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the center, which has no sign outside, is behind locked
doors, with the exception of a modest reception area, a conference
room and Nuovo's office. Nuovo said the exact number of designers
who work with him in Calabasas was a secret but that it was
``substantial.''
</P>
<P>
   Scattered about Nuovo's office are objects whose design he
admires: several scale models of luxury cars, a soap dish of
sculpted aluminum, and interesting springs, bottle openers and
spheres.
</P>
<P>
   Most prominent is a display of 75 or so expensive and unusual
pens, all of them miniature sculptures made of aluminum, titanium,
wood or cork, which Nuovo picked up in his travels through Europe
and Asia. Mobile phones, Nuovo said, are not far removed from what
he finds beautiful in pens. Pens are the ultimate handheld device.
They are intuitively easy to use, and everyone has a different
preference for shape, color and feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want it to be comfortable and in a sense, you want it to
tickle the right nerve,'' he said. ``It all adds up to an emotional
and physical attachment to the device. If you look at our phones,
you'll see a lot of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nuovo likens the design process to playing in a band. Designing
a product, he said, requires consistent communication among the
mechanical and electrical engineers, the manufacturing team and
other designers. ``You're only as good as the worst guy in the
band,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nuovo's boss, Yrjo Neuvo, Nokia's senior vice president for
product creation, said one of Nuovo's greatest talents _ unusual
for an artist _ was his ability to guide teams of designers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gives direction, and gives the final touch, but he's also
guiding the whole team,'' Neuvo said.
</P>
<P>
   Nuovo's analogy to music was no accident. By age 11, Nuovo, who
bears a striking resemblance to both Al Pacino and Dustin Hoffman
(he has been mistaken for Hoffman on the streets of Beverly Hills
and Pacino in a bar in Helsinki), was a professional drummer. While
growing up in Monterey, Calif., he played jazz and jazz fusion in
trios and big bands. ``My parents had to drive me to the gigs,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But art always beckoned. In 1983 he enrolled at the Art Center
College of Design in Pasadena, which is famous for turning out some
of the world's most successful industrial designers.
</P>
<P>
   While still a student, Nuovo caught the eye of Chuck Pelly,
chief executive of Designworks/USA, now a subsidiary of BMW, so
Pelly put him to work designing patio furniture and automobile
interiors. ``We watch key students all around the world,'' Pelly
said. ``Every few years you notice one that has a combination of
high learning skills, a natural business mind and is a very good
designer. He was clearly destined to grow like crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the lucky phone call from Nokia, Nuovo has had timing
work for him in other ways. His rise at Nokia, once a manufacturing
conglomerate known for rubber boots and toilet paper, coincided
with the company's gradual decision to focus almost exclusively on
cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after that move, the analog network in Europe was largely
displaced by a digital system called GSM. Nokia says it was the
first to market a GSM phone, designed by Nuovo, in 1992. When the
United States started shifting to digital in the late 1990s, Nokia
was ready with its 2100 Series, among the best-selling digital
phones at the time. While Motorola's light, pocketable cell phones
had been popular through the mid-1990s, the company was caught
short without a digital product.
</P>
<P>
   With the introduction of two analog phones with color faceplates
in the early 1990s, Nuovo and others at Nokia began presenting
phones as fashion accessories. In 1997 came the 5100 and 6100
digital phones. Nuovo was convinced that they would be a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, those phones look quite ordinary. They are what
designers call a monoblock form, as opposed to a flip phone like
the StarTac. They are small, light and sturdy. ``There are no
complex moving parts,'' Nuovo said, ``and you feel right away that
this is a solid product and very comfortable in the hand. We were
after a very robust, simple form.'' Another important ingredient,
he said, has been the phone's large screen, which lent itself
immediately to data services, like text messaging and caller ID.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the question of style. Nuovo attributes much of the
success of the 5100 series to the phone's interchangeable
faceplates (the 5100 faceplates pop off; those for the 6100 require
a screwdriver), something he and others at Nokia championed for
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole concept was about personalization,'' he said.
``People being able to make it their own.''
</P>
<P>
   The same holds for the relatively new 8860, a shiny conversation
piece of a phone that could be mistaken for a cigarette lighter.
Nuovo got the inspiration for the phone's chrome exterior from
other high-end accessories, like a chrome flask, a sterling silver
address book not much thicker than a cassette tape, a snuffbox, a
cigarette case, a woman's compact and a Zippo ashtray he found in
Japan. In Europe, the 8860 is nicknamed the Zippo phone.
</P>
<P>
   Nuovo is unapologetic about the oily fingerprints that so easily
ruin the gleam of the 8860 ($799). In fact, he said, it has
engendered a new form of ``completely acceptable'' social behavior.
He demonstrated by rubbing his heavily smudged phone on his
sternum, his silk Jhane Barnes shirt serving as a buffing cloth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're seeing a lot of people doing this,'' he said, then held
up the polished phone. ``See? Just like new.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
