<HEADER>
A3184 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-XMASCARD-ETIQUETTE-TE     12-08 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XMASCARD-ETIQUETTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW, WHEN, WHY AND TO WHOM YOU SHOULD SEND HOLIDAY CARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALYSON WARD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This month, I enter the Real World. I've been making this
transition since I graduated from college in the spring, slowly
starting to participate in activities reserved for Real People who
have Jobs and Established Lives. You know: going to bed at night,
eating meals beyond the microwavable, things like that.
</P>
<P>
   But in December, the metamorphosis becomes complete: In
December, Real People send holiday cards to their Real People
friends. And because this is my first December in years that's free
of the sleepy haze brought on by research papers and final exams, I
have no excuse. The Real People I know are expecting cards. And I'd
better send them.
</P>
<P>
   The first steps were easy. I chose my cards and updated the
address list. But then confusion set in. I know there are countless
ways to offend in this annual card exchange. An ill-timed or
ill-worded holiday card is an annoyance. I don't want to make my
Real World debut as an annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   So I consulted the experts. I called Hilka Klinkenberg,
etiquette expert, author, founder and owner of Etiquette
International, a business etiquette firm based in New York City.
Klinkenberg answered my questions. All of them. Politely. She
clearly did not consider me an annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   As an additional caution, I turned to Miss Manners herself,
Judith Martin. Her newest book, ``Miss Manners' Guide to Domestic
Tranquility,'' devotes an entire section to this complicated topic.
</P>
<P>
   I researched, I took notes; in my quest to find etiquette
truths, I entered a Real World December haze. Here's what I found.
</P>
<P>
   TIMING
</P>
<P>
   Here's what I thought: I've received cards as late as the middle
of January. What's a month or two? If I get busy this month, I'll
just address them while the Super Bowl's on. It's the thought that
counts, right?
</P>
<P>
   Wrong, Klinkenberg says. ``If the greetings get there after the
event, it's too late.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if you're late, you offend. You become an
annoyance. But there's an option. If your timing is off,
Klinkenberg suggests sending New Year's cards instead. ``You can
send those pretty well through January,'' she says. I guess saving
it all as halftime entertainment during the big game is pretty much
out of the picture then.
</P>
<P>
   THE PERSONAL TOUCH
</P>
<P>
   Here's what I thought: To be more efficient, I'll get my name
stamped onto the cards. I won't have to sign each and every card,
and my name will undoubtedly be more legible.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong again, Klinkenberg says. The stamped card is quite
impersonal _ and if you send an impersonal card, you defeat the
purpose of sending a card at all.
</P>
<P>
   Klinkenberg says her edict applies to the envelope, too.
Adhesive labels are another no-no. Yes, they're easier to read, but
Klinkenberg insists that you shouldn't use mailing labels under any
circumstances _ ``It looks like you're sending out a mass
mailing,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   THE DREADED NEWSLETTER
</P>
<P>
   Again, my thoughts: The newsletter rocks. I'll write a little
something about my accomplishments this year (going to bed at
night, eating those not-from-the microwave meals and all) and copy
it at the nearest copy center. Many families include the kids' SAT
scores in their mass-produced letters, but because I don't have
kids, I'll have to report my own score. And because I don't have
pets, perhaps I can improvise with an update on the pigeons that
keep eating the plants on my patio. People love that stuff, right?
</P>
<P>
   Welll, actually, some of them do. Martin and Klinkenberg both
say holiday news updates aren't inherently evil. Done correctly,
they're welcomed. It's the smug and rambling list of family
accomplishments that offends and annoys.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Manners reminds readers to consider the recipient's level
of interest. Some people just like to know they are remembered, she
says, so a brief greeting is more appropriate. Others really want
to hear family news, but be careful _ ``It is unlikely ... that
anyone's interests extend to three pages of single-spaced purple
mimeographing,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Klinkenberg says newsletters aren't the best option.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I really had my druthers, I'd have people write a personal
letter,'' she says. ``It really becomes special.''
</P>
<P>
   But she says she understands time constraints. And it doesn't
take too much time or effort to personalize a newsletter,
Klinkenberg says _ just add a personal note at the letter's
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personalize that first paragraph,'' she advises. ``Suddenly,
it makes the letter special.''
</P>
<P>
   But even this has its pitfalls. Klinkenberg said she recently
received an unfortunate version of the personalized newsletter. An
economical friend sent out letters that were indeed personalized _
but for five people at a time. That's right, the first five
paragraphs were ``individual'' greetings to five different people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know who the other people were,'' Klinkenberg says,
but she had to read through the writer's personal messages to them.
``It makes you feel like you're spying on someone else's life.''
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   A holiday greeting is a holiday greeting, methinks. So everyone
I know is going to receive a religious card of my choosing, whether
they observe Christmas, Hanukkah, Kwanzaa or the end of TV sweeps.
It's all the same thing, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the right way to think, the experts say _ although
lots of people do it. If you want to send a religious card, but
you're not sure if the recipient shares the same beliefs, err on
the side of sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   If you're in doubt, don't send religious cards, Klinkenberg
says. And be careful, because even if a card isn't overtly
religious, it can still scream out your religious take on the
holidays. You're better off with a generic type of card, she says _
a winter scene or a peace dove. Snow and birds never offended
anyone. That we know of.
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL ETIQUETTE
</P>
<P>
   I'm a Net-savvy girl. My friends will receive e-mail containing
a URL, which they can click on to find a personal greeting complete
with dancing Santas and cheesy music. Maybe this is a good
alternative, I begin to think.
</P>
<P>
   In this world of technophiles, could e-mailed holiday greetings
possibly be rude? Well, they're not as rude as they are
ineffective, according to Klinkenberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your greeting will be forgotten as soon as it arrives,'' she
says. ``The moment someone clicks out of their e-mail, the greeting
is forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   An e-mail card will only affect the visual sense, she says,
while a real card affects its recipient on several levels.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE THE LIST ENDS
</P>
<P>
   I realize, of course, that the holiday card relationships I
establish this year are likely to continue for the rest of my life.
When I'm 80, I'll still be getting cards that say ``Happy Holidays
from Traci and David!'' or ``Merry Christmas from Jenni and Mark!''
And I, of course, will be obligated to reciprocate, wishing I could
just remember how or when I knew them.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, say Klinkenberg and Martin. You shouldn't have to send
cards to people you no longer know or keep in touch with, and they
shouldn't have to send cards to you. It's a meaningless exchange.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you gracefully drop someone from your list? ``You
don't send them a card,'' Klinkenberg says.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
