<HEADER>
A3201 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     12-08 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV26-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., DEC. 26, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I am putting up a new fence by installing wood posts set in a
concrete footing.
</P>
<P>
   I did this years ago in my old house but found that after a
number of years some of the posts had loosened slightly and become
a little wobbly _ apparently because the wood had shrunk and was no
longer securely anchored inside the concrete.
</P>
<P>
   How can I anchor my new fence posts _ so they won't work loose
again _ without doing a lot of extra work?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are a number of ways to reinforce and steady fence
posts that are set into a concrete footing, but one of the simplest
and least expensive methods is the one shown here.
</P>
<P>
   Before inserting the posts in their holes, drive a series of
heavy galvanized nails (4- to 6-inch size) with large heads about
half way into the underground portion of the wood post so that they
stick out on all sides as indicated.
</P>
<P>
   After inserting each post into its hole, and while holding the
post upright, pour the concrete into the hole. The embedded nails
will provide a firm gripping surface for the concrete even if the
wood shrinks slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The house we bought several years ago has a problem that is
quite annoying. Many of the wood floors seem to creak or squeak
when walked upon, upstairs as well as downstairs.
</P>
<P>
   I am not handy, nor am I physically able to do much work around
the house, so I want to call in a carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   Do you think he will be able to fix this without major
construction and expense?
</P>
<P>
   A: Any experienced carpenter should be able to pinpoint the
source of the problem, but it is impossible to say how much work or
expense will be required to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   Most squeaking is caused by loose floor boards or subflooring
that has not been nailed or screwed down properly, but it's also
possible that the creaking is caused by other structural problems,
such as floor boards that have swelled or buckled.
</P>
<P>
   Try to get an estimate from your carpenter before you agree to
the job.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have a ceiling lighting fixture that we would like to
replace with a combination ceiling fan-and-light fixture.
</P>
<P>
   Is this something I can do myself?
</P>
<P>
   A: A lot depends on the type of ceiling outlet box that is
already installed for your existing ceiling light.
</P>
<P>
   A fan weighs considerably more than a simple lighting fixture,
so the ceiling box must be properly braced and mounted to support
this weight.
</P>
<P>
   If you cannot do this yourself (directions are supplied by most
dealers and manufacturers) then you may find it advisable to call
in a professional electrician to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   The electrician may also be needed if you are not able to do the
necessary wiring _ but this will depend on your ability to follow
the directions supplied with all such units.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My apartment is in a 70-year-old building that has walls of
plaster.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently these walls were all covered with canvas some years
ago and in some places this canvas has started to pull away from
the wall along the seams.
</P>
<P>
   Should I cut away and peel these loose areas off, or is it
advisable to simply try and paste these sections back with some
kind of adhesive?
</P>
<P>
   A: Lining old plaster walls with canvas was a common practice
years ago when the plaster had many cracks or loose areas.
</P>
<P>
   The canvas reinforced the plaster and covered up the cracks to
create a smooth new surface that could be painted or papered.
</P>
<P>
   I would, therefore, not advise peeling any of this canvas off.
</P>
<P>
   Instead paste the loosened sections back down with a vinyl
adhesive that is sold for this purpose in all paint stores.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``SECURING WOOD POSTS IN CONCRETE'' goes
with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Heavy nails driven half way into base of wood post on
all sides will help prevent future loosening.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
