<SLUG> BC-CIR-PHOTO-EDIT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIGHTENING OLD SNAPSHOTS WITH PHOTOGENETICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (Eds: A circuits article last Thursday that reviewed photo editing
programs inaccurately described the capabilities of one program,
Photogenetics, because an incomplete version of the software was
provided by the company, the Q-Research Corp. This is a review of
the full program. )
 (af)  
 By ROY FURCHGOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photogenetics is a highly rudimentary tool for altering
photographs. It may appeal to people who do not want to spend time
learning how to use more sophisticated programs like Photoshop LE
from Adobe or Corel Photopaint. Activating the program, which
retails for $39.95, requires calling up a registration form and
entering a code.
</P>
<P>
   The program's chief feature is a system that improves the color
of faded photographs. It works by offering two views of a photo,
side-by-side, then applying a slight color change to one of them.
The user then rates the improvement over the other photo on a
sliding scale from ``no improvement'' to ``much better.'' After
four comparisons, it institutes a change in the first photo, and
the process continues until the viewer is satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   The promotional materials says it can fix photos in two minutes,
but with some badly aged pictures, it took far more time _ about 60
tries worth over at least 10 minutes. And although the result was
much improved over the initial photo, a side-by-side comparison
with the same photograph modified using other software showed that
Photogenetics had produced less improvement in more time.
</P>
<P>
   The cropping feature worked as well as those of other programs,
but the red eye feature did not. It offers a virtual pencil which
is used to draw over the orange glow of red eye. The best that
could be managed, however, was a slight grey-green tinting of the
orange glow.
</P>
<P>
   The program did not offer any way to cut and paste images to
create photo collages, as other programs do. Nor did it offer tools
to repair cracks and spots in photos. The program also could not
open all kinds of image files, rejecting those in TIFF format.
</P>
<P>
   And it was difficult to determine what some features were. There
was no feature labeled ``convert to black and white,'' but clicking
on ``gray 2 blue-filter'' appeared to accomplish the task.
</P>
<P>
   There were other features that produced 1960s-style pop art
images by radically altering the colors of a photograph, and
another that produced a negative image. There was also a nice
``dewarp'' feature that compensates for the distortion a wide angle
lens adds to a photo.
</P>
<P>
   The company also offers more sophisticated versions of its color
modification program that will modify a single color in a
photograph, for an additional $29.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
