u a BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT     12-08 0393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Dec. 9, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A strong jet stream flow from the Pacific will continue to
direct low pressure systems across the nation while keeping Arctic
air locked in northern Canada. One low pressure zone will promote
inclement weather from the southern Plains to the Ohio Valley on
Thursday while a new disturbance sweeps into the West Coast states.
</P>
<P>
   Rain will fall near the track of a low pressure center as it
moves from northern Texas early Thursday to the central Mississippi
Valley on Thursday night. A narrow band of snow will occur at the
fringe of the rain area from the northern panhandle of Texas to
central Kansas. The precipitation will end quickly in northern
Texas and western Oklahoma as drier air arrives from the west.
</P>
<P>
   Showers will occur in the humid air from eastern parts of Texas
and Oklahoma to the southern Mississippi Valley. A band of potent
thunderstorms will develop Thursday afternoon as a vigorous jet
stream disturbance moves from the eastern Red River Valley into
Arkansas. Shifting winds will impart rotation to some of the
thunderstorms, which may spawn a few tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine will be plentiful along the the East Coast as strong
high pressure moves offshore. Some high clouds will dim the sun at
times over the Northeast, but, temperatures will be far above the
seasonal average.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, a cold front will produce rain from northern
California to the Pacific Northwest. Snow will fall in the Cascades
and Sierra.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: PERENNIAL STORMS
</P>
<P>
   A bout with high winds accompanied by rain and snow in coastal
southeastern Alaska on Wednesday signaled an active phase in the
life of one of this hemisphere's perennial storms. The Aleutian
low, named for its proximity to the Alaskan archipelago, appears on
weather maps for most of the year. Gales that develop off of the
east coast of Asia are drawn toward the large temperature contrasts
in the Aleutians that result as polar winds meet the warmer waters
of the Pacific. In the Atlantic, surges of frigid air from
Greenland provide energy for a similar atmospheric whirlpool, the
Icelandic low.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
