A3221 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-CHRISTMAS-TREES-O     12-08 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CHRISTMAS-TREES-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMAS TREES (NOT FOR DOWNLOADING) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If I am a snob about Christmas trees, blame my mother. When I
was small, she would march through the tree lot, suspiciously
searching for crooked trunks, missing branches and needle loss. In
her quest to acquire the biggest, fullest, freshest Scotch pine,
she was not above examining candidates already reserved for other
customers.
</P>
<P>
   One year she fell in love with a particularly graceful specimen
slated for the nuns at a nearby convent. She bribed the lot owner
$10 to snip off the ``reserved'' tag.
</P>
<P>
   All those trees were competing against a memory: the Christmas
tree of 1945, when my mother was 4 years old. The war had ended,
but tree lights were still scarce, at least in the secluded hills
and hollows of eastern Kentucky, where she grew up.
</P>
<P>
   So my grandfather, a mechanic, brought home taillights,
headlights and reflector lamps from the shop and attached them to
the branches. The next morning a new doll sat beneath, bathed in an
eerie red and orange glow. ``Prettiest tree we ever had,'' she
insists.
</P>
<P>
   And so, because I am my mother's daughter, I believe a proper
Christmas tree is six and a half feet tall and too bushy to fit
anywhere except right in front of the big picture window. It is
lighted by strings of old-fashioned, oversize colored bulbs that
give off an eerie glow (probably because half their paint has been
scratched off over the years). Not to be picky, but the foil angel
suspended in a glass ball should hang 6 inches above the miniature
creche in a beaded eggshell.
</P>
<P>
   You can imagine, then, that I was pretty nervous about buying a
Christmas tree over the Internet. First I telephoned four purveyors
of online trees _ www.xmas-trees.com, www.freshchristmastrees.com,
www.echristmastrees.com and
www.evermontproducts.com/eVermontChristmastrees/index.html _ to
grill, er, ask a few questions about how they could possibly
shoulder the responsibility of choosing the right tree, much less
pack and ship such a fragile item to my house within three to five
business days via United Parcel Service.
</P>
<P>
   All four assured me they would handpick only the finest tree,
painstakingly pack it in a long cardboard box and guarantee a
replacement if I was not satisfied. I could order ahead and specify
a delivery date, or, if I procrastinated, I could pay extra for
speedier delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle Cormier, who operates VermontProducts.com, vouched for the
packing process. ``I had one in a box for five days,'' she said.
``It looked like a cube at first. Within an hour, it regained its
shape.''
</P>
<P>
   To prove her point, Ms. Cormier mailed a 6-and-a-half-foot
balsam fir to me. It arrived within three days and, yes, regained
its shape within three hours. The only problem was that it was a
fir.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I know some people want a fir, and all four online tree
sellers offer them in heights from 3 feet to 7 feet and at prices
from $59.95 to $107.95 including shipping. And I don't even mind
that some people like a fir, even if Scotch pines _ my family's
choice _ are so obviously more beautiful and festive.
</P>
<P>
   Why, there even used to be a fir family on my block. Of course,
this family also believed in ``theme'' tree decorations. One year,
the decorations consisted of clumps of purple balls that looked
like gigantic bunches of fever-dream grapes.
</P>
<P>
   To get a Scotch pine, I had to narrow my choice to
Xmas-trees.com, a Web site operated by Guy Frederick, who grows
trees on a farm near Cadillac, Mich., that once belonged to his
grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   To maintain freshness, Frederick recommended unpacking the tree
right away, sawing one-half inch off the bottom of the trunk and
sticking it into water. ``You don't want problems with needle
retention,'' he warned. As if I could forget the year my father
burned out the motor on the vacuum cleaner while trying to suck
unretained needles out of the trunk of the car.
</P>
<P>
   I ordered, specifying a height of five and a half feet to six
and a half feet, which costs $50, including shipping.
</P>
<P>
   I requested that the tree be delivered on Dec. 3. That
afternoon, my daughters sat in the big picture window, waiting for
the UPS truck and bickering over whose year it was to hang the
carved wooden camel with the jeweled saddle.
</P>
<P>
   By suppertime, they gave up. But then, right after we lighted
the Hanukkah candles (yes, we celebrate both), the tree arrived.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like a cube. But by the next morning, the tree had
opened into a beautiful cone shape. It had, however, one problem.
It was not bushy. It was so slender and elegant that it would have
looked better in designer clothing than in the suddenly ridiculous
old-fashioned lights.
</P>
<P>
   I phoned Frederick, who said I should have noted my bushiness
preference on the order form's Comments section. ``People specify
all kinds of things _ down to the inch _ and we stand there in the
barn holding the order form while we pick one out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Next, I phoned my mother. After ascertaining that the tree had a
strong, high branch on which to hang the glitter-frosted Mad Hatter
ornament, she suggested _ somewhat to my horror _ that I change the
lights.
</P>
<P>
   A thinner tree could work if I put aside the traditional
fat-bulb lights with a string of tiny white lights, which my mother
always called ``Italian lights'' because she first saw them in a
spaghetti restaurant in the 1960s. ``Substitute Italians for
standards,'' she told me.
</P>
<P>
   The difference was remarkable. ``Prettiest tree ever,'' my
oldest daughter said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
