<HEADER>
A3233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-PARZINGER-FURNISH-NYT     12-08 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARZINGER-FURNISH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMMI PARZINGER: A VOGUE MODERNIST   IN A ROGUE MARKET  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, Calif.)  By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the well-dressed men about town in New York in
the 1950s was Tommi Parzinger, who designed furnishings for
fashionable decorators like Billy Baldwin and for private clients
like Marilyn Monroe (or Mrs. Miller, as she called herself in
making her evening appointments) and branches of the Ford, DuPont
and Mellon families.
</P>
<P>
   Parzinger was also a painter. An exhibition of 25 of his oil
paintings went on view Wednesday for the first time, along with his
furnishings, at Palumbo, a modern design gallery at 972 Lexington
Avenue through Dec. 22.
</P>
<P>
   A design contemporary of T.H. Robsjohn-Gibbings and Paul Laszlo,
Parzinger was born in Germany in 1903. He moved to New York,
opening for business in 1939. His last showroom, on East 57th
Street, closed shortly after his death in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Parzinger's furnishings are highly prized and heavily
collected as examples of a more idiosyncratic, rarefied midcentury
design _ an elegant aside to the Eameses, Knolls and Nelsons of the
period _ that the market calls ``high-style modernism.''
</P>
<P>
   Produced as custom studio pieces or expensive small factory
items, Parzinger's were cosmopolitan-looking designs, involving
costly, craft-intensive materials and processes like brass work and
lacquer _ cabinetry in the simple, antimachinist idiom of the
Wiener Werkstatte.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Palumbo, the gallery's owner, has become something of a
specialist in Parzinger's career, selling his vintage pieces. In
association with Donald Cameron, who worked with the furniture
designer for 32 years and who inherited the company, Parzinger
Originals, Ms. Palumbo recently began manufacturing reproductions
of Parzinger's designs. They are based on original working
drawings. The 25-piece line, priced from $2,200 to $20,000,
continues to expand; dinnerware is next.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron produced most of the designs during Parzinger's last 15
years, as the master devoted himself to his Expressionistic
painting, which bears no resemblance to his crisp furniture forms.
</P>
<P>
   The collecting market for Parzinger and the reappearance of
Cameron has raised an interesting point about high-style modernism
and its audience. With its chic entrance into the arena of
antiques, vintage modernism must now face a mature collecting
market's central issue: that of authenticity. Verification becomes
complicated with boutique or decorator operations like Parzinger's.
His custom work was not consistently labeled. Through licensing
agreements, designs were sold by other companies under his name, in
some cases unauthorized by Parzinger.
</P>
<P>
   Without corporate archives like Herman Miller's or documented
competitions like the Museum of Modern Art's that record and verify
its genesis, a design has no secure substantiation when it isn't
signed, aside from impeccable provenance.
</P>
<P>
   At galleries and auction houses, the field of high-style
modernism is clouded by so-called gray goods: great lines,
questionable lineage.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's Los Angeles, in its ``Innovators of 20th Century
Style'' auction on Sept. 15, put up for sale 12 lots described as
Parzinger's designs. Cameron, unknown to Christie's, said that
three were not.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw it, I thought, `This is crazy; it's just bad
design,''' he said, when a friend brought the catalog to his
attention. Cameron telephoned Christie's in New York. Jason Stein,
a decorative arts specialist at Christie's Los Angeles, called him
to ask if the lots could be described as ``in the style of'' Tommi
Parzinger. ``I said, `No, the designs are too ugly,''' Cameron
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's reattributed one contested lot, which failed to sell,
as ``in the style of'' in a sales announcement. Another, a floor
lamp, sold as a Tommi Parzinger design for $3,450.
</P>
<P>
   A Christie's spokeswoman, Andree Corroon, said the lot was
reviewed by internal and external experts. The auction house
remained confident that the attribution was correct.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid confusion over Tommi Parzinger furnishings being
produced now, Ms. Palumbo is branding her pieces
``Parzinger/Cameron Originals at Palumbo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
