r s BC-BBA-OAKLAND-HNS &LR;      12-08 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-OAKLAND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETICS LEADER PLANS TO KEEP TEAM IN OAKLAND FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) 
 By MATTHEW YI  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ A day after a local investment group decided
to give up its efforts to purchase the Oakland Athletics, a team
official said he expected the franchise to remain in the East Bay
for at least the near future.
</P>
<P>
   A's President Mike Crowley on Tuesday said a new deal is in the
making with city and county officials to keep the team in Oakland
beyond 2001, when the team's current owners can end their lease
with the Oakland Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic that something would come together,'' Crowley
said. ``The A's will be here for a while, that's for sure. We're
planning for the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the question remained Tuesday at what price the team
would be asked to stay _ and whether it will cost taxpayers any
money.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Crowley nor Oakland City Council President Ignacio De La
Fuente would confirm or deny reports that the team would stay
through 2004 in exchange for a cash contribution toward marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Dolich, the former A's executive who headed the local group
seeking to buy the team from current owners Ken Hofmann and Steve
Schott, said the lease already is a good deal for the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The A's already have one of the handsomest stadium lease deals
in baseball. That was a major point of attraction for our quest for
ownership,'' Dolich said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the current lease, which expires in 2001, the team
gets all proceeds from parking, concessions and pays no rent.
</P>
<P>
   An offer to give cash to help pay for marketing the team would
not only be more icing on the cake for the franchise, but an
unusual one, Dolich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been other public-private partnerships in sports
when it comes to generating more revenue through ticket sales or
corporate sponsorships ... but if it ultimately comes to a check
being written, that would be a little different,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Hofmann and Schott announced more than a year ago that they
would exercise their right to end the lease in 2001, some Oakland
and Alameda County officials believed a sale to new, local owners
was the only way to keep the A's here.
</P>
<P>
   They thought they had found those owners in a group led by
Dolich. But three months ago major league baseball owners refused
to approve the Dolich group's $122.4 million purchase, saying the
league must first study the viability of small market teams such as
the A's.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Dolich announced that he and his investors,
including Men's Warehouse founder George Zimmer and Modesto
supermarket magnate Bob Piccinini, had withdrawn their $12 million
deposit, effectively giving up their pursuit to buy the team.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Keeping professional sports teams in Oakland has been a
contentious issue in recent years with lawsuits being filed between
the Joint Powers Authority _ represented by city and county
officials _ and the Golden State Warriors pro basketball team, the
Oakland Raiders football team and the A's.
</P>
<P>
   The JPA earlier charged that the Warriors never paid the team's
share of the costs to renovate the new sports arena operated by the
JPA. Two months ago, an arbitrator ruled in favor of the city and
county, ordering the Warriors to pay $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Raiders, team owner Al Davis has been arguing that
the current lease _ set to last until 2011 _ is not valid because
city and county officials falsely promised sellouts.
</P>
<P>
   That trial is pending.
</P>
<P>
   When the Raiders were wooed from Los Angeles to Oakland, the A's
were upset, mainly because the JPA agreed to eliminate some
bleacher seats to make room for luxury boxes for the football team.
</P>
<P>
   Even without such disputes, it is difficult to keep professional
sports teams because of the intense competition between cities,
Dolich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a certain extent, the JPA has basically done a good job in
keeping these teams here,'' he said. ``Yes, it's been contentious.
Yes, there's been a lot of money floating around here. But if you
look at other cities spending money on new stadiums, we're better
than OK to have three sports franchises.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Fuente agreed, criticizing speculations that Oakland is
not a big enough market to keep the A's when the San Francisco
Giants are just across the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Although De La Fuente would have preferred to see the Dolich
group become the new A's owners, he said he's excited at the
prospects the team will remain in Oakland at least until 2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``The negotiations are pretty much done. We just need to get the
final approval from both sides,'' De La Fuente said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
