<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3244 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-OLD-TOOLS-ART-NYT &LR;      12-08 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-TOOLS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD TOOLS: WHEN ANTIQUES FOLLOW FUNCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The old wallpaper roller, inherited from my father, was the
first tool I treasured. Its wooden handle was worn, and when I
wrapped my hand around it, it was as comforting as a wooden shift
knob on a '66 Camaro. Besides its patinated handle, it had a curved
head of orange Bakelite, which was gentle in delicate corners _ it
didn't rip the paper the way the new hard and heartless plastic
ones do.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, although I treasured it, I am irresponsible. The wallpaper
roller was lost.
</P>
<P>
   But I know where to find another one.
</P>
<P>
   All kinds of wonderful old tools _ cheap and not so cheap _ can
be found in a lot of places these days: country auctions, flea
markets, swap meets and, maybe best of all, the Internet. I just
missed a set of five Bakelite-and-wood wallpapering tools, which
sold for $9 on eBay, the online auction site. Last week, eBay had a
whole box of wallpaper tools at a starting bid of $5.
Unfortunately, they were new, which the seller seemed to think was
their main selling point.
</P>
<P>
   But often old tools (the ones labeled ``antique'' seem to be
expensive) are made better, and, many of us believe, work better,
too. Just this week, eBay was peddling vintage wallpaper presses
from Maine (to imprint a ``wallpaper look'' on walls, the seller
said); Bakelite pottery tools in orange, red, green and amber;
planes made of Brazilian woods; and a rosewood-handle mortise gauge
trimmed in brass.
</P>
<P>
   If you are buying a gift, it doesn't matter if you don't know
what a mortise gauge is _ as long as the carpenter you love wants
one. This is not the same as buying a tie: ask for a list of
specific tools, and then ferret them out.
</P>
<P>
   And if you don't know an awl from an ax, the Internet may be the
best, cheapest place to search for old tools _ implements with
provenance and patina. Just take your list and enter the key words:
for a 14-inch steel-blade back saw, you enter ``back saw'' and see
what comes up.
</P>
<P>
   On eBay last week, a set of Lutz drafting tools from Germany,
arrayed lovingly in a polished hardwood box, sold for $15. A set of
chip-carving tools went for $6.61. An old L.L. Davis 26-inch wooden
level trimmed in brass brought $53.65. An antique rosewood Stanley
No. 96 brass-bound level sold for $358.34, with 24 people bidding.
(There's that word ``antique.'')
</P>
<P>
   I've done some buying and selling on eBay recently, and,
generally speaking, the items I bought were pretty much as
described and arrived soon after my check cleared. Shipping charges
are usually detailed in the item description. If you have
questions, be sure to ask before you bid; eBay makes it easy to
send e-mail to the seller.
</P>
<P>
   But suppose you can't find what the Christmas boy or girl wants?
</P>
<P>
   For the real collector, there is www.mjdtools.com, run by Martin
Donnelly, a 44-year-old amateur carpenter. A few years ago,
Donnelly went to a hardware store looking for a saw and could find
only one, with a handle cut out of a single piece of plywood,
priced at $28. ``I couldn't bear to buy it,'' Donnelly said. Later,
he found himself at a local auction bidding $15 for two saws made
in the late 1800s. They had rosewood handles with bushels of wheat
carved on them. ``Driving home, I had to stop the car and just look
at them,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Although www.mjdtools.com (or www.oldtools.com,
www.toolsrules.com, www.tooltimer.com or any number of other sites)
is full of esoterica (an early cooper's compass for $225; an
Atwater's Tiger wrench for $265; a Goodell-Pratt No. 4 gear-driven
hand drill for $550), Donnelly said plenty of good old tools are
floating around for $5 to $10. And they are practical.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Bakelite wallpaper roller, many of these tools work
better than new ones. Many are heavier and don't drift on a
workbench like newer ones. (Garrett Wade in New York sells new
tools made to old designs, at much higher prices than originals you
might find on eBay or in a bin at a country auction _ but then,
they're brand-new.)
</P>
<P>
   Take pliers and prying tools. Fifty years ago, they were made in
dozens of shapes, unlike the one-size-fits-all versions now sold in
hardware stores. It was easy to assemble a collection in no time. I
have a collection of old pry bars, including a long, thin handmade
bar of spring steel. It's perfect for removing old moldings; I got
it for 75 cents at a tag sale.
</P>
<P>
   Old planes, because their metal and wood parts were fitted by
hand, often have more adjustments _ useful for fine woodworking. As
an example, Donnelly cited Stanley's skewed-blade rabbet plane, a
specialist's tool on which the cutting iron is set at an angle,
indispensable for cutting figured woods. ``It's the best rabbeting
plane ever made,'' he said. Because such planes aren't made
anymore, and because carpenters need them, ``they bring even more
money than if they were only sought by collectors.'' He added that
he doesn't happen to have any in stock at the moment. The planes
usually bring $300 to $400.
</P>
<P>
   But the thrifty should not despair. Small, ordinary tools like
bevel gauges, planes and wood-handle hammers and screwdrivers might
sell for $1 to $5 at a flea market or swap meet. I once bought a
small wood and iron plane for $3 in an antique-junk shop in North
Scituate, R.I. The plane is a gem: It's handy in small places
(sometimes you can even plane a sticky door without taking it off
the hinges), the blade is easy to sharpen and, well, it feels very
good indeed. And the old rock maple, polished by decades of use, is
a joy to look at.
</P>
<P>
   Why would anyone ever buy plastic again?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
