<SLUG> BC-BEER-NUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEER NUT ISN'T A QUACK, BUT THIS BEER IS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN MELTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time I provided a pronunciation guide in this column,
for Japan's Asahi beer, a letter poured in from a reader. This
person took me to task for issuing bad information, and then
questioned my qualifications. This indicated to me that some people
have more time on their hands than is good for them and me. So
herewith, I set forth new rules: I pronounce it any way I want to,
and so can you.
</P>
<P>
   Which is precisely why I rhyme Kwak Belgian Ale with ``Quack.''
Nobody at the pub where we tried it knew how to pronounce it,
including the barkeep. But we all had a jolly good time making lots
of amusing duckie noises. So as far as I'm concerned, it's Kwak.
Jimmy Kwak corn, and I don't care, OK?
</P>
<P>
   Whew. Deep cleansing breath. All right, now that I've vented,
let's yak about Kwak.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, it is pronounced ``Quack,'' but with less emphasis
on the final ``ck.'' The Web site said so. So there. Second, you
may not be familiar with the beer, but you've probably seen those
top-heavy mugs with small globes at the bottom that require a
wooden stand for serving - that's a stirrup-cup, a Kwak
innovation/marketing gizmo. Third, Kwak has been brewed since 1791
by the same family operation, which is kind of neat.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's the beer. Kwak builds up an enormous head of
thick, creamy foam that throws off a nicely scented bouquet. Tiny
bubbles make delicate, textbook-style Belgian lace patterns on the
inside of the glass. The rich amber color confirms the spicy,
almost clove palate, and bitter, chewy caramel finish.
</P>
<P>
   One final thing: the complete name of this beer is ``Pauwel
Kwak,'' pronounced ``PAW-uhl KWA-ck.'' ``Pauwel'' is in teeny-tiny
letters, while ``Kwak'' predominates. Is it the name of the 18th
century, mutton-chopped dude pictured on the label, hoisting a cold
one? Is it a place? A thing? Animal, vegetable, mineral?
</P>
<P>
   Haven't a clue. Twenty minutes online couldn't help me, either.
I may not know what it means, but by God, I can pronounce it, which
means I can order it and drink it.
</P>
<P>
   What more do I need?
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 1750EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3250 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-DECK-THEHALLS-TEX     12-08 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DECK-THEHALLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING A RICH-PERSON YULE LOOK ON A PAUPER'S BUDGET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am looking at the raw materials of my Christmas, and frankly,
they're pretty pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   A box of 15 cheap glass ball ornaments, missing four that were
long ago broken. A 12-foot swatch of gold lam. Eight strings of
miniature white lights. Sixty mismatched tree ornaments, in every
shape, color and motif, including a hand-painted wooden teddy bear
that says ``Someone in Missouri misses you'' and a fraying red
satin ball decorated with my fifth-grade school picture. A couple
of strings of gold beads; two velvet stockings; a holly-flocked
table runner.
</P>
<P>
   This is the stuff I've been carting around for years, my
personal Christmas stash, culled from family hand-me-downs,
well-intentioned gift exchanges and the after-holiday sale bin at
Pier 1. Pretty much everyone who decorates for the holidays has a
version of this collection; the average family will spend just $77
on holiday decorations this year, according to an American Express
survey.
</P>
<P>
   So, every year, we haul the boxes out of the attic and try to
make the same old stuff look fresh. Also Christmas-y. Vaguely
reminiscent of whatever our parents did. And, if possible, stylish.
</P>
<P>
   The whole concept scares me so much that I usually just buy a
few poinsettias, throw ornaments onto the tree and keep the lights
low through the holidays. But this year will be different, because
I begged for this assignment. This year, I got to do what the rich
people do: use professional help.
</P>
<P>
   There is an entire industry of designers and florists who, for
$40 to $80 an hour, will bring in greenery, lights and decorations,
mix it in with your own belongings, and set up the whole shebang.
And they say there is nothing wrong with being sentimentally
attached to your decorations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We LIKE to use their stuff,'' says Lexa Northington, owner of
Lexa's Flowers and Gifts in Fort Worth, who decorates for private
homeowners and such clients as Rivercrest Country Club. ``It's more
personal that way. I don't like to just put a department store in
their house.''
</P>
<P>
   My decorator, of course, gets instructions from me that real
clients probably wouldn't use: We can't spend more than $100, we
have only a couple of days between planning and executing, and it
has to be easy enough that friends might believe I did it myself.
</P>
<P>
   To get a better idea of what I'm in for, I do my research,
consulting Tony King _ a decorator who once did Sylvester
Stallone's house and who now serves as the resident Christmas
expert at icelebrate.com, an Internet decor retailer based in
Irving, Texas. After reading up on King's Web site advice and
watching his tree-trimming video, I have a sense of false
confidence. How hard can this be?
</P>
<P>
   A few nights before decorating day, I take King's advice and get
everything out, spreading baubles and lights and ribbons all over
my dining room table. By the time my designer shows up _ Mary K.
Griffith, of the family-owned C.C.'s Touch of Nature, an
orchid-arrangement and antiques retailer in Fort Worth _ I've made
a few determinations: I probably have enough lights. My ornament
collection does kind of have a theme _ lots of stars, lots of gold,
good representation of tacky. And for the rest _ I need help.
Badly.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith sorts through the mess quickly, picking out the
highlights (the piece of gold lam, a pretty red ceramic
candleholder). Everything else she is brutally honest about, in a
way you can't be about your own stuff.
</P>
<P>
   A 100-bulb strand of white lights is tossed aside because
they're on a white cord _ they'd look tacky on the tree. A stack of
silver place mats and matching organza napkins that I love is
dismissed because they don't look right with the other colors. A
pine-cone wreath is inspected and deemed acceptable as long as the
garish white-and-gold bow is removed. (''It looks like it belongs
at a wedding,'' Griffith says.)
</P>
<P>
   All in all, she's very forgiving; she says that my mismatched
ornaments will be fine, that surely we can find something to do
with that stray gold embossed napkin and that plaid ribbon. She
even likes a carved wooden Santa wall hanging that I've never known
quite how to display.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour, Griffith leaves me with simple instructions: Buy
a pretty tree, plug in all the lights and make sure they work, cut
the piece of gold cloth into four equal strips, and find last
year's gold candles, just in case. She'll take care of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Griffith pulls up to my house with a minivan
full of Christmas. We unload poinsettias, boughs of pine, cedar,
noble fir and blue-berried juniper, a big branch of yaupon holly
with pretty red berries, some wooden fruit and pine cones, and a
fresh centerpiece of juniper, cedar, noble fir and pine cones.
</P>
<P>
   We do the tree first, starting with the lights. After that,
Griffith drapes the strips of gold fabric, starting at the top and
looping them in lazy, irregular S-curves toward the bottom, rather
than a horizontal wrap. She leaves me in charge of the ornaments.
Tony King recommends doing two trees _ one with the ``pretty
ornaments,'' one with the decorations the kids made _ to those
clients with the space and money. Since I have neither, I hide the
rattier-looking decorations at the back and put the shiniest ones
where they'll stand out. But even the teddy bear (a gift from my
10-year-old niece) and the ornament with my grade-school picture
(made by my favorite aunt around 1974) find a place of honor.
</P>
<P>
   On the mantel, Griffith arranges a flow of greenery and berries,
studding it with seven crosses that I usually display scattered
around the house. (She used a sprig of holly left over from another
job, but you can also sprinkle in cranberries.) Then she adds a
small arrangement of pine cones, green apples and lemons. More
greenery goes on the dining table, around a centerpiece that we
place on one of my gold napkins and top with a gold pillar candle
and two small mesh gift boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the tiniest of changes makes a difference _ she
suggests hanging the two velvet stockings next to each other,
rather than on opposite ends of the mantel, where they get lost.
Rather than hanging the carved Santas, she props them up in a
basket and surrounds them with scraps of fir and cedar. A
forest-green table runner that was too long for my dining table
gets wrapped around the base of the tree. A ceramic candleholder
that always seemed too small looks much better with a wreath of
greenery.
</P>
<P>
   It takes the two of us, plus a friend who mostly just lay on the
couch and pointed out the bare spots on the tree, 3 1/2 hours to do
the tree, the mantel and three table-top decorations.
</P>
<P>
   The bill? After we finagle a bit _ removing a few pieces of
fruit from the mantle, using one fewer poinsettias _ it comes to
just under $104. And the result? It looks like my house at
Christmas _ except a lot better.
</P>
<P>
   So I did what any smart person on a budget would do: I took
pictures. Next year, I'm going to have to re-create this myself.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Canard provided research assistance for this report. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
