<HEADER>
A3251 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV16-     12-08 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV16-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTENING SPIRITED SIBLING A STRUGGLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, Dec. 16)  
(lh) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is how much my son loves his little sister: We were making
chalk outlines of ourselves on the driveway, and Sarah had me trace
her in bright yellow chalk.
</P>
<P>
   After we were done, Adam laid down beside her outline so his arm
overlapped hers and said, ``Will you trace me like this so it looks
like we're holding hands?''
</P>
<P>
   So I traced a big, green outline of him, and the green and
yellow blobs did, indeed, look like they were holding hands. Which
is about as close to holding hands with Sarah as Adam is ever
allowed to get.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah, my 3-year-old, has been as independent as a wild mustang
since she came into her personality at about 9 months old. Feisty
and stubborn don't even come close.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the at-home Montessori preschool Sarah attends, where
she is actually encouraged to be an independent thinker, she tests
the teacher's resolve.
</P>
<P>
   In her ``Goals for the Year,'' Ms. Sharon stated that: ``Sarah
is a sweet, caring child I feel honored to be able to work with.
She is strong-willed and very intelligent. I think with patience
and commitment, we will be able to bring out the best in her. She's
adorable as well. It took me a while to figure out how to reach
Sarah without interfering with her own spirit. ... Every day I tell
her and the others that time out is not a punishment, it is a
choice that they make.''
</P>
<P>
   You see how carefully she has sprinkled in the words
``strong-willed,'' ``patience'' and ``spirit.'' Oh, sure, she threw
in ``sweet,'' ``intelligent'' and ``adorable'' to cushion the
impact. But I LIVE with the child she's writing about. I know.
</P>
<P>
   And listen: Ms. Sharon didn't even HAVE a time-out policy until
Sarah got there.
</P>
<P>
   At home, our new theory is this: Sarah has a little too much
spirit, and we intend to crush some of it. She spends a lot of time
in her room, and has even received a few swats on her bottom for
blatantly hurtful behavior that endangered herself or someone else.
(This from parents who never spanked their first-born and were
proud of it.)
</P>
<P>
   What we tolerated at 2 is getting a bit much at 3. But the thing
that pains me the most is to see the way Sarah offhandedly rebuffs
Adam's affections. He waits until she's asleep to kiss her cheek,
so he won't get pushed away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Sarah even likes me,'' he'll say at night, close
to tears. ``Why can't I have a normal little sister?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, a normal little sister would be boring,'' we tell him.
``And Sarah is definitely not boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Be sweet to your big brother, I tell her again and again.
``Someday, you're going to want him to do you some favors, and
he'll have given up.''
</P>
<P>
   But, to Adam's credit, he keeps trying. And sometimes, when you
least expect it, Sarah responds. Last night I went downstairs to
get some water and when I came back up, Adam was in bed beside
Sarah, finishing her bedtime story. And she was curled up next to
him, listening. I was so thrilled, I grabbed the camera. Sarah
noticed me out of the corner of her eye, and gave a big smile at
the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``ADAM,'' she said, in her most bossy stage whisper. ``SMILE.
Mama is taking our picture.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
