<HEADER>
A3252 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TE     12-08 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE `MATTER' THAN YOU MAY WANT 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``More Matter''
</P>
<P>
   by John Updike
</P>
<P>
   Essays
</P>
<P>
   Knopf, $35
</P>
<P>
   John Updike is America's pre-eminent man of letters, and, at age
67, he has published his 50th book.
</P>
<P>
   Man of letters? That's defined as one who does it all: composes
verse, hatches novels and short stories, reviews other writers,
works critically, and delivers essays that touch on many spheres _
religion, politics, sports, feminism, health, economics, the fine
and popular arts _ and is so esteemed that everything he publishes
in The New Yorker and sundry literary periodicals eventually finds
safe haven between hard covers.
</P>
<P>
   That's John Updike, and here we have one of his cut-and-pastes,
in which every component has previously appeared in print. He has
run out of titles, so this is merely ``More Matter,'' a 900-page
compilation of 184 essays, reviews and other ruminations.
</P>
<P>
   Updike is an acknowledged as major novelist, but subtract the
Rabbit Angstrom series from his fiction inventory, and few among
his 14 other novels rate as major. Nor is he an easily defined
poet, pitched uncertainly between traditional verse forms and the
oblique fashion of our day. It is as an essayist that John Updike
shines brightest. The reader is regaled by a persuasive
intelligence and serenaded by graceful prose bereft of cliches.
</P>
<P>
   The four-part organization identifies ``Large Matters,''
``Matter Under Review,'' ``Visible Matter'' and ``Personal
Matters,'' although all of it seems equally personal. Within each
subdivision are snippet entries and much longer compositions.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how John Updike writes, taking on the 1950s: ``The
Fifties in my mind's eye are a waxy blue-white, a shining Cold War
iceberg drifting by in the wake of the khaki-brown Forties and the
grit-gray Thirties. As a child of those two shabby, beleaguered
decades, I was happy in the Fifties; I entered them as a penniless
high-school senior and left them as a home-owning father of three
children and the author of three books, with a fourth, ``Rabbit,
Run,'' submitted to the publisher just as the decade ran out. Many
Americans were happy in the Fifties _ but not as happy, looking
back, as we should have been.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ``Gender and Health'' subdivision of ``Large Matters,''
Updike is curious that The Song of Solomon passed muster with the
Bible-makers: ``The Song, which never once mentions God, was
included in the Bible most probably because, like Proverbs and
Ecclesiastes and Job, it was a treasure of Hebrew literature. No
other love poem from this literature survives. Its attribution to
Solomon gave it the protection of a revered historical name.''
</P>
<P>
   Other topics serve appropriately as hors d'oeuvres, but
literature is Updike's entree, and he's keen and engaging,
especially in considering the shorter fiction of Herman Melville,
the identity struggles of John Cheever, and several takes on Edith
Wharton. Old movies are an Updike passion, and the best (and
longest) of several movie-themed pieces salutes ``Genial, Kinetic
Gene Kelly'': ``He had plenty of ginger but no Ginger: although he
danced affectionately with Leslie Caron, amusingly with Debbie
Reynolds, snappily with Judy Garland, bouncily with Rita Hayworth,
broodily with Vera-Ellen, and respectfully with statuesque,
stony-faced Cyd Charisse, we think of Gene Kelly as a guy in
loafers and a tight T-shirt tap dancing up a storm all by his
lonesome.''
</P>
<P>
   There's consistent charm in Updike's writing, but this would be
a more treasurable volume at perhaps two-thirds its present length.
Some entries are simply too trivial. ``The Twelve Terrors of
Christmas,'' for one, is a strain, something you or I might write,
although we aren't in Updike's league. Also, a shorter book might
be more modestly priced. At $35, /(More Matter/) is steep. However,
if you have his other 49 books, you'll certainly want this one. (
Larry Swindell, former books editor of the Star-Telegram, is now a
gentleman of leisure residing in California. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
