<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-LINEN-PARTIES-ART-2ND     12-08 0332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINEN-PARTIES-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: the parties.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stoddart gets his fabrics from Egypt, Italy and Belgium and then
sends them to workrooms in Portugal, Vietnam and Madeira. He finds
some hand-embroidered trim in the garment district. Much of his
cotton is Egyptian percale, ``390-thread count,'' he said _ not
thick but soft.
</P>
<P>
   While fine-linen companies often promote thread counts of 300 to
600 threads per square inch, sheet experts say superhigh thread
counts can be misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a difference between 120 and 250,'' said Warren
Shoulberg, editor of Home Textiles Today. ``You can feel and see
the difference.'' But beyond 250 threads per square inch, he said,
it doesn't really matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perceptible difference between 250- and 400-thread-count
products is probably more in your mind than in your hands,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``American mills are the only manufacturers in the world that
focus on thread count,'' Shoulberg said, adding that thread-count
wars, which started in America in the late 1980s, created a
competition to draw a new market. Until then, he said, it was hard
to find counts of over 200 threads in the mass market.
</P>
<P>
   High-end all-cotton sheets are not only expensive to buy, they
must be ironed by hand or sent out to fine launderers, said
Carolina Donadio, a spokeswoman for Leron.
</P>
<P>
   High cleaning bills didn't matter to Ms. White, who couldn't
contain her excitement. ``I adore cocktail napkins,'' she said. ``I
think I'll do them in deep reds or blues with a simple `F.' It's
too crowded with the whole monogram on the cocktail napkin.''
</P>
<P>
   What about Park Avenue white? ``Oh no, not white,'' the
maverick-minded future Mrs. Farkas said. ``I only use white out at
Water Mill'' _ a reference to Farkas' beach house.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Baldrige, who admits she loves sheets and fine linens as
much as anybody, has one warning for women: ``Monogram with your
maiden name, so you'll get all the monogrammed bed linens in the
divorce.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
