<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3267 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WEBER-BARBOUR-BOS &LR;      12-08 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBER-BARBOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEBER PR WORLDWIDE BUYS D.C. LOBBYING FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A unit of Weber Public Relations Worldwide &UR;  &LR; in
Cambridge, Mass. has acquired a lobbying firm headed by Haley
Barbour, former chairman of the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Weber has made a slew of acquisitions since it was bought by the
Interpublic Group of Cos. of New York three years ago. But Barbour
Griffith &AMP; Rogers of Washington will be the first lobbying firm in
its portfolio, chairman Larry Weber said.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the acquisition were not disclosed. Barbour Griffith &AMP;
Rogers projects 1999 revenues of $8 million, Weber said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Weber began life as a public relations firm
representing high-tech companies. As those companies have grown,
they've needed a host of new services, including government affairs
and lobbying, as decisions made by the federal government have
affected how high-tech companies do business.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. has found that out in an ongoing federal
antitrust lawsuit. Microsoft is one of Barbour Griffith's clients,
as are Delta Airlines, Glaxo Wellcome Inc., and CBS Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Since being bought by a unit of New York-based IPG three years
ago, Weber has been looking to buy firms with different areas of
expertise to serve its clients.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1998, Weber bought Ryan McGinn, since renamed Weber
McGinn, a Washington-area firm that specializes in government and
public affairs, a discipline that includes providing public
relations on behalf of firms embroiled in federal lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Government affairs is distinct from lobbying, which seeks to
influence bills before Congress and policies determined by the
executive branch of the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Geraldine Ferraro, the 1984 Democratic
nominee for vice president, joined Weber McGinn. Her job is to
advise corporate clients on women's issues such as glass ceilings
in the workplace, compensation, and health care.
</P>
<P>
   A future Weber acquisition could be of a Democratic lobbying
firm to complement Barbour Griffith.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a different unit of IPG purchased Cassidy &AMP;
Associates, a lobbying firm with Massachusetts ties. And recently
IPG's archrival, the Omnicom Group, saw a Canadian company it owns
buy McDermott/O'Neill &AMP; Associates of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Both IPG and Omnicom are scrambling to put together networks of
communications companies that can serve nearly every conceivable
need of large global clients such as Gillette Co.
</P>
<P>
   IPG also owns Hill Holliday Connors Cosmopulos and Mullen, two
of New England's largest ad agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Weber said Weber Public Relations Worldwide projects
1999 revenues of $97 million, up from $15 million in 1996, the
firm's last year as an independent public realtions shop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 1811EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
