<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WEB SITE HELPS THE DISABLED WORK, SHOP AND COMMUNICATE  
 WEB PORTAL FOR THE ARTS PROMOTES GENRE-HOPPING  
 A WAY TO FEED THE HUNGRY WITH ONLY THE CLICK OF A MOUSE  
 TONGA IS SET TO GO ONLINE TO STAKE ITS MILLENNIUM CLAIMS  
 PEEK AT COMING BOOKS AND MAKE A DONATION  
 CONSPICUOUS CONSUMPTION FOR THE INTERNET GENERATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.) (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moving the Internet a step closer toward fulfilling its promise
to be all-inclusive, We Media, a three-year-old company serving the
disabled and their families, recently unveiled a full-service Web
site aimed at that market.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, www.wemedia.com appears much like many other
commercial or service sites, with lots of information and links to
shopping. But each mouse click beckons users to explore a range of
offerings, including education, employment, travel and financial
services made to appeal to the needs of the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Cary Fields, co-founder of We Media, said that as many as 54
million Americans considered themselves disabled, a group that he
said had more than $1 trillion in spending power. Being able to buy
groceries, bank and communicate with friends and family by way of
the Internet is especially important for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The site also offers users free e-mail and computer-based
long-distance phone calls over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Portions of the site, like the We Media magazine, have special
software that enable users with impaired vision to hear rather than
read the site. Alexander Spinelli, We Media's chief technology
officer, said the company is being ``very aggressive in its ongoing
effort to make it completely accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   _ MICHEL MARRIOTT
</P>
<P>
   Web Portal for the Arts Promotes Genre-Hopping
</P>
<P>
   Culture vultures have a new place to nest on the Internet.
ArtandCulture.com, a portal site for all things aesthetic, was
scheduled to make its debut Thursday on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Each of its 1,000 entries on artists, performers and cultural
movements is accompanied by an incisive essay and a small set of
links to related Web sites (www.artandculture.com).
</P>
<P>
   Although the entries are categorized by artistic discipline, the
site's goal is to encourage visitors to explore subjects beyond
their usual enthusiasms. Marc Lafia, the site's founder and
editorial director, said, ``The great thing about the computational
platform is that it lets you put Rabelais next to William S.
Burroughs.'' The entries are assigned descriptive labels like
``intimate'' and ``bubblicious.'' Stephen Sondheim, the site says,
is bubblicious. Led Zeppelin is not.
</P>
<P>
   _ MATTHEW MIRAPAUL
</P>
<P>
   A Way to Feed the Hungry With Only the Click of a Mouse
</P>
<P>
   E-shopping may be easy, but a new form of charity on the Net is
absolutely painless: one click on the Hunger Site, and the U.N.
World Food Program gets three cups of rice, corn, maize or other
staples _ at no charge to the donor.
</P>
<P>
   The cost is borne by corporate sponsors, who contribute a
quarter-cup of staples (a half-penny's worth) for every Web browser
who clicks the Donate Free Food button at www.thehungersite.com.
Only one click a day per visitor is counted.
</P>
<P>
   For the sponsors, it's good image advertising because everyone
who donates sees a thank you screen carrying the logo of each
sponsor. For the world's 800 million hungry people, it's adding up
to a million cups of food a day. Worldwide, the United Nations
estimates, some 24,000 people die from hunger each day,
three-quarters of them children under 5. So this new use of the
networked world has been a boon for the food program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty incredible,'' said Abby Spring, a spokeswoman for
the program. ``It's a wonderful opportunity to involve individuals
around the world, and as more sponsors join, the amount of money is
really growing. The first check we got went to a school feeding
program in Ethiopia.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hunger Site, created and run by John Breen, a 42-year-old
computer programmer from Bloomington, Ind., began on a small scale
in June but is now gaining momentum rapidly. On Monday, the site
had 12 sponsors _ some signed on for a few days, others for longer
_ and more than 350,000 visitors clicked to donate food.
</P>
<P>
   _ TAMAR LEWIN
</P>
<P>
   Tonga Is Set to Go Online To Stake Its Millennium Claims
</P>
<P>
   While there is some debate about which piece of inhabited land
will be the first to greet the new millennium, the Pacific islands
that make up the Kingdom of Tonga seem to have a reasonable claim
to the honor. At the stroke of midnight in Tonga on New Year's Eve
it will still be 5 a.m. Eastern Standard Time.
</P>
<P>
   To mark the occasion, Forthenews.com, a San Francisco-based
Internet company, will offer a series of live Webcasts of the
Tongan millennium celebrations. ``They don't have a broadcast TV
station in Tonga, but they're doing some very sophisticated things
with the Internet,'' said Alan Shulman, president of
Forthenews.com. ``Tonga has been virtually ignored by all the
millennium committees.''
</P>
<P>
   At the stroke of midnight, Tongan time, Shulman said, the Real
Video feed to his company's site, www.forthenews.com, will show
King Taufa'ahau Tupou IV praying in front of a choir of 10,000
Tongans. Another part of the site will feature a series of
millennial firsts from the yet-to-be-created Hall of Firsts within
Tonga's Royal School of Sciences. Among the planned features are
the first cup of coffee, the first kissand the first profit and
loss statement. Shulman is trying to sell corporations on the idea
of sponsoring these firsts and will also auction the rights to
perform some of them. ``Some duffer is going to want the first golf
swing,'' Shulman said. ``It will be the highlight of their life.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the site will also train one of its Webcams on a
personal computer to, as a company announcement puts it,
demonstrate to the world ``the reality of Y2K problems, at least in
Tonga.''
</P>
<P>
   _ IAN AUSTEN
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Peek at Coming Books And Make a Donation
</P>
<P>
   The next book of nonfiction by historian Stephen E. Ambrose,
``Nothing Like It in the World,'' will not be published until next
summer, but fans can get a head start on Wednesday, when Chapter 6
will become available online.
</P>
<P>
   The early publication is part of a fund-raising effort by Simon
&AMP; Schuster and Reciprocal Publishing, a company that creates
technology to protect digital material from being illegally
reproduced. Excerpts from written works by at least six well-known
authors will be available for viewing at www.hotauthors.com. Those
who take a peek are asked to donate $1 to $10 to benefit a
nonprofit group called Literacy Partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that it takes a whole chapter to get people
reading,'' said Ambrose, who last week sent Simon &AMP; Schuster the
edited script of ``Nothing Like It,'' which is about the building
of the first transcontinental railroad.
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster plans to post other excerpts, including
chapters from Jackie Collins' upcoming novel ``Lethal Seduction.''
Stephen King, Mary Higgins Clark, David McCullough and the estate
of Kay Thompson will also take part.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raising effort marks the introduction of new technology
intended to prevent digital content from being copied and
distributed without the publisher's permission. Those who view the
chapters will not be able to cut and paste paragraphs, but they
will be able to view and print the chapters they select and even
forward them to friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will be able to e-mail this content around the world,''
said Matt Moynahan, general manager and a senior vice president at
Reciprocal. But when a recipient clicks on a link in the e-mail
message, Moynahan said, ``they will have to make a $1 donation to
receive a key to unlock it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA GUERNSEY
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuous Consumption For the Internet Generation
</P>
<P>
   Looking for just the right gift for that new Internet
millionaire on your Christmas list? Something that says both money
and technology? The Financial Literacy Center, in conjunction with
the Henry Ford Museum and Berner Machine Labs, has just the ticket,
or ticker: an exact replica of Thomas Alva Edison's original 1870s
universal stock ticker.
</P>
<P>
   Exact, that is, but for three things: It will set you back
$35,000, it gets its market data from the Internet and it is a
decidedly useless, if arguably delightful, anachronism, more
sculpture than tool.
</P>
<P>
   Any serious day trader can get financial data much more quickly,
conveniently and inexpensively by using a portfolio service on the
Internet. And when the day is over, the trader can walk out the
door without sweeping up several hours' worth of ticker tape.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Literacy Center, which says it ``provides
innovative, educational and motivational products to help people
use money effectively in their lives,'' is justifying this pricey
piece of nostalgia by limiting first-year production to 300 tickers
and by assembling what it calls a ``dream team'' of craftsmen to
reproduce the machine. The team consists of two machinists, a
historian, a computer specialist, a violinmaker (he studied old
wood finishes) a woodworker, a printer and a
``jack-of-all-trades.''
</P>
<P>
   Confounding categorization, the replica is described as a
``meticulously crafted, working replication'' with ``a glass dome
cover and a beautifully handcrafted mahogany pedestal.'' But hidden
inside that pedestal is a ``plug-and-play coputer interface'' that
also enables the ticker to spit out sports scores and personal
messages.
</P>
<P>
   So, if it helps, think of it as a $35,000 pager. Orders _ or
rather, ``reservations'' _ are being taken online at
www.edisonstockticker.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ ROB FIXMER
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
