<SLUG> BC-HEARST-MAGAZINES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST SELLS SPORTS AFIELD AND MOTOR BOATING MAGAZINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Hearst Corporation announced Wednesday that it
has agreed to sell Sports Afield magazine to SA Acquisition
Corporation and Motor Boating &AMP; Sailing magazine to Times Mirror
Magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The sales are expected to be completed in the first quarter of
2000.
</P>
<P>
   In making the announcement, Cathleen P. Black, president of
Hearst Magazines, said both magazines ``have enjoyed long and
illustrious histories thanks to their great staffs and committed
readers.'' Black said that because both magazines were highly
specialized titles, Hearst sold them to companies that are more
focused on niche publications.
</P>
<P>
   Robert E. Petersen, chairman of the board of SA Acquisition
Corporation, said Sports Afield was the oldest outdoor magazine in
America and ``one of the most prestigious titles in the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports Afield, ``The Magazine for Today's Sportsman,'' was
founded in 1887. The Hearst Corporation acquired the magazine in
1953.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine, targeted to the outdoor sports enthusiast market,
has been nominated for more National Magazine Awards than any other
outdoor magazine, according to a Hearst spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen is a real estate investor and owner of a jet charter
service.
</P>
<P>
   Efrem Zimbalist III, chairman and CEO of Times Mirror Magazines,
said the decision to buy Motor Boating &AMP; Sailing demonstrates Times
Mirror's commitment to acquire strong brands in attractive markets
that fit with the company's outdoor enthusiast editorial focus.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph Charles, senior vice president of Times Mirror
Magazines and the head of Times Mirror Magazines' Marine Group,
said Times Mirror's other marine titles include Yachting and Salt
Water Sportsman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having three major titles in the marine field will help us
better meet our advertisers' needs for a marketing partner, as well
as our readers' needs for quality content,'' Charles said.
</P>
<P>
   Motor Boating &AMP; Sailing, ``The Boat Owner's Magazine,'' was
founded in 1907 as a yachting publication with the original title
Motor Boating; the word ``sailing'' was added to the title in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   William Randolph Hearst acquired the magazine in 1909 as part of
his fledgling magazine operation. The legendary Charles F. Chapman,
author of the seaman's bible Chapman's Piloting, served as editor
and publisher for 55 years.
</P>
<P>
   Motor Boating &AMP; Sailing has won more than 50 editorial and
design awards, more than all other boating magazines combined,
according to a Hearst spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Other Times Mirror magazines include Field &AMP; Stream, Freeze,
GOLF MAGAZINE, Outdoor Explorer, Outdoor Life, Popular Science,
Ride BMX, Salt Water Sportsman, Senior Golfer, Ski Magazine,
Skiing, Snap, Snowboard Life, The Sporting News, Today's Homeowner,
TransWorld SKATEboarding, TransWorld SNOWboarding, TransWorld
STANCE, TransWorld SURF, and Yachting.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst Magazines is a unit of The Hearst Corporation and the
world's largest publisher of monthly magazines, with 16 U.S. titles
and 98 international editions distributed in more than 100
countries. Of these, Hearst publishes nine monthly magazines in the
United Kingdom through its wholly owned subsidiary, the National
Magazine Company Limited.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
