u i BC-IRELAND-ADAMS-BOS &LR;      12-08 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-ADAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINN FEIN LEADER SAYS BRITISH BUGGED HIS CAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Sinn Fein's president, Gerry Adams, accused British
spies Wednesday of bugging a car in which he held secret meetings
with IRA leaders last month, in negotiations that broke an impasse
in the Northern Ireland peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Adams and the Irish government demanded an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Prime Minister Tony Blair told the House of Commons
that he would not publicly discuss intelligence matters.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking privately, Sinn Fein officials said the bugging
controversy would make it harder for the Irish Republican Army, its
military wing, to take steps toward disarming by February. The
Ulster Unionist party says that by then it will leave the new
power-sharing government of Northern Ireland, unless it sees
evidence that the IRA is disarming.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the IRA remain skeptical about the thought of turning in
their arms, and there is a long history of mistrust between the IRA
and the British intelligence services. The IRA says that British
intelligence agents exploited truces that the IRA had called in
1972 and 1975, in a cynical attempt to target the guerrilla
organization's leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago Sinn Fein briefly pulled out of talks with the
British government after a routine scan for listening devices by
party officials detected what they said was a bug in a photocopier
that Sinn Fein was using.
</P>
<P>
   Adams had been scheduled Wednesday to unveil his party's agenda
for the power-sharing government that was formed last week. He
surprised a press conference at the Stormont assembly building by
displaying instead what he said was a sophisticated,
satellite-aided listening and tracking device.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said the device had been planted in the Ford sedan that he
and other Sinn Fein officials had used in negotiations mediated by
George Mitchell, the former US senator from Maine. Adams had used
the car to discuss with IRA leaders various proposals to break the
impasse over disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever authorized the bugging operation, he said, was trying to
return to a ``security agenda'' that prevailed when the problem in
Northern Ireland was considered to be fighting the IRA rather than
try to find a negotiated political settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This proves the `securocrats' are still fighting their little
war,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Because Downing Street officials refused to discuss the matter,
it remained unclear whether the bugging operation had been cleared
at the level of Blair's Cabinet, as most sensitive intelligence
operations are.
</P>
<P>
   If it was an unauthorized operation, the Blair government will
come under pressure to investigate who approved it and why. If it
was cleared at the highest levels of the government, Blair may be
forced to explain what Adams called ``a breach of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Seamus Mallon, deputy leader of the power-sharing government
formed last week, backed calls for an investigation into the
alleged bugging.
</P>
<P>
   The bugging allegation was an unsettling aftermath to the high
point reached last week when an arduously negotiated settlement
transferred power from London back to Northern Ireland for the
first time since 1974, turning governance over to the first-ever
Belfast government to include both unionists and Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
   But while the bugging controversy showed the dearth of trust
among the parties, there was also promising news in Belfast
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The largest loyalist paramilitary group, the Ulster Defense
Association, held a press conference at which six of its masked
leaders announced that it would begin discussions with the
international commission in charge of disarming paramilitary
organizations in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   But the loyalists, using their Ulster Freedom Fighters cover
name, said they would begin to disarm only after the IRA did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
