<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FORTUNE-BOOK-REVIEW-N     12-08 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORTUNE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FORTUNE'S ROCKS:' PAINTING THE ONSET OF DESIRE A RICHER COLOR IN
1899 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know more or less from the opening scene what is going to
happen in Anita Shreve's skillful new novel, ``Fortune's Rocks.''
On a warm June day in 1899, Olympia Biddeford, soon to turn 16,
walks out along a beach at the New Hampshire community called
Fortune's Rocks after the offshore hazard on which so many ships
have foundered. She does so forbiddenly during the men's bathing
hour and senses for the first time in her young life the nature of
desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``This first brief awareness of desire _ and of being the object
of desire, a state of which she has had no previous hint _ comes to
her as a kind of slow seizure,'' the narrative intones, ``as of air
compressing itself all around her, and causes what seems to be the
first faint shudder of her adult life.''
</P>
<P>
   You are certain that Olympia will shortly become entangled in an
illicit love affair, thus shattering the equanimity of her Boston
Brahmin father, a man of letters three generations removed from the
making of a Brockton shoe-manufacturing fortune, whose hopes for
Olympia are so high that he has taken it upon himself to educate
her at home in preparation for Wellesley College.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, a friend of his soon shows up, John Warren Haskell,
a doctor and essayist who does volunteer work in a medical clinic
serving one of the nearby mill towns. Despite Haskell's being 41
and married with four children, Olympia is attracted to him both
for his bearing and for his involvement in a world so alien to her
sheltered life, and her feelings are reciprocated.
</P>
<P>
   After accompanying Haskell on his medical rounds and watching
him conduct a breech birth, she begins a passionate affair with him
that culminates in a lurid scene in which his wife spies them
through a telescope as they make love on the altar of a
deconsecrated chapel in the Biddefords' summer cottage, which was
once a convent.
</P>
<P>
   The family's reputation is ruined. Haskell's marriage falls
apart. Olympia turns out to be pregnant, and after bearing a boy
and having him taken away from her and put up for adoption, she is
sent off to western Massachusetts to be trained as a teacher at the
Hastings Seminary for Females. Eventually she rallies and tries to
reclaim her child. The story climaxes in a stirring custody trial,
followed by a series of unexpected reversals.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite its hackneyed sound, this tale is engagingly told by
Ms. Shreve, among whose previous six novels are ``The Pilot's
Wife,'' ``Resistance'' and ``The Weight of Water,'' the latter of
which was set on the Isles of Shoals, not far from the site of the
present story. With the help of slightly heavy-handed
foreshadowings of disasters to come _ ``In time Olympia will learn
of the obsession with the `other,' that person from whom the theft
is made _ the wife, the former mistress, the fiancee'' _ the plot
draws you into its increasing tension.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shreve seems comfortable in the past, which she has visited
only intermittently in her fiction. Among the books Olympia's
father assigns her to read, she remembers in particular ``The
Valley of Decision,'' ``A Tale of Two Cities'' and ``The Scarlet
Letter,'' ``since they are all works written in one century about
another, the purpose of which is an issue her father and she debate
at some length (her father taking the position that the social
mores of a previous era might better highlight certain moral
dilemmas of one's own time, and Olympia holding to the notion that
Edith Wharton or Charles Dickens or Nathaniel Hawthorne might
simply have been drawn to the baroque language and richer color of
an earlier era).''
</P>
<P>
   Both these arguments seem valid in the case of ``Fortune's
Rocks,'' highlighting as it does the issues of women's autonomy and
their custody of children in a more repressive era, and celebrating
as it does if not baroque language then certainly a more formal,
ornate style of expression (except for occasional slips, like
``girls not much older than her,'' and ``the woman is not as tall
as her,'' which make Ms. Shreve sound more like a contemporary
teen-ager).
</P>
<P>
   The drawback, of course, is that at times you feel that you've
read it all before, in dozens of novels, including Judith Rossner's
powerful ``Emmeline,'' about a Massachusetts cotton-mill girl who
is seduced and abandoned. Ms. Shreve brings little particularly new
to the genre, as, for instance, John Fowles did to ``The French
Lieutenant's Woman'' by making his heroine a rebel against
conventional male-female relationships. (Ms. Shreve's heroine is a
rebel, too, of sorts, but she would happily settle into marriage to
Haskell if she could.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet there's pleasure in the conventional power of ``Fortune's
Rocks.'' At its best _ in the trial scenes, in the moral dilemma
posed by the trial's conflict and in Olympia's stalwart character _
it evokes those elemental emotions that are reborn in every new
reader and that remain like bedrock in the most sophisticated of
readers. Some stories never grow tiresome, and in ``Fortune's
Rocks,'' Ms. Shreve has captured one of them and kept it alive and
pacing in its cage.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FORTUNE'S ROCKS'
</P>
<P>
   By Anita Shreve
</P>
<P>
   453 pages. Little, Brown &AMP; Co.. $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 1830EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3287 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-REPLIGEN-DRUG-BOS &LR;      12-08 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPLIGEN-DRUG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGPLIGEN AUTISM DRUG IN SINGLE   DOSE SAID DEFICIENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Repligen Corp. said Wednesday that secretin, its drug to treat
autism, does not appear to work after a single injection, although
company officials predicted that more positive results will appear
with higher doses.
</P>
<P>
   The Needham, Mass. biotechnology company said the New England
Journal of Medicine will publish Thursday a study by a North
Carolina group that independently tested the drug on 18 patients.
``A single dose of synthetic human secretin is not an effective
treatment for autism or pervasive developmental disorder,'' the
study concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Repligen, which owns the drug, was not involved in the
evaluation but plans to launch its own test early next year with
about 100 autistic children taking multiple doses over three or
four months.
</P>
<P>
   Repligen stock closed Wednesday at 3 3/16, up 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Autism affects 500,000 Americans and is a disorder in which a
young child cannot develop normal social relationships. There are
no drugs to directly treat the disorder, although in some cases
drugs are used to control aggressive and self-destructive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Many autistic youngsters also suffer from gastrointestinal
problems such as repeated diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   Repligen maintains that multiple doses _ not the single dose
results chronicled in the New England Journal of Medicine _ will
lead to changes in behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids whose diarrhea disappears in 48 hours after taking
secretin tend to have normal stools and very often this leads to
improvement in autistic symptoms, such as better eye contact,
improved communications and trailing after siblings,'' said Walter
C. Herlihy, Repligen president and chief executive, officer whose
8-year-old daughter Lilian is autistic.
</P>
<P>
   He explained that in March, a Wall Street Journal article
revealed some promising results based on anecdotal evidence from
over 1,000 autistic patients who had used secretin as an
experimental drug. Those findings prompted a group of investors in
Ashville, N.C. to sponsor a formal clinical trial. However, they
relied on a single dose of secretin with four weeks of observation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they did is analogous to measuring behavioral changes in
an Alzheimer patient with one dose of a drug,'' said Herlihy. ``We
have always said a single dose does not produce significant
results.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 1832EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3294 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-RAMADAN-FASTING09-COX     12-08 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMADAN-FASTING09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fasting to reduce an `overstuffed ego'
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Later this month, Fawa Abukhali will
spend the last 10 days of Ramadan inside the small white mosque on
Purdy Lane in West Palm Beach. He will pray. He will fast. He will
rise before dawn from the carpeted floor each morning to spend his
day in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone will go to those lengths. But fasting during the
holy month of Ramadan is obligatory for every Muslim old enough and
healthy enough to go without food and water from sunrise to sunset.
The fast is undertaken to purify the body, promote self-discipline,
renew a focus on spirituality and increase compassion for those in
need.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how God wants us to feel,'' Abukhali said.
</P>
<P>
   This simple act of going without food for a sustained period of
time is one of the oldest and most universal religious practices in
the world. Fasting during Ramadan dates back to the seventh
century, when Muslims believe the Koran was revealed to the prophet
Mohammed. Buddhists fast periodically to clear their minds,
emulating the Buddha, who, they believe, reached enlightenment
1,000 years earlier while engaged in a 36-day fast. Jews, who fast
on Yom Kippur (the Day of Atonement), can trace their tradition
back to Scriptures written even earlier. And until the mid-'60s,
Catholics fasted from Saturday night until communion Sunday morning
as well as some days during Lent.
</P>
<P>
   But while there is more written in the New Testament about
fasting than either repentance or confession, most Protestants _
the largest religious group in America _ have never fasted for
spiritual purposes.
</P>
<P>
   That may change. Scholars of religion say that fasting gains
popularity during times of spiritual upheaval. (Fasts were
organized in the mid-1700s and early 1800s, for example, during
nationwide spiritual revivals.) And this, many evangelical
Christians believe, is a time of spiritual upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the way in organizing fasting in the evangelical
Christian community is Bill Bright, founder of the youth ministry
Campus Crusade for Christ. Bright said that in 1994 he heard the
voice of God tell him to lead the United States to repentance
through orchestrated communal fasts. He teamed up with other
high-profile evangelical preachers _ Pat Robertson and Promise
Keepers founder Bill McCartney among them _ to reach as many people
as possible. Organizers say that in the past five years, close to
10 million Christians have fasted as a result of their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these fasts take place during Lent. Others are
year-round, with a different member of a church fasting every day
for 365 days. Last month, 3,000 people gathered in Houston's
Astroarena and an estimated 2 million people from 40 countries
joined them via the Internet to take part in a 28-hour fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started this because I was so overcome by a sense of the
moral and spiritual disintegration in this country, from the inner
city to the White House,'' said Bright, who used the $1 million he
received as recipient of the Templeton Prize for Progress in
Religion to promote fasting. ``Jesus did not begin his ministry
until he fasted for 40 days.'' Bright says he believes a fast
remedies much more than a bloated body; it can deflate an
``overstuffed'' ego as well. And that, Bright says, is one of the
biggest issues facing Americans today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so self-indulgent,'' he said. ``There is something
about denying yourself that brings us closer to the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   Some evangelical Christians believe fasting can have societal
impact as well. Americans, they say, have grown almost arrogant in
their refusal to abide by spiritual laws: witness school shootings,
community violence, a degenerate media.
</P>
<P>
   These moral failings, many Evangelicals believe, will eventually
invite God's wrath. By fasting, Christians can not only forge a
closer relationship with God, they can better understand their
place in God's universe.
</P>
<P>
   Fasting, simply put, teaches humility, says Eddie Smith, a
coordinator with The National Prayer Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we have a choice,'' says Smith. ``Humility or
humiliation. If we choose to humble ourselves, then God won't lead
us down the road of humiliation. But if we remain self-centered and
materialistic, people will go through humiliation. Because God will
not be ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   Fasts undertaken by Christians today tend to be structured like
those in the Bible, lasting anywhere from one day, to three, seven,
21 and 40-day periods. Some are complete, others cut out only
liquor and sweets.
</P>
<P>
   Bright has talked at length about his 40-day fasts, where he
survives on fruit and vegetable juices. And Paul Cedar, a pastor
and chairman of Mission America, which champions fasting, says he
typically loses 22 to 24 pounds during his annual 40-day fasts. But
he is able to maintain his energy and keep up nearly a full work
load with just a glass of juice three times a day, he says. ``The
body goes through an acclimation process,'' said Cedar. ``The first
day or two is uncomfortable because your body is going through food
withdrawal. But when it realizes you aren't going to starve to
death, you really stop thinking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Troy Temple, an associate pastor at First Baptist Church of West
Palm Beach, fasted for 40 days in 1997 and said he became aware for
the first time of the incredible focus Americans put on food and
eating.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to his fast, Temple said, he and his wife were struggling
with infertility and money problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was driving one day and I was thinking about these things
and I just had this sense God was asking me, `What are you willing
to do to ... See me multiply your family or help you with your
finances?''' Temple said. ``I said, `God, I'll do anything,' and he
said, `Will you take 40 days and do it with me?'''
</P>
<P>
   Temple said he would. He used a juicer at home and drank kiwi,
orange, apple and pineapple juice every evening and canned fruit
juice and water during the day. He lost 44 pounds, and said he
became more humble and more clear-headed.
</P>
<P>
   And during his fast, the baby he and his wife would later adopt
was conceived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still hard for me to talk about,'' Temple said. ``I still
get choked up. I'll tell you what, there is an emotional intimacy
with God that comes along with fasting that is addictive.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
