<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-FAVORITES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRAPPING UP THE CENTURY WITH WHIMSY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MARIANNE ROHRLICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five thousand years of recorded history provided the House &AMP;
Home section with a few thoughts on holiday gifts for 1999. We
looked back, then we looked forward, and realized this: favorites
never go away.
</P>
<P>
   We narrowed the list to five categories, each with a range of
prices (half are under $50), with objects that excite the eye
(chrome, glass, design!), challenge the mind (technology, toys!) or
set the spirit soaring (a French Art Deco mirrored radio from the
1940s). Our choices were highly personal (what better way to give a
gift?) but with the universally useful within view, too. And these
collations of past and present could also make stylish predictions:
for the right recipient, a collecting direction in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
   We start with New York, on this page. A great town since 1626.
And getting better: we found the book that teaches you clever
things to do with empty MetroCards.
</P>
<P>
   Glass. It's been a glittering hit since 2,500 B.C. Jewels like a
1950s Murano paperweight won't break the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Radios. On the air since 1906. They are the frequency of
adolescence: give a 1960s model to your teenager.
</P>
<P>
   Toys have been around since the beginning. Made for children or
adults, our hand-crafted ones are pets you won't have to walk.
</P>
<P>
   And last but not last call: bar ware. The celebration can't
start without it. Think of New Year's Eve 1999 as the ``Last Gas
for 1,000 Years.''
</P>
<P>
   Glass:
</P>
<P>
   1. A glass hand to hold rings and other baubles was cast from a
19th-century mold. It is $11.25 at Fishs Eddy, 889 Broadway (19th
Street).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. A Murano glass paperweight was made in the 1950s, before
electronics made stacks of paper extinct. It is $110 at VW Home,
333 W. 39th St. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. A new Murano glass vase, 13 inches tall, takes the shape of a
classic-footed urn. It is $235 at Homer, 939 Madison Ave. (74th
Street). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. A Ribbon vase, of plate glass and aluminum, was designed by
Peter Hewitt in the late '90s. It is $48 at MOMA Design Store, 44
W. 53rd St., (800) 447-6662 or www.momastore.org. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. A frosty snowman paperweight is $78 at Adrien Linford, 927
Madison Ave. (74th Street) or 1339 Madison Ave. (94th Street). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6. A Murano glass vase with O-shaped handles is $279.99 at
Medici, 420 Columbus Ave. (80th Street). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   7. A vanity bottle from the '60s, made of milk glass, was never
used. From the French factory where it was made, it is $36 at Rosie
in the Paris Apartment, 860 Lexington Ave. (65th Street). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8. An Italian pitcher from the '70s is $95 at Lost City Arts,
275 Lafayette St. (Prince Street).
</P>
<P>
   9. A set of three bud vases, designed by Jan Vanderland, is $11
at the Museum of American Folk Art, Columbus Avenue at 66th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Radios:
</P>
<P>
   1. A handmade FM radio constructed of recycled wire and tin cans
from a workshop in Capetown is $90 at Tink, 42 Rivington Street
(Eldridge Street); (212) 529-6356. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. A French Deco radio from the 1940s is mirrored in the style
of the furniture of the period. The radio is in perfect condition
and working order (it has been rewired). It is $700 at Lorraine
Wohl, 860 Lexington Ave. (64th Street). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. A ball-shaped Panasonic Satellite AM radio from the late '60s
was meant to swing from a belt loop. Also available in other
colors, it is $48 from Penny Toys in Leola, Pa., (717) 656-0678. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. Sony's new ICF-B200 Emergency Radio (just in case) has a
hand-cranked generator; one minute of winding yields 30 minutes of
listening. It can also run on battery power. The plastic AM-FM
radio is $99.95 at Sony Style, 550 Madison Ave.(55th Street). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. A sophisticated new Wishbone radio designed by Philippe
Starck is supported by its wishbone-shaped easel back. It is $36 at
the Terence Conran Shop, which opened Wednesday at 415 East 59th
Street.
</P>
<P>
   6. A reproduction of the Crystal Rocket Radio, a 1957 design, is
tuned with the probe on its nose. It is $10 at Restoration
Hardware, (800) 762-1005 or www.restorationhardware.com.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   7. A reproduction of a '40s Bakelite clock radio is $59 from
Pottery Barn, (800) 922-5507. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8. The new Pick-Up Sticks AM-FM radio by Nexa, a simple
brushed-metal form, is named for the two sticks that control the
tuning and volume. It is $30 at Spectra, 903 Madison Ave. (73rd
Street). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toys:
</P>
<P>
   1. T-Rex, made in Zimbabwe of multicolored telephone wire, is
$225 at Craft Caravan, 63 Greene St. (Broome Street). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. A painted bird and horse, which were made in Vienna in the
first part of the 20th century. The pieces are made in the style
and colors of the Bauhaus. One piece is signed from the Wiener
Werkstautte workshop. Each is $850 at Kelter Malce, 74 Jane St.
(Greenwich Street). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. A wooden frog, handmade in Mexico and signed by the artist,
is $75 at Pan American Phoenix, 857 Lexington Ave. (65th Street). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. An imposing armadillo, hand-carved and hand-painted in
Guatemala, is $30 at the shop in El Museo del Barrio, 1230 Fifth
Ave. (105th Street).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. An articulated crocodile, 36 inches long, was carved in
Brazil from the woody parts of palm leaves. It is from a collection
of reproductions of traditional Brazilian toys. The crocodile is
$75 at El Museo del Barrio. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6. A little chameleon made of telephone wire is $18 at Craft
Caravan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   7. A wooden bird from Mexico encrusted with beads is $125 at the
American Museum of Natural History, Central Park West at 79th
Street. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8. A handsome lion, created from old tin cans, is from a
collection of animals made by a cooperative of five brothers in
Zimbabwe. It is $30 at the American Museum of Natural History. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bar Ware:
</P>
<P>
   1. A plastic corkscrew from Japan, which looks like a futuristic
animation figure, is $45 at Mxyplyzyk, 125 Greenwich Ave. (13th
Street). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. A chrome cocktail shaker with a Bakelite handle was made by
Farberware in the 1940s. It's part of a collection of vintage
shakers at Maya Schaper, 106 W. 69th St., for $85. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. A Corona Champagne flute was designed in Germany by Richard
Linxweiler for Kulturstadt Weimar in honor of the millennium.
Mouth-blown, the signed flute is one of a limited edition of 1,999
pieces. It is $130 at Mxyplyzyk.
</P>
<P>
   4. A horned Bull glass for red wine, designed in Germany in 1995
by Richard Linxweiler, is $42 at Mxyplyzyk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. A new rocket-shaped martini shaker in silver plate, which
stands on a separate base, is $78 at Adrien Linford, 927 Madison
Ave. (74th Street) and 1339 Madison Ave. (94th Street). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6. A replica of a 1928 Zeppelin-shaped silver-plated shaker,
originally made in Germany by Henckels, was modeled after the Graf
Zeppelin. The shaker is $55 at Restoration Hardware, (800) 762-1005
or www.restorationhardware.com.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   7. A dainty mid-20th-century shaker of faceted glass and silver
plate is $79 at Takashimaya, 693 Fifth Ave. (54th Street). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
