<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3327 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-SWEET-REVIEW-LAD     12-08 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SWEET-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SWEET AND LOWDOWN' HITS THE RIGHT NOTES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use Friday, Dec. 10 or later. Fact box at bottom) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Sweet and Lowdown'' is whimsical Woody, a charming little faux
biography that drolly combines a couple of Woody Allen's passions _
jazz music and artistic obsession _ into a delightful movie that
should go a long way to erase any lingering hard feelings over last
year's painful ``Celebrity'' misfire.
</P>
<P>
   Allen pops up in the movie as one of the expert commentators
examining the life of mythical 1930s jazz guitarist Emmet Ray (Sean
Penn). (Jazz expert Nat Hentoff also makes a cameo.) Emmet's a real
piece of work: On stage, he makes beautiful music; the rest of the
time, he's a selfish, cocksure lout. He's a man who loves the
ladies (his favorite dates: shooting rats at the dump and watching
trains), but refuses to become emotionally involved with anyone
because it might compromise his art.
</P>
<P>
   On a rare day off, Emmet meets a woman who improbably makes him
change his mind about love (insofar as Emmet ever alters his
outlook). Her name is Hattie (Samantha Morton), a mute laundress,
able to hear but not speak. In other words, she's a perfect
girlfriend for the self-absorbed Emmet; he comes to love her and
she him.
</P>
<P>
   But Emmet keeps butting up against his credo: I'm an artist; I
need to be free. Allen has explored the idea of the egotistical
artist throughout his career; movies have forever been his favorite
form of therapy (when he's not actually visiting the shrink
himself).
</P>
<P>
   Here, the autobiographical elements are out in full force for
Allen aficionados to sift through and ponder. Emmet sees himself as
the world's ``second-greatest guitarist,'' forever in the shadow of
gypsy great Django Reinhardt. The Woodman worships in the house of
Ingmar Bergman. (He was saying ``We're not worthy'' long before
Mike Myers.) He also has a messy personal life _ just like Emmet _
but excuses his failings by his devotion to his work.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't need to know any of this to enjoy this likable
movie. Allen has a knack for perfectly capturing earlier time
periods (``Bullets Over Broadway''), and he's aided here immensely
by long-time production designer Santa Loquasto, costumer Laura
Cunningham Bauer and cinematographer Zhao Fei, who bathes the
movie's nightclubs and shabby dives in a host of cheerful colors.
</P>
<P>
   Allen fills ``Sweet and Lowdown'' with deftly executed light
comedy and plenty of priceless sight gags, having great fun
throughout the movie with Emmet's Django obsession. Penn is perfect
as Emmet and Morton rates as an extraordinary find, an actress who
communicates on the level of silent film greats like Lillian Gish.
Uma Thurman again proves her Dietrich mettle in a wonderful
supporting turn, and director John Waters has a priceless cameo.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's sunny soundtrack, arranged by Dick Hyman with Howard
Alden supplying the sublime guitar work, is sweet music to the
ears, the best of the year. And why shouldn't it be? ``Sweet and
Lowdown'' comes from the heart, a bouncy meditation on music and
love that hits all the right notes with perfect style and finesse. &QL; 
_____ &UR;  &QL; 
The film: &LR;  ``Sweet and Lowdown'' (PG-13; sexual content). &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  Sean Penn, Samantha Morton, Uma Thurman. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR;  Written and directed by Woody Allen. Released
by Sony Pictures Classics. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  One hour, 35 minutes. &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR;  3 1/2 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
