<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITIGROUP-STATESTREET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE STREET AND CITIGROUP AGREE TO JOINT VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ State Street Corp. of Boston said Wednesday that it
would form a joint venture with Citigroup Inc. to gain a stronger
toehold in global pension markets, after the New York financial
services behemoth tried unsuccessfully to acquire parts of State
Street's business.
</P>
<P>
   Under the venture, State Street and Citigroup will combine their
401(k) retirement plan businesses. State Street will contribute two
units to the venture, to be known as CitiStreet. Citigroup, which
is the nation's biggest financial services company, will contribute
one subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston financial firm is a custodian for the mutual fund
industry, an asset manager, and the second-largest manager of US
corporate retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup had approached State Street last summer about
acquiring the two units, but the Boston company refused to sell and
instead proposed cooperating, according to James S. Phalen, a State
Street executive who will oversee CitiStreet.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup _ which owns banking giant Citicorp, the Travelers
insurance company, and brokerage and investment bank Salomon Smith
Barney _ did not try to acquire all of State Street, Phalen said.
</P>
<P>
   The venture, which unites two competitors with different
strengths, aims to blend State Street's leading presence in money
management and asset custody with Citigroup's strong marketing
clout and vast distribution networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good move for State Street, which has the technological
know-how but not the global reach of Citigroup,'' said Thomas D.
McCandless, an analyst who covers the Boston company for CIBC World
Markets.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Citigroup hopes the venture will put some fire
into its lagging asset management business and give it better
access to big retirement-plan customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The joint venture will help Citigroup improve its position in
the US defined contribution market, particularly in the large
corporate marketplace,'' said Thomas W. Jones, head of Citigroup's
investment management and private banking group.
</P>
<P>
   The 50-50 venture, to begin operating in the first half of next
year, will focus on 401(k) retirement plans, the fast-growing
segment of investment management that has transformed the way
Americans save for later years.
</P>
<P>
   State Street manages retirement plans for huge companies such as
Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co., but unlike Citigroup does not have the
marketing resources to pursue midsize and smaller companies _ a
fast-growing market.
</P>
<P>
   Citistreet's competitors will include Fidelity Investments,
Merrill Lynch, and Hewitt Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, which operates in more than 100 countries, will also
help the new venture expand into nascent retirement plan markets in
Europe and Japan, where State Street already has joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
   State Street oversees $5.3 trillion in assets and manages $582
billion. The company has had strong double-digit earnings-per-share
growth for nearly two straight decades, but it is not expected to
continue growing at that pace.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup manages $443 billion, claims 100 million worldwide
customers, and sports a full menu of financial services, including
banking, corporate lending, asset management, and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Stock in both companies fell Wednesday. State Street slipped 2
5/16 to close at 69 1/16, while Citigroup fell 2 7/16 to end the
day at 54 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Citistreet, to be located in Quincy, Mass., will initially have
3,000 employees, mostly from existing State Street operations, and
annual revenues of more than $300 million, Phalen said. It will
start out overseeing $200 billion in assets and servicing 4 million
retirement plan participants.
</P>
<P>
   Under 401(k)s, employees invest part of their salary in mutual
funds or other investment products and their employers match part
of the contribution. Such defined-contribution schemes have
increasingly replaced defined-benefit plans, in which employers
bear most of the burden.
</P>
<P>
   The joint venture combines two State Street units _ Retirement
Investment Services and WellSpring _ with Citigroup's Copeland Cos.
The two State Street units accounted for 6 percent of their
parent's 1998 revenue of $2.7 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
