<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTO HOLDS FINAL PRESS CONFERENCE OF MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A wistful-looking President Clinton acknowledged
Wednesday that living apart from his wife was not going to be easy,
but he said he was prepared to endure a long-distance marriage and
move to their newly purchased home in upstate New York when his
presidency ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be together as much as we can,'' the president said when
asked about Hillary Rodham Clinton's plans to move to New York,
where she is campaigning for a US Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's not the best arrangement in the world, but it's
something we can live with. I love the house, ... and I'm looking
forward to living there when I leave here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his final news conference of the year, Clinton was reflective
and at times defensive as he discussed his legislative record and
his adjustment to beginning a final year in office with both his
wife and his vice president away running their own political
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton jumped easily from questions about foreign policy to
queries about his difficult post-impeachment year and his looming
commuter marriage. The president deftly avoided commenting on the
current presidential campaign, except to say that Vice President Al
Gore would ``be a great president.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady has announced she will soon move into the
couple's home in Chappaqua, N.Y. _ an abode she referred to as ``my
home'' when asked about it this week. The phrase spurred new
questions about the couple's sometimes troubled marriage, which has
been excruciatingly dissected by the media throughout Clinton's
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton Wednesday said he planned to make the house his
home, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's got to spend a lot of time in New York, so she'll be
there a lot,'' Clinton said, tilting his head with a slight air of
sadness. ``She'll be here when she can. I'll go up there when I
can. We always make it a habit to talk at least once, if not more,
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The president bristled when asked whether Gore's campaigning was
making him an absentee vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, obviously, he's not around as much,'' Clinton said of
Gore, adding that he ``terribly'' misses the weekly lunches that he
and Gore used to have.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore was in the White House ``all day'' Wednesday, the
president insisted. ``In his critical functions, he's still
performing them,'' Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
   Only once did the president appear shaken by a reporter's
question _ one that centered on race, a favorite presidential issue
and the topic of a book Clinton is writing.
</P>
<P>
   Of 26 people who have held seven top advisory jobs at the White
House, not counting Cabinet members, all have been white, Clinton
was reminded. Why?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly taken aback, the president at first said he disagreed.
When he was told that ``not a single person of color'' had held the
position of chief counsel, press secretary or senior adviser on
domestic, economic and national security issues, Clinton was
momentarily and uncharacteristically speechless.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, you might be interested to know there were a
couple of people of color that I tried to get to do these jobs that
preferred other jobs in the administration,'' Clinton said, not
naming any staffer. ``They had ... jobs they liked better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can tell you is I have never not tried to recruit
minorities for any job that was open in the White House, and I've
never followed a quota system,'' the president added.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is at work on a book about race, as a follow-up to the
national dialogue on race he initiated two years ago, though he
said Wednesday he didn't know when he will finish the book. ``I've
got a day job, you know,'' the president quipped.
</P>
<P>
   The president bluntly denied that his comments at last week's
meeting of the World Trade Organization _ during which Clinton
defended the concerns of labor unions and environmentalists _ was
designed to boost Gore with those campaign constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's wrong,'' Clinton said flatly, adding that his
administration is committed to free global trade, with provisions
made to protect workers and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   When given an opportunity to criticize the health-care proposal
of Gore's opponent, former New Jersey Senator Bill Bradley, Clinton
demurred.
</P>
<P>
   The president criticized the failure of Congress to back health
care reform and spoke at length about the plan the Clintons had
proposed. But he would not discuss the competing proposals made by
his vice president and Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get in the middle of the Gore-Bradley
campaign,'' Clinton said, chuckling a little. ``I know you want me
to, but I'm not going to do that for you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
