<HEADER>
A3348 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOK-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      12-08 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOKS: OF WRITERS VS. PUBLISHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   They've undoubtedly been lamenting about one another since the
first author scratched some signs on someone else's cave wall, thus
creating the first publisher, and they'll very likely continue to
do so well into the millennium beyond the next. Since book
publishing has become list tickled _ this year the 100 best
nonfiction books written in English; last year the top 100 novels _
how about tabulating the top accusations that writers make against
publishers? And vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   But which comes first, the authors' complaints or the
publishers'? Do they have a cause and effect upon one another?
Whatever, they need one another the way Pinocchio needed his
elastic nose. And although they often sound whiny when carping
about one another, their grievances are usually not
inconsequential, for nearly always the issues involve pride,
literary fame and, of course, fortune. No waggery about any of
this, particularly if one lives the loneliness of a writer's life
and depends on putting words on paper for a living.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a column of analytic interpretation, nor is it based
on a survey. Rather it is a collection of plaintive pleas, gathered
from listening. If the inferential results seem a bit loaded on the
writers' behalf it is because so many writers seem to have one or
more of the same complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Publishers' complaints, on the other hand, are more particular
of certain writers, rather than the breed in general. And it's a
generic column, with no names, since the complaints, no matter how
legitimate, seem piddling when a name is attached.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest writer outrage of all is lavished on the ``no books
in the stores'' complaint. The novel or nonfiction work has
received a flourish of rave reviews; the touring author has been
interviewed so much on television and radio that the writer is
expecting his or her own groupies like professional basketball
players and, woe, there are not enough books in the stores, and
sometimes not any, when the customers ask for them.
</P>
<P>
   That can be the gallows for a book, and no publisher has ever
been able to come up with a proper excuse for that other than to
blame it on the delivery service, which is rather like saying the
check is in the mail but the post office lost it.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``the book as orphan'' ailment. That is, in the
incestuous and mercurial business of book publishing, editors pop
from house to house with such apparent regularity that a writer who
signs up with one editor finds that midway through authorship (or
just as ghastly, at the moment of publication) the editor has
vanished like a ghost, and the book is in sort of a publishing
black hole. In short, an orphan.
</P>
<P>
   A subtext to this is the ``no one home'' problem. The author
calls the editor, but there's no one at the other end of the phone
wire, and no one bothers to call back. (This allegation is
sometimes leveled at the author's agent as well, increasing the
degree of frustration.)
</P>
<P>
   No writer, except perhaps some authors of blockbusters, ever
thinks their publishers print enough copies of books. And worse,
writers say, although they seldom prove it, their publishers
actually print fewer copies then they've promised. It has a nice
bumper sticker sound: ``Promise 50,000; print 15,000.''
</P>
<P>
   One could go on. Some writers say they're supposed to get their
royalty statements every six months, but there's always a
three-month delay, so they actually obtain one every nine months.
Willingness or unwillingness to be flexible on covers; not enough
say over jacket copy.
</P>
<P>
   Both greatly irritate authors, although their say in those
matters depends partly on how tightly their agents have structured
their contract. Moreover, few publishers will finally print book
jackets or flap copy that truly offend the author's sensibilities.
Editing? Forget it. Authors complain about copy editing, and
attribute the bad editing to too few editors or lack of editing
talent or, sometimes, laziness. (See below for publishers'
response.)
</P>
<P>
   And, as they must, many complaints simply come down to money
matters: lack of ads, stinted book tours, too little money put into
marketing. Why bother paying for a book if you're not going to
spend any money promoting it, making it work in the marketplace?
</P>
<P>
   Publishers' complaints journey between the weighty and the
perplexed, with a stopover at the absurd. Writers don't meet their
deadlines; they don't deliver the big dreams that were promised and
anticipated in the book's original proposal; the work has slacked
off from the author's previous book; some authors are just
recycling old situations, in essence just repeating themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Editors are often bewildered when the author is not responsive
to their editing suggestions, their pleas to shorten or clarify
work and then become outraged when a reviewer says the book has
been poorly edited. (It must be noted here that a book is the
author's work, and should be published the way the author, not the
editor, wants it, even if that's not wise.) Writers don't always
have the material to substantiate blockbuster assertions in
nonfiction books.
</P>
<P>
   Writers refuse to accept the publishers' assertion that they try
as hard as they can to make their books work and that the writers'
own expectations might be out of whack with reality. (Hello!
Writers know that publishers have a pecking order, so authors are
not treated equally.)
</P>
<P>
   Publishers also complain that they are misunderstood, that their
writers simply don't accept the fact that Regis and Larry King are
competitors, and that if the writer is lucky enough to be booked on
one show she will not be on the other; that there are about 50,000
books published annually, and that a great many of those are
competing for the same air time and the same book review space.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many publishers' complaints border on the farcical. For
instance, they say that some writers gouge publishers on their book
tours by insisting on taking along a spouse or other companion at a
publisher's expense; other authors run up huge phone, food and bar
bills and demand limousines on tour.
</P>
<P>
   There are writers who try to press publishing houses into
publishing work by their significant others, which usually isn't
very good. One female writer always managed to cry during
interviews on tours, which didn't particularly bother the publisher
but she also brought on tears just as easily at business meetings
to get perks and that was vexing.
</P>
<P>
   This same author also refused to sign paperback books during a
book tour, insisting the fibers from the poorer quality paper
wafted up into her nasal passages. Which also made her cry.
</P>
<P>
   So there it is. A sampler list of outrages, some terrible and
some merely preposterous. But combatant as they can sometimes be,
writers and publishers do have one common complaint: Why can't
their latest work be on Oprah?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 1925EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
