u e BC-PORT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      12-08 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PORT OF LAST RESORT': HOLOCAUST STORIES FROM SOME OF THE LUCKIER
ONES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(th) 
 By ANITA GATES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Early in ``Schindler's List,'' Steven Spielberg's
eloquent Holocaust film, an impeccably dressed couple _ he in a
bowler, she in a fur coat _ are thrown out of their grand Cracow
apartment and herded to the ghetto. After carrying their bags up
their new building's narrow stairs, they find a tiny apartment, a
crying baby and half a dozen other new occupants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be worse,'' says the wife in a faint voice, straining
for optimism. Her husband looks at her as if she's insane. ``Tell
me,'' he shouts, ``how on earth could it possibly be worse?''
</P>
<P>
   Even a 10-year-old seeing the movie could give him the terrible
answer to that question and warn him that he is certain to find out
soon. That's what makes the scene so painful. That is also what
makes Joan Grossman and Paul Rosdy's documentary ``The Port of Last
Resort'' less powerful than it might have been.
</P>
<P>
   The film is about the 20,000 or so European Jews who fled the
Nazis between 1939 and 1941 by going to Shanghai, where they found
less than a perfect new life. The filmmakers describe it as a story
of survival, but the narrative stresses the difficulties rather
than the strength of the human spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arrival the immigrants were transported on trucks to a camp
of sorts, where they were served little more than noodle soup.
There was only a public bath. (One woman recalls almost being late
for her own wedding because it was the first time in months she'd
had a warm bath and she wanted to enjoy the luxury as long as she
could.)
</P>
<P>
   There were few jobs, so the unemployed men spent their days
playing cards and listening to the radio. Eventually the Japanese,
who took control of Shanghai in 1941, created a Jewish ghetto there
and thousands suffered great deprivation.
</P>
<P>
   This must have been a traumatizing experience for refugees of
all ages. Imagine the relief of escape and the hope of renewal,
only to find a new set of difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with ``The Port of Last Resort'' making those
points, of course, is that its words and images _ refugees'
letters, home movies, archival footage and present-day interviews _
have to compete with harrowing scenes from a host of other
Holocaust films, fictional and documentary. The overwhelming tone
of this film, while appreciating the difficulties, should have been
about how lucky the survivors were. Wouldn't the inmates of the
German camps have loved to have problems like unemployment and
boredom?
</P>
<P>
   This is not to diminish the tremendous hardships the Shanghai
refugees endured, but their story might have better been told
through fiction, having one person or one family's story provide
the kind of emotional close-up that drives such experiences home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Port of Last Resort'' is being shown at Anthology Film
Archives with ``Memory of Berlin,'' John Burgan's well-meaning but
unsatisfying documentary about his search for his biological
parents. Unfortunately Burgan, who often sounds bored by his own
voice-over, describes his search in painfully obvious terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happened to that other baby, Matthew?'' he asks
rhetorically. (Matthew was the name his German mother gave him at
birth; his British adoptive parents named him John.) ``Nature or
nurture: the question every adoptee asks sooner or later,'' he
intones as if this were a new thought. But he draws no conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Although Burgan finds his birth mother and learns about his
father, these discoveries have less impact on screen than do his
home movies of childhood vacations.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE PORT OF LAST RESORT: Zuflucht in Shanghai'
</P>
<P>
   Written, directed, produced and edited by Joan Grossman and Paul
Rosdy; director of photography, Wolfgang Lehner; music by John
Zorn; released by the National Center for Jewish Film. Running
time: 79 minutes. Shown with a 76-minute film, John Burgan's
``Memory of Berlin.'' These films are not rated. At the Anthology
Film Archives.
</P>
<P>
   WITH THE VOICES OF: Barbara Sukowa, Otto Tausig, Jaromir Borek,
Erika Deutinger, Fritz von Friedl and Brigitta Furgler.
</P>
<P>
   INTERVIEWS WITH: Fred Fields, Ernest Heppner, Illo Heppner and
Siegmar Simon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 1926EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3350 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-INTERVIEW-HNS     12-08 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-INTERVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CAUTIOUS BRADLEY DOESN'T RULE OUT TAX HIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times news service clients)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c. 1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTCLAIR, N.J. _ Whatever else he may be, former New Jersey
Sen. Bill Bradley said Wednesday he is no Walter Mondale.
</P>
<P>
   Mondale, the vice president under Jimmy Carter and the
Democratic presidential nominee in 1984, doomed his campaign in a
debate withg$uesi &UR; 4:K/4:Ygan when he said that as president he
would raise taxes. Reagan, if re-elected, would end up doing the
same, Mondale said, but would not be frank about it. Reagan went on
to swamp Mondale and win a second term.
</P>
<P>
   With Bradley refusing to rule out a tax increase to pay for his
ambitious universal health care proposal, the former New York
Knicks basketball star was shaping up as this election's Mondale in
the eyes of some Democratic strategists.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview on Wednesday, Bradley said it wasn't so.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be Walter Mondale, I'd have to go to the American people
and say `I'm going to raise your taxes,''' Bradley said. ``That's
different than what I'm saying. I think there's going to be no need
for a tax increase because I think we're going to have sufficient
levels of economic growth'' that will pay the extra cost of
Bradley's health plan.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, ``it would be irresponsible to say `no new
taxes,''' Bradley said. ``And that's my position. That's quite
different (from Mondale).''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's health care plan calls for universal coverage of all
uninsured children and adults through subsidies for those who
cannot afford insurance, as well as opening up the health plan for
federal employees to others. He estimated the annual cost of the
program at between $55 billion and $65 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, Bradley's rival for the Democratic
presidential nomination, had blasted the Bradley plan, saying it
would hurt more people than it would help and might lead to a tax
increase. Gore strategists reveled as Bradley seemed to tie himself
up in knots on whether he would _ or wouldn't _ raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore himself on Wednesday appeared to signal a retreat on
tax-bashing, saying in Washington that while he would not envision
a need for raising taxes while the economy remains solid, ``nobody
has a crystal ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley on Wednesday said that as a presidential candidate,
``you have to be honest with people and tell them what the reality
is out there. Who can predict what's going to happen in seven
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Economic growth undercuts the need for tax increases, Bradley
said. And in a recession, a tax cut is far preferable to a tax
hike, he added.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, ``if you are in charge of a multitrillion
(dollar) economy,'' a ``no-new-taxes'' pledge would be
``irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's avoidance of a pledge against tax increases ``means we're
in the same position,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, speaking to reporters at Montclair High School in the
affluent New York suburb where he lives, said his approach to the
presidency is to ``take this period of unprecedented prosperity and
use it in a way that strengthens the underlying productivity of the
country by making people better educated and healthier.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, ``I think Gore is more cautious,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Saying there are 45 million with no health insurance and 35
million with inadequate insurance, ``I view this as a big problem
and I offer a big solution,'' Bradley said. Gore ``has been much
more cautious, simply throwing money at a failed system.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to account for the different approaches, Bradley said that
Gore ``might be so cautious because he doesn't want to change
anything. If you don't change, you don't grow. And you contract.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The status quo is a momentary moment. If you're not
moving forward, you're falling back. That might be where he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's chief spokesman, Chris Lehane, said that as vice
president, ``it's been Al Gore on the court scoring points for
working families on the economy, the environment health care and
education.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Lehane said, ``Sen. Bradley has been on the bench
or in the stands, watching all of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bradley is competitive with Gore in New Hampshire,
which holds the nation's first primary on Feb. 1, he is well behind
Gore almost everywhere else, including California.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley insisted he has a shot in California, which holds its
primary March 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have a sense of California,'' Bradley said. ``The
very things I'm emphasizing in my campaign are important to
California, things like technological change, free and open trade,
environmental protection, diversity as a strength and not a
weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, Gore has won the endorsements of Gov. Gray Davis
and both senators, Sen. Dianne Feinstein and Sen. Barbara Boxer. In
addition, 20 of the state's Democratic House members have endorsed
the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Bradley said, the campaign there will not get
under way in earnest until after the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also said in the interview that:
</P>
<P>
   _ He would not be interested in being Gore's running mate if the
vice president wins the nomination. Asked whether he would endorse
Gore as the nominee, Bradley said: ``I'm a Democrat so, sure, I
want a Democrat to win, not a Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   _ He opposes same-sex marriages, but is against a ballot
initiative in California that would bar any official recognition of
gay marriages performed in other states. ``It's divisive and it
contributes to stigmatization'' of gays. ``In a world where gay
bashing has increased, I'm not going to be a party to a thing that
leads to that kind of action.''
</P>
<P>
   _ He supports moves in many jurisdictions to give gay couples
the same legal and financial rights as married couples.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Looking back at his long career as a basketball star and 18-year
veteran of the Senate, Bradley said voters ultimately would judge
him as a public servant, not a sports celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who knew me as a basketball and paid attention to my
work in the Senate didn't vote for me because I was a basketball
player,'' Bradley said. He won votes ``because of the work I was
doing, the vision I laid out for my state and the country.''
</P>
<P>
   As a former player for the Knicks, ``I have nothing to apologize
for,'' he said. ``It was a great life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
