<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3351 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TIMES-CAPSULE-NYT &LR;      12-08 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMES-CAPSULE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENSHRINING THE FLOTSAM AND JETSAM OF A MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   Jerry Adler is a senior editor at Newsweek.  
 (bl)  
 By JERRY ADLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As any archaeologist can tell you enviously, we live
now in a golden age of realia: the artifacts of daily life, the
clothes, tools, toys and decorations that are the unacknowledged
substrate of a civilization. In other words, a golden age of stuff,
not merely because we have so much more of it but because we invest
it with so much significance.
</P>
<P>
   As an intriguing new exhibition at the American Museum of
Natural History observes in passing, it is the realia of ancient
societies that captures our imagination these days. Who hasn't
wondered if Roman wines were really any good? Was it worse to live
in a hovel, or a yurt? What did people in the Middle Ages use for
diapers?
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, ``Capturing Time: The New York Times Capsule,''
represents an effort to anticipate and answer precisely those types
of questions from citizens of the next millennium. While seeking
suggestions for objects to be entombed for the next 1,000 years,
the editors of The New York Times Magazine, which sponsored the
show and underwrote construction of the container, turned to
citizens of the archetypal suburban town of Fountain, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from a sample on display at the museum, they did not
have to reach very far from where they were sitting to come up with
artifacts that evoked our civilization: cell phones and beepers,
Beanie Babies and barbed wire, a hood ornament from a Chevrolet and
a Purple Heart.
</P>
<P>
   Also on display through March 26 are the efforts of a number of
reporters and photographers, staff members of The Times and
freelancers, who canvassed New York at 9:09 a.m. on Sept. 9
(9/9/99) and found New Yorkers going about their predictable
rounds. One enterprising journalist snared for posterity a copy of
the lunch reservation list from the Four Seasons, proving that fame
of the sort achieved by, say, Barry Diller, might not be so
fleeting after all.
</P>
<P>
   There are some books _ ``Peyton Place'' and ``Go Tell It on the
Mountain,'' among others _ but the show implicitly acknowledges
what most visitors already know: that if you could choose one
volume to convey contemporary American culture, it probably would
not be a work of literature; it would be a Williams-Sonoma catalog.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, Spam is Spam, and you may find yourself curiously
unmoved to come face to face with a can of the stuff destined to
spend the next 1,000 years immortalized in thermal-gel insulation
and argon gas. The more interesting part of the show is devoted to
the practical question of building a time capsule: How do you keep
it safe without burying it so far that it will never be found?
</P>
<P>
   It's worth the trip just to view the solution chosen by The
Times, a stainless-steel sculpture by the Spanish architect
Santiago Calatrava. His design is a highly mathematical, abstract
symmetrical form, likened to a flower or an origami, representing
time as what the artist calls ``crystallized movement.'' Its
curving hollows can be packed with about 50 cubic feet of objects
and data. Its contents will be chosen from among the objects in the
exhibition and from elsewhere before the capsule is sealed next
spring and put on permanent display on the museum grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Calatrava's design represented a novel approach to
avoiding the fate of most time capsules, which is to be sealed and
promptly forgotten. An object of great beauty, the editors felt,
would always command attention _ even if it is a pretty inefficient
shape for a container _ and future generations would be badly
misled if they concluded that the current civilization valued
beauty over efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Many artists were invited to consider how to preserve and
identify time capsules, and their solutions make for provocative
viewing. Maya Lin suggested a granite slab in Central Park at the
center of a spiral of English oak trees.
</P>
<P>
   Jaron Lanier's electrifying proposal was to transcribe data into
a code based on the four molecular constituents of DNA, synthesize
the appropriate sequence and introduce it into the genome of a
cockroach. With an appropriate breeding program, he said, about
three gigabytes of data could be disseminated throughout New York
and preserved through enough cockroach generations to take it into
the fourth millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Why not use life? The tiny double helix has outlasted the
mightiest mountains. Only yards away from ``Capturing Time'' are
the museum's great halls of the dinosaurs. They left us only bones
and footprints, but those are still around after 100 million years.
Even preserved in argon gas and stainless steel, does anyone think
Furbies will do as well?
</P>
</TEXT>
