<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3354 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SCHOOL-CHEATING09-COX     12-08 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-CHEATING09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MORE TEACHER CHEATING EXPECTED IN THE FUTURE
 &HT;    420&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Many more school systems will erupt in testing
scandals like the one just uncovered in New York, friends and foes
of high-stakes testing agreed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After a 17-month probe of how state-mandated tests were given in
the the nation's largest school system, special investigator Ed
Stanick recommended action Wednesday against 52 educators. All were
suspended, giving school officials time to consider his
recommendation that two principals and 10 teachers be fired and
another 40 disciplined for using illegal or unethical methods to
raise their students' test scores.
</P>
<P>
   Those methods used included verbal hints to students by teachers
using lists of answers, and the erasure and correction of some
incorrect answers. The vast majority of the city's 70,000 teachers
and principals were not involved.
</P>
<P>
   New York uses test scores not just to judge how much students
know, but how good a job is being done by their school and by the
principals and teachers. Every state except Iowa has decided to
require all its public schools to administer at least some
standardized academic exams.
</P>
<P>
   They are called ``high-stakes'' tests because the scores can
affect both staff members' pay and assignments and students' hopes
for promotion or graduation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the latest and apparently biggest so far in a growing
trend of cheating to raise test scores,'' said Robert Schaefer of
Sanibel, Fla., spokesman for FairTest, an organization skeptical of
standardized testing.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to other scattered accusations of cheating by
educators in a few classrooms in Connecticut, Massachusetts,
Virginia, Ohio, Arizona, Maryland and Texas in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, it's likely to accelerate,'' Schaefer said.
``When the test score is all that matters in evaluating educational
quality, too many teachers will produce the scores they need by
hook or by crook.''
</P>
<P>
   Some school officials deny that cheating is widespread. They
said that probes of some suspect results determined that almost all
testing errors were due to mistakes or carelessness, rather than an
intent to distort the results.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, parents and the public need the tests in order to hold
schools accountable for results, said educational psychologist John
R. Stone of East Tennessee State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plainly there are strong pressures on schools to do well on
exams _ and there should be,'' Stone said. ``The cheating is not an
argument for lessening the emphasis upon accountability, but for
having tighter controls on the tests.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   States could hire outsiders to give the tests, Stone said. If
that is too expensive, random test sites and results could be
``sampled by people who are entirely independent of the schools,''
Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Stanick's report said some New York educators cheated as
blatantly as those involved in a recent scandal in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the other behavior was of the more ambiguous kind
spotted in many school districts in recent years. In one survey of
Kentucky teachers, one-third said that they sometimes offer hints,
recommend that wrong answers be revised or rephrase questions on
exams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to envision a a teacher (in the lower grades) who
spends her whole day helping students, glancing at a test answer
and saying 'Now, Johnny, you know we've talked about this
before','' said Mark Musick of Atlanta, president of the Southern
Regional Education Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, if you have more high-stakes testing, you are going to
have the statistical probability that you'll have someone somewhere
cheating,'' Musick said. ``But there are processes and precautions
that could identify this, just as they did a few years ago in North
Carolina, and apparently just did again in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
