<HEADER>
A3355 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BRAZIL-COELHO-2NDTAKE     12-08 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-COELHO-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 RIO DE JANEIRO: great communicator.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For his part Coelho complains more about booksellers who insist
on placing his works in their New Age or self-help sections rather
than on the fiction shelves. He does not gripe much, though, about
the critical hammering he often receives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the critics are right when they say my style seems
simple and superficial,'' he said. ``I am an extremely direct
person. I dry up the language to the maximum precisely to be able
to let the reader play with his imagination. But I preserve the
symbolism that is beyond the words. That is the language of the
future, and I am its vanguard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I write a first draft, I tend to overexplain, because I
feel insecure, because I'm not telling the story well,'' he said.
``So the rest is cutting, cutting, cutting. Instead of describing a
desert landscape with all its rocks, I will just say, `They were in
a desert.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to write `Ulysses,' but if you ask people if
anyone has read all of `Ulysses,' no one has,'' he continued.
``Joyce has become the parameter of a whole academic system for the
20th century, so when I come along with this more direct language,
of course I am going to provoke a reaction. I am not writing in
accordance with the establishment, but I am certain that in a few
years my language will prevail, because it is a modern language.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in his homeland Coelho first came to attention in the early
1970s not as a novelist but as a pop music lyricist, writing more
than 70 songs with the rock star Raul Seixas, described by Coelho
as ``the Jim Morrison of Brazil.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a bitter experience in the record business that set
Coelho on the road to writing fiction. He was an executive for CBS
Records, now Sony, when he was unexpectedly fired in an office
purge and, with ``the money I had saved up from publishing
royalties'' and nothing better to do, decided to travel.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point in his life, ``my rite of passage,'' he said,
came when he underwent the trial of walking the medieval Road to
Santiago in Spain, an experience recounted in the book that was
initially titled ``The Diary of a Magus'' and is now called ``The
Pilgrimage.'' His true spiritual home, he concluded afterward, was
a mystical brand of the Roman Catholicism in which he had been
raised and which now suffuses his books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to be a good Catholic, but I am not a Catholic writer,
like Graham Greene, for example, or as they tried to make Morris
West out to be,'' he said. His multilingual Web site
(paulocoelho.com) includes Buddhist, Hindu, Jewish and Muslim texts
and images.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that Catholicism is the best religion, but it is the
religion that is in my roots,'' he said. ``I believe in God, that I
am not here by chance, and that since I am here, I should do
something. I no longer have to ask, `What am I doing here?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
