<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3357 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ULLMAN-DIRECTS-NYT &LR;      12-08 1384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ULLMAN-DIRECTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIV ULLMANN DIRECTS A BERGMAN TALE OF TWISTS AND ENTANGLEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By SARAH LYALL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKHOLM _ ``His secrets are his secrets,'' the actress, author
and director Liv Ullmann said of the complicated inner life of
Ingmar Bergman, the 81-year-old Swedish director. ``What we have to
do is use our own experiences, our own lives, our own secrets and
our perceptions of Bergman to make the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie in question is ``The Faithless,'' and it is a project
thick with the pain and unresolved emotion of love and loss, in
life as well as fiction. Bergman wrote the script, about a doomed
love affair that has haunted him for more than five decades, but it
is Ms. Ullmann, his former lover and a woman who says she knows him
as well as anyone in the world, who is bringing it to life as
director.
</P>
<P>
   The personal tangles don't end there. The Swedish actors Lena
Endre and Thomas Hanzon, who have long worked in the theater under
Bergman's direction and who in the film portray a couple whose
marriage is destroyed by her affair, were married to each other
until about two years ago. They are now divorced and each has a new
partner, but there is no denying the pain of their shared past.
</P>
<P>
   If the swirling emotions aren't complicated enough, ``The
Faithless,'' which is to be released in the next year, is full of
enough darkness and moral agonizing to satisfy any Bergman
enthusiast. With Ms. Ullmann as director, it is perhaps a less
despairing film that it would have been if directed by Bergman
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's darker than I am; he's more pessimistic,'' Ms. Ullmann
said over a recent lunch of grilled salmon and spring water in a
cafeteria near the studio in Stockholm where some of the interior
scenes were filmed. ``But sometimes it's sunny where he sees rain.
I am truly hopeful that he's going to be happy with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of ``The Faithless'' takes place in the office of an
elderly film director, meant to be a stand-in for Bergman himself,
who sits at his desk, struggling to write about a disastrous affair
from his past with a woman who has long since died. He is
interrupted by the sudden arrival of an actress, played by Ms.
Endre _ it is left ambiguous whether she is a product of his
fantasies or is real _ who takes up the story as if it had happened
to her, as if she is the woman from long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Then the scene shifts to the past, and the narrative reveals
that all the protagonists in the fraught affair _ husband, wife and
lover _ are faithless, to themselves and to one another. The movie
is meant to show how moments of passion can yield years of
unhappiness, and its themes are utterly recognizable to all
involved in the production.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why the script is so fascinating,'' said Krister
Henriksson, the ruggedly handsome Swede who plays the Bergman-esque
lover in the film. ``This is a specific event in Ingmar's life, but
everybody has had similar things in one way or another in our own
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Henriksson spoke on a day in November when Ms. Ullmann was
directing a pivotal scene, in which the lover confronts the wife.
Emotions on the set were raw, but Henriksson, 53, was calm as he
munched on various kinds of Swedish crackers during a break from
his dramatic tete-a-tete with Ms. Endre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the name `Faithless': in one way that is what all actors
and directors are,'' Henriksson said. ``When you're doing a
production, it's a kind of love affair, and then you go away and
it's over. Of course sometimes you mix the two.''
</P>
<P>
   Henriksson has done his share of mixing work and love in the
past. (``I did it, and I had to get a divorce,'' he said.) So has
Ms. Endre. But both said that the project served as a sharp
reminder about the perils of being too carried away to remember
your responsibilities, especially to your children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been married twice and have two children, and I'm
familiar with all these problems,'' said Ms. Endre, 44, who is one
of Sweden's best-known actresses, having appeared extensively in
films, on television and at the Royal Dramatic Theater in
Stockholm. ``You think, `Is it really worth it to follow all this
passion?'''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, she said, would have to be no. ``I've had my
affairs, and I'm never going to have an affair again,'' Ms. Endre
said.
</P>
<P>
   As difficult as it was to work with her former husband in a film
whose story loosely parallels their own experience, Ms. Endre said,
the film has helped lay to rest some of the issues remaining
between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are friends, and that is the most important thing,'' she
said. ``It's been good in some ways, because we know each other so
well. Maybe it's helped us to talk through difficult things that we
didn't talk through before.''
</P>
<P>
   What of Bergman?
</P>
<P>
   The great director _ whose passions, doubts and moral wrestlings
have been well explored in movies like ``Scenes From a Marriage,''
``Autumn Sonata,'' ``Wild Strawberries'' and ``Cries and Whispers''
_ spent the fall directing a film for Swedish television and is now
preparing a production of ``Mary Stuart'' for the Royal Dramatic
Theater. He made a point, Ms. Ullmann said, of not interfering with
her vision of ``The Faithless.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ullmann is about to turn 61, and much of her adulthood has
been tied up with Bergman. They lived together in his house on a
remote island off the coast of Sweden for five years, when she was
in her early 20s and he was in his early 40s, and they had a
daughter, Linn. Ms. Ullmann has also worked with the director for
decades, appearing in a number of his films, and knows how he feels
and how he thinks, up to a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are his private confessions,'' Ms. Ullmann said of
Bergman's script. ``But he has given only lines. We have to read
what we will into the lines. I have built on my knowledge of him,
knowing him so well as a writer and director, as a father, as a
friend, as an enemy and as a lover. And then I build on my own
knowledge as a woman, as someone who's had love affairs and broken
up from love affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is as much about multiple points of view, about seeing
things from someone else's perspective, as anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the story from before,'' Ms. Ullmann said of Bergman's
love affair, which took place long before she met him. ``But if I
sat down with you and told it to you, and he sat down with you, you
would get a very different story. I think he's been very brave
about this. I think maybe he wanted it to be seen from another
perspective. He's curious about other people. He's a cannibal. He
wants to see things _ in the good and bad sense _ from other
people's points of view.''
</P>
<P>
   The passion in the film is presented as urgent, reckless and
all-consuming. ``The moment he falls in love with her, it's
forever,'' Ms. Ullmann said. ``He gives himself to her, skin,
heart, everything. He gives himself 100 percent, even more than she
does, because she has to think of her husband and daughter. But
he's free, as Bergman has always been free, to love. When love
comes, it comes.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Ullmann forgiveness is all-important. ``It never ends
well when you hurt a lot of people, but in their own ways they ask
for forgiveness,'' she said of the characters in the film. Though
she made it clear that she did not mean to speak for Bergman, who
declined to be interviewed, she added that perhaps the movie was
his way of seeking forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I feel is that I allow the people in the movie to forgive
each other in one way or another,'' she said. ``You can be forgiven
as long as you find a reason to say I'm sorry, somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   If the film is about the heartbreaks of the past, it is also
about an old man's terrible realization that the exquisite pain of
such heartbreaks will never come to him again.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you grow older, you're face to face with yourself,'' Ms.
Ullmann said. ``This is the older Bergman looking back at things he
experienced long ago but won't experience again, because his body
isn't the same, his eyes aren't the same, his skin isn't the same.
He's not the same. Deep down you long to experience it once more,
to have your heart go that way once more, to have your body go that
way once more. And it's not going to happen, because you're totally
alone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 1934EST &QL; 
