<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3363 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TVANUKE09-COX     12-08 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVANUKE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TVA to produce key atomic bomb material
 &HT;    By John Harmon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Agreeing to turn plowshares into swords, so to speak,
the Tennessee Valley Authority directors Wednesday voted to approve
a contract to manufacture a key component for atomic bombs at the
Watts Bar nuclear power plant in southwest Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the first time in U.S. history that a commercial
reactor will be used to produce material for nuclear bombs.
Tritium, the ``H'' in H-bombs, is a hydrogen isotope that greatly
enhances the explosive power of bombs.
</P>
<P>
   TVA officials defended their agreement to provide the material
to the U.S. Department of Energy as nothing more than a
continuation of the federal utility's long history of assisting in
U.S. defense projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We provided power to the Manhattan Project at Oak Ridge and we
provided power to a munitions plant in Alabama during World War
II,'' said TVA spokesman John Moulton.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan Project produced the atomic bombs dropped on Japan
in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   But anti-nuclear activists contend the decision to use a
nonmilitary reactor hurts America's standing in the effort to
curtail nuclear proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   ``On what grounds do we now have to tell other nations like
Iraq, Iran, India and Pakistan that they shouldn't blend their
weapons programs with their civilian programs?'' asked Mary Olson
of the Nuclear Information Resource Center's Southeast office in
Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   No other nation is officially known to be using commercial
reactors to make bomb materials. Olson said evidence has surfaced
that Pakistan utilized plutonium from power plants to build bombs,
and an article in Jane's Intelligence Review last year suggested
India obtained tritium for its nuclear tests from a commercial
reactor.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Bailey, a TVA vice president for engineering who headed the
yearlong contract negotiations, said the agency relied on a report
prepared for the White House by various federal agencies and issued
in 1998 that concluded that the deal did not violate any
international laws or treaties.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the issue is touchy with American allies.
</P>
<P>
   Several foreign nations that export uranium to the U.S.,
including Canada and Australia, are forbidden to sell the fuel if
it is used to make bombs. Therefore, TVA was forced to contract
with the sole U.S. source for enriched uranium fuel to power the
Watts Bar reactor, said Moulton.
</P>
<P>
   Because tritium decays fairly rapidly, it must be periodically
replenished in nuclear warheads. The DOE has not manufactured the
isotope in several years because of the 1988 shutdown of its
notoriously flawed reactors at the Savannah River Site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need this material to maintain the safety, security and
reliability of the nuclear stockpile,'' said Matthew Donoghue, a
DOE spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   DOE estimates it will need new tritium by 2005, meaning the
first tritium-producing rods would need to be inserted into the
reactor by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the contract, DOE will pay TVA $25 million to
make ``things ready'' for the project and then pay as much as $10
million annually for tritium production, said TVA's Moulton.
</P>
<P>
   While Watts Bar will be the primary source of tritium, the
contract allows TVA to shift production to its Sequoyah station
near Chattanooga if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
