<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3364 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BELARUS-ART-47     12-08 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BELARUS-ART-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA AND BELARUS SIGN ANOTHER UNION AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By MICHAEL WINES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After years of negotiations _ and, many say, calculated
delay _ Russia and Belarus agreed in principle on Wednesday to form
an economic and political confederation modeled roughly after the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
   But even after a glittering Kremlin ceremony to confirm the
accord, and the official predictions that the union could lead to a
larger and revitalized Slavic alliance, it seemed doubtful that
Russian leaders would carry out many of the alliance's grand
designs soon, if ever.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Belarus, Alexander Lukashenko, hinted as much
after the ceremony. ``Nothing obstructs the setting up of a
union-state but the lack of will on the part of the Russian
leadership,'' he said at a news conference. ``When there is a will,
we will resolve all the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukashenko and Russian President Boris Yeltsin said they expect
their parliaments to ratify the so-called Union Treaty immediately.
Leaders of the Russian Parliament said they would take up the
document at a special session on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Without waiting for that, Lukashenko and Yeltsin announced a
sheaf of related initiatives, chief among them the creation of a
joint army district stretching from Moscow to the border separating
Belarus from Ukraine and Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Lukashenko, a frequent and bitter critic of the United States
and NATO, said the new district's goal would be to defend against
an invasion from the West, and he suggested that the issue of
returning Russian nuclear weapons to Belarus was open to debate.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, however, said the confederation would keep the two
nations separate and was not aimed at any particular nation.
</P>
<P>
   It was exactly eight years ago, at a lodge in a national forest
in Belarus near the border with Poland, that Yeltsin and leaders of
other major Soviet republics signed an accord asserting their
governments' right to become independent of communist rule.
</P>
<P>
   The Belavezh treaty was the death blow to the Soviet Union,
which was officially dissolved three weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, speaking clearly but briefly becoming unsteady as he
fumbled with cards bearing his remarks, called the unification pact
``a remarkable day in the centuries-old history of the fraternal
peoples.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts almost uniformly disagreed. They said the Kremlin
largely sought the treaty ceremony as a flag-waving boost to its
candidates in mid-December parliamentary elections. The agreement
also sends a message to the West that Russia has no intention of
ceding still more influence on its western flank to Europe and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Substantively, though, the union treaty is long on flourishes
and all but devoid of political union, at least anytime soon. In
many respects, it differs little from an earlier statement of
principles the two men signed in early 1996.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The treaty envisions two independent nations, first developing
common tax, customs and other economic codes, and then, by 2005 or
so, a common currency, defense policy and other laws.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Russia and Belarus would be citizens of the new
state, but retain their current citizenship and governments. A new
parliament and executive council would oversee unspecified joint
issues.
</P>
<P>
   But that is a long way off. Even with quick ratification,
legislative changes might not begin until 2001, and major
integration would require constitutional changes which, in Russia,
are by no means assured.
</P>
<P>
   The pact also poses internal political dangers. The treaty
signing prompted some Russian republics like Tatarstan _ now
regarded as ordinary provinces _ to warn that they will want the
same economic benefits and independent status as Belarus should the
confederation be realized.
</P>
<P>
   Should that happen, the treaty would have sped the dissolution
of the Russian Federation rather than the expanded influence it
envisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all practical purposes, a merger of the two states is not
in the offing,'' said Dimitri Tenin, the deputy director of the
Moscow office of the Carnegie Institute. ``We can have a union
treaty, we can have a unified council of ministers, or what have
you. But those will remain ceremonial bodies without any actual
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukashenko is the driving force behind the union treaty. A
barely reconstructed Communist, he favors rebuilding a new Russian
colossus _ and, few doubt, eventually leading it from the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years he has stumped in at least 16 Russian provinces,
preaching a politics of resentment over lost Soviet greatness that
won him a landslide victory in 1994 elections in Belarus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
