<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3372 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-HNS &LR;      12-08 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL, SYRIA TO RESUME TALKS IN WASHINGTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pressing for comprehensive Middle East peace,
President Clinton said Wednesday that Israel and Syria will resume
suspended talks next week and urged them to grasp the opportunity
to end generations of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pledged to ``spare neither time nor effort'' in helping
the Israelis and the Syrians come to some peace agreement but
warned there ``can be no illusion here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On all tracks the road ahead will be arduous, the task of
negotiating agreements will be difficult. Success is not
inevitable,'' the president said, announcing the breakthrough
during the opening remarks of his final news conference of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``Peace has long been within our sight. Today, it
is within our grasp and we must seize it.''
</P>
<P>
   The critical development on the Israeli-Syrian front comes as
the Israelis and Palestinians continue to press ahead with their
ambitious plan to develop a framework for a final agreement by
February, with a final accord by September.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he hopes resumption of talks between Israel and
Syria will lead to new negotiations with Lebanon as well. Israel
already has peace treaties with Arab neighbors Egypt and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister
Farouk al-Sharaa agreed to meet next week in Washington for one or
two days and then return to the Middle East. Negotiations will
continue in the region at a site yet to be named.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israelis and Syrians still need to make courageous decisions
in order to reach a just and lasting peace. But today's step is a
significant breakthrough, for it will allow them to deal with each
other face-to-face, and that is the only way to get there,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Peace talks between the two nations were suspended three years
ago after a wave of suicide bombings beset Israel. The resumption
of negotiations stalled when Syrian President Hafez Assad insisted
that Israel had previously agreed to return the Golan Heights, a
patch of Syrian land seized by Israel in the 1967 war. He demanded
the return of the occupied land before renewing negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the talks would resume ``from the point where they
left off'' _ which means there are no preconditions. However,
Barak, who was elected in May, said previously he would be willing
to return the Golan Heights as part of a peace pact with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough came after months of work by the administration
and a personal visit to the region by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright. She met with Assad on Tuesday and Barak on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really is a sense that there is a historical moment to
be seized,'' Albright said during an interview with CNN. She said
the talks would include four subjects: the withdrawal from the
Golan Heights, the content of a peace agreement such as exchanging
embassies and trade relations, the security arrangements and the
timetable.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said she came to the Middle East just to do an
assessment of the status of the various negotiation tracks as the
year ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I found...was a sense that the moment needed to be
seized. When I arrived in Damascus, I found a President Assad who
also seemed to understand the historical moment and I think showed
some flexibility in his approach. And then I came to Jerusalem
where I met with Prime Minister Barak who also was determined to
seize the moment,'' she said. ``There's just kind of a sense that
the time is right for these talks to come together but nobody has
any illusions about how difficult they're going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright reportedly brought Barak a clarification of Syria's
position on a range of issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There clearly is a unique opportunity,'' Barak said, speaking
in Jerusalem. ``We have so many other things to do than be deployed
for another generation or two along the borders and bury our
youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli-Syrian talks broke down in 1996 just as it appeared
they might be achieving some movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if the Syrian track picks up ...
quickly,'' said Reuven Hazan, a political analyst at Jerusalem's
Hebrew University. ``The Syrians are ready to move again and the
Syrian track, once it starts, could move very fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also sought to move the talks along between Israel and
the Syrians and Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before us is a task as clear as it is challenging,'' Clinton
said. ``As I told Prime Minister Barak and President Assad in a
phone conversation with them earlier today, they now bear a heavy
responsibility of bringing peace to the Israeli and Syrian
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he also still believed the Israelis and
Palestinians would come to a final accord. ``I'm convinced it is
possible to achieve that goal, to put an end to generations of
conflicts, to realize the aspirations of both the Israeli and the
Palestinian people, and I will do everything I can to help them in
that historic endeavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Barak and Palestinian Authority President
Yasser Arafat are hashing out the most delicate issues such as the
status of Jerusalem, the formation of a Palestinian state,
refugees, prisoners and settlements. Previous accords have given
the Palestinian Authority a measure of control over portions of the
West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's talks with Palestinians hit another hurdle this week
when the Palestinian negotiators walked out of talks, contending
that Jewish settlements on the West Bank must stop. Barak later
announced a suspension of new settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged the parties to overcome those hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israelis, Palestinians, Syrians and Lebanese will have to
confront fateful questions. They face hard choices. They will have
to stand firmly against all those who seek to derail the peace and
sadly there are still too many of them,'' Clinton said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporter Deborah Horan contributed from Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
