<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3376 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GA-DISABLED09-COX     12-08 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-DISABLED09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ga. group aims to cut waiting lists for social services
 &HT;    By Alan Judd
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Timothy Ryals couldn't function without his parents.
He needs them to bathe him, clothe him, feed him and change his
diapers.
</P>
<P>
   He is 23 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Ryals, of Marietta, Ga., is one of more than 12,000 Georgia
adults on waiting lists for community-based social services. Some
on the list have severe mental retardation. Others have profound
brain injuries. Most are elderly people who need assistance to stay
out of nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Gov. Roy Barnes promised to help.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes appointed a commission to study ways to reduce the
waiting lists, and pledged additional state money next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a first for Georgia,'' Barnes said before he swore in
the commission's 15 members. The panel, he said, will ``find better
ways to include all Georgians in all facets of community life,
regardless of any type of disability or impairment.''
</P>
<P>
   But he admonished the commission members: ``Don't spend a lot of
time defining the problem. I understand what the problem is. Help
me find the solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Those solutions will be expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating the waiting lists for 12,193 Georgians would cost
about $80.6 million a year, according to state officials and
advocacy groups. The state now spends $160.3 million to serve
17,771 people.
</P>
<P>
   At the current funding level, Georgia serves fewer people in
community-based programs per resident than any other state,
according to an advocacy group called Unlock the Waiting Lists. The
state ranks 47th in spending per citizen on services for the
developmentally disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Those adults need the greatest amount of new spending. Many are
now in institutions and are waiting to be placed in group homes or
other small facilities. Others live with family members, who often
have provided round-the-clock care for years, even decades.
</P>
<P>
   Helping those people _ such as Angela and Joe Ryals, Timothy's
parents _ would ultimately save state money, advocates for the
disabled say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you begin to provide families with a little help up front,
you prevent crisis,'' said Grace Fricks of Cleveland, Ga., a member
of the governor's commission. ``When people reach that breaking
point, that's when they need total care. That's when it gets so
expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   It may take four years to get services for all who need them,
said Annette Bowling, the commission's co-chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way we'll eliminate the whole waiting list this
(legislative) session,'' Bowling said. ``But we'll be working very
hard to eliminate it as quickly as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Barnes hopes to start paring the lists next year. In
his budget message to state legislators next month, Barnes will
suggest that they increase funding for the programs by a few
million dollars, said Renay Blumenthal, the governor's policy
director.
</P>
<P>
   The exact amount of new spending Barnes will seek hasn't been
determined, Blumenthal said. But she said the money could come from
the state's tobacco settlement, or possibly from federal sources.
The new funding would be available during the fiscal year that
begins July 1.
</P>
<P>
   It won't come too soon for Timothy Ryals and his family.
</P>
<P>
   Ryals has suffered from severe seizures of unknown origin since
he was a year old. He can neither talk nor control bodily
functions. Like a baby, he doesn't know not to pick up broken glass
or not to touch a hot stove.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timothy needs 24-hour-a-day, seven-day-a-week, 52-week-a-year
care,'' said his mother, Angela. ``He is not able to do anything
for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   A state-paid nurse helps his parents care for him 10 to 15 hours
a week. But since February 1998, they have sought additional
services: a spot in a Cobb County day care program that would teach
him such basic skills as toilet training.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and I are not going to always be around,'' Angela
Ryals, a 53-year-old former teacher, said. ``He needs to be able to
do as many things as he can on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   But until the waiting lists are eliminated, she said, her son
isn't guaranteed to receive services.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good start,'' she said of the governor's
announcement. ``It is a far cry from everything we need. But it's
like they say: A journey of 1,000 miles begins with the first
step.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
