<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3377 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-PARENTING-CELESTE-COL     12-08 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENTING-CELESTE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NAKED AND THE DREAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC CELESTE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Usually, I try to write this column. Write it in the sense of
using words to express thoughts, the sense of employing clever
transitions and the ironic use of quotation marks. (''!'') Today,
though, we at Hey Dad Headquarters are going to give the public
what it wants: nonstop, real-life wacky anecdotes!
</P>
<P>
   Wacky Anecdote No. 1: My daughter, age 5, loves the cartoon
``Cow and Chicken'' on Cartoon Network. In fact, she likes to
pretend she's a cow, udder and all. The other day, I walked into
the TV room during ``Cow and Chicken'' time. Said daughter was
naked from the waist down, pinching herself.
</P>
<P>
   I can't handle anything having to do with my daughter and
nakedness. I am, after all, a dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aaah!'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a cow!'' she said, laughing. ``I'm giving milk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother! Your daughter needs you.''
</P>
<P>
   I left the room. Mom, I hoped, was explaining the difference
between cows and people. And putting daughter's britches back on
her. Mom emerged, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK. I told her that girls give milk up here.''
</P>
<P>
   My response is not fit for Family Day!
</P>
<P>
   Wacky Anecdote No. 2: I was working on the computer while my
daughter was getting ready for bed. She was supposed to be changing
into her night-night clothes. I lost track of time, though, and
looked over at her when I heard giggling. She was again, alas,
naked, with her legs in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aaah!'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm watching my toots!'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This time, I took care of the situation myself. I used this as
an opportunity to explain to her that tooting wasn't good manners.
As a bonus lesson, we went over the three types of matter: solid,
liquid and gas.
</P>
<P>
   Wacky Anecdote No. 3: My daughter came home with her second
report card. The card went into detail about how well she is doing
in class. It said that she is learning to read, that she is
learning to write, that her math aptitude is well above average. I
was exceedingly proud.
</P>
<P>
   On the back side of the card, there was some bad news, however.
The teacher marked her down in social skills. She included notes.
For example, she said that Maddison talks too much to others during
class.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother wanted to know what I thought of this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' I said, ``a girl's gotta know what her homies are up
to, right? Who's dating who, etcetera and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   The teacher also wrote that my daughter really needs to stop
``laughing at me when I tell her she's in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, this is the point of the story where I reveal what a sorry
parent I am. Because _ and I apologize for this in advance _ that
just cracked me up. Because, you know, she does that to me. I tell
her she's in trouble, she starts laughing, calls me a pumkin-head,
I start laughing, she gets away with it. So she's spoiled. Sue me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey,'' my wife said in a manner that told me she didn't mean
``Honey'' as a term of endearment, ``it may be funny to you,
because you were a brat, but we have to teach her to do what her
elders tell her.''
</P>
<P>
   She was right, of course. I called Maddison in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to me, now. When your teacher tells you that you're in
trouble, you can't laugh at her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not, Daddy?''
</P>
<P>
   I turned to the wife. ``She's got a good point, Honey.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, I've been recused from dealing with her on
school-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a borrowed anecdote. A single mother tells me about her
recent fight with nature's urge, ol' No. 1, goin' tinkle.
</P>
<P>
   While getting her two children ready for school, she heard a
yelp from the bathroom. She ran in to find her daughter frantic, as
she was ... wow, how to put this delicately? ... ``missing'' her
target ... in fact, missing high and wide, in some strange
displacement of the laws of physics, so that there was a mess
accruing on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aaah!'' the mother said.
</P>
<P>
   As she was trying to clean up her daughter's situation, her
still half-asleep son walked in and asked, ``Mom, what's on my
shirt?''
</P>
<P>
   This mother, a veteran of No. 1 wars, knew instantly what it
was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey, did you wear this when you went to the bathroom earlier
this morning?''
</P>
<P>
   It took the groggy kid a second to process this. When he did, he
responded, ``Aaah!'' Which is better than laughing about it, as my
kid would have surely done.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Celeste's Hey, Dad column appears every other Tuesday.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 1954EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0309 </DOCNO>
