<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3379 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-IBM-BUYOUT-TAXES-NYT &LR;      12-08 0294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-BUYOUT-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE VOIDS EX-IBM EMPLOYEES' SUIT ON BUYOUT TAXES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge in Utica, N.Y., has dismissed a lawsuit against
the IRS by 773 former IBM employees, who contend that job buyout
payments they received in 1993 were not taxable income.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal will be appealed, said Neil Kimmelfield of the
Ball Janik law firm in Portland, Ore., as will the dismissal last
July of a similar case in the U.S. Court of Claims brought by 2,500
other former IBM workers. He said the workers in the two cases are
seeking $100 million in tax refunds plus interest.
</P>
<P>
   IBM required employees to waive all rights to sue before making
the severance payments. Alan Shapiro, the Justice Department lawyer
representing the IRS, argued in court that this waiver did not
transform the severance payments, which were based on salary and
years of service, into tax-free damages.
</P>
<P>
   Pretrial testimony showed that IBM feared that workers might sue
the company over losing their jobs, Judge David Hurd wrote in a
ruling signed Friday and made available Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The workers contend that most of the severance pay was in lieu
of damages for lawsuits they could have filed against the company.
</P>
<P>
   Hurd held that even if IBM believed that 95 percent of the
severance payments were to avoid lawsuits, as an employment law
expert hired by the workers contended, the money was still taxable.
</P>
<P>
   ``IBM made the payments to maintain the good will of employees
and the community,'' Hurd wrote, not to settle any potential
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that since the workers did not suffer physical
harm, a tax law that exempts such damages from taxation does not
apply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 1955EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3380 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTON-CUBA-1209-COX     12-08 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CUBA-1209-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON WON'T INTERVENE IN FATE OF CUBAN BOY, YIELDS TO LEGAL
REMEDIES
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    With ISRAEL-SYRIA-1209.
 &HT;    By BOB DART 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Declining to intervene, President Clinton said
Wednesday that ``what would be best for the child'' should
determine whether a six-year-old boy rescued off the coast of
Florida will be returned to his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that politics or threats should have anything to
do with if and, if I have my way, it won't,'' Clinton said. ``We
should let the people who are responsible for this, who have the
legal responsibility, try to do the right thing by the child.''
</P>
<P>
   An international dispute has arisen over the fate of Elian
Gonzalez, who survived on Nov. 25 after his mother and stepfather
drowned when their boat capsized attempting to migrate to the
United States. Elian's father, who lives in Cuba, wants his son
returned and Cuban leader Fidel Castro has echoed his demands. The
case has ignited anti-American demonstrations in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the boy is staying with relatives in Miami. Many
Cuban exiles believe that Elian's mother died in helping her son
escape the Communist island, and that he should be allowed to stay
as a political refugee.
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly asked about the emotional case during a lengthy and
wide-ranging press conference, Clinton indicated that he would not
get personally involved but conceded the complexities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I think all fathers would be sympathetic'' with the
Cuban man who wants his son back, Clinton said. ``The question is,
and I think the most important thing, is what would be best for the
child, and there is a legal process for determining that.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I personally don't think that any of us should have any
concern other than that the law be followed.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the concerns of the Cuban-American community in
South Florida, Clinton said that ``of course'' he would rather
``grow up in the United States.'' But there may be other concerns,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even here, sometimes it's very hard to say. Would the children
be better off with their parents in America? Almost always, but not
always,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The best course is to ``try to take as much political steam out
of it as possible so that the little child can be considered,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In an hour-long news conference at the U.S. State Department,
Clinton also said it would be a mistake to cut off U.S. aid to
Russia because of its military campaign in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of this aid goes to safeguard Russia's nuclear
materials or destroy warheads, he said. ``I think it is plain that
we have an interest in continuing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the rest is aimed at building democracy and ``I don't
think our interests would be furthered in terminating that,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   While declaring that he has ``no sympathy'' for Chechen rebels,
Clinton said Russia will ``alienate the global community'' if it
continues its attacks.
</P>
<P>
   On other issues, Clinton said:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  He supports his wife, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, in
her New York Senate race but will miss her when she moves to a New
York house and begins full-time campaigning. ``It's not the best
arrangement in the world, but it's something that we can live with
for a year. And I love the house, you know. We picked it out, and
we like it, and I'm looking forward to living there when I leave
here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  He believes NASA is doing good work despite the loss of the
$165 million Mars Polar Lander.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep doing this if we ever hope to know what's
beyond our galaxy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  He was proud of ``accomplishments'' achieved with
congressional approval including funds to hire 100,000 new teachers
and 50,000 more police officers, and sweeping banking reforms.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  He was ``terribly disappointed'' that Congress did not enact
other programs that he supported including a patients' bill of
rights, tougher gun laws and changes to save Social Security past
the Baby Boom generation.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Al Gore is still performing ``his critical functions'' as vice
president despite the time spent seeking the Democratic nomination
for president.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
