<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0312 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3381 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ISRAEL-SYRIA-1209-COX     12-08 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SYRIA-1209-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAELIS, SYRIANS AGREE TO RESTART PEACE TALKS IN WASHINGTON
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    With CLINTON-CUBA-1209.
 &HT;    EDs: Box information attached to end of story.
 &HT;    By BOB DART and LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a major breakthrough in the oft-tortured Middle
East peace process, President Clinton announced Wednesday that
Israel and Syria agreed to resume peace negotiations at the point
they broke off more than three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The opening round of revived talks will be held next week in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at a pivotal moment in the Middle East peace process,
one that can shape the face of the region for generations to
come,'' Clinton said during an hour-long press conference at the
U.S. State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``History will not forgive a failure to seize this opportunity
to achieve a comprehensive peace,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton sidestepped questions on whether Israel would
return the strategic Golan Heights to Syria _ a key sticking point
in the negotiations for the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton praised Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian
President Hafez al-Assad for their courage in resuming the talks,
but offered no details on any preliminary agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israelis and Syrians still need to make courageous decisions
in order to reach a just and lasting peace,'' the president
conceded. ``But today's step is a significant breakthrough for it
will allow them to deal with each other face to face, and that is
the only way to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough came after Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright met Syrian and Israeli leaders in Damascus and Jerusalem.
Clinton said he had talked to both Barak and Assad by telephone
earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Peace talks between Israel and Syria broke down in 1996 with one
major disagreement coming over the future of the Golan Heights.
Israel captured the region in a 1967 war, and has been reluctant to
give up the highlands because of their military significance.
</P>
<P>
   However, peace talks with several Arab countries were
rejuvenated by Barak's election this year over the hardliner former
Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu. Clinton expressed hopes
that renewal of talks between Syria and Israel would lead to a
similar resumption of negotiations between Lebanon and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright announced
after a late-night session with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
that the latter had agreed to resume faltering negotiations with
Israel on an overall Middle East settlement. That timetable calls
for a reaching a framework for a final agreement in mid-February
and a final agreement in September.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton would not say what _ if any _ concessions had been
made to get the Israeli-Syrian talks back on track. ``It would into
be useful for me to get into details,'' he said when asked about
the Golan Heights, the talks ``will be resumed from the point where
they left off.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to Clinton's specification, a statement from Syria's
presidential palace said Assad welcomed the resumption.
</P>
<P>
   That vague phrasing is what got the two sides to face each
other, sidestepping the dispute over just what commitments, if any,
had been made.
</P>
<P>
   Syria claims that the late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin
agreed to give up this land, at the time talks broke off. Israel,
which broke off talks in 1996 after 59 people were killed in a wave
of suicide bombings against the Jewish state, has refused, saying
no such promise was ever made.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Israeli leaders seek a package from Syria including
access to the water sources on the Golan Heights and international
troops or monitors to prevent the strategic plateau from being used
as the source of Syrian attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Syria's demand for a complete withdrawal is now a
negotiating position, rather than a pre-condition to negotiations,
said a senior administration official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that talks between the two nations _ in a state of
war since 1948 _ would resume in Washington next week with Barak
meeting with Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Sharaa, and then
return to the region.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. official said naming al-Sharaa was a symbolic step that
would carry an important message to other Arab countries since
talks with Israel in the past have involved lower ranking
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Eyal Zisser, an Israeli expert on peace talks with Syria, said
the two sides were likely brought together by assurances he
believes they received from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Those assurances, he said, likely included promises of aid money
and security. Both sides say they expect billions of dollars in
American aid for making a deal.
</P>
<P>
   He said the talks with Syria should not be as difficult or
complicated as the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he cautioned, ``we have been in this movie before and
we thought everything would be OK, and we were surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Though upbeat Wednesday, Clinton was also cautious about the
chances for success.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be no illusion here,'' Clinton said. ``On all tracks
the road ahead will be arduous, the task of negotiating agreements
will be difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Success is not inevitable,'' he continued. ``Israelis,
Palestinians, Syrians and Lebanese will have to confront fateful
questions. They face hard choices. They will have to stand firmly
against all those who seek to de-rail the peace _ and sadly there
are still too many of them.''
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers Middle East correspondent reported from
Jerusalem and Bob Dart reported from Washington.)
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-ISRAEL ISSUES: LAND, WATER AND SECURITY
</P>
<P>
   Here are the major issues when Israel and Syria face off next
week:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  LAND _ Israel captured the Golan Heights, a plateau about the
size of Rhode Island, from Syria in 1967. Syria demands that the
land all be returned.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SECURITY _ Syria used to fire on Israeli villages from the
Golan. Israel will likely seek that any withdrawal be followed by
international troops or observers. Also, Israel will want to keep
some electronic listening posts on the plateau.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SETTLERS _ Since Israel captured the Golan, more than 18,000
Israelis have moved there. A withdrawal would require their
evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WATER _ The Golan is the source of up to a third of Israel's
water and Syria is asking that it be given land to the Sea of
Galilee and the Jordan River.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  LEBANON _ Israel occupies a nine-mile wide swath of southern
Lebanon, a country largely controlled by Syria. Israel may require
Syria to reign in Hezbollah guerillas who threaten Israel from
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  MONEY _ Both sides will want billions of dollars from the
United States. Israeli leaders claim that a withdrawal and
evacuation of residents will cost more than $10 billion. Syria,
which gets no U.S. aid currently, will seek an aid package similar
to what Egypt got for making peace with Israel _ $2 billion a year.
They will likely get much less.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RELATIONS _ Israeli leaders want to place an embassy in Syria
and allow movement between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
