<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3382 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BUICK-CHINA-475&AMP;ADD-N     12-08 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUICK-CHINA-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM'S BUICK VENTURE IN CHINA IS A SURPRISING SUCCESS STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MARK LANDLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ When General Motors chairman John Smith drove
the first Buick off an assembly line here a year ago _ after
fumbling to find the emergency brake _ it looked like an omen of
another American company's hapless foray into China.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a team of Chinese workers fussed over a white Buick
minivan _ tightening the bolts, pounding out the kinks and
otherwise putting the finishing touches on a vehicle that
represents GM's next big bet on the world's most populous nation.
This time, it rolled off the line without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   GM is off to an unexpectedly smooth start in its ambitious
campaign to conquer China's car market. The company will sell about
20,000 Buicks this year, double its own projections and those of
outside analysts. Emboldened by its success, GM plans to roll out
the new minivan next week, extending its product line from a very
expensive sedan to an equally costly family workhorse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were totally surprised to see how many cars they sold,''
said Michael Dunne, the president of Automotive Resources Asia, a
market research firm with offices in Beijing and Bangkok. ``For the
time being, they've got a lock on a very good market.''
</P>
<P>
   A few caveats are in order. A large majority of GM's sales are
to government officials and executives at state-run enterprises.
The government has cracked down on the smuggling of imported cars,
which has eliminated much of the Buick's potential competition. And
Volkswagen's Audi unit, which also produces in China, is about to
introduce a model that could be a formidable rival to Buick.
</P>
<P>
   Still, given the dire predictions of many skeptics in the
industry last December, GM executives here are allowing themselves
a low-key victory lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car is a lot better than people thought it would be,''
said Philip Murtaugh, the executive vice president of Shanghai GM,
which is a joint venture with China's largest sedan maker, the
Shanghai Automotive Industry Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before GM came here, the cars produced in China were
horrible,'' he said. ``The quality was poor, the service was
nonexistent, and the technology was 10 to 15 years out of date.''
</P>
<P>
   GM's early success is a beacon in the dismal landscape of
foreign joint ventures in China. The company's $750 million
investment in Shanghai GM is the largest single American investment
in the country. Its spit-and-polish assembly plant in an industrial
zone here has become a sort of shrine for Chinese and foreign
business people, who come to gawk at the cars and the camaraderie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in very early days,'' said Stephen Harner, a
former banker at Deutsche Bank here who helped arrange financing
for the venture. ``But if they can pay back their financing on time
or even ahead of schedule, it would strongly enhance the image of
the China market.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Given GM's surprising sales figures, Murtaugh said he was not
fazed by the next potentially big obstacle facing the automaker:
the landmark trade agreement between China and the United States.
The deal, which will lower tariffs on imported cars to 25 percent
from their current level of 80 percent to 100 percent by 2006,
could theoretically swamp China's market with luxury cars that cost
much less than the $40,000 Buick.
</P>
<P>
   By then though, Murtaugh said, GM will have cut its own costs
enough to bring down the price of the sedan and the minivan, which
also will be priced at about $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese trade deal with the United States also offers some
potentially enticing inducements to GM and other American
automakers. For example, it would allow them to make cars more
affordable by establishing auto loan services in China, where
buying on credit remains a relative novelty. Customers pay cash up
front.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of selling a $40,000 car in a country with an annual
gross domestic product of less than $800 a person remains baffling.
China's best-selling foreign car is a utilitarian VW sedan that
sells for less than $14,000. Never mind that outside of Shanghai,
Beijing and a few other cities, China's roads are ill-suited to the
soft ride and generous curves of a Buick sedan.
</P>
<P>
   The secret of GM's success is that the Buick was never intended
to be a mass-market vehicle in the broadest sense of the term.
General Motors is catering to government officials and managers at
state-owned companies, who get a chauffeur-driven car as a perk.
The Chinese government has encouraged these officials to buy
Buicks, and has made the choice easier by rooting out smuggled
imports. With 100 percent tariffs, legitimate imports like
Mercedes-Benz or GM's Cadillac are beyond the reach of all but the
most high-level officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of the China market as a fortress with walls built all
around it, and GM is the only American manufacturer inside the
walls,'' Dunne said.
</P>
<P>
   The question is: What will General Motors do after it sells
every bureaucrat a Buick?
</P>
<P>
   Jay Hunt, the marketing and sales director of Shanghai GM, said
the company was selling more cars to private buyers than it had
expected. In particular, the Buick is proving popular in the
freewheeling province of Guangdong, which has long been home to the
smuggled Mercedes with the missing hood ornament. Still, individual
buyers account for only 10 percent of the Buick's total sales.
</P>
<P>
   The minivan is GM's first attempt to broaden the market. Hunt
said the primary buyers would continue to be government ministries
and companies. But General Motors will also woo affluent younger
executives, who could use the van on weekends to ferry their
families.
</P>
<P>
   GM will market the vehicle under the name Buick GL8. Inside the
company, employees refer to it as the W-wagon, a bit of legerdemain
that is meant to satisfy Chinese officials, who granted a license
to produce minivans to a Mercedes joint venture that is defunct.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors may have to resort to such creative nomenclature
again. Beijing is stingy about allowing foreign manufacturers to
add new models to their product lines. But employees at Shanghai GM
say the long-term goal is to produce a smaller, cheaper car that
will compete head-to-head with Volkswagen, which sold 235,000 cars
in China in 1998 and is the leading foreign automaker here.
</P>
<P>
   GM's problems could proliferate as the Chinese market becomes
more crowded. Dunne noted that next year, VW, Honda Motor and Audi
will all come out with new, locally produced models that could
erode GM's franchise. As the market matures, he predicted, the
government will grant licenses for further new models, some of
which are bound to threaten Buick.
</P>
<P>
   China's bid to join the World Trade Organization is perhaps the
biggest imponderable. Some analysts contend that even if tariffs
were slashed to 25 percent, Beijing would limit imports through
taxes and other nontariff barriers. Yet Murtaugh acknowledged that
a more open China would be a tougher place for General Motors to
compete in. ``Over the long term, WTO will probably make our lives
more difficult,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 1958EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
