<HEADLINE>
`THE THIRD MAN' `THE LAST PICTURE SHOW' COME TO DVD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use Friday, Dec. 10 or later) 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peter Bogdanovich calls it a happy accident, like
``Casablanca.''
</P>
<P>
   He is referring to ``The Third Man,'' the Carol Reed-directed
film starring Joseph Cotten, Orson Welles, Trevor Howard and Alida
Valli.
</P>
<P>
   The Cold War thriller set in Vienna has recently been remastered
for its 50th anniversary, and has been released on DVD by
Criterion, $39.95 (VHS, $25.95).
</P>
<P>
   Bogdanovich wasn't being derogatory in his description of the
film. There were a number of major talents involved. The script was
written by Graham Greene, based on his novel. Cotten and Howard
were no slouches as actors, and Welles' prodigious talents were
legendary. Cinematographer Robert Krasker was considered a genius
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, though, was more a workmanlike director. Actually, at that
time he looked like a filmmaker who was coming into his own. He had
made a couple of highly regarded films (``Odd Man Out,'' ``Fallen
Idol'') previously, and whether he was at the top of his game when
making ``The Third Man'' or just smart enough to use the talents
around him doesn't really matter in the end. Filmgoers were given a
classic.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Krasker's Oscar-winning photography of the sinister
Vienna streets owes something to Welles' ``Citizen Kane,'' as
Bogdanovich points out. Welles, for his part, had a a great
``talked-about role'' as Harry Lime. In the story, Holly Martins
(Cotten) is an alcoholic pulp writer who has been summoned to
occupied Vienna by his old friend Lime. But he arrives to find
Lime's funeral under way. From Lime's girlfriend (Valli) and a
British officer (Howard), Martins learns of allegations of Lime's
involvement in racketeering. Not believing the charges, Martins
vows to clear his friend's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The reason Welles loved the role is that he didn't show up till
later in the picture but everybody talked about him before then _
so he became the most memorable character.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Welles and Bogdanovich, a special collector's
edition of ``The Last Picture Show'' has been released on DVD
(Columbia, $27.95). The DVD includes an additional eight minutes
added back into the film and the 65-minute ``Look Back'' feature in
which Bogdanovich explains that it was Welles who suggested to him
that he shoot the picture in black and white.
</P>
<P>
   A student of film, Bogdanovich wasn't shy about taking from the
masters like Welles and John Ford, but what he fashioned in ``The
Last Picture Show'' was purely his own, and in its own right a
classic.
</P>
<P>
   The casting alone was extraordinary _ Jeff Bridges, Cybill
Shepard, Cloris Leachman, Ellen Burstyn, longtime Ford regular Sam
Johnson, Eileen Brennan, Timothy Bottoms and Randy Quaid, with
Leachman and Johnson winning Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a novel by Larry McMurtry, ``The Last Picture Show''
tells the story of a small Texas town _ from football season to
football season _ in 1951. The title refers to the fact that the
main-street movie house is about to close for good. The spare
black-and-white cinematography (by the wonderful Robert Surtees)
evokes the loneliness and hopelessness that pervades the town. A
eulogy for the passing of an era, the film is brilliantly acted by
the entire cast, thanks to Bogdanovich.
</P>
<P>
   The feature also has remembrances from Bridges, Shepard,
Brennan, Burstyn and producer-director Frank Marshall (``Back to
the Future,'' the ``Indiana Jones'' trilogy), who was an assistant
to Bogdanovich and an actor in the film. But Bogdanovich is the
most interesting. Partly because although he had other successes,
his career never lived up to its promise, perhaps because the
classic style of filmmaking in which he was interested got lost in
the MTV slam-bam style popular today. (He did have ``Paper Moon''
and ``What's up Doc?'' but the rest of his career so far has been
hit-or-miss.)
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing this, he tells a story about a conversation he had
with Welles in which he lamented that Greta Garbo, an actress he
admired, had only appeared in two great movies. Welles' reply was
that it only takes one. It's a poignant comment. After all, Welles
always had ``Kane'' despite his other troubles, and Bogdanovich ...
well, there's ``The Last Picture Show.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 2001EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3387 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SCULPTURE-CITY-$ADV12     12-08 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCULPTURE-CITY-$ADV12-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 IN THE NEVADA DESERT: survivalists` hideaway.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1970, Heizer hired G. Robert Deiro, a pilot from Las Vegas,
to help him find the property. It had sand and gravel, running
water from a creek, isolation, the right climate _ and it was
cheap. Almost 90 percent of Nevada is public land. This was private
property surrounded by public land.
</P>
<P>
   Heizer gradually acquired three square miles, at $30 an acre.
The last parcel was paid off two years ago. ``Even I could save
$150 a month,'' Heizer says. ``Bob helped me get it, parcel by
parcel. He went into county records and researched the owners. They
all wanted to sell. Why not? Barren land in the middle of nowhere?
It was the best thing that ever happened to them.''
</P>
<P>
   At first Heizer lived in a trailer with his wife, Barbara (they
were divorced a couple of years ago). There was a weed-covered
livestock trail to the property, and Heizer wore out a new truck a
year getting to and from the place. Half the winter he'd be locked
in. Once he went for 10 months and saw only a couple of sheep
trailers and the occasional pickup truck in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   He began work on ``Complex 1'' in 1971. A farmer lent him a
paddle-wheel scraper to move dirt. Seismic engineers drew up plans
for the 30-ton, T-shaped and L-shaped concrete columns that
protrude from the complex. When the sculpture is viewed straight on
from a distance, these shapes align visually to make a frame around
the structure: an optical illusion causes the complex's slope to
seem to flatten into a monochrome rectangle, three stories high,
like one of Heizer's early paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Heizer was able to finish most of ``Complex 1'' by himself. He
began ``Complex 2'' in 1980 and ``Complex 3'' after that. But it
was becoming increasingly difficult to go on as his cash dwindled.
``A lot of money over the years went into simply trying to maintain
old, useless equipment,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He painted and made other sculptures during the '80s, including
one called ``Levitated Mass'' that was installed outside the IBM
building in Manhattan. ``I never stopped working on the pit and the
complexes, whenever I could afford to,'' he says. ``But we're
talking crazy optimism here.''
</P>
<P>
   Heizer had met the artists Walter De Maria in 1966 and Robert
Smithson in 1969 in New York, and they became linked with him as
Land artists. He brought them west. Smithson finished ``Spiral
Jetty'' in Utah in 1970. De Maria made ``Lightning Field'' in New
Mexico a few years later. Those works became famous. While Heizer
was immersed in his ``City,'' Smithson wrote articles that made him
the unofficial spokesman for the movement.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, Heizer felt usurped and cheated. He began to
seethe about the New York art scene, which he regarded as fickle
and amnesiac. His frustration grew as the years went by. His
freestanding sculptures included big stones carved into shapes that
recalled tools.
</P>
<P>
   They were sometimes perforated like Swiss cheese or wedged into
metal frames. Because of their size, he could never really show his
work properly in New York, he felt, so he couldn't ``play the
game.'' His first gallery show of any real size in the city _ and
therefore of any value to him, he says _ happened only five years
ago, at Ace Gallery, when he was already 50.
</P>
<P>
   Mention Robert Smithson or a few others associated with
Earthworks to Heizer and he's off. ``High-speed hustlers'' is one
of the few printable terms. ``What was some guy from New Jersey
doing building a sculpture like mine on a lake in Utah?'' he asks
about Smithson and ``Spiral Jetty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I figure, how much more original can you get than having
nine different people doing what I did first, and none of them
giving me credit? Actually, it's the academics who did not do a
good historical job who are really to blame. I wasn't political
enough to write articles about myself or go to cocktail parties,
meaning that not only has my art been pirated and my intellectual
property rights stolen, but my work has been misrepresented.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1997, Heizer was feeling exhausted and thinking about
demolishing what existed of Complexes 2 and 3, leaving just Complex
1. Then Michael Govan, the director of the Dia Foundation, stepped
in and, with money from both Dia and the Lannan Foundation (nobody
would say how much), he arranged to pay to complete the three
complexes and pit.
</P>
<P>
   There was an irony about this that wasn't lost on Heizer. Dia
had offered to underwrite the whole project when Heizer started it
30 years ago, but he had declined. Heiner Friedrich, who founded
Dia, had been Heizer's first dealer, and the two had fallen out.
</P>
<P>
   With money, Heizer was able to hire outside help. Decades of
pent-up desire combined with the inexperience of the construction
crew to make the situation sometimes rocky at first. Heizer can be
warm and solicitous, but also touchy, anxious and strong willed.
</P>
<P>
   The men had never worked on a project like this, which involved
unusual materials, gigantic forms in odd shapes and tricky
conditions. Storms would sweep across the valley and, in minutes,
wipe out $30,000 of labor on one of the steles. This happened four
or five times. The surfaces of the complexes required constant
readjustment.
</P>
<P>
   Heizer would become upset when the shape of one of the forms he
had drawn was not reproduced as he wanted. He wanted everything to
be just right. At one point, he asked that hundreds of thousands of
yards of dirt be moved 27 inches to align Complexes 2 and 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a dogmatic, purist psychopath,'' he insists. ``There's
an unfair image of me _ mean, crazy, hostile. I'm really a very
gentle person.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago Heizer got sick. He felt pain in his fingers and
toes, which he mistook for frostbite because he had been standing
in the cold 12 hours a day working on his sculpture. But when the
pain moved to his shoulders and back, a Medivac helicopter had to
fly into the valley and rush him to a doctor, who sent him home and
told him he was drinking and smoking too much.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
