u a BC-MA-WORCESTER-FIRE-BOS     12-08 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WORCESTER-FIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND BODY FOUND IN `BUILDING FROM HELL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAC DANIEL AND STEPHANE EBBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ Just after midnight Wednesday, firefighters
picking through the wreckage of a burned-out warehouse retrieved
the body of a second firefighter who died Friday in the ``building
from hell.''
</P>
<P>
   James Lyons, 34, was found in a corner of the second floor of
the Worcester Cold Storage and Warehouse Co. and taken to the
Boston Medical Examiner's office, where his remains were
identified.
</P>
<P>
   But the painstaking search for the remains of his four
colleagues, carried out by 40 firefighters, continued for most of
the day in a process one described as both tedious and horrible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish to hell it was over,'' said an exhausted,
soot-covered firefighter, Norman Beck, who emerged at 5:30 p.m.,
after a full day of sifting through ash. ``And then you come out of
there and you see these people and you see these flowers and you
see these cops and they're all heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, President Clinton and thousands of firefighters from
around the world are expected to attend a tribute to the victims.
</P>
<P>
   But District Chief Walter Giard said many Worcester firefighters
would remain at the warehouse, continuing the difficult search for
their comrades.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many Worcester firefighters that would rather be
working here than attending the memorial service,'' Giard said.
``To them, this is much more important.''
</P>
<P>
   The men who died in a search for two homeless people purported
to be inside the fiery warehouse included: Paul Brotherton, 41;
Jeremiah Lucey, 38; Lt. Thomas Spencer, 42; Joseph McGuirk, 38; and
Timothy Jackson, 51, whose body was removed Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Worcester authorities arrested Julie S. Barnes, 19,
and Thomas S. Levesque, 37, a homeless couple who had lived in the
warehouse as squatters. They were charged Tuesday with six counts
of involuntary manslaughter for allegedly sparking the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they knocked over a candle during an
argument, setting papers ablaze. Unable to extinguish the fire,
they left the warehouse without reporting it.
</P>
<P>
   Known to local homeless advocates, the pair had faced criminal
charges in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes was charged with shoplifting cosmetics from a CVS in
Worcester Sept. 13. Levesque, meanwhile, was charged with assault
and battery in October 1989 and with domestic assault and battery
in May 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, who had reportedly dropped out of school, most recently
attended Wachusett Regional for about two weeks beginning March 30,
according to Principal Tom Pandiscio. She had also attended
Worcester's South High and North High.
</P>
<P>
   The firefighters were trying to give the homeless ``another day
to live. And they lost their lives doing it,'' said Lt. Greg
Zinkus.
</P>
<P>
   Tears welled to his eyes as he noticed for the first time a
billboard memorializing the six firefighters, whose images stared
down at him near the scene of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   The outpouring of sympathy, which started as news of the tragedy
spread, continued Wednesday. Flowers, wreaths and sympathy cards
continued to mount on a Worcester fire truck that has become a
makeshift shrine to the fallen.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this has taught me is that people in this city, in this
state, in this country care when it matters the most,'' said
Worcester Fire Department EMS Coordinator Tom Creamer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone we don't know stands in front of the fire truck
and starts crying over someone they don't even know, they have lost
someone,'' he added. ``They may not know them, but they know they
lost something.''
</P>
<P>
   Five days after the raging fire, flames were still visible
inside the wreckage, and the emotions among firefighters were just
as raw. Some firefighters, frustrated by the slow pace but
determined to find their fallen comrades, are still working,
despite just 16 hours of sleep over five days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not one of us, you don't even know what it's like,''
said Alfred K. Whitehead, general president of the International
Association of Firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehead said the families of the six victims will be presented
with the IAFF's medal of honor, the highest award bestowed by the
agency, during Thursday's ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers continued to use cadaver-sniffing dogs and metal
detectors in the hopes of picking up even the slightest clue of
firefighters' remains, from fragments of air tanks to belt buckles.
</P>
<P>
   Even after darkness fell, crews used a huge spotlight to
illuminate the building for their grim task: Sorting brick-by-brick
through the rubble, as forensic experts sift the ashes for even the
smallest clues.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're looking for pieces. You're looking for anything. You're
using your hands. You're screening the piles,'' said Beck. ``You're
looking for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, firefighters had only covered one-third of the building,
Giard said.
</P>
<P>
   District Chief Randy A. Chavoor said they found several hot
spots which forensic experts examined, using a quarter-inch screen
to sift through debris. They found only buckles and pieces of
straps for air tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe today we've made more progress than in previous
days,'' Giard said. ``But the building still has not surrendered
our people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff writers Cindy Rodriguez and Joanna Weiss contributed
to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
