<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS OFFER CAMPAIGN VOLUNTEERS ROOMS AT SWANK HOTEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY and LANCE WILLIAMS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The California Democratic Party is offering
legislative staffers up to four free nights at the San Francisco
Hilton if they agree to spend their days walking precincts for
Mayor Willie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The state party is offering the free rooms to induce Democrats
to help Brown fend off Board of Supervisors President Tom Ammiano
in the Dec. 14 mayoral run-off election.
</P>
<P>
   The party contributed $80,000 to Brown's re-election campaign in
the November election, said Bob Mulholland, a longtime Democratic
strategist, and may drop another $100,000 in the run-off.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a former state Assembly speaker, was elected mayor in
1995 and faced a tough re-election last month. He failed to win an
absolute majority, forcing him into a run-off race with Ammiano, a
write-in candidate who finished second.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor has a lot of friends in Sacramento,'' Mulholland
said Tuesday. ``People remember that when we were out in the
desert, under (Republican governors) Wilson and Deukmejian, he was
our shining star.''
</P>
<P>
   Staffers for state Senate Democrats said volunteers were being
offered up to four nights at the Hilton, starting Friday.
Mulholland said he was not sure if it would be the Hilton, but
said, ``They won't be at a nonunion hotel. This is very important
to the Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the effort was independent of Brown's campaign. Such
so-called soft-money campaigns are exempt from the city's tough
political contribution limits, and independent Brown boosters are
expected to spend more than $1 million in the run-off.
</P>
<P>
   In November, anywhere from 40 to 120 legislative employees
traveled to San Francisco to work for Brown on Election Day. Some
rode on a bus supplied by the campaign and spent the day in the
city making phone calls, hanging campaign literature from doors,
encouraging Brown supporters to vote and then making sure they did.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the volunteers were employees of state Senate President
pro tem John Burton, D-San Francisco, one of Brown's closest
friends. Others came from the office of Assembly Speaker Antonio
Villaraigosa, D-Los Angeles, and Assemblyman Kevin Shelley, D-San
Francisco, who also are close to Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I predict there will probably be the same amount of people who
want to work for Willie in the run-off,'' said Dave Sebeck, a
spokesman for Burton. ``We'll be arguing over who gets to walk
Union Square, so we can get our Christmas shopping done, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano campaign spokesman Hunter Cutting said the effort is a
sign that the Brown campaign is nervous about the outcome of the
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's important ... is it seems the Brown campaign is
not too confident in what it's doing to win,'' Cutting said. ``It's
interesting that they have to call in all their chits from all over
the state.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not illegal for legislative staff members to do political
work, but they are not allowed to do it on the state's dime.
</P>
<P>
   There is a long tradition of staff members, both Republicans and
Democrats, traveling hundreds of miles to work tight elections in
places like Fresno or Bakersfield.
</P>
<P>
   They are not paid, but they usually get a meal, transportation
and a party afterward. But in the past, those efforts almost always
involved a battle for a key legislative or congressional seat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
