<SLUG> BC-ATHOME09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Excite At Home strategy creates a 'major player'
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Excite At Home, the largest provider of high-speed
Internet access, plans to significantly widen its lead next year
through overseas expansion and retail sale of its service.
</P>
<P>
   The service, which uses digital cable TV systems to connect to
the Internet, is well on track to meet its ambitious goal. It's
adding tens of thousands of new subscribers a month and doubling
its market penetration every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great growth story and we intend to be a major
player in the Internet business in 2000,'' said Kenneth Goldman,
Excite At Home's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's comments were part of a briefing he gave Wednesday on
the future of his company at the annual PaineWebber media
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The conference, being held in Midtown Manhattan through
Thursday, is attended by about 1,000 media executives, investors
and Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The Silicon Valley, Calif.-based company's session was one of
the more well-attended.
</P>
<P>
   Excite At Home, a pioneer in high-speed Internet access, uses
the digital cable networks of 23 different cable operators to
connect users to the Internet at speeds up to 100 times faster than
traditional telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Among Excite At Home's partners are Atlanta-based Cox
Communications Inc. and Philadelphia-based Comcast Corp., each of
which own about 12 percent of the Internet provider.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Excite At Home has 1 million subscribers nationwide,
including some in metro Atlanta through Comcast systems. That's
more than double the number of the second largest provider of
high-speed access, Road Runner.
</P>
<P>
   The Road Runner Service is offered in metro Atlanta by MediaOne,
the area's largest single cable TV provider. MediaOne is in the
process of being acquired by AT&AMP;T, which has an exclusive deal with
Excite At Home through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Excite At Home hopes to boost sales even further through selling
its service in retail stores and with computer makers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, both Dell and Compaq now offer sale of the service
with its computers. Consumers must purchase a cable modem
separately.
</P>
<P>
   SELF-INSTALLATION
</P>
<P>
   Initially, users have to lease a modem from their cable
operator, which also installs the service. The time it takes to
install the service now averages about one hour and thirty minutes,
said Goldman.
</P>
<P>
   Cable Internet access is considered a premium service and costs
more than regular cable TV service.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, though, said his company is working hard toward the day
when consumers can buy a computer already equipped with both a
cable modem and their service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus is on self-installation, making it easy and seamless
for users,'' said Goldman.
</P>
<P>
   Another area of growth is overseas. Already, Excite At Home
offers its service in Canada, Japan, Germany, Australia, Belgium,
Holland and Luxemburg.
</P>
<P>
   In total, said Goldman, Excite At Home's service was available
to 71 million homes worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Said Goldman, ``Our focus next year will be on execution,
getting more and more of the homes we pass to sign up for the
service.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
