<HEADER>
A3397 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-STOCK09-COX     12-08 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-STOCK09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke stock makes comeback
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After two tough days on Wall Street, Coca-Cola stock
rebounded Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Shares rose 50 cents to close at $60.50, getting a boost from
analyst Caroline Levy of Schroder &AMP; Co., who upgraded the stock to
``outperform significantly'' from ``outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy, who is not a fan of retiring Chief Executive M. Douglas
Ivester, also predicted the stock would rise to $76 within 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   The stock tumbled 12 percent over Monday and Tuesday after the
company announced that Ivester would retire as chairman and CEO in
April. He will be replaced by Douglas Daft, a 30-year company
veteran who was named president and chief operating officer until
he ascends to Ivester's job.
</P>
<P>
   Levy said Daft is ``the kind of guy who puts people at ease
right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivester has been criticized by Levy and other analysts for being
less diplomatic than he needed to be when dealing with important
problems, such as those with European regulators or Belgian
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The critical thing we see in Monday's announcement that Doug
Daft will become CEO is recognition that the company has been hurt
by a confrontational culture,'' Marc Cohen, an analyst with Goldman
Sachs, wrote Wednesday in a research report. ``He is also viewed as
politically savvy and a consensus builder.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Cohen added, ``this sudden leadership shift clearly raises
two issues that we expect to hang over this stock for awhile.''
Unlike Levy, Cohen rates the stock as a just a ``market
performer.''
</P>
<P>
   The first issue, he said, is the ``likelihood of more management
turmoil over the next year.''
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum, he said, Coca-Cola ``will almost certainly now
name another No. 2 in April.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivester, who was the No. 2 executive under the late Roberto
Goizueta, did not name a president and CEO when he rose to the top
spot. Many analysts believe that issue caused a disagreement
between Ivester and the board of directors, prompting Ivester's
decision to retire. The board then chose Daft to be president until
Ivester leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, however, was still very complimentary of Ivester.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Doug Ivester made an immeasurable contribution to the
Coca-Cola Co.,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The second issue that may contain the stock, Cohen said, is the
possibility that the new management may lower its ``customary
long-term growth objectives.'' They include annual case sales
growth of 7 percent to 8 percent and earnings per share growth of
15 percent to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the company has said it will stick by its goals, even though
it has not been able to reach them lately.
</P>
<P>
   Even if those targets are hit again, some analysts do not
believe the company will be able to sustain the performance for
several years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts expect case sales to rise 5 percent next year,
compared with about 1 percent this year. And earnings per share,
which are likely to fall about 8 percent this year, are expected to
rise about 17 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
