<SLUG> BC-HDEPOT-MEETING09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot hammers home growth theme
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot wheeled out a war chest of growth plans at
its annual investors conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   From high-tech hammers to home improvement loans, the retail
giant made it clear that it's bent on getting bigger. And that
seemed to please nearly 200 analysts and investors who came to Home
Depot's headquarters to hear the message straight from the top
brass.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a remarkable show of force,'' said analyst Dan Wewer
of Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown. ``Home Depot has always been clever
with its growth plans, but Wall Street rarely gets to meet the
managers behind those plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's immediate response sent the stock to a 52-week
high of $85.50 Wednesday. The stock closed at $84.30, up $1.05.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot had a captive audience at its Atlanta complex. Nearly
40 percent of the company's stock was represented at the two-day
meeting, said Ron Brill, executive vice president and chief
administrative officer.
</P>
<P>
   Braced by a strong housing market, Home Depot has turned in
quarter after quarter of strong earnings growth in recent years.
With more than 900 stores currently, it plans to double in size in
the next several years.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at several current moves designed to boost sales:
</P>
<P>
   _ Tool rentals, which represent a $20 billion market, have
become a profitable test that will roll out to more markets. Home
Depot plans to operate roughly 400 of the rental centers inside
stores next year. The current 150-store test is popular with
contractors, Brill said.
</P>
<P>
   _ New proprietary products are designed to differentiate Home
Depot from Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co., Lowe's Home Improvement Warehouse
and other competitors. One of its newest brands is RoboHammer, a
shock-absorbent hammer with custom right- or left-hand grips.
</P>
<P>
   _ New home improvement loans are being tested at 60 stores and
will extend to all U.S. stores next year. Customers can obtain
unsecured credit lines up to $20,000 through two unidentified
lenders. Home Depot gets the origination fees, plus the loans tend
to inspire homeowners to spend more on projects.
</P>
<P>
   _ Major appliances will be offered in most stores by the end of
next year through partnerships with General Electric and Whirlpool.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its store growth, Home Depot's Internet strategy
has been a high-profile topic. Brill said that online product sales
would start next year with a city-by-city launch. The company is
still working on local product and pricing issues, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot's strategy for contractors and professional customers
may present the biggest opportunity for growth, analyst Wewer said.
The company has been testing pro departments in several cities,
including Las Vegas, Chicago and Austin, Texas. In those tests,
Home Depot carries large quantities of commodity products, and it
staffs the stores with salespeople dedicated to the pro customers.
</P>
<P>
   Sales at those stores have risen 20 percent, far above the
annual sales increases at existing Home Depot stores, Wewer said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
