u f BC-MYWAY-BELLSOUTH09-COX     12-08 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MYWAY-BELLSOUTH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deal with MyWay.com gives BellSouth new Internet portal
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth has become part-owner of MyWay.com in a deal
that will make that Internet portal the start page for BellSouth's
Internet customers.
</P>
<P>
   For BellSouth, which is the Southeast's second largest Internet
service provider, the deal seems aimed at proving that BellSouth is
committed to the cutting-edge technologies that are likely to drive
the Internet in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   MyWay, which is owned by holding company CMGI Inc., offers a
site that can be customized to a user's tastes and interests, and
BellSouth plans to add a series of features that will be available
only to its subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The companies declined to say how much BellSouth is investing or
how much of MyWay.com BellSouth will own.
</P>
<P>
   However, the arrangement announced Wednesday provides for
BellSouth to receive part of the revenue from the Web portal, said
Bill Smith, BellSouth's chief technology officer. ``We do get to
share in the upside of helping MyWay to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, MyWay expects to get a boost to its revenue from
the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The company, like many on the Net, makes much of its money from
advertising, as well as through deals with companies that have
links to its site. But the rates that can be charged depend on how
many visitors the site has, how often they view MyWay, how much
time they spend there and how much of the site they see.
</P>
<P>
   MyWay hopes for a quick boost as its Web site starts to enjoy
visits from BellSouth's 700,000 subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have responsibility for the media half of this,'' said Jeff
Cunningham, MyWay president and chief executive officer. ``We give
the user simpler tools, faster access and _ we think _ a more
colorful experience. BellSouth is responsible for the feet on the
street of the alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, MyWay has tried to eliminate requests for
information that could then be sold to advertisers. The tactic may
trim revenue opportunities for each user's visit, but MyWay hopes
the policy will bring users back more often, Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a convenience-stores mentality, put into a strip mall,
so it's available on a 24-hour basis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Web page can be used by anyone on the Web, the
feature-enhanced version of the service is to be available to
BellSouth users by early February. Among the features to be added
are local information and the ability to interact with BellSouth
customer service through the page.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI Inc. is a Massachusetts-based holding company with dozens
of Internet start-ups beneath its umbrella, including Alta Vista
and Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with BellSouth, in the works for several months, got
its start in informal talks between executives of the two
companies. An alliance with CMGI could offer BellSouth a chance to
include new Net technologies as they are developed.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth and MyWay hope eventually to add unified messaging _
features that let users combine and track their voice mail and
e-mail messages. BellSouth also believes MyWay can be the core of
new services for users of wireless devices as well as BellSouth's
high-speed data lines.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
