<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulls not cowed for new year, gurus say
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The greatest bull market in Wall Street history won't
end in the new year. That's the message from a group of stock
market gurus profiled by Money (December) in its special year-end
investment double issue.
</P>
<P>
   Among them is Harry Dent Jr., whose book, ``The Roaring 2000s,''
argues that the aging baby boom generation will keep the bull alive
well into the next century. Another is Wharton scholar Jeremy
Siegel, whose ``Stocks for the Long Run'' demonstrates that stocks
have always outperformed bonds and other investments.
</P>
<P>
   But Money cites weaknesses in their arguments, noting that they
don't agree with each other on certain key points. ``The only thing
that's certain'' says Money, ``is that after five years of almost
uninterrupted prosperity, we're in uncharted territory now. ...
Don't be too sure of anything.''
</P>
<P>
   TOO MUCH, TOO FAST?
</P>
<P>
   If the bull market appears safe, there are at least a few doubts
about the future of the ``new economy,'' according to Business Week
(Dec. 13).
</P>
<P>
   Columnist Jeffrey E. Garten cites a number of uncertainties that
could threaten the current business cycle. Among them is a
potential backlash in the marketplace against ``today's
mind-boggling pace of technological innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``None other than Intel Chairman Andrew Grove worries that rapid
advances in the computer industry might not be digestible by
society, leading to lower consumer spending and lower corporate
investment,'' writes Garten.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA IS ON THE MAP
</P>
<P>
   Does location really matter to a growing business? Inc.
(December) says it does and ranks metro Atlanta as the third-best
location in the nation for a start-up or young company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Success depends on the CEO's ability to marshal resources, and
many key resources are available only if the company is in the
right place,'' says Inc., which bills itself as ``the magazine for
growing companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Among 50 large metropolitan centers ranked according to the
number of new companies over the last decade, Atlanta was behind
first-place Phoenix and second-place Salt Lake City-Provo.
</P>
<P>
   Three other Georgia cities were on Inc.'s list of the 50 best
``small metro areas'': Savannah, 4th place; Macon, 26th; and
Columbus, 43rd.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Atlanta came in fifth in Fortune's recent ranking
of the ``best cities for business,'' behind Dallas; San Jose,
Calif.; Austin, Texas; and New York.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE POST-MORTEM
</P>
<P>
   The Economist (Dec. 10) blames last week's protest in Seattle on
governments that ``have not merely failed to make the case for free
trade'' but have ``pandered to their (unappeasable) critics.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about trade and globalization deserve to be addressed,
the magazine says. If governments did that job properly, they would
tell people that trade ``makes people better off, especially the
poorest people in the poorest countries,'' and ``improves the
environment because it raises incomes,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
