<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-LETTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON WROTE HERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Washington had a sense of humor but wanted to hide it
from history. That's why a puckish letter he wrote to his
brother-in-law, Burwell Bassett, in 1762 is expected to boost
bidding into the stratosphere Thursday when it is auctioned off at
Christie's in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The one-page letter is valued at between $140,000 and $160,000 _
three to four times what Washington's more strait-laced
correspondence is worth. In the letter, 30-year-old Washington
tweaks Bassett for writing to him on a Sunday when ``you ought to
have been in church praying as becomes every good Christian Man who
has as much to answer for as you have.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington, not a churchgoer, adds that his brother-in-law might
``behold with what religious zeal I hye me to Church on every Lords
day.''
</P>
<P>
   How refreshing to see the whimsy of a man most Americans think
of as a brilliant but tight-lipped icon. Washington engineered much
of that image, taking care to reveal little of a personal nature in
his writing.
</P>
<P>
   But in his unguarded moments he was a relatively fun guy.
Kenneth Bowling, co-editor of the First Federal Congress Project at
George Washington University, notes that the father of our country
liked to play cards, have drinks with friends, and was ``a
tremendous lady's man'' in his bachelor days.
</P>
<P>
   Such tidbits are fascinating to a culture that is inundated with
the most intimate details of current political lives. But even with
the media saturation, one wonders whether the public really knows
its national leaders and whether future generations will discover
clues that today's generation missed.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's pre-Revolutionary War letters were not considered
important by many 19th-century collectors _ the Bassett letter
languished in Europe for 100 years before a California collector
found it. Chris Coover at Christie's thinks there could be a lot
more ``wonderful Washington letters out there that haven't been
found.''
</P>
<P>
   Check the attic, and double-check misperceptions of a legend
that obscure the human being.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 2023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
