<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTNOTES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    England, Germany in same group
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Both England and Germany paid the price for poor form
since last summer's World Cup. This week, they were placed in the
same 2002 World Cup qualifying group.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 200 nations were placed in their respective FIFA draws
Tuesday in Tokyo, with the European side of the slate catching most
of the attention.
</P>
<P>
   England, which backed into Euro 2000 despite a lackluster
qualifying showing, lost to Germany both in the Euro '96 and the
1990 World Cup semifinals on penalty kicks. Playing a two-leg
series with the Germans, who twice lost to the United States this
year, will rule out such a dramatic conclusion in qualifying, which
begins next year.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team is through to the Football Confederation (formerly
CONCACAF) semifinals, along with Mexico, Jamaica and Costa Rica.
The best bets to advance out of the opening rounds are Trinidad and
Tobago and El Salvador. The top three go to the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 South American nations were not included in the draw
because theirqualifying consists of a single-group, 18-game
competition, with the top four advancing.
</P>
<P>
   Africa's four strongest teams _ South Africa, Cameroon, Nigeria
and Ghana _ have relatively easy opening groups and should nail
down four of the continent's five berths. The other one could be
current African champion Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   In Asia, becauseJapan and South Korea are automatic as co-hosts,
only two more teams are guaranteed places. The road could be a long
one for Saudi Arabia, which has made the past two World Cups.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, all nine group winners advance, along with defending
champion France, while the top eight runners-up will be redrawn to
determine four other places. Another runner-up will meet an Asian
team to select another spot.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise announcement, FIFA said it is moving up the next
Women's World Cup by a year to 2002, ostensibly to help promote the
event. It will take place in the fall, probably in Australia, only
a few weeks after the men are done.
</P>
<P>
   CHAMPIONS LEAGUE: KEANE CASHES IN
</P>
<P>
   Manchester United captain Roy Keane celebrated a lucrative
contract extension with the opening goal as the Red Devils thrashed
Valencia 3-0 on Wednesday to pick up its first three points in the
second round of group play.
</P>
<P>
   Keane, the Irishman who threatened to play abroad unless United
gave him a substantial raise, re-upped for four years at an
estimated $4.23 million per year, the largest such package in
England. His weekly salary of $81,500 is estimated to be Europe's
highest. Also on Wednesday, Barcelona pounded Sparta Prague 5-0,
Porto got a late goal to defeat Hertha Berlin, and Fiorentina and
Bordeaux played to a scoreless draw.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Real Madrid ignored its domestic league problems
with a 3-1 thrashing of Rosenborg Trondheim, while Chelsea got a
valuable point in Rome in a 0-0 draw with Lazio.Feyenoord dropped
Olympique Marseille 3-0, and Bayern Munich, missing numerous
injured and suspended players, held on to beat Dynamo Kyiv 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Champions League resumes on Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: CRUZ AZUL, AMERICA MEET
</P>
<P>
   Mexico City rivals Cruz Azul and Club America begin the first of
their two-leg Torneo Invierno semifinal series tonight. America,
the richest Mexican club, has not won a domestic title of any kind
since 1989. Cruz Azul has only one title since 1980, the 1997
Invierno. Tonight's game will be shown on tape delay at 11:30 p.m.
on Telemundo. In the other half of the draw, Atlas met Pachuca, an
upset winner over Toluca, in a late Wednesday game. The second legs
of both series will be on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: MADRID IN DANGER ZONE
</P>
<P>
   In charge not even three games, interim manager Vicente del
Bosque might be on his way out for Real Madrid, whose 5-1 thumping
by Zaragoza over the weekend was its worst home loss in 25 years.
Word is that president Lorenzo Sanz is angling to bring in another
former Madrid short-term boss, Jorge Valdano, for the rest of the
season. Sanz reportedly would like to lure Spain coach Jose Antonio
Camacho after Euro 2000. Madrid is in 17th place in the 20-team
Primera Division. GERMANY: OFFICER TO VISIT MATCH
</P>
<P>
   French police officer Daniel Nivel, left with permanent brain
damage after being beaten by German hooligans during the 1998 World
Cup, will be a guest of Kaiserslautern tonight as it entertains
Lens, his hometown club, in the UEFA Cup. Four young Germans were
sentenced to as many as 10 years in prison last month for the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: RAVANELLI MOVES TO LAZIO
</P>
<P>
   Marseille forward Fabrizio Ravanelli has completed a one-year
transfer deal worth roughly $1 million to be a benchwarmer at
Lazio. The flamboyant, silver-haired Ravanelli figures he'll get
playing time with the Serie A leaders, because they also should
advance in the Champions League and the Italian Cup. He sought the
return to Italy to improve his chances of playing in Euro 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker's International Soccer column will appear next on
Dec. 30 (wparker(at)ajc.com).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
