<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3413 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HOCKEY-CRIME-NYT &LR;      12-08 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOCKEY-CRIME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOCKEY PLAYER, 15, IS CHARGED AFTER SERIOUSLY INJURING AN
OPPONENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill. DUPLICATION WARNING: Also moving in ``s'' news file.)  (rk) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Prosecutors have charged a 15-year-old youth league
hockey player with aggravated battery, saying he slammed an
opponent into the boards with his stick seconds after a game ended,
leaving the player partly paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Lake County state's attorney, George
Strickland, said Wednesday that in a Nov. 3 game in suburban
Northbrook, the 15-year-old, whose name was not released because he
is a juvenile, ``got up a head of steam'' as he skated toward the
opposing player, whose back was turned.
</P>
<P>
   The player who was charged was on the losing team, Strickland
said, and the injured player, Neal Goss, 15, of Glencoe, had scored
several goals. Goss has been unable to use the lower half of his
body.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland also said that bystanders had told prosecutors that
the accused youth taunted Goss, saying, ``This is what you get for
messing.''
</P>
<P>
   But The Associated Press reported that Alan Kray, president of
the Northbrook Hockey League, which sponsored the game, said
several witnesses had thought there might still have been time left
in the game when the boy was hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened within the context of the game,'' Kray said.
</P>
<P>
   The charges have renewed an old debate over whether the actions
of athletes on the arena ice or the playing field should be held to
the standards of criminal law. Only a handful of professional
athletes and coaches have been charged with crimes over the years,
and experts on sports say they do not know of any criminal charges
being filed in a youth sports event.
</P>
<P>
   The youth hockey player was charged with two counts of battery,
one for using ``a deadly weapon'' and the other for inflicting
``great bodily harm.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Steinback, a lawyer for the player who was charged, said
prosecutors were wrong to treat the incident as criminal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious this isn't a crime,'' Steinback said. ``What's
being responded to is a tragic incident.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his client ``was upset from the beginning,'' adding,
``he's been devastated and wracked with feelings of remorse.''
</P>
<P>
   Players in the hockey league wear uniforms that bear the names
of their high schools, but the schools do not sponsor or sanction
the events.
</P>
<P>
   Athletic officials at New Trier Township High School, where the
injured boy is enrolled, and at Glenbrook North High School, where
the accused youth is a student, declined to comment on the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   In professional hockey, prosecutors have brought charges in only
a relative handful of cases.
</P>
<P>
   The boxer, Mike Tyson, was suspended from boxing for biting an
opponent's ear off, but never faced criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, prosecutors in Kansas decided not to press
charges against Ben Christensen, a former Wichita State University
pitcher, for striking a batter near the on-deck circle in the face
with a thrown ball.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Robinson, a professor of law at Northwestern University,
said the courts generally hold that participating in a violent
sport means consenting to violence, as long as the action is part
of what is deemed as a generally accepted part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when somebody is injuring somebody else clearly outside
the normal violence of the game, why shouldn't it be prosecuted?''
he said. ``Prosecutors rarely make such charges. Probably they
don't do it enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 2027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
