<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3416 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-`RIVER-HORSE'-TE     12-08 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-`RIVER-HORSE'-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HEAT-MOON'S LATEST SAGA, THE JOURNEY IS THE DESTINATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GEOFFREY CAMPBELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``River-Horse: The Logbook of a Boat Across America''
</P>
<P>
   by William Least Heat-Moon
</P>
<P>
   Travel/Memoir
</P>
<P>
   Houghton Mifflin, $26
</P>
<P>
   John Steinbeck's ``Travels With Charley: In Search of America''
had held up pretty well for me. Discovered in adolescence, when the
urge to see the country was heavily upon me, ``Travels'' became a
book I periodically enjoyed rereading as a worthy surrogate for the
open road.
</P>
<P>
   That changed rather abruptly, however, after I read ``Blue
Highways'' by William Least Heat-Moon. ``Travels'' suddenly seemed
shabby, much as one's comfortable furniture suddenly suffers from
comparison with that of a better-off friend. Heat-Moon returns to
the travel narrative with his latest offering, ``River-Horse: The
Logbook of a Boat Across America.'' ``River-Horse'' is an engaging
account of Heat-Moon's 5,000-mile journey across the United States,
a trip made almost entirely by water aboard a small C-dory he named
Nikawa, a combination of the Osage words for ``river'' and
``horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the physical trip is compelling, ``River-Horse''
derives much of its strength from Heat-Moon's implicit
understanding that a cross-country adventure is as much a journey
into the mind as it is a trip across the physical landscape. The
interior forays are skillfully blended with accounts of the rivers,
land and people Heat-Moon confronts as he battles floods,
mosquitoes and flotsam across America. Heat-Moon's expedition, the
first of its kind, took him from New York Harbor to Astoria, Ore.
Along the way, he followed the routes taken by some of the nation's
pre-eminent explorers, including Henry Hudson and Lewis and Clark.
Liberally sprinkled with history and lore, ``River-Horse'' brings
the past alive while never losing a keen sense of the present. For
those who find it difficult to go to a shopping mall without
leaving in bewilderment that the United States has emerged as the
lone superpower, Heat-Moon provides a ready antidote with his
beautifully drawn celebrations of the humor and innate wisdom of
the so-called Common Man.
</P>
<P>
   Vignettes of his encounters with average Americans provide comic
relief and poignancy in the face of very real physical dangers. The
narrative is presented in trademark Heat-Moon style. His sentences
are like nesting dolls, a new surprise lurking behind each
successive word. The sentences almost become metaphors for the
trip: One never knows quite what to expect beyond the next comma,
just as Heat-Moon was unsure what he'd find around the next river
bend. One thing remains a certainty, however. Heat-Moon is still a
tad cranky about the homogenization of American culture and becomes
livid when confronted with littered landscapes. Such sentiments
will not ingratiate him with the chamber of commerce crowd but may
spur others to take a closer look at the consequences of our
one-use society.
</P>
<P>
   Heat-Moon's vast vocabulary is again on display, which no doubt
will draw Bronx cheers from some critics. I, for one, have never
felt it an author's duty to write to the lowest common denominator
and find no fault with Heat-Moon's approach. Most of the words that
many will find unfamiliar can easily be discerned from context, and
dictionaries remain a useful tool. Heat-Moon became something of a
literary sensation with the publication of ``Blue Highways,'' which
set him up as an important new voice in American letters. But his
next effort, ``PrairyErth,'' received a decidedly chilly reception,
622 pages about a sparsely populated county in Kansas apparently
being a bit too much for some. I happened to like ``PrairyErth,''
so much so that I put off my native Missourian's distrust of all
things Kansas and made a special trip through the tall-grass
prairie Heat-Moon had chronicled, and, for me at least, made come
alive.
</P>
<P>
   My own sentiments notwithstanding, the lack of critical acclaim
for ``PrairyErth'' significantly raised the stakes for
``River-Horse,'' with some believing that the latest work will make
or break Heat-Moon's reputation. His strength of voice, expert
characterization and vivid renderings of a truly remarkable and
fascinating voyage in ``River-Horse'' should bring accolades.
``River-Horse'' is a thoroughly enjoyable account of a journey and
of the American people.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
