<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3420 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CALIF-POLITICS-635(2T     12-08 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-POLITICS-635(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA'S MORE CRUCIAL THAN EVER, AND CANDIDATES KNOW IT, BIG
TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Call it the fire wall, the big state where Al Gore
and George W. Bush must stop any serious challenge to their
presumptive nominations for president.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the harbinger, the bellwether state where Republicans
and Democrats will first face each other on a single ballot in a
sign of their comparative appeal to the November electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the riddle, the sprawling state in which new electoral
rules and a speeded-up calendar make the usual dubious predictions
doubly dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody in the political world seems inclined to call the
March 7 California presidential primary anything but important.
</P>
<P>
   In both parties, that contest will decide about 20 percent of
the delegates needed for the nomination, and the leading candidates
all have Californians in crucial roles in their campaigns. They all
have spent substantial time in the state, not only raising money
but also showing the flag in visits of up to 10 days at a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, they all may be braving the winter rigors of Iowa
and New Hampshire, but come February, all hope to be here for
reasons considerably more compelling than their health.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only two ways of looking at California today,'' said
Gale Kaufman, former Sen. Bill Bradley's senior campaign adviser
here. ``That it's a really big state, and it's really, really
important, or that it's a really big state, and it's really, really
important after Iowa and New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the polls show Bush with more support here among
Republican voters than all his Republican rivals combined and Gore
with more than twice the level of Democratic support that Bradley
draws. But the experts agree that those numbers could change
quickly, depending on what happens in New Hampshire on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, for the first time next year under a new system
passed by voters here, the presidential candidates in California
will compete in a blanket primary, in which the names of all
candidates will appear on the same ballot, regardless of party, and
voters of any party may choose anyone they like.
</P>
<P>
   ``So even if one or both of the nominations has been settled by
California, there's an incentive for the nominee to work California
really hard to make that good showing,'' said Dan Schnur, a veteran
California Republican worker who is communications director for the
campaign of Sen. John McCain, whose best hope is that a strong
showing in New Hampshire might help him raise enough money to be a
viable competitor here in his neighboring state.
</P>
<P>
   In a further wrinkle, because the rules of both national parties
have long required that convention delegates be chosen solely by
party members, primary voters in each congressional district will
be asked to use computer-coded ballots specifying their party. That
way, the overall vote can be broken down by party for purposes of
selecting delegates. That conceivably means that one candidate _
say Bradley, with his potential appeal to crossover voters _ could
win more total votes than Gore, while Gore won the partisan contest
for actual delegates, sending a mixed message on a day when voters
in New York, Georgia, Ohio and most of New England will also choose
delegates. (On the Republican side, the winner of the most
Republican votes takes all a state's delegates, while Democratic
rules divide them proportionally.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You could have Bradley and McCain finish one and two over all
and the other two finish three and four, but win the delegates,''
said Bill Carrick, a leading Democratic consultant here who gets
calls seeking advice from both the Gore and Bradley campaigns. ``I
don't know. That would be a meltdown in pundit-land, in which
they'd all say, `Now, to the definitive results in the Georgia
primary.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   These days, the candidates are mostly conspicuous by their
absence, as Californians, not especially attentive to politics even
in the heat of campaigns, focus on the coming holidays and the
contenders work the coffee shops in colder climes. But their
campaigns are buzzing below the radar with varying degrees of
visibility.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other day, the McCain camp announced that it had added
Ken Khachighian, a California Republican strategist who has worked
on seven presidential campaigns dating back to Richard M. Nixon. On
Friday, the Bush campaign officially opened its statewide
headquarters in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Gore has locked up the support of most
of the state party establishment, and a major health-care workers
union, but some of his supporters worry that his operation here has
not been as vocal or as visible as it should be, compared with
Bradley's, which has offices in Sacramento, San Francisco and Los
Angeles and is led by Ms. Kaufman, a longtime Democratic consultant
who has scored some major successes in union campaigns in recent
years. Bradley's national campaign manager, Gina Glantz was raised
and cut her teeth in New Jersey politics, but for more than a
decade has lived in San Francisco, before leaving to run Bradley's
presidential campaign from its New Jersey headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's point person in California is Kathy Bowler, who has been
the executive director of the state Democratic Party and, until
recently, was still working out of the party's offices in
Sacramento. But she has now established a Gore 2000 office there,
and another is to open soon in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common complaint here about the Gore campaign from Day 1
has been that there was not enough of a physical presence on the
ground to keep people feeling tied in, and as if they were an
integral part of the campaign,'' said Garry South, the senior
political strategist for Gov. Gray Davis, who long ago endorsed
Gore. ``I think everyone involved is aware of that. Part of the
problem has obviously been that the Gore campaign was spending
money at too rapid a pace, and nobody wanted to spend any more here
right now. But this is California, and this is really the fire wall
for Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gore staff members say they have suffered from comparisons with
President Clinton's 1996 re-election campaign, when he ran
unopposed in the primaries and state party money helped pay for a
network of offices around California.
</P>
<P>
   They say that they fully expect Gore to ``become a resident'' of
California by February, as one senior aide put it. The campaign's
national press secretary, Chris Lehane, said Gore was positioned
``very well in California,'' because his policies on such issues as
opposition to further offshore oil-drilling, support for gun
control and abortion rights ``translate into good politics in
California.''
</P>
<P>
   South, the California governor's adviser, said he was hopeful
that the Gore forces would soon step up their efforts, but there is
some irony in his complaint, since Gore has taken particular pains
to woo California, which Clinton reclaimed for the Democrats in
1992 and which remains vital to any Democratic strategy for
retaining the White House. As vice president, Gore has visited the
state more than 60 times and named a former California congressman,
Tony Coelho, as his national campaign chairman.
</P>
<P>
   But both Bradley and Bush have been outpacing Gore in
fund-raising in the Silicon Valley, and in Hollywood, prominent
Bradley supporters like the entertainment moguls Barry Diller and
Michael Eisner have done much to take the shine off Gore's support
from other stars and executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The twin pillars of Bill Clinton's support here have always
been Silicon Valley and Hollywood, and neither of those communities
has been terrifically enthusiastic about Al Gore,'' said Schnur,
the McCain adviser who was a senior aide to former Gov. Pete
Wilson. ``So what do you have left? Gore's running a campaign
oriented toward the traditional Democratic constituencies'' like
labor, minorities and women. ``He's running an organizational
campaign in a state that isn't very organizational.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Bradley made a great show last summer of
taking a 10-day tour of the state, talking casually with
grass-roots groups in an effort to introduce himself, and although
his aides profess success in drawing volunteers, their candidate
has hardly surged in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last guy who said he was going to spend a lot of time and
meet people in California was Al Checchi,'' said Kam Kuwata, a
senior adviser to Sen. Dianne Feinstein, recalling the maverick
millionaire businessman who staged an expensive but spectacularly
unsuccessful race for the Democratic nomination for governor last
year. ``He did nothing but go around the state for a whole year,
and met several thousand people. Well, several thousand people is
nothing in this electorate. And I don't think even presidential
primary voters here will be tuned in until after the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the conventional wisdom here is that the only way to run
statewide campaigns is with widespread television advertising. But
the rates are so high _ about $1.5 million to run an advertisement
that would be seen 10 times by a typical viewer _ that no one here
expects candidates to go on the air until a couple of weeks before
Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to see one of those campaigns where you've got
the bio ad and the issue-framing ad and you run five ads before you
get around to doing anything,'' said Carrick, the consultant. ``It
will be the opposite of Iowa and New Hampshire: short on
organization and long on whirlwind media campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, California held its primary in June, and once upon a
time it was pivotal. But in recent years, the accelerated national
primary schedule left California an afterthought, so the state
moved up the date, first to late March and then to the beginning of
the month, only to find other states leapfrogging as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already seen the impact,'' said state Sen. James Brulte,
a Republican from San Bernardino County who recently stepped down
as state co-chairman of the Bush campaign, with the candidate's
encouragement, to become finance chairman of the debt-ridden state
Republican Party in an effort to build its ability to compete next
fall. ``Candidates have been crisscrossing the state for months.
It's no coincidence that George W. picked California as the venue
for announcing not only his first major education speech but his
first foreign policy speech.''
</P>
<P>
   But the ultimate impact remains anybody's guess. In the words of
Davis' strategist, South: ``This is really terra incognita.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
