<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3422 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-GRAMMOPHON-CENTENARY-     12-08 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMOPHON-CENTENARY-MUSIC-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MUSICAL MARCH THROUGH AN EVENTFUL ERA  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For good reasons, Deutsche Grammophon's Centenary Collection is
heavily concentrated in the decades after World War II, a period
including the history of the LP and the boom time of the CD.
</P>
<P>
   In these years, recording fidelity started from a high plateau
and generally climbed, and political and social side issues
gradually fell by the wayside. The performers are now better known
if not necessarily more distinguished.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the material here will be familiar to collectors of my
postwar generation. The conductor Ferenc Fricsay, for example,
looms as large as Wilhelm Furtwangler, and the violinist Wolfgang
Schneiderhan as large as David Oistrakh. Five big boxes present a
year-by-year march through the last half-century in 10 entries
each, with a CD or, in opera, a two-disc set representing a single
composer, work, performer or group.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the first postwar set (459 067-2) ranges from Monique Haas
playing Ravel and Stravinsky piano works in 1948 to Lorin Maazel
conducting the Berlin Philharmonic in Berlioz, Tchaikovsky and
Prokofiev in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Fricsay and Igor Markevitch also conduct, Scheiderhan and
Oistrakh play, and a young Dietrich Fischer-Dieskau sings. But to a
listener who learned much of his Bach from the Deutsche Grammophon
standby Karl Richter in the '60s and '70s, one of the more
fascinating items here is Bach as yet untouched by the early-music
movement: the first two cantatas of the ``Christmas Oratorio,''
with Fritz Lehman conducting the Berlin Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside the obvious in the next set (459 068-2, ranging from
1958 to 1967) _ Karajan leading the Berlin Philharmonic in
Beethoven, Karl Bohm conducting Mozart and Richard Strauss, and
Wilhelm Kempff playing Beethoven piano works _ an inevitable sense
of arbitrariness arises with the 1967 disc devoted to the guitarist
Narciso Yepes.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the producers unerringly pluck the highlight
from Eugen Jochum's set of Bruckner symphonies: the Seventh in a
glowing performance by the Berlin Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Grammophon's catalog has become so rich and diverse in
recent decades that even in a selection this vast, the sense of
arbitrariness takes firmer hold in the later sets. Contemporary
music, for example, is represented only by Hans Werner Henze's
Symphonies Nos. 5 and 6 (in 459 069-2, running from 1968 to 1977)
and Leonard Bernstein's theater music (in 459 070-2, from 1978 to
1987); the years 1988 to 1997 (459 071-2) offer nothing. And opera
ranges narrowly, with two discs from Karajan's ``Ring'' (1969),
Carlos Kleiber's ``Traviata'' (1977) and Carlo Maria Giulini's
``Falstaff'' (1982).
</P>
<P>
   But there are many treasures along the way: the pianist Martha
Argerich in the Chopin Preludes (1975); the violinist Gidon Kremer
in concertos by Mendelssohn and Tchaikovsky (1979); Vladimir
Horowitz's Moscow recital (1986); the pianist Krystian Zimerman in
Chopin and Liszt (1987); Pierre Boulez conducting Debussy and
Stravinsky (1991); the Emerson String Quartet in Beethoven (1997).
</P>
<P>
   Should a collection like this present the best or merely the
most typical of the company's labors? In the end, of course, it's
Deutsche Grammophon's party, and the label can represent itself as
it likes, a fact that makes all the more remarkable some decisions
in the earlier material: the ``Great Voices'' box discussed above
and, particularly, ``The Early Years'' (459 065-2), which in five
discs sweeps from 1898 to 1947.
</P>
<P>
   The set begins innocuously with the voice of Emile Berliner, the
company's founder, recorded in 1898. The same disc, ``Recording
Pioneers,'' offers vocal numbers by Enrico Caruso with and without
Nellie Melba, who on her own sings ``Auld Lang Syne,'' appropriate
to the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Three discs of orchestral, concerto and solo and chamber
recordings give little cause for offense beyond the inclusion of
Strauss' soulless ``Japanese Festival Music,'' conducted by the
composer in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   But the fifth disc offers a shocking Mozart Requiem, with Bruno
Kittel conducting the Berlin Philharmonic in 1941. Even listeners
aware that texts were bowdlerized to suit the Nazi regime may be
unprepared for the visceral impact of hearing them.
</P>
<P>
   All references to the Jewish roots of Christianity are purged.
``Quam olim Abrahae promisisti'' (``As was promised to Abraham'')
becomes ``Quam olim homini promisisti'' (``As was promised to
man''). ``Deus in Sion'' (``God in Zion'') becomes ``Deus in
coelis'' (``God in heaven'').
</P>
<P>
   The scrupulous liner notes quote a craven 1940 article in the
redoubtable journal Zeitschrift fur Musik: ``Mozart's Requiem is
the most profound and deeply moving of all Masses for the Dead that
are dedicated to the memory of the dearly departed and should not
be allowed to languish in obscurity simply because of a handful of
passages in the text that are unsuited to our age.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in its sheer perversity, this practice yields the most
disturbing _ and ultimately, in its inadvertent way, ``deeply
moving'' _ document in the entire collection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
