<SLUG> BC-FBC-ROSE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSE BOWL COACHES MEET THE PRESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The countdown to Rose Bowl Y2K began in
earnest Wednesday morning as coaches Tyrone Willingham of Stanford
and Barry Alvarez of Wisconsin spoke to the media about their
teams, their strategy and the Jan. 1 game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game will be a fitting bookend to an exciting century of
football in Pasadena,'' said Ken Burrows, president of the
Tournament of Roses Association, which has sponsored the game since
1902.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the business-as-usual nature of Wednesday's
get-together at Tournament House, the circumstances were a bit
unusual. Alvarez, recovering from knee surgery three weeks ago,
appeared as a talking head on a television monitor via satellite
from Madison, Wisc. He remained home on doctor's orders.
</P>
<P>
   Willingham, whose Cardinal is making its first Rose Bowl
appearance since 1972, appeared in person. He sat at a table next
to the television beaming Alvarez's image across the country.
Alvarez's Badgers are making their third Rose Bowl appearance since
1994. But, for the first time, they enter the game as favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked No. 4 in the nation, the Big Ten champion Badgers rode
the powerful legs of Heisman Trophy candidate Ron Dayne to the Rose
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford, ranked No. 22, got there on the strength of the
Pac-10's top-rated offense. But it also took a little help from a
faltering University of Washington, which lost two conference
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Jan. 1 match-up resembles the 1999 game when the Badgers
took on and dismantled UCLA's high-powered attack.
</P>
<P>
   The key in Y2K will be Dayne, the NCAA Division I career rushing
leader. To win, Stanford will need to stop Dayne. It's not going to
be an easy task, Willingham admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there is a method or a system to stop Ron
Dayne,'' Willingham said. ``What we would hope to do is slow him
down . . . I don't know if anybody has the ability to stop him.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Willingham praised the Badgers for their balanced
attack on offense and defense. He noted that Dayne isn't the sole
reason for Wisconsin's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get to three Rose Bowls with just being a one-person
show,'' Willingham said. ``They are an extremely talented, complete
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez doesn't expect Wisconsin to have an easy time with
Stanford. He compared the Cardinal's passing attack to Michigan's
and noted that the Wolverines passed for 257 yards and a pair of
touchdowns in their win over the Badgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really have some excellent skill players,'' Alvarez said.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the season it appeared that neither Stanford (8-3) nor
Wisconsin (9-2) had much chance of reaching the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers began the season with easy wins over Murray State
and Ball State only to lose to Cincinnati (17-12) and Michigan
(21-16) in consecuitive weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Through that difficult time, Alvarez said he tried to keep his
team focused.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we tried to emphasize was improvement,'' he said. ``The
bottom could have fallen out, but we still felt we were a good
football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's start was even shakier. The team's first game was a
69-17 loss to Texas. But the Cardinal seemingly redeemed itself
with wins over Pac-10 rivals Washington State, Arizona and UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Then the team sank to an another low a 44-39 loss to San Jose
State.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to navigate those difficult waters was to ``focus
on our next ballgame and what we could do to keep ourselves in the
best light,'' Willingham said.
</P>
<P>
   New Year's Day will be the first Rose Bowl meeting of Wisconsin
and Stanford. The Badgers have made five appearances and compiled a
2-3 record. The Cardinal has been to 11 Rose Bowls and is 5-5-1.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams have met four times; Wisconsin holds a 3-0-1
advantage. Their last meeting was in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams will arrive in the Southland and begin practice the
week before the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
