<HEADLINE>
UCLA, PEPPERDINE READY TO DO BATTLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two local schools, UCLA and Pepperdine, will
square off in two different sports. In each case, one eagerly
awaits the matchup more than the other.
</P>
<P>
   The women's volleyball teams have reached the NCAA Sweet 16 and
meet today at 2 p.m. PST at Penn State. UCLA has wanted a shot at
the Waves since Pepperdine overcame a two-game deficit and beat the
Bruins Nov. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the charge for retribution is captain Elisabeth Bachman.
She hasn't hit below .450 in the last 11 matches and her .441
percentage this season ranks second nationally. Against Pepperdine,
Bachman had 14 kills in 21 attempts with three errors _ a .524
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure we come out strong and stay strong,''
Bachman said. ``Once the match starts, everyone wants to make sure
that what happened last time won't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory means a matchup Friday against Minnesota or No.
1-ranked Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   The women's basketball teams face off Saturday at Pepperdine at
3 p.m. This is a matchup Pepperdine coach Mark Trakh has said is
key for the Waves.
</P>
<P>
   __ Early tennis rankings: UCLA's men earned the No. 1 preseason
ranking in the Intercollegiate Tennis Association team rankings.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins return four of six starters from last season's NCAA
runners-up, including All-Americans Jean-Noel Grinda, Brandon
Kramer and Jong-Min Lee.
</P>
<P>
   In the women's poll, UCLA (sixth), Pepperdine (eighth) and USC
(10th) made the top 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
