<HEADER>
A3427 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-KING-CASE09-COX     12-08 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-CASE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    King trial closes with conspiracy verdict
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ For the family of the Rev. Martin Luther King
Jr., vindication came swiftly Wednesday after a 31-year wait.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours after they started deliberating, a civil trial jury
of six blacks and six whites found that Loyd Jowers, the former
owner of a small-time greasy spoon restaurant, was guilty of being
part of a conspiracy to kill King.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like triumph over tragedy,'' said Dexter Scott King.
``The fact that 12 independent jurors have spoken is all we've
wanted and we've ever asked for.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts a period at the end of a chapter for my family.''
</P>
<P>
   King's widow and her four children were awarded $100 in damages,
to go toward funeral costs. Dexter King said the family will donate
the money to a charity to benefit Memphis sanitation workers, since
it was their plight that brought his father to Memphis when he was
gunned down April 4, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   The trial was not about money, the Kings have said since filing
the civil suit against Jowers last year. Instead, the family wanted
a jury to hear evidence that King was not killed solely by James
Earl Ray, the escaped convict who pleaded guilty in March 1969 but
recanted three days later.
</P>
<P>
   By pleading guilty, Ray never faced a jury. He died in April
1998 of liver disease while serving a 99-year sentence and still
insisting he was set up by a mysterious smuggler he only knew as
``Raul.''
</P>
<P>
   Although King's assassination has been investigated by federal
and Tennessee authorities, this was the first time a jury had
listened to any evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very gratifying to be given a opportunity before a
jury,'' said King family attorney William Pepper, who also
represented Ray in his final attempts to win a trial. ``This is all
James Earl Ray wanted. At least the family will benefit from this.
Most of the evidence that we presented would have been put forth in
a trial for Ray.''
</P>
<P>
   Juror David Morphy said he thought the assassination was too
complex to be accomplished by one person.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all thought it was a cut-and-dry case, with the evidence
that Pepper brought forth that there were a lot of people involved.
Everyone from the CIA to the military had involvement in it,'' said
Morphy. ``Jowers was involved in it, we felt.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 90-minute closing argument Wednesday, Pepper talked about
conspiracies, cover-ups and Jowers' admission on nationwide
television that he was a part of a conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Jowers, who owned Jim's Grill cafe in the same building where
Ray rented a room on the day of the shooting, told ABC News in 1993
that he received $100,000 to hire a hitman to kill King. The rear
of Jim's Grill was across the street from the Lorraine Motel, where
King was staying and was shot.
</P>
<P>
   Jowers said he got the money from Memphis produce dealer Frank
Liberto, who has been tied to a New Orleans organized crime family.
According to Pepper, the hitman was Earl J. Clark, a now-deceased
Memphis police officer who had won honors at the FBI Academy for
his sharpshooting skills.
</P>
<P>
   Although parts of Jowers' story have changed over the years, he
said the assassin fired his shot from behind Jim's Grill and then
handed Jowers the still-smoking gun to hide.
</P>
<P>
   Jowers' attorney, Lewis Garrison, said the lawsuit should have
been dismissed because the statute of limitations had expired.
Garrison contended the Kings should have filed the lawsuit around
the time of Jowers' TV appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Garrison said, while it might be reasonable to conclude
that King was the target of a conspiracy, any role Jowers could
have played would have been minor.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison told the jury it was hard to believe that ``the owner
of a greasy spoon and an escaped convict'' could have pulled off
King's assassination. Jowers, who at 73 is suffering from cerebral
arteriosclerosis, was absent from court for most of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The jury's verdict was welcomed by some spectators, including
Charles A.L. Oliver Jr., who said he has listened to every word of
the monthlong trial since the second week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a vested interest in finding the truth. I always felt
there was a conspiracy,'' said Oliver, 43. ``Now we can be free and
get on with our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   For many in Memphis, the end of the trial brought closure for
them personally.
</P>
<P>
   Tending his niece's gift shop on Beale Street, Lafayette Davis
said he delivered bread to the Lorraine Motel the day King was
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are concerned about the trial because people want to
know what happened,'' said Davis, who has lived in Memphis since
1951.
</P>
<P>
   He said he missed King the morning of the assassination so he
and a friend went to the home of the Rev. Samuel B. Kyles to meet
King, who was to have dinner with the Kyles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were waiting at Kyles' house for King,'' said Davis. ``He
never made it.''
</P>
<P>
   Neady Masters never got to meet him, either. On the stormy night
of April 3, Masters' sister saw King's ``I've Been to the
Mountaintop'' sermon at Mason's Temple. She told Masters how
inspiring it was and that she felt electricity after touching King.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me I had to go see him,'' said Masters, 57, adding
that on April 4, she and a friend headed to the motel to meet King.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, traffic was bad that day, so my friend turned
around,'' said Masters. ``As we were driving back, we heard on the
radio that he had been shot. We could have been there. Had I been
driving, we would have been there.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why she has been at the trial. She sat intently through
most of the proceedings. During breaks, she talked to members of
the King family, telling stories and taking pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to hear the truth,'' said Masters. ``I have children
and grandchildren and I want them to hear and see history. And to
know the feel of the Kings. To feel the electricity.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial will have wide-ranging effects, Dexter King said.
</P>
<P>
   ``History will have to be rewritten,'' he said. ``People can no
longer look the other way.'' Outside the courtroom Wednesday
morning, about 100 schoolchildren walked around with signs reading,
``Who killed Martin Luther King.''
</P>
<P>
   Across town at LeMoyne-Owen College, the only historically black
college in Memphis, Clodetra McGee and Samantha Mitchell, both
freshmen, said they have been living with theories about the
assassination since birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they should find out who really killed Dr. King, so
that he can rest in peace,'' said Mitchell, 19. ``I never thought
James Earl Ray did it. I always thought it was a cover-up.''
</P>
<P>
   John Campbell, a prosecutor with the Shelby County district
attorney general's office who has investigated the assassination
but was not involved in the Jowers trial, said the conspiracy
claims have no merit. Campbell said several of Jowers' friends and
associates said he was merely hoping to get a movie or book deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at this off and on for five years,'' Campbell said,
``and I've still seen nothing that would change my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno ordered a limited
investigation by the Justice Department into two allegations of a
conspiracy. One was Jowers' possible involvement; the other was a
claim by former FBI Agent Donald Wilson that he found papers when
Ray's Ford Mustang was found in Atlanta after the assassination
that would support a conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokeswoman Carol Florman said Wednesday the
review is ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   Headed back to Atlanta to prepare for an 11 a.m. news conference
at the King Center, Dexter King said he hopes the verdict silences
critics who bashed the family's pursuit of Jowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the critics, you would hope they will be converted or
be able to admit they were wrong,'' King said. ``For my family,
this is the end of the road. Our final legal remedy. I think my dad
would be proud of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
