<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN SACHS TO FOCUS ITS FOUNDATION ON EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co., which set aside $200 million
from its public stock offering earlier this year to endow a new
foundation named after the company, said Wednesday that the
institution would focus exclusively on education.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said that former co-chairman John Whitehead
would serve as chairman of the new entity, which will be the sixth
largest corporate foundation in the country and be called the
Goldman Sachs Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Bell-Rose, the former counsel at the Andrew W. Mellon
Foundation and an expert on underachieving minority students, was
named as president.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs chairman and chief executive Henry Paulson said
that while there was debate on how much money to put into the
foundation _ one proposal called for $350 million _ there was no
debate on the focus on education. He said that $200 million was
seen as ``enough to make a difference.'' If it turns out not to be
enough, he said, more money can be added.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has raised about $3.7 billion in its stock
offering, said that its executives will match the new foundation's
giving in the first year and possibly in the future years.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is being created as financial markets and
corporate profits have been rising but corporate philanthropy has
remained flat. Whitehead recently teamed up with actor Paul Newman
and about three dozen corporate executives to press companies to
raise their giving.
</P>
<P>
   Several philanthropy experts said Wednesday that while it is not
unusual for newly wealthy executives to give money to charity, they
could not think of another example in which a company had set up a
foundation out of the earnings of a public stock offering, as
Goldman has.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's independence from the Goldman Sachs corporation
also is unusual. Three of the foundation's initial seven trustees
will be Goldman executives. But Whitehead said the foundation's
bylaws do not require that representation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty rare to find a foundation set up in the name of a
company that isn't under its control,'' said Curt Weeden, a former
corporate philanthropy executive who now runs the Corporate
Contributions Management Academy in Palm Coast, Fla., which runs
programs on corporate philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehead said that there were advantages to working closely
with Goldman while remaining free to make independent decisions.
Ms. Bell-Rose said the foundation plans to make a small number of
large gifts each year in the United States and abroad, and will
probably give ten $1 million grants, each matched by Goldman Sachs,
next year. The foundation's new trustees also will include John
Thornton, Goldman's president, and Thomas Payzant, superintendent
of the Boston public schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
