</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SYRIA-TALKS-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL AND SYRIA TO RESUME HIGH-LEVEL PEACE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Subs 2nd graf to make it Assad, not al-Assad; subs 6th graf
to delete reference to Yitzhak Rabin) (EDS: 2nd take will move by 9:15) 
(ART ADV: Photos _ NYT10,11,12 _ are being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton announced on Wednesday that
Israel and Syria would launch top-level peace talks here next week
after a nearly four-year suspension. He said both sides wanted to
reach an agreement as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough came after Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright met with the Syrian leader, Hafez Assad, in Damascus on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The final details were arranged in a series of phone calls on
Wednesday morning from Clinton to Assad, who said he would send his
foreign minister, Farouk al-Sharaa, to Washington, and to the
Israeli prime minister, Ehud Barak, who will be the chief Israeli
negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   ``These negotiations will be high-level, comprehensive, and
conducted with the aim of reaching an agreement as soon as
possible,'' Clinton told a news conference on Wednesday afternoon.
He called the decision of the two leaders to start negotiations ``a
significant breakthrough for it will allow them to deal with each
other face to face, and that is the only way to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said there was no guarantee that the talks would
yield success, but said they left open the goal laid out by Barak a
few months ago: to seek a comprehensive peace settlement embracing
Israel, the Palestinians, Syria and Lebanon by next September.
</P>
<P>
   One of the barriers to resuming the talks between Syria and
Israel, which broke off in early 1996, has been an argument over
what both sides had agreed to when the talks stopped.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the past negotiations and the new talks is the
question of the return to Syria of the Golan Heights, which Israel
seized during the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several months, as the possibility of talks have
been discussed and the administration has tried to find a formula
for their resumption, Assad has insisted that Israel agreed four
years ago to withdraw to the border that existed between the two
countries on June 4, 1967.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis have refused to agree to this precondition and have
said that the 1996 talks ended inconclusively on this point.
</P>
<P>
   The president said on Wednesday that both sides had agreed to
resume negotiations ``from the point where they left off,'' but
Clinton did not specify what that point was.
</P>
<P>
   This appeared to be a face-saving mechanism for both sides, and
Clinton declined to elaborate on the terms of the negotiations when
questioned during the press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Berger, the national security adviser, said in an
interview after Clinton's statement that ``everything'' would be on
the table next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``All issues will be on the table _ borders, security and the
nature of the peace,'' Berger said. ``These are the issues that
will be determined in the negotiations.'' Even though Assad was
sending his foreign minister, Assad ``will be the chief decision
maker,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been lots of talk at lots of levels,'' Berger said.
``Now we've got Barak and the foreign minister on behalf of
Assad.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement on Wednesday was the culmination of a series of
phone calls by Clinton _ 31 in all to Barak and Assad since August
_ and a letter from the president to Assad three weeks ago, Berger
said.
</P>
<P>
   In that letter, Clinton gave a ``very strong argument that now's
the moment,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Assad told Albright on Tuesday that he was prepared to respond
favorably to the letter and start negotiations where they left off.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called Barak on Wednesday morning and told him of
Assad's willingness to talk, Berger recounted. The Israeli leader
suggested that the two sides start ``as soon as possible,'' an idea
that Clinton relayed to Assad by telephone. With the Syrian's
agreement to a prompt start, Clinton called Barak back to iron out
more details, Berger said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
