<HEADER>
A3443 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-E-COMMERCE-HOLIDAYS-A     12-08 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-HOLIDAYS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EToys EDGES TOYSRUS.COM IN RANKING OF ONLINE USERS  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The holiday battle to be the leading toy store in cyberspace
shifted last week as Etoys, the Internet startup, pulled ahead of
Toysrus.com, the Web site of the big toy chain, according to the
research company Media Metrix.
</P>
<P>
   Etoys became the fourth most visited commerce site over all,
with an average of 384,000 people visiting the site each day last
week, an increase of 53 percent from the previous week and 72
percent from the most recent three-week average.
</P>
<P>
   Toysrus.com fell to fifth place, with 314,000 daily users, up
2.3 percent from the previous week and 23 percent from the most
recent three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   With Internet sales expected to triple this year over last year,
many companies expect the holiday season to help sort the ultimate
winners from the losers online. And the toy market is shaping up as
a typical struggle between well-known retail chains, like Toys
``R'' Us, and fast moving Internet upstarts, like Etoys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toys `R' Us may be generating traffic by virtue of its brand
name in the real world,'' said Ken Cassar, an analyst with Jupiter
Communications. ``But when people came to the site, people may not
have found the retail experience they had expected and not have
purchased because of that. Etoys has a better sense of how to
merchandise on an Internet site.''
</P>
<P>
   Over all, Media Metrix found that eBay, the auction site, was
the most visited site, as in the previous week, followed by
Amazon.com. Buy.com, a discounter of computers and other goods,
jumped into third position from seventh place.
</P>
<P>
   Mypoint.com, Vvitaminshoppe.com, and eGreetings.com all dropped
off the Top 10 ten list from two weeks ago to last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Media Metrix ratings are one of the best publicly available
windows into holiday buying trends on the Internet, but they have
significant limits. Using a method similar to the Nielsen ratings
for television, Media Metrix monitors the Web surfing behavior of
15,000 computer users in the United States. Still, some Internet
companies complain that Media Metrix's ratings underestimate their
own user count, and most likely underrepresent users in offices and
universities.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, Media Metrix measures the number of people who
view sites, not those who actually buy from them. And sites vary
widely in how well they persuade visitors to become paying
customers.
</P>
<P>
   That difference can be seen in one measure of actual buying
behavior, an index by NextCard, an issuer of MasterCard and Visa
credit cards, of the online sites where its 140,000 cardholders
make purchases. In November, a period in which Media Metrix says
Toysrus.com had more visitors than Etoys, Toysrus.com was not among
the top 25 sites patronized by NextCard customers, while Etoys
ranked No. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly eBay, ranked No. 1 by Media Metrix, was ranked 13th by
Next Card, indicating that eBay attracts a large audience of people
who regularly look at and bid at auctions, but that the number of
actual purchases is far less.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Media Metrix nor NextCard can determine how well
Amazon.com is doing at selling merchandise other than books. Amazon
is spending a considerable portion of its marketing budget to
promote its toy department, for example. But Amazon continues to
increase its lead in NextCard's tally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazon has really pulled away from the pack,'' said Jamie
Hale, the director of new product development for NextCard. He said
that Amazon now represents nearly 40 percent of all online
transactions by Next Card holders.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Toysrus.com has slowed down, three of the four sites
that have gained the most visitors recently, according to Media
Metrix, were linked to traditional brick-and-mortar retailers.
KBKids.com, affiliated with KB Toys, the No. 2 chain, increased its
visitors by 132 percent. KB is spending $40 million to advertise
its web site this holiday season. Both Sears.com and Wal-Mart.com
more than doubled their traffic over the previous three weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
