<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL, SYRIA TO RESUME TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In a dramatic breakthrough in the Middle East peace
process, Israel and Syria agreed Wednesday to resume negotiations
that had been suspended for more than three years.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton announced the development, saying that talks
between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian Foreign
Minister Farouk al-Sharaa would be held in Washington next week and
that they would begin at ``the point where they left off'' in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``These negotiations will be high-level, comprehensive, and
conducted with the aim of reaching an agreement as soon as
possible,'' Clinton said. ``Peace has long been within our sight.
Today, it is within our grasp, and we must seize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a nationally televised news conference from the
State Department, Clinton added, ``There can be no illusion here.
On all tracks the road ahead will be arduous. . . . They face hard
choices. They will have to stand firmly against all those who seek
to derail the peace, and sadly there are too many of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Syria and Israel suspended negotiations 3 1/2 years ago amid a
wave of terrorist attacks against the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the announcement after Secretary of State Madeleine
K. Albright, who is touring the Middle East and who met with Syrian
President Hafez Assad on Tuesday, brought Barak a clarification of
Syria's position.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters after that briefing, Barak said, ``There
clearly is a unique opportunity. We have so many other things to do
than to be deployed for another generation or two along the border
and bury our youngsters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press, meanwhile, quoted a senior US official as
saying that Syria had made key concessions that allowed the
resumption of direct talks.
</P>
<P>
   Assad had held a tough bargaining position insisting that he
would not restart negotiations unless Israel picked up where he
says the two sides left off under the government of slain Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   Assad said that Rabin had promised that Israel would return to
the borders of June 4, 1967, before it captured the strategic Golan
Heights in the Six-Day War.
</P>
<P>
   Israel denied having made such a promise.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, the US official said, Damascus agreed that the
talks could resume without conditions. While Syria was not dropping
its demand for the Golan, it was no longer insisting the talks open
with the assumption of a full Israeli pullback, said the official,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Another Syrian concession, the official said, was its agreement
to have Sharaa head its delegation. Talks with Israel in the past
have involved lower-ranking diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Eyal Zisser, a Tel Aviv University professor who has written
extensively on Syria, said, ``This is a very dramatic development.
We have not had talks with Syria for three years and we have never
had talks on such a high level.''
</P>
<P>
   Zisser said, however, that Clinton's assertion that the talks
will begin ``where they left off'' in 1996 could indicate that
Assad received key assurances that heightened his expectations.
</P>
<P>
   And Zisser cautioned, ``If the Syrians come with an assumption
that they will get what they want and then they realize this is not
what Barak had in mind, it could become a problem quickly and end
in a fiasco.''
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough comes at a time when the Palestinian-Israeli
track had been bogged down over the issue of Jewish settlement
expansion and over which 5 percent of West Bank land Israel should
turn over to the Palestinians next. The land was to have been
handed over a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Albright announced late Wedneday night, however, after meeting
with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in Ramallah, that he had
agreed to resume negotiations with Israel and pledged a ``good
faith'' effort to find a way to settle the land dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, meanwhile, called the announcement of renewed
Israeli-Syrian talks good news for the Palestinian people and Arab
nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that peace moves on all tracks, especially the
Syrian and the Lebanese tracks, and I wish these negotiations
success,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said Clinton would not devote energy to helping Israel
and Syria make peace at the expense of the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fully understand that the Palestinian issues are at the
core of a comprehensive settlement,'' Albright said. ``One track is
not being favored over another and actions will not be taken with
one at the expense of the other.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Syrian-Israeli talks lead to an agreement, that could
pave the way for Israel to reach a settlement with its northern
neighbor Lebanon, where 30,000 Syrian troops are deployed.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Lebanon, where Israel occupies a roughly 9-mile wide
swath of territory it calls its ``security zone,'' is the last
active war front in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   In an almost daily spiral of recriminations, Israeli troops have
been mired in a war against guerrillas from the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah, which opposes the Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
   One of Barak's central campaign promises when he was elected
five months ago was to bring Israeli soldiers home from Lebanon
within one year.
</P>
<P>
   But to accomplish that, it has always been clear that a deal
with Syria had to be reached first.
</P>
<P>
   The core of the Israeli-Syrian dispute is the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   A return to the pre-1967 war borders would mean Syria would
regain control of the northern bank of the Sea of Galilee and other
valuable water assets in the region that are now under Israeli
control.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Barak's office released a statement aired on
Israeli Television stating that Israel would not agree to withdraw
to the 1967 borders but ``at the same time it expressed willingness
for a territorial compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli left generally accepts the giveback of the Golan as
the only way to achieve peace with Syria and end the bloody
conflict in Lebanon. The Israeli right sees any giveback of the
strategic Golan as a fatal security risk. Barak will have to
delicately balance the two political sides as he tries to bring his
coalition government along the path to peace without alienating
either side in a way that could disintegrate his coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Ramona Bar-Lev, a spokesman for the Golan Residents Committee,
said, ``We are shocked. Barak promised us that he would speak to us
before resuming the talks and instead we are left to find out about
it on CNN.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If these talks are to `pick up where they left off,' as
Clinton described it, it would mean full withdrawal. This would
mean the end of all we have invested here, the end of security for
Israel, for its water needs,'' Bar-Lev added. ``This is a disaster.
We will do everything necessary to be sure it doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
