<HEADER>
A3452 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-VCHIP-PRIMER-TEX     12-08 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VCHIP-PRIMER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING YOU ALWAYS WANTED TO KNOW ABOUT THE V-CHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHAT IS THE V-CHIP?
</P>
<P>
   The v-chip is used to filter programming as it comes into your
TV set. It's an electronic chip that works with your television,
cable box, VCR or its own retrofit device to block shows that
parents may feel are inappropriate for their children.
</P>
<P>
   Between the ages of 3 and 12, the average child will see 8,000
killings and 100,000 violent acts on television, according to a
study by the National Association for Family and Community
Education. Many parents want to block programs with a lot of
violence and sex.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the v-chip comes in. The ``v'' stands for
violence.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 8, 1996, President Clinton signed into law the
Telecommunications Act of 1996, which included a section
authorizing the v-chip. Section 551 is called ``Parental Choice in
Television Programming.'' It gave broadcasters the chance to
voluntarily create a television ratings system and broadcast
signals containing those ratings. The ratings don't apply to news
and sports.
</P>
<P>
   HOW DOES IT WORK?
</P>
<P>
   The chip intercepts the ratings signal transmitted by
broadcasters, and passes it to your television. The program will be
denied access to your television if it exceeds a ratings limit set
by the television's owner _ that means parents.
</P>
<P>
   WHO DESIGNED THE V-CHIP?
</P>
<P>
   John Olivo, an electrical engineer, created the v-chip to help
parents stop kids from calling adult telephone hot lines. He
applied for a patent in 1987, and received patent approval in 1989.
Shortly afterward, he adapted his invention for use in VCRs, and
later for television. Olivo's patent was licensed by Parental
Guide, an Omaha, Neb., company that develops screening devices. The
company is now marketing the v-chip.
</P>
<P>
   DO ALL TELEVISIONS HAVE ONE?
</P>
<P>
   Not yet, but most of them will soon. The Federal Communications
Commission mandated that all TV sets 13 inches or larger
manufactured after Jan. 1, 2000, have v-chips installed. For older
TVs, a stand-alone retrofit device is available.
</P>
<P>
   HOW DO THE RATINGS WORK?
</P>
<P>
   The TV ratings system, also known as TV Parental Guidelines, was
created by the National Association of Broadcasters, the National
Cable Television Association and the Motion Picture Association of
America. You see these ratings in the top left corner of your TV
screen during the first 15 seconds of rated programming. Shows that
are longer than one hour have the ratings displayed for 15 seconds
at the start of each hour.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S IT RATED?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quick guide to TV parental guidelines
</P>
<P>
   TV-Y, ``All children''
</P>
<P>
   This programming is appropriate for all children. It's designed
specifically for very young children and shouldn't frighten them.
</P>
<P>
   TV-Y7, ``Directed to older children''
</P>
<P>
   Programs with this rating are designed for children 7 and older.
Fantasy and comedic violence may be included.
</P>
<P>
   TV-G, ``General audience''
</P>
<P>
   This rating doesn't mean the program is designed for all ages,
although many parents may feel comfortable letting young children
watch it unattended. The program has little or no violence, few or
no sexual situations and no strong language.
</P>
<P>
   TV-PG, ``Parental guidance suggested''
</P>
<P>
   Parents may want to watch these programs with their kids.
Material unsuitable for younger children is presented.
</P>
<P>
   TV-14, ``Parents strongly cautioned''
</P>
<P>
   Parents are encouraged to monitor viewing of this program, as it
contains material unsuitable for children younger than 14 to view
alone. It may contain sexual content, violence and strong language.
</P>
<P>
   TV-MA, ``Mature audience only''
</P>
<P>
   These programs are designed for adults and may be unsuitable for
children younger than 17.
</P>
<P>
   EXTENDERS
</P>
<P>
   Extra letters, called extenders, sometimes follow regular TV
ratings. They provide additional information about content by which
programming can be screened. Each rating level increases the
intensity of the extender. For example, a movie rated TV-PG with a
V extender will contain bits of violence. A movie rated TV-14 with
a V extender will have intense violence. The extenders are:
</P>
<P>
   S Sex: This program contains sexual situations
</P>
<P>
   L Language: This program contains strong language
</P>
<P>
   V Violence
</P>
<P>
   D Suggestive Dialogue
</P>
<P>
   FV Fantasy violence: This extender is only used with programming
rated TV-Y7 and indicates cartoon violence
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
