u a BC-MOBSTER-PLEADS-BOS &LR;      12-08 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOBSTER-PLEADS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULGER ALLY EXPECTED TO PLEAD GUILTY TO RACKETEERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Reputed New England Mafia Boss Francis ``Cadillac
Frank'' Salemme is poised to plead guilty Thursday to a federal
racketeering indictment that alleges he killed four men and plotted
with South Boston crime boss James ``Whitey'' Bulger to control the
region's illegal rackets, according to sources familiar with the
case.
</P>
<P>
   If US District Judge Mark L. Wolf accepts Salemme's plea, the
66-year-old don, who has been jailed without bail since August
1995, could be a free man in 6 1/2 years under an agreement with
federal prosecutors, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The plea agreement calls for a sentence ranging from 10 years
and 10 months to 13 1/2 years, but Salemme will be credited with
the time he has been jailed while awaiting trial in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike confessed Mafia hitman John Martorano, who has been
granted leniency in exchange for his cooperation against Bulger,
who is a fugitive, and Stephen ``The Rifleman'' Flemmi, Salemme has
not agreed to cooperate with investigators, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   US Attorney Donald K. Stern's office declined to comment
Wednesday on Salemme's scheduled change of plea; lawyers Anthony
Cardinale and John Mitchell, who represent Salemme, could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for federal prosecutors to negotiate plea
agreements without getting cooperation from defendants in
complicated racketeering cases that would involve lengthy trials.
This case is even more complex than most because of revelations
that Salemme's codefendants, Bulger and Flemmi, were FBI
informants.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with Salemme could cause a shift in strategy by
prosecutors who brought the indictment five years ago and are not
even close to a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Salemme's plea will leave only Flemmi, Bulger, and reputed
mobster Robert DeLuca in the case. But it appears DeLuca may not be
in the case for much longer.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Randy Gioia, who represents DeLuca, said Wednesday,
``Bob DeLuca has absolutely no desire to remain in a case where his
only codefendants are government informants, the functional
equivalent of FBI agents. And he has absolutely no connection to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   If Flemmi and Bulger become the only defendants remaining in the
case, prosecutors could decide to drop the racketeering indictment
and file new charges against the pair.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Salemme's lawyers had planned to argue that he should
be released on bail as there is still no trial date set in the case
that has dragged on for five years in the wake of the disclosure
that Bulger and Flemmi were longtime FBI informants.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Salemme to plead guilty comes a few months after
he lost a bid to get the landmark racketeering case dismissed on
the grounds that Bulger and Flemmi were working for the FBI and
therefore could not also have been genuine members of a
racketeering enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Wolf held lengthy hearings and listened to a parade
of witnesses who exposed a cozy relationship between Bulger and
Flemmi and their FBI handlers. One former FBI supervisor confessed
that he pocketed $7,000 in bribes from the informants and routinely
tipped them to cases.
</P>
<P>
   In a 661-page decision in September, Wolf refused to dismiss the
racketeering case or toss out a key piece of evidence: FBI tapes of
a 1989 Mafia induction ceremony in Medford that was attended by
mobsters from around New England.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf rejected Flemmi's claim that the FBI had promised him and
Bulger immunity from prosecution. Still, Flemmi enjoyed a partial
victory as Wolf ruled that prosecutors are barred from using any
evidence agains Flemmi that was gleaned directly or indirectly from
him while he was an informant.
</P>
<P>
   Stern's office is waiting for approval from the solicitor
general to appeal Wolf's ruling. Meanwhile, more hearings are
expected in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The racketeering indictment alleges that Salemme, who reputedly
assumed control of the Patriarca crime family in 1991, and Bulger
divided up illegal rackets through New England, controlling
bookmaking and loansharking, and shaking down drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Salemme is charged with killing four men during the 1960s gang
wars, but earlier Wolf warned that he might dismiss the
racketeering acts involving murder because they were added late in
the case and might have involved a misuse of the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The murder victims include three brothers, Edward, Walter, and
William Bennett, and another man, Richard Grasso, who were all
killed in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Salemme spent 15 years in prison for trying to kill a lawyer in
1968 by blowing up his car. The attorney, John E. Fitzgerald, whose
leg was blown off, represented mob-hitman-turned-informant Joseph
``Baron'' Barboza. Flemmi was initially charged in the attack, but
the charges were later dropped.
</P>
<P>
   After his release from prison in 1988, Salemme became a ``made''
member of the Mafia and quickly rose through the ranks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
