<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CDREVIEW-NASTRADAMUS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S HOPE `NASTRADAMUS' FORETELLS FUTURE OF HIP-HOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
by MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there's one thing there's not a shortage of this holiday
season, it's hip-hop releases. What there is a shortage of, though,
is good hip-hop releases. And when we say good, we don't mean rap's
same ol', same ol', which is: discs filled with gunfire,
woman-bashing, I'm-so-great-bow-before-me posing,
ya-better-buy-my-records threats and endless tales of how fine the
high-life is and how horrible it must be to live without stacks of
money, garages full of limos and an endless posse of girls, girls,
girls. That stuff got old about, oh, five years ago. So it's
incredibly refreshing when a hip-hop artist refuses to go with such
a shallow flow, and for the past few years, Long Island rapper Nas
(mom calls him Nasir Jones) has done just that, crafting records
with down-to-earth lyrics and strong, memorable melodies. And,
unlike Will Smith, Puff Daddy and other top-drawer hip-hop stars,
Nas doesn't rely solely on samples, although he does his share of
pop-catalog pilfering. Yet for the most part, Nas is somewhat of a
hip-hop outsider, which, thankfully, he proves once again on
``Nastradamus,'' his second effort this year (back in April, he
released the equally good ``I Am ...''). Here you will find very
little posing, very little misogyny and very few samples _ you just
get a lot of great hip-hop. In Nas' case, this means you get
stories about looking at life through the broken window of an
apartment in the projects. You see your friends die (''Shoot 'Em
Up''), grow up and move on (''Some of Us Have Angels'') or stay
behind (''Life We Chose''). Never once does Nas bash or condone
gang life (although he does attack drug use); he simply raps about
the chaos swirling around him; he's not pro- or anti-anything, just
an observer. And the mellow-voiced singer wraps these observations
around different styles of music, from the soulful balladry of
``Project Windows'' (that's Ron Isley singing backup) to the
jazz-tinged ``Life We Chose,'' which stylishly samples Maceo
Parker's ``Peace Fugue.'' In between, there are nods to pop and
rock, making ``Nastradamus'' an overwhelmingly eclectic listen _
and an intelligent one, as well. (Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 2137EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3464 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-SYRIA-TALKS-AR     12-08 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SYRIA-TALKS-ART-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL AND SYRIA TO RESUME HIGH-LEVEL PEACE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for rewriting throughout; story is now complete) 
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT10,11,12 _ are being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton announced on Wednesday that
Israel and Syria would begin top-level peace talks here next week
after a nearly four-year suspension. He said both sides wanted to
reach an agreement as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came after Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright met with the Syrian leader, Hafez Assad, in Damascus on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The final details were arranged in telephone calls on Wednesday
morning from President Clinton to Assad, who agreed to send Foreign
Minister Farouk al-Shara to Washington, and to Prime Minister Ehud
Barak, who will be the chief Israeli negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   ``These negotiations will be high-level, comprehensive and
conducted with the aim of reaching an agreement as soon as
possible,'' Clinton told a news conference on Wednesday afternoon.
He called the decision to start negotiations ``a significant
breakthrough, for it will allow them to deal with each other face
to face, and that is the only way to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said there was no guarantee the talks would
succeed, but he said the talks left open the goal laid out by Barak
a few months ago: to seek a comprehensive peace settlement
embracing Israel, the Palestinians, Syria and Lebanon by next
September.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the negotiations is the question of the return
to Syria of the Golan Heights, which Israel seized during the 1967
war and which it has considered important to its security.
</P>
<P>
   One barrier to resuming the talks, which broke off in early
1996, has been an argument over what both sides had agreed to when
the talks stopped.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several months, as the administration has tried to
find a formula to reopen talks, Assad has insisted that Israel
agreed four years ago to withdraw to the June 4, 1967, border. But
the Israelis have said the talks ended inconclusively on this
point.
</P>
<P>
   The president said on Wednesday that both sides had agreed to
resume negotiations ``from the point where they left off,'' but
Clinton did not specify what that point was. His phrasing appeared
to offer a way for both sides to save face, and he declined to
elaborate on the terms for resumption of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Berger, the national security adviser, said in an
interview after Clinton's statement that ``everything'' would be on
the table next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``All issues will be on the table _ borders, security and the
nature of the peace,'' Berger said. ``These are the issues that
will be determined in the negotiations.'' Even though Assad was
sending his foreign minister, Assad ``will be the chief decision
maker,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been lots of talk at lots of levels,'' Berger said.
``Now we've got Barak and the foreign minister on behalf of
Assad.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement on Wednesday was the culmination of a series of
phone calls by Clinton _ 31 in all to Barak and Assad since August
_ and a letter from the president to Assad three weeks ago, Berger
said.
</P>
<P>
   In that letter, Clinton gave a ``very strong argument that now's
the moment,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Assad told Albright on Tuesday that he was prepared to respond
favorably to the letter and start talks where they had left off.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called Barak on Wednesday morning and told him of
Assad's willingness to talk, Berger said. The Israeli suggested the
two sides start ``as soon as possible,'' an idea Clinton relayed to
Assad. With the Syrian president's agreement to a prompt start,
Clinton called Barak back to iron out more details, Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the new talks represents a fulfillment of a
pledge made by Barak soon after he came into office: that he would
take on what his predecessors had refused to do and conduct talks
with the Palestinians and Syrians on two tracks, but
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   (START OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Most Israeli leaders seem to have felt that their public was not
prepared to absorb two big undertakings that would involve hard
compromises _ one to determine the shape of a Palestinian entity,
which will involve negotiations on giving up areas of the West
Bank; the other on an accord with Syria that will mean talks on
relinquishing the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the basics of the new Israeli-Syrian talks were defined
by former Secretary of State Warren Christopher, who shuttled more
than 20 times between Israel and Damascus until the talks collapsed
in early 1996.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Officials have said the coming negotiations will focus on the
conditions under which Israel would relinquish control of the Golan
Heights. These include the extent and timing of the Israeli
withdrawal, the size of demilitarized zones on either side of the
boundary, an early-warning station for Israel atop Mount Hermon,
which dominates the border, and the makeup of an international
observer force.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis also want ``normalization'' of relations with
Syria, including a halt to Syria's support of terrorist groups, an
opening of Syria's border and an end to the Syrian dogma that
Israel is the enemy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the last several months, Assad has told militant Palestinian
groups based in Damascus to end their ``armed struggle'' and
transform themselves into political organizations. Syria remains on
the State Department's list of nations that it says support
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   These moves were interpreted as an effort by Assad to establish
his seriousness about wanting to start talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   When Barak come to office, he indicated that he would be willing
to deal on the Golan Heights. President Assad welcomed the new
overture and indicated that he was interested, but in the last few
months his sentiments appeared to have cooled. But Assad is said to
be ailing and may want to seal a deal before handing power to a
successor.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to prepare the Israeli public for the possibility
of a deal, Barak said on Israeli television in October that
negotiations would entail ``painful territorial compromises,''
which would particularly affect the thousands of settlers who now
populate the regions.
</P>
<P>
   In his news conference, Clinton said he hoped the resumption of
talks with Syria would lead to talks between Israel and Lebanon.
Barak has said he wants to live up to another campaign pledge: to
withdraw Israeli forces from Lebanon by July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Assad called the Lebanese president, Emile Lahud, late on
Wednesday to urge him to start discussions, according to reports
from the region.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, administration officials said they were
surprised, even taken aback, by the outcome of Assad's meeting with
Albright. As an indication of how unprepared some in the
administration were, Albright is scheduled to be in Panama and in
Europe next week, when Barak and Shara are due here.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said Clinton would most likely meet with the Israeli
leader and the Syrian foreign minister before the talks. The two
would probably then meet with the secretary of state, if she is
here, or Dennis Ross, the administration's chief Middle East
negotiator, he added.
</P>
<P>
   During his news conference, Clinton also defended his policy
toward Russia. He reiterated that the Russians would pay a ``heavy
price'' internationally for the way they are attacking Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also repeated that he was against cutting American aid
to Russia, which now goes to two areas: safeguarding nuclear
weapons and supporting nongovernmental projects intended to promote
democracy. ``I haven't decided what else I can do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he added: ``I do think, first of all, they may believe that
because of their position in the United Nations and because no one
wants them to fail and have more problems than they've got, that
they can do this. But you know, most of life's greatest wounds for
individuals and for countries are self-inflicted; they're not
inflicted by other people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 2137EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3467 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BUSH-EXECUTION-NYT &LR;      12-08 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EXECUTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.H.)  
 TEXAS FLIES MURDERER FROM INTENSIVE CARE TO EXECUTION CHAMBER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ With several high-profile death penalty cases in Texas
in coming weeks, the execution of a convicted murderer, David
Martin Long, was not expected to generate much fanfare. He had been
scheduled to die by lethal injection Wednesday evening, making him
the 32nd person executed in Texas this year.
</P>
<P>
   But when death row guards found him unconscious from a drug
overdose on Monday morning, Long himself became a high-profile
case. Placed in intensive care on a ventilator in a Galveston
hospital, Long suddenly presented a politically delicate question
for Gov. George W. Bush, even as he campaigned for the Republican
presidential nomination in New Hampshire:
</P>
<P>
   Would the state of Texas remove an inmate from intensive care so
that he could meet his date with the executioner rather than stay
the execution for 30 days? The answer is yes.
</P>
<P>
   With the Supreme Court's rejection Wednesday of Long's final
petition for a delay, Texas officials Wednesday evening to
transported him to the death chamber in Huntsville for execution.
Because Long's doctor deemed such a move ``risky,'' state officials
apparently used an airplane staffed by medical personnel to ensure
that he arrived in good health after the 25-minute trip. With Bush
out of state, the decision on Long's fate Wednesday night
technically fell to Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, but Bush's spokeswoman
said the governor agreed the execution should proceed.
</P>
<P>
   A staunch advocate of the death penalty in a state that strongly
shares the same view, Bush has made no pretense of extending his
campaign theme of compassionate conservatism to death row. But the
Long case and other upcoming cases might present politically
ticklish moments for Bush as death penalty opponents try to paint a
grim picture of the system in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday for example, the state is scheduled to execute
another convicted murderer, James L. Beathard, whose accuser has
recanted and whose original lawyer now admits he had a conflict of
interest. In January, three inmates who committed homicides as
juveniles are scheduled to die. That same month, Johnny Penry, a
convicted murderer who is considered mentally retarded, is
scheduled for lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   ``These cases challenge our assumption of the death penalty as
fairly and justly administered,'' said Maurie Levin, executive
director of the Texas Capital Defense Project, a nonprofit group
that helps death row inmates.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, which leads the nation with 195 executions since 1982,
public support for the death penalty is very high, and Bush's
Democratic predecessor, Ann Richards, also was a strong advocate.
</P>
<P>
   The Long case, however, has presented very unusual
circumstances. Convicted of the 1986 hatchet slayings of three
women, one of whom was blind, Long ingested an overdose of
anti-psychotic drugs on Monday morning. Doctors in Galveston placed
him on life support and found themselves in the odd situation of
trying to restore to good health a man with only two days left to
live.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alexander Duarte, the physician in charge of the case, said
Long, 46, was removed from the ventilator on Tuesday, and by
Wednesday his condition had improved to serious from critical.
Duarte said Long still required oxygen and continual medical care.
Under normal circumstances, he said, he would likely keep Long in
the intensive-care unit for another day or two.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Duarte said state officials asked him to sign an
affidavit stating that Long could be safely transported to
Huntsville, a request he said he refused. But Duarte said he signed
an affidavit that stated Long's health had improved, that he had
suffered no seizures and was responding to questioning _ but that
transporting him could be risky without appropriate medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Long's lawyers argued before a state court judge Wednesday
afternoon that their client was no longer competent enough to be
executed. Lawyers for the state Attorney General John Cornyn argued
the opposite, and Judge Edwin V. King agreed.
</P>
<P>
   With that, and rejections by the Supreme Court (a 6-3 vote) and
the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals (a 4-3 vote) Long's appeals
were all but exhausted. Earlier in the week, the state Board of
Pardons and Parole had rejected his clemency application. So his
last chance was the governor. With Bush in New Hampshire, Perry
rejected Long's request for a 30-day stay of execution. Under Texas
law, when the board rejects clemency, the governor has two options:
reject clemency or grant a 30-day stay.
</P>
<P>
   Why not just delay the execution 30 days?
</P>
<P>
   `` Long has been convicted of three murders,'' Sullivan said.
``The Texas Department of Criminal Justice determined that
transporting him from Galveston to Huntsville is not life
threatening. He has received his court appeals, and barring any
additional court actions, we expect the execution to go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Long's lawyers, John Blume disagreed. ``It seems like a
pretty sick process when you jerk a guy out of intensive care on a
ventilator,'' he said, adding, ``What's the huge rush?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
