<HEADER>
A3488 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBA-CHILD-NYT &LR;      12-08 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-CHILD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. HINTS AT RETURNING REFUGEE TO CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Even as Elian Gonzalez, 6, wrapped in the arms of his
relatives, said he wanted to stay in Little Havana here, State
Department officials seemed willing Wednesday to consider reuniting
the boy with his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Elian, who survived for two days adrift on an inner tube in the
Atlantic Ocean after a failed crossing from Cuba drowned his
mother, stepfather and nine others, told reporters at a small news
conference late Tuesday that he wanted to stay in the home of a
great-uncle and great-aunt, who have showered him with presents.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's happy here,'' said his 21-year-old cousin, Marisleysis
Gonzalez. ``Let's not turn this into a political thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But State Department officials said Wednesday that they
recognized the rights of the boy's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, to
reclaim his child, and would send agents to meet with him in Havana
to discuss ``an appropriate resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   To many Cuban-Americans, it seems as if the State Department,
which had at first said the issue of the boy's custody would have
to be settled in Florida courts, is capitulating, giving in to four
days of broad, well-organized anti-American protests outside the
United States diplomatic mission in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday in Washington on a wide range of
issues, President Clinton would not say how the case should be
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, and I think the most important thing is, What
would be best for the child, and there is a legal process for
determining that,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the latest effort by the boy's relatives to keep
him in Miami, family members applied on the boy's behalf for
political asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Elian, who celebrated his sixth birthday last Sunday, is at the
epicenter of an international incident, complete with two sides _
the Cuban government and the Cuban exiles in Miami _ who have used
his predicament to advance their positions. The boy's face adorns a
billboard in Havana, and the Cuban government has trucked in
thousands of marchers, waving signs that read, ``We want Elian back
home.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami's exile neighborhoods, people say those protests are
disingenuous, at best, and just another case of Cuban President
Fidel Castro's manipulating his people for political gain. In
Little Havana, marchers protested Castro's efforts to turn Elian
into ``a little Communist.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro, without being specific, has warned United States
officials that they will regret not returning the boy to his
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``When our commandante talks, they tremble,'' Elian's father
said in an interview with The Miami Herald. Gonzalez, who has said
he had to sell his car, a 1956 Nash Rambler, to pay for daily
long-distance telephone calls to his son, has refused to come to
Florida to fight for Elian in court. Castro has said that is
because the courts here are corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   But the State Department seems ready to give Gonzalez a way
around the state courts. ``The regulations of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service recognize the right of a parent to assert
parental interests in an immigration proceeding,'' said James B.
Foley, a State Department deputy spokesman. ``The INS will be in
contact with Gonzalez in the near future to explain the process by
which it will evaluate his rights in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people here believe that if Gonzalez had the freedom to
speak his mind here, not only would he allow his son to stay but he
also would seek asylum himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only hostage here is the father, who is not being allowed
by the Cuban government to come here to the United States and make
the decision along with the family,'' said Ninoska Perez Castellon,
a spokeswoman for the Cuban-American National Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   In a custody case involving any other country, experts on
immigration said, Elian would have already been returned to his
closest relative.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have been back a week ago,'' said David Abraham, a
law professor at the University of Miami who specializes in
immigration issues. Both American laws and treaties involving child
custody and abduction would provide for the boys' immediate return,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the correct legal thing to do,'' Abraham continued. ``You
must give custody to the surviving parent unless there is proof of
abuse or neglect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Only in Miami,'' he said, could the child's custody explode
into a diplomatic incident. ``Miami is the last front in the Cold
War.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Cuban Adjustment Act of 1966, those who make it here
from Cuba are granted an immigration status enjoyed by no other
country. Under the law, Elian is automatically paroled into the
exile community here, and is eligible to apply for permanent
residency in one year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 2154EST &QL; 
