<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WTO-SEATTLE-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DEFENDS HIS ROLE AT SEATTLE TRADE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Wednesday defended his
handling of last week's failed trade negotiations, and said his
insistence that labor and environmental issues be central to the
talks was not intended to provide political cover for Vice
President Al Gore's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   For days there has been sniping within his administration about
how the World Trade Organization meeting in Seattle had gone so
wrong, and criticism from developing nations and free-trade
advocates at home that he had sacrificed an opportunity for a round
of trade liberalization to narrow domestic political interests. But
Clinton said it was unrealistic to believe that international
economic agreements could avoid dealing with issues like worker
rights and pollution.
</P>
<P>
   In his first extensive remarks on the subject after rioting in
Seattle's streets and a deadlock around the negotiating table,
Clinton said at a news conference that he remained a strong
supporter of expanding free trade and optimistic that another round
of trade liberalization would eventually get under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the position of Americans, including some in my own
party, that trade is bad for America and bad for the world is just
dead wrong,'' Clinton said. ``I think that the world is more
prosperous, and I know America is more prosperous, because of the
continuing integration of the world's economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had told the trade officials meeting in Seattle that
they should ``open up'' to the concerns of the demonstrators in the
streets. And Clinton had caused an uproar among poor nations by
saying that he would at some point support using sanctions against
developing countries that failed to live up to internationally
agreed upon labor standards.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Clinton sought to explain his statement on sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the world grows more interdependent, it is unrealistic to
think that there will be an international economic policy with
rules unrelated to an emerging international consensus on the
environment, an international consensus on labor,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That does not mean I would cut off our markets to India and
Pakistan, for example, if they didn't raise their wages to American
levels,'' he said. ``I know that's what the sort of stated fear
was. I never said that. I don't believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said he had sought to address labor and
environmental concerns in trade agreements since the 1992
presidential campaign, when he supported ratification of the North
American Free Trade Agreement with Mexico and Canada on the
condition that those issues be included.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he said, it is ``wrong'' to suggest that he
sabotaged last week's trade talks by pressing an agenda backed by
two constituencies vital to Gore in his pursuit of the Democratic
presidential nomination and the general election: organized labor
and environmental groups.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I think I've got a good position here,'' Clinton said. ``It
has nothing to do with this campaign. It's a position I've had for
years, and I believe the world will slowly come to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton and Gore face a tricky balancing act in the
coming months as they move on to the administration's next big
trade initiative: winning approval in Congress for China's entry
into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor has made clear that it intends an all-out effort
against China's entry on the grounds that China exploits it workers
and threatens the viability of jobs in many American industries.
</P>
<P>
   But with the encouragement of the White House, business groups
are planning a lobbying counteroffensive to convince both Democrats
and Republicans that blocking a trade deal with Beijing will reduce
the ability of the United States to profit from China's rapid
growth and forgo an opportunity to promote democratic capitalism
and human rights through economic engagement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged that the battle over China would be
difficult, and would be especially divisive among Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good deal of support for it and a good deal of
opposition to it, and then some questions,'' Clinton said. ``But
I'm going to make an all-out effort to pass it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would make his case on both economic and
strategic grounds, saying that the United States would be the big
winner from increased trade with China and that closer economic
ties would allow the United States to have a more constructive
relationship with the world's most populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he would not single out China in pressing for
improvements in the rights and working conditions of its labor
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think having China in a rule-based system for the
international economy is profoundly important, and I think it would
be a terrible mistake not to do it,'' Clinton said. ``Now, do I
agree with all their labor standards? No. But we shouldn't impose
conditions of membership on China that we don't impose on any other
country to get into the WTO.''
</P>
</TEXT>
