<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3490 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NATWEST-MARKETPLACE-N     12-08 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATWEST-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BANK OF SCOTLAND RAISES ANTE IN HOSTILE BID FOR NATWEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Bank of Scotland showed some fancy footwork but
failed to score a knockout Wednesday in its attempt to take control
of National Westminster Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Its hostile offer, which has been on the table since September,
has been rebuffed by NatWest and prompted the Royal Bank of
Scotland to make a counteroffer for NatWest last week.
</P>
<P>
   So Wednesday, the Bank of Scotland raised the ante by providing
details on how it aimed to take over NatWest, a bank twice its
size, and planned to wring out 1.015 billion pounds, or $1.65
billion, in savings in the next three years from the combined
operations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Scottish bank, with revenue growth of about 15
percent a year, pledged that it would raise NatWest's revenue
growth by 5 percent a year, to about 10 percent to 11 percent
annually once their operations are combined.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve the promised cost savings, it said it would integrate
the banks' back offices, merging their complex databases and
computer systems. While it took great pains to say it would not be
closing NatWest branches, it did say that it would shrink at least
half of the branches, in most cases moving them to smaller retail
spaces and cutting staff.
</P>
<P>
   Its rival, the Royal Bank of Scotland, made its intentions a bit
less, well, hostile. It does not plan to cut branches or integrate
back offices to the same degree that its rival said it would. But
it has yet to show how it would achieve its projected savings, at
1.18 billion pounds within the next three years, slightly greater
than its what its rival plans.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Phin, a stock analyst with Williams de Broe, said it was
hard to tell who would be the victor after attending the Bank of
Scotland's presentation. Bank of Scotland's pitch seems more
plausible ``because they showed us some substance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While NatWest has vowed to remain independent, ``the perception
from my vantage point is that NatWest's days are numbered,'' Phin
added.
</P>
<P>
   But neither of the offers is especially enriching to NatWest
shareholders at first glance. ``There's a greater chance now than
ever before that NatWest will remain independent,'' countered
Michael Lever, an analyst at HSBC in London. ``I can't recommend to
any NatWest shareholder to accept any of these bids.''
</P>
<P>
   NatWest's shares are trading 14 percent below the Bank of
Scotland's offer price of 1,552 pence a share. Shares of NatWest
closed down 1.8 percent at 1,336 pence. Royal Bank of Scotland has
fared worse. Its share price has fallen 18 percent in the 10 days
since it made its bid.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Royal Bank's offer for NatWest is now valued at
only 22.8 billion pounds, or 1,364 pence a share, less than its
rival's bid.
</P>
<P>
   NatWest has been trying to fight off the hostile bids by
promising to sell four units, return more than 1 billion pounds of
capital to shareholders and cut costs by dismissing people. Its
board forced out its chief executive in October and gave its
chairman the additional power to help fend off suitors.
</P>
<P>
   Sir David Rowland, NatWest chairman and chief executive, has
repeatedly said that the Bank of Scotland offer is poorly thought
out. ``Its proposals threaten significant losses and value
destruction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With NatWest pledging its own cost cuts, the promises of
combined savings with another bank are hard to evaluate. Merger
savings often prove illusory.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods found that only 2 of
15 banks that made acquisitions in 1997 and 1998 met their
per-share-earnings goal for 1999. It should be noted, though, that
the study looked only at United States banks and that European
banks generally have more fat, and thus a merger has a better
chance of reaching its savings goals through cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Banks typically project savings by cutting jobs and by selling
divisions. All too often, though, they do not take into
consideration the possibility of at least a short-term dip in
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   A National Westminster spokesman said a reduction in revenue of
6.5 percent would eliminate all of Bank of Scotland's claimed
savings.
</P>
<P>
   During any merger transition period, service disruptions and
change can cause customers to take their business elsewhere,
perhaps leaving lingering problems. The Bank of Scotland
acknowledged there could be transition problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customer attrition will always happen during the transition,''
Phin said. ``It's what happens in the long term that matters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
