<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Friday, December 9, on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call Georgie Dennison at 415-777-6055
or the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business stories running
in main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SPORTS  &LR;  _ Just a few years ago, a Polaroid camera and a long piece
of wire constituted high-tech innovation in the National Football
League. Teams used to string that wire from the press box high up
in the stands down to the field. Assistant coaches in the box would
snap the self-developing photos of the game in progress and slide
them down to the field on shower hooks.
</P>
<P>
   That way, the players could get a bird's-eye view of how their
opponents were lining up against them. But now, new technology is
changing the way the most popular sports are played and broadcast,
and nowhere is that more apparent than in the NFL. Not only have
teams replaced that old Polaroid-on-a-wire with high-tech computer
printers on the sidelines that spit out better-quality digital
photos, but the league has gone totally wireless for on-field
communications. By Benny Evangelista
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTSSIDE _ &LR;  In addition to on-the-field changes, new
technology is about to revolutionize the way sports leagues and
teams connect with their fans, according to a recent study. The
Internet will cause a ``power shift'' in the way sports
entertainment is delivered to fans, a Forrester Research Inc. study
concludes. Instead of relying on traditional television and radio
broadcasts, professional sports franchises will use the Web to
deliver merchandise and even the games themselves directly to their
fans. And aspects of sports that historically were considered
background information, such as player statistics, scores and game
highlights, will become commodities that generate revenue, said
Mark Hardie, Forrester senior analyst. By Benny Evangelista
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MACQ&AMP;A  &LR; - Installing Netscape as preferred browser. By Henry
Norr
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MEDIABYTES &LR;  _ Whenever Paul Allen makes an investment, it's
worthwhile to see where he might score some synergies with his
other holdings. So when the billionaire co-founder of Microsoft
bought San Francisco's all-computing cable channel ZDTV last month,
the folks there were most cheered because Allen owns the country's
fourth-largest cable television company, Charter Communications.
But more intriguing was Allen's investment in Cnet, ZDTV's
crosstown rival. Not only is Cnet the most formidable competition
for ZDTV's onetime sister company ZDNet, but it also produces its
own television programming about computing, which airs on other
cable channels. Allen's Vulcan Ventures owned somewhat less than 10
percent of Cnet, enough to put Vulcan President Bill Savoy on the
Cnet board of directors. By Dan Fost
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; EBAY _ &LR;  Days after the riots in downtown Seattle over the World
Trade Organization, rubber bullets, spent tear gas canisters and
broken police clubs turned up for sale on eBay. But yesterday, the
online auction site decided to halt bidding on the items because it
couldn't be sure who actually owned them _ the Seattle Police
Department or the protesters who kept them as souvenirs. ``I can't
even begin to guess the motivation of people selling these items,''
said Kevin Pursglove, an eBay spokesman. By David Lazarus
</P>
