<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETRATINGS-NETRATINGS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Firm Tracking Web Users Has Upbeat Debut  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Despite its underdog status in the Web-tracking business, shares of
Milpitas' NetRatings Inc. popped 64 percent, or $11, to close at
$28 yesterday in its first day of public trading.
<P>
   NetRatings raised $68 million by selling 4 million shares at $17
each, up from the $14 to $16 range it had initially planned.
</P>
<P>
   NetRatings is backed by Nielsen Media Research, &UR;  &LR; known for its
television ratings. The companies jointly market a service called
Nielsen/NetRatings, which uses panels of computer users to
extrapolate the numbers and characteristics of Web surfers.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers and Web sites pay for detailed reports to decide
where to place ads and learn about the demographic profiles of
their visitors. Nielsen/NetRatings has 170 customers compared with
more than 500 for Media Metrix.
</P>
<P>
   In its prospectus, NetRatings said it expects to one day rule
the Web measurement business, although it now plays second fiddle
in both number of customers and revenues to Media Metrix of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the market for Internet audience measurement
services will eventually gravitate toward a uniform standard based
on data collected by a single service provider,'' the prospectus
said.
</P>
<P>
   But it acknowledged that Media Metrix, of New York,  &LR; ``as the
first mover in this market, has a head start in becoming the
industry standard for such services.''
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix representatives could not be reached late
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview yesterday, Steve Gross, NetRatings vice
president of finance, said NetRatings' advantage is Nielsen's
respected sampling methodology.
</P>
<P>
   NetRatings is partnering with AC Nielsen, a separate and also
well-regarded polling company, to handle sampling in foreign
markets, Gross said. NetRatings owns 19.9 percent of the joint
venture with AC Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage for NetRatings is that it is well positioned
to measure audiences in the event that computer and television
technology merge, the prospectus said.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from the offering will be used for general corporate
purposes. The funds may also be used to acquire complementary
businesses and technologies, the prospectus said.
</P>
<P>
   NetRatings had an accumulated deficit of $16.3 million on
September 30.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues for the nine months ended in September totaled $1.5
million, up from $132,000 for the same period a year ago. The net
loss was $10.7million, compared with $2.4 million for the first
nine months of 1998. The Nielsen/NetRatings service launched in the
first quarter of this year. NetRatings first started its
Web-tracking service in March 1998 using a different methodology.
</P>
<P>
   For the first nine months of 1999, Media Metrix posted revenues
of $12.9 million and a loss of $7.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen Media Research is awaiting antitrust approval to buy a
controlling interest in NetRatings, the prospectus said. It now
holds a minority stake.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
