<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-EBAY </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 EBay Halts Auction of Seattle Riot Memorabilia  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Days after the riots in downtown Seattle over the World Trade
Organization, rubber bullets, spent tear gas canisters and broken
police clubs turned up for sale on eBay.
<P>
   But yesterday, the online auction site decided to halt bidding
on the items because it couldn't be sure who actually owned them _
the Seattle Police Department or the protesters who kept them as
souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even begin to guess the motivation of people selling
these items,'' said Kevin Pursglove, an eBay spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Carmen Best, a spokeswoman for the Seattle Police
Department, said she had no idea if the department would claim
ownership of the disputed goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we'd have gone back and collected the stuff,''
she said. ``I don't know if we'd have arrested anyone for theft.''
</P>
<P>
   Best also didn't know if the Police Department would have any
use for used gas canisters and rubber bullets even if officers had
gone to the trouble of rounding them up after the protests.
</P>
<P>
   As of yesterday afternoon, the only item listed on eBay under
``Seattle riots'' was 216592258: Footage showing police going up
against demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawyers welcome,'' it said. ``About 2 hrs of protesting and
unconstitutional beatings /bring down those responsible for the
mayhem _ the government!!!''
</P>
<P>
   For the past couple of days, however, the site contained a
number of protest-related items, including a ``tear gas fun pack''
selling for $102.50 (it attracted five bids) and a police baton
selling for $51 (it drew six bids).
</P>
<P>
   ``They're in violation of our user agreement in a number of
areas,'' Pursglove said.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he said, rubber bullets and used tear gas
canisters could be considered weapons, which eBay doesn't allow to
be sold on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the items could be considered government property, and
you can't sell that, either.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they might still be the property of the Seattle cops,
and eBay takes a dim view of users fencing stolen goods on the
site.
</P>
<P>
   It also doesn't like it when people try to sell human organs,
babies, and other such oddities that have popped up in recent
months. But that's another story.
</P>
<P>
   Pursglove said the Seattle items were spotted by vigilant eBay
users, who self-police the site and report any contraband they come
across. He said all offending items had been pulled from bidding by
yesterday morning.
</P>
<P>
   But one enterprising seller, Adam Cohn, re-posted his items at
his University of Washington home page. They included two tear gas
canisters, two detonated concussion grenades, a broken police club
and ``a handful of rubber bullets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On November 30 and December 1, 1999, protesters took to the
streets of Seattle to prevent the convening of the World Trade
Organization,'' Cohn wrote. ``The cops did their darndest to keep
the unruly mob at bay and resorted to all sorts of entertaining
devices including those offered in this rare package!''
</P>
<P>
   Cohn said he is keeping track of the e-mail addresses of those
who bid for his offerings on eBay and will contact them in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
