<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3496 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MEDIA-STUDY-AD-COLUMN     12-08 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-STUDY-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: BREAKING DOWN WHEN, WHERE AND HOW YOUNG ADULTS GET
INFORMATION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)   By JANE LEVERE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A new study by BBDO New York of consumers'
perceptions of the media says that newspapers have the most
traditional image of all media and that the Internet has replaced
television as the favored medium for escape.
</P>
<P>
   The method used by BBDO New York might at least be partly
responsible for the conclusions. To conduct the study, the agency,
whose clients include Campbell Soup, FedEx, Mars, the New York
Stock Exchange, PepsiCo and Visa, interviewed 104 adults, ages 22
to 34, in eight markets across the United States in September. The
relative youth of the group might have influenced their perceptions
of the newest medium _ the Internet _ as well as their thoughts on
one of the oldest, newspapers. BBDO New York is a unit of BBDO
Worldwide, whose parent is the Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   This possible bias notwithstanding, the study appears to confirm
beliefs previously held by advertising and marketing executives on
the roles various media play.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Olshan, executive vice president and director of strategic
operations at BBDO New York, said the study stemmed from the notion
``that if the medium is the message, then the consumer's view of a
given medium could contribute to or detract from the image of an
advertised brand.''
</P>
<P>
   It looked at the reasons consumers use each medium; who
consumers think uses each medium; and the psychological rewards
consumers say they get in using each medium.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents said they used the Internet for escape and mental
stimulation and to obtain specific information on travel, business
and health issues. Users were perceived positively, as young
career-oriented adults. Respondents said using the Internet gave
them feelings of innovation, intelligence, creativity, power and
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents said they read magazines for information on current
fashions, recipes and health issues and to reward themselves. They
perceived magazine readers as being physically attractive; they
also said reading magazines gave them feelings of sexiness,
self-esteem, luxury and creativity.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ms. Olshan, magazines ``have the most aspirational
image among all major media.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``People go to them to reward themselves. Sitting
down with a magazine takes time; it implies you have time. It's a
nice feeling, a relaxing thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The study found that respondents watched television for
entertainment, to end the day or to spend time with family. Viewers
were perceived largely as homemakers and families, while
respondents said watching TV gave them feelings of happiness,
comfort and fun.
</P>
<P>
   Radio was perceived as a background medium, to be listened to
first thing in the morning or while doing other things. Listeners
were seen as young and hip, while respondents said radio gave them
feelings of peacefulness, relaxation, inner harmony and
youthfulness.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents said they also read newspapers first thing in the
morning and to obtain in-depth news, financial and sports
information, and movie reviews. Readers were perceived as
middle-aged or older, more often male than female. Respondents said
reading newspapers gave them feelings of tradition, stability,
security, maturity, respect and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Olshan said these findings suggested that TV was an ideal
medium for advertising products that entertained or were associated
with fun, like soft drinks, candy or amusement parks. Magazines
make the most sense, she said, for luxury products and beauty and
fashion brands, while newspapers are suited to advertising for
technology and e-commerce companies.
</P>
<P>
   Marketers using the Internet must address consumers' desire for
mental stimulation and escape in their advertising, she added,
while radio advertising must find a way to move its messages from
the background to the foreground.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, Ms. Olshan said it was important for marketers to
consider the image of a medium when deciding where to advertise
because this can reinforce the desired image of a brand.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Silver, senior vice president for advertising and
brand management for Visa USA, said she was pleased the Internet
``had a well-developed profile in the study.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``I'm glad to see its profile has moved beyond geeky
guys, that there's mainstream stuff going on.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said the study had confirmed her intuition about the
use of different media, but that it ``was not changing my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The most noteworthy section of the study, according to Jim
Spaeth, president of the Advertising Research Foundation, was its
definition ``of the appropriate slice of the pie for the Internet''
_ something he said he had not seen measured or documented before.
</P>
<P>
   Other observers were more skeptical of BBDO's findings, however.
Roger Lavery, a professor at the Adcenter at Virginia Commonwealth
University in Richmond, warned: ``They need to be careful making
this all too tidy. Marketers like things tidy, but unfortunately,
the world isn't that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Erwin Ephron, a media consultant in New York, called the study's
findings ``very superficial,'' and questioned the size and age of
the group surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   BBDO New York executives said they were likely to do surveys of
consumers who are younger and older than those polled in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
