<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TO SEEK MATCHING FUNDS IF HE WINS GOP NOMINATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Karl Rove, chief political strategist for George W.
Bush, confirmed Wednesday that the Republican presidential
front-runner plans to seek federal financial help for his general
election campaign if he wins the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's fund-raising prowess, which has netted his campaign a
record $70 million in nine months, has enabled him to forgo federal
matching funds through the 2000 Republican convention this summer
and avoid spending restraints during the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The fall campaign season was too short for a similar
fund-raising juggernaut, Rove said. ``It is awfully difficult to
raise $60 million between the time you get the nomination (in late
summer) and the November election.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the matching fund system, the federal government matches
up to $250 of each individual donation to a candidate who agrees to
abide by state-by-state spending restrictions. The Republican and
Democratic presidential nominees will be eligible for up to $66
million in taxpayer funding for their fall campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want your candidate attending a lot of fund-raisers.
You want him out shaking a lot of hands,'' Rove said. ``There's a
limited number of days from August to November, and it would be
awfully difficult to raise that kind of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing polls that show Bush with a double-digit lead over
his Republican opponents nationally but tighter races in early
primary states, Rove predicted that ``the numbers will tighten
appreciably.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, a survey released by the American Research Group
showed Bush trailing U.S. Sen. John McCain by 7 percentage points
in New Hampshire, the nation's first-primary state. A separate
survey by Zogby International showed Bush behind McCain by 3
percentage points among New Hampshire Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a rough patch or two in the road,'' Rove
said. ``But we have built a campaign that is able to endure and win
and compete everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about assertions by Bush's Republican opponents that he
might lack the intellectual muscle to occupy the White House, Rove
said: ``It's the burden of the front-runner to take the slings and
arrows shot his way by others.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove acknowledged that Bush comes across better in person than
he does on television, but predicted that he would improve in the
coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last five days, Gov. Bush has doubled his debate
experience,'' Rove said, referring to candidate forums in New
Hampshire and Arizona in the past week and his debates against
former Gov. Ann Richards in 1994 and Democratic gubernatorial
candidate Garry Mauro in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Bush got some support about his television demeanor from a voter
at a Bedford, N.H., town-hall meeting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After the man said he watched Monday's debate and found Bush
intelligent enough to be president, Bush responded: ``I'd rather be
underestimated than overestimated. I've been underestimated before
_ and Governor Richards regrets it.''
</P>
<P>
   About the perception that Bush smirked at his opponents in New
Hampshire and Arizona, Rove said voters ``will make their judgments
about the whole person'' and not facial expressions. ``Does he come
across better when he's sitting two feet away from you? You bet,''
the strategist said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This brief fascination with whether it was a smirk or a smile
will pass quickly,'' Rove predicted.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Bush was in New Hampshire focusing on high
technology issues.
</P>
<P>
   But other issues crept in, as a voter asked Bush at a Manchester
high-tech town hall meeting, if he would pardon Michael New of
Conroe, who was convicted for refusing to wear U.N. insignia. ``I
don't know enough about the case but I'll tell you what I will tell
you: We're never going to put U.S. troops under U.N. command,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush appeared alongside Jim Barksdale, founder of Netscape, in
an interview on WMUR-TV.
</P>
<P>
   Bush reiterated his support for extending the moratorium on
taxing Internet commerce for three to five years, and he stated his
opposition to taxing Internet access. Texas this year removed
Internet access from state sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say let the Internet develop,'' Bush said. ``It's important
the next president understand the power and the promise of the
Internet, the power and promise of technology. The Internet can
change how we educate our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Barksdale said the most important issue to the technology
industry is education, and he said Bush has been a leader among all
the presidential candidates when it comes to improving public
education. Barksdale said the industry is short about 300,000
workers because U.S. schools are not producing students interested
in math.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next president has to be knowledgeable. That doesn't mean
he has to be a technologist,'' Barksdale said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporter R.G. Ratcliffe contributed to this story from
New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
