<HEADER>
A3499 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES     12-08 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA BYTES/DAN FOST 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Paul Allen Loses Interest in Cnet After Buying Crosstown Rival 
 ZDTV 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Whenever Paul Allen makes an investment, it's worthwhile to see
where he might score some synergies with his other holdings. So
when the billionaire co-founder of Microsoft bought San Francisco's
all-computing cable channel ZDTV last month, the folks there were
most cheered because Allen owns the country's fourth-largest cable
television company, Charter Communications.
<P>
   But more intriguing was Allen's investment in Cnet, ZDTV's
crosstown rival. Not only is Cnet the most formidable competition
for ZDTV's onetime sister company ZDNet, but it also produces its
own television programming about computing, which airs on other
cable channels. Allen's Vulcan Ventures owned somewhat less than 10
percent of Cnet, enough to put Vulcan President Bill Savoy on the
Cnet board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   The synergy is not to be, however. Vulcan has been unloading its
stake in Cnet, and Savoy has left the board. In August, Vulcan
announced its intention to sell 850,000 shares of Cnet, for $29.9
million, and last month, the company said it would sell an
additional 2 million shares for $97.1 million, according to filings
with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   After those sales, Allen's stake in the company will be
``basically zero,'' said Cnet spokeswoman Karen Wood. ``He was the
first big investor, other than friends and family.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Allen pumped $5 million into the company in 1994 and
1995. As much as his money helped, his reputation in the industry
also gave the fledgling firm a big boost in credibility.
</P>
<P>
   It looks like Cnet repaid the favor: Adjusting for splits, its
stock is worth more than 10 times as much as when the company went
public. Adjusted for splits, the IPO prices was $4. Yesterday, Cnet
closed at $64.06.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ZIFF STAFF ZILCHED &QL; 
Sometimes when a big media firm is sold, the corporate powers cut
in the little guys who helped build the company. Such was the case
earlier this year when CMP Media was sold to Miller Freeman, and
such was also the case in years past when Ziff-Davis was first sold
to an outside investor.
</P>
<P>
   Ziff-Davis's publishing unit was sold yet again this week, but
employees shouldn't look for any bonuses in their holiday
paychecks. Although some ``key employees'' will see benefits as
their stock options vest, Ziff spokesman Robert Borchert said there
will be ``nothing like CMP's lump-sum payment.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale of Ziff's magazines, the most dominant in the computer
industry with such titles as PC Magazine and PC Computing, follows
ground broken by the sale of Wired magazine last year. In the Wired
sale, Advance Publications' Conde Nast bought the magazine, and
then several months later, Lycos bought the Web properties.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, investment firm Willis Stein &AMP; Partners bought Ziff's
publishing properties for $780 million, but not the hot Internet
site ZDNet. ZDNet gets about one-fourth of its content from Ziff
magazines and will continue to do so for at least five years under
a licensing deal.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Conde Nast, which did not get the rights to the
www.wired.com domain name, Willis Stein owns the domain names
associated with Ziff's magazines and could pull them from ZDNet
after the deal expires in five years, Borchert said. But why
speculate? ZDNet has not yet been sold _ and its controlling
investor, Softbank, may choose not to sell it.
</P>
<P>
   And, as Borchert points out, ``Five years is an eon in Internet
time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SALON TV: &QL; 
In the desperate rush to get established, Internet companies
typically buy ads in old media and even search out ways to put
their content on television and in newspapers. But Salon.com chief
executive Michael O'Donnell said television programmers had been
courting the hip San Francisco Web company in an effort to
transport its literate content to the small screen.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Salon announced a deal with Rainbow Media Holdings, a
subsidiary of giant Cablevision Systems Corp., to produce a show
based on its Internet content that will hit the air next spring.
Rainbow owns the cable film and arts network Bravo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a corporate initiative to get on television as
much as it was traditional media coming to us,'' O'Donnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Just what kind of show is still up in the air, but don't look
for a new sit-com or cops drama. It could be a talk show, it could
be a news show, and it could be something completely different,
said Salon spokeswoman Emma Hurley. ``We haven't ruled anything out
and we haven't decided anything for sure,'' she said. Whatever it
is, she said, it ``will certainly reflect Salon's character and
Salon's attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting the site's own show on the air is certainly a better
move than just buying more ads. ``The advertising space is so
cluttered right now on television that an actual TV show with
references to the Web site will do more to increase traffic than a
30-second spot,'' O'Donnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Salon founder, Chairman and Editor in Chief David Talbot is
leading the effort to develop the show, but he has high-powered
help: Salon counts on its board of directors television pioneer
Norman Lear (producer of ``All in the Family,'' among many other
shows) and former CBS President Jim Rosenfield.
</P>
<P>
   Salon has pushed into other media as well, publishing books,
selling its writings via the United Features Syndicate and creating
radio for use online and on the air.
</P>
<P>
   With its foray into television, Salon is following in the
footsteps of many other Internet companies, like Cnet,
MarketWatch.com and TheStreet.com, which have launched their own
cable shows.
</P>
<P>
   These deals, in which new media firms use established media to
make a name for themselves, have a strange evolutionary feel to
them. After all, what happens to the television networks and print
products that take ads and give airtime to Internet firms once
those companies are the giants?
</P>
<P>
   They probably won't die, like dinosaurs giving way to mammals.
The old media brands will survive, but they'll all be Internet
companies as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Media Bytes appears every Thursday in The Chronicle. Send buzz,
dirt, tips and comments to fostd &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
