u w BC-CLINTON-REFLECTIONS-N     12-08 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REFLECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PRESIDENT'S REFLECTIONS AS HIS FINAL YEAR NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, alternately wistful and wonkish,
reflected Wednesday on the fate of a Cuban boy torn between feuding
family members, on a year marked by numerous policy defeats and on
the legacy of the figure he pronounced the century's greatest,
Franklin D. Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   In an hourlong news conference, Clinton once again displayed his
mastery of minutiae while also seeming a bit subdued as he
contemplated his last year in office.
</P>
<P>
   The president appeared painfully aware that he was presiding
alone now over a White House that for most of his tenure was run by
a troika that included the first lady, Hillary Rodham Clinton, and
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is preparing to move out of the White House to run
for the Senate from New York while Gore has all but abandoned his
vice presidential duties, including his weekly lunches with
Clinton, to seek the Democratic nomination for president.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Mrs. Clinton's decision to pursue her own political
career, Clinton said he was ``very happy for her,'' without exactly
sounding so. He said the two of them spoke at least once a day by
telephone when apart but admitted it was not an ideal situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's not the best arrangement in the world, but it's
something that we can live with for a year,'' the president said.
``But I've got a job to do, and she now has a campaign to run, and
so we'll have to be apart more than I wish we were. But it's not a
big problem. She'll be here quite a lot, and I'll go up there when
I can, and we'll manage it and I think it will come out just
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The session with reporters was held in the Dean Acheson
Auditorium at the State Department, relocated from the White House
because the East Room, the traditional site of presidential news
conferences, was crammed with holiday decorations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was asked whom he regarded as the ``Man of the Century''
and responded with a long, articulate essay on Franklin Roosevelt,
complete with Justice Oliver Wendell Holmes' assessment of the new
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, you know,'' Clinton said, ``when Franklin Roosevelt was
first elected, Oliver Wendell Holmes was still on the Supreme
Court; he was 92 years old. And he was taken _ President Roosevelt
was taken to see Oliver Wendell Holmes, who was still reading Plato
in his 90s and all that. And Holmes was a pretty acerbic fellow
when he said, after meeting Roosevelt, that he thought he might not
have had a first-class mind, but he certainly had a first-class
temperament, and he did. He understood that reality is more than
the facts before you, it is also how you feel about them, how you
react to them, what your attitude is. That was the _ `the only
thing we have to fear is fear itself' was much more than just a
slogan to him, he had lived it before he asked the American people
to live it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's answer betrayed his obsession with his place in
history as his political career wound down. Clinton has told
friends that he regrets that he was never tested by war or
depression and thus could never secure a place among the nation's
greatest leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But on a more current note, the president offered little
guidance to a state court in Florida that is struggling with the
case of Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old Cuban boy who drifted ashore
on an inner tube two weeks ago. His mother and stepfather drowned
in the crossing. His father, who lives in Cuba, wants him returned,
while relatives in Miami are seeking permission to keep him in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The matter has become highly politicized because Fidel Castro
wants the boy sent back to Cuba while thousands of vocal Cuban
expatriates in Florida insist the child will be better off in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton refused to give an opinion on how he would like the
painful case resolved, but the tone of his answers revealed a hint
of the sadness of a boy whose own father was killed in an
automobile crash before he was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, of course, I think all fathers would be sympathetic,''
Clinton said. ``The question is, and I think the most important
thing, is what would be best for the child, and there is a legal
process for determining that.''
</P>
<P>
   He added later, ``I can't serve any useful purpose by commenting
on it because I don't know enough about the facts of the family
life or even the governing law on this.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point in the news conference, the President was
offered an opportunity to confess error or crime in the Monica
Lewinsky affair and curtly declined. He offered no revision of his
view that Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, had overstepped
his authority and criminalized a trivial matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mistake I made was self-inflicted,'' the president said,
``and the misconduct of others was not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 2206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3501 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MACQA-MACQA_SFCHRON &LR;      12-08 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACQA-MACQA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAC Q&AMP;A/HENRY NORR 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Installing Netscape as Preferred Browser 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: I got my new Power Mac G4 hooked up last night, but when I
clicked on my ``Browse the Internet'' icon, what should come up but
Microsoft Internet Explorer! Yech. What is it doing on my Mac? Part
of the reason I stay with Mac is to avoid Microsoft. It feels dirty
and creepy to have IE. I even have to use the Microsoft Outlook
program for my e-mail. Is there a way to get Netscape Navigator 4
and another e-mail program?
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: You bet _ in fact, they're already on your hard drive. Back
in 1997, in exchange for a $150 million investment by Microsoft,
Apple agreed to make Microsoft's Internet Explorer and Outlook
Express the Mac's default Web browser and e-mail application,
respectively. But to this ,day Apple continues to load Netscape's
software, too, on all new Macs.
</P>
<P>
   To find it, open the Internet folder on your hard drive. At
first glance you may not see any sign of Netscape (apparently Bill
Gates even got to design the window layout), but if you scroll down
to the bottom of the window, you should see an icon that points to
Netscape Communicator, a mega-application that combines the
Navigator browser with Netscape's Messenger mail program, plus a
calendar, news reader, Web-page editor and other features.
</P>
<P>
   To make Netscape your default browser, so it will open
automatically when you double-click the ``Browse the Internet''
icon, go to the Apple menu, then to Control Panels, and select the
Internet control panel. Click on the tab labeled ``Web.'' At the
bottom of the window, find the pop-up menu labeled ``Default Web
Browser'' and set it to Netscape Communicator.
</P>
<P>
   If you also want to make Netscape's Messenger module your
regular mail program, stay in the Internet control panel but switch
to the E-mail tab. There, a similar pop-up menu lets you set
Communicator (or any other mail program you'd like) as your default
for e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Video Plug-and-Play
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'd like to include some images from video in a newsletter I
produce on my iMac. Since there are no expansion slots on the
machine, how can I add a frame grabber?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: USB to the rescue! Every iMac includes ports for something
called the Universal Serial Bus, a truly plug-and-play way to
connect external peripherals to your system. It doesn't move data
fast enough for high-quality motion video _ for that your best bet
is a new iMac DV and a digital camcorder _ but it works fine for
single frames or low-resolution, compressed video clips.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least three USB devices for the Mac that can handle
this job with aplomb. The least expensive, Logitech's QuickCam VC
($79.95 list price), is mainly intended to function as a Webcam or
video-conferencing camera, but it can also capture still images and
sequences from other video sources at resolutions up to 352 by 288
pixels (www.logitech.com/us /cameras/ca29100.html).
</P>
<P>
   InterView USB from a company called XLR8 ($99 list) captures
high-quality video at up to 320 by 240 pixels and stills at up to
twice that resolution (www.xlr8.com/interview/index.html). It comes
with a full, though slightly out-of-date version of Strata's
capable VideoShop video-editing application.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Dazzle Multimedia's Digital Photo Maker (also $99 list)
offers much higher resolutions for stills _ theoretically, up to
1,600 by 1,200 pixels _ and also captures video in MPEG format at
up to 320 by 240 pixels. It's a recent port from the PC world, but
I recently tried it out on an iMac and it worked well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AirPort for PowerBooks
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a PowerBook G3, and I just picked up new iMac DV,
which has a slot for an AirPort card (Apple's new wireless
networking product). Can I add an AirPort card to the PowerBook, so
I can surf the Web with it from my deck?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can't add the Apple card, because the company doesn't
make a version that's compatible with current PowerBooks, but you
can add a third-party equivalent. My advice, though, is to wait a
month or two.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless networking cards that will fit in your PowerBook's PC
Card (a.k.a. PCMCIA) slot are available from a growing list of
companies, including Lucent (the company whose technology is behind
AirPort), Farallon (longtime experts in Mac networking) and Dell
(the PC giant). These three companies, like many others, base their
products on the same standard Apple uses, known as IEEE 802.11. In
theory, they should be compatible with the AirPort products.
</P>
<P>
   So why wait? Three reasons: First, most of the third-party
802.11 products you can buy today are based on an older version of
the standard that's limited to 2 megabits per second, compared to
the 11-Mbit rate AirPort can support. Third-party products matching
AirPort's speeds are just now coming on the market, but for the
moment, they're not easy to find.
</P>
<P>
   The slower and faster versions are supposed to be
``interoperable'' _ i.e., you can combine them on the same network
_ and in real life the speed difference isn't as great as it
sounds. But unless you're desperate to starting surfing from that
deck this winter, you might as well wait for the faster cards to
arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Second, there's the question of a base station, the device you
need to connect a wireless local-area network to the Internet. When
Apple unveiled AirPort last summer, it announced a stand-alone base
station, which is now available at $299.
</P>
<P>
   But the company also said then that any Mac with an AirPort card
and a wired Internet connection (via modem or Ethernet) would be
able to function as a base station for other machines with AirPort
cards but no direct Internet connection of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Apple hasn't delivered this feature yet; it's
scheduled to be added in an upcoming update to the AirPort
software, but the company won't set a date. So even if you could
get a card for your PowerBook today, it would be useless unless you
also shell out for Apple's hardware base station (or a third-party
equivalent). If you wait for the software, and it works as
advertised, you can save the $300 or so by letting your iMac do the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, remember that the cutting edge can make your life a
bloody mess. The whole point of standards is to ensure
compatibility among different vendors' products, but the reality is
that it sometimes takes months for them to get everything working
smoothly together. So even after the new cards appear, you might
want to let someone else test the promise of interoperability.
</P>
<P>
   An Apple tech note on AirPort compatibility with older Macs is
at til.info.apple.com/techinfo.nsf /artnum/n58521. For a very
thorough hands-on assessment of the technology, including tips on
setup and notes about some problems and limitations, see
www.macintouch.com/airport.html. I especially enjoyed Part II of
that review, which includes details about the effects of hair
dryers, microwave ovens, cordless phones and other appliances on
AirPort performance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
QUICK TIP
</P>
<P>
   Looking for in-depth info on Mac OS 9? You can download 76
densely packed but relatively readable pages of it, in Adobe
Acrobat format, at
www1.fatbrain.com/asp/bookinfo/bookinfo.asp?theisbn EB00003840.
Distributed under FatBrain.com's innovative ``eMatter'' electronic
publishing program, the document consists of material from several
issues of MWJ, a $10 per month online publication that calls itself
``The Weekly Journal for Serious Macintosh Users.''
</P>
