<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-SPORTS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Gridiron Goes Wireless _ New Technology Makes Life Easier
for  Football Coaches 
 &HT;     Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Just a few years ago, a Polaroid camera and a long piece of wire
constituted high-tech innovation in the National Football League.
<P>
   Teams used to string that wire from the press box high up in the
stands down to the field. Assistant coaches in the box would snap
the self-developing photos of the game in progress and slide them
down to the field on shower hooks.
</P>
<P>
   That way, the players could get a bird's-eye view of how their
opponents were lining up against them.
</P>
<P>
   But now, new technology is changing the way the most popular
sports are played and broadcast, and nowhere is that more apparent
than in the NFL. Not only have teams replaced that old
Polaroid-on-a-wire with high-tech computer printers on the
sidelines that spit out better-quality digital photos, but the
league has gone totally wireless for on-field communications
</P>
<P>
   Wireless headphones, speakers and pagers have all become as
integral to the game as blitzes, stunts and sacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it a lot easier for coaches on the sidelines to
anticipate what's going to happen,'' said Bobb cq  &LR; McKittrick, the
longtime offensive line coach for the San Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change this NFL season is the return of video
instant replays as a tool for coaches to challenge officials'
rulings, the most direct use of technology in any sport. With
instant replay, coaches can protest certain calls made by game
officials, who consult replays from various angles to either uphold
or change their on-field verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL scrapped an ineffective, heavily criticized instant
replay system using a TV monitor and videotape that was employed
from 1986 to 1991. This time around, the league has brought in
computerized digital playback equipment that allows officials to
use touch screens to instantly find up to seven different angles
for any play in question.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the revised new  &LR; instant replay is a new wireless
communication network that connects coaches, quarterbacks and
referees.
</P>
<P>
   Until two years ago, head and assistant coaches patrolling the
sidelines were physically tethered by phone cords connecting their
communication the  &LR; headsets they used to talk to each other &LR;   &LR; to a
central hub.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while, many coaches had someone carry the cord, to keep
it coiled so it wouldn't get tangled,'' McKittrick said. ``If you
had four coaches with an extra person to carry the wire, that's
eight people on the sidelines. It was so frustrating. You were
always getting your cord tangled or someone was always standing on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the league switched to a wireless system designed
specifically for football by Telex Communications Inc. of
Minneapolis and provided to the NFL this season under a marketing
agreement with Motorola Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The system includes a combination headset-microphone connected
to a belt pack worn by each coach. The belt pack transmits the
radio signal, digitally encoded to prevent the opposing team from
learning key secrets, to a central receiver-transmitter on the
sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The transmitter relays the audio to assistant coaches in the
press box or onto the field to the quarterback, who has a small
speaker inside his helmet next to his ear.
</P>
<P>
   If the head coach wants an instant replay, he presses a button
on the belt pack that activates a beeper worn by the game referee
and umpire on the field. It also sends a signal to the replay booth
officials in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   The replays shows up on special monitors on the field and the
booth. Fans watching the game at home would see the same set of
replays on TV that the on-field referees use to review their calls.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches have only 30 seconds after a play is over to request an
appeal and, ``It's come right down to the microsecond,'' McKittrick
said. But with the wireless system, he said, coaches no longer have
to yell and scream above the crowd noise or frantically wave their
arms to get the officials' attention, or for that matter, to get
the next play to the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   About one-third of the country's major college football teams,
including Stanford University and the University of California at
Berkeley, now use a version of the NFL's wireless headset system,
said Peter Amos, general manager of CoachComm, an Alabama company
that markets the devices to college teams. At about $45,000 for
each system, Amos said smaller colleges have balked at the cost.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
