<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3503 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SPORTSSIDE-SPORTSSIDE     12-08 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTSSIDE-SPORTSSIDE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Internet Getting In on the Game  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
In addition to on-the-field changes, new technology is about to
revolutionize the way sports leagues and teams connect with their
fans, according to a recent study.
<P>
   The Internet will cause a ``power shift'' in the way sports
entertainment is delivered to fans, a Forrester Research Inc. study
concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of relying on traditional television and radio
broadcasts, professional sports franchises will use the Web to
deliver merchandise and even the games themselves directly to their
fans.
</P>
<P>
   And aspects of sports that historically were considered
background information, such as player statistics, scores and game
highlights, will become commodities that generate revenue, said
Mark Hardie, Forrester senior analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``By 2004, the sports power shift will dictate new roles for the
major players in the sports marketplace,'' Hardie said. ``The
Internet will become more than just another distribution channel.''
</P>
<P>
   In four years, advertising on sports-related sites should top $4
billion annually, while the Web will account for about 15 percent
of revenues for U.S. professional sports leagues, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball and hockey fans who have the best seats at New York's
Madison Square Garden this season are getting an early glimpse at
that power shift.
</P>
<P>
   CSI Inc. of New York has installed interactive touch-screen
monitors on 557 courtside seats at the Garden and on 100 seats in
Tropicana Field, home of baseball's Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   With the ChoiceSeat screens, courtside basketball fans can view
replays of Latrell Sprewell slam dunks from up to eight different
camera angles and then pull up how many three-point shots he has
made in his career. They can also order a drink or buy a souvenir
Knicks jersey from their seats.
</P>
<P>
   The screens are linked through an intranet in the Garden, but
eventually, CSI plans to make the same replays and data available
to fans at home via the Internet, said Barry Goldberg, a CSI vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   CSI, which has Intel Corp. of Santa Clara as a minority
investor, hopes to install more ChoiceSeat screens in outdoor
stadiums like the new Pacific Bell Park in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Other NHL and NBA teams have already installed a computerized
system designed by IBM that compiles the official game statistics,
video clips, and a real-time play-by-play of the game to send out
instantly on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of 50 U.S sports franchises showed that individual team
Web sites now generate an average of $100,000 in revenue, mainly
through ticket sales, Hardie said. By leveraging the fan-drawing
power of the stats and highlights they already have, teams can
expect to increase their Web site revenues to an average of $1
million per team by 2004, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, instead of selling blanket broadcast rights to local
stations or national networks, teams may license rights to
statistics, ticket sales, merchandise or live telecasts of games in
progress to a variety of Internet outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might have a big network partnering with a dot-com,''
Hardie said. ``It's not inconceivable to see CBS and Yahoo put
together a football deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports purists may argue that all the high-tech gadgetry
detracts from the enjoyment of the games on the field or court,
said Susan Hofacre, professor of sports management at Robert Morris
College in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   But the encroachment of technology in sports is inevitable,
especially in pro sports, where team owners are constantly trying
to stay ahead of rising player salaries, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All sports can't rely on just the sports purists,'' said
Hofacre, who is originally from Walnut Creek. ``They have to do
everything they can to appeal to the casual fan. In five or 10
years, people will simply accept it in the same way as people who
used to think instant replay was distracting.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
