<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3521 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-TAX-NYT &LR;      12-08 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE CONCEDES SOUR ECONOMY MIGHT CAUSE TAX RISE
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Replaces GORE-RUSSIA) 
(rk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After days of lacerating former Sen. Bill Bradley for
acknowledging that he might have to raise taxes, Vice President Al
Gore Wednesday admitted that if the economy took a turn for the
worse, he would not rule out a tax increase either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under current economic circumstances, I have no intention of
proposing any tax increase,'' the vice president said.
</P>
<P>
   But when pressed by a reporter as to whether he was flatly
ruling out ever raising taxes, he said, ``I am ruling them out
under circumstances that approximate what we have today,'' and
added, ``Nobody has a crystal ball.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview here Wednesday night, he elaborated, saying he
would not raise taxes ``under current circumstances, or anything
remotely similar to current circumstances, so long as we have a
surplus, so long as we have a balanced budget, so long as we don't
have a deep economic crisis of some kind that changes the
circumstance.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president took a reporter's pen and notebook and drew a
grid to explain his position on taxes as well as Bradley's.
</P>
<P>
   Under ``current circumstances,'' he wrote: ``AG: No New Taxes!''
For Bradley, he wrote: ``BB: ``May Raise Taxes ... to pay for
health care plan.''
</P>
<P>
   But under ``unknown future of Economy,'' he wrote: ``AG:
Possibilities Hard to Rule Out.'' For Bradley, he wrote ``BB:
same.''
</P>
<P>
   To the Bradley campaign's ears, Gore was finally acknowledging
that the two candidates' positions were the same.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Hauser, a spokesman for Bradley, responded almost
triumphantly to Gore's remarks Wednesday, saying, ``It's clear that
the vice president is in the same place as we are, and it makes me
wonder why he spent the better part of a week attacking a position
he holds.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were gleeful at the sight of Democrats fighting over
taxes. At a news conference Wednesday morning in Washington, Jim
Nicholson, chairman of the Republican National Committee, called
Gore and Bradley ``the Frick and Frack of higher tax,'' adding,
``The only difference between Bradley and Gore is that Bradley
admits he'll raise our taxes, while Gore wants us to believe he'll
limit himself to raising taxes on smokers.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a challenge by Bradley on Monday that Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, the Republican presidential contender, take a
pledge not to raise new taxes, Nicholson said Bush already had, as
have all six of the Republican presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute in the Democratic race reflects the widely accepted
view in politics that any mention of taxes is poison to a campaign,
whether it is realistic or not.
</P>
<P>
   The examples are seared in the nation's consciousness: Walter
Mondale, the Democratic nominee, said during his 1984 campaign that
a tax increase was nearly inevitable, and he lost 49 states to
Ronald Reagan. And when President George Bush's famous assertion to
voters _ ``Read my lips: No new taxes'' _ was violated, he too was
consigned to history.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley says Gore has completely distorted what he said about
raising taxes. In a transcript of an interview with The Washington
Post, where the issue first came up last week, Bradley never
specifically asserted that he would raise taxes. In fact, he was
nearly as vague then as Gore was Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was asked by The Post if a tax increase might be
necessary. According to the transcript, Bradley roamed all over the
question, saying at first, ``You tell me what the growth rate is,
I'll give you the answer.'' He added: ``You have to deal with it at
the time.'' But he said that his desire to provide near-universal
health care coverage was non-negotiable, and depending on what else
happened, the options were ``cutting spending or increasing
taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore in the interview in Manhattan, after helping children light
a menorah at the 92nd Street Y, said: ``If you're talking about the
unknown future of the economy, you can't begin to rule out
possibilities. But I have no intention of it. His position is the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore insisted there was a difference in their positions,
too. ``Under our current economic circumstances, I rule it out,''
he said. ``Under our current economic circumstances, he doesn't
rule it out. He has to say that he may have to raise taxes because
he cannot explain the huge gap in his health care plan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
