<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3523 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-ALBRIGHT-NYT &LR;      12-08 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ALBRIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS FIND STARTING POINT AND ROOM FOR MIDEAST HOPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After three hours at the hilltop palace in Damascus,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright left her meeting with
President Hafez Assad of Syria on Tuesday, drove straight to the
American ambassador's house and made a secure call to President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Although the groundwork had been laid in previous diplomatic
meetings, Albright clearly had good news to report. She had
apparently broken through an impasse and found a formula that would
allow direct Israeli-Syrian negotiations to resume after nearly
four years.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's absolute condition for re-entering negotiations _ that
Israel agree to turn over the Golan Heights down to the border of
June 4, 1967, the border that defined the land Syria held on the
eve of the Arab-Israeli war that year _ had melted into a
negotiable position.
</P>
<P>
   Assad repeatedly cited that condition because he considered it
the point where negotiations with the Israelis, under Yitzhak
Rabin, the assassinated prime minister, had broken off. The
Israelis did not agree, and the disagreement over where
negotiations ended had bedeviled the effort to rekindle talks.
</P>
<P>
   Assad decided, in his meeting with Albright, that he no longer
required a public confirmation of his viewpoint before negotiations
began. He agreed to the Americans' proposed formula, which
deliberately allows what diplomats call a ``constructive
ambiguity'' _ talks will resume where they left off, with the
understanding that each side will emphasize different points about
the past.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, after Albright arrived late in Israel, both
she and Clinton separately telephoned Prime Minister Ehud Barak of
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Albright said merely that she was more hopeful that
the negotiating track could be ``re-energized'' than she had been
when she flew into Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, after she met Barak at his residence here,
the two took their place before microphones for a news conference.
Barak appeared to be in particularly good spirits, beaming, making
wisecracks and playing the jovial host to a Hanukkah breakfast.
Mocking his own habit of declaring meetings ``fruitful'' when he
does not want to reveal more, he pronounced the breakfast meeting
``literally fruitful.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither he nor Albright would say whether there had been
progress with Syria. ``I cannot predict it,'' Barak said. ``It's
too early. It takes two to tango.''
</P>
<P>
   Things had appeared solid enough during their breakfast meeting,
though, that Barak called Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader,
during their conversation. He alerted Arafat to the potential
development and sought to assure him that Israel would not abandon
its intense, and until now undistracted, focus on final status
negotiations with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Their deadline to reach an outline for a final peace agreement
is 68 days away.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, the Israeli leader had two more phone
conversations with Clinton, who also spoke with Assad, a senior
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   By 2 p.m. Washington time, Clinton was ready to announce that
Barak would meet with Farouk Shara, the Syrian foreign minister, in
Washington next week. Israeli-Syrian negotiations were not only
resuming, but, unlike previously, they would be at the highest
political level, with following meetings also expected to be
between high political officials.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Albright will both attend the first meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Previous diplomatic meetings were conducted at the technical and
ambassadorial levels. ``To move up to the highest political level
is a major, major change in this area and will echo around the
Mideast in profound ways since Syria is a critical country that
Israel has not had these discussions with before,'' a senior
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   As he said during the news conference, Barak was more than ready
to begin the talks. ``We have so many other things to do other than
to be deployed for another generation or two along the borders and
bury our youngsters, and let the others bury theirs,'' he said.
``So it's time to make decisions. I feel, somehow, the opportunity
is clear also to President Assad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically we know all that we can know about his positions,
and he knows all that he can know about our positions, short of
making the decision,'' Barak continued.
</P>
<P>
   Under Barak's two predecessors, there were periodic contacts but
no face-to-face negotiations between Syria and Israel. His
immediate predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu, held conversations
through an American businessman, Ronald Lauder.
</P>
<P>
   When he took office in July, Barak pledged to withdraw Israeli
troops from southern Lebanon within a year. The pledge was
originally based on the expectations that talks with Syria would
resume, and that the withdrawal from Lebanon, much of which is
controlled by Syria, would be done in the cooperation with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   On taking office, Barak immediately began wooing Assad through
public messages complimenting his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Assad responded, sending equivalent messages of
interest the Israelis' way.
</P>
<P>
   Five months passed with little overt progress, but the Americans
were working on the Syrians during this time. Clinton and Albright
both met with Shara, on several occasions. Diplomatic messages
traveled back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was the withdrawal from the Golan Heights discussed
substantively, but so were security arrangements, issues such as
water, and the timetable for carrying out the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Progress was being made when Shara had an aneurysm, was
hospitalized and underwent bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Assad is also reported to be in frail health, although Albright
found him to be vigorous and in full command during their meeting,
a senior administration official said. He is expected to take part
in future talks, although Shara will represent Syria for now.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beside Albright at a news conference at his compound in
Ramallah Wednesday night, Arafat looked wan and said little. But he
praised the revival of Israeli-Syrian negotiations as ``good news
that will bring happiness to the Palestinian people and all the
Arab world.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright said that Israeli-Palestinian final status talks,
briefly disrupted before her arrival, would continue and that
Arafat would visit Washington early next year to meet with Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
