A3529 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-BIGGIO-HNS     12-08 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BIGGIO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Astros have reached an agreement on a three-year contract
extension with second baseman Craig Biggio, a source said
Wednesday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed, but the contract is
believed to include an average annual salary of $8 million to $9
million, which would make the seven-time All-Star the highest-paid
player in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement could be made today.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio already was signed for the coming season; the extension
should keep him in an Astros uniform through 2003, when he will be
37 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker declined comment, as has
been his stance throughout the negotiations. Biggio's agent, Barry
Axelrod, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio, 33, has been in the Astros organization since 1987, when
he was selected in the first round of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   He hit .294 with 16 homers, 73 RBIs, 28 stolen bases and a
club-record 56 doubles in 1999, becoming only the sixth player in
history to reach the 50-doubles mark in back-to-back seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there was a trade rumor circulating Wednesday,
linking Astros lefthander Mike Hampton and the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to confirm or deny conversations about specific
players,'' Hunsicker said. ``But I am going to the winter meetings
to explore all the options we have to improve the ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players that are going into the last year of their
contracts are candidates to trade until we get to a point where we
know that we can sign them past the 2000 season.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, center fielder Carl Everett and right fielder Derek
Bell are the most prominent Astros who can become free agents after
the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   In other Astros-related news, the club officially announced
Wednesday it will not offer salary arbitration to its four
remaining free agents _ shortstop Ricky Gutierrez, infielder Jack
Howell, outfielder Stan Javier and pitcher Brian Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros cannot negotiate with or re-sign any of the four
players until afterMay 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
