u a BC-MANDELA-SPI &LR;      12-08 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANDELA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANDELA TACKLES TOUGH ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH SCHUBERT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ On the first day of his tightly orchestrated trip to
Seattle, Nelson Mandela made it clear his speeches would be filled
with more than gracious thank-you's and bland pleasantries.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of events that took Mandela and his wife, Graca
Machel, from a morning welcome at Boeing Field to a black-tie
benefit dinner downtown, Mandela spoke with quiet firmness and
characteristic humor about a range of issues.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela chided the United States for flouting the United
Nations, spoke of the dire poverty faced by many children in
Africa, implored business leaders to address the AIDS epidemic and
personally thanked the anti-apartheid protesters in Seattle who
fought for him while he was in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In some of his most pointed remarks of the day, Mandela told a
special meeting of the Seattle Rotary Club that the United States
had no right to take certain military actions without going through
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``To take a decision with Britain to go and bomb Iraq without
going through the United Nations, to go and bomb in Kosovo together
with NATO without going through the United Nations, we condemn that
in the strongest sense,'' Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has led to comments, which I don't believe (are) true,
... that now that the United Nations is led by a black man, that
the United States has lost respect for that organization.''
</P>
<P>
   That black man is U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan of Ghana,
who spoke last week to the Rotary Club during the World Trade
Organization meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela and Machel's three-day trip was planned to bring
together the couple's considerable moral capital with the financial
capital of the Northwest's growing philanthropies.
</P>
<P>
   The Craig and Susan McCaw Foundation and Bill and Melinda Gates
Foundation created an itinerary focused on issues Mandela and
Machel are trying to address through their own organizations. These
include health care, education, peace, conflict resolution and
economic development.
</P>
<P>
   Last night's fund-raising dinner at the Seattle Sheraton Hotel
attracted about 800 people who paid at least $250 per plate. For
$1,000, guests were invited to a reception and got their photos
taken with Mandela and Machel.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's packed itinerary Wednesday kicked off with a
welcoming ceremony at Boeing Field, where hundreds of Seattle
schoolchildren greeted them with cheers and smiles.
</P>
<P>
   As they walked from McCaw's jet to the podium set up in a
hangar, the couple stopped to shake hands and kiss some of the
children pressing against the velvet ropes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exciting; it was surprising,'' said Courtne Clark, a
student at Leschi Elementary School. ``It made me happy.''
</P>
<P>
   In remarks addressed to the children as much as the community
leaders and politicians on the dais, Mandela talked about why
children's issues are so important to him.
</P>
<P>
   He told the story of a cold winter day when a group of children
asked why he loved them enough to give part of his Nobel Peace
Prize money to help children.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were saying we enjoy no parental love and security,''
Mandela said. ``We have no future because we are the outcasts of
society.''
</P>
<P>
   It was because of them that Mandela gave one-tenth of his salary
to help children. With the support of American businessmen, he
built schools around the country. Mandela exhorted the children
gathered before him Wednesday to stay away from drugs and alcohol
and work hard in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to reach the position of the presidency like Bill
Clinton, like George Bush, ... you must listen carefully to your
teachers,'' Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela made a point of thanking the anti-apartheid
demonstrators who helped move his cause forward when he was in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief, but emotional, meeting after the ceremony, Mandela
personally thanked a small group of Seattle anti-apartheid
activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even without the international community, the people of South
Africa would have won, but the struggle would have cost a lot of
bloodshed and suffering, and the fact that the anti-apartheid
movement came to our assistance certainly made that struggle less
costly,'' said Mandela, who spent 27 years in prison, much of it in
solitary confinement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept saying `thank you' and I kept saying `thank you' to
him, because I think he's done more for us than we did for him,''
Maryamu Eltayeb-Givens, the last president of the Seattle Coalition
Against Apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   Selma Waldman, who served as the historian of the coalition,
said that meeting Mandela was an honor. But after all of the years
of reading his speeches and protesting against anti-apartheid, the
activists almost felt like they already knew him.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it's layer after layer of meaning and freedom and
justice,'' Waldman said. ``You know, you do win a few.''
</P>
<P>
   At a special meeting of the Seattle Rotary Club, Mandela was
treated to a special performance by the Seattle Symphony and handed
the baton to lead the symphony and a choir of high school students
in the South African national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks at the Rotary Club meeting, Mandela focused on
the ``poverty, squalor, ignorance and disease'' that are the daily
companions of so many people in South Africa and Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where it is taboo to talk about sex, Mandela and
Machel have worked to find ways to address HIV, which has infected
millions of Africans. In a kind of prelude to the Global Health
Forum that Mandela and Microsoft CEO Bill Gates will lead Thursday
morning, Mandela implored the U.S. to help educate Africans about
AIDS and help with medical assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela's remarks included a call for the U.S. to pay its United
Nations dues, lift the sanctions on Libya and aid in a more
comprehensive peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he visited small business owners and community leaders in
the Central District, where a small crowd spontaneously gathered to
wave and cheer as the motorcade drove off from the Manning
Childcare Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out off of my sickbed to see him,'' said neighborhood
resident Sylvia Wesley, who was nursing a cold but wore a delighted
grin. ``He waved to us, he smiled. That made me feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   At Madrona Elementary School, Mandela shook the hand of
fourth-grader Keyaunna Johnson, who had thanked him in a letter for
``coming to make peace.'' He patted the awed child's cheek and
politely asked, ``Are you the principal of this school?''
Starstruck, the girl softly replied, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyaunna later said that she had learned about Mandela in class
but already knew his face _ his portrait hangs in her family's
living room along with those of Martin Luther King Jr. and Malcolm
X.
</P>
<P>
   Madrona Principal Rickie Malone praised Mandela as ``a man who
shook up a nation, and then went on to shake up a world.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone had worked in both the civil rights and anti-apartheid
movements, joining regular Saturday pickets of the house of the
South African counsul in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela signed a souvenir for Malone _ a picture she has kept
throughout the years of herself picketing against apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   The newly formed Nelson Mandela Foundation promotes health care,
education, peace and conflict resolution on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
   Machel, the former minister of education in Mozambique, helped
form the Foundation for Community Development, which is concerned
with economic development, health care and other needed programs in
Mozambique and other African countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
