<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MICROSOFT JOINS ERICSSON IN A WIRELESS WEB VENTURE
</P>
<P>
   Ericsson of Sweden, the mobile phone maker, and Microsoft said
they would create a joint venture to market and deliver mobile
e-mail and other Internet services for wireless network operators.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Ericsson will provide its Wireless
Application Protocol to Microsoft and will adopt Microsoft's Mobile
Explorer, a new version of its Internet browser, in future cellular
phones. Shares of Microsoft closed at $91.75, down $1.25, while the
American depository receipts of Ericsson rose $5.125, to $64.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS PAUSE FROM RECENT RALLY
</P>
<P>
   Stocks closed mostly lower as investors took a break from their
recent buying spree in the technology sector and failed to find any
reasons to buy stocks in the broader market. The Dow Jones
industrial average fell 38.53 points, to 11,068.12. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index declined 5.29 points, to 1,403.88, while the
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index fell 0.84 point, to
3,586.08.
</P>
<P>
   SEC OPENS UP BIG BOARD TRADING
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission approved a rule that
opens up trading in the shares of New York Stock Exchange companies
and is expected to spur competition and lower costs to investors.
</P>
<P>
   SUITS SEEK ONLINE TRADEMARK NAMES
</P>
<P>
   Trademark holders nationwide are filing lawsuits to win the
rights to online names they consider their property under a new law
banning ``cybersquatting,'' the registration of trademark names as
Internet addresses in the hope of selling them at huge profits.
</P>
<P>
   FOUNDATION TO FOCUS ON EDUCATION
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs Group, which set aside $200 million from its
public stock offering earlier this year to endow a foundation named
after the company, said that the institution would focus
exclusively on education.
</P>
<P>
   BANK OF SCOTLAND DETAILS OFFER
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Scotland provided details on how it intends to take
over National Westminster Bank and generate $1.6 billion in annual
savings from the combined operations. But neither its offer nor
that of its rival, Royal Bank of Scotland, is especially enriching
to NatWest shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WORLDCOM EXECUTIVE TO RESIGN
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom said that Timothy Price, the president and chief
executive of its largest unit, the communications group, would
leave on Feb. 28, the third resignation by an executive of the
former MCI Communications since it was acquired by Worldcom last
year. MCI Worldcom did not say why he was leaving. Known for his
marketing savvy, Price is credited with helping turn MCI into
AT&AMP;T's biggest rival before the Worldcom buyout.
</P>
<P>
   MANNESMANN CHIEF CITES SUPPORT
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of Mannesmann, Klaus Esser, said that he had
the support of large institutional stockholders representing 30
percent of the company's shares in his campaign to thwart a $127.7
billion hostile takeover bid from Vodafone AirTouch of Britain. But
he was unable to say whether they will actually reject Vodafone's
offer.
</P>
<P>
   ETOYS TAKES LEAD FROM TOYSRUS
</P>
<P>
   The holiday battle to be the leading toy store in cyberspace
shifted last week as eToys, the Internet start-up company, pulled
ahead of Toysrus.com, the Web site of the retail toy chain,
according to Media Metrix, a Web research company.
</P>
<P>
   FED SURVEY REPORTS SOLID GROWTH
</P>
<P>
   The economy continued to expand at a ``moderate to strong'' pace
in October and November with little sign of inflation, the Federal
Reserve said in its latest regional economic survey, known as the
beige book.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT SUISSE UNIT CHARGED IN JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   Japanese authorities charged a unit of Credit Suisse Group and
its former Tokyo branch manager with helping 60 Japanese companies
cover up losses and hide evidence.
</P>
</TEXT>
