<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-CHEATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEATING ON SCORES CHEATED THE CHILDREN, SAY PARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LYNETTE HOLLOWAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Valerie Wright, 37, of the South Bronx said she began
to suspect that her sons' school was encouraging cheating two years
ago when her older boy came home one day and said his practice test
was a lot like the citywide reading exam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was after the fact, so I didn't do anything about it,'' she
recalled Wednesday as she dropped her younger son off at the
school, Community Elementary School 90. ``But I told him it wasn't
right and that it was cheating.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents like Ms. Wright said they often found themselves in the
uncomfortable position of having to teach their children that what
their teachers were doing was not right. On Tuesday, school
investigators accused 43 teachers, 2 principals and 2
paraprofessionals of giving answers on standardized tests to
students in 32 New York City schools.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph Brown, 35, a furniture mover whose son, James, is in
the third grade at CES 90, said he was deeply disturbed by the
accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that school is an extension of the home,'' Brown
said. ``Don't lie. Don't cheat. The morals you teach at home should
be carried over to the school setting. This is wrong that they are
teaching the kids the cheater's route. Firing the teachers is a
good step.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, parents said they were more shocked than surprised, given
the long history of neglect of the school and its Bronx district.
</P>
<P>
   CES 90 is on Sheridan Avenue, at Grand Central Concourse and
166th Street in Community School District 9, which has been racked
by scandal for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on a windswept stretch of narrow sidewalk in front of
the school, several parents said Wednesday that they had always
suspected that cheating was going on, but had never tried to do
anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing about this school surprises me,'' said Ms. Wright, who
was dropping off Raymond, 8. She acknowledged that she did not try
to report her suspicions two years ago. ``The last principal left
after he was accused of taking money from the school. There are
rodents in the cafeteria. Why not cheating?''
</P>
<P>
   Other parents said that the machinations at the school made it
difficult for them to assess how well their children were doing.
Daisy Diaz, 26, recalled how her daughter, Daisy Ferrer, 9, scored
above average on the citywide reading test in the third grade,
though she was just an average student.
</P>
<P>
   ``I help her with her homework,'' Ms. Diaz said. ``I wasn't
seeing what the test showed. It showed that she was a really smart,
above-average kid. She's just average.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Edward Stancik, the special investigator for New
York City schools, announced that the 47 educators had engaged in
systematic cheating to improve students' scores on citywide reading
and mathematics tests during the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators found that some teachers and principals
allowed students to mark their answers on scrap or notebook paper,
then told them which answers to correct on the test booklet. Others
directed students to erase wrong answers, or even changed answers
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew held a last-minute news conference
on Tuesday at which he pledged a thorough investigation and
announced that he had reassigned many of those involved to ``desk
duty.'' He played down differences that he and Stancik had had in
the past. Crew has accused Stancik of grandstanding, while Stancik
has accused him of being slow to act on problems.
</P>
<P>
   But in praising Stancik's findings, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
tiptoed around a potential squabble with Crew, with whom he has
been in conflict over education overhaul. At a news conference,
Giuliani declined to discuss how the findings might affect Crew,
who is trying to decide whether he wants to seek a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Ed Stancik does very, very good work,'' the mayor
said. ``The board has to take this very seriously, and it can't be
in denial of it. They have to face up to it, make people
accountable and make sure it doesn't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   The report cited flagrant cheating in CES 90 and 88 in District
9 in the Bronx and Public School 234 in District 12 in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation began at CES 90 after a teacher, Stacey
Moscowitz, reported the school's practices to Stancik's office and
a television news reporter. Jon Nichols, a mathematics teacher, and
others came forward to support the accusations. Mrs. Moskowitz, who
started at the school in 1990, and Nichols, who started in 1993,
told investigators that the principal, Richard Wallin, coached them
to help students cheat. They did so, they said, under pressure to
succeed.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1998, Wallin was transferred to the District 9
offices because of an unrelated, unspecified disciplinary matter,
the report said. Later that year, the school's third-grade reading
scores dropped to 39.9 percent, from 66.7 percent the year before.
The school has students from kindergarten through fourth grade.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, parents suggested that Wallin's transfer may have
been related to questionable spending practices. Several parents
said he might have spent money on an aquarium that was intended for
school supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money was supposed to go for the kids, but he spent it on
animals, expensive aquarium fish, snakes and rabbits for his
office,'' said Madeline Vega, 27, the vice president of the
school's Parent-Teacher Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vega, whose daughter, Angelica, 9, is in the fourth grade,
said that she had heard reports of cheating for years, but that
nothing had ever been done because parents felt powerless. Many
said they thought their children were being shortchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to know anything,'' said Yvonne Gonzalez,
30, who was at the school to pick up her niece. ``What's going to
happen when the kids get to junior high and they can't read? They
were cheating the children out of their education.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Thomas, 33, knows the results firsthand. Several years
ago, she found out that one of her two grown daughters who had
attended the school was unable to read or write, she said. Now, her
5-year-old daughter, April, is enrolled at the school. She would
prefer to send her to a private school, but she cannot afford it,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my suspicions,'' Mrs. Thomas said. ``When I transferred
Cindy out of the school, she didn't have any records. The records
they did find were incomprehensible. You couldn't understand what
they wrote. They were passing her from grade to grade and she
couldn't read or write.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 2253EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
