u w BC-CLINTON-CONFERENCE-HN     12-08 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONFERENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CAUTIONS RUSSIA IN YEAR'S FINAL NEWS SESSION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton warned Russia on Wednesday it
risks alienation from the international community and investors
because of its military campaign against Chechnya but he refused to
suspend U.S. aid to punish Moscow for attacks on civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The president, hosting his final news conference of the year,
also said politics and threats should have no place in the
emotional debate over the fate of a 6-year-old Cuban boy found
clinging to an inner tube. Cuba and his father demand his return.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's session with reporters, held at the State Department's
Dean Acheson Auditorium, underscored his emphasis on international
issues. But, the president boasted of a number of domestic
accomplishments, despite beginning this year with a historic
impeachment battle.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cautioned Russia that it should not rely on the world's
desire to see it succeed, both economically and democratically, to
protect it from an international backlash caused by its punitive
Chechen policy.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow warned Chechen civilians this week to flee the capital of
Grozny by Saturday or face death. The Russia military wants to
destroy the Islamic rebels seeking independence.
</P>
<P>
   He said the continued military campaign and the resulting mass
of refugees ``will further alienate the global community from
Russia.'' He said that was bad because Russia needs support, not
just from the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need investors. They need people to have confidence in
what they're doing. So there will be a heavy price there,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF suspended a $650 million loan installment to Russia but
based the decision, technically, on economic reasons. Clinton
raised the prospect that the Chechen conflict also could affect
Russia's loans. ``That's a bridge we'll have to cross when we get
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton placed foreign aid sanctions off the table,
noting Russia, as a member of the United Nations Security Council,
could veto any international effort. He said U.S. aid, about $600
million yearly, to Russia is dedicated to defusing and safeguarding
Moscow's nuclear weapons or supporting democratic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our interests would be furthered by terminating
that,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Cuba matter, the president was questioned about his
feelings and concerns over Elian Gonzalez and he repeatedly tried
to sidestep the emotional issue.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the United States should follow its legal process
to determine the fate of the boy, found in the ocean between Cuba
and Florida. His mother was among 11 people who drowned while
fleeing Cuba. President Fidel Castro and the boy's father are
demanding his return, but relatives in Florida and the Cuban
community want the youngster to remain in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba says the United States' failure to immediately return Elian
to his father violates the spirit of accords signed to stop an
exodus of tens of thousands of Cubans in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that politics or threats should have anything to
do with it,'' Clinton said. He added that the boy's status was not
his decision to make; it was the court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton addressed a series of topics during the hour-long
session. They included:
</P>
<P>
   _ Defending his handling of the World Trade Organization session
in Seattle, predicting labor and environmental concerns backed by
the United States eventually will become a part of the WTO agenda.
</P>
<P>
   _ Saying the Housing and Urban Development's planned lawsuit
against gun manufacturers is not intended to drive the gun makers
from business but to make public housing safe.
</P>
<P>
   _ Naming Franklin D. Roosevelt as his nominee for ``man of the
century'' for the four-term president's handling of the nation's
affairs during the Depression and during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   _ Praising Al Gore's decision to lessen his official role as
vice president in his quest for the Democratic nomination for
president.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reaffirming Panama's control over the Panama Canal and denying
conservatives' charges that a Hong Kong company that will operate
the ports could give China control over the critical waterway.
</P>
<P>
   _ Defending his record in hiring women and minorities for senior
positions. ``I have never not tried to recruit minorities for any
job that was open in the White House,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stating that America's racial problems ``will stay at the
center of my concerns,'' even though he has yet to release the
report on race that he promised more than a year ago. He said he is
rewriting the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The president also backed the decision by the first lady to move
out of the White House and into their new New York home as she
prepares to run for the Senate. ``So she'll be up there a lot,
she'll be here when she can,'' Clinton said. ``I'll go up there
when I can. And we'll be together as much as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton was urged to run for the Senate after her
popularity soared during the Monica Lewinsky scandal. However,
she's expected to be in a difficult race against Republican Rudolph
Guiliani, the mayor of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's candidacy is another odd turn of events coming
out of the Lewinsky scandal. Clinton was impeached by the House for
lying to a grand jury about the affair and trying to cover it up.
Only the second president in history to be impeached, Clinton was
acquitted by the Senate in January.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton retains high job approval ratings from the public and he
listed many accomplishments for this year, including U.S. led
involvement in Kosovo, a 2000 budget that helps fund more teachers
and police, progress on peace in Ireland and the Middle East and
the curtailment of North Korea's nuclear weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
