<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-SALE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL BIDS HAVE BEEN SUBMITTED FOR SALE OF JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Final bids to acquire the New York Jets were
submitted Wednesday to Goldman, Sachs, but the investment banking
firm for the Leon Hess estate did not release the names of the
potential buyers or their offers.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Grubman, a managing director at Goldman, Sachs, confirmed
the deadline for the bids and said, ``It's very competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   The bidders include Charles Dolan, the chairman of Cablevision,
Robert Wood Johnson IV, an heir to the Johnson &AMP; Johnson fortune,
and Sam Grossman, a Phoenix real estate developer, who bid
unsuccessfully for the Washington Redskins. John McMullen, the New
Jersey Devils' owner, is believed to be Dolan's minority partner.
Stephen M. Ross, a New York developer, was also expected to bid.
</P>
<P>
   The opening round of bidding two months ago narrowed the field
of suitors and brought preliminary indications above $510 million.
</P>
<P>
   The competition is expected to be the fiercest between Dolan,
whose company is the majority owner of Madison Square Garden, and
Johnson, who is active in fund-raising for the Republican Party and
the Juvenile Diabetes Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Grubman was unwilling to comment on how long it will take to
declare a winner. If the process follows a typical course, Goldman,
Sachs, will analyze the bids and their financing, and could pick a
winner quickly if one greatly exceeds the others.
</P>
<P>
   If two or three are close together, the firm will probably try
to negotiate the bids higher and hope that one separates itself
from the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the process, the investment banking firm will consult
with John Hess, the son of the late Jets' owner, and the other
executors of his father's estate. Ultimately, the winning bid
requires the approval of the National Football League's finance
committee and a three-quarters vote of its full ownership. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
