<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-DELAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOVERY LAUNCH PUT ON HOLD AGAIN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ NASA has delayed for at least one day the
launch of the shuttle Discovery on a mission to the Hubble Space
Telescope so that engineers can assess damage to a dented fuel
line.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery and a crew of seven had been scheduled to lift off at
11:42 p.m. EST Saturday from NASA's Kennedy Space Center.
</P>
<P>
   If the 6-foot section of line must be replaced, the liftoff will
be delayed by several days, said NASA's Joel Wells, a shuttle
program spokesman. A decision on how long to delay the planned
10-day flight was expected Thursday after an engineering analysis
of the damage, Wells said.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's countdown was to begin early Thursday, but those
activities were postponed as well.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttle managers have said they want Discovery back on the
ground by Dec. 27 to avoid potential Y2K surprises. If the launch
does not occur by Tuesday, shuttle managers would consider
shortening the planned 10-day flight, but no liftoff is planned
beyond Dec. 17, Wells said.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's crew plans four lengthy spacewalks to replace the
Hubble's failing gyroscopes and make other repairs. Astronomers
were forced to halt Hubble observations last month after four
gyros, crucial components of the telescope's pointing system,
failed.
</P>
<P>
   The dented fuel line is the latest in a series of difficulties
that have led to postponements since the initial launch plan of
mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   The damage is to a line that recirculates supercold liquid
hydrogen between the shuttle's three rocket engines and its large
external fuel tank prior to liftoff. It was discovered by
technicians working in Discovery's engine compartment early
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As they removed a protective covering called ``elephant wrap,''
technicians found a 12-inch-long, half-inch deep dent in the metal
line. The 4-inch-wide vacuum conduit includes a fuel line and an
outer sleeve that insulates the chilled fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers are assessing whether the dented outer sleeve would
hamper the insulation, Wells said. X-ray examinations and other
evaluations revealed no cracks in the line.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the damage is unclear, but it could have been
caused by a worker inadvertently stepping on the line, said Jack
King, a spokesman for the United Space Alliance, NASA's shuttle
contractor.
</P>
<P>
   King said workers must wear protective headgear and clothing
because of the toxic fuels in the shuttle's cramped engine
compartment, making it difficult for them to maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency suspended all shuttle missions after the
shuttle Columbia experienced an electrical short during liftoff in
July. When the short was traced to wiring with damaged insulation,
shuttle managers ordered inspections and repairs to each of the
winged space shuttles.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery required 57 repairs to the insulation on internal
wiring.
</P>
<P>
   Additional delays were announced because NASA decided to replace
a rocket engine containing a half-inch-long broken drill bit;
inspect and repair a bundle of wires linking the shuttle and its
fuel tank; replace a data cable linking the fuel tank and the solid
rocket boosters; and replace a wire harness linking a rocket engine
and its computerlike controller.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
