<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORK TIME OFTEN EATEN UP ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) You hit your minimize button to hide your Internet
window. You turn your computer screen to be less visible to
passers-by. You can't remember when you last wrote a letter from
home.
</P>
<P>
   You have a Web-linked computer at work.
</P>
<P>
   If you're like the majority of employees surveyed in September
by Vault.com, a career information and company gossip Internet
site, you spend a lot of work time online.
</P>
<P>
   Only about one in 10 of the 1,244 workers surveyed said that Web
surfing for nonwork reasons was unethical and that they didn't do
it. More than one-third said they surfed ``constantly.'' More than
half admitted surfing more than 30 minutes a day.
</P>
<P>
   Only 16 percent said they never sent personal e-mails from work.
The rest admitted sending and receiving from one to more than 20
nonwork messages a day.
</P>
<P>
   About three-fourths said they didn't take special measures to
avoid detection nor had they been caught. Fifty-six percent
acknowledged that Net time decreased their productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Vault.com also queried a similar number of employers (1,438) for
the company perspective. Bosses see that the Internet is here to
stay.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 40 percent of the employers said 30 minutes or more a day
online was permissible; 4.2 percent of them condoned more than an
hour, citing stress relief and ``balancing life's needs'' as
reasons for leniency.
</P>
<P>
   Same with personal e-mailing. All but 14 percent of employers
said sending nonwork e-mails from work was permissible.
</P>
<P>
   It could be that managers are too busy to police personal
computer use. Whatever the reason, only about half said they had
``caught'' an employee online; only half said worker productivity
was hurt by nonwork surfing.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the statistics are opinions. For example: Do employers
have the right to monitor employee Internet use?
</P>
<P>
   Some employees and employers say no, a company has no right to
open a postal envelope addressed to a recipient, so neither should
e-mails be fair game. Others say it's the company dime _ equipment,
Internet access and time _ so, yes, the employer has the right to
control use.
</P>
<P>
   And what about control of content? Do employers have the right
to punish a worker who has e-mail or opens a Web page with content
someone else finds objectionable?
</P>
<P>
   Some employees and employers alike say yes, of course _ the
workplace must protect workers from offensive exposure that could
be classified as discrimination or harassment. Others say no _
controlling access threatens freedom of speech and rights of
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The universal conclusion is that the Internet consumes work
time. Seven out of 10 employers know it but still don't have
policies to monitor or restrict it. It's hard to know if they're
ignoring the issue, don't care about it or haven't had time to
address it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, employees who surf on company time and equipment
should remember that employers can trace their activity. Success in
the cyberspace work world may not require you to watch your back,
but rather watch your tracks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
