u a BC-CONN-MEDICARE-FRAUD-N     12-08 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-MEDICARE-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE FRAUD CASE IS SETTLED FOR $74 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ One of Connecticut's largest health care
providers has agreed to pay $74 million for distributing millions
of dollars in unnecessary Medicare payments to hospitals in the
late 1980s and early '90s, federal investigators announced
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The amount represents the largest fraud settlement related to
health care in the state's history, they said, and is the
second-largest fraud settlement in the country involving a Medicare
contractor.
</P>
<P>
   According to the terms of the civil settlement, the provider,
Anthem Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Connecticut, will pay the
government $41.8 million within 10 days, said U.S. Attorney Stephen
Robinson, speaking to reporters from his offices in New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining $32.4 million of the settlement represents the
amount of illegal overpayments Blue Cross officials made to fewer
than 10 hospitals around the state, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The enormous amount of excessive payments was a complicated
combination of miscalculation and, later, blatant cover-up by Blue
Cross officials, Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   This is how prosecutors said the scheme worked: Between 1989 and
1991, Blue Cross inadvertently overpaid some hospitals their share
of Medicare expenses. But rather than ask for that money back, the
company altered its accounting records to make it appear as though
it had actually underpaid those hospitals. Then, to cover up the
mistaken overpayments, Blue Cross knowingly overpaid other
hospitals it had initially underpaid.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the intentional overpayments to some hospitals
eventually matched the amount of inadvertent overpayments to other
hospitals. In the end, the company's books appeared to be balanced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's complicated, what they did,'' Robinson said, ``but it was
all with an intent to have the books and records be balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Blue Cross overpaid and covered up $32.4 million
over three years to preserve its $3.5 million annual contract with
the Federal Health Care Finance Administration, which rates how
accurate health care companies are in delivering Medicare payments
to hospitals nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money does not become as important as the evaluation,''
said Assistant U.S. Attorney John Hughes, explaining the company's
reasoning for the overpayments.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, Blue Cross was administering about $450
million dollars in Medicare payments a year statewide, Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   The excessive payments, both mistaken and intentional, did not
go unnoticed by many hospital administrations that received them,
Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some level of understanding that it did not belong
to them,'' Robinson said of the excess money. Some hospitals placed
the extra money in savings accounts and neither spent nor reported
it; other hospitals reported the excessive payments to ``various
individuals,'' he said, but declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the illegal payments escaped notice by auditors at
the Health Care Finance Administration and by federal prosecutors.
Prosecutors did not learn of the scheme until July 1998, seven
years after the payments were made.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials have already recovered about $25 million of
the $32.4 million in unwarranted payments, Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   The company that made the illegal payments was Blue Cross and
Blue Shield of Connecticut, which merged in August 1997 with Anthem
Health Plans of Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Accountants for the resulting company, Anthem Blue Cross and
Blue Shield of Connecticut, discovered the payment scheme in May
1998 and started an internal investigation, said Jim Parker, a
company spokesman. Around that same time, federal prosecutors began
their investigation, Robinson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 2326EST &QL; 
