<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0429 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3694 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-FARMLAND-MEETING-KAN &LR;      12-08 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARMLAND-MEETING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARMLAND STILL OPEN TO CENEX MERGER, MEMBERS TOLD AT ANNUAL
MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The ``door is still open'' for a merger of
Farmland Industries Inc. and Minnesota-based Cenex Harvest States
Cooperatives, said Harry Cleberg, head of the Kansas City-based
farm cooperative, at its annual meeting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the nation's two largest farm cooperatives voted on a
merger in late November. Although Farmland members overwhelmingly
supported it, the Cenex vote fell just short of the required
two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still think it is the right direction to go,'' Cleberg said
near the end of Farmland's two-hour general session.
</P>
<P>
   Cleberg also said there was continued merger interest at Cenex,
whose members held their annual meeting last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be extremely surprising and unbelievably
disappointing ... if that issue didn't come up for re-evaluation on
their part,'' Cleberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The two co-ops have said a merger would save $500 million over
six years.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, however, have said previously that many of those
savings could come from joint ventures without a merger. Some Cenex
members also questioned Farmland's financial condition because of
its greater use of debt.
</P>
<P>
   The topic played prominently in Cleberg's speech, which was a
review of the 70 years that Farmland has been a cooperative. He
emphasized moments when the board of directors agreed to borrow
heavily to expand or enter new businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1940, the co-op ``bet the farm'' on its first oil well,
Cleberg said. Though the well paid for itself in 18 months, the
move was risky.
</P>
<P>
   ``If some think Farmland is stretching its balance sheet today,
boy, they should have been around in 1940,'' Cleberg said. ``Yes,
Farmland has been gutsy and aggressive ... since its early
beginnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleberg also pointed to the co-op's decision in the late 1940s
to build its first nitrogen fertilizer plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was again when Farmland stretched its balance sheet,'' he
said. ``It was so tight they had bankers sitting around the board
table.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1959, Cleberg told the members, ``you bet the farm again when
you entered the pork business.'' Similarly, expansion and mergers
throughout the 1990s have depended on borrowing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Block, who was secretary of agriculture in the Reagan
administration, also spoke at the session. He urged Farmland
members to accept the reality of industry consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's undeniable,'' Block said. ``Figure a way it can work for
you, especially if farmer co-ops can have some of that muscle.''
</P>
<P>
   Members and employees of three local Farmland co-ops who
attended said they would support another attempt to merge with
Cenex.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they'll try,'' said George Bett, an employee of
Farmers Cooperative Elevator Co. in Garden Plain, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Kirby Moon, a member and director of Prairie Ag Cooperative in
Mount Union, Iowa, said Farmland had benefited from the increased
attention and discussion sparked by the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been good for the co-op system to have this,'' Moon said.
</P>
<P>
   The loudest applause came when Cleberg talked about Farmland's
victory last week in a 16-year dispute with the Internal Revenue
Service. The tax court ruling lifted a potential $400 million tax
bill from Farmland, though the IRS may appeal the ruling. An IRS
spokesman said Wednesday that the agency would not comment on the
case.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, Junior Strecker, general manager of the Scott
Cooperative Association in Scott City, Kan., received the 1999
Dreyer Award. The award annually recognizes outstanding management
of a local cooperative in the Farmland system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
