<HEADER>
A3697 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-COMPUTER-VIRUS-PLEA-N     12-08 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-VIRUS-PLEA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUILTY PLEA EXPECTED IN COMPUTER VIRUS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A New Jersey computer programmer will plead guilty Thursday to
having unleashed a computer virus in March that disabled thousands
of corporate e-mail systems, several people close to federal and
state prosecutors said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The programmer, David L. Smith, 31, was arrested on April 1
after FBI agents and officials from America Online helped
investigators from the New Jersey attorney general's office
identify the Internet access provider that was apparently first
used to send the virus. The program, named Melissa, spread faster
than any previous virus and was reported to have infected more than
100,000 computers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who will plead to both federal and state charges, will
acknowledge that the Melissa program caused more than $80 million
in damage, a sum largely reflecting the hours spent by computer
system administrators to remove the virus, people familiar with the
plea negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   The $80 million figure is significant, legal experts said,
because it suggests that Smith will receive the maximum sentence
provided under a federal computer crime statute: five years in
federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   The length of a sentence in such cases is determined by factors
including the amount of damage, cooperation with prosecutors and a
guilty plea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government is trying to send a message that they
take these kinds of Internet crimes very seriously,'' said Mark D.
Rasch, a former federal prosecutor who is president of the Global
Integrity Corp., an Internet security company based in Reston, Va.
``This is also a recognition that a single individual with a
computer has the ability to cause tens of millions of dollars of
damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies including Microsoft were forced to shut down their
electronic mail servers and cut themselves off from the outside
world temporarily to clean out the infection.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, no federal charges had been brought against Smith,
with state prosecutors taking the lead. He was initially charged
with violating four state laws; if convicted on all the state
counts, he faced a maximum of 40 years in prison and a $480,000
fine. Several people involved in the case said he would plead
guilty to one state count and one federal count.
</P>
<P>
   The Melissa program spread by making use of features in the
Microsoft Outlook e-mail program that permitted it to automatically
mail itself to people in the user's electronic address book. The
subject line of the resulting message read, ``Important Message
From'' and then listed the name of the sender, who was likely to be
known by the person receiving the message. The message itself said,
``Here is that document you asked for, don't show anyone else.
;-).''
</P>
<P>
   The attached document contained a list of passwords to
pornographic web sites. When an unsuspecting computer user opened
the document, a program hidden within the file spread the virus
through electronic mail systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Melissa virus did not intentionally destroy data on infected
computers. But because it spread with exponential speed, it caused
electronic mail congestion and stoppages around the country and led
to widespread panic in corporate offices.
</P>
<P>
   Although the virus was intended to be the work of an anonymous
author, investigators said Smith had made several errors that led
to his quick apprehension. They said he had left a variety of
digital ``fingerprints'' in the virus-carrying document that
included his name, the names of several of his employers and a
serial number that identified the computer upon which the virus had
been created. That information was quickly discovered by amateur
antivirus investigators and computer security experts and turned
over to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, although the program was first posted to an Internet
news group from a stolen America Online account, investigators used
Internet connection data and telephone records to quickly trace the
starting point to Smith's apartment in Aberdeen Township.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's lawyer, Edward Borden Jr., and state and federal
officials declined to comment Wednesday on the terms of the plea
bargain. But state officials issued a statement that a court
proceeding involving the Melissa case would take place Thursday
morning at the Monmouth County Superior Court in Freehold.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the United States attorney's office said a news
conference had been scheduled for immediately after a court
proceeding on the case Thursday afternoon at the Martin Luther King
Federal Courthouse in Newark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
