<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-PCS-KAN </SLUG>
  
 AMAZON.COM SHOPPING OFFERED ON iNTERNET-READY SPRINT PCS PHONES  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Sprint PCS customers now can ring the
registers at Amazon.com using their wireless telephones.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle-based online retailer and Sprint PCS introduced a
service Wednesday that will allow customers with Internet-ready
phones to open accounts or to access existing ones and browse a
series of menus to buy items ranging from music and books to movies
and toys.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time ever, this is shopping from your wireless
phone,'' said Andrew Sukawaty, president of Sprint PCS. ``It opens
up a whole new avenue of e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   As wireless phones and the Internet grow in popularity,
carriers, software companies and content providers are rushing to
move popular Internet services to mobile devices.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS' agreement with Amazon.com is unlikely to generate
big merchandise sales or lots of calling volume this holiday
season, analysts said. The number of customers using Web-capable
phones is still tiny, and most consider Web browsing on a wireless
phone tedious.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS has 5 million customers, about 1 million with
Internet-ready phones. It won't say how many customers have
subscribed to its wireless Web service, but the Kansas City company
could help Amazon.com add customers as the mobile Internet market
grows.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a Yankee Group study, the companies estimated that 48
million consumers would use ``smart'' phones by 2002, and 204
million by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the Amazon.com deal is a significant marketing
announcement for Sprint PCS, which is trying to include as many
brand-name content providers in its service as possible, including
Yahoo, CNN, Bloomberg and Ameritrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``About every 45 or 60 days, you'll see another one of these
content deals,'' Sukawaty said. ``We're very much focused on what
people want, on people's lifestyles.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Mark Zohar of Forrester Research, consumers will
demand price plans with unlimited Web access, phones that are more
Web-friendly and applications that are more customized before they
will adopt wireless Internet devices en masse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still very early in this game,'' he said. ``The pricing
isn't there, the devices aren't there, and the applications are
rudimentary.''
</P>
<P>
   Sukawaty agreed that the services were still in their infancy
but said the company already was seeing a fair amount of general
browsing through the existing sites.
</P>
<P>
   He said consumers would see the services evolve constantly and
probably would see new pricing packages this year geared
specifically to Internet usage rather than voice calls.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS also aims to sell its services to trucking, delivery
and utility companies, which often are heavy users of wireless data
applications. Earlier this month, Sprint PCS announced an agreement
with IBM Corp. to develop custom applications for companies that
would allow employees to access their corporate networks through
their wireless phones.
</P>
<P>
   Sukawaty would not release financial details of the Amazon.com
deal but said, ``We get a share of the activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS stock closed Wednesday at 99 1/2, up 5 3/16, after
hitting a 52-week high of 100. Amazon.com ended at 88 9/16, up 2
1/2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
