<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S TOURNEY TO BE MOVED UP TO 2002
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the midst of all the euphoria in the qualifying draw for the
men's 2002 World Cup, Sepp Blatter, the president of sport's
worldwide governing body, announced on Tuesday that the next
women's World Cup would be moved up a year, from 2003 to 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can present us with a unique financial obstacle,'' Jim
Moorhouse, a spokesman for the U.S. Soccer Federation, said
Wednesday from the federation's headquarters in Chicago. ``We have
a 50-50 breakdown for men and women, and it can be a problem
committing money and resources for both in the same year.''
</P>
<P>
   The men's World Cup in Japan and South Korea will be played from
June 1-30. The women's is expected to be scheduled for the fall,
very likely in Australia, and Blatter apparently wants the hoopla
of the men's tournament to carry over to the women.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women's team will compete in the Australia Cup next
month. The defending World Cup champions will play the Czech
Republic on Jan. 7, Sweden on Jan. 10 and Australia on Jan. 13.
</P>
<P>
   As the defender, the U.S. women automatically qualify for the
women's next World Cup. The American men must go through qualifying
rounds to advance to the finals.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
