<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNN-BIRTHDAY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN CELEBRATES AT LEAST 113 YEARS OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE NICELY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Today is the 114th birthday anniversary of
Susanne Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   Or the 113th or the 115th.
</P>
<P>
   The records in Texas, where she was born, near Houston, haven't
survived as long.
</P>
<P>
   And don't ask Lynn how old she is. It's a touchy subject, and
she won't answer.
</P>
<P>
   Her 82-year-old granddaughter, Lula Jackson, thinks 1885 is the
correct year of her birth. It couldn't be much later because Lynn
had a baby in 1900.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a birthday party at 2 p.m. at the Medicalodge Post
Acute Care Center at 6500 Greeley Ave., Kansas City, Kan., where
she has lived nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the birthday girl will attend remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very feisty, very strong,'' said Tammy Boisselle,
activity director. ``If she doesn't want to do something, she's not
doing it. She'll hold her wheelchair.''
</P>
<P>
   The staff at the Medicalodge calls her ``grandma.''
</P>
<P>
   Grandma. Even her granddaughter has grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn's health is about as good as it can be for her age, Jackson
said. She can hear if you speak up. She can see well with her one
good eye.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said her grandmother was a gardener who enjoyed eating
vegetables, especially greens such as turnip, mustard and collards.
Fatback and greens was a familiar dish in her household.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn's other ingredients for longevity are staying out of the
hot sun and living as close to the Ten Commandments as possible,
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn is a Baptist who always attended church.
</P>
<P>
   Her face lit up when asked if she was looking forward to meeting
Jesus some day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always ready to go all the time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't say much, but when the soft-spoken woman does, it
helps to have someone who is familiar as an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Some of her favorite expressions are, ``Lord have mercy,'' and
``I don't know why I'm still here.''
</P>
<P>
   But asked Wednesday how much longer she wanted to live, she
said, ``I want to live a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly she is a favorite among her caretakers, who greet her
with hugs and kisses.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing assistant Yvonne Jackson, who is not related to Lula
Jackson, stopped for a kiss at the end of her workday and agreed to
help interview Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you drink alcohol?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you smoke?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you chew tobacco?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you like snow?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you like sweet potato pie?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Um-hum.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you like snakes?''
</P>
<P>
   No response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you like to swim?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No. Only in a tub.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you like men?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're lazy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you like to cook?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes. Eat, too. All the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Yvonne Jackson promised to bring Lynn some candy for her
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something easy to eat,'' Lynn cautioned. ``Don't bring me no
tobacco.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
