<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3703 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CHIEF-FUNERAL-KAN &LR;      12-08 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIEF-FUNERAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE DEPARTMENT BURIES BELOVED DEPUTY CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TRISHA L. HOWARD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Jim Schneider had two loves in life: His
family and his fire department.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, both families laid the lifelong Raytown, Mo.,
resident to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider, deputy chief of the Raytown Fire Department, died
Saturday after a two-year battle with brain cancer. He had
undergone three surgeries and many rounds of chemotherapy. Through
it all, he kept his job with the department he had served for
almost 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a strong will to survive in the face of adversity,''
Fire Chief Rick Mawhirter said.
</P>
<P>
   The entire Raytown Fire Department attended, in dress uniform,
the funeral of a man they described as quiet, gentle and, above
all, dedicated.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider, 49, joined the department as a volunteer in 1970.
Even then, he would sometimes spend nights at the station, said
Linda Schneider, his wife of 28 years. On their wedding day, when
Linda went to pick up Jim's tuxedo, she spotted him dressed as
Smokey Bear, riding on the Fire Department's float in the Raytown
Roundup Days parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the men liked so much about him was that, rather than
assigning them something to do, he was right there doing it with
them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Being a firefighter was a job made for Schneider, who spent much
of his childhood in Raytown helping out at his father's bus
company. That early love of buses and big trucks lived on in
Schneider's career with the department, Linda said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Cheatham, a former Raytown firefighter, couldn't count the
number of fix-it projects that he and Schneider undertook. They
built a storage cage for the department's tools. They replaced the
plumbing in the old fire station on 63rd Street, saving the fire
district the cost of a plumber. They overhauled an old pumper
truck.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they designed a portable cascade system to fill
firefighters' fresh-air bottles at the scene of a fire. When
Cheatham left the department in 1986, Schneider ordered the parts
from a catalog and put the system together by himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``His need to keep these trucks running kept him running,''
Cheatham said.
</P>
<P>
   So it was until the end. Schneider returned to work a week after
his first operation, two years ago. Almost every morning, he
struggled to get out of bed, to perform even such simple tasks as
putting on his socks and shoes, Linda Schneider said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to keep doing what he had done for as long as he
could,'' she said. ``And when he couldn't do it anymore, he came
for the companionship of the men.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Schneider was frustrated at all the tasks he could no longer
do, said Battalion Chief Kevin Foster. More than once, Foster found
him out in the department's garage, cleaning the wheels of the fire
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Through the pain and the exhaustion, Schneider kept pressing on,
until, finally, a week ago, he was so sick that his co-workers had
to carry him home.
</P>
<P>
   But family and friends alike said that work had kept Schneider
alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he would have stayed in bed those mornings, we would have
lost him sooner,'' Foster said. ``He was an inspiration to us
all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
