<HEADER>
A3705 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CYBERSQUAT-LAWSUIT-NY     12-08 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSQUAT-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CYBERSQUATTING LAW TOUCHES OFF LAWSUITS OVER NAMES IN
CYBERSPACE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It has been less than two weeks since President
Clinton signed a new law banning ``cybersquatting,'' _ registering
trademark names as Internet addresses in the hope of selling them
at huge profits. But trademark holders around the country are
already filing lawsuits to win the rights to names they consider
their property.
</P>
<P>
   In California, New Zealand's America's Cup team Wednesday won a
temporary injunction preventing two New Zealand men who own the
americascup.com domain from using it for a Web site. Harvard
University accuses two men of trying to auction off a number of
Harvard-related domains, and the National Football League has sued
a man who runs NFL-related sites that it says violate the league's
trademarks and promote gambling.
</P>
<P>
   All three suits cite the anti-cybersquatting legislation that
was signed into law Nov. 29 as part of the omnibus budget bill.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the law say large companies will use it to muscle
coveted domain names, as Internet addresses are known, away from
small companies and individuals with legitimate claims to the
addresses. But even they see a bright side to the suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I argued against the law,'' said A. Michael Froomkin, a
University of Miami law professor. ``But now that we have it, I
guess we will all win by getting some convergence on what the
standards are.''
</P>
<P>
   The law was also opposed by the Clinton administration, which
feared it would undermine attempts by the Internet Corp. for
Assigned Names and Numbers, or Icann, to cut the number and cost of
complicated international lawsuits over cybersquatting by
consigning trademark-related spats to arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Icann was picked by the administration last year to take over
management of the Internet's domain name system. It has already
approved rules for assigning trademark disputes to international
arbitration centers. Those rules, however, only apply to domain
names dispensed by newly created registrar companies.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of the more than five million domain names
already assigned with the popular .com, .net and .org suffixes were
distributed by Network Solutions, a Herndon, Va., company that
until this year had a monopoly over those domains. Only domains
Network Solutions assigns after Jan. 1 will be subject to Icann's
rules.
</P>
<P>
   The first dispute under the Icann process was filed last week
with the World Intellectual Property Organization. The names of the
parties have not been made public.
</P>
<P>
   The Icann rules were intended to give trademark holders recourse
against cybersquatters who were, in effect, using domain names to
extort money from trademark holders, or in some cases to
intentionally mislead or misdirect consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But trademark holders felt the rules did not go far enough. They
persuaded Congress to pass the new law, which allows them to sue
cybersquatters for possession of domains and to seek up to $100,000
in damages.
</P>
<P>
   The America's Cup suit was filed by Quokka Sports, a company
handling the Web sites for the New Zealand America's Cup yachting
team, the same day the law was signed.
</P>
<P>
   The New Zealand team first began trying to wrest americascup.com
from two Auckland men, Arron Brett and Justin Nicholas, in June,
but the dispute has been tied up in litigation in New Zealand ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   Quokka's lawyer, Terry Gross, Wednesday persuaded a federal
judge in San Francisco to issue an injunction barring the use of
the americascup.com domain until it can be determined whether the
address should be turned over to the America's Cup New Zealand
team, which as the current holder of the cup also holds the
trademark.
</P>
<P>
   Gross insists it is a clear-cut case of cybersquatting, that the
men were using the trademark to attract advertisers and to
misdirect people looking for the official America's Cup site,
americascup.org. He said they also violated trademark laws by using
official race logos.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer representing Brett and Nicholas, however, insists the
case is an example of trademark holders trying to abscond with a
legitimately owned domain name that the plaintiff covets after
failing to register it.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Peter Dengate-Thrush, said: ``These young
entrepreneurs are being singled out unfairly. How are they going to
defend themselves in California?''
</P>
<P>
   On the East Coast, meanwhile, Harvard filed a suit Monday in
U.S. District Court in Boston, alleging that Michael Rhys and
Michael Douglas registered 65 domain names that use the words
Harvard and Radcliffe. The men are accused of violating both
cybersquatting and trademark infringement laws.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard says that after the names were registered through
Network Solutions at its standard $70 rate, the defendants put the
names up for auction on the Web site HarvardYardSale.com, asking
thousands of dollars per name.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, the National Football League filed suit in U.S.
District Court in New York City, accusing Ken Miller of Clearlake
Park, Calif., and his Web sites _ NFLtoday.com, NFLtoday.net and
NFLtoday.org _ of violating a number of trademark and
anti-cybersquatting rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
