<SLUG> BC-RAC-PINCAY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINCAY WITHIN ONE OF SHOE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Laffit Pincay did have cause for celebration
Wednesday _ it was his son's 24th birthday and the Panamanian
Mother's Day _ but the steak dinner that will follow the jockey's
record-setting victory would have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   After winning aboard Millie's Quest in the sixth race at
Hollywood Park to draw within one victory of Bill Shoemaker's
career-record 8,833, Pincay finished out of the money in two
attempts at the mark and will have to try again with four scheduled
mounts this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do it (Wednesday)`'' Pincay said, intending the
record as a gift for his older son, Laffit III, and mother,
Rosario. ``And I really thought I was going to do it. . . . But
it's only one (away), so I know someday I'm going to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay rallied the slow-starting Millie's Quest through traffic
to a half-length victory for trainer Bobby Frankel and owners
Charles and Audrey Kenis in the sixth race. Millie's Quest was the
2-1 second choice of the bettors in the 1 1/16-mile turf race.
</P>
<P>
   The 52-year-old Panama native finished second with well-backed
Golden Arches in his first race of the day, and no closer than
fourth with four other mounts, including two tote-board favorites.
Russemira, morning-line favorite in the fourth race, was reported
ill and scratched.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (early) races, I couldn't do any good,'' Pincay said. ``I
used to get stressed out when I couldn't win on favorites, but now
I realize my horses just weren't running good enough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay's four mounts today include morning-line favorite I Be
Casual in the fourth race and a mare auspiciously named Finally in
the fifth. He's scheduled to ride five horses Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
