<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3711 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TOYS-CHILD-INVENTORS-     12-08 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYS-CHILD-INVENTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TOY IDEAS DANCE IN THE HEADS OF PRECOCIOUS INVENTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass., Mich., Colo., La., N.J., N.Y.)   (bl)  
 By KATHLEEN O'BRIEN   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the holiday season marches on, children fill their
wish lists with action figures, Furbies and the oh-so-popular
Pokemon. Next year there may be a new item on those lists: Mr.
Itchy Pants.
</P>
<P>
   The wiggling stuffed doll, which sings ``I've Got Ants in My
Pants,'' was chosen from 40 finalists as a grand-prize winner of a
toy invention contest for children. It is expected to be
manufactured and sold in time for next year's holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Itchy's creator, 11-year-old Nadia Smith of Voorhees, N.J.,
based the doll on a variety of acquaintances. ``There is a boy in
my class who never sits still, so we named him Mr. Itchy Pants,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Itchy's waggling eyebrows were inspired by another friend.
Among other phrases, the doll asks, ``Hey, do you think you can
help me out?'' and says, ``I'm still itchy!''
</P>
<P>
   The prototype, made from five knee-high nylon stockings, is
autographed on the stomach by its creator. Nadia said she never
thought her idea would take first prize, and was in tears of joy
and surprise after receiving the award. Her mother, Ellen Smith,
remembers that her daughter was reluctant to attend the event. She
says she would say, ``No, Mom, everyone's going to laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Nadia advises other children to ``try hard and never give
up.'' She will receive a $10,000 college savings bond, as well as 7
percent of the royalties from the doll.
</P>
<P>
   The ants-in-the-pants doll was one of several humorous toys
spotlighted in a gathering Saturday in Manhattan. A clay prototype
submitted by Natalie Perach, 11, of Farmington Hills, Mich., showed
a monkey that smashed a banana in its face if the listener did not
laugh at its jokes.
</P>
<P>
   The Monster Spy Truck, designed by 6-year-old Scott Klein of
Antioch, Calif., came with a hidden camera behind the windshield
and could be used for several undercover purposes. ``There is a
remote control to drive it,'' Scott wrote in the description, ``and
then you can take a picture of your sister without her noticing.''
His sister, Erinn, 3, was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   There was the House for Change by Rebekah Glickman-Simon, 8, of
Boston, a doll house bank that divides a child's money into
Savings, Spendings and Charity. Rebekah got the idea for the house
when her parents increased her allowance, with the condition that
she organize her fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only had glass jars for my money,'' she said. Her doll house
has room for all her change, as well as a closet to stash that
other childhood treasure, candy.
</P>
<P>
   The contest was divided into two age groups, 8 and under and 9
to 12, with 20 finalists chosen from each group. The runners-up
were Daniel Fremont, 8, of Palo Alto, Calif., and Megan Griffin,
11, of Englewood, Colo., each of whom will receive a $2,000 college
savings bond.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel won for his Robopet, a cone-shaped remote-controlled pet
robot that wheels around and talks. ``I just thought about what
children would like,'' he said philosophically. Robopet ``will
follow you, and if it crashes into something it will say, `Ouch.'''
</P>
<P>
   Megan's design was the Karaoke Hair Care Brush, which plays
music and features a microphone so kids can sing along. ``My
friend's younger sister has a toothbrush that plays music and you
sing to it,'' she said. ``I thought it would be neat to have a
hairbrush that did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Megan, with wavy, waist-length hair, admits she already uses her
hairbrush as a microphone when jamming to the radio with friends.
</P>
<P>
   The grand prize for inventors 8 and under went to Nicholas
Englisis, 7, of Morganville, N.J., who created a doll with a
picture-frame face where a child can put a snapshot of a friend.
Nicholas suggests that his My Favorite Friend doll come with a
disposable camera to take the pictures, as well as trading cards
that can be personalized with information on the friend. Also, the
doll should have different types of hair. ``You can change the
hair,'' he said, ``if your favorite friend changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Page, 8, of West Monroe, La., creator of the
action-figure Karate-Chop Kenny, had lots of ideas on marketing.
``Who knows,'' Matthew wrote in his proposal, ``there may be a
movie of him, and it will be good! And maybe a comic book to come
with it!''
</P>
<P>
   Another idea came from Jay Lonski, 10, of Shelby Township, Mich.
His bath-time boat, the Tubtanic, is designed to break up when it
hits the side of the tub and dump lifeboat-shaped soap into the
water. ``If I win, I am planning on making a sister ship called the
Sudsoapia,'' Jay said, ``and when it travels along, liquid soap
comes out the back.''
</P>
<P>
   The contest was sponsored by Amazon.com. Jeff Bezos, the
company's founder, was a judge. ``We wanted to do something to
celebrate toys, to celebrate innovation, and to celebrate kids,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two grand prize toys will be manufactured and sold online
through Amazon.com Toys. Seven percent of the royalties will be put
in a college fund for the winners.
</P>
<P>
   The four other judges, in addition to Bezos, were: the Olympic
skating gold medalist Katerina Witt; Lonnie Johnson, inventor of
the Super Soaker water gun; Richard Levy, a developer of the Furby
doll; and Thomas Edison Sloane Jr., a veteran of the toy industry
and a great-grandson of Thomas Alva Edison. The gathering also
featured a sticky Velcro Wall and Human Bowling.
</P>
<P>
   Each child appeared onstage to introduce his or her toy. ``It
was very emotional to see the kids come up and introduce their
toys, and say, `I invented this,''' Bezos said. Although the event
featured fun and games, the presence of the toy manufacturers
showed that toy making is also a serious commercial endeavor. After
the ceremony, Levy, who has developed more than 100 toys and other
products, said the children showed creativity that is often lost in
adults. ``I just hope they stay like this, because they don't know
what can't be done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, whose Johnson Research and Development, in Atlanta,
focuses on toys, said of Nadia Smith: ``I wonder if she understands
how much her life has changed this day. Itchy Pants has the
potential to make her a millionaire.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
