<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3717 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-RELIGION-MILLENNIU     12-08 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RELIGION-MILLENNIUM-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME FAITHS ARE OFFERING SPIRITUAL ALTERNATIVES TO MILLENNIAL
PARTYING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By NADINE BROZAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In and of itself, New Year's Eve is not a religious
occasion, though there have always been people who have felt drawn
more to churches than to parties full of Champagne and noisemakers.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the sense of historic transition into the new
millennium appears to have increased the yearning among many for a
spiritual experience. If priests, ministers, rabbis and zen masters
in and around the city are correct, thousands of people will be
sitting in pews as the ball drops in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Some have decided to hold services and let their parishioners go
on to activities of their own choosing. Others are building the
celebration into the service.
</P>
<P>
   For example, parishioners at the Episcopal Church of the
Intercession in Harlem will hold a prayer vigil on Dec. 31. At 11
p.m., they will renew their Baptismal vows and receive the
Eucharist. They will stay on for a blow-out party in the church
with African-American, West Indian and Hispanic food and music.
</P>
<P>
   Worshipers at the Roman Catholic Church of St. Rose of Lima in
Rockaway Beach, Queens, will pray the rosary in the different
languages of the neighborhood _ English, Spanish, French, Polish,
Italian and Gaelic _ watch the ball drop in Times Square on a giant
television screen, say Mass, and remain for Champagne and soda
bread and bagels until 3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are looking for something more. The Graymoor
Spiritual Life Center in Garrison, N.Y., sold out its annual New
Year's retreat months ago. Normally, 30 people come. This year, the
center, which is the world headquarters for the Franciscan Friars
and the Sisters of the Atonement, expects more than 100. They will
gather on top of the Mount of the Atonement near the chapel and
wait in silence for midnight. When the clock strikes 12, they will
march down the mountain carrying torches as onlookers ring bells.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have come close to extinction in this century through
natural disasters and through things people inflict on each
other,'' said the Rev. James J. Gardiner, director of the center.
``I think that somehow, for some strange reason, the year 2000 is
getting through a lot of clutter out there, and people are being
touched deep within themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Buddhist Village Zendo Temple in Greenwich
Village will go on a retreat to Litchfield, Conn., for six days of
silent meditation that they will break by chanting and ringing
bells at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   For Jews, the holiday poses a dilemma this year. New Year's Eve
falls on a Friday night, coinciding with the Sabbath, whose
observance is sacrosanct. The last time that a new Christian
century began on the Sabbath was in 1200.
</P>
<P>
   As an observant Orthodox Jew, Danny Heumann, a 24-year-old New
York University law student who runs social events for young Jewish
professionals, was aware of that when he began getting inquiries
about New Year's Eve last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``People wanted to have an experience within the parameters of
observing the Sabbath,'' he said. So he rented Mendy's, a Kosher
restaurant in Manhattan, planning a sit-down Sabbath dinner, ``with
blessings over the wine, challah, a traditional dinner and a speech
about the weekly Torah portion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it was on a Friday night there was to be no music
except for Sabbath songs, and mainly we were planning schmoozing,''
Heumann explained. (Kosher restaurants may open on the Sabbath if
they are paid in advance for meals, the food is cooked in advance
and no Jew works on that day.)
</P>
<P>
   Heumann sold 150 tickets at $150 each and was expecting an
additional 100 reservations. But he didn't reckon with the
objection of the Orthodox Union, an organization that certifies
that food production facilities and restaurants meet Kosher
standards. When the union learned that the restaurant planned to
have an open bar until 1 a.m., it forbade the restaurant to hold
the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have an open bar till 1 a.m., what started out in the
first part of the night to be a Shabbaton suddenly becomes a
subterfuge for a New Year's Eve party,'' Dr. Mandell Ganchrow,
president of the Orthodox Union, said, using the Hebrew word for a
mixture of prayer, discussion, and social events. ``And New Year's
Eve is a Christian holiday. My friends and I don't celebrate New
Year's Eve, no matter what night it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are telling people is `Please remember it may be the
millennium, but the fact of the matter is that Shabbos has been
around for 3,500 years and will be here for the indefinite future.
The future of your children, family and people depends on
Shabbos,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Heumann found another site for his dinner, a vacant
space at Columbus Avenue and 89th Street. Yes, he said, there would
be an open bar.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Rabbis in the Conservative movement expect their adherents to be
in synagogue for Sabbath services too, but they advocate
acknowledging the millennium rather than ignoring it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that this is the millennium New Year's Eve, not a
small event in anyone's lifetime, and we also recognize the fact
that this is our Shabbat,'' Bruce Greenfield, executive director of
the New York Metropolitan Region of United Synagogue for
Conservative Judaism, said. ``We are asking congregations to have
family dinners that night, with singing and dancing, and perhaps
bring in a scholar-in-residence or a rabbi to do a program to
combine the holiness of Shabbat and recognition of the new year as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   He was astonished, he said, by the number of Conservative
synagogues _ more than 60 out of the 120 in the metropolitan area _
that announced they were planning special celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   In the world of Islam, there will be little if any recognition
of the millennium. ``Muslims acknowledge that this is the beginning
of a secular new year, but it is not the Muslim New Year and
everyone will be preoccupied with Ramadan,'' said Peter Awn,
professor of Islamic religion at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   Some churches in the neighborhoods surrounding Times Square, the
epicenter of New York City's celebration, have logistical concerns.
</P>
<P>
   On every Friday evening before the first Saturday of each month
for 30 years, there has been an all-night vigil with Masses and
prayers at St. John the Baptist, a church on 31st Street between
Seventh and Eighth Avenues. ``It was only canceled once in all
those years, when the church had a fire in 1997,'' The Rev. Francis
Gasparik said, ``and we were certainly planning it this month, on
the eve of the millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the people who run it started getting anxious when they
heard major restaurants were closing, theaters were going dark,
wondering about Y2K and whether the subways would work,'' he said.
``To me this is all paranoia. In anxiety we are supposed to trust
in God and not crawl into a hole, but unfortunately we had to make
a decision not to have the vigil this one time.''
</P>
<P>
   So what will Gasparik and his associates do instead?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll lock up and then have a New Year's Eve party in the
friary,'' he answered. ``We've been known to take a drink now and
then.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
