<HEADER>
A3724 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-EWING-NYT &LR;      12-08 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-EWING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS ARE COOLING THEIR HEELS OVER EWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For more than two weeks, Patrick Ewing's teammates
have watched him plodding around the paint like a grape-stomper
without signs of a limp, a wince or trepidation. And still, Ewing
waits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected him back before now,'' Allan Houston said Tuesday
night. ``He looks like he's not scared of being banged. I don't
know. You can't judge anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than two weeks, Ewing's teammates have seen him wave
for the ball in the post and turn plays that left coach Jeff Van
Gundy marveling last week at how the 37-year-old center was one of
the New York Knicks' best players _ as is. And still, Ewing waits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's going on with the guy,'' Marcus Camby
said. ``He just does his thing, and he doesn't say anything to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he began to practice all-out Nov. 22, Ewing has said very
little at all. For violating league policy on news media
accessibility, Ewing was fined $10,000 Wednesday by the National
Basketball Association, while the Knicks were assessed a $25,000
penalty for not enforcing the rules.
</P>
<P>
   But as members of the Knicks' organization have experienced, it
is hard to prod the stubborn Ewing into doing anything he doesn't
want to do. That is why his comeback will be on his terms, on his
schedule, when he says so.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not fully explain Ewing's cloak-and-dagger
behavior. On the rare occasion that he has uttered an update, Ewing
has said that his Achilles' tendon feels fine but that his body
needs time to get in ``basketball shape.'' Even so, as Van Gundy
has acknowledged, most athletes coming off an injury get in game
condition only by playing games.
</P>
<P>
   So why isn't he playing? One theory behind Ewing's protracted
wait is far more complex than any physical reason for his absence:
maybe he is afraid. After missing 88 regular-season games over two
seasons, after coming back from a devastating wrist injury only to
endure a partly torn Achilles' tendon, after watching his number of
great nights decrease with each injury-marred season, Ewing may be
wondering just how much superstar is left in him.
</P>
<P>
   Is he still one of the league's elite centers? Will his taped-up
body betray him again?
</P>
<P>
   Each question could be causing him to pause and make sure he
returns with as grand an entrance as possible, whether that is
Friday against Philadelphia or next week. Appearance has always
been important to the proud Ewing. Even when no one else expects
miracle recoveries, he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to go out, have a great game and score
50,'' Ewing said after playing against Indiana in the 1998
playoffs, his first game in four months after major wrist surgery.
``No, not really. But I thought I would have had a better game than
I did.''
</P>
<P>
   He shot 3 for 11 in 27 minutes that day. In the summer months
afterward, teammates close to Ewing that season said he was wounded
when he read that his best days were over and that it was time to
phase him out as the team's go-to man.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Ewing proved those theories wrong _ to a point.
After takeout food and long nights behind close doors in the labor
negotiations, Ewing emerged from the lockout last January mentally
drained and physically soft, but pushed onward in a cram-session
season. Playing with Achilles' tendinitis, his numbers dropped off
and he missed a series of game-winning shots, but he also unearthed
an amazing effort to save the Knicks from playoff elimination in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, his Achilles' tendon partly tore. In a suit and
tie, Ewing watched the team go on to the finals. Latrell Sprewell,
Houston and Camby emerged as a trifecta of entertainment for the
Madison Square Garden crowds that adored their style.
</P>
<P>
   In Ewing's absence, the Knicks had grown new stars. Now, it is
hard to tell exactly where Ewing fits in on the star charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is such a macho league that `whose team is it?'
becomes a question that matters to some people,'' Van Gundy said.
``The answer should be, `We're a team, and we share in success
together.' Maybe that is bothering him. I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   No one fully understands what is at work in Ewing's mind. He has
become increasingly reclusive and has growled at teammates who have
discussed his progress. The one player he has chosen to befriend
speaks little English and fawns over Ewing. It is an odd match, but
Mirsad Turkcan may offer Ewing something other teammates don't:
unconditional respect and 24-hour flattery.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Ewing is not viewed as ``the man'' in the locker room,
there is no underestimating the impact he can make on a team that
is an unspectacular 11-9 this season without him. Although he may
not openly admit it, Ewing may be ready to play a supporting role
next to Houston and Sprewell, as David Robinson has learned to do
beside Tim Duncan in San Antonio. Or he may, as he has suggested
since last summer, resist changing his ways.
</P>
<P>
   In whatever capacity he returns, the Knicks need Ewing as a
low-post force who can help their woeful rebounding, ease the
burden on Houston and Sprewell and stand side by side with Camby to
block shot after shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny how people go back and forth,'' Van Gundy said.
``Some players don't want him back and say, privately, they believe
they are just as good without him. And yet they know that's false.
They just don't want him to take away from their individual
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ewing can play, isn't he displaying an act of selfishness? No
one will take away the heroic way he played through pain last
season, but if he is truly feeling fine after two weeks of
full-throttle practice, why isn't he playing? After all, Camby is
playing through tendinitis and so is Larry Johnson. Whatever the
reason _ whether he is wary of his physical condition or afraid of
what he will look like _ Ewing is keeping a few bewildered
teammates guessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they see him practicing and wonder what is
happening,'' Van Gundy said. ``I'm sure, for some of them, it's a
tough situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 2345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3728 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-STADIUM-CARDS-AZR &LR;      12-08 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STADIUM-CARDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TASK FORCE QUESTIONS CARDINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT FLANNERY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - Some members of the task force seeking a home for a
new Arizona Cardinals stadium say it's time for the team to answer
the multimillion dollar question:
</P>
<P>
   How much will the team put up?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Phoenix are hoteliers are up in arms over reports
that the panel is eyeing a new hotel-motel bed tax to raise public
funds for the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The task force, appointed by Gov. Jane Hull, began talking about
financing for a proposed $329 million stadium last week. But some
members say their recommendations hinge on how much public money
will be needed.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody will know that amount until the Cardinals and the NFL
disclose how much they plan to kick in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a number that doesn't exist,'' said Robert
Fannin, a Phoenix attorney on the task force. ``It's kind of hard
to come up with a number when we don't know what the team will come
up with.''
</P>
<P>
   Task force member C.A. Howlett, an America West senior vice
president, said the atmosphere will be ``fraught with suspicion''
if the panel arbitrarily recommends public and private funding
levels without knowing how much the team and the league will ante
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for the committee to be of value to the governor and
the Legislature, the committee needs to make recommendations which
are fair to all parties,'' Howlett said. ``The only way to make
fair decisions is to have adequate, accurate information.''
</P>
<P>
   Howlett already has asked for projections showing how much money
the Cardinals would earn from a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Developer David Beckham, another task force member, said the
panel also is supposed to learn at its next meeting, scheduled for
next Thursday, Dec. 16, how certain Arizona taxes compare with
those in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals public relations director Paul Jensen said Wednesday
that team Vice President Mike Bidwill thinks it is ``premature to
get specific.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too many variables in the air,'' Jensen said,
including the site and type of stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, we'll do the right thing,'' he said. ``The
Cardinals are committed to being a major contributor.''
</P>
<P>
   The team committed $75 million to Rio Salado Crossing, a
proposed stadium and convention center rejected by Mesa voters
earlier this year. The NFL said it would have allocated about $25
million to the cost, a commitment that would probably remain the
same, said Ted Ferris, Hull's deputy chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Consultants told the task force last week that private funding,
on average, accounted for 29 percent of construction costs in 14
new NFL stadiums. Public funding supplied the rest. But Ferris said
that won't be acceptable to Hull.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to have to be more private money,'' Ferris said.
</P>
<P>
   That would mean that, based on a cost of $329 million, the
Cardinals would have to spend more than $75 million to make a
stadium deal fly.
</P>
<P>
   As for the public portion of the financing, Hull has said she
wants the panel to focus on user fees, such as sports ticket
surcharges, and specialized taxes, such as a bed tax or a rental
car tax.
</P>
<P>
   Ferris reiterated Wednesday, Dec. 8, that Hull will not consider
a general tax increase to finance the project.
</P>
<P>
   But tourism officials said Wednesday that the local hotel
industry is in an economic slump and unprepared to pay a new tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members certainly are not supportive of a tax to pay for a
Cardinals stadium,'' said Debbie Sweeney, executive director of the
Valley Hotel and Resort Association. ``There's no benefit to them
paying for a Cardinals stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   During meetings this week, Ferris discussed a proposal to pour
more money into state tourism promotion activities, using some of
the money raised by a new hotel bed tax.
</P>
<P>
   David Flack, a Scottsdale resort manager who is vice president
of the resort association and a member of the Arizona Tourism
Alliance, said such a plan makes the bed tax ``more palatable, but
it doesn't make it a slam-dunk by any stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   In Scottsdale, he said, hotel bookings through October were down
7.5 percent, compared with last year. Most hoteliers don't think
the industry is healthy enough to take on an added burden.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has complained for several years that Arizona's
tourism promotion lags behind other states, but the Legislature has
not responded with extra money.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McDermott, director of the Arizona Office of Tourism, said
this year's budget is $8.8 million, with the national average being
$10.8 million. Arizona, he said, spends about half what the top 20
tourism states spend on average.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Hotel &AMP; Motel Association is meeting next week to
hash out its position on the issue. Executive Vice President
Michele Eckert said only one thing is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is concern about any increase in the bed tax,'' she
said, ``in an economy where the hotels are having a tough year.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pat Flannery can be reached at pat.flannery(at)arizonarepublic.com &QL; 
or at (602) 444-8629. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
