<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0448 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3729 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MINELLI-CONCERT-REVIE     12-08 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINELLI-CONCERT-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MINELLI ON MINELLI': LIZA, WITH FEARS, VULNERABILITY AND SONGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT8 and 9 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the ghosts refuse to go away, you might as well
learn to dance with them. So there is Liza Minnelli, that most
haunted of popular entertainers, acting as an anxious but willing
hostess to a whole party of phantoms at the Palace Theater, where
her new concert show, ``Minnelli on Minnelli,'' opened Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Minnelli also has six cosmetically perfect chorus boys to
keep her company, but they are little more than window dressing.
It's the spectral presences of her famous father, the director
Vincente Minnelli, and her even more famous mother, Judy Garland,
who are her real co-stars here.
</P>
<P>
   Well, they and the shadows of her former selves, from the child
of Hollywood and backstage corridors to the hard-partying,
love-seeking gamine whose erratic career, love life and medical
problems were tabloid fodder for decades. There was a time when Ms.
Minnelli, 53, tried to ignore such ghosts when she performed. Now
she invokes them eagerly. As she is the first to say, she needs all
the assistance she can get these days.
</P>
<P>
   Liza Minnelli comeback concerts, and there have been many, are
phenomena unto themselves, glittery but unsettlingly primitive
exchanges of affection between a star and her fans. This is, of
course, an element in every veteran performer's courting of an
audience.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Minnelli is no contemptuously cool Marlene Dietrich or
flamboyantly strutting Mick Jagger, daring those watching not to be
impressed. She lets her needs and her neuroses take center stage,
and she has never articulated them as consciously and bluntly as
she does here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minnelli on Minnelli,'' which has been directed and written by
lyricist Fred Ebb, the star's longtime friend, has been shaped as a
tribute to the films of Minnelli senior. But if you focus just on
the slide show of family photographs and the clips and songs from
those movies, performed by Ms. Minnelli and her solicitous chorus,
you're missing the point. And that is watching Ms. Minnelli's
presence grow from a fitful ember to a full if unsteady flame, fed
by those who come not just to worship but to reassure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm dying up here,'' Ms. Minnelli seems to be saying as soon
as she steps onto the stage where her mother, who died in 1969,
perfected the art of show business as support therapy in legendary
appearances in 1951 and 1967. ``Bring me to life.''
</P>
<P>
   The process, in this instance, requires a shaky, even painful
first act. Only in the evening's second part does Ms. Minnelli look
and sound as if she is feeling at home again. It is that evolution
rather than any sustained slickness of presentation that makes
``Minnelli on Minnelli,'' which runs through Jan. 1, so perversely
compelling. The exorbitant $125 top ticket price is for the
spectacle of raw emotion, not professional polish.
</P>
<P>
   Though she still sports the black helmet of hair that has been
her trademark for decades, Ms. Minnelli is at first almost
unrecognizable. It's not just that she is substantially heavier;
it's that the famously dynamic Ms. Minnelli, who has had hip
replacement surgery several years ago, seems so sedentary.
</P>
<P>
   When she raises her arms and points her fingers, to signal
projections of photographs and film stills and sequences associated
with her father, who died in 1986, the gestures are tentative, as
if this fabled Tony and Oscar winner had never tried them out
before.
</P>
<P>
   In her spangly, form-concealing Bob Mackie outfits she initially
brings to mind a rich suburban housewife who has always wanted to
pursue a singing career and now, finally allowed to do so, is
scared out of her mind. The big, brimming eyes, however, sending
out their silent S O S, are pure Minnelli.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, is the voice, although it is definitely more limited in
range and rougher at the edges than it once was. This is
particularly true in the opening numbers, which include the
standards ``If I Had You,'' delivered statue-still before a
microphone, and a more animated rendition of ``Taking a Chance on
Love.''
</P>
<P>
   The burden of most of the dancing falls to the handsome young
men who act as fawning suitors to Ms. Minnelli's uneasy diva. They
are, for the record, Jeffrey Broadhurst, Stephen Campanella (whom
Ms. Minnelli ogles in a tiresome and repeated bit of comic
business), Billy Hartung, Sebastian LaCause, Jim Newman and Alec
Timerman.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these singer-dancers have been seen to better advantage
in other Broadway shows. Here they are the male equivalents of
Vegas chorus girls, cozying up seductively to Ms. Minnelli,
striking provocative poses or pushing the star around in a chair to
the strains of ``Shine on Your Shoes'' from ``The Band Wagon.''
Their time alone onstage, haplessly tumbling and kicking to such
would-be show-stoppers as ``That's Entertainment,'' is largely time
wasted.
</P>
<P>
   It's in the second act, which is also the occasion for Ms.
Minnelli's scripted reminiscences of life with father, that she
finds her own feet, not to mention her larynx. Her hypnotic,
luxurious interpretation of ``Baubles, Bangles and Beads'' (from
``Kismet'') is the evening's most fully accomplished vocal moment.
And she does a truly stirring version of Lerner and Lane's ``What
Did I Have That I Don't Have'' that resurrects the high-gear
Minnelli of yore.
</P>
<P>
   When she takes her final leave of her audience, after a musical
ode to her father written for the occasion by John Kander and Ebb,
the professional gestures are all in place again, right down to the
don't-forget-me smile she flashes over her shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, this strange, awkward evening will be remembered less as
one of song than as a conscious manipulation of a fragile, needy
persona. She admits to having ``a panic attack'' in the middle of
one song, adding that she quelled it by thinking of ``all of you.''
When she observes that people still treat her as if she were 16
years old, a middle-aged man in the audience yells out, ``That's
because we love you!'' and it is one of many such declarations.
</P>
<P>
   The show also features a drolly revised version of ``I'm Glad
I'm Not Young Anymore'' (from ``Gigi''), with new lyrics by Ebb, in
which she alludes to her friends in Alcoholics Anonymous, her salad
days at Studio 54 and even her weight gain: ``How sweet to eat food
not caring that/Someone will say, `My God, she's fat.''' The
central premise of this exercise in theater as therapy is clearly
that things are better dealt with out in the open.
</P>
<P>
   You should also know about the production's most brazen act of
ghost-raising, which occurs just before the encore, in which Ms.
Minnelli sings along with ``The Trolley Song,'' while Judy Garland
performs the number in a clip from ``Meet Me in St. Louis.'' It's
worth noting that while Vincente Minnelli is mentioned often, by
his full name, Garland is referred to as ``my mother.'' Those who
don't know the reference, and what it signifies, will be utterly at
sea at this show.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `MINNELLI ON MINNELLI'
</P>
<P>
   Songs from the movies of Vincente Minnelli; written and directed
by Fred Ebb; choreography by John DeLuca; sets by John Arnone;
costumes by Bob Mackie; lighting by Howell Binkley; sound by Peter
J. Fitzgerald; projections by Batwin and Robin; film sequence
prepared by Jack Haley Jr.; musical arrangements and supervision by
Billy Stritch and Marvin Hamlisch; vocal arranger, Stritch; dance
music arrangements, David Krane and Peter Howard; music contractor,
Russ Kassoff; production stage manager, Karl Lengel; technical
supervisor, Neil Mazzella; general management, 101 Productions
Ltd.; executive producers, Gary Labriola and Edward J. Micone Jr.;
musical director, Bill LaVorgna. Presented by Radio City
Entertainment, LM Concerts, Scott Nederlander and Stewart F. Lane.
At the Palace Theater, 1564 Broadway, at 47th Street.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Liza Minnelli, Jeffrey Broadhurst, Stephen Campanella,
Billy Hartung, Sebastian LaCause, Jim Newman and Alec Timerman. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
