<HEADER>
A3736 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      12-08 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMOKE SCREEN FOR A BONFIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - Twelve Texas A&AMP;M University students died horribly on
his watch, and the thing Ray Bowen really wants you to be upset
about is an editorial cartoon.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty-seven young people were hurt. Another remains in critical
condition. All of the injuries, all of the deaths, could have been
pre vented by university President Bowen and the other grown-ups in
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bowen rails against a car toon by The Arizona
Republic's Steve Benson, turns down The Re public's $10,000
donation to victim relief funds, and says in a letter to the
newspaper that accepting the money would ``do violence to our
ethical standards.''
</P>
<P>
   The university president mentions nothing about the violence
done to young bodies when a 40-foot pile of logs collapses on them.
</P>
<P>
   He says nothing about the violence done to the families of
students crushed under an avalanche of tim ber. &QL; 
A LOT OF SMOKE &QL; 
He says nothing in his letter about the ethical standards that
allowed a largely unsupervised group of kids, some of them drunk,
to attempt to construct what amounts to a four-story building with
no blueprint and little professional guidance.
</P>
<P>
   It made a big mess.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to cover up that much debris is with a lot of
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators in Texas now say that one of two crane operators
working on the annual Bonfire at A&AMP;M when it collapsed was a
student, not a licensed operator.
</P>
<P>
   The university also has admitted that freshmen and sophomores
were al lowed to work on the upper levels of the log tower, another
violation of school rules.
</P>
<P>
   A former A&AMP;M construction science professor and Bonfire adviser
said recently that he believes the structure collapsed because
safety and design features were ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, there was not someone over seeing all of this to make
sure it was being done,'' said Larry Grosse, a professor at
Colorado State Univer sity.
</P>
<P>
   However, the thing we should be most concerned about, according
to President Bowen, is a cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   The ``violence to ethical standards'' Bowen mentions doesn't
include the man he named to lead an investiga tion into the
disaster. He's the head of a construction company who also happens
to be chairman of Texans for Lawsuit Reform, which pushed for
limits on punitive damages in injury and death cases.
</P>
<P>
   Like, maybe, lawsuits filed against the university. &QL; 
NO CONFLICT OF INTEREST
</P>
<P>
   Another member of Texans for Lawsuit Reform is the owner of a
company that supplied one of the cranes used to build the Bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   All of them say there is no conflict of interest. No violence to
anyone's ethical standards.
</P>
<P>
   Autopsies have shown that two of the 12 who died were legally
drunk, and another had been drinking.
</P>
<P>
   The university could have outlawed the Bonfire years ago. Near
as I can tell, the only defense offered for cutting down and
burning thousands of trees _ rather than using the timber to, say,
build houses for the poor _ is ``tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   The last excuse for any bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   Benson's cartoon pictured the Bon fire disaster sharing space
with the inferno at Waco and the racially motivated murder of James
Byrd in Jasper, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter turning down the 10 grand, Bowen says, ``Texas A&AMP;M
will not allow itself to become an agent for The Arizona Republic
as it tries to manage the public criticism it is receiving.''
</P>
<P>
   He should have added, ``Instead, I'd like to deflect the
criticism we should be receiving by raising a big stink over a
cartoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice try.
</P>
<P>
   But when the smoke clears, any violence done to the ethical
stand ards at Texas A&AMP;M will prove to have been self-inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   And the university bigwigs will find out you can't reclaim the
moral high ground by standing on the bodies of the dead. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; arizona republic.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 2359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3737 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-JET-SKI-THEFTS-NYT     12-08 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JET-SKI-THEFTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
55 ARE INDICTED IN INQUIRY INTO JET SKI THEFTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Puerto Rico)  (rk) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a city that is constantly struggling to reduce
crime and improve the quality of life, few have noticed a
bedeviling problem on the city's edges: Jet Ski theft.
</P>
<P>
   This evil has not gone ignored by city, state and federal
authorities, however. Wednesday, some of the city's top law
enforcers announced that they had smashed a network of Jet Ski
thieves who scouted the city's waterways and snapped them up, and
then resold them in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   It may sound like a ``Baywatch'' plot line transferred to the
Rockaways, but officials said it was all too real: a 17-month
sting, naturally called ``Operation Jet Ski,'' resulted in the
indictment of 55 people and the recovery of 27 of the 55 Jet Skis
they traced, worth $412,000. Teaming up for the arrests were the
Queens district attorney's office, state and city investigators and
the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said the ring was suspected of
stealing 300 Jet Skis, three-quarters of all the ones stolen in the
metropolitan region since 1995. Nevertheless, only 27 such thefts
were reported last year as the investigation continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jet Skis are proliferating all over the United States,'' said
Safir, standing by one of the stolen watercraft in the Queens
district attorney's office. ``This sends a message that anyone
stealing Jet Skis will wind up in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   While one might have thought Jet Skis as alien to the city as
dog sleds, 60,000 such motorized water scooters are registered in
New York state, and aficionados have taken a shine to the coastal
waters around New York City, including Jamaica Bay and the Rockaway
Inlet, said a spokeswoman for the Queens district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the police department's vessel theft unit noticed an
increase in stolen water scooters, and notified police precincts
containing waterfronts.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 4, 1998, police officers from the 100th Precinct on the
Rockaway Peninsula of Queens noticed a suspicious truck with four
water scooters by the waterfront, and ``Operation Jet Ski'' was
born.
</P>
<P>
   Officers followed a crime wave that the authorities said led
from the home of Kim Aiello Jr., 21, of Mill Basin, Brooklyn, to
Wascar Valenzuela, the owner of Caribbean Central Sport, in San
Juan, Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Officials contend that Aiello oversaw a band of thieves who
either stole water scooters or gave up their own to defraud
insurance companies. At least 52 craft were stored at Aiello's
residence and then shipped to Puerto Rico with the help of
middlemen in Oceanside and West Hempstead on Long Island, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Aiello's lawyer, Joseph Mure Jr., said his client pleaded not
guilty yesterday. ``They got him down as a ring leader, but he's 21
years old and he really doesn't have a criminal past,'' said Mure.
``He has Jet Skis of his own, but he claims to have no involvement
in sending these Jet Skis to Puerto Rico.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela could not be reached for comment Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Forty people have been arrested, and 15 more are being sought. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-99 2359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991208.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-08 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3740 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      12-08 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMOKE SCREEN FOR A BONFIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - Twelve Texas A&AMP;M University students died horribly on
his watch, and the thing Ray Bowen really wants you to be upset
about is an editorial cartoon.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty-seven young people were hurt. Another remains in critical
condition. All of the injuries, all of the deaths, could have been
pre vented by university President Bowen and the other grown-ups in
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bowen rails against a car toon by The Arizona
Republic's Steve Benson, turns down The Re public's $10,000
donation to victim relief funds, and says in a letter to the
newspaper that accepting the money would ``do violence to our
ethical standards.''
</P>
<P>
   The university president mentions nothing about the violence
done to young bodies when a 40-foot pile of logs collapses on them.
</P>
<P>
   He says nothing about the violence done to the families of
students crushed under an avalanche of tim ber. &QL; 
A LOT OF SMOKE &QL; 
He says nothing in his letter about the ethical standards that
allowed a largely unsupervised group of kids, some of them drunk,
to attempt to construct what amounts to a four-story building with
no blueprint and little professional guidance.
</P>
<P>
   It made a big mess.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to cover up that much debris is with a lot of
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators in Texas now say that one of two crane operators
working on the annual Bonfire at A&AMP;M when it collapsed was a
student, not a licensed operator.
</P>
<P>
   The university also has admitted that freshmen and sophomores
were al lowed to work on the upper levels of the log tower, another
violation of school rules.
</P>
<P>
   A former A&AMP;M construction science professor and Bonfire adviser
said recently that he believes the structure collapsed because
