</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, there was not someone over seeing all of this to make
sure it was being done,'' said Larry Grosse, a professor at
Colorado State Univer sity.
</P>
<P>
   However, the thing we should be most concerned about, according
to President Bowen, is a cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   The ``violence to ethical standards'' Bowen mentions doesn't
include the man he named to lead an investiga tion into the
disaster. He's the head of a construction company who also happens
to be chairman of Texans for Lawsuit Reform, which pushed for
limits on punitive damages in injury and death cases.
</P>
<P>
   Like, maybe, lawsuits filed against the university. &QL; 
NO CONFLICT OF INTEREST
</P>
<P>
   Another member of Texans for Lawsuit Reform is the owner of a
company that supplied one of the cranes used to build the Bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   All of them say there is no conflict of interest. No violence to
anyone's ethical standards.
</P>
<P>
   Autopsies have shown that two of the 12 who died were legally
drunk, and another had been drinking.
</P>
<P>
   The university could have outlawed the Bonfire years ago. Near
as I can tell, the only defense offered for cutting down and
burning thousands of trees _ rather than using the timber to, say,
build houses for the poor _ is ``tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   The last excuse for any bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   Benson's cartoon pictured the Bon fire disaster sharing space
with the inferno at Waco and the racially motivated murder of James
Byrd in Jasper, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter turning down the 10 grand, Bowen says, ``Texas A&AMP;M
will not allow itself to become an agent for The Arizona Republic
as it tries to manage the public criticism it is receiving.''
</P>
<P>
   He should have added, ``Instead, I'd like to deflect the
criticism we should be receiving by raising a big stink over a
cartoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice try.
</P>
<P>
   But when the smoke clears, any violence done to the ethical
stand ards at Texas A&AMP;M will prove to have been self-inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   And the university bigwigs will find out you can't reclaim the
moral high ground by standing on the bodies of the dead. &QL; 
 &QL; 
